<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PAK-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW GOLFER SE RI-PAK BECAME A SUPERSTAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In South Korea, golf is a game primarily for the wealthy, with
annual membership in country clubs costing $200,000 to $1 million.
Se Ri-pak's family was not on that level. Her background was
considered middle class, and her father had a reputation of being
in the Korean underworld.
</P>
<P>
   When she was a sophomore in high school in Taejon, Pak played in
the Golf Digest Cup tournament. On the first day of the tournament,
her father, Joon Chul-pak, saw several parents of young golfers
talking. He approached them to say hello.
</P>
<P>
   ``They completely ignored me,'' he said recently. ``I guess my
daughter and myself didn't seem like much to them, because of their
high social status. So I called Se Ri in front of the trophy and
handed it to her, saying, `This is yours.' The others looked at me
as if I was some crazed lunatic. So I screamed back: `So what if I
touch it! My Se Ri is going to take it home with her anyways!' Se
Ri nodded in agreement. Later, she did take the trophy back home
with her.''
</P>
<P>
   That trophy, to be sure, was not the only one Se Ri-pak would
win. She dominated the amateur and the professional ranks in South
Korea, and this year, as a 20-year-old rookie on the Ladies
Professional Golf Association Tour, she has demonstrated precisely
what her father envisioned for her when she first picked up a club
at age 11: that she would be a star on the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   But even he could not know the full measure of what she would
accomplish so soon. On Sunday, she won the Giant Eagle LPGA Classic
in Ohio, her fourth victory of the season and third in the last
four weeks, giving her a tour-best $768,211 in earnings. Two of the
victories came in major championships, the McDonald's LPGA
Championship in May and the U.S. Women's Open this month. She is
the youngest Women's Open champion ever and the youngest player to
win two women's majors in a season.
</P>
<P>
   At the Jamie Farr Classic in Ohio this month, she wreaked havoc
on the record book: a four-round total of 261 that was four strokes
lower than the record for an LPGA event, a 23-under-par total that
tied another tour record and a second-round score of 61 that was
the lowest in LPGA history. Through it all, she has seemed immune
to pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, who will try to win a third major in the Du Maurier
Classic, beginning Thursday in Windsor, Ontario, has made an impact
in golf on a level of Tiger Woods' phenomenal rookie splash last
year, and her debut has been compared to that of Nancy Lopez. As
the latest of the sudden stars who have captured golf's spotlight,
winning with attitude and the fearlessness of youth, she joins the
likes of Woods, Ernie Els and Justin Leonard, and this year's
upstart amateurs, Matt Kuchar of the United States and Justin Rose
of England. And like Woods, who is of Thai descent, Pak has
energized an already fervent Asian market in a sport that is
rapidly globalizing.
</P>
<P>
   For all this, Se Ri (pronounced suh-REE) credits the father who
grabbed that trophy back in Yeo Ju City and willed her to win it.
And while there is a strong patriarchal quality to family life in
South Korea, the relationship between this father and daughter
seems to have gone beyond even the aggressiveness of the
conventional, and notorious, Hollywood stage mother.
</P>
<P>
   Joon Chul-pak often scolded his daughter so severely for not
following his golf instructions from the time she was a
pre-teen-ager that he sometimes reduced her to tears. Every day
that she was not in school, he said, from early in the morning into
the evening, regardless of whether there was a heat wave or
freezing cold, he worked with her at the one golf course in Taejon.
Sometimes, in the cold, icicles would form in her hair while she
practiced.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the golf course, the father occasionally camped out in
a tent with her in a cemetery, then left her alone in the dark to
develop, he said, ``her bravery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' he told the trembling girl, ``I will not let
the ghosts get you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the neighborhood, at the golf course, said I was
crazy, that I was insane,'' Joon Chul-pak recalled. ``My wife was
worried that I would kill Se Ri. And for what _ a game that was not
so popular in Korea? But I was very straight, very stern with Se Ri
about her golf because I believed she had the talent, the patience
to one day be a great player in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, in the glow of her success, the relationship between
father and daughter has softened _ at dinner, she will push a plate
of vegetables toward him, and he will smile and say, ``She takes
care of me now.'' But her discipline and hard work remain. ``I had
good mental training,'' she said. ``I think the way my father
taught me: `Attack the course.'''
</P>
<P>
   After finishing anywhere from 11th to missing the cut in her
first nine events this season, Pak burst onto the women's golf
scene by winning the LPGA Championship in mid-May. Her reign at the
top has provided considerable drama, including a classic duel with
the amateur Jenny Chuasiriporn in the Open, which Pak won in a
20-hole playoff; her record performance at the Jamie Farr, and a
birdie putt on the final hole to win last Sunday in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Meg Mallon, a former U.S. Women's Open winner herself, was
paired with Pak for that stunning round of 61 at the Jamie Farr
Classic. ``I had a chance to observe her closely,'' Mallon said.
``I felt like she plays just one shot at a time. She never gets
ahead of herself. Each shot is like the only shot of the day for
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallon laughed. ``But my favorite quote of Se Ri's is, `I have
no nervous.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pak, like her father, is solidly built at 130 pounds, with
muscular legs. (She was a sprinter and hurdler in high school.) At
5 feet 6 inches, she is about his height, and her hands appear as
strong as his.
</P>
<P>
   Both believe that he knows her game so well, the rhythms of her
swing so clearly, that after several practice swings he will tell
her, ``That's enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' he said, ``I will tell her in midswing, and she
will stop.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the cemetery tactic was ``my creation,'' and several
times a year for several years he would take her there at night.
When she was about 16, he said, she said to him one night, ``I'm
warm here,'' meaning she was comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I knew her heart was strong,'' he said. ``We never
went back to the cemetery.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Pak's confidence and self-possession are so strong that recently
she politely but firmly turned down an invitation from the
president of Korea, Kim Young-sam, to return there to be honored in
a parade and receive the Blue Dragon, the nation's highest medal of
achievement for sports. She wrote him that she is committed to
playing golf for the rest of the season but would be delighted to
return for any presentations later.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Korea,'' said Steve Sung Yong-kil, her business manager,
``she is a great sports hero.'' The only other internationally
prominent South Korean athlete at this time is Chan Ho-park,
pitcher for the Los Angeles Dodgers. ``But,'' Kil said, ``Se Ri is
like Michael Jordan there. Park is like, well, Scottie Pippen.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Pak's achievements receive huge coverage in the South
Korean news media, and her image can be found on television and in
advertisements. Her playoff victory in the Open was televised live
in South Korea, at 1 a.m. there, and was watched by millions. At
the recent JAL Big Apple Classic in New Rochelle, N.Y., there were
so many fans of Asian background in her gallery that signs were
posted in Korean requesting a common courtesy: Please don't move
before players hit shots.
</P>
<P>
   Pak does not seem overwhelmed by the attention she has received.
``I like it,'' she said. ``It means I'm playing good. If I not play
good, nobody want to talk to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Joon Chul-pak was so driven by the notion of his daughter's
becoming a champion that he made a bet with his life, he said, and
his daughter's. He would devote his time and energy and money _
costs for fees and travel would come to thousands of dollars a year
_ to her golf future. He placed his construction business in Taejon
_ about 100 miles south of Seoul _ in the hands of his wife, Jeong
Suk-kim, but she was inexperienced in that area, and the business
declined. Yet Joon Chul did not change course.
</P>
<P>
   He also did something else for his daughter _ and his family. He
quit being, as he said, a gangster.
</P>
<P>
   The Shisa Journal, a South Korean weekly, reported on July 23
that Joon Chul-pak, ``who was a member of the underworld in Taejon
City, fled to Hawaii in 1988 ... when the police began clamping
down on organized crime there.'' Joon Chul confirmed this. ``To be
honest,'' he said, ``I was a thug in the past. I lived a tough
life.'' He displayed long scars on his stomach and thigh that he
said came from stabbing wounds.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to South Korea by himself after four months, and his
family followed soon afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Joon Chul-pak had been a good-enough amateur golfer to represent
his city in South Korean national tournaments, and one day he was
in a park in Hawaii practicing his chip shots. Se Ri, then 11, had
tagged along. She asked to try it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In less than 30 minutes,'' he recalled, ``she was gripping the
club perfectly and hitting surprisingly good shots.'' He decided
that she was a natural. She just thought it was fun. Soon, though,
the father had made a business out of it for her.
</P>
<P>
   She bridled. She wanted to play with friends. He said he was her
friend. She kept at the game, getting better and better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he would say: `Keep pushing. Why you cannot do like
this? I teach you like this,''' Se Ri recalled. ``I was really
upset many times because I just wanted my dad to give me more rest,
but he didn't do that. It made me strong. Many, many times I cried.
But then I thought to myself: `Show your dad you can do it. You can
do anything if you want.'''
</P>
<P>
   There were times in her late teens, recalled her mother, when Se
Ri had hit a bad shot in a tournament and she stayed hitting that
shot for hours afterward. ``We would call her, `It's midnight; it's
time to come in,''' her mother said. ``And Se Ri would call back,
`Just five more minutes.'''
</P>
<P>
   Se Ri said: ``I had respect for my father, and I stayed with
golf in the beginning because I wanted to prove to people that he
wasn't crazy for what he was doing with me. He was pushing me,
pushing me to be better. I knew that. I wanted to make him and my
mother proud. And then I began to love golf.''
</P>
<P>
   When Se Ri began showing real talent, Joon Chul joined a country
club with a $200,000-a-year membership fee. But after a year, Joon
Chul could no longer afford the fee, and of the 86 18-hole golf
courses in South Korea, only one on the mainland is public. So, to
give his daughter the competition and instruction he felt she
needed, he began to travel with her to national tournaments around
South Korea and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Se Ri demonstrated remarkable skill _ a satiny smooth but potent
swing, a singularly consistent putter _ and won 30 tournaments in
South Korea before turning pro in 1996 and winning six of 14 events
there, and finishing second seven times.
</P>
<P>
   Joon Chul understood that while he knew something about golf, he
did not know everything. So last year he sent Se Ri to live in
Orlando, Fla., by herself to train under David Leadbetter, the
noted instructor who had worked with Nick Faldo and Greg Norman,
among others. Samsung, the South Korean conglomerate that signed Se
Ri in 1996, paid Leadbetter's salary.
</P>
<P>
   She continued to improve, and last fall she tied for first at
qualifying school for the LPGA Tour in her first attempt.
</P>
<P>
   She has learned English well enough to comprehend and converse.
Her father, in his limited time in America, has picked up a few
catch phrases. He used one recently when his daughter left the
restaurant earlier than the others in order to get her rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take it easy,'' he said to her. He smiled. She smiled. She
pursed her lips. It was just that mixture of ease and intensity
that has helped catapult Se Ri-pak to the top of the golf world.
</P>
</TEXT>
