<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SPIELBERG'S-WAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SPIELBERG'S WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, July 28:
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, each generation grows into the news its elders could
not quite impart. But war is news that lies hidden even within the
generation that experiences it. Men who have survived combat find
that what they knew in that irretrievable now is something they
will always know. But they can barely tell each other what it was.
If nothing else, their silence is a kind of respect for the dead,
whose understanding _ though it is a metaphor to call it that _
surpasses explanation.
</P>
<P>
   So it falls to the generations that did not experience war to
come at the truth of it somehow, not only in order to understand
their elders but to protect themselves as well. We will know how
close we get by how shattering the attempt feels.
</P>
<P>
   Every boy or girl who leafs through the history books looking
for pictures of war dead is trying to look at death itself _ always
a kind of missing information _ and, more importantly, at the
happening of death, the moment portrayed when, for instance,
Praskukhin dies, killed by shrapnel in the second of Tolstoy's
``Sebastopol Sketches.'' By profound instinct we cannot help
gracing the act of dying with ceremony, whether, as in Tolstoy's
case, it resembles a procession of mourners leaving a cathedral or
whether, as in Pat Barker's ``The Ghost Road,'' it merely ends
awareness. But something is denied, and with difficulty reaffirmed,
when death erupts everywhere, at once, with profligate disrespect
for instinct or cause or ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   That is how it is portrayed in Steven Spielberg's new movie,
``Saving Private Ryan.'' There is every reason to believe that this
is as close as one generation can come to an artistic knowledge of
war elicited from the firsthand experience of its elders. Certainly
no one has ever come closer, cinematically. Spielberg depicts in
battle here not only the knowledge that results from war, but what
has been, and remains, the inexplicable knowledge _ pure trauma in
which consciousness itself is all the narrative there can ever be.
</P>
<P>
   Art elicits faith and distrust. Faith, in watching ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' is measured by the extent of one's personal horror.
Distrust _ call it an awareness of artistic conventions _ is
measured by the realization that there was, for tens of thousands
of men 54 years ago, a place and time where art's ultimate
usefulness _ the ability to shape experience _ was utterly lacking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
