<HEADLINE>
MOSLEY, DEFEATING UKRAINIAN, SHOWS HIS BOXING POTENTIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Colo., Ga., Texas)   (bl)  
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At 18, Larry Mosley Jr. is being billed as the next
hope for the beleaguered U.S. boxing program. Monday night in the
first round at the Goodwill Games, Mosley showed glimmers of that
promise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mosley scored mostly on counter-punches to defeat Sergei
Dzinziruk of Ukraine by 6-3 in a 147-pound bout at the Theater in
Madison Square Garden. The Los Angeles-based welterweight gave
himself a ``7 or 8'' out of 10 for his performance in a competition
that is by far his most significant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave him an 8,'' said his coach, Kenny Croom. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That should be enough for American boxing, which is still
reeling from winning just one gold at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics and
no medals at all at the 1997 world championships. Mosley was not at
either, but the whispers were already beginning that he could
reverse the trend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't try to put that much pressure on me,'' said Mosley,
the cousin of Shane Mosley, the World Boxing Association
lightweight champion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mosley, a 5-foot-7-inch right-hander, entered the arena with his
usual bravado, beating his chest and winding up his right hand as
he circled the ring. But he was tentative against a seasoned
opponent. The 23-year-old Dzinziruk, a 6-0 left-hander, was a 1996
Olympian and finished second in the world championships. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was off-balanced a little bit and I was trying to maintain
my composure,'' Mosley said. He took control in the second round,
sneaking in a right to the chin for a point and then countering
Dzinziruk's jab with another right. Mosley began to move with more
fluidity and throw more punches. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mosley absorbed a scoring left in the third round, then
increased his lead to 4-1 with another right counter off
Dzinziruk's left jab and a lunging right that caught Dzinziruk by
surprise. The round ended with Mosley grimacing from a low blow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mosley began to trade punches out of anger, and Dzinkziruk
tagged him with a left. Mosley settled back into his style. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mosley surrendered 2 points in close quarters in the fourth and
fifth rounds, but he retaliated with a right-left combination and a
long right that smashed against Dzinkziruk's cheek. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a learning experience,'' Mosley said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 201-pound division, DaVarryl Williamson of Aurora, Colo.,
unleashed a right that dropped Giocachino Mocerino of Italy to his
knees in the first round, stopping the bout. ``I wanted to get the
jitterbugs out,'' Williamson said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other Americans advancing into the semifinals were Jose Navarro
(106 pounds) of Los Angeles, Antonio Rodriguez (119) of Waianae,
Hawaii, Jacob Hudson (132) of Augusta, Ga., Miguel Espino (147) of
North Hollywood, Calif., and Jose Santa Cruz (119) of Monterey
Park, Calif., and Malcolm Tann (201) of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban heavyweight Felix Savon, the 1992 and 96 Olympic champion,
stopped Dmitri Gerasimov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
