<HEADER>
A5659 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-FAN-DEATHS-NYT &LR;      07-28 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-FAN-DEATHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LURE OF HIGH SPEEDS MAKES RACES A THREAT TO FANS, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ind., Ala.)   (bl)  
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Experiencing the speed of race cars up close is, without a
doubt, what attracts fans to the track. But that is just the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's accident at Michigan Speedway, where three fans were
killed and six others were injured by flying debris from a car, was
another reminder of the danger that auto racing poses to fans.
Although the accident at Championship Auto Racing Teams' most
prestigious race, the U.S. 500, marked the first time in 11 years
that spectators were killed at a major auto race in the United
States, the possibility of fans being killed or injured always
exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot guarantee that things like this won't happen,'' said
Fred Nation, the publicity director for the Indianapolis Motor
Speedway, which will be host to the Brickyard 400 NASCAR race
Saturday. ``There is an element of risk for spectators, as there is
risk in anything we do. I think fans know the risks. Whenever you
have a car going 220 miles per hour, there is the potential for a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Races held by CART and its rival open-wheel circuit, the Indy
Racing League, routinely see speeds of 230 mph in the
straightaways, although Indy Racing League cars are less powerful
by design and therefore run slower average speeds. Formula One, the
open-wheel circuit based in Europe, uses road courses, which has
two effects: speeds are slower and fans are seated farther from the
track. NASCAR racers can reach 200 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The danger to fans, it seems, increases as the speed of the cars
on the track increases. The last two spectator fatalities have
occurred on superspeedways, oval tracks that are more than a mile
in circumference (Michigan Speedway, in Brooklyn, is a two-mile
oval) and where speeds get higher because of the longer
straightaways and banked turns.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, both NASCAR and CART have taken measures to slow cars
down on superspeedways in an attempt to protect drivers and fans.
</P>
<P>
   An accident involving the driver Bobby Allison in 1987, in which
his car flew into the catch fence at Talladega, Ala., and nearly
through it, inspired NASCAR to require the use of restrictor
plates, which cut down the flow of air into the carburetor. NASCAR
has also employed roof flaps, aerodynamic devices that help
stabilize a car when it is in danger of losing contact with the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   CART introduced a new aerodynamic wing, designed to slow its
cars, in Sunday's race. Called the Handford device, it is a small
extension on the rear wing, which reduces speeds by as much as 15
mph on superspeedways.
</P>
<P>
   The debris Sunday came off the car driven by Adrian Fernandez.
After he lost control of his car, it hit the concrete retaining
wall, and a wheel and several pieces of the suspension flew into
the grandstand. The parts, which were heavy and traveling fast,
landed on top of spectators sitting in the eighth and 10th rows.
The victims did not have time to move out of the way, witnesses
said.
</P>
<P>
   CART officials did not comment Monday. pending further
investigation of the incident. But at a news conference Monday at
Michigan Speedway, Gene Haskett, the track's president, said that
extending the 15-foot catch fence by several feet was very likely.
The Indianapolis Motor Speedway has a 19-foot fence.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, when debris from a race car becomes airborne, the parts
are kept on the track by the retaining wall or fence, which is
angled on the top toward the track. Sunday, the wheel did not hit
any part of the 15-foot fence on its way into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at the percentages,'' said Kevin Triplett,
the director of operations at NASCAR. ``What happened yesterday,
while it was a tragic situation, it is rare. When you look at the
number of laps run at Michigan since 1969, it's easy to see that
this is not a common thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the injured spectators, Doris Shuman, 70, remained
hospitalized Monday. She was in good condition. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
