<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAGICALLY-HIP-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAGICALLY HIP: OF CANADA, IN SLOW MOTION BUT NOT ON ICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just how Canadian is the Tragically Hip? Well, the
band started its set Thursday night at Wetlands with ``Fireworks,''
in which the singer is astonished to meet a girl who couldn't care
less about hockey. ``I never saw someone say that before,'' he
marvels.
</P>
<P>
   The Tragically Hip fills arenas in Canada and Detroit but is
still on the club circuit in most of the United States. Its
five-night stand at Wetlands, which ended Saturday, sold out
completely, with a prominent Canadian contingent in the audience
chanting ``Hip! Hip!''
</P>
<P>
   Formed in 1986, the Tragically Hip harks back to 1960s rock,
building songs on guitar riffs that look back to the Rolling
Stones, the Byrds, Neil Young and the blues. The lyrics are about
endless varieties of disillusionment, with titles like ``The
Inevitability of Death'' and ``Chagrin Falls.'' Gordon Downie, the
band's lead singer, sounds frustrated but dogged, an Everyman whose
consolation, as he sang in ``Springtime in Vienna,'' is that ``We
live to survive our paradoxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Having outlasted grunge and other alternative-rock vogues, the
Tragically Hip could find a place alongside jam bands and
neo-folk-rock bands if a broader audience could get used to
Downie's lead vocals, delivered in an earnest, quavering tenor
voice that teeters between Michael Stipe and Harry Chapin.
</P>
<P>
   And the band's guitar riffs are both its strength and its
limitation. Many of its songs go no further than their riffs; the
band settles too often for one-note tunes, and it has to push
itself to write full-fledged melodies. But onstage, the riffs
foment jams that are as determined and resilient as the lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   In a set that concentrated on the band's current album,
``Phantom Power'' (Sire) and its previous studio album, ``Trouble
at the Henhouse'' (Atlantic), the songs worked their way from
frustration to triumph, with brash guitars to clear away any
doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden, a Canadian songwriter who opened the show, plays
slow-motion music that is not exactly lackadaisical. In one song,
he sang about trying to get off a couch where he'd been inert for
four days; in another, he sat on a resort beach watching a girl
getting seduced. His songs are laconic, usually placing a verse or
two between a measured introduction and a long instrumental coda by
his band, and he sang in a scratchy, lethargic voice until his last
song, when he worked himself up to a grunge growl.
</P>
<P>
   But like one of his obvious models, Dinosaur Jr., he puts
melodies and character into his somnambulistic repertory. He just
demands that listeners adjust to his sense of time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
