<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5666 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-SAFETY-HNS &LR;      07-28 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SAFETY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Spectators' deaths bring safety concerns
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grand Prix of Houston will exceed precautionary standards
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The tragic death of three spectators during the U.S. 500 CART event
Sunday at Michigan Speedway left the entire racing community
stunned and saddened.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Houston will be the site of a new CART event Oct. 4,
and officials want the fans to know that the chances of a similar
occurrence at the Texaco Grand Prix of Houston are extremely
remote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunday's tragedy was only the second time in CART history this
has happened,'' said Dick Stahler, marketing director of the
Houston race. ``But it never has happened at a street race.''
</P>
<P>
   Three people in the grandstand were killed at Michigan on Sunday
when the car of driver Adrian Fernandez slammed into the outside
wall of the fourth turn, snapping off the right front wheel.
</P>
<P>
   The wheel and tire, which weigh more than 40 pounds, flew into
the air and barely cleared the 11-foot debris fencing, which is on
top of the four-foot concrete barrier.
</P>
<P>
   The wheel was airborne _ flying parallel to the track _ for more
than 100 feet before it landed about 10 rows up in the stands,
instantly killing two people. It then bounced and struck another
spectator, who also died. Six other people were injured as the
wheel ricocheted through the grandstand.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in 11 years that any non-race official had
been killed at a major racing event.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle Kurtenbach, 41, was killed at the Indianapolis 500 in 1987
when he was struck by a tire that flew into the stands after a
crash involving the cars of Tony Bettenhausen and Roberto Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtenbach's widow filed a $9 million wrongful-death lawsuit
against the Indianapolis Motor Speedway, which was settled out of
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of those incidents were at superspeedway ovals where the
cars reach speeds in excess of 200 mph, including the turns,''
Stahler said. ``The cars in Houston will be making turns at less
than 100 mph.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though no spectator death ever has occurred at a street
race, TGPH officials have gone beyond the standard safety
requirements that CART uses for a street or road course.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are using eight-foot debris fencing, which has never been
done before at a street race,'' Stahler said. ``These races usually
have six-foot debris fences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cost us an additional $500,000 over our budget to do it,
but we want everything in Houston to be state-of-the-art in safety.
It will be the highest and strongest fence (with reinforced steel)
ever constructed for a street race.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston race will have more than 40,000 seats in temporary
grandstands that will be set up along the 1.68-mile course, which
has 10 turns.
</P>
<P>
   The start-finish line will run in front of the George R. Brown
Convention Center, and the fastest part of the course will be a
seven-block backstretch on Austin Street at the eastern edge of
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The Champ cars are expected to reach speeds of 180 mph on the
Austin straightaway, but the drivers will need to slow to a crawl
on some of the turns, which are at a 90-degree angles or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the layout, many of the seats are near a
braking zone,'' Stahler said. ``It's not comparable to an oval
track where the cars are coming out of a turn at 220 mph.''
</P>
<P>
   But there have been rare incidents in which fatalities happened
at street courses.
</P>
<P>
   At the Molson Indy Toronto Grand Prix two years ago _ a race
similar to the one that will be run in Houston _ CART flagman Gary
Avrin was killed when he was struck by the crashing car of driver
Jeff Krosnoff, who also was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Avrin was standing in a spot next to the course where a paying
customer would not be allowed to stand.
</P>
<P>
   One spectator was killed at Michigan in 1969 in a Trans Am road
race on the speedway infield when a car went out of control and
veered off the asphalt, striking several people who were standing
in the infield grass. The infield road course has not been used
since that accident.
</P>
<P>
   Even on high-speed ovals like Michigan, a fatality among
spectators is less likely than being struck by lightning.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was the first time in the 31-year history of the speedway
that a death was caused by flying debris in the grandstand. But
that is little consolation to the families and friends of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dawson, 31, was treated for minor arm lacerations, but his
friend Kenneth Fox, 38, was killed in the seat next to Dawson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve is devastated by this,'' said Nancy Dawson, Steve's
mother. ``He told me he saw the tire coming and had just enough
time to turn away, but it hit his friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Miller, 40, who came to the race from South Bend, Ind., was
sitting one row behind the other two people who were killed _
Sheryl Laster, 40, and Michael Tautkus, 49, both of Milan, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tire had to be coming at us at 200 mph,'' Miller said.
``It makes you realize this is an inherently dangerous sport and
you take certain risks when you come to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Thompson, who works as a nurse at the Jackson, Mich.,
hospital where the victims were treated, attended the race and
suffered a minor leg injury when the tire bounced in front of her
and her husband, David Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were watching the race, but the next thing I knew, a black
blur hit two rows in front of me, then hit my leg,'' Joyce Thompson
said. ``It was like a bomb going off. People were lying around with
blood everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Bramer, 31, and his brother Richard Bramer, 20, also
suffered minor arm injuries when hit by the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it was coming,'' Gerald Bramer said. ``I
was looking at it thinking, `Why is this tire coming at me?' The
only thing I could do was throw my arms up to protect myself and
keep it from hitting me in the head. I've never seen anything
coming at me that fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Haskett, the president of the Michigan Speedway, said track
officials will conduct an exhaustive investigation to determine
exactly what happened Sunday and why.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will evaluate every aspect of the accident,'' Haskett said.
``We want to know if anything can be done to prevent this in the
future. It's very unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   The next major race at Michigan is less than three weeks away.
The NASCAR Winston Cup series will make its second stop of the
season at Michigan for the DeVilbiss 400 on Aug. 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
