<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-COLUMN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: THE METS SAVE WORST FOR NL LEAST TEAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some people in baseball have this misguided notion
about how some teams should beat other teams. A contending team,
for example, should beat expansion teams, they believe. But the
idea must be misguided because Bobby Valentine thinks it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate the thought that we're supposed to beat another major
league team because of something in the standings,'' the Mets'
manager said one day last month.
</P>
<P>
   He was speaking after the New York Mets lost to the Florida
Marlins, after it was suggested that the Mets were supposed to beat
teams like the Marlins, that indeed if the Mets wanted to contend
seriously for the wild-card spot they had to win those games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a New York mentality that gets people in a rut,''
Valentine said. ``And I'm sorry that my team believes it when they
hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Marlins, he added: ``They're a major league
team, one that's playing pretty good out there, and so is Montreal.
To think we should just beat them because they don't have a good
record or because they have younger players is appalling.''
</P>
<P>
   The reality of the situation, however, says teams that seek
division championships or wild-card spots should beat up on certain
other teams.
</P>
<P>
   En route to some of the best seasons in history, the 1927
Yankees (.714) won 21 of 22 games from the St. Louis Browns (.386),
the 1939 Yankees (.702) wiped out the Browns (.279) 19 games to 3,
the 1909 Pittsburgh Pirates (.724) annihilated the Boston Braves
(.294) 20 of 21 times, the St. Louis Cardinals (.355) 18 of 21 and
the Brooklyn Dodgers (.359) 18 of 22.
</P>
<P>
   In this new era of wild-card playoff spots, each league has
become basically divided into four segments: the division leaders
and their serious challengers, the wild-card contenders, teams that
can be competitive but fall too far back to be in playoff
contention and the weakest teams, those least likely to win any
given series unless it is against another team in their group.
</P>
<P>
   With this category open to some challenge, the members of the
National League Least this season have been the expansion Arizona
Diamondbacks, the dismantled Florida Marlins, the low-paid Montreal
Expos and two teams that have their moments but never had a chance
once the season began, the Cincinnati Reds and the Pittsburgh
Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   In April and May the Mets compiled a respectable 13-5 record
against the Marlins, the Pirates, the Reds and the Diamondbacks.
But in June and July the Mets stumbled badly against the NL Least,
winning 7 and losing 12 against the Marlins, the Pirates and the
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   That was no way, despite Valentine's view, to challenge for the
wild-card lead. By losing to those inferior teams, the Mets gave
themselves no cushion for their games against tougher opponents;
Atlanta, for one.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets lost all three games of a three-game series in Atlanta
early this month, then dropped the first two games of a four-game
series at Shea Stadium against the Expos. Last month the Mets took
two of three interleague games from Boston but could not capitalize
on 13 consecutive games against expansion Tampa Bay (of the
American League Least), the Marlins and the Expos. They won 6, lost
7.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine is right about one aspect of games against the weaker
teams: nothing is automatic. That's why they play the games. But
that does not mean the contending teams should not expect and be
expected to win the bulk of those games.
</P>
<P>
   While the Mets were struggling to a 7-12 record against the NL
Least in June and July, the Chicago Cubs amassed 13 victories in 17
games with the Marlins, the Pirates, the Diamondbacks and the
Expos. That's a seven-game difference in the standing between two
wild-card rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Reverse the records against the NL Least _ make the Mets 12-7,
the Cubs 4-13 _ and the wild-card standing would look drastically
different today. It would be the Mets ahead of the Cubs by a
whopping 10{ games instead of trailing the Cubs by 3{.
</P>
<P>
   If only the Mets' part of the wild-card equation were reversed,
if the Mets had won 12 of those 19 June-July games, they would lead
the Cubs by a game and a half.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Giants are half a game ahead of the Mets in
the race for the fourth spot in the NL playoffs. They have
benefited from games against the NL Least, winning 22 of 30.
Philadelphia is in the wild-card race with the help of 11 victories
in their last 12 games against the NL Least.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the Mets lost two games to the Braves and
evenly split four-game series with the Phillies and the Cubs. The
outcome of none of those series was surprising. The Mets are not
good enough to dominate any of those teams. But that reality makes
it all the more imperative for them to dominate the teams they
should beat, Valentine's view notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have only 14 games remaining with teams in the NL Least
so they basically have squandered their best chance to gain ground
in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Now they will have to win it the old-fashioned way. They will
have to earn it by beating good or, at least, competitive teams. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 0022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
