<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5672 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-ASSUMESCU     07-28 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-ASSUMES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS HOPE FOR WILD FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 CUBS VICTORY TONIGHT-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It will be hot and sticky tonight on the floor of
Veterans Stadium, but the Dodgers better get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   With two months remaining in the 1998 season, the Dodgers are a
part of the heated National League wild-card race at 5{ games
behind the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   And with four days to baseball's trading deadline, it also could
mean a deal for a starting pitcher to replace Ismael Valdes. The
right-hander will miss two starts with a strained left side.
</P>
<P>
   From the less-than-overwhelming crowds during the past two home
stands, it appears fans have not bought into the concept of the
wild card, which rewards the team with the fourth-best record to
qualify for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   But it means so much to the Dodgers that new general manager Tom
Lasorda was boasting at the Hall of Fame weekend in Cooperstown
that his club will be playing in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee we're going to make the playoffs,'' Lasorda said.
``I told our players that, and I believe it. I told them we would
catch the Giants, and we have. Now we're going to catch the Cubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda's future as general manager probably depends on that,
which is why he will be busy working the phones this week.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects the Dodgers to overtake the division-leading San
Diego Padres, who lead them by 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox, the new ownership, has not been as quick as Lasorda to
guarantee that anyone in the front office will be back next season.
</P>
<P>
   And the Dodgers haven't exactly caught the Giants, who fell out
of the top spot after a 1-8 road trip to start the second half. The
Giants trail Chicago by 3{ games and are a half-game ahead of the
New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are entering a critical stretch. The first seven
games on this road trip are against the Phillies and Mets, two
teams ahead of the Dodgers for the wild card.
</P>
<P>
   Races, even wild-card races, rarely are won in head-to-head
matchups, making the nine games that follow so important.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers close the trip with three games in Montreal, where
they traditionally do not play well. Then they come home for six
games against lowly Pittsburgh and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really haven't taken off yet,'' center fielder Raul Mondesi
said. ``Looks like now is the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Dodgers have won nine of their past 14, they still
have not won four in a row this season. They dropped two of seven
on the just-completed home stand, but both were difficult losses.
</P>
<P>
   The team will be tested further now that it has lost Valdes, who
was placed on the 15-day disabled list Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think with their pitching the Dodgers cannot be
counted out of any race,'' said St. Louis manager Tony La Russa,
whose team split with the Dodgers two weeks ago. ``It's great for a
team to be able to throw that many good arms at an opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   The wild card, which began in 1995 when the leagues were
expanded to three divisions, has a far different look for the
Dodgers this season.
</P>
<P>
   The first year, they won the West by a game over the Colorado
Rockies, who qualified as the wild card.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Dodgers lost the division title on the final
weekend of the season when they were swept by the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the front office thought the Dodgers lost that year
because there was little incentive to win. They still qualified for
the wild card, although they had to play the eventual National
League champion Atlanta Braves in the first round and were swept in
three games.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Dodgers finished out of the playoffs. The Florida
Marlins, the wild-card team, won 93 games during the regular
season, beat first-place Atlanta in the playoffs and went on to win
the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we showed, we were a great team,'' said the Dodgers' Bobby
Bonilla, who played with the Marlins last season. ``We beat the
Braves all year. This year you don't see real races except maybe
with Houston and the Cubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Some managers accept their wild-card fate. Others refuse to
acknowledge that second place is all that is left.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be realistic,'' Giants manager Dusty Baker said.
``If we get to within five games of the Padres, that's great. Then
we'll think about that. But get real. The race is for the wild
card.''
</P>
<P>
   Mets manager Bobby Valentine disagrees. He saw how quickly
everything can change last weekend. His club moved within 1{ games
of the Cubs before losing two in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran track in high school and learned a valuable lesson,'' he
said. ``When you reach a turn, concentrate on that one and not the
next one. Why should I limit myself to saying we're only in this
for the wild card? We're in this to win the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman, 18-13 since taking over for Bill
Russell on June 22, knows the wild card is his only chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been going a day at a time since I've been here, and
we've started to move a little,'' Hoffman said. ``That's what
matters. We're in a good spot right now, but we have to play
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 0031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5676 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-VALDES-LA     07-28 0274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-VALDES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALDES PUT ON 15-DAY DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dodgers right-hander Ismael Valdes was placed on
the 15-day disabled list Monday with a strained oblique and
intestinal muscle on the left side.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes suffered the injury in Sunday's win over the Arizona
Diamondbacks. He was replaced on the roster by Sean Maloney, whose
contract was purchased from Triple-A Albuquerque. Valdes' spot in
the rotation goes to rookie Mike Judd, who was promoted from
Albuquerque last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He strained his left oblique, and he's missing the next two
starts,'' head trainer Charlie Strasser said. ``But right now
that's all we know. He stayed in L.A. and will be working with
therapist Pat Screnar. We'll just have to watch his progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes (9-9, 3.92 ERA) won his third consecutive start Sunday
but left after throwing two pitches in the sixth inning. Valdes
leads the Dodgers with complete two games and 1432/3 innings
pitched. He is tied for the team lead in victories with Chan Ho
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes said Sunday that he never had back problems during his
career. His only other appearance on the DL was from July 10-28 in
1997 with a strained left hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers signed Maloney, 27, to a minor-league contract on
March 20. At Albuquerque, he was 2-1 with a 4.30 ERA and nine saves
in 22 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney spent time last season at Triple-A Tucson and Milwaukee.
With the Brewers, he was 0-0 with a 5.14 ERA in three appearances
before undergoing surgery on his right shoulder Aug. 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
