<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5680 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOL-HNS &LR;      07-28 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   Floyd quickly sees &QL; 
dark side of NBA
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IT has been nearly a week since Chicago Bulls general manager Jerry
Krause installed Tim Floyd as director of basketball operations,
and as yet there has been no white-smoked puff of approval from the
residence of either the Pope or Michael Jordan, who, with the
exception of the beanie, are regarded in many quarters as being
identical in infallibility.
</P>
<P>
   There is no surprise in Jordan's reticence to comment, since it
is obviously more fun for the King of the NBA to keep Krause
squirming and wriggling before Bulls fans like a millipede having
its legs removed with a dull butter knife.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, we already know Jordan's opinion of the erstwhile head
coach of the Iowa State Cyclones. In conversations with friends and
reporters alike, he has referred to the new man on the job
derisively as ``Pink,'' as in the rock group Pink Floyd. All in
all, it's just another brick in the wall of contempt that His
Airness has constructed between himself and team management.
</P>
<P>
   The assumption is that by giving Floyd only the title of
director of basketball operations and not naming him as the new
head coach, the Bulls are hoping that Jordan will acquiesce on his
threats to retire again and actually get to know and come to
respect the new man as Phil Jackson's successor. Then, sometime
between now and November _ or whenever the knuckleheads on both
sides of the NBA labor dispute settle their differences _ Floyd can
be given the reins to the Bulls' bench.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Jordan might go out and hug a porcupine like it was
Ahmad Rashad before that happens.
</P>
<P>
   A stack of reasons to return
</P>
<P>
   However, there are several reasons why Jordan might not want to
go public, not the least of which is his desire to play basketball
next season, and the only place he can be paid his going rate of
$36 million or more per season is right there in Chicago, where
Krause and team owner Jerry Reinsdorf still control the purse
strings.
</P>
<P>
   There is also Jordan's current position as one of the unofficial
leaders of the NBA Players Association. If he were to simply
denounce Floyd and say he is retiring this minute, a Jordan-less
union would be minus one very big hammer in its negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is another possibility: Jordan is waiting for Floyd
to show up at his front door on bended knee and kiss his, ah, ring.
</P>
<P>
   The more puzzling question in the soap opera is why Floyd would
have been thrust into this no-win situation by his good pal Krause.
</P>
<P>
   There is an inevitability to the end of any dynasty, and to be
put in charge of the dying days is like being given a spotlight
dance on the Titanic. From a practical standpoint, fans, players
and management all know that the end is inevitable and expectation
levels must be lowered.
</P>
<P>
   But emotionally, that never happens. When close games become
painful defeats, when losses begin to pile up, there is always a
rush to find the guilty party. And while much of the blame will
rightfully fall on the heads of Krause and Reinsdorf if the makeup
of the team is different next season, Floyd, too, will catch flak.
Wrongly.
</P>
<P>
   Footsteps are hard to follow
</P>
<P>
   If Krause truly believes that the 44-year-old Floyd is the right
man to lead the Bulls into the next millennium, then it makes no
sense to serve him up now as a sacrificial lamb. And history says
that is exactly what he will be _ Gene Bartow following John Wooden
at UCLA, Dan Devine following Ara Parseghian at Notre Dame, Camilla
Parker-Bowles following Princess Di at Buckingham Palace, unable to
measure up to the record or the myth. In the NBA, the last three
sinking dynasties to change coaches saw Ron Rothstein in Detroit,
Jimmy Rodgers in Boston and Mike Dunleavy in LA all gone after no
more than two years on the job.
</P>
<P>
   For any coach who comes from the outside, this a job that stands
on a trapdoor. Much of the Zen phony Jackson's popularity in recent
years had to do with his public feud with Krause. He was shrewd to
cultivate an ``us-against-them'' attitude that reeled in Jordan and
Scottie Pippen and forged the team.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to keep that air is to maintain continuity. That
would mean naming one of the current assistants, Frank Hamblen or
Bill Cartwright, as the new head coach. The Bulls could keep right
on running the triangle offense of the venerable Tex Winter, and
Jordan could keep right on running the whole show.
</P>
<P>
   The dynasty could run its course, Jordan could retire in a year
or two, and then Floyd could move in as head coach for a fresh
start.
</P>
<P>
   The end of an era is never pretty. But it doesn't have to
include the blood of an innocent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
