<HEADER>
A5681 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-WORLD-U.S.-HNS &LR;      07-28 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-WORLD-U.S.-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Team USA 
braces for 
Greek fans
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flying projectiles just &QL; 
part of Athens game
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATHENS, Greece _ Greek fans are legendary for their zest in
supporting the local sporting arts.
</P>
<P>
   Impassioned doesn't begin to describe them. They don't just blur
the lines of good sportsmanship. They erase them and draw up all
new rules of etiquette. And Rule No. 1 is: Anything goes.
</P>
<P>
   If the U.S. basketball team that begins play in the Federation
Internationale de Basketball Association World Championships on
Wednesday included such recognizable names as Grant Hill, Gary
Payton and Tim Duncan, perhaps the team might be spared some of the
wrath of the Greeks.
</P>
<P>
   But without NBA players, who undoubtedly would command more
respect, the Americans don't expect any preferential treatment from
the home fans in this country, which has been smitten with hoops
fever. When the 16-team World Championships begin at the Olympic
Stadium and the Peace and Friendship arena, these fans will do
anything they can get away with to help their team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't believe the hatred the opposing crowd will have
for us,'' says David Wood, who played a season for the team in
Greece that uses Olympic Stadium as its home court. ``When you go
someplace, if they can get you in an alley and beat your face in,
they would do it. They truly hate the visiting team, especially in
the playoffs. They'll try to hit you in the face with coins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything they can throw at you, they will. It's weird. In
America, you might get some hecklers who want to hurt your feelings
and have you look at them so they can smile and joke with their
beer-drinking buddies. But they don't want to kill you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played in Thessalonika one year, and they throw everything
they can get their hands on. I've been on the court when it's been
like machine-gun fire with the coins hitting the floor at such a
rapid pace. After the game, the janitor had a pocketful of coins.
And Greek coins are big. They're like big 50-cent pieces. They'll
probably have to have at least 500 armed guards at the games just
to keep the fans under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Horror stories like these often don't come to pass. And the
Americans will have one thing going for them: They won't play the
Greeks until at least the quarterfinals, assuming both make the top
eight.
</P>
<P>
   But several of the American players have played in Europe and
agree this tournament will feature the rowdiest fans in all of
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of heckling, a lot of `USA go home,' and a lot of
anti-American sentiment, that's what we'll get,'' said Wendell
Alexis, a 10-year veteran of European basketball. ``I think we're
going to get a lot of disrespect, but I think that most
importantly, we just have to go out there and win every game and
not worry about the other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all about winning at this tournament. And even though NBA
players aren't involved, the U.S. still is a strong candidate for a
medal and most insiders believe they have a decent shot at the
gold. But they will have to beat not only Yugoslavia and Australia
and Greece but the Greek fans as well. The Greek players are well
aware how rabid their fans are.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to improve on our (fourth-place) finish in the 1994
World Championships,'' said Panagiotis Fassoulas, a Greek center.
``Our fans won't accept anything less.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans know how tough it's going to be. Most of them have
played in Europe before and know all too well about the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can be very tough,'' says Michael Hawkins, whose
Olympiakos team last season used one of the World Championships
venues, the Olympic Stadium, as its home floor. ``As Americans, we
wouldn't dream of throwing objects on the floor and trying to harm
the other team or even the referees or their own team. But they
have no control. They're tough fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Jimmy Oliver: ``I know some of the European cities have
really rowdy crowds. They get to the point where they are throwing
cigarette lighters and money and toilet paper. It can get
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   And not just for the visitors. Alexis has hopscotched across
Europe in his pro career, and he has learned that fans will turn on
their own team if things aren't going well.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the opposing team, the underdog team, comes in and starts
kicking butt, things turn very quickly in an international game,''
Alexis says. ``If there's an upset or their team is not doing well,
things can get very ugly quickly. The idea is not to let the home
team and home crowd get going. It can be really tough on the
visiting team if that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   But as much as the Americans are prepared for the worst as the
tournament prepares to open, they also are wary of just how
difficult the atmosphere could be. This tournament, dubbed
WorldBasket '98 in Europe, is the most coveted gold medal of all
for teams on this continent, even surpassing the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The Greeks will be in rare form when it comes to distracting
everybody but their team. And especially so for the Americans,
since the fans here were hoping for NBA stars but were delivered
replacement players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking about it and experiencing it are two different
things,'' Rudy Tomjanovich says. ``We all know it's going to be
crazy. I just hope we can keep our composure and play smart when it
gets wild.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
