<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5682 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      07-28 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Stop us if you've heard this one before _ you know, the one about
how the Astros fare against pitchers they've never faced.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someone forgot to brief Florida Marlins rookie Brian Meadows,
who just happened to be on the mound on a night when the Astros'
offense felt like taking out some frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros beat up on Meadows and fellow rookie Ryan Dempster on
their way to a 9-1 victory over the Marlins on Monday night before
a scattered crowd of 20,888 at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last couple of years, the Astros have had their share
of problems against new pitchers. In fact, the last time they were
in the Dome, Colorado Rockies rookie Mark Brownson fired a four-hit
shutout against them.
</P>
<P>
   That game sent the Astros on the road with a bad taste in their
mouths, and their buds weren't exactly satisfied by the 2-3 West
Coast road trip. Whether it was home cooking or easy prey, the
Astros feasted on the carcass of the defending World Series
champions.
</P>
<P>
   Former Marlin Moises Alou was 4-for-4, tying his career high for
hits in a game. He smacked his 26th homer and paced the Astros'
14-hit attack. Derek Bell and Jeff Bagwell each homered and drove
in three runs.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Lima held the Marlins to six hits and tossed his second
complete game of the season. The Astros gave Lima all the runs he
needed and then some with a five-run outburst in the first that
silenced anyone who thought this would be another big night for an
opposing rookie pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other people may think that way, but I guarantee you none of
our hitters think that way,'' Bagwell said. ``We don't feel like
anyone is going to get us out consistently. If we score four runs,
people around here think we stink. No matter how many runs we
score, the bottom line is that we're going after wins. That's all
that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   They should have plenty of opportunities to pile up victories
over the next nine days. The stripped-down Marlins are in town for
three more days before the Astros leave on a six-game road trip to
Pittsburgh and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for us to play for a week or so and be on top
of our game,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``We need to
prove to ourselves that we're the kind of team our record says we
are.''
</P>
<P>
   What better time to have the schedule stacked with the Marlins
and Pirates?
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper, we should be able to win some games,'' Bagwell said.
``But you know baseball. The Marlins took three of four from the
Braves, and they're very capable of beating you.''
</P>
<P>
   But they haven't proved that to the Astros, who have won each of
their first three games against the Marlins this season. Alou has
played a major part in the early dominance, going 8-for-11 (.727)
at the plate against his former team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of thing should happen more often with the type of
lineup we have,'' Alou said. ``We've been in a little team slump
lately, but it was nice to score those five runs early and give
Lima some support. He pitched a hell of a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Meadows, who made his first appearance at the Astrodome, didn't
have much time to get comfortable with the surroundings. He hit
Craig Biggio with his first pitch of the game and proceeded to
allow the next four Astros to return the favor.
</P>
<P>
   After Bill Spiers and Bell singled, Bagwell drove them home with
a towering three-run homer to left. It was his 22nd home run of the
season. Alou followed with a first-pitch homer into the
general-admission seats in left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you can put up a five-spot in the first inning,
that's obviously a good thing,'' Bagwell said. ``It was nice to
have that cushion.''
</P>
<P>
   Meadows retired nine of the next 11 batters he faced, before his
misery was resumed in the fifth. The Astros opened the inning with
five consecutive hits, including an RBI double by Spiers and
run-producing singles by Bell and Alou. Meadows left the game
because of a strained right groin after Spiers' double.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's 15th homer, a leadoff shot in the seventh, ended the
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very aggressive,'' said Bell, who was 3-for-4.
``Sometimes when we face guys we haven't seen, we let them bring it
to us instead of taking it to them. Tonight, we took it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The only Marlin who scored never should have reached base. Cliff
Floyd led off the fifth with an infield pop-up that dropped between
Biggio and shortstop Ricky Gutierrez. Floyd scored from third on
Mike Redmond's double-play ball.
</P>
<P>
   Lima retired the first 11 It was the fewest runs he has allowed
since June 6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
