<HEADLINE>
YOUNG _ ACTOR, FATHER, FRIEND, ICON _ LAID TO REST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LEE CONDON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Calif. _ Actor Robert Young was remembered as ``an
icon of American fatherhood'' at a memorial service held at Forest
Lawn Memorial Park in Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   Best known for his roles as perfect dad Jim Anderson on the
1950s sitcom ``Father Knows Best'' and as a trusted physician on
``Marcus Welby, M.D.,'' Young died Wednesday at 91 at his home in
Westlake Village.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder how many people wish they had a father like the one
on `Father Knows Best,''' said the Rev. Jim Obermeyer, who led the
service Monday at the Little Church of the Flowers at Forest Lawn
in Glendale north of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost much of the innocence of that era when `Father
Knows Best' aired,'' said Obermeyer of the Christ the King Church
in Santa Clarita. ``America needs those values now.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1954 through 1960, Young's Jim Anderson dispensed fatherly
advice to his three children, Princess, Bud and Kitten, all of whom
faced a different moral dilemma for their father to solve each
week.
</P>
<P>
   Later, from 1969 through 1976, he became a role model for
doctors across America when he took on the part of ``Marcus Welby,
M.D.'' Instead of helping Princess cope with prom stress, this time
around he offered comfort to the sick and dying.
</P>
<P>
   At the service Monday, his daughter Carol Proffitt remembered
her father as her own ``Papa,'' of getting her first pony as a gift
and of spying on his Saturday night poker games with Lucille Ball
and Desi Arnaz.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Proffitt, Young is survived by three other daughters.
Young's wife, Betty, died in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Wyatt, who played Young's wife, Margaret, on ``Father Knows
Best,'' said her co-star was a ``wonderful actor.'' Their TV
marriage was a happy one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked together six years,'' Wyatt said as she left the
memorial service. ``In all those six years we never had a cross
word with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Gray, the actor who played Bud on ``Father Knows Best''
also attended the service. Gray, now 60, said on TV Young counseled
his children each week on the show but in real-life he ``wasn't
into giving advice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5685 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI &LR;      07-28 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD PRO MOON LACKS LEVERAGE OF ROOKIE LEAF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Warren Moon and his super-agent, Leigh Steinberg, have
spent the summer crying foul at the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   They claim Paul Allen's slush-fund franchise has under-budgeted
for the quarterback position by about $4 or $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Moon won't accept the Seahawks' explanation that the
Hawks have no cap room to pay their starting quarterback want he
wants.
</P>
<P>
   Show Moon the money?
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks seem like they're leaning toward showing Moon the
door.
</P>
<P>
   Like Shawn Kemp's divorce tiff with the Sonics, in which Kemp
went nuts over the Sonics' 1996 summer spending spree on free
agents, Moon and Steinberg suggest it was the Seahawks'
responsibility to clear cap room.
</P>
<P>
   That way, the Hawks could make a new deal, two or three years in
duration, to ``take care of Warren Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   This explains why Moon is working out somewhere with a personal
trainer while his teammates sweat through two-a-days in sunny
Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the proverbial twist of the knife: It can't make
matters any easier for Moon now that the Chargers have made rookie
quarterback Ryan Leaf a very rich man _ if you consider an NFL
contract worth $31 million to be really big bucks.
</P>
<P>
   A rookie with nothing on his resume but a ton of promise gets a
bundle of dough.
</P>
<P>
   A future Hall of Fame quarterback gets a phone and fax machine
that still won't ring with an improved offer from Seahawks' vice
president Randy Mueller.
</P>
<P>
   The Moon-Seahawks' standoff has reached nine days. No one is
budging.
</P>
<P>
   Not the Seahawks, who have offered $2 million, plus $1.6 million
in incentives.
</P>
<P>
   And not Moon, who wants a three-year, $15 million deal that
includes a $6 million signing bonus. Last week, Moon told reporters
he would be willing to settle for a two-year deal worth $7-8
million, but he hasn't told the club that.
</P>
<P>
   It cannot help one bit that the tall kid with the cannon arm who
took Washington State to the Rose Bowl for the first time in 67
years could now fill his swimming pool full of dollar bills.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just from his signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers, who already traded away players and draft picks
galore just for the right to draft Leaf, have just given Leaf an
unprecedented lump sum of $11.25 million, just for being Ryan Leaf.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of Matchbox 20 CDs and chicken enchiladas, two of
Leaf's favorite things.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Moon believes he should get similar high-priority
treatment, simply for being Warren Moon.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where Moon is mistaken. That is where he has little
clout or leverage, especially on a team where he has played only
one season. He is a short-term, short-time solution for the
Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing Moon's career in pro football to what Ryan Leaf might
do is like comparing apples and oranges.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't the same thing. Moon's value is only what the
Seahawks will pay him. Leaf's value is what the Chargers will pay
him, which could top out at $5 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the Chargers took a gamble trading away so much and
committing so much cash to Leaf, although it's a gamble the
Chargers had to take.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the Colts now will be lavishing more money on Peyton
Manning, drafted No. 1 ahead of Leaf.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFL, the chance for a team to draft a top-rated
quarterback around whom you bank on building your franchise is the
most dramatic and most expensive move you can make, more than
hiring a general manager or coach.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf and Manning are not only the arm of the future, they are
the face and the marketing tool to sell tickets, jerseys and
TV/radio ad time.
</P>
<P>
   The reward for these sorts of monster rookie deals can be just
as awesome as the risk.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Drew Bledsoe and Rick Mirer were the top two picks in
the NFL draft. Both were franchise-saviors. Both were lavished with
monster contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer's deal was so cleverly constructed, the Seahawks wound up
paying Mirer an additional $2 million, even after it was clear
Mirer was not going to cut it. But Mirer had the leverage because
his contract included some nebulous incentive clauses, which Mirer
reached and the Hawks were forced to pay.
</P>
<P>
   At least in New England, the Patriots got their money's worth in
Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, the key to these blockbuster rookie quarterback deals
is time.
</P>
<P>
   The signing bonuses and incentives are spread out over several
years. Leaf and Manning have at least that to offer their new
employers. Time is on their side to make the huge investment
somewhat palatable.
</P>
<P>
   Moon does not have that luxury. Moon, who will turn 42 in
November, lacks the one thing necessary to structure such a
high-priced deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks are unwilling to enter into any deal that commits
money to Moon that would extend their financial obligation to him
beyond this single season.
</P>
<P>
   That's not as much ageism as it is practical salary cap-ology.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
