<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO PROBLEMS WITH WATTERS; SEAHAWKS EMBRACE HIS INTENSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY _ One question: Who is that wearing No. 32 at the
Seahawks' training camp?
</P>
<P>
   The roster lists him as Ricky Watters. The face inside the
helmet looks like Ricky Watters. When teammates and coaches call
that name, the guy in the No. 32 jersey answers.
</P>
<P>
   But it just can't be Ricky Watters.
</P>
<P>
   When the Seahawks signed him as a free agent in March, Watters
checked in with more personal baggage than the touring cast of
Cats.
</P>
<P>
   Watters has tried to say and do all the right things, but has
not been able to run from the ghosts of his previous stints with
the San Francisco 49ers and Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   He's selfish, one critic points out. He's a malcontent, another
chimes in. He's a human time bomb who is wound too tight and could
go off at any moment over any number of things, others predict.
</P>
<P>
   Well, nine days and 14 practices into training camp, and three
days shy of the Seahawks' preseason opener at Dallas, Watters has
displayed none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've see nothing but the best out of Ricky, and I've been
pleasantly surprised by how hard he works,'' fullback Mack Strong
offered. ``Ricky Watters has been the hardest worker at each of the
camps we've had _ the minicamps and now in training camp. It just
goes to show you can't always listen to what you hear or believe
everything you read about a guy.''
</P>
<P>
   As for that capital ``I'' that is supposed to be the focal point
of Watters' first name, linebacker Darrin Smith shakes his head at
even the suggestion. Smith and Watters were teammates in
Philadelphia last season and bitter rivals in 1993 and 1994, when
Watters was with the 49ers and Smith was playing for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got to Philadelphia, there was a negative perception of
Ricky in a lot of people's minds,'' Smith said. ``What I saw was a
guy who wants to win. What's wrong with that?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Michael Jordan. You would never hear Michael Jordan
say, `No, let him take the (game-winning) shot.' No, Michael says,
`Gimme the ball,''' Smith said. ``That's Ricky. He wants the ball
with the game on the line. It's a desire to get it done. I want to
play with players like that.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Watters goes at interviews the same way he runs
toward holes in the offensive line _ with quickness, exuberance and
no fear.
</P>
<P>
   No questions are off limits, including those about his past and
the problems his frankness have created.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I'm tired of trying to defend myself,''
Watters said. ``If you already have a slanted view of somebody, it
doesn't matter what they do because you're already looking at them
like, `I don't like him.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I have people come up to me and say, `I love the way you are,
don't change a thing.' Then I'm going to have the people who say,
`I don't think you should do that.'''
</P>
<P>
   No one has ever questioned Watters' talent. He has averaged
1,105 yards rushing and 50 receptions in his first six seasons and
been voted to five Pro Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   And he sounds content to be one of the guys, rather than the
guy, on his new team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're going to remake the offense around me,''
he said. ``They were the No. 1 passing offense last year, and they
were in the top half of the league in rushing, so it's already
here. The nucleus is here. I'm just going to try and fit in and
help this team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Can this be the same guy who ruffled egos by complaining about
not getting the ball enough on a 49ers team that included Steve
Young and Jerry Rice? Can this be the same player who ignited a
thunderstorm of negativity in Philadelphia in 1995 by failing to
extend for a pass over the middle at the end of a blowout loss and
then tried to explain it by asking, ``For who? For what?''?
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks did extensive research into Watters' troubled past
before signing him to a four-year, $13 million deal. Their
conclusion was that each of the incidents that have become such a
large part of the Watters' legacy was related to his wanting to win
and a feeling that he can help a team do that only if he has the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to say that I'm an emotional player, that's
true,'' Watters said. ``That I'm a fiery competitor? That's true.
Do I want to win every game I'm in? Yes. Do I want to do well? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can do is play my game and be the person I am.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good. And then some.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
