<HEADLINE>
L.A. CHARMS DEMOCRATS IN BID FOR 2000 CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With mariachis, a helicopter cruise over the city
and a tour of Universal Studios, Los Angeles officials began wooing
52 Democratic Party officials who will determine the site of their
party's 2000 national convention.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way Monday, city, business and union officials
announced that they have solved potential labor problems that could
have scuttled the city's selection and cost it 30,000 visitors and
an estimated $137 million boost to the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   With the Los Angeles unity show lined up, even the weather
cooperated to an extent. A cooling breeze blew through the historic
Olvera Street Plaza, easing the high-90s temperatures just as Mayor
Richard Riordan, city, county, state and federal officials staged a
``Heritage of Welcome'' for the delegates and about 300 other
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Italics) Yo quiero (end italics) DNC,'' Riordan chanted at
one point. ``Los Angeles is a city that has what it takes to host
the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will find everything you need in L.A., the city of the
next millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Gloria Molina sought to counter the historical
arguments being made by cities such as Boston and Philadelphia by
citing California's history as well as its history of being active
in Democratic politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the election of John F. Kennedy (nominated at the 1960
convention in Los Angeles) that inspired so many of us to be a
Democrat,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members said they weren't bothered by the hot weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think this is hot? I'm from Louisiana and that's hot,''
committee member Ben Jeffers said.
</P>
<P>
   Vice Chair Yolanda Caraway said heat would not be a factor in
the final decision among the seven contending cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be in July and it will be hot everywhere,'' Caraway
said. ``What's more important is if it's the right city.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee member Kiki Moore said her concern is with how much
the city wants the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the city really wants it, when problems come up, it means
they will be solved,'' Moore said. ``I want to see the city's
enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is a political aspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``California has 54 electoral votes and everyone is aware of its
importance,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, officials from the Staples Center
sports arena said they have resolved any potential problems with
the Hotel and Restaurant Employees Local 11. Union officials had
threatened to picket during the convention tour if the arena did
not sign a long-term contract to employ its members. The union
wanted an arena neutrality agreement, which would allow workers to
join a union and allow Local 11 to represent them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an understanding with the union,'' said Tim Leiwecke,
who is in charge of overseeing the construction of the $300 million
facility. ``We recognize the importance of labor peace and are
going to have a longstanding agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Elena Durazo, president of the union, did not return
telephone calls. But those close to the sides said a session is
planned this morning to resolve issues.
</P>
<P>
   Labor peace is important to Democrats, who have a policy that
prevents them from meeting in nonunion facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, one of the other six cities seeking the
convention, was forced to delay its meeting with the site selection
committee earlier this month because of a transit strike. Committee
members refused to leave an airport because it would mean crossing
picket lines.
</P>
<P>
   The real work for the city comes today, when officials make a
formal presentation in a morning session at the Convention Center.
Later in the day, subcommittees of the panel will meet privately
with local officials to discuss specifics regarding logistics,
facilities, hotel rooms, security, transportation and other
factors.
</P>
<P>
   But, the parties for the committee will continue. Among the
events is a semi-private reception at Riordan's personal residence
as well as a tour of the Getty Center and a late-night party hosted
by actor Jimmy Smits.
</P>
<P>
   And some observers said such glitz could have an impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Los Angeles, after all,'' political analyst Susan
Estrich said. ``I'd have to say this is for Los Angeles to lose.
Most everyone feels it is Los Angeles' turn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
