<SLUG> BC-GOLF-MERIDIAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLFERS SHARE LAUGHS DURING USOC FUND-RAISER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENT, Wash. _ Peter Jacobsen tees it up and yuks it up at the
same time. You might know him as the fun-loving PGA golfer from
Portland who has won six tournaments in his 22-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Jacobsen was an instructor and an impersonator,
providing lessons and laughs during the Merrill Lynch Invitational
at Meridian Valley Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Along with LPGA star Michelle McGann, Jacobsen headlined the
fund-raising event for the United States Olympic Committee. Joining
the two golfers were former Olympians Mark Spitz, Mike Eruzione and
Seattle's Debbie Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen, who earned $35,000 for his appearance, and McGann
conducted a clinic on the driving range before playing in a charity
skins match. Jacobsen added levity to the proceedings, firing at
flagsticks and Canadians, the latter shots being playful ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ya know the difference between a canoe and a Canuck?'' he
asked about 200 spectators in the bleachers. ``A canoe will tip.''
</P>
<P>
   When Eruzione, captain of the 1980 gold medal-winning U.S.
hockey team, stepped onto the driving range, Jacobsen checked him
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you an American?'' Jacobsen wondered as he inspected
Eruzione's mouth. ``Most Canadians have more toes than teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Jacobsen delivered his best material, imitating the quirky
characteristics of fellow golfers Johnny Miller, Lee Trevino, Gary
Player, Arnold Palmer and Craig Stadler.
</P>
<P>
   Stadler's ritual is his favorite. Jacobsen talks about Stadler's
rear end and says the Walrus actually looks more like ``the
refrigerator repair guy.'' McGann emptied a bucketful of range
balls into Jacobsen's shirt to better represent Stadler's lumpy
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's clinic and skins game raised $90,000 for the USOC. The
Invitational continues today with a junior golf clinic at 10 a.m.
followed by a nine-hole celebrity shootout featuring Curt Warner,
Jack Sikma, Don James, Spitz and Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   SAHALEE SPECTACLE: Jacobsen said next month's PGA Championship
at Sahalee Country Club will be well-received, in large part
because of Seattle's supposedly cooler weather. Other PGA
Championships have been held in pressure cookers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually you're sweating all the way down through your
underwear,'' said Jacobsen, who did not qualify to play at Sahalee
but picks Colin Montgomerie to win the tournament. ``It's not a
pleasurable feeling. Players love the Pacific Northwest. They are
going to push to come back and play more here.''
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Championship could be the start of an annual tradition.
The PGA Tour plans to return here next year with a tournament stop
at the Jack Nicklaus-designed Snoqualmie Ridge. Dates have been
awarded in July, the week after the British Open. A sponsor is now
needed.
</P>
<P>
   LATEST SENSATION: McGann, who is known for her long drives and
wide-brimmed hats, talked about another popular golfer, Se Ri Pak,
the 20-year-old South Korean who has won three of the last four
LPGA tournaments and is the favorite at this week's du Maurier
Classic in Windsor, Ontario. Pak will play at the Safeco Classic at
Meridian Valley in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her impact on tour has been awesome,'' McGann said. ``We're
all learning quite a bit from her. She doesn't seem to be bothered
by anything.''
</P>
<P>
   SWIMMING ALONG: Spitz, who won seven gold medals in swimming in
the '72 Olympics, looked fit at 48. His hair is graying and his
moustache is gone. He lives in L.A. and still swims in the UCLA
masters program. ``It's an organized workout,'' Spitz said. ``I
can't aimlessly swim.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitz and his wife of 25 years have two sons, 6 and 16. Neither
child swims competitively.
</P>
<P>
   Spitz stays busy now with his own business. He co-founded Smart
Talk Teleservices, a phone card company.
</P>
<P>
   After looking at his swing on the driving range, you could say
Spitz still has his best strokes in the pool.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
