 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, July 28.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MILITARY (Beijing) _ A look at China's military and the
changes it is undergoing. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-TRIBUNAL-RAPE (The Hague) _ A rape case before the Balkan
tribunal has drawn much attention from lawyers and women's and
human rights groups. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-CANOES (Peterborough, Ontario) _ Like other men who have
dipped paddles into dark, clear waters and felt the soulful
satisfaction of gliding through perfect silence, John Jennings has
been captivated by canoes. He has been that way since he was a boy,
and he can think of few things better than to enter the northern
wilderness with four weeks of supplies in a 16-foot canoe and
simply disappear. For more than 15 years, Jennings has pursued an
obsessive, some might think odd, dream that has made his treasured
wilderness outings rare. A bookish, soft-spoken college professor
whose enthusiasm for Canadian history is matched only by his
passion for the fine elegance of canoes, Jennings has devoted
himself to founding a museum dedicated to the Canadian canoe. By
Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SWEEPSTAKES-ELDERLY-I (Vero Beach, Fla.) _ Across the country,
people are fooled every day into believing they have won
sweepstakes and other contests, misled by attention-grabbing
graphics and official-sounding language. Most people understand
that these pitches are come-ons to buy magazines and other
products. But from big cities to the nation's Sun Cities, the
mailboxes that fill fastest are those that belong to the elderly.
And all too often the people who believe the sophisticated pitches
and spend large sums they cannot afford on hundreds of magazine
subscriptions or on other goods they do not want are elderly, too.
By Douglas Frantz. (First of two articles.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT12,13) have been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-WESTON-MENTALHEALTH (Undated) _ Russell Weston chose an
unusually public place, but he appears to have a great deal in
common with other delusional mentally ill people who become
violent, illustrating the gaping cracks in the nation's
mental-health network. His illness was well-known to family, mental
health officials and even federal authorities, but because of the
closing of state mental hospitals, the treatment of choice for him
was the honor system: counting on him to take the often unpleasant
psychoactive drugs prescribed for his schizophrenia. He lived in
rural areas, where psychiatric monitoring of him was extremely
limited. And he traveled between two states, encouraging at least
one to solve his long-term care by sending him back to the other.
By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   NADER-MUSEUM (Winsted, Conn.) _ Ralph Nader wants to open a
Museum of Tort Law in his hometown, complete with exhibits on
Corvairs and Pintos. By Jonathan Rabinovitz.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo
[NYT17) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR-ASSESS _ An examination of the legal issues
involved in issuing a subpoena for the president to testify before
a grand jury. By Linda Greenhouse
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FLOWER-DISTRIBUTION (Miami) _ USA Floral Products wants to take
the floral-distribution business along the consolidation route
recently traveled by the automobile, office-supply, video-rental
and equipment-leasing businesses. Its plan is to buy up small,
independent distributors, wholesalers and bouquet makers, and
consolidate such operations as accounting, finance, insurance and
employee benefits. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT9,16) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-ECON-OBUCHI (Hong Kong) _ Japanese voters are not the only
people who reacted tepidly to the election of Keizo Obuchi as the
leader of Japan's governing party. The choice of Obuchi has
deflated many in the rest of Asia, who were hoping that a forceful
new leader would step up to recharge Japan's weak economy and
repair its faltering financial system. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   TROSTER-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ National Association of
Securities Dealers Regulation Inc. censured and fined Troster
Singer Corp. for fraud in connection with a series of 28
intentional Nasdaq trade reporting violations in 1994. In settling
with the NASD, the firm neither admitted nor denied the regulator's
findings; but it agreed to pay $950,000. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   WOLF-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Larry Wolf, described by The Globe
and Mail of Toronto as perhaps ``the most successful unknown
advertising man in Canada'' _ has been snapping up shops on both
sides of the border with the twin goals of becoming a top-20 agency
company in billings and going public. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TWELFTH-NIGHT-SETS (New York) _ The setting for ``Twelfth
Night'' is an Oriental fantasy of the mind. As far as the eye can
see, there is a road winding through water. At the front of the
Vivian Beaumont stage, actors are lolling sybaritically, surrounded
by burning candles and incense. Nearby is a pool for swimming and
dunking. Later in the play there will be a rainstorm. In Bob
Crowley's enchanting scenic design for Nicholas Hytner's
production, water is the central motif _ more than 10,000 gallons
at every performance. By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT5,6) have been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   TOP-NOVELS (Undated) _ With all due respect to Arthur
Schlesinger Jr., A.S. Byatt, William Styron and the others who,
acting at the behest of the Modern Library, produced a list of the
100 greatest English-language novels of the century, the truth is
that the entire endeavor is so drenched in subjectivity as to be
close to silly. Still, the purpose of the exercise was to provoke
discussion, always a good thing. So, while the conversation swirls,
here's another question that emerged from a recent conversation
duly provoked by the Modern Library list. How many of the books on
it would still be there if the selections had included works of the
19th century as well? My own quick answer to that question is ``not
that many.'' By Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STYLE (Moved in ``l'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-FASHION (Undated) _ Paris: review of the couture shows. By
Amy Spindler.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT10,11) have been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Una, Brazil) _ In Brazil, writes Thomas L.
Friedman, politics is the ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-GIANTS (Albany) _ Giants camp: One of the experiments in
camp is Jason Sehorn running back kickoffs and Tiki Barber running
back punts. How risky is it, using two starters in these positions,
where they could get hurt? By Bill Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JETS (Hempstead, N.Y.) _ Ron Wolf, Green Bay's general
manager, talks about his unusual exchange program with Jets; or
more on Kyle Brady and the tight end situation. By Gerald Eskenazi.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-ARATON-COLUMN (Hempstead, N.Y.) _ Sports of The Times column
on Julie Foudy and women's soccer, how the women's world cup is
almost the flip side of the men's world cup; in the women's game,
the U.S. can teach the world. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-PAK (Undated) _ As a 20-year-old rookie on the women's tour,
Se Ri Pak has continued to demonstrate precisely what her father
envisioned for her when she first picked up a club at age 11: that
she would be a golf star on the world stage. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BEETLES (Undated) _ Despite a longstanding fascination with
beetles, biologists have been able to do little more than speculate
about how the 330,000 known species have come to dominate the
living world. Now a study in the latest issue of Science says that
the secret to the diversity of beetles lies in what they eat. Those
groups of beetles that long ago evolved to eat flowering plants
spun off thousands of species, many more than those beetles that
continued to eat more primitive and less diverse plants. By
feasting on flowering plants _ which widely diversified _ the
beetles were apparently able themselves to produce many species. By
Carol Kaesuk Yoon. (1375 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Color graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WOMEN-AGGRESSION (Undated) _ Researchers are discovering
that, in contrast to the usual stereotypes, aggression among girls
and women may sometimes mirror or even exaggerate those seen in
boys and men. In dozens of studies of physical hostility in
heterosexual relationships, a psychologist at the University of
Central Lancashire in Great Britain has found that although women
sustain more serious and visible injuries than men during domestic
disputes, they are overall no less likely than men to resort to
physical aggression during an argument with a sexual partner. By
Abigail Zuger.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPUTE-MINSKY (Undated) _ Dr. Marvin Minsky, 71, a
rumpled-looking man who wears shirts mended together with masking
tape, is professor of computer science at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology and one of the world's leading theorists of
artificial intelligence. In the late 1950s, Minsky and a
collaborator founded a research program that would evolve into the
MIT Artificial Intelligence Laboratory. A conversation with Minsky.
By Claudia Dreifus.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT1) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INTERSEX-SURGERY (Undated) _ In spite of all the medical
advances, unusual anatomies _ specifically those born with
ambiguous sexual organs _ generally cannot be fixed in any
significant way without significant risk, and that risk, when
medically unnecessary, should be approved by the person at risk. By
Alice Dreger.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GRANDPARENTS-STRESS (Undated) _ For many grandparents,
joyful dates with the grandchildren have been replaced by the
responsibility of full-time child care. And that is taking its
toll. They are suffering from problems like depression, anxiety,
high blood pressure, alcoholism and strokes that doctors link in
part to the stress of being parents all over again, this time under
far more difficult circumstances than the first time around. By
Susan Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo s [NYT2,3,4) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HUMAN-FOSSILS (Undated) _ An analysis of African fossils,
including a few new specimens, has revealed a puzzling anatomical
difference between two major species of the early human family, one
from southern and the other from eastern Africa. The discoverers of
the difference suggest that the evolution of the human body thus
was more complicated than previously understood, possibly requiring
some rearrangement of branches on the family tree. By John Noble
Wilford.
</P>
