<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-POLITICS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION FOES KEEP GOAL, ADJUST STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a political climate of tightening restrictions on abortion
and violence against clinics, some abortion-rights supporters
foresee a day when abortion is legal but offered only by an
underground network of doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The result, critics fear, will be that women will have fewer
choices and will turn increasingly to clinics with shoddy
practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's reminiscent of the back-alley abortions in the past,''
said Sen. Ann Day, R-Tucson, chairwoman of the state Senate Health
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy of making abortion legal but unavailable seems to
be working, and critics worry that a death this year at a Phoenix
abortion clinic _ cited last week in Congress by lawmakers to help
override a presidential veto of a partial-birth abortion bill _
will contribute to still more calls for restrictions at the state
level and, ultimately, more back-room deaths. In the Phoenix
matter, a patient of Dr. John Biskind bled to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The precedent for this type of activity is the minor consent
bills, the informed consent bills, the waiting periods, the other
restrictive bills that chip away at access and at the right to
safe, legal abortion without touching `Roe vs. Wade,' '' said
Joseph Feldman, director of education and counseling at Planned
Parenthood of Central and Northern Arizona in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an orchestrated . . . strategic attempt to limit American
women's access to abortion without running headlong into the
Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sue Gerard, R-north central Phoenix, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the bills. There aren't any more to make abortion
illegal,'' Gerard said. ``Now it's informed consent, parental
consent, waiting periods. It's trying to make it more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion foes freely admit that they are concentrating on
tightening access to abortion. Rep. Karen Johnson, who entered
politics largely because of the abortion issue, said it's a way of
facing political reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're faced with a Supreme Court at the national level that is
not going to overturn `Roe vs. Wade' until some new judicial
appointments are made,'' said Johnson, R-Mesa. ``It's just
realistic that we look at the most egregious aspects of abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathi Herod of the Center for Arizona Policy, a Scottsdale-based
conservative advocacy group, agreed. But she added that ``we will
always have the goal . . . to have abortion outlawed in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Herod said that the abortion laws in recent years that Arizona
and other states have enacted are reasonable, common-sense reforms.
The parental consent law makes sense, for example, because doctors
need permission before operating on minors for most medical
procedures, Herod said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically the (abortion rights) lobby has opposed any law in
Arizona over the past 15 years that would have imposed reasonable
regulations on the abortion industry,'' Herod said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court declared abortion constitutional in 1973,
but subsequent court decisions allowed states to regulate it. In
Arizona, lawmakers enacted a parental consent law in 1996 and a
partial-birth abortion law in 1997, although both are now in court.
</P>
<P>
   An informed-consent bill that would require doctors to tell
women about the physical and emotional risks of an abortion at
least 24 hours before the procedure failed earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is considering a Child Custody Protection Act, which
would make it illegal to transport minors across state lines for an
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Taken as a whole, these restrictions mean that fewer clinics are
willing to provide abortions and that when demand outstrips supply,
in competent doctors, or clinics with lax standards and procedures,
will be encouraged to remain in business, critics say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without speaking to Dr. Biskind's competence, it's certainly
true that the smaller a pool of providers for any service, the more
in demand each one of them becomes,'' Planned Parenthood's Feldman
said. ``And certainly that means that some physicians who may
normally have trouble getting work will easily find work if they're
able and willing to perform abortions.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion foes dismiss those arguments as groundless. They say
it's a cop-out for abortion-rights advocates to blame the abortion
foes for such occurrences as those at the Biskind clinic.
</P>
<P>
   If abortion is becoming increasingly dangerous, they say, it's
because abortion-rights supporters have fought every attempt at
clinic regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we come up with something that would offer some
protections for women in abortion clinics, they fight it,'' Johnson
said. ``They want it wide open so they can rake in the money.'' &QL; 
(Chris Moeser can be reached at chris.moeser(at)pni.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
