<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGAL-AID-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTICA'S GHOST IN THE SHADOW OF PATAKI VETO 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Leven did not wear a jacket to work on Monday,
partly because it was hot and partly because, he figured, why
bother when no clients would be showing up at his office near City
Hall. It has been very slow lately at Prisoners' Legal Services,
where he is executive director.
</P>
<P>
   That is because Gov. George Pataki decided that New York does
not need a program like Leven's, which for two decades has provided
legal counsel for inmates, past and present, who say they have been
ill treated in the state's prisons.
</P>
<P>
   In this election year, Pataki has sought to spiff up his
tough-on-crime image by vetoing $4.8 million that the State
Legislature approved to keep Prisoners' Legal Services going for a
23rd year. If inmates want to sue the state, the governor reasoned,
let them do it on their own time and on their own dime.
</P>
<P>
   Without state money, Leven was forced to shed more than his
jacket. Most of his 60 lawyers, paralegals and assistants had to be
let go, and those who stayed are on reduced salaries. His staff
cannot take on new cases. Basically, with $470,000 thus far in
foundation grants, his organization is trying to limp its way to
1999 in the hope that the political mood in Albany will be
different then.
</P>
<P>
   ``But unless we're able to raise another million, we're not
going to be able to keep our doors open past October,'' Leven said.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, many New Yorkers would respond: Who cares? An awful
lot of them have no use for any program that remotely smacks of
coddling criminals, especially not on a day like Monday, when a
young ex-convict was accused of shooting Police Officer Gerard
Carter in the head on Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   But a closer look at this gubernatorial veto raises questions
about whether Pataki has done New York taxpayers a favor.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not even venture into loftier moral climes of the state's
obligations when inmates say they have been beaten by guards or
subjected to other indignities that violate rules of decency
separating U.S. prisons from, say, China's.
</P>
<P>
   Prisoners' Legal Services came into being as a direct result of
what is widely accepted to have been a gross abuse of state power:
the brutal suppression of a 1971 inmate uprising at the prison in
Attica, N.Y. State troopers poured into an inmate-occupied yard
with guns blazing, firing indiscriminately and killing 39 convicts
and guards who had been taken hostage.
</P>
<P>
   That violence _ the bloodiest one-day encounter between
Americans since the Civil War _ was followed by brutal reprisals
against inmates that amounted to torture. They were so vicious that
a federal court jury in Buffalo last year awarded $4 million to a
former Attica prisoner, Frank Smith. Among other things, Smith had
been beaten with batons, burned with cigarettes, and made to lie
naked on a table for hours with a football tucked under his chin
and threatened with castration if the ball dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Attica's ghosts linger, in part because Albany will not let them
fade away. Just this month, state-paid lawyers went before federal
appellate judges seeking to overturn the award to Smith. Of course,
the taxpayer will get stuck with the legal bill, the same way that
he may have to absorb hidden costs of the Pataki veto.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that Leven's staff does is weed out silly inmate
gripes, those of the ``they served melted ice cream'' variety. It
boasts of never having had a case tossed out as frivolous by a
judge, despite handling 12,000 prisoner complaints and 150 court
cases a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be more litigation if we're gone,'' Leven said.
``We discourage cases that we feel don't have merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Guess who will pick up the tab for any flood of unfiltered cases
brought by inmates themselves? The same may hold true if Legal
Services is not around to see that inmates get full credit for jail
time served. Its vigilance frees up valuable cell space, saving the
state millions.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, who wants needlessly angry convicts? A place where they
can take legitimate grievances provides a safety valve that can
avert another (and, need it be added, costly) Attica.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the state's obligation, and they ought to step up
to the plate and honor it,'' said Paul Curran, board chairman of
Prisoners' Legal Services.
</P>
<P>
   Curran, it might be noted, is a Republican and a former U.S.
attorney in Manhattan. Not your run-of-the-mill bleeding heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
