<SLUG> BC-NY-GREEN-SENATE-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN CRITICIZES RIVAL D'AMATO'S ETHICS  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mark Green, a Democratic candidate for the Senate,
attacked Sen. Alfonse D'Amato Monday as an ``election-year
opportunist and a shakedown artist,'' delivering the kind of
blistering assault on D'Amato's ethics that Green said his
Democratic opponents were unwilling to make.
</P>
<P>
   The speech by Green, the New York City public advocate, amounted
to a compendium of 12 years of accusations that Green and others
have directed at D'Amato's fund-raising practices and votes. The
attack made clear that Green would seek to distinguish himself in
the Democratic field by making the Republican senator the issue,
and with oratory that was harsh even by the standards of New York
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al D'Amato is dangerous, not because of his principles but
because he is altogether unprincipled,'' Green asserted in a speech
to a small group of labor leaders. ``He has shown that he will do
and say anything to maintain his power and his incumbency.
</P>
<P>
   Green said D'Amato's ``career has always been framed not by
beliefs and principles but by contracts and deals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ethics,'' Green said, ``are invariably sacrificed on the altar
of expediency.''
</P>
<P>
   Green's speech was, to a certain extent, a reprise of
accusations he has leveled since he first ran against D'Amato in
1986. At times Monday, Green even quoted himself, as is his habit.
His decision to attack D'Amato with such strong language was also
at least in part pragmatic: short on cash, Green needs to draw the
kind of news coverage that would give free publicity to his
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato, who is known to have particular antipathy to Green
because of their history of hostility, declined comment Monday on
his opponent's remarks. Instead, a D'Amato spokesman, Harvey
Valentine, said: ``Mark Green obviously hasn't gotten over his
defeat of 1986. It's sad.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Green's speech highlighted a debate among Democrats
contemplating the best way to unseat D'Amato: whether attacks on
D'Amato's ethics, many of which are familiar by now, have any
resonance with the electorate. Green said his opponents _ Rep.
Charles Schumer and Geraldine Ferraro, the former representative _
were making a fundamental mistake in not attacking D'Amato over
ethics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats seeking to replace Al D'Amato must be able to show
the link between his bad ethics and bad votes,'' Green said,
referring to what he said was the connection between D'Amato's
legislative votes and campaign contributions. ``Any Democrats
unwilling or unable to make both the ethics and legislative cases
against D'Amato _ not one to the exclusion of the other, but both _
won't and shouldn't be the nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said he would raise questions about D'Amato's ethics but
that such attacks would ultimately have only a limited effect.
``Most people in New York State know that D'Amato is hardly a
paragon of ethics,'' he said. ``But most people do not know that he
has voted like Jesse Helms on choice, that he has voted against gun
control and that he has voted to cut Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Ms. Ferraro, Stephen Gaskill, also said such
attacks had only limited effect. ``We're talking about D'Amato's
record on the issues,'' Gaskill said. ``And that's the great
distinction between D'Amato and Gerry Ferraro, as well as the other
candidates in the race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 0131EDT &QL; 
