<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-MEDICINE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORTAGE OF ABORTION DOCTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By Vanessa DeRuyter  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Access to safe abortions is threatened by a shortage of doctors
qualified to perform the procedure, according to experts in the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Even though national trends show the number of abortions has
been decreasing nationally _ from a record 1.43 million in 1990
down to 1.21 million in 1995 _ abortion advocates say there are not
enough doctors willing to perform the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion is not taught in medical school, and physicians are not
required to learn how to perform it, even though the Arizona Board
of Medical Examiners, for example, requires that training in
abortion be offered to physicians in obstetrics and gynecology
residency programs.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, fewer OB-GYN doctors have the training, and those
who are familiar with the procedure may not be willing to perform
it, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Beth Weber, medical services director for Planned Parenthood
of Central and Northern Arizona, said that young physicians are
unwilling to take advantage of the training in part because of
historical ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the younger physicians are unaware of the pre-`Roe
(vs. Wade') days when women did seek illegal abortions,'' she said.
``They don't understand the repercussions when abortion is not
provided and not provided safely.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Brian Finkel has performed abortions in the Valley since
1982 and fears for the future safety of women who seek them. He
said he has requested many times that Midwestern University in
Glendale send him students to train, but the school has
consistently declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a problem. You have administrators at medical schools
refusing to make available to students quality health-care
training,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Finkel alleges that the university and many others avoid
teaching abortion because it is controversial, and they are
overwhelmed by the fear of losing funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that most of these bureaucrats in medical school have
backbone and gonad deficiencies,'' he said. ``They are more
interested in getting tax dollars than they are in doing the right
thing. They are afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Midwestern Associate Dean Thomas McWilliams denies that. ``It's
erroneous that it's the medical schools' fault,'' McWilliams said.
``It's not part of the curriculum, and I don't believe that it's
part of the curriculum in most schools.''
</P>
<P>
   McWilliams recognizes that the issue is politically and
emotionally charged, but he says that is not why abortion training
isn't part of the curriculum. He said students must cram a lot of
information into four years, and schools have to set priorities in
pre-doctoral instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our curriculum, training in termination of pregnancy is
not an objective. It's not that it's not important. It's not that I
don't recognize that there is a need for some people to do that,
but not at the pre-doctoral level,'' McWilliams said.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Arizona hospital does not perform or teach
abortions, either. State legislators banned University Medical
Center in Tucson from performing abortions in 1974, except in cases
where the mother's life is in danger. The ban was clamped on as a
stipulation to a measure authorizing the university to sell bonds
for the expansion of the football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors deciding to learn the procedure during their residency
may become discouraged from practicing it by the stigma, said Dr.
Paula Nadell, who doesn't perform abortions but believes in
abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Most doctors performing abortions are older men, veterans of the
political battle over ``Roe vs. Wade,'' said Berry Sweet, former
executive director of Right to Choose, a grass-roots
abortion-rights organization.
</P>
<P>
   These doctors have witnessed deaths from unsafe abortions and
lobbied nationally to have trained medical providers perform the
procedure, Sweet said.
</P>
<P>
   But now many fear for their lives because of increased violence,
and some have been forced to remove their practices to more
discreet settings, Nadell said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 0134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
