<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5709 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-A'S-SFCHRON &LR;      07-28 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-A'S-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A'S FIND NO RAYS OF HOPE IN LOSS  
BY STEVE KETTMANN
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The A's deserve far better than to have
one four-game series in a hellhole of a dome stand as the epitaph
for a season, but that's the fate that now hangs around their necks
like a cheap-plastic lei.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion Tampa Bay Devil Rays swept the A's in four games,
and whether it is fair or not, that's so damning an indictment that
it may end up overshadowing many or most of the positives that have
characterized this season to date.
</P>
<P>
   To put it bluntly, it takes a bad team to lose four games in a
row to a team that entered the series with a 37-62 record. The A's
have been a good team at times this year, but right now they are
not, and that was painfully clear in an 11-5 defeat Monday that ran
their losing streak to seven games, their worst in 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nightmare, terrible, horrific, unbelievable _ those are the
terms that describe it perfectly,'' A's second baseman Bip Roberts
said. ``To lose every game on a road trip, that's tough, man.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Wade Boggs lined a single to center in the eighth to
start the rally that made it a rout, the A's had a dazed look, like
kids wishing Mom would call them home to dinner and say that the
game really didn't mean anything anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Streaks have a way of developing a momentum of their own, and
the A's current run looks more and more like a runaway train. The
hitting came around Monday, but only after Tampa Bay banged up
starter Blake Stein (4-6) and jumped out to a 7-1 lead by the
fifth, turning the remainder of the game into garbage time. The
defense was wobbly again, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were soundly beaten again,'' manager Art Howe said. ``We
didn't pitch and we didn't make plays. They won the series, hands
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the A's are a season-low 12 games under .500 and it's back
to the Coliseum for a potentially punishing 10-game homestand
against the Red Sox (60-43), Indians (59-45) and Yankees (73-26).
</P>
<P>
   But Howe and others in the clubhouse seemed to look forward to
the challenge of playing some good teams again, instead of going
against a team like Tampa Bay that had lost 16 of 18 going into the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't play any worse,'' Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone shudders at who is coming to town, just
like they don't take anyone for granted,'' general manager Billy
Beane said Monday. ``We've played Cleveland tougher than Kansas
City. We've had the lead in every game against the Yankees. We've
had the lead in every game but one against Boston and that was when
Pedro Martinez beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was so bad last night that even Ben Grieve, the oasis of hope
in a whole desert of painful reality, had an ugly game. He's the
real thing, a lock to hit .300 season after season, but he's a work
in progress in the outfield and last night he made two bad plays.
</P>
<P>
   He fielded catcher Mike DiFelice's run-scoring double in the
second cleanly but looked confused about where he wanted to throw.
He ended up nonchalanting the ball to Roberts, and the throw
tailed. Roberts couldn't handle it, and a second run scored to make
it 2-1, putting the Devil Rays ahead to stay. Then in the seventh,
Mike Kelly hit what was scored a triple, but Grieve first misjudged
it badly, then let it bounce over his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can a triple bounce?'' wondered one irate teammate.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fetters got out of that jam, but once the fans had gone
wild in the eighth when Boggs passed Babe Ruth on the career hit
chart, Tampa Bay was off and running for a four-run rally that left
the A's with that familiar kick-to-the-gut feeling. It only got
worse when fans pulled out the brooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw fans standing up with brooms, yelling `Sweep,''' A's
third baseman Mike Blowers said. ``If you're not embarrassed, you
don't have pride in what you do. I would hope everyone is
embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
