A5712 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-28 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS GO ON ROAD IN TRADING MODE  
BY HENRY SCHULMAN
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The fickle finger of fate has deigned to give the
Giants a break. They will not have to face left-hander Carlos
Perez, the ace of the Montreal pitching staff, in a three-game
series beginning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Perez suffered a broken nose in an auto accident Sunday night,
but his turn in the rotation would not have come up against San
Francisco anyway.
</P>
<P>
   While the Giants visit Canada in search of victories, general
manager Brian Sabean will be itching to fire his not-so-fickle
trigger-finger on one or two more deals to bolster the Giants'
sagging chances of winning the National League wild card.
</P>
<P>
   How convenient it would be if the Giants could leave for
Philadelphia on Thursday night with Perez on their team plane,
ready to face the Phillies in the first of four games on Friday
night, assuming Perez is able to pitch with a broken nose.
</P>
<P>
   Could it happen? Probably not. Is it out of the question? Not
necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   With Friday's trading deadline looming, many of the dozen or so
teams still in the wild-card hunt will be searching for pitching
help, and Perez is the best catch out there. Forget his 7-10
record, a product of playing for the worst run-producing team in
the National League. He is a tough strikeout pitcher who could be
the No.1 starter on many staffs.
</P>
<P>
   The payroll-conscious Expos usually try to trade players who
figure to get a big raise the following season, in return for good
prospects. Perez is making $1.5 million this year and figures to
get a hefty raise this winter as an arbitration-eligible player.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos reportedly are looking for young outfielders, and the
Giants have several they could dangle, including Dante Powell.
</P>
<P>
   But some baseball people believe the Expos are not in their
usual hurry to deal. They have slashed their payroll so low, to $9
million, they could probably afford the bump in Perez's salary for
1999. Furthermore, the Expos are trying to gain public support for
a new ballpark, and trading their best pitcher could hurt the
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Word is, the Expos are willing to trade Perez, but only if they
are bowled over by an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Sabean will not go to Montreal. Rather, he will stay in San
Francisco and work the phones, no doubt talking to the Expos about
Perez, the Cardinals about Todd Stottlemyre and Brian Jordan, the
Royals about Tim Belcher, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   But Sabean said the market is so full of buyers and short of
sellers, teams with pitchers to deal are seeking outrageous
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we're shopping at Neiman Marcus,'' he said. ``Teams
are highbrow about what they want in return, or they're really not
sure what they want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, sources said, the Giants were interested in
Cincinnati right fielder Reggie Sanders before they dealt for Joe
Carter last week. But the Reds were asking for top pitching
prospects Jason Grilli and/or Scott Linebrink in return.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were not about to part with young pitchers on their
untouchables list for an injury-prone .260 hitter who has a $3.7
million contract for next season. They told the Reds to lower their
sights, the Reds refused, so the Giants dealt for Carter instead.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the market imbalance, Sabean predicts fewer impact
deals than usual before Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be a situation where you may see more action after
July 31,'' Sabean said. ``You may see, especially in our wild-card
race, there won't be five or six teams still in contention when
August 31 rolls around. Things may open up then.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, deals still can be made after Friday, but the players
must clear waivers first. August 31 becomes a second key deadline,
because players must be on a team's roster by then to be eligible
for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Trades or no trades, this is an important time for the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   After their three games in Montreal, they play four at
Philadelphia and three at New York, two teams entwined in the
wild-card race with the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're due for a good road trip, especially after the last
one,'' manager Dusty Baker said. ``We're due for one of those
monster road trips you have once or twice a season that set your
whole year up.''
</P>
<P>
   That the Giants will see the Phillies for the first time is one
of the more bizarre aspects of this year's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird, this late in the season,'' Baker said. ``This is
something I haven't experienced before.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
