<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERRY EXPECTED TO LEAVE USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rod Perry Jr., one of the most sought-after high
school football players two years ago, is expected to announce he
is transferring from USC this week to concentrate on a baseball
career.
</P>
<P>
   Perry Jr., the son of former Rams cornerback Rod Perry, has
already contacted Cal State Fullerton about enrolling and playing
baseball next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very concerned about his two knee surgeries,'' USC
baseball coach Mike Gillespie said. ``Rod has approached us about
his concern with continuing with football.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie said he already spoke with Fullerton coach George
Horton and Perry has also been in contact with the school.
</P>
<P>
   Perry wanted to remain at USC, but Gillespie does not have any
available baseball scholarships for the coming school year.
</P>
<P>
   Perry met with USC football coach Paul Hackett on Monday, and
said he would make an announcement within a few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every indication is he will not be with us,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, a star wide receiver at Mater Dei High School, was a
unanimous prep All-American. He also played baseball and was
drafted in the 37th round by the Baltimore Orioles his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   But he has had two knee operations in the past three years, and
redshirted last season at USC after undergoing knee surgery for
torn ligaments. He also missed part of his junior year at Mater Dei
with a similar operation.
</P>
<P>
   Perry recovered from the surgery and was an occasional starter
on USC's national championship baseball team this spring. He batted
.250 and played center field.
</P>
<P>
   His departure leaves USC vulnerable at wide receiver: Windrell
Hayes, a JC transfer, is currently facing felony charges and his
status is uncertain while leading receiver R. Jay Soward has been
suspended for the season-opener against Purdue.
</P>
</TEXT>
