A5877 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLIND-PHOTOGRAPHER-LI     07-28 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLIND-PHOTOGRAPHER-LIFEBEAT-CORRECTION-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLIND PHOTOGRAPHER PROVES EYESIGHT ISN'T ALL YOU NEED 
</HEADLINE>
  Corrects jumbled text 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 Includes photo 
 By BEN WIDDICOMBE 
 c.1998 
 World rights except Britain and Australia 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Dugdale lives on one of New York City's prettiest streets,
an avenue lined with lazy trees and hundred-year-old townhouses.
The Chelsea skyline is visible through the conservatory of his
top-floor apartment, where turn-of-the-century Americana sits next
to his collection of antique glass and porcelain. It's so
beautiful, it's a pity he can't see it.
</P>
<P>
   Dugdale is almost blind.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him how much sight he has and he makes an eye shape with his
thumb and forefinger, poking through the bottom with the tip of his
pinky. ``Oh, about that much in one eye,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between 1993 and 1994 I lost more than three quarters of my
sight; I have a little bit out of the bottom of my left eye, but
it's very blurry,'' Dugdale adds.
</P>
<P>
   Dugdale recently returned from two weeks in Britain, where he
completed almost 100 landscape and interior compositions. The
results will be a show called Nature and Spirit, opening in London
this fall before moving to New York's Wessel and O'Connor Gallery
in November.
</P>
<P>
   After also exhibiting this year in Rome and Sydney, Dugdale
reflects that losing his sight propelled him from being just
another commercial photographer for magazines like Vogue and Martha
Stewart Living to an internationally recognized artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tested HIV positive in 1985, but I was always very
healthy,'' says Dugdale. ``I thought it was the end of my
commercial career, but as a way to make my family feel better, I
said: 'Don't worry, I'll be a great, blind, art photographer.' They
were surprised that I said it and so was I, because it was the
first time I verbalized it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As his sight dwindled, Dugdale came to rely on the help of
assistants to focus his camera and set up shots. For composition he
uses intuition and memory of other artwork, often putting himself
in the pictures so he gets the right pose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely have a full, clear visual picture of everything
that I photograph,'' he says. ``That really starts inside my head,
because eyesight and vision are completely different. I felt very
happy and safe when I realized my vision was totally intact. It's
just that my mechanical sight isn't working as well as it used
to,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Able to make out dim outlines of buildings or natural features
in strong daylight, Dugdale relies on touch to establish details
like texture. Once he has felt an object or studied part of it with
a magnifying glass, he explains, he sees it in his mind. ``I can
tell from the light and the objects shape and from the 100
questions that I ask people who are with me what is in front of me,
and then I compose the shot in a very geometric way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Describing things to people, when they're doing the framing
for me, I have to break it down to the utterly simplest kind of
composition, because that's what people understand,'' Dugdale says.
``You can't really communicate a photographic style or an eye to
people, but what happened was the simplicity of the photographs
turned into their style.''
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't stopped traveling, but the limitations of blindness
mean much of his work concentrates on immediately available
subjects, such as family, his upstate New York home and antiques.
</P>
<P>
   It was the classic, almost timeless feel of his art which two
years ago attracted the attention of New York's Metropolitan Museum
of Art. Associate Curator of Photography Malcolm Daniel was
involved with the decision to acquire a photograph of Dugdale's
house, shot outdoors and inverted through the lens of a
19th-century glass vase.
</P>
<P>
   ``The photograph expresses something about photography itself,
and the way that the world that we've created is reflected through
art,'' says Daniel. ``What particularly appealed to us about this
was the element of self-referentiality it seemed to be about
photography, and about light and images, and the way the vase
itself acts as a lens to show the wider world that you don't
actually see in the camera itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel denies that Dugdale, as a blind photographer, is a
novelty act. ``It's not like the person who paints with their toes,
where you say, 'Isn't it remarkable for somebody who doesn't have
hands to be able to do that just with their feet?''' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His deteriorating eyesight makes Dugdale more conscious of
trying to capture certain effects of light and shadow which are
essential to his work.
</P>
<P>
   And he's clear on the meaning of that work. ``My pictures are so
accessible. They're about sadness, joy, beauty, death, life. All
perfectly straightforward, unfettered emotions,'' he says,
admitting to having run the gamut of those emotions himself.
</P>
<P>
   As AIDS began eroding his life, he admits, fear gave way to
depression. ``I've had the experience of being lost in my own front
</P>
<P>
   yard at my house in upstate New York. Most people have some
ambient vision,'' Dugdale says, ``they can pick up shapes in the
dark but as I lost my sight I would be plunged into total blackness
when the sun went down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only found the house by throwing pebbles and listening to
where the sound came back from,'' he notes.
</P>
<P>
   His first book, ``Lengthening Shadows Before Nightfall,'' was
published in 1994 and dealt with his feelings as doctors gave him
less than a year to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't a specific message in the book but there was a
sense of calm and tranquillity, because after struggling with the
disease, I had to prepare to pass away,'' Dugdale says. ``Every
time my friends and family came I had to say goodbye to them. At
first I was hysterical, but then towards the end of it I realized
there wasn't anything I could do by being insane, so I relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dugdale's health improved with new therapies and the book was a
success, drawing attention for his use of techniques and equipment
more at home in a history book than the studio of a contemporary
artist.
</P>
<P>
   The distinctive blue of his work is the result of making
cyanotypes, a ferrous-metal developing process pioneered in 1842.
``I'd like to close out this century with the biggest body of
cyanotypes that I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides that process, Dugdale uses a 1912 camera in the field
and shoots studio work with a 250-pound, 63-year-old behemoth.
</P>
<P>
   Dugdale's method has been such a success that his work commands
up to $6,000 a print. As well as being in the permanent collection
of the Metropolitan, his patrons include Elton John, who hosted him
on his recent visit to Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Dugdale used John's estate as a base during his visit. From
there he photographed English landmarks including Stonehenge.
Printing a self-portrait taken on Britain's south coast, near a
cliff called Beachy Head, Dugdale was struck by his unconscious
choice of composition, a new theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Beachy Head picture is so much about the precipice, and
interestingly I didn't place myself on the edge of it,'' he says.
``I'm standing away, looking inland. Without getting too
psycho-interpretive, that's a telling thing. I'm feeling present
here and not on the edge anymore.''
 &UR; -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (BEN WIDDICOMBE is a free-lance writer based in Sydney,
Australia.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COPYRIGHT BEN WIDDICOMBE 1998 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 0905EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 09:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5878 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLIND-PHOTOGRAPHER-LI     07-28 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLIND-PHOTOGRAPHER-LIFEBEAT-CORRECTION-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLIND PHOTOGRAPHER PROVES EYESIGHT ISN'T ALL YOU NEED 
</HEADLINE>
  Corrects jumbled text 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 Includes photo 
 By BEN WIDDICOMBE 
 c.1998 
 World rights except Britain and Australia 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
