<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5947 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-BOOKS28-COX     07-28 1539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-BOOKS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Struggling African American booksellers are victims of their own
success
 &HT;    By Norma Martin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A youthful woman quietly hands out square stickers
with penciled numbers to people arriving at the evening reading by
award-winning author Gloria Naylor at the Shrine of the Black
Madonna Bookstore and Cultural Center.
</P>
<P>
   Customers talk softly about Naylor's books, especially her first
one. ``The Women of Brewster Place,'' told in the voices of urban
African American women, earned Naylor literary acclaim, including
the National Book Award in 1984. Later, Naylor would tell her fans
that her new novel ``The Men of Brewster Place'' will be her final
words about the fictional street.
</P>
<P>
   It's Naylor's last night in Texas. A few hours earlier in a
hotel lobby, the tall, quiet author said the book signing and
reading would have been impossible 15 years ago. Then, there was no
thought of a book tour _ national, regional or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``My publisher felt there wasn't an audience for the book,''
Naylor said about ``The Women of Brewster Place.'' These days,
Naylor's books are published by Hyperion.
</P>
<P>
   Houston marks the 11th stop on Naylor's 18-city book tour. Her
appearances have featured an array of bookstores, chain and
independent, niche-market and general-interest. Her readings in
Texas were exclusively at black bookstores, something that couldn't
have happened back in the early 1980s because most of them didn't
exist.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, African American bookstores have
flourished and faltered. They've provided a valuable service to
their communities by providing an outlet for African American
writings that were hard to find at mainstream bookstores, by aiding
the fight against illiteracy, by buying books from small presses
and distributors and by giving once-emerging black authors, such as
Naylor and Terry McMillan, a chance by personally promoting their
early books.
</P>
<P>
   Now, these niche-market bookstores must compete with the mammoth
chains that can offer money-making, brand-name authors at super
discount prices. Unfortunately, the stores are a victim of their
success; they helped turn obscure authors into popular mainstream
writers. If these stores disappear, it may be more difficult for
the next generation of writers to break into the market.
</P>
<P>
   When Rosalind Oliphant, owner of Folktales, opened her business
in February 1992, she said, ``it was real hard to come by an
African American book in Austin.'' She started with a cart in
Highland Mall. ``We broke records, every month. Austin was just
that hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   One competitor responded like this: ``They didn't even have a
pre-printed sign. They took a sheet of paper that said `black
literature' and put it in the plastic slot on the shelf,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Oliphant entered a market that Emma Rodgers of Dallas, the dean
of Texas African American booksellers, had been working for nearly
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s Rodgers went looking for party favors for her
son's birthday party. She wanted children's books that featured
positive images of African American children. She drove all over
Dallas, going from bookstore to bookstore, until she found them.
Her frustration eventually led to Black Images Book Bazaar. Its Web
site states that the business is ``the oldest black bookstore in
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers and a business partner started their enterprise in 1977,
as a home-based mail-order business. The retail store opened in
September 1986.
</P>
<P>
   As Black Images was expanding its retail space, bookstores in
Houston, Beaumont, Killeen and Arlington were opening their doors.
</P>
<P>
   Black Images' first big-name signing was acclaimed actress Ruby
Dee. There were times when authors demanded a bigger space and book
readings had to be held in neighborhood churches or public
libraries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always bring in groups to help develop an audience,'' said
Rodgers, who recently held sold-out signings for singer Patti
LaBelle and BET host Tavis Smiley.
</P>
<P>
   These days Black Images is a must-stop for any African American
author on a book tour in the state. ``We're booked until
November,'' said Rodgers, who is on the board of directors of the
American Booksellers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Competing with the chains
</P>
<P>
   Independent booksellers are in a David-and-Goliath battle with
national chains. At first the general interest stores watched their
profits decline; now it's the niche stores' turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has finally crossed over into the black market,'' said
Manie Barron, associate editor at Random House and a specialist in
African American trade book sales.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally in the last year or so, many black bookstores have
closed, said Barron. If it's happening in America, it's happening
in Texas. Two stores have closed in Houston, another went under in
San Antonio and, in April, Austin's Just for Us closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted our life back,'' said Juanita Stephens, co-owner of
the former North Austin store. ``A small business is very tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephens said she and her husband, Paul, plan to launch a
Web-based business they can operate from their home.
</P>
<P>
   The closings, Barron said, are coming at an ironic time. Sales
of books by black authors continue to go up; publishers are
releasing them in volume like never before and not just the
Naylors, Terry McMillans and Toni Morrisons.
</P>
<P>
   An increasingly important player is the self-published author,
said Rodgers. ``They are vital to our business, next to the trade
(market) reps. They are our lifelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because successful self-published authors are working hard
to create a grass-roots buzz for their works, which in turn brings
customers through the doors and to the cashiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are books the mainstream bookstores are not going to
have. These are the books the distributors don't know exist.''
</P>
<P>
   For Rodgers, those self-published authors could be the future
brand-names that might sell out a book signing in a couple of
years. If you doubt her, she can tell you stories about the
then-unknown Terry McMillan, who wasn't self-published but who like
Naylor didn't have publisher-backed book tours with her early
books. Then there are the tales of New York Times best-selling
author E. Lynn Harris, Violet Crown winner Anita Richmond Bunkley
and Ella Patterson, a nonfiction author who landed a hefty book
deal. All three started their writing careers in self-publishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The black bookstore will always be here,'' said Rodgers. ``It
might not have the strong presence you have now, but it will be
there, serving the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Expanding markets
</P>
<P>
   African American bookstores are moving outside the major Texas
cities. On West Jasper Road in Killeen is the 3,000 square-foot
bookstore Under One Roof. It's a rival in size to Black Images in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Babatunde went into the book business full-time after retiring
from the military. His main competition is the Fort Hood base
store.
</P>
<P>
   ``They carry the crossover books, but I carry them all,'' he
said, noting that he offers a good-size selection of writings from
African authors.
</P>
<P>
   Although the vast majority of the space is dedicated to books,
Babatunde said African artifacts and Afrocentric art keep the doors
open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I carry all these other things to keep books on the shelf,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other booksellers intent on surviving say they are expanding
their markets, too. They're offering space for literacy classes,
writing workshops and book club meetings. They're cementing
relationships with schools. They're working conventions,
conferences and trade shows. They're working with the local prison
system so inmates can get books.
</P>
<P>
   In Texarkana, Alvester Gibson and his wife, Glenda, used to take
weekend road trips. They drove the 175-mile round trip to Dallas or
the 144-miles round trip to Little Rock or the 70-mile round trip
to Shreveport. All the excursions were for the same purpose: buying
African American books.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, these bibliophiles parked the car and opened
House of Knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We draw our customers from a 75-mile radius,'' said Gibson.
``We're providing a need for this community.''
</P>
<P>
   Closing Naylor's evening
</P>
<P>
   Naylor is a former missionary for the Jehovah's Witnesses. She
knows how to hold an audience, make her point and then become
silent. She doesn't waste words, not in speech or in print. ``The
Men of Brewster Place'' is a slim novel of less than 180 pages. Her
shortest book in some years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The characters had said enough and wanted to sit down,'' says
Naylor. Will she return to Brewster Place in the future? ``No,''
she says. ``There will be no children, no pets of Brewster Place.
We have closed that chapter on Brewster Place.'' As fans wait their
turn to talk with Naylor, they talk about black bookstores. ``It's
a nurturing center,'' says Alitash Tafui. ``We need more of them.
This place embraces our blackness; it fortifies you to go out into
the world.'' Nodding in agreement, DeAnn Collins says: ``It's the
smell. It's the music. It's the atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Norma Martin is a staff writer for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
