<HEADER>
A5951 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBAN-JEWS29-COX     07-28 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-JEWS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pope's visit to Cuba inspiration for other religions
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ The synagogue has an aerobics instructor, but no rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   Temple dues _ which can run $1,000 a year in South Florida _ are
five cents a month.
</P>
<P>
   As with most everything else in Cuba, Judaism survives on this
tropical island by sacrifice and invention. The Sephardic Hebrew
Center uses its community room for aerobics, dance classes and
weight training, earning a few dollars for the upkeep of the
44-year-old building.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbis left Cuba along with 90 percent of the Jewish
population after the 1959 revolution led by Fidel Castro. While
visiting rabbis come several times a year for bar mitzvahs,
weddings and conversions, weekly services are performed by lay
members, said Jose Levy, synagogue president.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban Jewish community's long isolation may be nearing an
end, thanks in part to Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, a delegation of 32 Jews from South Florida, including
Cuban Americans, will travel to Cuba on a six-day reconciliation
mission with their Jewish brethren. The visit is the first trip to
Cuba organized by the Greater Miami Jewish Federation in nearly
four decades, according to an official with the American Jewish
Joint Distribution Committee in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul's visit to Cuba in January broke down barriers
for all religions, said Will Recant, the committee's special
projects director.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope's visit played a large role in enabling these
relationships to be renewed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is paying for a $250,000 restoration of Havana's
main synagogue, the crumbling Temple Beth Shalom.
</P>
<P>
   The project won approval four months ago from the U.S. Treasury
Department, which enforces the U.S. embargo against Cuba, Recant
said. Donations for the restoration came primarily from South
Florida Jews, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jews in Havana welcome the support.
</P>
<P>
   Miami-based Jewish Solidarity Inc. reports that it has been
delivering medicines and food to Cuba for the last five years, but
receives only limited support from people in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Levy, of the Sephardic Hebrew Center, said Miami Cubans have for
years turned their backs on Havana.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of the Cuban Jewish community in Miami thinks we
are in bed with Castro,'' said Levy, 59.
</P>
<P>
   While the temples have not been as outspoken against the Castro
government as other religious groups, Levy said Jews have won new
freedoms over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Levy's temple sued the Cuban government to evict
a state-operated cultural office from the temple. The Cuban courts
sided with the temple, freeing space for the congregation's
community room.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Cuban Jews won the right to comply with Aliyah,
the Israeli law that grants citizenship to Jews in the diaspora. So
far, about 160 Jews have emigrated to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Levy, whose parents came to Cuba from Turkey in the 1920s, said
he has no plans to emigrate, because his 90-year-old mother and
nine-year-old daughter live in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   He said he tried once before to leave, in 1980. Since he worked
for 20 years as a chief officer in the Cuban merchant marine, the
Cuban government denied him permission to leave Cuba, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Levy's synagogue is one of three in Havana, a city of 2.2
million. Levy said only 1,050 Jews are left in the capital and only
a third go to temple regularly. Nationwide, about 1,500 Jews remain
in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Next week's trip to Havana will be led by Jacob Solomon,
executive vice president of the Greater Miami Jewish Federation,
who is making his first trip to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   His delegation's mission is to provide spiritual, material and
``moral support for our brothers and sisters in Cuba,'' Solomon
said. The group plans to take religious and medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Those invited to be part of the delegation are major
contributors to federation fund-raising programs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going with independent agendas,'' said Solomon. No
meetings are planned with Cuban government officials, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The visit signals changing attitudes in Miami's exile community,
said John Fischer, a Boca Raton businessman who has delivered
supplies to the temple being restored. Fischer, who spent his early
childhood in Havana, said the temple's broken windows and bird
nests in the rafters disturbed his memories of the once elegant
structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great idea,'' Fischer said of the visit. ``We
are finally seeing the Cuban hardline in Miami starting to bend a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
