<SLUG> BC-TECHREPORT29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech Report: A new VCR for non-techies
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Maybe you have gotten used to that blinking 12:00 on
your videocassette recorder, but you don't have to.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, you could be getting a lot more out of a VCR. You could
have something easy to use, easy to program and chock-full of neat
features. Of course, you may have to buy a new one to replace the
one that's blinking.
</P>
<P>
   Time was, we were so relieved to have a machine that could play
movies at home we didn't much care whether we could ever figure out
how to program it to record television shows. And for those
persistent souls _ or Georgia Tech engineers _ who actually figured
out how to program VCRs, well, everything else was gravy.
</P>
<P>
   But, finally, the manufacturers are coming around.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, the makers of VCRs are offering easy-to-use
features aimed at non-techies, while packing more technology into
the box. For example, the Zenith VRA423, which retails for $240,
comes with four heads. The one blinking in your living room may
have just two. Double the heads should mean better audio and video.
</P>
<P>
   Like most current VCRs, the VRA423 comes with a feature that
sets your machine to record using the code that runs with most
television listings. The VRA423 also has automatic tracking, an
automatic head cleaner and a feature for letting you skip
commercials on playback. You can view recordings in slow motion.
Want to see that Chipper Jones homer again? How about Uncle Peter's
wedding?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps best of all for the technologically challenged, the
machine comes with a feature called SpeakEZTM _ voice-directed,
on-screen instructions for programming, adjusting the picture and
searching a tape.
</P>
<P>
   It will even explain how to set the clock so it doesn't blink.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, check out the Zenith site on the Web
(http://www.zenith
</P>
<P>
   .com).
</P>
<P>
   Portable Net music
</P>
<P>
   It's like the Sony Walkman, a palm-size device you can use to
amuse or entertain yourself, listening to the pounding beat or the
classical strings or maybe Toni Morrison reading. It can also plug
in to your home or car stereo. But it does not play a compact disc
or cassette.
</P>
<P>
   And it would like to be the future of portable music.
</P>
<P>
   It's called MPMan. The device, made by NullSoft, is designed to
handle the audio increasingly available off the Internet. You
transfer the files from your personal computer to MPMan.
</P>
<P>
   MPMan uses the MPEG 3 form of compression for handling audio off
the Internet, a technique capable of compressing data up to a dozen
times. The machine uses a built-in 32- or 64-megabyte flash card.
The device costs between $250 and $500 and comes with a docking bay
that connects to your PC, a carrying case, rechargeable batteries,
and the appropriate software for transferring PC to MPMan and for
playing MP3 files on your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, MPEC compression is also good for making illegal copies of
music, something that ``is making the recording industry soil
itself with fear,'' as Wired magazine so indelicately put it.
``Still some legal MP3 music is floating around the Web; in time,
this may become the indie-rock distribution channel of choice.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information, visit the company Web site
(http://www.nullsoft.com).
</P>
<P>
   Fishing reels go high-tech
</P>
<P>
   A technologist looks at everything and wonders: How can this be
better?
</P>
<P>
   Even the devices that symbolize a life apart from flashing
lights and beeping gizmos, and time spent far from the rush of a
high-tech world. Yes, even fishing reels. For proof, see that even
a fishing reel is high-tech enough for Wired magazine's July issue.
The new Model 8500 fly-fishing reel from Charlton Outdoor
Technologies is designed to take fishing to new levels.
Technologically speaking, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Engineered by Jack Charlton _ who worked for three decades in
the aerospace industry _ the reel's drag system is made of carbon
fiber, the same material used in B-2 bomber brakes, says Wired. The
result is a line tension that is stunningly smooth. At $3,600, it
isn't for the casual fisherman. But fishing is about something much
more elevated than mere economics, anyhow.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, visit the Web site
(http://www.fishdoc.com).
</P>
<P>
   Fingers do the talking
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Computer has recently unveiled a fingerprint
identification technology meant to protect computers from unwanted
use. The product, meant primarily for small businesses, will cost
about $100 and be available in August. Only the right set of
fingerprints would be able to log on to the computer. For more
information, call Compaq (1-800-OK-COMPAQ) or visit the company Web
site (http://www.compaq.com).
</P>
<P>
   Speak no evil
</P>
<P>
   Talking is an important part of the job for a lot of
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   A certain breed _ especially doctors and lawyers _ spend a lot
of time talking to tape recorders, making tapes that must later be
transcribed. Turning the tapes into briefs, reports and letters is
a time-consuming and costly process.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon Systems suggests a shortcut.
</P>
<P>
   The accuracy of voice recognition software has continually
improved. But voice recognition from companies like upstart Dragon
and mighty IBM has mostly been built for personal computers. The
systems allow a user to sit at the desktop and talk into a PC. But
what about the wandering professional _ the lawyer dictating
letters in his car, the doctor making notes while on her rounds?
</P>
<P>
   Dragon will market a hand-held digital system for speech
recognition that uses the minidisc player-recorder from Sony. A
user creates the text by speaking into the minidisc recorder.
Later, the recording can be transcribed by Dragon software.
Dragon's mobile system will be on the market in August, with a
price tag of about $1,300.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call Dragon Systems or visit the company
Web site (http://www.naturalspeech.com). For IBM products, start at
the company Web site (http://www.ibm.com).
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Wired magazine suggests a word to describe the
mistakes that a voice recognition system makes. You can't say typo,
because it involves no typing. So what is a mis-transcribed word?
</P>
<P>
   A speako.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
