A5955 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-WATER29-COX     07-28 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-WATER29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drip by drip, Austin's water slips away
 &HT;    By Kelly Daniel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Patty Thomas thought she was conservative with water,
maybe even frugal, until the phone rang and she got news she never
imagined she'd hear about her West Lynn Street house.
</P>
<P>
   The home was the 10th-largest residential water user in all of
Austin last year, a City of Austin utility employee told Thomas.
Her jaw dropped, a reaction shared by others who heard they were
among the largest water consumers in the nation's 22nd-largest city
_ now under voluntary water restrictions thanks to this summer's
drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not flagrantly pouring water all over the place,''
Thomas said. She said a leaky underground sprinkler system on their
1-acre lot in West Austin is the reason they used 1,246,200 gallons
last year _ more than four times as much water a month as the
average family of four. The Thomases limit their teen-age son to
10-minute showers, run sprinklers just 15 minutes and try to save
water to the extent that ``I don't even flush the toilet every time
I go,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's top water users, both residential and commercial, say
they try to conserve. But though they cut back, they still use
enough water to fill at least 15 swimming pools a month.
</P>
<P>
   Several top users said they conserve by watering only twice a
week. But that's still more than Austin's 150,000 water customers
are allowed under the city's voluntary water conservation measures.
The city asks that residents water only once every five days.
</P>
<P>
   The list of top water users was provided by the City of Austin
utilities department under state open records laws.
</P>
<P>
   Thirsty chips
</P>
<P>
   At Motorola, where water is crucial to the chip-making process,
technicians are working on a $1.5 million project to recycle 60
percent of the water the company uses. Motorola currently recycles
20 percent of the water it uses to rinse electronic parts between
each of the 120 steps it takes to build a chip. If it can recycle
more, the company can cut overall water use by 50 percent within
three years, said Asanga Weerakoon, Motorola's director of
environmental safety and industrial hygiene. Motorola was Austin's
top commercial water user in 1996-97, draining 1.9 billion gallons.
</P>
<P>
   A parched Austin is 5.63 inches below normal rainfall for the
year. After recording only 1.56 inches of rain in June, Austin has
seen just .9 inches this month.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the drought, Motorola has been using rainwater
collected in its retention pond to water the grass and turning up
office thermostats to use less water in cooling towers that power
the air conditioning. Other big users are trying somewhat similar
methods to conserve.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Texas, which ranked third-highest among
commercial water users in 1996-97, collects water used in
professors' laboratories and classrooms and uses it in cooling
towers for air conditioning, said Miles Abernathy, an engineer in
the utilities and energy management department. The towers need
more water than the university can recycle, so Abernathy's
department is exploring whether it can afford to buy reclaimed
water _ wastewater that has been treated but isn't drinkable _from
the city to use in the cooling towers. If so, UT will cut down its
water consumption from the current 825 million gallons a year.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, the No. 4 commercial water user last year, reuses 60
percent to 70 percent of its water, said Lynn Denton, a spokesman.
This year, IBM has had to buy extra water from Austin to irrigate
its grounds for construction projects, but the company usually
relies on nine wells it keeps on site, Denton said. Because water
conservation methods are built in to the company's operations, IBM
hasn't changed its routine for the drought, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other agencies, however, have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've cut watering 20 percent,'' said Rick Crawford, executive
director of the State Preservation Board, which maintains the St.
Augustine grass around the Capitol. They could've used a
less-thirsty type of grass, but picked St. Augustine because of its
beauty and lushness, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since June, the Capitol grounds have been watered four days a
week, instead of five, with timed sprinklers soaking the grass 15
to 40 minutes. Meanwhile, the rest of Austin is asked to water
lawns only once every five days. Austin's current voluntary
restrictions become mandatory only if the city's 150,000 water
customers use 210 million gallons a day for three straight days or
215 million gallons on a single day. Usage hit record levels
Saturday, with 202 million gallons, and Sunday, with 205 million
gallons.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitol also uses low-flow toilets and sink faucets that
activate only when someone's hands are directly under the nozzle,
so water can't be wasted, Crawford said. Across the street, the
Governor's Mansion grounds get water every day, but by zones, so
the same area isn't watered more than three times a week, said
administrator Anne DeBois.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford didn't know how much water it takes to keep the Capitol
grounds lush, because the water bill lists everything from grass
maintenance to toilets and water fountains inside the building. A
$7.9 million renovation project that included redoing the grounds
was completed in 1997, so keeping the grass healthy is as much an
investment as source of pride for the symbol of Texas government,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lush lawns
</P>
<P>
   Roy A. Butler, a former Austin mayor, understands pride in a
yard. His Niles Road estate is a paradise of lushness, with green
St. Augustine grass covering most of his two-acre lot. The Butlers
were Austin's second-highest residential water users last year,
using 201,000 gallons a month _ nearly as much as the average
family of four uses in a year. Across the street, Frank P.
Krasovec's Niles Road home was No. 6 last year. Their neighbor, the
Pease Mansion, now owned by the General Services Commission but
owned by the Shivers family in 1996-97, was the top residential
user. The Pease mansion is following Austin's voluntary watering
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Butler said his family has cut back watering this summer,
running sprinklers only at midnight when they figure demand is at a
low and only twice a week. So far, that level has kept the yard
thriving, he said. If water restrictions kick in, the Butlers will
have to follow the schedule other Austinites already use.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still sort of experimenting, frankly, in cutting back
and seeing if everything lives,'' Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the homeowners listed as top water users quibble with
the figures, saying they can't believe it's possible to use that
much water at their homes. Like Thomas, several said leaky
sprinkler systems are to blame and they are hiring contractors to
fix the problems. Several also said they did not pay their monthly
bills themselves, giving that chore to accountants, for example,
and therefore had no idea their use was that high until city
utility employees called them after the Austin American-Statesman
requested the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock to us, needless to say,'' said Duane Albrecht,
a UT physiology professor whose Newning Drive home in South Austin
was the No. 3 residential water user last year. `` It just doesn't
seem physically possible somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
