<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5956 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIBLE29-COX     07-28 1951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIBLE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With credibility at stake, news media goes soul-searching
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Embarrassing retractions and admitted
fabrications have caused media credibility to come under fire this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of CNN's apology for an erroneous report alleging
that the U.S. military used nerve gas on defectors and civilians
during the Vietnam War, a recent Newsweek opinion poll found that a
majority of Americans believe news reports are often inaccurate.
Even more, 63 percent, say recent inaccuracies have made them less
likely to believe news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Recent journalistic scandals have prompted news organizations to
engage in some serious soul-searching in the past few months. How
can a CNN-level disaster be prevented, and how can the public be
convinced that truth is more important than hype and profit? Since
an overwhelming majority of Americans depend on TV as their primary
source for news, credibility is a serious issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are broader problems in our industry than just these
crash-and-burn incidents,'' said Arthur Kent, a former reporter for
the Canadian Broadcasting Co. and NBC who now free-lances foreign
news from London. ``Real reporters need to help management see the
need to re-establish credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Increased competition has caused some journalists to relax their
standards,experts say. CNN's egregious error came about in a report
by veteran journalist Peter Arnett on the debut telecast of
``NewsStand,'' a newsmagazine that airs every night. Going up
against nearly a dozen other newsmagazines, the program wanted to
premiere with a big story that would make news. That goal was
accomplished, but not in a positive light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seasoned journalists have never had less influence in setting
the news agenda,'' Kent said. ``We need to point out that if we
abandon traditions of balance, perspective and reason, credibility
will be blown and profits from softer news will fritter away. The
public will lose confidence in broadcast news, as they're beginning
to do now.''
</P>
<P>
   The CNN fiasco is certainly not the first humiliating blow to TV
news. In 1993, NBC admitted it staged an explosion in a ``Dateline
NBC'' report on truck safety. In '95, ABC apologized (as part of a
lawsuit settlement) for alleging that tobacco companies manipulated
the level of nicotine in cigarettes. ABC also was forced to settle
a lawsuit brought by a grocery store chain that said the network
practiced deceitful reporting when an undercover reporter lied to
gain employment in one of the stores.
</P>
<P>
   And TV news isn't alone in suffering credibility problems. Time
magazine, which ran the CNN story, also ran a retraction and an
apology to its readers. Before that, the Boston Globe fired
columnist Patricia Smith for making up quotes and characters in
several columns; the New Republic fired reporter Stephen Glass for
making up all or part of 27 magazine articles; and the Cincinnati
Enquirer retracted a report on Chiquita Banana that was based on
information stolen from voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   Sensational stories
</P>
<P>
   Confidence in the news media was strong during the Vietnam War
and Watergate, according to polls at the time, but has eroded
steadily since the advent of so-called tabloid news. Many consumers
see little difference between network news stories, such as the
frenzied coverage of the O.J. Simpson murder trial and President
Clinton's alleged womanizing, and reports on gruesome murders and
Hollywood sex scandals covered by shows such as ``Hard Copy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a Catch-22 for TV news executives, since the Simpson trial
reports sent ratings soaring. Newsmagazines, newscasts and news
specials attracted record numbers of viewers during that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we deliver top ratings but undermine our credibility, we
have failed,'' said David Westin, president of ABC News. ``Ratings
shouldn't be the be-all for the news divisions. Success should be
judged on the quality of reporting, integrity and a sense of
responsibility. Are we explaining or just pulling something off a
wire and putting on a pretty face?''
</P>
<P>
   With so many places for people to turn for news, news
organizations are clamoring for attention with sensational stories
that are easy to promote. The Lewinsky story took on a life of its
own, with breathless reports from the White House lawn about new
revelations _ or rumors about revelations _ every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can turn anything into a daily soap opera, and people will
watch,'' Kent said. ``People are willing to be entertained by all
that stuff, but they probably don't believe a word of it. President
Clinton is still popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the credibility problem is the focus on sensational
stories to the exclusion of serious, issue-oriented coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 50 crews in D.C. following Monica Lewinsky, but the
networks had no reporters in India when the nuclear bomb was set
off,'' Kent lamented. ``Balance used to be the hallmark of network
news, but now I think we've lost perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Concurring with him is Ted Turner, who founded CNN and nurtured
it from its early days as the ridiculed ``Chicken Noodle Network''
to the serious, worldwide news organization it is today .
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure for profits is so great,'' he said in an
apology-filled appearance in front of the Television Critics
Association in Los Angeles recently. ``We're all trying to cut
expenses and increase profits. And there are so many other sources
available to people. . . . We're working on hundreds of stories at
any given moment. We've made mistakes and near-mistakes before, but
nothing this big has ever happened. Maybe we tried to take on too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC, which will add another newsmagazine to its lineup this
fall, has long prided itself on in-depth reporting of domestic and
foreign news. But in the past two years, ``World News Tonight'' has
fallen behind NBC's flashier, more feature-oriented ``Nightly
News'' in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pivotal time for TV news,'' Westin said. ``Because
there's been a dramatic increase in competition, there's been a
tendency to try to be noticed or be quicker on the trigger. All of
us have seen some risk-taking. . . . It's always more important to
be right than to be first. We all have a competitive zeal, but we
have to have checks and balances. We continually ask ourselves,
'Are we sure about that story?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Newsweek opinion poll found that 77 percent of those
surveyed felt that journalists were more likely to be influenced by
pressure for higher ratings and profits than in the past, and 71
percent believed journalists were too concerned with becoming
celebrities or getting rich.
</P>
<P>
   Who's behind the news?
</P>
<P>
   The CNN incident may have seemed more shocking than other
incidents because the on-camera reporter acknowledged that he had
little to do with the broadcast. Arnett, who helped establish CNN
with his sharp reporting from Baghdad during the Persian Gulf War,
admitted he came late to the story, which had been reported
primarily by two producers, April Oliver and Jack Smith. Arnett,
who earned a Pulitzer Prize covering the Vietnam War for the
Associated Press in 1966, was the face on the screen, but he was
merely responsible for supplying the voice-over and conducting a
couple of interviews using questions from the producers.
</P>
<P>
   What many viewers may not realize is that TV news producers are
reporters, too. They're just not presenters. That task is usually
performed by the ``news stars'' whom viewers have come to know and
trust. After the CNN retraction, CNN President Tom Johnson fired
the two producers but only reprimanded Arnett. CNN has said it will
no longer allow its reporters to ``front'' a story without being
involved in fact-gathering and reporting.
</P>
<P>
   But the practice of on-camera reporters functioning as
presenters rather than investigators and fact-gatherers is not
uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Participation of reporters runs the gamut,'' Kent said.
``Sometimes we research, write, edit and present. You do run into
situations where you're asked just to present. It's not unusual.
You trust your producers with your credibility, but you have to be
confident in the material you bring to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC reporter Jack Smith (not the same Jack Smith who was fired
from CNN) said he has done voice-overs, too, although he prefers to
report and write everything he puts on the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's very difficult to do absolutely everything,'' said
Smith, a Vietnam veteran and the son of legendary TV reporter
Howard K. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Although reluctant to criticize Arnett, Smith said the nerve gas
story ``didn't pass even the most elementary journalistic smell
test. ... Serious reporters I know haven't bought into these kinds
of Rambo stories. (The CNN producers) really believed the story at
the outset, and that's always a danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said when a story seems suspicious, on-camera reporters
should check the facts themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Westin, ABC News president, said his reporters ultimately are
responsible for stories they present on the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would never, never do a serious investigative piece and
have a correspondent come in at the last minute to do a
voice-over,'' Westin said. ``Producers do a lot of reporting, but
our correspondents wouldn't want to just be a face on the piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Crisis management
</P>
<P>
   CNN's faulty reporting prompted heated criticism, but the way
the cable network handled the aftermath has earned almost universal
praise. CNN's Johnson quickly hired media attorney Floyd Abrams to
investigate the accuracy of the reporting, and when Abrams
concluded that the evidence did not support the conclusions, an
on-air apology was made.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also took steps to prevent future problems. On-air
reporters at CNN are now responsible for all stories they present,
and CNN executive Rick Davis will review all significant reporting
for accuracy and fairness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the way this situation has been handled by Tom Johnson
and his management team has been striking and most effective,''
Kent said. ``They let the journalists themselves explain their role
in this controversy. They've thrown open their books, their
archives, their outtakes. . . . That was almost unprecedented, and
I think that has helped work toward a constructive solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The mea culpas and corrective actions must have worked because
the Newsweek poll found that CNN remains the most believable news
organization, followed by newspapers and network news.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson learned from this summer's disaster, media insiders
say, is that news organizations need to be ever-vigilant in
maintaining high standards. Putting a story on the air without
complete evidence and balanced reporting will backfire, ultimately
undermining credibility and driving viewers away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't guarantee anything,'' Turner said. ``This was a very
poor journalistic decision, and we're doing all we can to make sure
it never happens again. Everybody makes mistakes, and this was a
really big one.''
</P>
<P>
   Media watchdog groups suggest that TV news should follow the
lead of the print medium and set aside regular spots for
corrections and clarifications. The last few minutes of the Friday
evening newscast would be a logical place. Broadcast news rarely
runs corrections, unless the goof is major and/or involves legal
action. Some media experts think a corrections segment would show
viewers that accuracy is a major concern and inspire reporters to
be more careful.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Holloway is the TV critic for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
