<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RV-TIPS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tips on RV travel
 &HT;    By Ricardo Gandara
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Get a brochure from Cruise America (800-327-7799), one of the
largest RV rental companies with 100 outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Get a free video on RV cruising from the Recreational Vehicle
Industry Association (888-467-8464).
</P>
<P>
   Before booking a trip, go to an RV dealership in your area to
get an idea of their size and type. Check the Yellow Pages under
``Recreational Vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   The RV America Web site (www.rvamerica.com) has a list of
dealers, clubs and RV resources.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO PREPARE
</P>
<P>
   When you pick up your RV, you'll get a short orientation. Take
notes. Ask plenty of questions. Make sure you're clear on how to
hook up electricity, sewer and water at a campground. Don't leave
any doubts about operating the appliances. Ask where the fuse panel
is located. Then, read the manual that explains all the functions
of the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Before you leave for your trip, you may want to go to a local
dealer to get a practice run of setting up at a campground. They
are glad to help.
</P>
<P>
   The RV rental outlet will try to sell you extra kits (bedding,
utensils, flashlight, etc.). If you take it with you, the savings
are significant.
</P>
<P>
   Bring tools (a flat screwdriver, a Phillips screwdriver, an
adjustable wrench, pliers).
</P>
<P>
   Make reservations at all campgrounds, even state parks. KOA's
Web site is www.koakampgrounds.com. Call that state's tourism
department for RV parking at state parks which can be cheaper than
private camps.
</P>
<P>
   ONCE YOU'RE THERE
</P>
<P>
   When parking, have someone get out and guide you.
</P>
<P>
   Plan your trip so that you get to your camping sites in the
daylight. There is nothing worse than a first timer pulling into
into a camp at 10 p.m. and trying to hook up hoses. Always ask for
a full hookup site because this enables you to use their water and
sewer disposal instead of your vehicle's tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Most rental agencies have a toll-free number to call for
problems you encounter on the road. Use it often.
</P>
<P>
   Renting a motor home is not like renting a car. You have to
maintain the RV. If it's trashed out, it can cost $50; $100 for a
sewer tank that's not empty.
</P>
<P>
   Using RV toilet paper and chemicals to keep your sewer lines
flowing will save you nasty maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
