<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5958 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RV-TRAVEL29-COX     07-28 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RV-TRAVEL29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A wheel family vacation
 &HT;    By Ricardo Ga(accent)ndara
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Entry in my travel journal:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can lose myself on this road through the old growth forest
of lacy ferns, towering Douglas fir and even taller Sitka spruce. A
herd of Olympic elk cautiously watches me as I bring my rig to a
stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotta get a picture. Just ahead is the Hoh Rain Forest with
its Hall of Moss walking trail. There's an alert about possible
encounters with a cougar and a black bear and her cub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travel is great in a motor home. Susan can grab me a Coke from
the fridge. And when the kids need to potty, I pull off to the
shoulder so they can use the on-board toilet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is hassle-free traveling.''
</P>
<P>
   This was real adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Logging 1,000 miles in a rented 29-foot motor home in the
Pacific Northwest was a vacation we had only imagined. We always
fly to point A, rent a car and drive to tourist sites B, C and D.
This was different, pleasantly different. If my family of five,
plus mother-in-law, can survive each other in tight quarters for a
week, anyone can.
</P>
<P>
   Our excursion gave new meaning to travel. Sure, we could have
rented a sport utility vehicle and a cabin near a lake. This,
however, provided more independence and self-sufficiency. On
conventional vacations, we often are at the mercy of other people's
schedules and rules. This time, we could do what we wanted, when we
wanted, and everything we needed _ clothes, food, a hot shower _
was on board.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder RV rentals were up 30 percent last year, according to
the Recreational Vehicle Industry Association. More than 10 million
recreational ational vehicles _ everything from folding camping
trailers to conversion vehicles to motor homes _ are on the road
today with more than 16,000 public and private campgrounds
nationwide to park them.
</P>
<P>
   Why an RV vacation? Think this was a guy thing?
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   My wife Susan decided this would be our big getaway for the
year. I always had been curious when I passed a majestic Winnebago
on the road, and we were crammed in our SUV. What did they look
like inside? Were they as luxurious as we imagined?
</P>
<P>
   I always thought of them as too big, slow and out of my price
range. But, like more and more families each year, I learned that
vacationing in an RV is not only affordable but has great family
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Kids love them.
</P>
<P>
   My girls _ 6-year-old Alexandra, 4-year-old Victoria and
22-month-old Isabella _ had a ball. The older girls loved sleeping
in the bed over the cab of our Class C motor home, which is the
preferred family setup that sleeps four to six people.
</P>
<P>
   The girls enjoyed the scenic drives in Oregon, Washington and
British Columbia, Canada, through the RV's sightseeing-friendly
large windows. And they enjoyed the antics of Austin author Joanne
King Holtzman's ``The Fat Rat and This and That'' audiocassette, a
treasure of children's songs that encouraged them to dance and
move, and kept them occupied on some of the longer stretches of
highway.
</P>
<P>
   RV vacations are comparable to conventional getaways. They can
cost less, especially if six or more people are in your party ($600
to $1,200, plus gas, food and campground fees). Our seven-day
package (picking up and returning the motor home in Portland) cost
$866 plus $130 in gas. The first 1,000 miles were free, then we
were charged 29 cents a mile. The Kampgrounds of America sites
where we stayed were $28 to $32 a night for a full hookup of
electricity, water and sewer.
</P>
<P>
   The ``California Flyer'' on a Chevy van chassis we rented had a
queen bed, a restroom complete with shower, a fridge and freezer, a
stove and microwave and plenty of storage space for souvenirs.
Larger and more luxurious motor homes we saw at campgrounds had
washers and dryers and televisions with satellite dishes to pick up
300 channels _ basically the amenities of a home on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Mealtimes were a snap. Susan cooked hot breakfasts for the
adults, and the kids ate cold cereal. We stopped at delis for
sandwich meat. The fridge and pantry were stocked with kids'
snacks, juice and milk. In the morning, I always had fresh coffee.
</P>
<P>
   The lure of the outdoors is the biggest draw. You can take an RV
to the mountains, beaches, on ferries to parts of Canada, just
about anywhere. We rented our rig in Portland, drove northwest into
Washington and camped at Monte and Frances Decker's KOA in Port
Angeles. This was more than a campground. It offered miniature
golf, horseshoes, basketball, volleyball, pool, video arcade,
billiards, cable TV, hot tub, showers, cabins and a laundry. Tours
to Victoria, B.C., were available with transportation provided from
the campground.
</P>
<P>
   A motor home is not a total party. You have to dump your black
water (sewage) at campgrounds. It's a snap and not messy if you
wear plastic gloves and pay close attention during the 15-minute
orientation when you rent the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   You may feel uneasy the first day, but RVs are pretty easy to
drive and it gets easier each day.
</P>
<P>
   Hit the road
</P>
<P>
   Our first full day of exploration was the diverse and beautiful
world of the Olympic National Forest where, if a rain forest
doesn't capture your attention, a glacier will. We pulled over
several times along winding U.S. 101 to take photos of calm and
sparkling Lake Crescent. The Sul Doc Hot Springs were elbow to
elbow with bathers, so we walked the easily accessible
three-quarter-mile trek to Sol Duc Falls. On to the Hoh Rain
Forest, where you are in another spectacular world of ferns
carpeting the ground and moss draped from Sitka spruce trees.
</P>
<P>
   We could have stayed at Olympic National Park an entire week and
taken in other sites like Hurricane Ridge, but the Butchart Gardens
and the old world charm of Victoria, B.C., awaited us. The ferry
from Port Angeles, Wash., accommodated RVs ($60 one way). A
comfortable night's stay at John and Kathy Erickson's KOA
Kcampground tucked into a forest north of Victoria was just what we
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Be prepared to be overwhelmed by 50-acre Butchart Gardens, where
rare and exotic plants share space with native varieties. If
wildlife is your thing, marine safaris to see killer whales,
porpoises, seals and marine birds are plentiful. Or take in the
historic and magnificent Empress Hotel for pricey ($32 in Canadian
dollars) high tea.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop was Seattle, where during breakfast at the revolving,
520-foot Space Needle restaurant downtown _ built for the 1962
World's Fair _ we saw an unobstructed view of mammoth 14,410-foot,
snow-covered Mount Rainier. We had no trouble parking in public
lots but paid for two spots.
</P>
<P>
   Pike's Market on the water is a gem. Come hungry to enjoy food
from around the world. Seattle's, with 54 Starbucks, has an obvious
love affair with coffee.
</P>
<P>
   The monstrous motor home did not hamper us. In fact, it provided
us with flexibility. We met people on the road who towed a car or
rented one to get around cities while their RV was at a campground.
</P>
<P>
   Totally satisfied
</P>
<P>
   Usually, as I get close to the end of my vacation, I want my own
bed. Home starts sounding good. We did not feel that way. The kids
were sad their ``camping'' trip was over. Their comfy bed over the
cab had become home.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Gandara writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
