<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5960 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RV-TRIP29-COX     07-28 1649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RV-TRIP29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern Comfort, RV-Style
 &HT;    By Melissa Segrest
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I am not an RV kinda gal.
</P>
<P>
   When my friends learned that I would be traversing the South in
a rented 27-foot recreational vehicle, they snickered. What had
overcome their Vogue-readin', Pinot grigio-sippin', Volvo-drivin'
buddy, they asked. Heretofore, they reminded me, my idea of a
recreational vehicle has been a Mercedes with tinted windows on a
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   So you might find it surprising to learn that somewhere on a
desolate stretch of Interstate 10, between Biloxi, Miss., and
Vinton, La., I began to understand the RV allure. I believe my
enlightenment struck as I lay atop the king-size bed, reading old
New York Times Magazines and munching Cheez-Doodles _ all while
hurtling down the highway.
</P>
<P>
   That, my friends, is a strange and wondrous sensation.
</P>
<P>
   It started with my 7-year-old daughter's obsession with RVs _ a
more costly fascination than Beanie Babies and Barbies.
</P>
<P>
   And it's my old boss's fault, too. When you get a new job, she
advised, it's important to drive to one's new home, to feel the
country under your wheels, to cross the miles and put your old home
behind you.
</P>
<P>
   So when a new job in Austin materialized, it seemed that the
time was right to give the RV thing a try.
</P>
<P>
   Getting one was simple enough. A call to (800) 334-4110
connected me to the nearest RV rental outlet: Cruise America in
Miami, a mere 80 miles from our Palm Beach Gardens, Fla., home.
After some telephone negotiations, and a $300 deposit, our RV was
reserved. The total cost would be a little more than $1,500; we had
to pay an extra $375 for the one-way rental.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before our departure, my husband and I drove to Miami to
make the pickup. After a wait in line, we watched a 20-minute
instructional video featuring a portly and disturbingly friendly
fellow who told us of propane monitor panels and gray water holding
tanks.
</P>
<P>
   I hoped my husband was listening. Taking a Flyer
</P>
<P>
   We signed some papers and were escorted to the parking lot
where, with a flourish, we stepped aboard our vehicle _ a
glistening white, new ``California Flyer.'' I was stunned. This was
nice. There were two beds _ one king and one queen, a bathroom with
a shower, a kitchen complete with four-burner stove, double sink,
refrigerator/freezer and kitchen-area table with bench seats on
either side. There were little closets beside the master bed, with
little rods with little hangers where I could hang my clothes.
</P>
<P>
   I could see myself living here for a while. After a few more
instructions, we were on our way.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Fred was on his way. The idea of my getting behind the
wheel of any vehicle that beeps when it is backing up is too far
from my frame of reference, so my husband gallantly offered to
drive our home-on-wheels home.
</P>
<P>
   He also had gallantly plotted our plodding course across the
South, allotting not too much and not too little time on the road
each day. We would stay in a few of the many RV parks and
Kampgrounds of America sites along the way. We would see the
country. We would bond as a family.
</P>
<P>
   On the road
</P>
<P>
   Day 1's journey ended a mere five hours north on Florida's
Turnpike, in a wide spot in the road called Wildwood. We decamped
and plugged in, as they say in RV-speak, and then took in the
sights of the KOA campground: a grizzled mini-golf course, a clean
swimming pool and plenty of room for our two standard poodles to
stretch out. After Fred went through the 10-minute process of
connecting us to electricity, water and sewer lines, we were set.
</P>
<P>
   And we were alone. This park, desolate in the Florida heat, was
pocketed behind a truck stop and a Steak &AMP; Shake. No frills. And
not much fun.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, a quick exit was in order, and it was on to
Panama City Beach at the crook of Florida's Panhandle. Our bustling
KOA campground was near the heart of the tourist area and a stone's
throw from the Gulf of Mexico. Now this was more fun. Lots of
families here, enjoying the beachy scene from the luxury of their
lavish RVs. The ``Flyer'' was dwarfed by Winnebagos with living
room ``slide-outs'' and 60-foot bus conversions complete with
satellite dishes and Surround Sound systems.
</P>
<P>
   We began to feel inferior.
</P>
<P>
   A stroll to nearby restaurants and kitschy shops _ along with
another round of mini-golf _ put a lovely capper on the evening.
Heck, we even had a cable hookup for the tiny TV we brought along.
(No, I cannot function without TV.)
</P>
<P>
   Biloxi or bust
</P>
<P>
   Day 3 began with the now-traditional Waffle House breakfast, and
it was off for the drive to Biloxi, Miss. Beautiful Gulf vistas and
impressive houses raced by the picture windows. We talked. We
walked around. We napped. We played cards and laughed. We ate
lunch. We yelled at the dogs _ all within the comfort of our RV.
Lots of forced quality family time. We were getting closer. I could
just feel it (or was that just fleas?)
</P>
<P>
   We were virtually singing ``Kum-ba-yah'' by the time we pulled
in to our RV park for the day. The good mood ended abruptly when we
were told that all of the campground's sites were taken for the
night. Why, I asked, would an RV park in the middle of Biloxi,
Miss., be full in the middle of the summer? My answer lay right
across U.S. 90: a sprawling casino. The last time I had been in
Biloxi, a decade earlier, the city had been serene and sedate. Now
it was neon-pocked and buzzing with the hubbub of dozens of
casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Driving down the Gulf Coast highway in search of another RV
park, we noticed the beaches were oddly deserted at midday. But the
casino parking lots were jammed. Who wants to swim when the slot
machines are calling?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we found the Cajun RV Park _ tucked behind an adult
bookstore and a motel. Despite the seedy setting, the place looked
clean and serviceable, so we paid our $25, hooked up and settled
in. My husband and daughter headed off for the pool, and I hunkered
down in the cool darkness of the RV. Outside, the temperatures
hovered around 100 degrees. Dozens of lavish RVs were there, but
not a soul was moving around outside. Everyone was hiding from the
heat in their luxury vehicles. It seemed odd that someone would
spend tens of thousands of dollars on a recreational vehicle only
to come to a place like Biloxi, park behind a dirty bookstore and
hide from the world.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. It was too hot for such deep thoughts. We asked for a
good restaurant and were told that the only decent food was _
surprise _ at the casinos. Conveniently, a shuttle made regular
stops at the RV park, so we boarded one and headed for the Grand
Casino. Inside, the bright lights and bells and whistles of the
glistening, bustling casino seemed like a fantasy wonderland to our
7-year-old. We tried to explain the wages of sin and gluttony to
her as we waited in line for a lavish and reasonably priced buffet
of Cajun dishes and fresh seafood. My warnings about the dangerous
lure of gambling must have seemed empty after I wandered off to
drop $10 in the slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   Before I surrendered to the urge to don a halter top and start
playing craps, we escaped from Biloxi _ stopping only for another
hearty Waffle House breakfast. We abandoned the picturesque road
that hugged the Gulf coast to join the speeders on Interstate 10,
lunched at _ guess where _ a casino in Baton Rouge and sped through
southwest Louisiana to Vinton, La., about 120 miles east of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Et tu, etouffee?
</P>
<P>
   We pulled into a crowded Vinton/Lake Charles KOA by late
afternoon, plugged in and hit the mini-golf course and pool. We
eagerly looked forward to a dinner of etouffee , boudin and
jambalaya at some down-home diner here in the heart of Cajun
country. Imagine our disappointment to learn that all the down-home
Cajun eateries had been run out of business by _ you guessed it _
casinos. Now this was getting irritating. Whole stretches of the
South, it appeared, had been swallowed up by the gluttonous
gambling industry. Mom and Pop diners were gone, replaced by Golden
Nugget casinos where all the food was fried and all the patrons had
the glassy-eyed stares of people who had just gambled away that
month's rent.
</P>
<P>
   Disgusting.
</P>
<P>
   So we went to the horse races.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that the track was a stone's throw from the RV park,
and I had never seen a horse race before and Emily loves horses and
. . . oh, forget it. We had lost any semblance of propriety. We
were taking our child to gambling establishments and eating fried
food, and I had stopped putting on any makeup somewhere around
Sulphur, La.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the heat, or the laid-back RV culture, or perhaps
it was the fact that we had been staying in close quarters with a
couple of poodles for too many days _ something had messed with our
well-ordered sensibilities. We were losing our sense of self. I
yearned for a walk-in closet.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with some relief that we pulled into the Elk Rental
and Leasing lot on U.S. 290 to return the Flyer to the good folks
at Cruise America. I was back in my home state of Texas, behind the
wheel of the Volvo. All was right with the world.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the RV experience wasn't fun. It's a great way to
see the country, and it's far superior to actual camping out of
doors. But given my druthers, I'd rather spend the money on a
massage at a beachfront Ritz-Carlton.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and child, however, are already planning our next
trip, talking about the relative merit of Class A vs. Class C RVs
we pass on the road and longing for the day when we might own a
recreational vehicle of our own.
</P>
<P>
   That will be nice.
</P>
<P>
   I hope they send me postcards.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Segrest is Assistant Managing Editor/Features for the
Austin American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
