<HEADER>
A5961 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN29-COX     07-28 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Subtle victories mark grandma's early feminism
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio. Feminism was not a word in my Grandmother
Parker's vocabulary. She lived and died too soon, long before Betty
and Gloria
</P>
<P>
   showed up and much too long before I was of an age where we
might have talked woman-to-woman. And that is too bad.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Parker (I was encouraged to call her that to avoid what she
referred to as ``simpering sobriquet'') was, without doubt, a woman
ahead
</P>
<P>
   of her time. She fought no visible battles for equality nor did
she burn a bra on the courthouse steps (in fact, rumor has it, she
never wore
</P>
<P>
   one). Her skirmishes were more personal, more subtle, her
victories unproclaimed but no less sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Grandmother Parker didn't like me - but that's okay. She didn't
like her daughter either. ``I love you dammit Doris,'' I remember
her
</P>
<P>
   admonishing my mother on more than one occasion, ``but that
doesn't mean you don't irritate the hell out of me. Now, quit
whining.'' Mother would
</P>
<P>
   bug out to her old bedroom room to pout. I'd cadge a ``Co-Cola
over ice, please'' from the kitchen and disappear onto the shady
screened porch to
</P>
<P>
   play with Granddaddy's poker chips and watch for bugs.
</P>
<P>
   My fear of Florida's creepy-crawlers exasperated Grandmother. It
made no difference to her that I had not grown up with flying
cockroaches the
</P>
<P>
   size of pterodactyls or house spiders larger than saucers. With
her it was a matter of principle. ``Who's going to kill bugs for
you when your
</P>
<P>
   daddy isn't around?'' I told her I had no idea. She told me not
to count on a husband.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Parker had gone her own way long before women were
encouraged to bob their hair and roll down their stockings. Oh, she
still participated
</P>
<P>
   in the ``lady things'' as she referred to her afternoon teas,
bridge parties, and Red Cross drills, but it was not unheard of for
her to drop
</P>
<P>
   a handful of cards (or teacakes) and race out the door when she
heard a fire engine's blare on nearby Osceola Street - one of the
main drags in
</P>
<P>
   the Riverside section of Jacksonville. Day or night, she never
resisted the siren's call
</P>
<P>
   Granddaddy suggested she get a job at the newspaper so she could
have a press card to snap onto the sun visor; that way he said,
it'd look
</P>
<P>
   like she was a working person instead of a nosy old lady.
Grandmother's standard reply to advice like that was: ``Anyone who
has the time to
</P>
<P>
   worry about what I'm doing has nothing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, Grandmother did worry about other folks' business -
usually for all of the right reasons. Frequently, she would offer
her
</P>
<P>
   time and resources to some ``poor old soul'' who might be living
down the street in suddenly reduced circumstances or whose husband
was suspected
</P>
<P>
   of having taken to hard liquor and even harder women. In her own
odd way, she always tried to help.
</P>
<P>
   In the early part of this century when Mrs. Parker was a young
mother (very young with three babies), pretty much everything
needed in the
</P>
<P>
   running of a house was delivered to the back door. Grandmother
saw that as imprisonment and began preaching the virtues of
mobility. It was her
</P>
<P>
   solemn belief that a woman who couldn't drive was doomed to live
a life in bondage. Her solution: she taught her entire Sunday
School class to drive.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday mornings when she should have been recounting meaningful
parables to six young matrons, she could be found leading them out
the
</P>
<P>
   back door of the First Baptist Church and into her husband's
Packard for a practice run to Riverside Park. Everybody got a turn.
Grandmother was
</P>
<P>
   meticulously fair.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long before the word was out and Mrs. Parker's driving
school was scandalizing the town. Irate husbands called Granddaddy,
</P>
<P>
   worried about their wives skidding down the highway to
degradation or worse - independence. ``I'll speak with Mrs.
Parker,'' was always his
</P>
<P>
   response. And he did. My mother loved to recount one of these
sessions that occurred over a family breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edna,'' Granddaddy began with his pince-nez glasses firmly
clamped onto the bridge of his nose, ``you're upsetting a lot of
folks with this
</P>
<P>
   driving thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good, Ernest,'' was his diminutive wife's reply as she
concentrated on buttering her toast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shall you stop it then?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Very well.'' There was no discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Parker picked up his newspaper and resumed reading. Mrs.
Parker finished her toast and the ad hoc driving school remained in
operation.
</P>
<P>
   No signs. No banners. No marches. Just one lady determined to
make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
