<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5962 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN29-COX     07-28 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Great surplus giveaway
</P>
<P>
   By John Young
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   It must be a joke. Congressman John Kasich poses before the
National Debt Clock on the ``Kasich 2000'' web page that touts him
as presidential material.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers on that clock _ $5.36 trillion as of Monday, $20,490
per person _ are supposed to alarm us all to action.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of action? Gut-wrenching patriotic sacrifice?
Visionary tough decisions? You must be joking.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio Republican might as well be posing before a gumball
machine with a screw driver plunged into its bowels. Step right up
and have a gumball. Have three. We've got 'em coming out our ears.
</P>
<P>
   Step right up. Come get your tax break. We have a ``surplus'' of
funds based on one year's budget cycle.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. What's more, projections for a decade's
accumulated annual surpluses now amount to $1.6 trillion. Now, the
Debt Clock be damned, visionaries like Kasich and House Speaker
Newt Gingrich are thinking of ways to fritter that away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you want to take a trillion dollars from the
American people that the government doesn't need?'' said Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Don't mind the Debt Clock and the money it says our government
owes. Kasich, chairman of the House Budget Committee, and Gingrich
are talking about cutting taxes by $700 billion over the next 10
years. Roll out the barrel, by gum.
</P>
<P>
   You are excused for seeming dense when you ask the question,
``We've been trying desperately to reduce debt, or so we assumed.
Now that we're in a position to actually carve into the national
debt, why do this?''
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that lots of Americans are scratching their
heads. The better news is that among them are Senate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, Senate Budget Committee
chairman Pete Domenici and Texas Sen. Phil Gramm all have distanced
themselves from talk by Republicans in the House about such
monumental tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   On this subject the GOP Senate leaders sound _ hari-kari,
anyone? _more like President Clinton. Although he supports measured
and targeted tax cuts, he says that Social Security should get the
lion's share of attention and savings.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich, for his part, would divide the $1.6 trillion in half _
half going to tax cuts, half going to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   You can't talk about the federal debt _ at least you can't
honestly _ and not mention Social Security. The surplus of the
Social Security trust fund is borrowed to mask the deficit, with
$600 billion owed back.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, of the $1.6 trillion Gingrich and Kasich are talking
about having as surplus revenue, all but $169 billion would come
from surpluses in the Social Security trust fund. That means that
not only is the deficit masked, so is the ``surplus.'' It is owed
back to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   True-believer supply-side conservatives tout the economic boost
that comes with tax cuts. But that's nothing new. Anytime the
government spends money, someone gets an economic boost. One of the
great deceits of Reaganomics was the supposed distinction made
between deficit spending and tax cuts in a deficit situation. When
the books don't balance, tax cuts are deficit spending and nothing
but.
</P>
<P>
   Someone has to pay back what we've borrowed. What about that
federal debt, Congressman Gumball?
</P>
<P>
   The trumpeting about ``money government doesn't need'' is
repudiated by every tick of the clock behind you.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
