<HEADER>
A5963 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EYMAN-ZANUCK29-COX     07-28 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ZANUCK29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book Review: Sloppy mistakes taint earnest look at Zanuck's
career
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TWENTIETH CENTURY'S FOX: Darryl F. Zanuck and the Culture of
Hollywood, by George F. Custen. Basic; 435 pages; $27.50.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Zanuck is the forgotten mogul. He lacked the flamboyance
of Selznick, the endearing accent and malapropisms of Goldwyn, the
crummy jokes of Warner, the thuggish brutality of Harry Cohn.
</P>
<P>
   He was short, homely, had a nasty gap between his front teeth.
He was also a hellacious filmmaker who made 20th Century Fox
studios as close to a writer's studio as the classic period of
Hollywood could offer.
</P>
<P>
   Because Zanuck was low on stars _ after Tyrone Power and Betty
Grable, things got very thin very fast _ he concentrated on story.
Fox films were not the best-photographed or the best-directed, but
they were usually the strongest in narrative.
</P>
<P>
   Because Zanuck was an ex-writer himself _ not a good one, but a
writer nonetheless _ he had more respect for the breed than the
producers did, and he treated the aces of his staff, Nunnally
Johnson and Lamar Trotti, far more gently than was the general rule
around town.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to directors, the ace of his staff was John Ford,
with whom Zanuck had a professional relationship that was usually
idyllic but occasionally abrasive. The rule was simple: Zanuck left
Ford alone to shoot his picture as he saw fit, but Zanuck edited
the footage. The collaboration resulted in such evergreens as ``How
Green Was My Valley,`` ``The Grapes of Wrath'' and ``My Darling
Clementine,'' so they must have been doing something right.
</P>
<P>
   George Custen's ``Twentieth Century's Fox'' _ does the title
irritate anybody besides me? _ is a serious attempt at examining
Zanuck the filmmaker; Custen pays little attention to the man, a
hard-driving workaholic with little time for family, and the usual
weaknesses of his breed _ women and high living.
</P>
<P>
   Custen chooses primary films from all phases of Zanuck's career,
from his early days at Warner Bros. through his last hurrah, ``The
Longest Day,'' using letters, production notes, scripts and the
very occasional interview to illuminate Zanuck's working methods
and aims.
</P>
<P>
   Custen wisely devotes a good deal of space to the largely
ignored early days of the struggling young writer.
</P>
<P>
   He digs up copies of Zanuck's short stories and an early book,
as well as the first attempts at screenplays. He then segues to
Zanuck's time at Warner Bros., where he worked his way up from
junior writer to production chief, and then formed an independent
outfit called 20th Century productions, which Zanuck later merged
with the moribund Fox organization.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 20th Century period that proved to the industry at
large that Zanuck was the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures he made there aren't terribly interesting today _
``House of Rothschild,'' ``Call of the Wild,'' ``The Bowery,''
``Clive of India'' _ but they were all ambitious, well-reviewed and
they made money.
</P>
<P>
   At Fox, of course, Zanuck walked into two lifesavers named
Shirley Temple and Will Rogers. But Rogers died in a plane crash in
1935, which meant Zanuck had to further develop a focus on story.
</P>
<P>
   I could quibble about some of Custen's conclusions; I think he
makes larger claims for Zanuck's influence on the 1927 ``The Jazz
Singer'' than are entirely warranted, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   What mars _ no, nearly destroys _ Custen's book are some of the
more ridiculous factual lapses I've ever encountered in a
putatively serious work of scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   The Douglas Fairbanks Sr. film ``Reaching for the Moon'' is
characterized as ``a science-fiction musical.'' It has no science
fiction element whatever (it's a typical Fairbanksian
lift-yourself-up-by-your-bootstraps story about a tycoon that was
disastrously released shortly after the stock market crashed);
writer/director Richard Brooks gets a name change to Peter Brooks;
Helen Hayes' name is misspelled ``Hays.''
</P>
<P>
   There's more: The actor Edward Woods is called James Woods. The
leading man of ``The Broadway Melody'' is identified as Harry
Richman, when Charles King played the part. I could go on, but you
get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   The first error simply indicates that Custen hasn't seen the
films he's writing about _ a bad idea; the rest are just sloppy
mistakes that call into question the writer's attention to detail
and overall seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   If a historian can't be trusted to get well-known names right,
why should he be trusted about anything else?
</P>
<P>
   Scott Eyman's column appears in the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
