<P>
   These feature stories for release Wednesday, July 29, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-PARENTTRAP _ A review of an updated remake of Disney's
``The Parent Trap,'' about the reunion of identical twins who were
separated shortly after birth by a parental breakup. Funny (Grade:
B) (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ ATLANTA _ In-depth coverage: National Geographic
($5) is famous for its prize-winning photography, but this month's
cover is truly eye-popping. The landmark issue features 3-D images
of the surface of Mars and the wreck of the Titanic. And other
reviews of this week's magazine offerings. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED 7/27.
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ZANUCK _ TWENTIETH CENTURY'S FOX: Darryl F. Zanuck and the
Culture of Hollywood, by George F. Custen. Basic; 435 pages;
$27.50. Darryl Zanuck is the forgotten mogul. He lacked the
flamboyance of Selznick, the endearing accent and malapropisms of
Goldwyn, the crummy jokes of Warner, the thuggish brutality of
Harry Cohn. What mars _ no, nearly destroys _ Custen's book are
some of the more ridiculous factual lapses I've ever encountered in
a putatively serious work of scholarship. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SOUNDSHOPPING _ ATLANTA _ Emmylou Harris and Vince Gill, two of
country's ultra-respected singers and songwriters, have
career-marking albums coming Aug. 11. (DeVault, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED 7/27.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   CREDIBLE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Embarrassing retractions and admitted
fabrications have caused media credibility to come under fire this
summer. In the wake of CNN's apology for an erroneous report
alleging that the U.S. military used nerve gas on defectors and
civilians during the Vietnam War, a recent Newsweek opinion poll
found that a majority of Americans believe news reports are often
inaccurate. Even more, 63 percent, say recent inaccuracies have
made them less likely to believe news reports. (Holloway, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POLL-PARANORMAL _ Some results of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution's Southern Focus Poll may bring smiles of
recognition to readers of supermarket tabloids. A sizable minority
of respondents believe in UFOs, ghosts, extraterrestrials and
psychic healing. An even greater number place credence in devil
possession, superstitions and ESP. (Warmbold, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-JEWS _ HAVANA _ The synagogue has an aerobics instructor,
but no rabbi. Temple dues _ which can run $1,000 a year in South
Florida _ are five cents a month. As with most everything else in
Cuba, Judaism survives on this tropical island by sacrifice and
invention. The Sephardic Hebrew Center uses its community room for
aerobics, dance classes and weight training, earning a few dollars
for the upkeep of the 44-year-old building. The rabbis left Cuba
along with 90 percent of the Jewish population after the 1959
revolution led by Fidel Castro. While visiting rabbis come several
times a year for bar mitzvahs, weddings and conversions, weekly
services are performed by lay members, said Jose Levy, synagogue
president. (Douthat, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-WATER _ A parched Austin is 5.63 inches below normal
rainfall for the year. After recording only 1.56 inches of rain in
June, Austin has seen just .9 inches this month. In response to the
drought, Motorola has been using rainwater collected in its
retention pond to water the grass and turning up office thermostats
to use less water in cooling towers that power the air
conditioning. Other big users are trying somewhat similar methods
to conserve. (Daniel, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   RV-TRAVEL _ This was real adventure. Logging 1,000 miles in a
rented 29-foot motor home in the Pacific Northwest was a vacation
we had only imagined. We always fly to point A, rent a car and
drive to tourist sites B, C and D. This was different, pleasantly
different. If my family of five, plus mother-in-law, can survive
each other in tight quarters for a week, anyone can. Our excursion
gave new meaning to travel. Sure, we could have rented a sport
utility vehicle and a cabin near a lake. This, however, provided
more independence and self-sufficiency. (Gandara, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RV-TIPS _ When you pick up your RV, you'll get a short
orientation. Take notes. Ask plenty of questions. Make sure you're
clear on how to hook up electricity, sewer and water at a
campground. Don't leave any doubts about operating the appliances.
Ask where the fuse panel is located. Then, read the manual that
explains all the functions of the vehicle. (Gandara, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RV-TRIP _ AUSTIN, Texas _ I am not an RV kinda gal. When my
friends learned that I would be traversing the South in a rented
27-foot recreational vehicle, they snickered. What had overcome
their Vogue-readin', Pinot grigio-sippin', Volvo-drivin' buddy,
they asked. Heretofore, they reminded me, my idea of a recreational
vehicle has been a Mercedes with tinted windows on a Saturday
night. (Segrest, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BOCARATON _ The Garfield exhibit at the International
Museum of Cartoon Art in Boca Raton, Fla., marks the comic strip
character's 20th anniversary; also, Boca Festival Days, Aug. 1-31,
golf, tennis, wine tasting. (Paterau, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SALE _ Road Trip: World's Longest Outdoor Sale, Aug.
13-16. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   FROZEN _ Frozen desserts are so cool because they are so easy to
prepare. (Heller, Dayton Daily News) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   READY _ Dayton Daily News panel evaluates Meijer Fresh Oven
Ready Stuffed Peppers. (Heller, Dayton Daily News) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD _ Food briefs. (Heller, Dayton Daily News) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY (also in f category)
</P>
<P>
   TECHREPORT _ ATLANTA _ Time was, we were so relieved to have a
machine that could play movies at home we didn't much care whether
we could ever figure out how to program it to record television
shows. And for those persistent souls _ or Georgia Tech engineers _
who actually figured out how to program VCRs, well, everything else
was gravy. But, finally, the manufacturers are coming around.
(Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ ATLANTA _ As expected, I got a number of e-mails
after the column in which I tried to help a correspondent with his
concerns over whether his telephone line would be acceptable for
56k bps modems. The most helpful info came in messages informing me
there is indeed a way Bob Wildaus can check the quality of his
telephone line. I'm going to give primary credit to Jerry A. Smith
of Smyrna, because his message had the most details. (Warner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ ATLANTA _ Sometimes I take after my namesake, my
Great Uncle Bill, a man who had only a nodding acquaintance with
reality and who delighted in worrying about improbable things.
Maybe you're like me and my Uncle Bill when it comes to computers
and the Internet, spending more time worrying about the meteorites
of computing and not enough time about the widow makers. Let's talk
today about what's worth worrying about and what isn't. (Husted,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION (a and/or l category)
</P>
