<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5969 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KABAT-COLUMN29-COX     07-28 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Clumsy is our dog's middle name
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It pains me to say this, but we have a clumsy dog.
</P>
<P>
   We got Sandy as a pup from the animal shelter about two years
ago. She was so tiny she fit neatly into the palm of my hand.
</P>
<P>
   We carefully examined the size of her paws, relying on our
knowledge that puppies grow into their paws. Her paws were tiny.
Her paws grew.
</P>
<P>
   From the very first, Sandy was, shall we say, uncoordinated.
</P>
<P>
   She would sit, and her back legs would splay out haphazardly,
her rear skittering across the floor. Sitting, much less sitting
up, seemed to be well beyond her ability. We always felt like we
needed to prop up her backside when she tried to sit.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong with her back legs?'' we asked a friend who knows
a thing or two about dogs. ``Are they weak?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope. She's just clumsy,'' we were told.
</P>
<P>
   Great. A certified clumsy dog.
</P>
<P>
   Well, she may be clumsy, but she loves to play. Sandy runs and
fetches and jumps and scampers with the best of them. She just
can't control the back part of her body very well. She reminds you
of those old comedies when the driver falls asleep at the rear end
of the fire engine as it goes careening down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Ask her to give you her paw for a shake and, as she dutifully
lifts it, she often rolls backward, initiating an impromptu belly
rub.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she's not clumsy at all. Maybe she's just smart.
</P>
<P>
   Although she can't sit very gracefully, she does manage to jump
on her hind legs like a kangaroo. Put her outside and she comes to
the back door and does a hind-footed tango that would make Carmen
Miranda proud. Her vertical jump is right up there with Michael
Jordan's. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   She once came down our linoleum-floored hallway to our bedroom
during the night to sleep beside our bed. But when we rose that
morning to let her outside, she got so excited that she lost
traction when she hit the slick flooring and wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   Legs and tail went flailing in all directions as she slid
halfway down the hall. Think Bambi on the frozen pond. Yelping and
crying, she struggled to the carpeting and sat there (sort of)
shaking and whining.
</P>
<P>
   From that day forward, she has not stepped into the hallway. She
stands at the threshold, tentatively places one paw on the linoleum
and then resignedly sits down (sort of).
</P>
<P>
   We've tried to help her overcome her linoleum phobia. My husband
has eased her along the floor slowly, patting and stroking her as
he speaks comforting words. In her anxiety, though, she begins
digging in her nails, finds nothing, and goes skittering. Both man
and dog end up in a tangle of fur, skin, legs, feet and paws
against the hallway wall.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the clumsiness, or perhaps because of it, my husband
really loves this dog. He has much more patience with her than I
do. In fact, he came home from the store one day with a new
tootbrush and toothpaste ... yes, for Sandy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're kidding!'' I exclaimed. ``You're not going to actually
brush this dog's teeth, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The vet said she has plaque,'' he said. ``Her breath stinks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course her breath stinks,'' I answered. ``She's a dog!''
</P>
<P>
   Farm girls typically aren't sensitive to the need for canine
hygiene.
</P>
<P>
   He brushed her teeth _ or at least tried to. The problem, other
than the distraction of my loud guffawing, was that Sandy wouldn't
sit for the Doggydent toothpaste experience.
</P>
<P>
   She tried, but down she went. My husband bent over her prone
body, vigorously scrubbing her teeth with meat-flavored toothpaste.
I wonder _ if I made my boys use it, could I cut down on the meat
bill at the grocery?
</P>
<P>
   After much gnashing of teeth, my husband accomplished his task.
Sandy arose smacking her chops, looking for dessert. She was so
excited, she sat up and begged for more.
</P>
<P>
   Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
