<HEADER>
A6034 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     07-28 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, July 28, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;  (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
 &UR;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   UNIVERSITY-RESEARCH (Albany, N.Y.) _ Federal research grants to
colleges and universities in New York have plummeted, school
officials say. What's happening in New York is part of a national
trend. In 1996 and 1997, the federal government doled out about 10
percent less in research grants _ adjusted for inflation _ than it
did at its high point in 1994. By HARVY LIPMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SF-HOUSING (San Francisco) _ At the rate this city is adding
affordable housing aimed at low- and moderate-income residents, the
need will be met in about 50 years, if everything goes well. But
housing activists acknowledge that the housing crisis is close to
intractable and that San Francisco is never going to build its way
out of it. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   VETS-RYAN (San Francisco) _ To steel himself for questions from
veterans in his therapy group, Dr. Nick Kanas went to see ``Saving
Private Ryan.'' He's glad he did. A Vietnam-era vet who meets with
men in their 60s and up, Kanas says that after seeing the film, ``I
can understand better why it's so hard for them to explain their
experiences to those who haven't been there.'' By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   ARK (Port Aransas, Texas) _ Tony Amos resembles the biblical
Noah, although the ``ark'' under Amos' care is a group of
land-bound tanks and cages rather than a seaworthy craft. Every
morning, the white-haired and bearded Amos scours 7.5 miles of
beach for creatures native to this area and returns to the Animal
Rehabilitation Keep at the University of Texas Marine Science
Institute here. By RALPH WININGHAM.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AREA-CODE-BLUES (Washington) _ Houston will soon become the
latest city in the nation with an area code overlay _ an area code
that is not geographically distinct. It's part of a national trend
that's leading to a patchwork or dialing rules where you'll dial 10
digits in Baltimore, 11 in Chicago and 7 in Austin, Texas. By DAVID
IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   SF-UNIONSQUARE (San Francisco) _ A fight among merchants vying
for coveted space in Union Square here has made real estate near
this tiny plot of land more expensive than it has been in decades,
elevating San Francisco's retail center into one of the world's
most desirable. Neiman Marcus, the Texas retailer, will spend $50
million to purchase a 50,000-square-foot building, demolish it and
put up what will be the 30-store chain's largest outlet. By
VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KITCHENS (Albany, N.Y.) _ As our homes and lifestyles evolve
into the next millennium, kitchens will still be the hub of
activity and heart of the home but with a new mindset. Now
designers are working to adapt kitchens to meet the multiple-use
needs of ever-busy families, including working couples, children
and longer-living grandparents. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   DOGHOUSES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Summer is the time to consider that
doghouse you've been wanting to get for Fido to sleep in at night.
It's a good time to shop around or have one custom designed for
your pooch, and will give your dog time to get acclimated to its
new digs before chilly temperatures set in. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WRITERS-CLASS (Albany, N.Y.) _ It's the big Albany political
novel William Kennedy has always intended to write. He spent the
last four decades assiduously avoiding it, while publishing seven
novels and two books of nonfiction. Now, at age 70, Kennedy is
wrestling with the beast. He unveiled the results recently at the
New York State Summer Writers Institute. By PAUL GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   TV-70`S (undated) _ Even though Fox's ``Ally McBeal'' received a
slew of Emmy nominations last week, including best comedy, it's
been a long time since the network developed a hit half-hour
sitcom. The wait may be over. Based on the pilot for its latest,
``That 70's Show,'' this could be the funniest new program of the
year. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-FAME (Albany, N.Y.) _ Immortality finally has gotten
around to settling up with George Davis. The baseball Hall of Fame
is dusting off a cozy place for Davis, one of the best all-around
players of the turn of the century who last appeared in a
major-league game in 1909. Davis didn't make it easy for
immortality to find him. He has spent nearly six decades in an
unmarked grave in Philadelphia. By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FLORES-COLUMN (San Antonio) _ For many in the nation's capital,
the drug war has become little more than tough-sounding rhetoric.
The latest hot air comes from two Republicans _ Rep. Bill McCollum
of Florida and Sen. Mike DeWine of Ohio _ who have unveiled a plan
to drastically reduce the flow of cocaine and heroin into the
United States through more interdiction. By VERONICA FLORES.
</P>
</TEXT>
