<SLUG> BC-KITCHENS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMORROW'S KITCHENS WILL BE WARMER, FAMILY-FRIENDLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ As our homes and lifestyles evolve into the next
millennium, kitchens will still be the hub of activity and heart of
the home but with a new mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1990s have worn out the family,'' said Wolfgang Hafele,
president of Hafele America, a leading manufacturer of furniture,
cabinets and design hardware. ``Their workdays are longer and their
family time is shorter, so they are creating a room in their house
that gives them back what the world has taken family time and a
feeling of relaxation. That room is the kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hafele (pronounced hay-fa-la) America is a 75-year-old company
headquartered in Germany, with offices in seven North American
cities. In May, Hafele sponsored a symposium in San Francisco on
trends, titled ``The Kitchen of the 21st Century,'' which brought
together kitchen designers from the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The designers' challenge? To readapt kitchens to meet the
multiple-use needs of ever-busy families, including working
couples, children and longer-living grandparents. Their emphasis?
To make the kitchen practical, versatile and aesthetically
pleasing.
</P>
<P>
   Appliances will be rearranged, walls knocked down and the shapes
of traditional cabinets and counters will change, according to
Wolfgang Hafele. This new kitchen will be more user-friendly and a
more enjoyable place in which to spend time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kitchen will be smarter and more room-like, rather than a
sterile, cold kitchen setting. It will feature more gizmos for
cooking and storing groceries, dishes and so-on,'' said Philip
Martin, product marketing manager for Hafele in Archdale, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes forecast for in early 21st century kitchens:
</P>
<P>
   _ Kitchens will have smaller, auxiliary features and appliances
to accommodate shared cooking duties and reduce congestion.
</P>
<P>
   _ The stove, range and ovens will be spaced out around the
kitchen, instead of being clumped together, for easier
accessibility.
</P>
<P>
   _ There will be double sinks, with the second in a central work
island. Soap dispensers will also be built into the sink, as well
as a water-filtration system incorporated into the faucet.
</P>
<P>
   _ Appliances, such as the dishwasher and stove, will be raised
for greater accessibility, and may also be hidden behind decorative
wood cabinet panels.
</P>
<P>
   _ An extra table that can be placed in the room if there is
enough space, or in the pantry, will be commonplace for preparation
or paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   _ Space will be concealed in cabinets under counters that can
easily slide out when needed.
</P>
<P>
   _ A computer also will play an important role in the efficiency
of the kitchen, from making grocery lists and organizing staples
and recipes to serving as a message center.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kitchens also will feature more sophisticated lighting, with
multiple lighting fixtures and dimmers, to provide adjustable mood
or function lighting.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pull-down and pull-out cabinets will make things easier to
reach and get to.
</P>
<P>
   _ Counter tops will come in multiple levels to accommodate
people of different ages and sizes.
</P>
<P>
   _ A ``pet center'' will store pet foods, with dispensers serving
up the animal's dry kibble.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo Peterson, a certified kitchen designer and educator in
Brookfield, Conn., noted the walls will be the first thing to go
from yesterday's kitchen. There will be window views, lots of
natural light and open space into the family room to provide for
more family interaction.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the appliances in the kitchen of the not-too-distant
future will also be commercial (restaurant) grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ovens will be more customized, so they can handle roasting and
convection cooking all in one unit,'' said Sarah Reep, director of
design for StarMark in Sioux Falls, S.D., and a member of the Color
Marketing Group, a national not-for-profit association in
Alexandria, Va., that predicts color trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the commercial ranges may even be programmed to inject
a burst of steam at intervals, like professional bake ovens,'' Reep
said. ``You may even see rotisserie units. You'll also see pizza
ovens for making restaurant-style pizzas.''
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Zarrillo, kitchen designer with Custom Design Kitchens in
Schenectady, N.Y., said she's finding that many of her customers
are asking for some of these features when remodeling their
kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing a lot of unfitted work, where cabinets are all
different heights to look more like standing furniture,'' Zarrillo
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are also adding armoires to give the kitchen a more
room-like appearance and storage space to look like an old butler's
pantry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Appliances are all high-end stainless steel and when they are
not high end, clients want them concealed behind wood cabinets.
Hood vents over cooking surfaces have become more architecturally
distinctive, with paneling and hand-carved moldings, to give the
kitchen a more friendly feeling,'' Zarrillo said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Cheever, vice president of dealer development for Heritage
Custom Cabinets in New Holland, Pa., predicts the style of kitchens
in the new millennium will be eclectic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow's family will surround themselves with their
treasures and very personal items,'' Cheever said. ``There will be
a great mix of antique pieces, artwork, photographs, solid wood
cabinets and stainless-steel appliances. Incorporate family history
into a functional part of the kitchen. For example, use grandma's
broken china, to create a custom mosaic backsplash.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheever believes the contemporary style will prevail, but
interpreted in natural materials that include granite, concrete and
marble.
</P>
<P>
   An element that will tie the kitchen together is color, Reep
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hot cool color for the kitchen of the (early) 21st century
will be blue, such as cobalt and cornflower,'' she said. ``Blues
have a calming effect and are ideal for the kitchen at the end of
the day. Color stains for cabinetry will also be popular, such as
those in soft orange values, like pumpkin or honey. Color will play
a bolder part and be used throughout the kitchen from appliances to
paint and wallpaper to cabinetry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
