<SLUG> BC-TV-70S-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX TACKLES THE '70S, WARTS AND ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Even though Fox's ``Ally McBeal'' has
received a slew of Emmy nominations, including best comedy, it's
been a long time since the network developed a hit half-hour
sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   The wait may be over. Based on the pilot for its latest, ``That
70's Show,'' this could be the funniest new show of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Sure it's politically and grammatically incorrect, but the
history and the humor is right on. It helps that the show (which
debuts Sunday, Aug. 23, check local listings) takes place in 1976,
the year of the Bicentennial, with lots of loud colors, and very
cool music. The bad news is, if this show lasts it will have to
revisit disco.
</P>
<P>
   Six teens come of age in a small fictitious Wisconsin town. They
do the normal right-of-passage things for that or even this era:
hang out, listen to music, date, go out of town against their
father's wishes, to a concert, and, yes, smoke pot.
</P>
<P>
   There's been plenty of buzz among critics ever since the pilot
came out (it started out as ``Feelin' Alright'' and has gone
through at least five name changes; there will be a sixth when they
correctly move the apostrophe from ``70's'' to ``'70s.''). While
the buzz about the series is justly deserved, much of the talk has
centered on the ``buzz'' some of the characters get on the show.
</P>
<P>
   In the first episode, four of the teens are hanging in a
basement, obviously stoned (although the actual smoking is never
shown). They even wave their arms frantically to clear the air when
Eric's (Topher Grace) father calls downstairs for one of the kids.
Eric heads upstairs to talk to Dad; his vision is fine but the
walls are moving. It's funny. It's accurate. But what about ... the
message?
</P>
<P>
   ``What we feel we've written ... is portrayed the '70s, that
era, 1976, in a very honest form,'' said co-executive producer
Bonnie Turner, who with husband and writing partner Terry Turner
created ``3rd Rock From the Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we would have been criticized if we ignored it,
you know, and criticized if we did it.''
</P>
<P>
   This show has and will come under attack, mainly for showing pot
use in a manner where every kid who takes a hit does not end up in
a hospital, asylum or morgue. And although drug use is portrayed in
the pilot, the producers say it will not be seen in every episode.
</P>
<P>
   How many times did Lou Grant reach into his desk and pull out a
bottle? How many times did Hawkeye and Trapper and B.J. sip
homemade hooch before heading off to the operating room?
</P>
<P>
   Remember, this is a sitcom, this is funny, isn't that its
obligation?
</P>
<P>
   The young actors who play the teens said that they weren't
freaked out playing characters from the flamboyant era. Well, for
the most part anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the fact my parents were alive (and young) then was
creepy,'' said Ashton Kutcher (Michael Kelso), who grew up in a
tiny town in Iowa. But with '70s styles and music having a
mini-renaissance, the whole scene is not too weird for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '70s are in,'' said Danny Masterson (Steve Hyde). ``I'm
just scared when the '80s come back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
