<HEADER>
A6161 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-KINDER-SPI &LR;      07-28 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-KINDER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINKING AND SALVAGE TALES PROVE STORMY ORDEAL FOR SEATTLE WRITER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Photo available through Wieck Photo Database)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Author's acknowledgments are often as dry as sand,
that section of a book that is mainly a list of people and places
owed thanks of one kind or another _ supportive friends, helpful
editors, knowledgeable librarians, etc., etc.
</P>
<P>
   But the author's acknowledgment in the new best seller by
Seattle author Gary Kinder eloquently sets out what it takes to
persevere with a book project that consumes an entire decade, the
sacrifices required, the price extracted in the most personal
terms.
</P>
<P>
   These include the father who joked about not living long enough
to see the book ever published and, in fact, died three years
before it happened. These include two young daughters who grew to
be 11 and 14 during the period of the book's gestation, a time when
they, as Kinder writes,``have hardly known me.'' And these include
a spouse who was closest witness to a writer's obsession, a spouse
who, as Kinder also writes, ``was waiting the whole time, with
dreams of her own. She deserves to have them fulfilled.''
</P>
<P>
   It is little wonder then that when Kinder's ``Ship of Gold in
the Deep Blue Sea'' (Atlantic Monthly Press, 507 pages, $27.50)
recently muscled its way to a high spot on best-seller lists, the
message that conveyed to the writer himself was more spiritual than
monetary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is comforting and reaffirming to know that I didn't waste
all that time,'' Kinder emphasizes. ``My greatest fear when I was
working on the book was that I would finish and it would come out
and people would say, `It's a great story if only Norman Mailer or
some writer like that had gotten there first.' In other words,
they'd be saying, `You blew it!' Because, as a writer, you just
don't know if it's going to turn out well. Even when you've
finished the book, you don't know that.''
</P>
<P>
   The 51-year-old Kinder knows that now. His stirring,
page-turning true tale of the sea was so often a lead title in the
Atlantic Monthly catalog _ only to be postponed again _ that it
became a source of some embarrassment for the publisher. Now,
``Ship of Gold'' has finally been launched and is sailing out of
bookstores, a successful book that, by a strange quirk of fate,
seems perfectly timed in what has increasingly become a marketing
driven industry.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of ``Titanic'' underscored the public's
fascination with stories of tragedy on the high seas. So did the
unexpected best seller ``The Perfect Storm'' by Sebastian Junger.
Now in their wake comes Kinder's book, which melds the best
elements of both those stories, without resorting to either an
imaginary love story or speculative disaster scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   The sinking of the SS Central America in 1857 was the greatest
American sea tragedy of that time, a tale of terror and heroism
widely covered in the newspapers of the day, since more than 400 of
the 600 people on board were lost (but there were still many
survivors with harrowing stories to recount). Also lost was a huge
cargo of gold on its way to New York City from the California gold
fields, a shipment so sizable the financial markets shuddered from
the sinking.
</P>
<P>
   The recovery of undamaged artifacts and gold from the Central
America in 1989 _ 200 hundred miles off the Carolina coast and from
the depth of 8,000 feet _ was the greatest feat of underwater
recovery ever, accomplished by an Ohio-based team of
techo-mavericks who had done what all undersea experts advised them
was impossible. And Kinder, after receiving exclusive book access
to the team and their story, was aboard their recovery ship when it
sailed into a Virginia port with gold bars and gold coins that may
be worth $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But combining the two stories of the sinking of the Central
America in a hurricane and the salvage of its precious cargo soon
swamped Kinder. A lawyer turned writer, he had done two non-fiction
books previously _ ``Victim,'' a highly praised and triumphantly
humane account of a monstrous Utah crime and its aftermath, and
``Light Years,'' a much more pedestrian look at UFO investigations.
Neither had really prepared him for what he faced with the Central
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was so much information that it was just overwhelming,''
Kinder recalls. ``There was the sinking and all the historical
accounts of it; that research had to be done. Then I had to
research maritime law and, even being a lawyer, maritime law has a
lot of funny little rules and I had to learn all those. Then I had
to research the California Gold Rush. I realized early on that my
biggest problem was going to be how to structure this story and how
much history to use.''
</P>
<P>
   This mother lode of golden material was so strong that Kinder
could easily have written two books, one on the sinking, one on the
salvage. He had great characters from both, including William
Herndon, the heroic captain of the Central America who had been the
first American to explore the Amazon, and Ansel and Adaline Mills
Easton, who had been married in California just before departure
for New York, their bags packed with newlywed dreams and presents
for their life ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Tommy Thompson, the brilliant, yet eccentric Ohio
scientist who masterminded the salvage efforts, an intense
iconoclast who despised being called a ``treasure hunter'' since he
believed he was an original thinker pursuing a higher scientific
calling. As Kinder writes, ``Working on the bottom of the deep
ocean wasn't impossible, it was only considered impossible, and
that was the distinction Tommy had learned: Other people labeled
things impossible not because they couldn't be done, but because no
one was doing them.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties of Kinder's own writing mission, in some ways,
paralleled Thompson's task. What seems obvious now _ that the
stories of the sinking and the salvage needed to be woven together
in alternating chapters _ proved elusive. So Morgan Entrekin, the
publisher and editor at Atlantic Monthly, flew from New York a
dozen times to huddle with Kinder in a Seattle hotel room, trying
to solve the various dilemmas with the manuscript through rewrite
after rewrite.
</P>
<P>
   There were times the two colleagues and friends, who had worked
together on Kinder's two previous books, could barely stand the
sight of each other. There were times, too, when Kinder felt he had
``hit the writer's wall and couldn't write any more.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, Kinder's advance of more than $100,000 for the
much-postponed book had all been spent and he and his family were
living instead on the money he makes from teaching writing seminars
for lawyers across the country. That income proved a lifesaver for
the book-battered writer and his family, although the seminars did
take time away from the writing.
</P>
<P>
   But the manuscript was finally wrestled into a publishable
shape, to everyone's great relief. But that proved short-lived
indeed when Thompson demanded postponement because of the
unresolved legal battles with insurance companies over the rights
to the recovered treasure. Thompson wanted a four-year delay before
publication; Entrekin and Kinder reluctantly agreed to two.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was really devastating,'' Kinder remembers. ``We had
spent so much time and we thought we had a book then.''
</P>
<P>
   The book no doubt benefited from the revisions that continued
during that period, but the waiting and wondering extracted a toll
that may never quite be overcome by how much the book earns or how
much is paid in the current bidding for movie rights.
</P>
<P>
   As Kinder relates, ``The toughest part on a marriage when you
write a book is that you can spend three, four, five years of your
life _ or, in this case, 10 _ and then at the end of it, they hand
you a lottery ticket. If you're lucky, your number comes up.
</P>
<P>
   ``But so many things can go wrong and you have to navigate
through so many difficulties, what could be project-killing
difficulties. So this is definitely not something I would advise
other people to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
