</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN FOOD WATCHDOGS GO TOO FAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- It being summer, my wife and I snuck a few days to
go hit golf balls and hang with my saintly mother-in-law. For some
reason, visiting her is about the only time I eat potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   This year, like a phenomenal number of weight-conscious
consumers, this delightful Mississippian had switched brands.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of her usual fare, she had switched to one of the new
kinds containing the fat substitute called Olestra, from Procter &AMP;
Gamble Co., that has taken off like no other new product in the
'90s off its claims that with no change in taste you can snack
moderately with a lot less fat and considerably fewer calories.
What has started in some potato chips and a cracker could
eventually spread very far.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to see for myself, having just witnessed the latest
round in a decade-long fight against the additive by the Center for
Science in the Public Interest _ a Ralph Nader spinoff of long
standing around here.
</P>
<P>
   From casual acquaintaince with this dispute, I was on notice
that the watchdogs were raising the kinds of digestive consequences
that all fastidious Americans fear _ cramps, etc.
</P>
<P>
   So each day, I had a couple of ounces of my mother-in-law's
potato chips and waited to see if Vesuvius would remain quiet. And,
of course, it did _ as has been the case for nearly everyone who
snacks with at least some restraint.
</P>
<P>
   This was basically what a Food and Drug Administration advisory
committee concluded last month in calling the Center for Science's
widely disseminated fears baseless, but continuing to recommend a
label cautioning consumers about digestive problems in the context
of immoderate use.
</P>
<P>
   That's more than good enough for me, as it should be for
everyone. But the battle is certain to go on, which ought to be an
occasion for some critical thinking about the condition of
watchdoggery in general these days.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of the Naderite contribution to our culture for the
last 30 years (huge and overwhelmingly positive) has been the
exposure of products where scientific evidence about causation
shows clear and actual or potentially widespread danger. From cars
to bad meat, this function has been performed in the face of
industry and governmental timidity and malfeasance.
</P>
<P>
   But more recently the watchdog function has become polluted with
concepts not of danger put of more preachy notions of what one
group of activists thinks is good for you.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, for example, the Center and its indefatiguable,
ever-quotable director, Michael Jacobson, has railed against ethnic
food _ especially Chinese, Italian, and Mexican. The campaign
against Olestra did not come out of the blue, but it is
illustrative in its blurring of scientific evidence of real danger
and broader concepts of nutrition philosophy. The problem with this
is that it dilutes the meaning of warnings when they truly need to
be serious.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Olestra, Jacobson calls it ``crazy'' to permit
the use of an additive with no nutritional value, and he is trying
to get the FDA to revoke its approval. Now he wants to petition the
Federal Trade Commission to halt the major advertising campaign
behind the product.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign doesn't come out of thin air. Olestra, a synthetic
fat, is the combination of various vegetable oils and table sugar.
The phony fat molecule is made so large that it cannot be
metabolized and leaves the body intact. That's why it's called
no-fat, that's why there are much fewer calories, but that's also
why (in laymen's terms) it can go right through you and why you
should eat it in moderation to avoid stomach problems. For
analogous reasons, I wouldn't recommend eating an entire package of
apricots, either.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson's Center offered anecdotal evidence off its Web site of
consumer complaints not otherwise examined, but it confined itself
before the FDA panel to criticizing Procter &AMP; Gamble's actual
studies. The FDA group was not impressed, and even its decision to
leave the mild caution intact can be criticized as self-protecting
rather than consumer-protecting.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the game, however, the battle was escalated to include
the ``C'' word. It is a fact that Olestra will take with it four
fat-soluble vitamins if it encounters them (A, D, E, and K) along
with carotenoids that may or may not protect the body from cancer
(science remains unclear).
</P>
<P>
   That was a cheap shot. In the normal course of regulatory
events, the Olestra makers have already fortified their product
with the four vitamins. As for carotenoids, not only is the cancer
protection unverified, the center's late hit ignored a simple fact:
Olestra sweeps these substances out only if they are in the system.
It wouldn't hurt those who, for example, gobble beta-carotene pills
every morning to wait before eating potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, if we're not careful, does consumer protection and policy
advocacy degenerate toward farce.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that Olestra's potential to help an overweight
society lighten up dwarfs potential problems almost entirely
associated with excessive consumption. The fact also is that
wolf-crying endangers the credibility advocacy groups need when
real dangers are at hand. And the fact is I have another reason to
look forward to my next visit to my mother-in-law's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
