<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6165 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-CELLUCCI-SOFT-BOS &LR;      07-28 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CELLUCCI-SOFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI KEEPS QUIET ON SOFT MONEY GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Citing a loophole in campaign finance laws, Acting
Governor Paul Cellucci has declined to reveal the source of
hundreds of thousands of dollars in political donations he
solicited recently from a host of Massachusetts corporations and
wealthy Republican donors.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, through his aides, declined Monday to divulge the
names and the amounts of each of the special interest donations
that his fund-raising operation collected as part of an event on
June 26 during the Republican Governors' Association meeting in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The money was raised for a national Republican Party account
that is governed by federal campaign finance law. Neither state nor
federal law requires Cellucci, who in the past has called for
campaign finance reform and a ban on so-called soft money
donations, to disclose where the contributions came from or the
amount of the individual donations.
</P>
<P>
   The national party will distribute the money to state party
organizations, which then will decide how much to allocate to each
candidate in the general election. How much Cellucci's campaign for
governor will benefit for his fund-raising efforts for the national
party if he becomes the Republican nominee is not known. Republican
Party sources estimate that Cellucci, using his chief fund-raiser
James Connolly, GOP national Republican committeeman Ron Kaufman,
and Boston businessman Herbert Collins, raised about $300,000 at
the event from corporations and individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Massachusetts state law, which limits the amount of
donations to the state parties at $5,000 per person, there is no
restriction on contributions to the national party organizations.
In addition, unlike state law, there is no restriction on corporate
donations.
</P>
<P>
   Such donations are called ``soft money'' because they can skirt
state laws and be hidden from public examination. Cellucci in the
past has sharply attacked the use of soft money by political
parties, but defended his raising it, saying he and other GOP
officeholders need the funds so long as Democrats finance their
attacks on him and others with soft money.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton visited Massachusetts earlier this year to
raise money for the Democratic National Committee. Some of that
money will be spent for the benefit of Massachusetts Democrats in
the general election this year.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, state elected officials of both parties, particularly
governors, have taken to raising money for national political
committees, money that is often then returned to help finance state
and local elections.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the federal loophole, Cellucci is taking advantage of
a state law that does not require office-holders to disclose
contributions raised for out-of-state candidates. Although a 1994
state campaign finance reform bill contained a special provision
calling for disclosure for money raised for out-of-state
candidates, the section applies only to money raised for
individuals. National political committees and other organizations
that distribute money to candidates are not covered, leaving
Cellucci free to refuse a Globe request for the list of donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has a legitimate interest in knowing where these
donations come from,'' said Joshua Friedes, executive director of
Common Cause of Massachusetts. ``I think we need to ask ourselves
whose interest is being served by the acting governor's refusal to
provide this information. Certainly it's not the public's
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedes and other campaign finance reform advocates have
referred to such soft-money donations as ``money laundering''
because it allows politicians to skirt local campaign finance
regulations and raise huge amounts of money from special interests
that have business pending before the state.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's campaign manager, Rob Gray, Monday referred all
inquiries to the Republican Governors' Association. He said it
would be improper for the acting governor to release contributions
made to the Republican Governors' Association, even those solicited
by Cellucci and his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We helped raise money for this event so the Republicans would
not be at a disadvantage when Democrats pour millions of dollars in
soft money into Massachusetts in the fall,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Cellucci's opponent, Joe Malone, would benefit from
the donations Cellucci helped raise if he upsets the acting
governor in the September primary.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Republican Governors' Association said the
group could not provide a breakdown for the contributions Cellucci
and his supporters raised for the national Republican Party. But a
press aide, Kirsten Fedeway, said the association was ``pleasantly
surprised'' at the total, saying it was above original estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Particularly because Massachusetts is seen as such a
Democratic state where Republicans are not as strong,'' Fedeway
said. She also said other governors in the Northeast had helped to
raise funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Governors' Association's federal disclosure
reports do not list which donations were solicited by Cellucci and
his fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1997, as he pushed his legislation to ban soft money from
state campaigns, Cellucci said: ``The bottom line is that special
interest groups are able to hide behind a curtain of anonymity and
the voters are left in the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   The June 26 fund-raiser was set up as a cruise around Boston
Harbor during the weekend that the Republican Governors'
Association and 31 other GOP governors met in Boston. Contributions
ranged from $5,000 for an annual membership in the Republican
Governors' Club to $40,000 for a seat on the association's board
and access to national GOP affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
