<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-IRISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW, CONFIDENT IRISH-AMERICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE NEW IRISH AMERICANS 
By Ray O'Hanlon 
Roberts Rinehart, 246 pp., Illustrated, $15.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In case you haven't noticed, the Irish are on something of a
roll, both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   If some people were surprised that ``The Beauty Queen of
Lenane'' won four Tony awards, the Irish weren't. In fact, they
thought it should have gotten best play, too. There is an
unprecedented confidence in Ireland, where the booming economy is
considered Europe's most robust, a confidence that helped to
produce, finally, an agreement on how to share the island. It is a
confidence manifesting itself among the natives and the hyphenated,
i.e., Irish-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   There have been few voices as perceptive in chronicling that
confidence and the changes among Irish-Americans as Ray O'Hanlon,
who has used his perch as senior editor at the Irish Echo in New
York to chart the rising political and economic clout of an ethnic
group that most people assumed had already made it. In his new
book, O'Hanlon's portraits of 1980s immigrants and 1990s political
activists show how the Irish have reinvented themselves to make it
again.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Irish famine of 150 years ago, the relationship
between the United States and Ireland has been interdependent.
America supplied the economic sustenance that Ireland could not.
Ireland supplied the bodies who dug the canals, built the railways,
wrote the newspapers, and, after a few generations, ran the banks
and multinational corporations.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, however, the vast majority of those 40 million or
so who list themselves on the US census as being of Irish ancestry
became assimilated to a point that their ancestry had little to do
with the land of their forebears. O'Hanlon argues that the new
Irish-Americans are those who over the past 15 years have brought a
level of sophistication to political, business, and social life
that is more reflective of modern Ireland, an increasingly secular,
pluralistic, and affluent poster child of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hanlon shows how pragmatism has replaced dogma. The activists
who got more visas for young Irish did not rely on mere
sentimentality, he explains, but used empirical evidence to show
that the young Irish were putting more into the system than they
were taking out.
</P>
<P>
   His account of the dispute over whether a gay group should be
allowed to march in the New York St. Patrick's Day parade perfectly
frames his argument that there are at least two types of
Irish-Americans: the ``Irish Irish,'' who are old-fashioned and
close-minded about what being Irish constitutes, and the ``New
Irish,'' who are more open-minded and less dogmatic about religion,
politics, and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Conor O'Clery's fascinating book, ``Daring
Diplomacy,'' which, when published in Ireland was called ``The
Greening of the White House,'' gave an intricate explanation of how
the Clinton administration became deeply involved in the Northern
Ireland peace process. O'Hanlon paints a broader picture,
explaining how and why Irish-Americans were in a position to exert
such pressure in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hanlon describes how the Irish government was able to get the
White House to consider Dublin's view on equal footing with London,
America's staunchest military ally and its biggest foreign
investor. He focuses a spotlight on some of the lesser-known
figures who contributed to the greening of America. One of them was
Dermot Brangan, who through much of the 1990s was the Irish
government's press officer in New York. With the persistence of a
salesman, Brangan kept knocking on doors and making phone calls,
getting in to see influential editorial writers at the biggest
newspapers. His persistence was rewarded by a greening of American
editorial pages, a process O'Hanlon demonstrates.
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of full disclosure, O'Hanlon has some nice
things to say about this newspaper, but he balances them by
leveling criticism also. That is a strength of the book. The Irish
are notorious for kissing their allies and beating up their
enemies, especially the British, in print. O'Hanlon is scrupulously
fair, though just how objective an Irishman can be when the British
enter the equation is a subject worthy of a book in itself.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the late William Shannon gave an overview of the Irish
in America has anyone provided as worthwhile and readable an
account of how the Irish arrived, again. During this Year of the
Irish, it is a welcome addition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
