<SLUG> BC-LIVING-COLUMN-HAHN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER NIGHT'S A NO-GLOW WITHOUT FIREFLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are no fireflies in Seattle because they get turned on and
burn out too fast.
</P>
<P>
   Local beetles belonging to the firefly family don't demonstrate
that characteristic bioluminescence their cousin beetles use east
of the Rocky Mountains. But why they don't seem to flash west of
the Rockies has been a puzzlement to us former flatlanders who
associate fireflies with deep-summer nights.
</P>
<P>
   Known also in the flat Midwestern vernacular as ``lightnin'
bugs,'' these silent sentinels of summer evening are as much a sign
of true summer in the nation's midsection as popping Scotch broom
seed pods are here in Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   We transplants truly miss those back-home beetles as much as we
don't miss Midwest mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   I wince now to recall how we mistreated those thousands, nay,
millions and gazillions of fireflies that punctuated our childhood
summer evenings with pale yellow twinkles at about bellybutton
level.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did we incarcerate jillions of them in Mason jars,
making ersatz lanterns, but we also commonly made ``firefly
rings.'' That is, we caught a firefly and ripped off the flashing
lower abdomen, pasting the pulp onto our fingers to create little
glowing jewels. Children who wouldn't think of ripping the wings
off butterflies would dash into the summer evening, prepared to rip
apart the fragile little bodies of 10 fireflies, one for each
finger.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, I miss them. After the sun has plopped behind the
Olympics or into the Pacific Ocean or just behind the apartment
building across the street, and the sky turns gold and pink and
blue, and then lavender and dark blue ... this is when fireflies
should start twinkling in cadence with cricket chirps.
</P>
<P>
   For awhile, I thought the answer was bats. Never before,
certainly not back in the Midwest, have I ever seen as many bats as
I do around my Woodinville digs once the sun goes down. And that's
just fine with me, because as summer wears on, I figure the bats
will gorge on the summer swarms of termites that pose real threats.
</P>
<P>
   But I attributed the lack of fireflies, as well, to those zippy
little bats aiming their radar-guided stomachs at the thousands of
flying insects. It was a trade-off, I figured, for the relative
scarcity of mosquitoes here in the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds semiscientific, but hardly sexy. And sex, I suggest, is
what the Great Firefly Shortage really is all about, hereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   It is generally thought that most adult fireflies west of the
Rocky Mountains do not light up. Some firefly eggs and wormlike
larvae display a modicum of bioluminescence, hence the term
``glowworm.'' But adults _ we're talking fireflies here _ in this
area just don't get turned on like they do back East.
</P>
<P>
   I postulate that they don't light up because our Puget Sound
fireflies are oversexed, and that firefly foreplay leads to their
speedy elimination. Thus, the perceived lack of fireflies.
</P>
<P>
   Stay with me on this: It is generally accepted that fireflies _
seeking to do in the summer evening the same thing many of us are
seeking, if not doing _ signal their availability. But they flash
their message in a firefly code that you and I cannot see or
decipher.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, female fireflies shamelessly flash phony codes to attract
male fireflies under false pretenses. When they have the males in
their cold coleopteran grasp, they murder them. Talk about sting
operations gone bad!
</P>
<P>
   And even before the hapless male can literally turn on, his
lights get punched out. She eats him!
</P>
<P>
   Thus, this overaggressiveness of the female Puget Sound firefly
eventually made most of the male fireflies retreat back over the
Rocky Mountains. On their way, they commissioned a huge billboard
some of you may remember:
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the last firefly leaving Seattle please turn out his
light!''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, would I lie to you?
</P>
<P>
   Jon Hahn is a staff columnist for the P-I. He can be reached at
206-448-8317 or e-mail him at jonhahn(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
