<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TRAP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PARENT TRAP' CAPTURES CHARM OF EARLIER FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the last few years, the Disney Co. has become such a
purveyor of junked-up, low-humor comedies (``RocketMan,''
``Krippendorf's Tribe'') that critics shudder every time one of its
various logos appear on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   And the prospect of this insensitive bunch remaking one of
Walt's better live-action movies from a more innocent era _ the
1961 Hayley Mills hit, ``The Parent Trap'' _ is further cause for
alarm. It seems a particularly plum opportunity for cultural
vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   But surprise! A few too many Nickelodeon-style slime jokes
aside, this remake assiduously avoids the new-Disney low-humor
route. It's not high art but it's uniformly well-cast, reasonably
funny and finally a charming little family heartwarmer.
</P>
<P>
   The story, you may recall, is about two young look-alike girls
(both played by Lindsay Lohan) who meet cute one summer at a posh
Maine girls' camp and gradually discover, after much animosity,
that they're twins separated at birth by divorced parents.
</P>
<P>
   Twin One, Hallie, went to live with her American father (Dennis
Quaid) on his Napa Valley winery; Twin Two, Annie, went to live
with her British clothes designer mother (Natasha Richardson) in
her Mayfair townhouse. Neither twin previously knew of the other's
existence.
</P>
<P>
   So, naturally, the twins decide to switch identities so they can
get to know the parent they've never officially met, and maybe even
bring the estranged couple back together romantically. A
conspiracy, as it were, to trap their parents.
</P>
<P>
   The original benefited greatly from Mills' tomboyish charm and
remains her best-remembered role. It was also one of Disney's most
popular live-action movies of the '60s, and had TV-movie sequels in
1986 and '89 (with a grown-up Mills being trapped by kids of her
own).
</P>
<P>
   This new script by the writer-director-producer team of Nancy
Meyers and Charles Shyer (``Baby Boom,'' ``Father of the Bride'')
credits David Swift's original (which was, in turn, based on a 1954
British movie, ``Twice Upon a Time'') and follows it so closely
that both movies have ended up being exactly 124 minutes long!
</P>
<P>
   Happily, Meyers and Shyer also had the backbone to resist the
pressures to ``modernize'' (that is, junk up) the proceedings with
the flatulence jokes and other vulgar elements new-Disney has come
to institutionally believe are absolutely essential to connect with
young audiences of our crasser time.
</P>
<P>
   The casting works. The 10-year-old, exquisitely freckled-faced
Lindsay Lohan may not have Mills' unique star appeal, but she's
quite endearing as each of the twins; and Quaid and Richardson seem
even more likable _ and destined for a reunion _ than their
predecessors, Brian Keith and Maureen O'Hara.
</P>
<P>
   In other roles, Simon Kunz and Lisa Ann Walter do well as the
girls' respective housekeepers and surrogate parents. And Elaine
Hendrix is splendidly hateful as the biggest threat to family
unity: a scheming publicist out to trap Dad herself. (Joanna
Barnes, who played this part in the original, does a cameo as the
character's mother).
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the new ``Parent Trap'' seems to have put a great
deal of its budget into its visuals, and the production was _
rather unlikely _ designed by Hollywood's top art director, Dean
Tavoularis, who usually finds employment in the biggest Oscar-class
epics and star vehicles (``Apocalypse Now,'' ``The Godfather,''
``Bonnie and Clyde'').
</P>
<P>
   It's entirely possible, of course, that the film's attention to
travelogue beauty has more to do with the new Hollywood's strategy
of defraying costs with internal ``product placement'' _ and the
British Air logo is very prominently displayed. But, commercial or
no, London and the California wine country have rarely looked quite
so gorgeous on film.
</P>
<P>
   The Parent Trap. Directed by Nancy Meyers. Written by Meyers and
Charles Shyer from David Swift's 1954 version. Cast: Dennis Quaid,
Natasha Richardson, Lindsay Lohan. Walt Disney Pictures. 124
minutes. Rated PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
