<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6174 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-GUNS-BOS &LR;      07-28 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTINGS CHANGE FEW MINDS ON CAPITOL HILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last week's shooting at the US Capitol that left
two police officers dead and a woman injured has shaken many
Republicans who favor the right of law-abiding citizens to bear
arms. But few predict it will soften their opposition to gun
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should cower to the fear imposed on us
Friday,'' said Representative Howard Coble, a Republican from North
Carolina. ``If you are opposed to gun-control laws, you should
still be opposed to gun-control laws, what happened Friday
notwithstanding,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, neither side of the debate seems to have shifted
position since Russell Eugene Weston Jr., who authorities said has
a history of mental illness, allegedly stormed into the Capitol,
killing Detective John M. Gibson and Officer Jacob J. Chestnut, and
wounding tourist Angela Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson was assigned to protect House majority whip Tom DeLay,
and a colleague of the Texas congressman said DeLay has grieved for
Gibson as he would a brother. But DeLay continues to oppose gun
control, said John Feehery, DeLay's press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy has ``just magnified differences in the debate. Some
people say if more people had guns, we could have defended
ourselves better against this kind of crazy gunman,'' Feehery said.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control opponents on Capitol Hill acknowledge that the
tragedy is likely to reopen the issue, but they are determined not
to allow the other side to capitalize on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not even through the mourning period yet,'' said John
Czwartacki, spokesman for Senate majority leader Trent Lott. ``If
people on the one side or the other want to use this as sort of a
gun-control debate, I don't think there's much appetite right now
to do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some, such as Coble, argue that the District of Columbia bans
handguns but has a crime problem nonetheless. ``The guy who is
going to violate the law, he is going to find a way to get his hand
on the guns,'' Coble said.
</P>
<P>
   One irony of the shooting is that it has temporarily stopped the
House Judiciary Committee from considering, for the first time, a
bill that would create a national standard for carrying a concealed
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, an Illinois Republican, postponed
Tuesday's meeting ``out of respect to the memory of the slain
officers,'' said his spokesman, Sam Stratman.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, any person with a permit to carry a
firearm in one state would be allowed to use that same permit in
the 29 other states that allow concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, sponsored by Representative Randy Cunningham, a
Republican from California, would also allow any qualified current
or former law enforcement officer to carry a concealed handgun. The
provision on the portability of permits was introduced by
Representative Bill McCollum, the Florida Republican who is
chairman of the subcommittee on crime.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Democrat from Lowell and
member of the crime subcommittee, opposes the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly there will be politics involved in what legislation
we deal with between now and Aug. 7, and what legislation we don't
deal with,'' said Meehan, referring to the date the House is
scheduled to begin its summer recess.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Walker, president of Handgun Control Inc., a gun-control
lobbying group, said about the bill, ``It doesn't matter if it is
considered three days or three years after such a shooting, it
still poses a risk to public safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Carolyn McCarthy, a New York Democrat whose
husband was killed and son seriously wounded in the Long Island
Rail Road shooting five years ago, is hopeful some of her
colleagues will rethink the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just watching a number of members of Congress who are
certainly pro-guns and seeing their heartfelt sadness, maybe it
came a little closer to home,'' she said. ``We lost two wonderful
men here on the Capitol. I always believe that sometimes things
happen for a reason. Maybe this happened to put some focus on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
