r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-NEGOTIATOR-SPI &LR;      07-28 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NEGOTIATOR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEGOTIATOR' DOES FRESH TWIST ON THE COP MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood has cranked out so many hundreds of cop movies since
``The French Connection'' began the modern incarnation of the genre
more than 25 years ago that it's almost impossible for one to seem
fresh and original anymore. Yet, for all its flaws, ``The
Negotiator'' does just that.
</P>
<P>
   Its hero is Danny Roman (Samuel L. Jackson), an ace Chicago
police department hostage negotiator: a man skilled in reading the
subtle signs of various hostile psychological types, and
manipulating them into vulnerable situations or into giving up
their hostages.
</P>
<P>
   But Danny has a big problem. When his partner is murdered
shortly after telling him about a huge internal conspiracy within
the department to skim from their pension fund, Danny is framed to
take the fall for both the murder and the embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
   What does he do? He bursts into the office of the crooked
internal affairs officer (the late J.T. Walsh) and takes the man,
his secretary and a bystander hostage. So the tables are turned.
The negotiator is the hostage-taker, and another negotiator (Kevin
Spacey) has to come in to negotiate with him.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good premise, and the solid script (by James DeMonaco and
Kevin Fox) and nail-biting direction (by F. Gary Gray) make the
most of it, for at least three-fourths of the running time. The
portion of the film set within the confined space of the besieged
office is simply first-rate.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has rarely been better, and he seems more like a movie
star here than in possibly any film he's ever made. With his aura
of street smarts and his gift of gab, he's totally convincing as a
negotiator, and he also makes us believe his character's Kafkaesque
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the movie doesn't know when to let well enough
alone and ultimately wears out its welcome. Almost as if it doesn't
know how effective it is as a psychological drama, the script
finally disintegrates into a series of unlikely action scenes and
contrived plot twists.
</P>
<P>
   And why does the movie have to be so darn long _ an exhausting
two hours and 21 minutes? Obviously, a lot of that extra time is to
give co-star Spacey _ who doesn't make his entrance until 40
minutes into the movie _ some big scenes in the last act.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that, as engaging a movie presence as Spacey
undeniably is, his character is basically irrelevant to the
dramatic arc of this story. He's there entirely for his marquee
value, and the bulk of his hefty but supporting role just seems
like unnecessary padding.
</P>
<P>
   The Negotiator. Directed by F. Gary Gray. Written by James
DeMonaco and Kevin Fox. Cast: Samuel L. Jackson, Kvin Spacey,
David Morse, J.T. Walsh. Warner Bros. 141 minutes. Rated R for
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
