<HEADLINE>
LOST IN A LEXICAL LABYRINTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Constant reader Bill Thoen e-mailed not long ago to question a
Globe editorial on labyrinth walking. A labyrinth, the writer had
declared, is not the same as a maze; while a maze is purposely
confusing, with dead ends and confusing turns, a labyrinth is flat
on the ground and entirely visible, with one continuous path to the
center and back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did the Globe get those unique definitions?'' asked
Thoen. His Bulfinch's told him that the Minotaur of Greek myth had
been imprisoned in a labyrinth, and the bull-headed monster could
hardly have been penned in by a path marked on the ground. Nor
would Theseus, who finally slew the Minotaur, have needed Ariadne's
ball of string to find his way out of such a structure. And Thoen's
dictionaries assured him that a labyrinth was a maze, and vice
versa.
</P>
<P>
   For most of us, most of the time, a labyrinth is indeed a maze.
But there is a difference between unicursal mazes _ those with only
one path to the center _ and multicursal mazes, with their wrong
turnings and dead ends. The unicursal maze, or labyrinth, may be a
long and winding road, but it offers no choices. Multicursal mazes
_ like the pencil puzzles in newspapers and the hedge maze that
baffled Jack Nicholson in ``The Shining'' _ are made for getting
lost in.
</P>
<P>
   Both labyrinth and maze have been in the language since the 14th
century, and most often we use them figuratively, and
interchangeably, to describe any confusing territory: the plot of
``The Big Sleep,'' the federal tax code, the streets of Boston. But
the revival of labyrinth walking has brought back the long-dormant
distinction between the words. People who walk the path of a
labyrinth as a meditative exercise _ and over the past decade,
thousands of people have taken up the practice _ want it understood
that their course is not a confusion of choices but a simple route
to clarity.
</P>
<P>
   This push for precision has come upon us very suddenly; as
recently as 1992, a New York Times story about labyrinth walking
treated labyrinth and maze as synonyms. In the years since,
newspaper stories on the practice have begun to include a paragraph
explaining the difference _ often in a tone of offhand authority
that implies you ought to know it already. But the issue isn't
quite that simple.
</P>
<P>
   Exploring on the Internet _ a wonderful maze of labyrinth lore _
I found that puzzle mazes of the wrong-turn, dead-end variety seem
to be quite recent inventions, unknown till the late 17th century.
(Labyrinths, by contrast, are ancient designs, starting with the
Minotaur's holding pen in Crete and reproduced in Roman mosaics, in
Christian churches, in British and Finnish fields.) If that's so,
the words maze and labyrinth were truly synonymous in English for
more than three centuries, since they both described the only kind
of maze around before the late 1600s.
</P>
<P>
   This history also suggests that the Minotaur's labyrinth was a
unicursal maze, though presumably one with high walls to confine
both the monster and his sacrificial victims. That makes it sound
simple, but as one Web wizard points out, a high-walled, one-path
labyrinth could be just as confusing to a first-time explorer as
the most devious maze; Theseus had no way of knowing he didn't need
his ball of string. And even an open labyrinth is a puzzlement in
its way, leading the walker first near the goal, then unexpectedly
away once more. Today's labyrinths may look superficial, but the
word retains its freight of mystery.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with reviving the distinction between the
two words, now that labyrinth has a special meaning for a
particular (and growing) band of devotees. In fact, any word fan
who has ever bemoaned the loss of a nice semantic distinction is
bound to applaud this development. But let's not get rigid about
it: For everyday figurative use, to describe a baffling
bureaucratic or geographic thicket, either maze or labyrinth _ as
taste and rhythm dictate _ will continue to be just fine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cart before the horse
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A colleague was surprised recently to see the Fenway Park
Jumbotron hawking wares with the logo of the All-Star game coming
to Boston next summer. It wasn't the hustling he minded, but the
news that 1999 All-Star ``souvenirs'' were ``on sale now.'' A
souvenir, of course, is a reminder, a token of something you've
experienced (from the French for remember). Unless those $15
baseball caps have very special powers, they aren't likely to evoke
memories of next year's game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
