<HEADLINE>
HOUSE RACE SHOWS LABOR'S WEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The saying that ``labor creates all wealth'' may apply to the
8th Massachusetts Congressional District, where labor is wealthy in
the number of candidates who are strong supporters of unions,
organized labor, and working families.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the 8th congressional race has so many such candidates
that the Massachusetts AFL-CIO decided not to endorse any of them,
making it the only one of the nine congressional races that
received no endorsement from the 400,000-member organization.
</P>
<P>
   There are strong, politically pragmatic reasons why the
executive council decided not to give an endorsement in the
most-publicized congressional race in the Bay State.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rogers, field director for the state AFL-CIO, said one
reason was the fact that all but possibly two of the 10 candidates
support the state AFL-CIO's agenda and it is virtually a certainty
that one of the pro-labor candidates will be elected to succeed US
Representative Joseph P. Kennedy II, who decided earlier this year
to not seek re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strategically, it made no sense for us to try to pick one
candidate from a field packed with proven allies,'' Rogers said.
Rather, he added, ``our resources are being allocated to the Third
and Sixth congressional districts, where the outcome could have
enormous national significance.``
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was referring to the congressional re-election bids of
Representative John F. Tierney of Salem (6th District), who will be
again facing former GOP Representative Peter G. Torkildsen of
Danvers, whom Tierney narrowly defeated in 1996 by a slim margin;
and Representative James P. McGovern of Worcester (3d District),
who will be facing the GOP challenger, state Senator Matthew J.
Amorello of Grafton.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the state's congressional races, in which some Democrats
are unopposed, Tierney's and McGovern's apparently are the only
races where there are serious GOP bids to unseat the two Democrats.
The state AFL-CIO as well as the candidates themselves expect the
national GOP to help Amorello and Torkildsen.
</P>
<P>
   If one or both of two Democrats are defeated, it would further
erode the Democrats' chances of retaking control of the US House of
Representatives this year.
</P>
<P>
   As for the 8th district race, the AFL-CIO and other labor
activists apparently view it as one that is virtually assured to be
in the ``win'' column this year.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the 10 candidates, including Raymond L. Flynn, former
Boston Mayor and former US ambassador to the Vatican; Majorie
Clapprood, former Sharon state representative and talk show host;
Mike Capuano, mayor of Somerville; Susan Tracy, former state
representative from Allston-Brighton; George Bachrach, former state
senator from Watertown; Charles Yancey, Boston City Councilor; John
O'Connor, businessman and environmental activist; and Alex
Rodgriguez, former state and federal government official.
</P>
<P>
   The only candidates who might not have the least chance of
winning an AFL-CIO endorsement, had there been one, would have been
Boston City Councilor Thomas Keane, who opposed the labor-supporter
living wage ordinance in Boston; and venture capitalist Christoper
Gabrieli, whose support for charter schools runs counter to the
Boston Teachers Union stance on these schools.
</P>
<P>
   While some unions are quietly watching this 8th congressional
race from the sidelines, other unions have been quietly lending
their support this year to some of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn, who is considered by political pundits to be the
frontrunner at this stage of the election, has been actively
seeking, and receiving, the backing of some labor unions. Others
also receiving labor support include Tracy, Capuano, and Clapprood,
based largely on their current and past alliances.
</P>
<P>
   Some labor groups are also looking at O'Connor, who is viewed by
some political analysts as the candidate who sounds more like
Kennedy in his ads and his campaign visits.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, if one of the eight candidates who supports labor's
agenda wins in Novemer -- as most political assessments suggest --
the state AFL-CIO, the umbrella group for organized labor in
Massachusetts, also wins. That is what these endorsements, and even
the lack thereof, are all about.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
