<SLUG> BC-BELL-GTE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC-GET MERGER WOULD CREATE LARGEST LOCAL PHONE FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Corp., which already has been angling to provide
long-distance service on its home turf of New York, could catapult
into the $70 billion-a-year long-distance market nationwide if its
merger takes place with GTE Corp., an independent phone company
with two million long-distance customers.
</P>
<P>
   The regional Bell operating company, which has a virtual
monopoly on local phone service from Maine to Virginia, is
reportedly in merger negotiations with GTE, which has far-flung
local phone operations in 28 states, with a strong presence in
parts of Florida, Texas and Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Initial estimates are that a Bell Atlantic-GTE merger would be
valued at about $55 billion. That price would be less than GTE's
recent market value.
</P>
<P>
   GTE Monday closed at 55, down 2 3/16, while Bell Atlantic was
off 3/16, ending at 45.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company would be the nation's largest local
telephone company in revenue, with $53 billion in yearly sales and
62 million local telephone lines in 40 states.
</P>
<P>
   A Bell Atlantic-GTE combination would continue the breakneck
pace of telecommunications industry consolidation this year as
phone companies merge to take advantage of newly deregulated
markets and new technology.
</P>
<P>
   For Bell Atlantic and the other Baby Bells that have monopolies
on local service, long-distance has been their most sought-after
prize in the last decade. The possibility of getting into
long-distance became even more tantalizing after passage of the
Telecommunications Act of 1996. While the act allowed the Baby
Bells to enter new markets, it bars them from offering
long-distance until they open their own local phone markets to
competition. So far, none of the regional Bells have met the act's
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic hopes to be the first local phone company to offer
long-distance. In New York, it has reached an agreement with state
regulators and the United States Justice Department to allow some
competitors to tie into its phone switches. If the New York
proposal is carried out to the satisfaction of the Federal
Communications Commission, Bell Atlantic would become the first
Baby Bell to offer long-distance on its home turf.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic's potential union with GTE would be the second leg
of its grand strategy to become a nationwide long-distance carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bell Atlantic will have a two-pronged long-distance strategy
if this deal goes through _ one for its backyard and the other for
the rest of the country, or otherwise the Federal Communications
Commission would not be happy,'' said Ford D. Cavallari, &UR;  &LR; vice
president at Renaissance Worldwide, a Newton-based consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   GTE, in theory, would let Bell Atlantic offer long-distance over
much of the country. Unlike the regional Bell companies, GTE, an
independent phone company offering long-distance service in 50
states, isn't bound by the same restrictions of the telecom act.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Bell Atlantic-GTE would still have to comply with
the act in the 13 states that Bell Atlantic currently serves, the
merger would give Bell Atlantic clear sailing with long-distance
customers in much of the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   However, some analysts maintained that Bell Atlantic's use of
GTE as a launching pad for long-distance might not pass antitrust
scrutiny. A Bell Atlantic-GTE merger would be examined with a fine
tooth comb, observers said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said one sticking point may be that Bell Atlantic
may not be allowed under the telcommunications act to pick up GTE's
long-distance customers in the 13 Eastern states. Analysts
speculated that GTE could be required to shed some of its
long-distance customers in the east as a condition for regulatory
approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expect regulators to have a heyday with this one,'' said
Jeffrey Kagan, president of Kagan Telecom  &UR;  &LR; Associates, an Atlanta
telecommunications market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts noted that GTE's long-distance capabilities _
plus its other services such as Internet access and wireless
technology _ could help Bell Atlantic compete against other Baby
Bells. GTE offers Bell Atlantic ``a perfect position from which to
launch a competitive attack from within another Bell's region,''
said Kagan.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that GTE is the local phone company in the
Raleigh-Durham area of North Carolina, while BellSouth controls the
rest of the state. Bell Atlantic could use Raleigh-Durham to attack
BellSouth's dominance in North Carolina. Bell Atlantic could then
claim that its merger with GTE increases competition, Kagan said.
</P>
<P>
   If Bell Atlantic and GTE can demonstrate to regulators that they
will vigorously compete in long-distance against other regional
Bell companies, Kagan maintained, the merger will be in the
public's interest and should win approval. ``Without this promise,
the deal will be self-serving and have a really rough ride on the
regulatory roller coaster,'' said Kagan.
</P>
<P>
   GTE has had a checkered career in long-distance service.
Initially, it created Sprint and later sold it. In 1997, it tried
unsuccessully to acquire MCI Communications Corp. But it succeeded
last year in acquiring BBN Corp. of Cambridge, Mass., a leading
Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it offers its predominantly suburban customers local and
long-distance phone service, Internet access, wireless and paging
services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
