<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELO A GOOD BET AT SARATOGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Saratoga meeting begins Wednesday and the many fans who will
head to The Spa, which will be open through Labor Day, are looking
for handicapping tips that will make a day at the most charming of
racetracks even more enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   Who, then, better to ask than John Angelo, an expert of the
Saratoga races, who will be there every day of the meet? Angelo's
credentials are impressive. He published ``Saratoga Scorecard,'' a
bettor's handbook, from 1988-92, when it was bought by the Daily
Racing Form, which published it for two years before it was
discontinued. He currently is the racing writer for the Glens Falls
Post-Star, which takes its coverage of Saratoga very seriously, and
collaborates with Jim Mazur on ``The Saratoga Handicapper,'' a
gambler's guide packed with statistics, which is updated twice
during the 36-day stand. Both of Angelo's parents grew up in Glens
Falls and John, when he was 14, saw Damascus win the Travers in
1967.
</P>
<P>
   So, starting with the always interesting subject of track bias,
here are some of Angelo's observations:
</P>
<P>
   ``When the main track gets hot and dry, it becomes more speed
favoring, so I look to the weather. Plus, there is always the
chance that, right off the bat, there will be a speed bias. The
Saratoga track can be exactly the opposite of the Belmont Park
surface, where you want to make that sweeping move off the turn
about four-wide. You need to lay up close on the main track at
Saratoga. I key off Jerry Bailey the way I used to key off Angel
Cordero when he rode. If Cordero gunned his mounts, you knew the
track was speed-favoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for slop, horses either like the Saratoga slop or they
don't. Don't confuse their Belmont slop form with what they can do
at Saratoga. A horse might well like the Belmont slop but hate the
Saratoga slop. When it's sloppy, closers tend to do well in the
route races.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about the turf?
</P>
<P>
   ``The grass course was so firm last year that a lot of records
were set. In general, you have to save ground and stay within sight
of the leaders. In the old days, you tended to get a ton of closers
winning, but in recent years you better stay within 5 lengths of
the pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Angelo believes the key to success at The Spa is to follow the
trainers, more so than the jockeys or horses. ``Saratoga lends
itself to trainer patterns,'' he said. ``What you need to know is
who starts quickly and who comes along.'' On Angelo's list of fast
starters are Mark Hennig, Elliott Walden, John Kimmel, and Shug
McGaughey. On his list of closers are Gasper Moschera, Todd
Pletcher, Leo O'Brien, and Rusty Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   As for betting strategies, Angelo thinks Bill Mott's horses are
overplayed. ``It's probably best to try to beat Mott because he's
so overbet,'' Angelo said. ``There are a whole slew of guys you can
do better with. The name folks get overbet because Saratoga draws a
casual crowd. When they hop on somebody, they really hop on him. If
your going to spot play a trainer try Angel Penna Jr., Mohammed
Moubarak or Jonathan Sheppard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sheppard is known for training jumpers but every year he puts
over a flat winner. He gives them a prep at Atlantic City or Penn
National or Delaware, so they always look outclassed on paper, but
they always run well at a pretty generous price.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the true highlights of the Saratoga meeting is the
2-year-old racing. And, once again, Angelo says look for a price.
``Mott's not great with first-time starters,'' he said. ``He's 3
for 24 over the last three meetings. D. Wayne Lukas is another
trainer whose firsters are generally overbet. He's 3 for 22 over
the last three years. The idea is to toss those two guys out and
take a stand against them. One to watch is Linda Rice, she's very
good with 2-year-olds.''
</P>
<P>
   Post position is always a consideration. How does the post
affect a horse's chances at The Spa? ``Post is important in the
7-furlong races,'' Angelo said. ``At 7 furlongs, it's a real
disadvantage to be in the 1 hole. Also, it's really hard to go
wire-to-wire at 7 furlongs.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some stats of interest before you make that trip to
upstate New York:
</P>
<P>
   ``The favorites ruled last year, winning at a 42 percent clip
(the average is 30),'' said Angelo. ``Of the favorites who won, 19
percent were odds-on. Still, you would have made a 30 percent
profit if you placed a two-dollar wager on the longest shot in
every race. It was certainly a strange year.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you're looking for perfection, trainer Guadalupe
Preciado, who is based at Philadelphia Park, is your man. Angelo
points out that Preciado started one horse at Saratoga in 1996,
which won at 9-1, and then came back with one more last year, which
scored at 23-1. Take that Mott and Lukas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
First time for everything
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trainer  &UR; Bob Baffert  &LR; described himself as ``sort of baffled''
after Silver Charm finished last, beaten 27 lengths, in the
$250,000 San Diego Handicap at Del Mar Saturday. It was the first
time that Silver Charm, who went off at odds of 3-10, has finished
worse than second in 15 career starts (8-6-0). Following the race,
rider  &UR; Gary Stevens &LR;  thought Silver Charm had ``probably bled
significantly,'' but that turned out not to be the case. ``He bled
very slightly, but not enough to stop him,'' said Baffert Sunday.
``His legs are fine. We just don't know what happened. We'll just
see how he is in the next few days. We're going to take him back to
the track this week and we'll do some tests. We'll know better in a
week what we're going to do with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
