<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION MUST TAKE IT FROM THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Revolution appear to be allowing an unworkable situation to
degenerate into absurdity. The team has failed in almost every
sense, falling into last place in the Eastern Conference with a 2-1
defeat to Miami Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Management apparently does not want to scapegoat coach Thomas
Rongen. But by leaving Rongen in command the Revolution are risking
turning a bad situation into something much worse.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a matter of assigning blame, though most of Rongen's
player selections have been poor. Most of the team's personalities
have been eliminated. Rongen has tried nearly everything to solve
the problems and now has resorted to desperate tactics.
</P>
<P>
   There is little evidence the situation will improve.
</P>
<P>
   By stubbornly supporting Rongen, the Revolution are failing to
manage the situation. The tension is bound to increase, sides are
being taken, and no winners are likely to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution's record and uninspired performances indicate
Rongen is drowning and he is taking the team with him. Neither
Rongen nor management wants to admit failure. But it is unhealthy
to ignore reality.
</P>
<P>
   Miami had won only three times in regulation before replacing
coach Cacho Cordoba with Ivo Wortmann. At least the Fusion had a
contingency plan and have been able to confront a desperate
situation with a dramatic solution.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows if the Fusion's plan will work. But this is how
professional sports function: if a team is floundering, a change
must be made at the top, almost always the coach. It is not a
matter of fault. To defy this axiom calls into question the
credibility of an organization.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Net gains
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Major League Soccer officials have a much more
demanding set of circumstances than those in other US sports
because they are measured against international standards. They
have few assets worthy of consideration on the worldwide market and
are often managing those assets from a position of weakness. They
do, however, have strong sponsorships and solid ownership, plus the
advantage of being a league with great growth potential.
</P>
<P>
   MLS made a profit on Frankie Hejduk, who will join Bayer
Leverkusen after Tampa Bay's season ends. The price was low _ about
$200,000 _ but this will be an excellent deal for Hejduk, who was
earning only $27,000 from MLS and would become a free agent after
his contract expires in December.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger gain is about to be realized from the sale of Sean
Bartlett, who played for Colorado and the MetroStars then was
loaned to a South African club and scored twice for the Bafana
Bafana in the World Cup. A European club has offered $1 million for
Bartlett, and most of that would go to MLS.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest potential earning is from D.C. United defender
Eddie Pope, who seems reluctant to depart. The league got a bargain
by signing Pope for seven years at about $236,000 per. Sources said
Pope's value on the open market is between $1.5 and $2 million but
MLS deputy commissioner Sunil Gulati said he has been offered $3
million for Pope.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Arena's arena?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Arena is emerging as the most viable candidate to succeed
Steve Sampson as US national team coach.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Queiroz has been dropped from consideration after signing
a multimillion-dollar contract as technical director for the United
Arab Emirates. Queiroz is bringing a team of coaches to the UAE,
including Toni, who guided Benfica to its last two Portuguese
League titles.
</P>
<P>
   Arena, who has guided D.C. United to two successive MLS titles,
will meet with US Soccer Federation president Alan Rothenberg
before Sunday's MLS All-Star Game in Orlando. Arena would have to
be allowed the freedom to experiment with new players and also to
express himself. In the past USSF officials have been too sensitive
to Arena's remarks. Rather than censor the coach the USSF should
confront the issues Arena raises and capitalize on the publicity.
</P>
<P>
   If this doesn't work out, Queiroz will become available before
long. He has a one-year contract with a one-year option in the UAE.
And if the UAE fails to defeat Saudi Arabia in the Gulf Cup,
Queiroz certainly will be out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Nakata controversial
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kazu Miura was a trailblazer for Japanese soccer, performing for
teams in Brazil and Italy. But he had not made much of an impact at
Santos or Genoa, where he scored once in 21 games before returning
to Japan in 1996. In fact, Genoa would not likely have given Miura
a chance except a Japanese corporation paid his contract. Miura was
an excellent vehicle for marketing; his girlfriend was a glamorous
actress, he was the subject of Herb Ritts's artwork. But he simply
was not fast or clever enough to excel outside Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Hidetoshi Nakata is a different story. Nakata, 21, is expected
to start in midfield for Perugia, newly promoted to Italy's Serie
A. Miura projected a positive image. Nakata is controversial,
though he has removed the yellow dye from his hair.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Nakata virtually had to escape Japan after refusing to
sing the national anthem during World Cup matches, then receiving
death threats after saying in a magazine interview, ``I will never
sing. Because I refute the lyrics, which are profoundly
imperialistic, an anthem to the war of domination and expansion
that doesn't enter into my concept of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Perugia president Luciano Gaucci is willing to gamble on Nakata
in an attempt to stay in Serie A. He has added several players on
loan: Pietro Strada, Brazilian Ze Maria, and, possibly, Luigi
Apolloni from Parma; goalkeeper Angelo Pagotto from Milan. But
coach Ilario Castagner is not so sure, especially since Nakata will
require an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among other things, Nakata put in his contract that he doesn't
want a roommate, I don't know why,'' Castagner said. ``Being close
to an Italian could help increase his rapport with the others.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Change of signals
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   South Korea is sending signals that it will pull out of its
cohost role with Japan for the 2002 World Cup. Chung Mong Joon, the
Hyundai heir and South Korean federation president, proposed
delaying the tournament's start until late September to avoid the
rainy season. Since the Europeans never will agree to such a
change, this could allow the Koreans to save face ... Nigeria
departed the World Cup in disarray after a 4-1 loss to Denmark last
month in Paris. Now, midfielder Nwankwo Kanu and defender Taribo
West have fallen out of favor by reporting late to training camp
with Inter. West, a fan favorite and an important player last year,
likely will be sold. He had similar troubles with Auxerre in
France, according to coach Guy Roux. ``He always has a relative who
died when he returns to Nigeria, so that delays his return,'' Roux
said. ``One of his cousins has already died three times.'' ...
Johan Cruyff was among those critical of France's World Cup
championship team. ``Attack was the Achilles' heel of Les Bleus,''
Cruyff wrote in L'Equipe magazine. ``It is rare to make it to the
final without an attacker or midfielder scoring in three successive
matches.'' Basically, France would unleash Zinedine Zidane for the
first half of the first half of games. But with only one striker,
and with seven field players concentrating on defense, it was
almost impossible to create an attack. Opponents would soon contain
Zidane, who would continue with his pyrotechnics but without
offensive support. Cruyff and Germany's Franz Beckenbauer bridged
the ``King of Soccer'' gap between Pele and Diego Maradona. The
throne remains empty now, and those who might qualify for it
(Zidane, Roberto Baggio) have been throttled by conservative
coaching mentalities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
