<HEADER>
A6191 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      07-28 1400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX SHOULDN'T TRIP UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Three time zones and a continent away, Red Sox
progress over the next two weeks will best be charted by night
crawlers and insomniacs, those who close the bars and open the
doughnut shops, the cabbie picking up his last fare, and the
deliveryman dropping off his first crate of orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's the reason, this collective anxiety that stems from
having to wait until morning to find out whether their team won or
lost, that causes Red Sox fans to look upon West Coast trips with
such foreboding.
</P>
<P>
   Bad things tend to happen in the middle of the night, which is
when, on Atlantic clocks, most Red Sox activity takes place when
they're on the Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams was ejected for the first time as Red Sox manager
in Anaheim last August. That same night, Darren Bragg was beaned.
</P>
<P>
   It happened in broad daylight, but it was here in Oakland that
Roger Clemens got himself thrown out of a playoff game eight years
ago, when he showed up on the mound wearing eye black and an
attitude and was expelled by umpire Terry Cooney.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the New England bias toward the Left Coast, which
in the provincial view offers little but earthquakes, mudslides,
and O.J. in a place inhabited solely by hedonists, weirdos, and
assorted other nut cases.
</P>
<P>
   It was in Anaheim, after all, the Sox fan will tell you with a
knowing nod, that Wade Boggs met Margo Adams.
</P>
<P>
   So, it is with some trepidation that Red Sox fans watched their
team embark Monday on a 14-day, 12-game trip that begins Tuesday
night with the first of three games in Oakland, is followed by a
three-game set in Anaheim, continues with a pair in Seattle, then
has the added bonus of four games tacked on in Texas, where
sometime before the end of the millennium the temperature is
expected to drop below 100 degrees again.
</P>
<P>
   Total air miles: 7,300.
</P>
<P>
   The trip, their longest of the season, begins with the Red Sox
holding a 4 1/2-game lead over the Rangers in the American League
wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   When it is over, the Red Sox will stray only infrequently from
Boston. Of their last 47 games, 31 are scheduled to be played at
Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   So this odyssey is looked upon as a potentially dangerous detour
from a hoped-for appointment with the playoffs in October. If the
Red Sox survive this forced march, the smart money says, they
should be in great shape for the stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to the heart of the matter: Just how
perilous is this journey likely to be?
</P>
<P>
   The record, especially in the '90s, suggests it's not as bad as
the worriers would like to think.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have a winning record this decade on the Coast
(81-69), and have yet to finish any season in the '90s with a
losing record in games played here. But there's an asterisk
attached: That record does not include games played in Texas, where
the Sox came into this season with a record of 13-28 and this May
were soundly beaten in their only two games there.
</P>
<P>
   It should also be noted that the Sox opened the season here, and
after beating the A's twice, won once in their last six games
against the Mariners (1 of 3) and Angels (three straight losses).
The Sox managed just one run in each of the three games in Edison
International Field.
</P>
<P>
   What awaits the Sox on this go-round? Well, two of the four
teams they're playing, the Angels and Rangers, are battling each
other for the AL West division lead, with the eventual runner-up
figuring to be Boston's stiffest competition for the wild-card
spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, meanwhile, were 16 games out of first place in the
West July 1, but they're 14-7 so far this month and begin the day
just 8 1/2 games out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get to .500 first before we can start thinking
about the playoffs,'' said manager Lou Piniella, but it was just
three years ago the Mariners overtook the Angels with a late-season
push, and they've been in the playoffs every season since.
</P>
<P>
   A city-by-city look at what the Red Sox are facing:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Oakland:  &LR; While the Red Sox left Boston Monday morning and had
all day to adjust to their jet lag, the A's were still back in
Florida Monday night, closing out a series with the expansion Tampa
Bay Devil Rays, and didn't figure to arrive home until 4 a.m.
They've lost seven in a row and been outscored, 48-23. The A's not
only have yet to beat the Red Sox in five meetings this season,
they have yet to score a run off Sox closer Tom Gordon, who has a
win and three saves to go along with his 0.00 ERA. Always a
potential headache for the Red Sox, however, is Rickey Henderson,
who has 43 stolen bases and is bidding to become baseball's oldest
stolen base champ. Ex-Sox Kevin Mitchell, the jumbo-sized
outfielder, is tied with Sox DH Midre Cummings for most pinch hits
in the league, seven.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Anaheim:  &LR; The Angels, who went a franchise-record 22-6 in June,
have not been able to keep up that pace, partly because in the last
11 days, their players have gone to the hospital six times. That
includes lefthander Chuck Finley, who in an April duel against
Pedro Martinez held the Red Sox to four hits and a run while
striking out 10 in nine innings in a game won by the Halos in extra
innings. Finley went to the hospital three times: He sustained a
gash in his right knee that required eight stitches, he bruised his
right forearm when struck by a foul ball while sitting in the
dugout, which caused his start to be pushed back, and then when he
finally did pitch, he was hit in the left elbow by another line
drive and forced to leave the game. Finley is scheduled to pitch
Thursday against the Yankees and thus is unlikely to face the Sox
this go-round. Also a possibility to miss the series is Dave
Hollins, who played briefly for the Sox in '95 and whose intensity
marks him as the team's spiritual leader. Hollins injured his right
shoulder sliding into first base and may not be back until after
the weekend. There is concern, too, about closer Troy Percival, who
has complained of dizziness for three straight days and was
undergoing neurological tests to determine what is causing the
condition. Both Jim Edmonds and Darin Erstad have been slumping,
but outfielder Garret Anderson has a 24-game hitting streak, tying
Nomar Garciaparra for the longest in the majors this year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Seattle:  &LR; The Mariners hit nine home runs in three games
against the Red Sox in April and lead the majors with 161 home
runs. Junior Griffey is chasing Roger Maris, of course, and Alex
Rodriguez, who just turned 23 Sunday, needs just two stolen bases
to become the sixth player in AL history with at least 30 home runs
and 30 stolen bases in a season. The 40-40 plateau achieved
previously by only Jose Canseco and Barry Bonds is within reach.
The Mariners have scored 58 runs in their last eight games, an
average of better than seven a game, and when Griffey isn't hitting
home runs, he's stealing bags. He had three Sunday, and he and
A-Rod will be a handful for Sox catchers Scott Hatteberg and Jason
Varitek. The good news here is that the Sox will not face the Big
Unit, Randy Johnson, who goes Tuesday night against the Indians and
may be pitching for either Cleveland or New York by the time the
Sox arrive in town.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Texas:  &LR; The Rangers are just 8-9 since the break, their
fortunes fading alongside their staff ace, former Sox righthander
Aaron Sele, who has gone from 13-3 to 12-7 and faces Roger Clemens
Tuesday night. The Sox will see Sele in Arlington, where the big
story remains the big bats of outfielder Juan Gonzalez and catcher
Ivan Rodriguez. Gonzalez leads the majors in RBIs and has driven in
15 runs in his last six games after being held without an RBI in
back-to-back games. Gonzalez's 116 RBIs in 104 games is six more
than Hack Wilson had in the same number of games in 1930, when he
set a major league rec-ord with 190 RBIs. The Rangers are
desperately seeking another starting pitcher and figure to have one
by the time the Sox arrive. But Rangers GM Doug Melvin conceded
Sunday that it won't be Clemens, whom he had hoped the Blue Jays
would be willing to move after the Red Sox took three of four from
Toronto last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   So there are pitfalls aplenty facing the Sox. But none, it would
seem, worth losing too much sleep over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
