<SLUG> BC-MA-CELLUCCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FIRST YEAR, FEW LEGISLATIVE WINS FOR CELLUCCI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The first thing Paul Cellucci did after taking the
reins of state government one year ago this Wednesday was to file a
bill to roll back the state's personal income tax rate to 5 percent
from 5.95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   His first official act was orchestrated to show off his
credentials as a fiscal conservative and aggressive tax cutter who,
after serving 6 1/2 years as lieutenant governor and 14 years as a
legislator, knew how to get things done on Beacon Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve months later, the tax-cut bill does indeed stand as a
testament to the Cellucci administration, though not in the way the
acting governor intended. Like most of the 86 other bills Cellucci
filed over the last year, the tax-cut legislation is mired in
committee with no chance of winning passage this year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to point to one significant legislative victory, Cellucci,
during an interview with the Globe on Friday, said it is the $770
million tax cut _ authored by Democratic leaders _ passed by House
and Senate as state coffers were overflowing because of the booming
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really concerned about credit, I'm concerned about
whether we're getting things done to benefit the people of this
state,'' Cellucci said. ``I signed the largest tax cut in history a
few days ago. It wasn't everything I wanted, but it was a big down
payment on what I was looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   If Cellucci's first year in office can be used as an indicator
of the type of governor he would be if elected in November, some
political analysts conclude it would be low-key, uninspiring, and
tentative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anything he pushed and got signed into law,''
said Michael Cudahy, an independent media consultant who left the
Republican party. ``He is clearly banking on the strength of the
economy and everybody being lulled into just a wonderful, calm
frame of mind because everything's going so well. I think that's a
dangerous strategy. He hasn't pushed any major legislation for fear
of upsetting the apple cart.''
</P>
<P>
   But Todd Domke, a Republican media consultant in Holliston, says
it's unfair to measure Cellucci's performance solely on the number
of bills he introduced and signed. Republican leaders, by
definition, would rather do less with government, not more. And
Cellucci, of course, must work with a Legislature controlled by
Democrats who have no interest in handing him legislative victories
during an election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulty there is with a Republican governor who wants
to limit government and a Democratic Legislature that generally
wants to expand government,'' Domke said. ``Progress has to be
measured as things not happening, and that's hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a list things that didn't happen has to include such
legislative priorities as reinstating the death penalty, returning
the income tax rate to 5 percent, and testing all state teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci takes the long view, however, when it comes to his
accomplishments. He said that ideas often take years to become law,
and he will keep pushing until his own are adopted. Despite the
disappointments, Cellucci said he is proud of his first 12 months
in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether I'm sitting in this office for 18 months or for six
years or for 10 years, I want to be able to look back and know that
I got some things done that helped the people of Massachusetts,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's chief of staff, Virginia Buckingham, contends many of
the administration's losses are actually wins because the acting
governor can promise to continue fighting for them on the campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will say Cellucci didn't deliver and he's not an
`effective governor,''' Buckingham said. But, she said, voters will
have to decide if they want someone who will continue fighting for
these issues or someone for whom they are not a priority at all.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's failure to win passage of a death penalty bill last
fall was perhaps the first sign that his legislative intiatives
were in trouble despite furious lobbying on their behalf by the
acting governor.
</P>
<P>
   Caught off guard when the bill failed on a tie vote in the House
last October, Cellucci lashed out at Speaker Thomas M. Finneran and
accused him of dirty tricks. A lone state representative, John P.
Slattery, a Peabody Democrat, had changed his mind and opposed the
bill, saying he worried that there were not enough safeguards for
juveniles and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, few issues have both captured the public's attention
and put Cellucci at the center of the action. Most recently,
Cellucci appeared hesitant to take charge when 59 percent of
would-be teachers in Massachusetts failed a state certification
exam and the Board of Education then voted to lower the standards
and increase the number of those who passed.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said at the time that there was nothing he could do
about the board's vote to lower standards. Three days later, he
stepped into the fray, calling on the board to take another vote
and raise the bar back up on the teachers' exam. The board then
reversed itself. He also filed a bill to require testing of current
teachers, and the firing of those who fail the test. The
legislation has been left for dead by the Legislature, but has
handed Cellucci an issue to talk about in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he seems tentative and more modest than an elected
governor,'' Domke said. ``It's a question of how much of that is
strategy, in terms of avoiding risks, or second nature after 20
years in elective office.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of Cellucci's work in the legislative arena over the last
year has been to stake out political positions, rather than making
a concerted effort to move bills through the Legislature to become
law.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Cellucci switched his stance on the minimum wage in
May, filing a bill to raise the hourly rate from $5.25 to $6.15
over the next two years. After that, he rarely mentioned the
subject, except to make a pitch for the wage hike at a hearing by
US Senator Edward M. Kennedy and US House Minority Leader Richard
A. Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Cellucci's support for the minimum wage bill, it has
been hung up in the House due to objections by Finneran. Lawmakers
say it is not clear whether the bill will clear the final hurdles
before the end of the session July 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always fun to get to this point in the legislative
session when the clock is ticking,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the major legislation Cellucci filed over the last year, only
four bills became law, while the rest have sat in House and Senate
committees. But Cellucci also claims credit for bills filed by his
predecessor, William F. Weld, that Cellucci later signed. Those
include measures to deregulate electricity rates and reduce
unemployment insurance rates for businesses by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bills Cellucci has proposed on his own have ranged from the
fiscal, such as returning the income tax rate to 5 percent, to the
social, such as combating drug-induced rape and kidnapping. He said
he hopes he will also be given the opportunity to sign legislation
he proposed to impose life sentences on all second-time sex
offenders and allow civil commitments even after the offender has
already served a prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most significant measure Cellucci proposed and
signed was actually the brainchild of Senator Edward M. Kennedy.
Congress passed a $30 billion measure to provide grants to states
to expand publicly assisted health care to children. Massachusetts
_ and every other state _ was required to pass its own legislation
to put the program into place.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci did initiate, and eventually signed, a bill to
improve the state's child support enforcement. A new law makes
timely support payments a condition of parole and probation,and it
also broadens employer reporting requirements to include
independent contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci has also signed numerous bills that were conceived and
written by Democratic members of the House and Senate, but reflect
a socially liberal approach to government. Highlights include: a
prohibition of smoking in certain state office buildings; a
requirement to divest tobacco stocks and securities from public
pension funds; a bill of rights for mental patients; and an
employee leave measure.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders credit Cellucci with salvaging a $194
million cut in businesses' unemployment insurance tax bills. A
stalemate between the House and Senate over reducing the tax rate
prompted Cellucci to step in and point out that the unemployment
insurance trust fund had hit $1.25 billion, enough to pay out
benefits for almost two years without new contributions. That broke
the logjam and Cellucci signed the bill last September.
</P>
<P>
   While he has signed 354 bills during his one year as acting
governor, Cellucci has only used his veto 10 times, and six of
those were overridden. For example, herejected a Cape Cod land bank
bill designed to fund preservation with state aid and an assessment
on local property tax bills. And he vetoed a convention center
bill, saying tax increases should not be included in the
legislation without voter approval. Those vetoes were overridden.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, Cellucci apparently has been banking on a strong
economy and voter apathy to cruise into his first elected term as
governor. He has been reticent to take positions on controversial
issues, such as pay raises for legislators and bonuses for top toll
collectors.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude has translated into a legislative record with few
accomplishments worth bragging about but also few major blunders,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that will matter if Cellucci is elected governor,
said Kevin Sowyrda, a GOP consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to the Republicans taking back the corner office (in
1990) was economic malaise,'' Sowyrda said. ``Now, we will probably
hold onto power because of economic prosperity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
