<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SECURITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SAYS 50,000 PEOPLE CHARACTERIZED AS THREATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although the Secret Service maintains a database of
50,000 people considered ``possible threats'' to the president,
including the alleged gunman who killed two Capitol Police
officers, only about 100 are under regular surveillance, according
to people familiar with the system.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged gunman, Russell Eugene Weston Jr., was considered
the lowest-level threat and was not being watched. Like many on the
list, Weston had been diagnosed as a paranoid schizophrenic.
</P>
<P>
   For the Secret Service, the issue of whether to monitor people
diagnosed as paranoid schizophrenics more closely has long been
studied, but deemed impractical. The agency has compiled many
studies that conclude that most schizophrenics are not prone to
violence. The reports also say it is difficult or impossible to
predict if any particular schizophrenic will turn violent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a lot more important to know whether there has been a
prior arrest for a violent crime'' than if a person is
schizophrenic, said David Shore, associate director for clinical
research for National Institute of Mental Health.
</P>
<P>
   Shore, who has studied hundreds of people who came to Washington
and demanded to see the president, said most of them had some form
of schizophrenia. But that did not mean they would become violent,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people have a right to buy a gun, refuse treatment, enter
a building,'' Shore said. ``Therefore, it is extremely hard to
prevent the kind of things that went on here.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the shooting Friday at the Capitol has prmpted the
Secret Service, which has no direct role in protecting the Capitol
or members of Congress, to review whether the number of closely
watched individuals should be increased.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service, which has about 2,200 agents, adds about
3,000 names a year to its database of 50,000 people who have made
threats against the president. Other names are regularly dropped
from the list.
</P>
<P>
   The list has three categories, with 100 people considered the
most serious threat, and the remaining individuals divided between
the next two levels. While people in the first two categories
usually are interviewed by the Secret Service and are ``read the
riot act,'' those in the third and lowest category are typically
interviewed by local law enforcement officers, according to Ronald
Kessler, author of ``Inside the White House.'' Kessler's book
focuses in part on how the the Secret Service does its job.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler, in the course of his research, found himself impressed
by the way the Secret Service goes about finding and tracking
people who are threats to the president. Although he does not know
of a case when a potential assassin turned out to be on a watch
list, he said the work done during the investigation of potential
threats probably prevents some incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the threats are based on hearsay information, sometimes
as vague as one person overhearing another at a bar saying
something threatening about the president. The Secret Service also
tracks people who have written letters or e-mail to the president
and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, for example, the Secret Service investigated two
18-year-olds in Scarborough, Maine, who allegedly sent a
threatening e-mail to Hillary Rodham Clinton. The teenagers, whose
names were not released, were pulled out of class by Secret Service
agents but were not arrested, according to local news reports. A
person convicted of threatening to harm the president's family
faces a maximum penalty of three years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Secret Service were to turn into a Soviet-style
security agency, it would be impossible to track all of the people
who are considered threats, former agents have said. The agency
also must balance an individual's freedom of speech against whether
a real threat has been made.
</P>
<P>
   Secret Service officials declined Monday to discuss on the
record how they track people who are possible threats to the
president. But former top officials of the agency have said the
president is the subject of thousands of threats a year, with about
1,200 annually considered very serious.
</P>
<P>
   People who are considered the highest threats are watched more
closely when the president, vice president, or first lady is
visiting localities where those who made the threats live. But the
Secret Service has no way of knowing whether a person on the watch
list has shown up at one of the president's public events except to
try to find such an individual by watching the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   At most public events, the people who can get closest to the
president are known by name and are checked out in various
databases. But the audience is not screened by name. Instead, the
audience must pass through a metal detector, which the Secret
Service hopes will prevent someone with a gun or other weapon from
getting near the president.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of reports that Weston was a paranoid schizophrenic,
some specialists on mental illness said they hope the Weston case
will focus attention on the lack of follow-up treatment for
paranoid schizophrenics. Weston reportedly did not take medication
that had been prescribed. Some specialists said that while it would
be impossible for the Secret Service to track everyone who is a
threat to the president, it would be more beneficial if there were
a national health policy that required follow-up care for people
with schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   The National Alliance for the Mentally Ill, based in Arlington,
Va., reported that more than half of the more than 2 million people
diagnosed with schizophrenia have substandard care. Valerie
Rheinstein, a spokeswoman for the alliance, said Monday that
Weston's case ``begs the question of why there is not more
treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving I. Gottesman, professor of psychology at the University
of Virginia and the author of ``Schizophrenia Genesis,'' said the
Secret Service probably ``had no way of knowing'' that Weston would
turn violent.
</P>
<P>
   Gottesman said that if people with schizophrenia were required
to have the equivalent of a mental-health parole officer to monitor
their condition, then it might have been discovered that Weston was
not taking his medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who have mental illness and are treated for it have
a high probability of recovering,'' he said, whereas criminals are
more likely to remain lawbreakers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
