<HEADER>
A6200 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-HEATLORE-TEX     07-28 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HEATLORE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SUMMER GOES TO BLAZES, TEXAS PUNDITS GET FIRED UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Texas is hot, blistering hot. The kind of
hot that once irked Gen. Phil Sheridan enough for him to claim,
``If I owned Texas and all hell, I would rent out Texas and live in
hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere else would unrelenting heat and withering drought be
cause for humor. But in Texas, politicians and pundits, ranchers
and writers historically have poked fun at their own sun-baked
misery, turning scorching summers into part of the state's lore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing to come out of a drought is a dry sense of
humor,'' said Austin humorist Cactus Pryor. ``People keep laughing
about it, because it's supposed to be dry; that's Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so dry the trees are whistlin' for the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want wet, you go to Seattle. If you want cool, go
somewhere in the Northeast. If you want heat, you come to Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Pryor said historian Walter Prescott Webb once wrote that a lot
of the Texas bravado came not from having, but from lacking certain
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that would apply to good weather, too,'' Pryor said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' imperfections have been visible before. The late U.S.
Sen. Ben ``Pitchfork'' Tillman of South Carolina once said, ``Texas
has more trees and less timber; more rivers and less water; more
resources and less cash; more itinerant preachers and less
religion; more cows and less milk, and you can see farther and see
less than any damn country in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Civil War, Gen. Sheridan came to Galveston and
offered his infamous opinion. Nearly 20 years later, he explained
that he had been asked his opinion of Texas by a reporter just
after an exhaustive, dusty trip from San Antonio to Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan was mad, he said, and blurted out his well-known
statement. ``Now I want to assure you,'' he said later, ``that by
that expression I only meant to convey how much I was disgusted
with that newspaper man. It did not represent my opinion of
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Texans didn't hold Sheridan's statement against
him. In fact, one man who heard the general's explanation
commented: ``I have never understood that there was any feeling of
bitterness towards General Sheridan on account of his having made
that remark. The only reason people thought hard of him, at all,
was on account of his failing to kill that reporter,'' according to
a Galveston Daily News account.
</P>
<P>
   Texans, particularly West Texans, have always recognized the
shortcomings of the land and managed to find their own humor in the
hot, arid climate. It should be noted, however, that folklorist J.
Frank Dobie said that Texas didn't have a climate, just weather.
</P>
<P>
   Elmer Kelton wrote in ``The Time It Never Rained,'' his
descriptive novel about the 1950s drought: ``During the long Texas
drought of the 1950s a joke _ probably already as old as the state
_ was told again and again about a man who bet several of his
friends that it never would rain again, and collected from two of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Men like humorist Boyce House and writers Alex Sweet, Wallace O.
Chariton, Dobie and others have kept alive the humor of a hot, dry,
unforgiving Texas. They have repeated hundreds of stories in their
writings. No one knows any longer where most of them originated,
but they live on.
</P>
<P>
   There was the one about a drought so severe that the preacher
suggested a meeting be held to pray for rain. An old-timer
cautioned, ``Go ahead if you want to, but prayin' ain't gonna do
you a bit o' good unless the wind's outa the east.''
</P>
<P>
   Another relates how a motorist was traveling through West Texas
one day and stopped for gas. ``Nice town you have here,'' he told
the man at the gas station. The man fired back, ``It's hotter than
blazes in the summer and liable to drop 40 degrees in a couple of
hours in the winter. And the wind blows all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The motorist, a bit flustered, said, ``Well, I guess the people
are all right, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Naw,'' answered the man, ``They're the orneriest, triflin'est
folks you can find anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' the exasperated motorist said, ``except for the
climate and the people, I guess you could say the town is all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   The man looked up and said, ``Yes, and you could say the same
thing about hell.''
</P>
<P>
   And during a particularly dry spell, legend has it, a sad Texan
once prayed, ``I wish it would rain _ not so much for me, I've seen
it _ but for my 7-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   So how hot and dry can it get?
</P>
<P>
   Some responses gleaned from Texas folklore:
</P>
<P>
   _It was so dry, the cows were giving evaporated milk.
</P>
<P>
   _It was so hot, we had to feed the chickens cracked ice to keep
them from laying hard-boiled eggs.
</P>
<P>
   _It was so hot the birds had to use potholders to pull the worms
out of the ground.
</P>
<P>
   _It gets so dry is some parts of West Texas that citizens have
to fasten stamps to letters with safety pins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drought in Texas is so intense,'' a Kentucky newspaper
wrote in 1886, ``that potatoes are cooked in the ground, and all
the people have to do is dig them up and eat them. Workmen carry
salt in their pockets and don't have to go home to dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, a visitor to Texas once asked, ``Does it ever rain
out here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it does,'' a rancher quickly answered. ``Do you remember
that part in the Bible when it rained for 40 days and 40 nights?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm familiar with Noah's flood,'' the visitor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' the rancher puffed up, ``we got 2 1/2 inches during
that spell.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
