<HEADLINE>
HIV TRANSFUSION VICTIM FACES THE FUTURE WITH BRAVERY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SALLY JACOBS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTON, Mass. _ To be a 15-year-old girl and to be HIV positive
is to live a life like no other.
</P>
<P>
   It is to consult with the doctor before kissing your boyfriend.
It is to take eight pills a day probably for the rest of your life.
It is to believe you will never have sex or children. It is to be
plunged into panic when your sister cuts herself with a razor that
might be yours. It is to get a call after a party from someone
worried that they drank from your glass of Diet Pepsi. It is to
wonder how long you will live.
</P>
<P>
   Liz Kaplan has more reason to wonder than most. At 15 months,
she developed a fierce form of cancer. At 3, it was discovered that
during treatment, she had received a blood transfusion infected
with HIV. Twenty-five other people received blood from that donor
and Kaplan is one of only two who survived. Kaplan knew none of
this, not even that she was HIV positive, until her parents told
her after her bat mitzvah, a coming-of-age ritual Jewish youths
undergo at age 13. Born at a time when AIDS was no more than a
whisper, a horror as yet with no name, and having come of age as
the virus appears loosely corralled, her life had spanned its
rampage without her knowing it.
</P>
<P>
   A sage young woman in baggy jeans and white T-shirt, Kaplan
regards the warring forces in her life with Zen-like aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it as lucky and unlucky,'' explains Kaplan, twirling
a lock of her straight brown hair in her fingers. ``I was unlucky
to get cancer. I was lucky to survive. Obviously, it was unlucky to
get HIV, but it is lucky that if you are in a house with 25 other
people your name is drawn. And then you think, why me out of 25
people?''
</P>
<P>
   Her doctors would like very much to know the answer to that as
well. The virus in Kaplan's system is barely detectable. It has
been that way her entire life except for a brief period, after she
learned she was HIV positive, when her immune system cells, called
T cells, dropped precipitously. Doctors are fascinated that the
virus has remained inconspicuous for so long, significantly longer
than the median 10-year incubation period. But they are
particularly interested because she was infected when her immune
system was already weakened by cancer and chemotherapy. Generally,
when people are infected at such a vulnerable time, the virus's
pace is accelerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liz is completely unique,'' said Dr. Jerome Groopman, an AIDS
researcher at Harvard Medical School who has supervised Kaplan's
case since she was an infant. ``She has been doubly unfortunate,
doubly fortunate. Why she has remained so healthy, I don't know. It
could be something innate about her genetics or that she received a
weakened form of the virus. We have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kaplan's parents sat Liz down in the kitchen on that
December night and told her she was HIV positive, she was
catapulted down a shadowy emotional road. She was angry. Afraid.
Shocked. Resentful. But as the months passed, Kaplan also found she
was profoundly lonely. Who, really, could she talk to? Not her two
sisters, then only 8 and 11. Not her parents, who were, after all,
pretty OK but still her parents. Not her boyfriend, who, honestly,
didn't quite seem to get it.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan does not know anyone who is HIV positive. She is, she
says, ``not into the support group thing.'' She has found some
solace from a friend in her sophomore class at Newton North High
School, a girl who is epileptic and can understand the infuriating
rigors of doctors and medicine. Kaplan met a gay man with AIDS in
an on-line chat room and spent several months talking with him
about medicine and men before the conversation faded. Over the past
two years, she's told about 20 friends.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, she threw the net wider. On a bitter cold morning
in January, she stepped before her classmates during the school's
Martin Luther King Day celebration and, in a speech, announced that
she was HIV positive. Friends and even neighbors have rallied to
her. The phone rings. The notes are still coming. But to this day,
not a single person who has the virus has stepped forward, as
Kaplan had secretly hoped. Now, it feels lonelier than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have this personal philosophy that I can't really know how
anyone else is feeling. I can't because it's not my situation,''
declared Kaplan. ``My friends are warm and compassionate and they
try to put themselves in my shoes but they can't be totally in my
shoes. It's a very unique experience to be faced with your own
mortality like this, you know?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It started with a stomach ache.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1983 and baby Liz had spent the morning playing peekaboo
with her father, but by midday she pulled at her stomach in
distress. Her mother drove her to the pediatrician and listened
incredulously as the doctor told her the impossible. Her baby had
cancer. She had a massive tumor called neuroblastoma attached to
her pelvis, its vascular tenticles already routed through her
groin. Her tiny body was laid on the operating table the following
night. She was 15 months old.
</P>
<P>
   Liz Kaplan endured a five-hour operation, six months of
chemotherapy, fevers, infections, transfusions, emergency hospital
visits, more surgery, and perennial tests. By the end she could
neither walk nor talk. But she was alive.
</P>
<P>
   By the time their daughter was 3, the Kaplans had rediscovered
hope. Liz, it seemed, was going to live a normal life. The terror
was over.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fall of 1985 the phone rang; the doctor relayed the
news that Liz had been infected with HIV through a transfusion and
horror began again.
</P>
<P>
   For the Kaplans, both of whom are lawyers, the news was
particularly enraging. By early 1983, scientists had discovered
AIDS was transmitted via blood, although a test for the virus
wasn't formulated until 1985. The Kaplans asked Children's Hospital
to allow them to use blood donations from people known to the
family. But like many hospitals, Children's refused, saying that to
do so would be discriminatory and possibly put pressure on family
members unfit to donate. The hospital vowed to use only blood
platelets from the esteemed Dana-Farber Cancer Institute and only
those obtained from a process that generally drew regular donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bunch of malarkey,'' declared Kaplan's mother, Fern
Frolin, 50. ``The reason they didn't want designated donors was
because it was a pain in the butt. You've got to store it. Get the
right amount. They just didn't want to be bothered.''
</P>
<P>
   Dana-Farber did obtain blood from a regular donor, who gave 14
times in 17 months. However, he was HIV positive. After it was
discovered, the hospital barred the donor from giving more blood
but, citing confidentiality, has refused to identify him or say
what happened to him. As to why Liz Kaplan, who was just then
relearning how to play and at last beginning to talk again, should
have been given his blood on that March day in 1984, is a question
her parents have raised often to the black night sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed this was too much,'' sighed Mitch Kaplan, 48,
Kaplan's father. ``It was too much to deal with. It was hugely
unfair, unfair personally to me, unfair to my family. It was just
unfair. I concluded it was fate. Things happen and whether you are
a good person or a bad one does not act as a shield.''
</P>
<P>
   Plagued by memories of Ryan White, the 13-year-old hemophiliac
who that year had been kicked out of school and ostracized after it
was learned he had AIDS, the Kaplans moved slowly. They told a few
family members, even fewer friends. They also told Janice Golden,
owner of the Golden Days Childrens Center now in Newton, the
nursery school Kaplan had attended for a year. Golden said Kaplan
could come back. But only for one day. To say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not, in fairness to the other families, say she could
stay. If the worst possible scenario happened and someone else
became (HIV) positive, I could not live with myself,'' said Golden.
``And it has haunted me since the day she left. It has been a
really, really hard thing for me. I could not serve her. But at the
time, I felt I had no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kaplans did not talk to Golden for years. They also decided
to tell as few people as possible, including their daughter.
Despite the opposition of several professional counselors, they
decided not to tell her until after her bat mitzvah. That way, they
reasoned, she could enjoy a period of childhood innocence. The day
would come soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6206 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAINTED-BLOOD-I-2ND &LR;  &UR;      07-28 1526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAINTED-BLOOD-I-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... the recommendation.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When an HIV test became available in March 1985, and Dana-Farber
discovered that the donor was positive, he was barred from further
donations. As the hospital began to search its records to see who
had received his blood, the word moved like a wave along the
corridor of the pediatric oncology unit on the eighth floor of the
old Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Blackledge, the slender young man with a knack for
motors and a love of slam dancing, the same young man who seemed to
have beaten the leukemia that brought him into the hospital in the
first place, had been infected with HIV. So had Melanie
Fitzpatrick, the boisterous 3-year-old who had battled cancer for
nearly a year and was still confined to a sealed room undergoing
bone marrow transplant. And Liz Kaplan, the 3-year-old who had
survived a five-hour operation to remove her tumor and six months
of chemotherapy. And so had two other children on the ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like a bomb had dropped on me,'' said Debbie
Fitzpatrick of Quincy, Melanie's mother. ``We were fighting every
day to survive, and then this.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick marched off the unit and headed to the office of Dr.
Kenneth Anderson, medical director of the blood component
laboratory. ``I was so upset, I stormed into his office. I was
beside myself,'' recalled Fitzpatrick. ``I said, `How can you let
people like that come in here and give blood? How did this happen?'
He told me the donor himself probably didn't know. You could see
that he was devastated. He had babies himself.''
</P>
<P>
   James Blackledge, Matthew's father, was on a break from his
bread delivery route in Fall River when his son told him the news
on the phone. ``I went through the ground 10 feet,'' he said. ``It
was horrifying. You realize you cannot save your kid. That's what
it comes down to.''
</P>
<P>
   For the eighth-floor staff, the realization that they probably
could not save their patients was also horrifying. But for some it
was made profoundly more complicated by the realization that it was
their employer, in a bizarre way the staff themselves, who had
infected the five children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not even know what words to say that you could write
which would describe what it felt like,'' declared Deborah Hirsch,
a former social worker at Dana-Farber and now director of social
work services at Wentworth Douglass Hospital, in Dover, N.H.
``Terrible is an understatement. It was horrifying, devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   Added one staff member, who declined to be identified: ``There
was a feeling of horror. It was a time of real fear of AIDS and
contamination, and no one knew quite what to do or say.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. James M. Croop, a pediatric hematologist-oncologist
formerly at Dana-Farber and now at the James Whitcomb Riley
Hospital for Children in Indianapolis, says that staff members were
upset but did not blame the hospital. ``We all knew that at the
time there was no sure way to eliminate HIV from the blood supply.
It was just very precarious going. Everyone knew there were risks,
but we were sort of stuck because we had to give transfusions.''
</P>
<P>
   Years later, a group of social workers and psychologists
involved in the incident published a paper in the Journal of
Psychosocial Oncology describing the impact of the tragedy in hopes
that others could learn from it. The 1990 article says that four of
the five children infected with HIV died, three from AIDS, one from
complications including pneumonia. Kaplan, the fifth child, remains
healthy: The level of virus in her system is barely detectable, and
her cancer is in remission.
</P>
<P>
   The experience, they wrote, ``humbled us. We have been humbled
by the effects of causing, albeit unknowingly, a fatal disease in
the process of trying to cure children of cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   A few found themselves questioning their loyalties. Hirsch was
working with another family whose child needed a transfusion and
was desperate to use a known donor. ``I was an employee of the
hospital, but I was also a social worker whose job was to advocate
for my client,'' Hirsch said. ``Should I tell them to go to another
hospital, or the media, or to take legal action? Who should I align
myself with?''
</P>
<P>
   As red-alert notices warning of the need to take special
precautions went up on the eighth floor, medical workers also
grappled with their own fear of the virus. Some nurses, according
to the Journal paper, ``suffered from insomnia, nightmares, and
loss of appetite and described friends' and roommates' fears of
contagion.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also the question of how much information to release
and to whom. Information was guarded carefully, not just to ensure
the confidentiality of the five infected children, but also to
prevent panic among other patients. Clearly, some were not told the
scope of the incident. Although Fitzpatrick's and Blackledge's
parents shared their news with one another, they all say they were
never told that other patients had been infected by the same donor,
not to mention 24 others, and news of Kaplan's January speech at
Newton North came as a stunning surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Kaplan, a lawyer who works for Choate Hall &AMP; Stewart, the
same law firm that represents Dana-Farber, and his wife, Fern
Frolin, also a lawyer, were given different information. Hospital
staff, said Frolin, told them the victims totaled 12 children and
13 adults. When Frolin periodically asked how the others were
doing, she said doctors told her, ``Not good. Not as good as Liz.
Liz is very lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Dana-Farber, said several sources, was anxious about releasing
any information. ``The hospital wanted to have a meeting with the
parents, but it was unclear how to advertise it,'' explained
Hirsch. ``We didn't want people to get hysterical. We certainly
didn't want media coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   And they didn't get much. In the end, the only coverage was two
stories in the Globe, a brief one describing the Annals paper in
1986 and another following Kaplan's speech. Although the hospital
was not identified in the first story, Brenda Darling suspected
instantly that it was Dana-Farber. Six months earlier, Darling's
only son had died of AIDS, unable to walk or care for himself, his
brain ravaged by the virus. His cancer was in remission. Darling
picked up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called my lawyer,'' Darling, 59, a retired Internal Revenue
Service adjuster living in Fall River, said as tears filled her
eyes. ``The hospital never told us anything, just that we were the
only one. But when I saw that article, I said, `That's our guy.
That's our donor.' I wanted to know what had happened.''
</P>
<P>
   But to this day, only Dana-Farber knows for sure. Even some
physicians who treated the patients were not told any details about
the donor. Asked whether the hospital should have been able to rule
the donor out, Dr. Jerome Groopman, an AIDS researcher at Harvard
Medical School who treated three of the infected children, said he
did not know ``enough about the screening to comment. ... I just
thought it was a tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Learning now of the incident, several public health officials
said that while the event was uniquely tragic, Dana-Farber appeared
to have acted appropriately, presuming they told all the patients
they had received infected blood. None would comment on details of
the incident because they were not familiar with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hospital was using state-of-the-art techniques and
processes at the time,'' said Nancy Ridley, assistant commissioner
of health quality management for the Massachusetts Department of
Public Health. ``They couldn't have known the donor was positive
because there was no test.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick did not know about the others who were infected
until a Globe reporter contacted her for this story. Her daughter,
Melanie, died of pneumonia and other complications in January 1986,
14 months after she received a transfusion from the infected donor.
Although medical staff were uncertain whether her pneumonia stemmed
from the transplant or the virus, according to the Journal paper,
her mother is sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The HIV didn't have anything to do with her death. Nothing
whatsoever. There is no shame of dying of HIV here,'' declared
Fitzpatrick, a nurse at Spaulding Rehabilitation Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick, who has donated blood to Dana-Farber ever since her
daughter got sick, thinks of her little girl every day. But she
does not think badly of the hospital that cared for her. ``I really
don't blame anyone there for this, not anyone,'' she said. ``They
told me they screened the best they could. They don't owe me a
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Liz Kaplan is fresh back from summer camp in Maine. She thinks
sometimes during these long, hot days about the children who died
from the same blood that was pumped into her veins. She does not
know any of their names. She has never met their families. Nor does
she want to, at least not now. But she thinks about them. And
probably will for the rest of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very sad that they all died,'' said Kaplan. ``It's very
strange to feel I am connected to all these dead babies, but I am.
So maybe part of them is in me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
