<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6218 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAINTED-BLOOD-I-2TAKE     07-28 1474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAINTED-BLOOD-I-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIV BLOOD DISASTER HAUNTS FAMILIES, HOSPITAL WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SALLY JACOBS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Liz Kaplan should not be alive.
</P>
<P>
   As an infant she developed a rare cancerous tumor that swelled
within her pelvis like a summer melon. She survived surgery,
chemotherapy, and more surgery only to discover in 1985 that she
had been transfused with HIV-infected blood. Twenty-five patients
received the same blood, and today all but two of them are dead.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan, a very much alive 15-year-old with a leather thong
around her neck and quizzical green glasses perched on her nose, is
one of the survivors. In January, she stood before a packed
auditorium at Newton North High School and revealed that she was
HIV positive. In doing so she lifted the veil not only on a
profound personal secret, but on a medical disaster that has
remained largely out of sight of both the public and at least some
of the families of the dead. It is a tale not only of a sweeping
loss of life, but one that offers a rare glimpse back to the onset
of one of the most deadly plagues in modern medical history.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators at Boston's Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, where
the blood originated, point out that the tragedy occurred in the
early 1980s, before there was a test for the blood-borne human
immunodeficiency virus. Although they say they informed each of the
patients' families that they had received HIV-infected blood, some
families say that they were told little and that their questions
remain unanswered to this day. Even some hospital workers, who
found their faith in their profession shaken at the time of the
incident, remain haunted by shadows of the 23 dead patients, four
of whom were children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor took us aside and said our son had been infected
with the AIDS virus through a transfusion,'' recalled Brenda
Darling of Fall River, whose 20-year-old son died of AIDS in 1986,
two years after he received a transfusion. ``I was devastated. I
said, `Is he the only one?' The doctor said, `Yes. He is the only
one.'''
</P>
<P>
   He was far from it. Nor was Dana-Farber the only institution
grappling with the virus's resolute march forward. By the time a
test for the virus became available, in March 1985, an estimated
12,000 people nationwide were infected through blood transfusions,
as were an additional 8,000 hemophiliacs, according to the National
Academy of Sciences. Because many did not develop symptoms until
years after infection, the scope of the virus's spread in its early
years was not grasped until much later. Today, health officials say
the blood supply is virtually free of HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from the swath of death left in the virus's wake,
however, the Dana-Farber tragedy stands alone. In no other case did
a single donor infect so many people with so deadly an outcome, at
least in no case that was reported in scientific literature or that
is recalled by public health officials or those at Dana-Farber.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tragedy from any perspective. There were 25 patients in
all, ranging in age from 17 months to 75 years old. Each of them
had cancer. Each of them had undergone treatment requiring blood
transfusions. And each of them was given new blood from a donor who
gave 14 times in the 17 months before a test for HIV became
available. Although the male donor had tested positive for a virus
then associated with homosexuality, doctors did not pursue the
issue to determine if he had been exposed to HIV.
</P>
<P>
   He had.
</P>
<P>
   The virus moved fast. By the time doctors discovered that the
blood was tainted, 15 of the patients were already dead, all but
two of them felled by their original cancers, according to one of
the medical papers, a clinical study published in 1986 in the
Annals of Internal Medicine. Frozen bodily fluids of two of the
dead patients tested HIV positive, but fluids from the other dead
patients were not available for testing.
</P>
<P>
   All but one of the 10 living patients tested positive for HIV.
So, too, did the wife of one of the patients. Of the 10 patients
alive at the time the study began, five died of cancer and three
died of complications stemming from HIV, according to Dana-Farber
officials. Citing confidentiality, the hospital refused to provide
information about the donor or about the two patients who remain
alive. Nor would the hospital allow staff members to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David G. Nathan, Dana-Farber president, said in a letter to
the Globe that the hospital has experienced no other case of HIV
infection through its blood products and currently uses three tests
to ensure that its blood is HIV-free. The hospital, he added, ``has
always adhered to the most rigorous clinical guidelines available
for blood products. ... As an institution dedicated to caring and
healing, we were deeply saddened by this tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit filed in 1988 on behalf of Darling's son, Matthew
Blackledge, generated a $500,000 settlement from Dana-Farber but no
information about the other patients. Suspecting that other
patients had been infected, Darling's lawyers requested names, but
the hospital refused to release them and the court agreed. The
hospital also paid a settlement to at least one other patient who
sued, and both sides agreed to keep the matter confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Because Dana-Farber was not required to report the incident to
any state or local government body, it went largely unnoticed until
Kap-lan addressed her classmates earlier this year. The hospital
says that all of the patients were notified that they had received
infected blood within days of the hospital's discovery that the
donor was HIV positive. But Andrew C. Meyer, a Boston lawyer who
represented Darling, questions not only how much they were told but
whether some patients were told they had received tainted blood at
all.
</P>
<P>
   To tell the families of the already dead ``would have been to
open the door wide to lawsuits, and that was something the hospital
did not want,'' declared Meyer. ``They did not want information
about this to get out because they wanted to keep beds filled. They
wanted to instill public confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Kaplan was feeling immensely confident in the hospital,
bullish really, back in the summer of 1985. His then-3-year-old
daughter, Liz, had come through a chilling bout with cancer. Her
tumor was gone. Chemotherapy appeared to have eliminated her
illness. At last, she was beginning to walk and talk again.
</P>
<P>
   And then one evening Kaplan was in the kitchen of his Newton
home when the phone rang. It was Liz's doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't get five words out, and I knew where he was going,''
recalled Kaplan, a lawyer. ``I read the newspapers, and everybody
knew that the blood supply was tainted. The possibility of HIV
infection had always been in the back of our minds. Now, it had
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kaplans had tried to take precautions, asking Children's
Hospital to allow them to use known donors rather than the blood of
strangers. Like many hospitals at the time, Children's refused but
assured the Kaplans that it would use blood only from the
world-renowned Dana-Farber, blood taken through a process that
generally drew long-term donors. The blood, they assured, would be
safe.
</P>
<P>
   They were hollow promises at best. By early 1983, it seemed
highly likely that HIV was blood-borne, but it would take two more
agonizing years before there was a way to test blood for the virus.
In the meantime, blood banks asked donors a set of questions
designed to ferret out those at high risk. The process was
problematic in part because no one wanted to ask donors if they
were homosexual, but mostly it was a problem of not knowing what to
ask.
</P>
<P>
   Unwilling to turn away donors unnecessarily, many blood banks
simply asked those in apparent high-risk groups, such as IV drug
users and Haitian immigrants, to screen themselves out, but did not
summarily reject them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had no idea what donors were risky,'' said Peter Page,
former medical director of the Red Cross regional blood service in
Boston and now based in Arlington, Va. ``It was a moving target, an
evolving system. We never thought HIV was as prevalent as it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer, Darling's lawyer, argued that Dana-Farber should have
identified the donor as high risk and rejected him, or at least
screened him more thoroughly, because he tested positive for
cytomegalovirus, which was prevalent among gay men. He also argued
that the hospital failed to test the donor for Hepatitis B, as the
US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention suggested, although
most blood collection agencies also ignored the recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
