<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6220 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAINTED-BLOOD-II-2ND &LR;      07-28 1538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAINTED-BLOOD-II-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 NEWTON, Mass.: ... soon enough.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And come it did on that December evening two years ago. Liz's
two sisters were at sleepovers. A team of professionals, including
a psychiatrist and social worker, were on alert should Liz need
them. She walked into her brick home in Newton and her parents told
her to sit down. Mitch Kaplan will not talk about what happened
next. Neither will Frolin. ``It was the most difficult day of my
life,'' said Frolin, ``except for the day of finding out she had
cancer.'' Liz listened to her parents and when they were done she
asked what had happened to the other children. When she was told
they all had died, she got up and ran for the stairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went upstairs and cried,'' she said quietly. ``I refused to
eat dinner, which is very unusual for me. I was afraid. I was in
the eighth grade, so I was not uneducated. I knew this was not a
death sentence. But it seemed I would be more likely to die sooner
than most of my classmates and that seemed very unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   She was also angry. ``I was really, really angry with my
parents. Why hadn't they told me sooner?'' Kaplan said. ``I
deserved to know. On the other hand, I was kind of like, do I
really want to hear about this at all? I don't want to deal with
it. I don't want to die. That was kind of a big issue, really not
wanting to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Did she think she would die? ``Yes,'' she says, staring at the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Part of her anger had to do with the sense that she'd been
deceived. All those blood tests she'd had every six months, which
she had been told were for cancer, had often been to measure the
HIV in her blood. All those times when one of her classmates had
gotten chicken pox and she'd been given a temporary vaccine, she'd
been told it was related to her cancer, but it had really been to
bolster her immune system. All those people who'd known, when she
had not. She felt, she said, ``completely lied to.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was she sure her parents had told her everything. Although
they'd said she was healthy, her T-cell count dropped dramatically
just months after she learned she was HIV positive. First, she had
an allergic reaction to an antibiotic that landed her in the
hospital. Second, her doctors put her on a three-drug ``cocktail''
regimen including a protease inhibitor, AZT, and a similar
medication to shore up her immune system that she continues to
take. Finally, she underwent a preventive inhalant treatment to
ward off an HIV-related pneumonia that required her to be in a
sealed cubicle.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, she was introduced to Groopman, the AIDS
specialist who had supervised her case since she was an infant. He
explained her condition to both school and camp officials. But by
that time her feet were dug deep in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   She did not want see a doctor; and she particularly did not want
to see Groopman. ``It weirded me out that this guy had been so
behind the scenes. It was just weird,'' said Kaplan. ``My first
impression was, here's a guy who's pretty high on himself. I felt
like he was trying to be my rabbi, like he was playing God. I made
it clear that I did not like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, this guy said he wasn't going to give me any bullshit
and an hour later he said I had a choice about medicine and all
that. Well, the way I see it, it's like you're running towards a
cliff and the choice is you can keep running and fall off or you
can stop. Like, where is the choice?''
</P>
<P>
   Although doctors were concerned that the drop in Kaplan's T
cells meant the virus was becoming active, her count returned to
normal and has remained steady. Kaplan, meanwhile, packed her pills
into her knapsack and headed back to school. While her life had
changed radically, she found her condition didn't interfere with
her regular activities, like acting, skating, and editing the arts
page of her school paper.
</P>
<P>
   Soon she began to want to tell some people about her disease,
but knowing who was not always clear. She called Melissa Simon, one
of her closest friends, that first night. And it was Simon with
whom she often consulted before telling others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acceptance was really important to her,'' said Simon, 16, now
living in Mill Valley, Calif. ``She would be worried, wondering how
it would affect a relationship. Sometimes it would and sometimes it
wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Before she addressed her school, she had told nearly two dozen
friends, ``mostly when I got to the point when I was so close to
them I felt like I was lying almost if I didn't tell them. It was,
like, this is the biggest secret I have and I would like to trust
you with it.'' Virtually all of them have reacted positively,
although there have been a couple of ``weird reactions,'' like the
friend who called her after an afternoon they spent together
because she had discovered a scratch on her skin beneath her watch.
She wanted to know if Kaplan, too, had a scratch, and whether she
should have an AIDS test. And then there was the girl who called
her after a party because she was afraid she had drunken from
Kaplan's glass. She said she didn't want to get Kaplan's cold.
</P>
<P>
   Although her parents have left virtually all decisions about who
to tell up to Kaplan, her father advised her not to tell her
friends at her summer camp in Maine. It was, after all, a small
world in which word could travel fast. . Kaplan agreed at first and
attributed her pill regimen to stomach problems, pointing to the
long, jagged surgical scar running down her stomach. But by the end
of the month she told two more friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd seen her huge collection of medicine, so it was
surprising, but not too much,'' recalled Paul Heckler, 15, of Cross
River, N.Y. ``It certainly didn't change my thoughts about her. I'd
rather think about who she is now than who she'll be in 10 years or
what will happen to her.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there was a boyfriend to tell. ``I'd learned from
countless, stupid health classes that HIV isn't communicable like
the common cold,'' said the boyfriend, who didn't want to be
identified for reasons unrelated to her condition. ``She'd asked
her doctor if it was OK to kiss, and that was good enough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship ended this year for reasons both say had
nothing to do with Kaplan's health. But Kaplan thinks a lot about
future relationships. Unless there is a vaccine or cure for AIDS,
she does not expect sex or children to be in her future. Although
only about 25 percent of women with the virus pass it on to their
babies (and that rate drops to about 8 percent with the use of
anti-viral drugs), Kaplan's vision of married life in a Maine
cottage includes two adopted children.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't guarantee that a kid will be born without HIV,
why not give a home to one that is already born,'' she said. ``Like
right now, I'm pretty cool about that.''
</P>
<P>
   What she is somewhat less cool about is not knowing anyone who
has the virus. It was that, in part, that led her to tell her
classmates about her condition. It also was ``at a pretty confident
time in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   She decided last fall she would share her secret with her school
and community through the sophomore English writing contest. The
assignment was to write about someone who embodied the spirit of
Martin Luther King. The winners would read their essays to the
school assembly marking the holiday. Kaplan reasoned that, if her
essay won, she would know her essay was an eloquent way to make her
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan settled on Mary Fisher, the AIDS activist who spoke at
the 1992 Republican convention. The more she worked on the piece,
the more it seemed like a good idea. Not only might it prompt other
teens to take precautions, but it was ``lending a purpose to
something which is utterly purposeless, my having HIV.''
</P>
<P>
   The adults were not so sure. Her English teacher reminded her
pointedly she would have to read her essay in public if she won.
The principal asked her if she was absolutely sure it was what she
wanted to do. Her father asked the same. As the contest deadline
approached, even Kaplan grew nervous, she said, because ``the
adults were rubbing off on me.'' And then her essay won. By the
time she stepped to the podium in January, her hands were shaking
but she knew her speech by heart. She still does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Mary Fisher, you would probably never expect me to have
the virus. I am not gay or a drug addict,'' she said to a hushed
auditorium. ``It just happened, the way people who are black are
born black. ... You only have to be human to be part of a minority
_ you only have to be human to get AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems like a long time now. The thunderous applause. The
swarming of supporters. The outpouring from the community and
invitations to speak. But in a way, telling her secret has let her
put the whole thing away for a while. She thinks about it at
certain times, like when she goes to the doctor or takes her pills.
But there's a lot of other things to think about, like packing her
trunk for another year of camp. And school. And that guy she's
going to visit next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be perfectly honest, I talk about my social life more than
I do HIV,'' said Kaplan. ``I have a lot of other things to do. I
mean, I'm only 15.''
</P>
