<HEADLINE>
NEW ENGLAND KEEPS TABS ON ITS BEACHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While ocean pollution remains a serious problem among many
coastal communities, and public health standards vary widely in the
region, New England's beaches generally rank among the best in the
nation when it comes to knowing when pollution makes ocean
recreation a genuine health risk, according to the Natural
Resources Defense Council.
</P>
<P>
   The council notes that disease-causing microorganisms in
contaminated waters can cause a wide range of diseases, including
gastroenteritis; dysentery; hepatitis; ear, nose, and throat
problems; and respiratory illness. The consequences of these
swimming-associated illnesses can be greater for children, elderly
people, and those with weakened immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   When beaches are closed, most of the problems are caused by
sewage overflows and stormwater.
</P>
<P>
   The NRDC singled out the beaches at Wellfleet on the Cape as
among the best vacation beaches in the nation in terms of its
regular monitoring for pollution and public notification of the
presence of pathogens that can cause health problems. Others rated
highly are beaches at Half Moon Bay, Calif.; Rehoboth Beach, Del.;
Indiana Dunes National Lakeshore, Ind.; Cape May, N.J.; Cape
Hatteras, N.C.; and Myrtle Beach, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, there were at least 140 days of beach closing
and advisories last year, according to the council's report
``Testing the Waters: Has Your Vacation Beach Cleaned Up Its
Act?,'' an annual survey covering 29 coastal and Great Lakes states
and three US territories.
</P>
<P>
   The report noted that Boston area beaches have benefited from an
aggressive monitoring program by the Metropolitan District
Commission and that in New Hampshire and Rhode Island there were no
beach closings or advisories for the sixth consecutive year,
although Rhode Island requires that pollution levels be detected
repeatedly above the standards before closing a beach or notifying
the public. In Maine, there were at least 20 closings or
advisories, as well as three permanent closings. Connecticut led
the pack with 263 days of closings or advisories, although almost
50 were caused by a New York City sewer line break.
</P>
<P>
   Because beaches are a significant vacation and recreation
resource for millions of residents, ``Massachusetts communities
seem to clearly understand the important link between a clean
environment and a healthy economy,'' said Peter Lehner, an NRDC
clean-water specialist. Unfortunately, the report noted that
Barnstable County on Cape Cod does not always close beaches when
the standards are violated. The report said that the beaches are
closed only after a second sample of water is taken.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Testing the Waters'' report is available through NRDC's
Web site at www.nrdc.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Great rate
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among places to get the most for your dollar is Australia. Last
January, one US dollar equaled $1.25 Australian, but now the dollar
buys about $1.62 Australian. The best way to get the most on a
package in Australia is to buy it in Australian dollars and take
advantage of the low exchange rates offered by credit card
companies. P&AMP;O Australian Resorts, which features nature-based
resort travel, sells its packages in Australian dollars. For
information on their packages, call 800-225-9849.
</P>
