<HEADER>
A6231 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-PRINCESS-2TAKE     07-28 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PRINCESS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW GRAND PRINCESS: ONE BIG BOAT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL _ From Istanbul to Barcelona, we would be visiting some
of the world's most fascinating cities. But what fascinated me
right now was this city at sea.
</P>
<P>
   There it was, the world's largest and most expensive cruise ship
_ the new Grand Princess, from Princess Cruise Lines. And it didn't
take long after coming aboard to learn that ``Grand'' is no
exaggeration. This 109,000-ton, $450 million ship-on-steroids is
201 feet high, 159 feet wide, and 951 feet long. That, the cruise
line notes, makes it four times longer than Grand Central Station,
28 feet taller than Niagara Falls, 53 feet wider than the Panama
Canal, and 49 feet higher than the Statue of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, although the Grand Princess carries 2,600 passengers
and 1,100 crew members, its combination of space and design left me
never feeling crowded.
</P>
<P>
   There was no scrambling for a lounge on deck. After all, there
are three acres of open deck space.
</P>
<P>
   There was no looking in vain for a seat in the theater. After
all, there are three main show lounges, as well as 12 other lounges
for entertainment, dancing, and refreshments.
</P>
<P>
   There never was a feeling that we were dining with a mob. After
all, there are three main dining rooms and three smaller
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   There were no long lines for embarking or disembarking. After
all, there are two gangways.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, in fact, I found myself wondering where all the
people had gone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Size and style &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So intriguing was the Grand Princess that my wife, Linda, and I
delayed our exploration of Istanbul _ our first port on a 12-day
Mediterranean cruise _ to explore the 18-deck ship, which,
incidentally, had become the tallest ``building'' in the city. And
there was a lot to see. As one cruise staffer quipped, ``It's just
five minutes from one side of the ship to the other ... by cab.''
</P>
<P>
   It became apparent that a big ship can be tasteful. The decor of
the Grand Princess is, if anything, understated, with sea greens,
ocean blues, russets, tans, and a lot of wood predominating. The
walls have plenty of art attached, some of it reflecting the dream
ports we would be visiting: Istanbul and Kusadasi/Ephesus, Turkey;
Athens; Venice, Naples/Capri, and Livorno/Florence/Pisa, Italy;
Monte Carlo, Monaco; and Barcelona, Spain. (In fall, winter, and
spring, the ship switches to a seven-day Caribbean itinerary, and
will return to the Mediterranean in late spring.)
</P>
<P>
   Our stateroom was on Dolphin Deck, which was easy for me to
remember because it sounds like Donald Duck. Even before entering,
we knew that there would be room for everything because cabins on
modern cruise ships are marvels of efficiency, filled with nooks,
crannies, and amenities.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Princess has 1,300 cabins. Of these, 1,092 are the
so-called standard staterooms featuring twin beds that can make up
into a queen-size bed; color TV with good movies, CNN, the BBC, and
a variety of other channels; a music system; a refrigerator; a
big-enough closet; turndown service (with chocolates left on the
pillows); terrycloth robes; hairdryers; a private safe; a
multifunction telephone; and a bath with shower. I wish I could
have brought that shower home because it had a separate,
set-and-forget control for water temperature. And my wife and I
both wish we could have brought our cabin steward, Narciso, home
because he quietly kept the room ultra-neat.
</P>
<P>
   On 710 outside cabins, there are private balconies _ the most of
any ship afloat _ for relaxing, sunning, sightseeing, and watching
sunsets. That's something anyone should enjoy, but for those with
the inclination (and the budget), there are also 180 minisuites, 24
suites, two grand suites, and two family suites that add space,
televisions, sofa beds, and other amenities, including the service
of a butler, complete with black tie, tails, and (often) a British
accent.
</P>
<P>
   This is a ship of ``firsts'' and ``largests,'' some of which we
would check out immediately and others that would wait for the two
days during the voyage that we would be completely at sea, so to
speak. Among the firsts and biggests:
</P>
<P>
   _The largest casino afloat, with 13,500 square feet of space in
which to lose money. Instead of blinding you with neon, the
Neptune's Lair casino features walls with holographic images of sea
creatures, and during my first visit I would have sworn a sea horse
was swimming out to greet me.
</P>
<P>
   _The first wedding and renewal-of-vows chapel at sea, called
Hearts and Minds. (This, after all, is the fleet that calls itself
the Love Boat.) On the Grand Princess's maiden voyage, Captain
Michael Moulin performed the first wedding at sea in modern times.
And that led marine historian John Maxtone-Graham, who delivered
engrossing lectures aboard, to nickname the veteran captain
``Marryin' Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   _The first virtual reality center at sea, with a motion
simulator ride and interactive games. I confess to enjoying the
simulator ride, which is shaped like a giant squid, while the
smattering of youngsters aboard appeared to relish the shoot-em-up
and drive-till-you-drop games. (Whether this room will become
crowded when there are more youngsters aboard remains to be seen.
There is a charge for the games.) The ship also has a digital photo
studio, in which passengers can place themselves into a wide array
of wild photographic scenes, such as skydiving.
</P>
<P>
   _The first ship with a swim-against-the-current lap pool _ one
of five pools aboard. You can even adjust the strength of the
current.
</P>
<P>
   _The launch of a telemedicine program, SeaMed, which can link
the Grand Princess medical staff with the emergency department at
Cedars Sinai Medical Center in Los Angeles. I was fortunate not to
need medical care during the cruise, but did peek at the facilities
and found them impressive. Only one thing: The magazines in the
waiting room were far too recent for a doctor's office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Dining &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most important features of any cruise are the dining
and the entertainment, and jet-lagged and flight-fatigued though we
might have been, we skipped neither during our first night aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The three main dining rooms are the Da Vinci, the Michelangelo,
and the Botticelli, featuring murals paying homage to the works of
the artists. We were assigned to the Da Vinci, and thus Mona Lisa
smiled upon us from across the room at every meal. There are two
seatings in each of these dining rooms, which are sectioned to give
a feeling of coziness. Well, semi-coziness, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
