<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6232 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-GRAND-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     07-28 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-GRAND-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 ISTANBUL: ... semi-cizoness, perhaps.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Grand Princess has a $10 million kitchen _ two kitchens
actually, both the length of two football fields and employing a
total of 208 workers. Under executive chef Antonio Cereda,
everything is made from scratch, using food from Italy, France,
Holland, the United States, and elsewhere. The result is six-course
meals that include such dishes as filet of dover sole florentine,
boneless chicken kiev, young tom turkey with all the trimmings,
grilled black angus sirloin steak, broiled lobster tail, and royal
pheasant in pan juices. There are always a healthy-choice offering
and a vegetarian menu. And certain popular dishes are available any
night. There also always is a pasta course, and I found Princess
pasta, from fettucini nicotera to ravioli con salsa di funghi
porcini, to be as delicious as any I had ashore in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   But the eating doesn't stop there. There is also the Painted
Desert, the first Southwestern-themed restaurant aboard a cruise
ship (ho-hum, another Grand Princess ``first''), and the Sabatini
Trattoria for casual Italian dining. (Reservations are needed at
these restaurants, and there is a service charge of $3.50 a
person.) In addition, there are breakfast and lunch buffets, a
24-hour cafe called the Horizon Court, a poolside pizzeria, a
patisserie/caviar bar, a hamburger-and-hot-dog grill, and the Ice
Scream sundae bar, where concoctions such as a Chocolate Obsession
and a Shaken Jamaican are made with Haagen-Dazs ice cream (but,
unlike almost all other food on the ship, cost extra). And there is
24-hour room service. With 24-hour dining, there is no need for a
midnight buffet. One certainly isn't needed, but I missed one
staple of such buffets: the displays in which ordinary food items
have been sculpted objets d'art, although examples of this art can
still be found aboard ship.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Entertainment &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are three main show lounges, the two-level Princess
Theater, with its 36-foot proscenium arch stage; the Vista
Showlounge; and the Explorers Lounge, where the waitstaff dresses
in safari costumes, a la Disney World. All feature the kind of
dazzling Broadway, Las Vegas, and cabaret shows that cruise ships
are known for. ``Gotta Sing, Gotta Dance,'' for instance, features
hits from more than two dozen Broadway shows. But a new production,
``Glamour,'' features what is believed to be the largest (there's
that word again) cast of any cruise-ship production _ four singers
and 18 dancers _ and contains some surprising scenes. Audience
reaction appeared mixed at the performance I attended, but it
certainly grabbed everyone's attention.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Princess will always have celebrity entertainers
aboard, too _ two on the Mediterranean cruises and one on the
Caribbean sailings. Celebrities have included, or will include,
Rita Moreno, Red Buttons, Alan King, David Brenner, and Lorna Luft.
In addition, there are comedians, musicians, acrobats, and special
performers like Bob Anderson, who gives outstanding singing
impressions of everyone from Sinatra to Neil Diamond, and the
Macaggi Duo, a husband and wife who balance their bodies in ways I
haven't seen since I surreptitiously leafed through an illustrated
copy of ``The Kama Sutra'' when I was 14. What's more, the shows
are sequenced so that you can see two and sometimes three a night
if you have the stamina.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to go to a formal show, though: Entertainment is
sprinkled throughout the Grand Princess. A Hungarian quintet plays
in the three-level atrium. There are singers and entertainers in
several of the lounges. The Skywalkers Disco &AMP; Observation Lounge,
a unique aluminum structure 150 feet above the water, is a lively
star-spangled club by night and an observation lounge by day. (You
can get to it only via a glass-enclosed traveling ``skywalk.'') The
Snookers Sports Bar has the big games via satellite TV (and, on the
lounge walls, memorabilia such as jerseys autographed by Ted
Williams, Dan Marino, Troy Aikman, and Michael Jordan, as well as
Muhammad Ali's boxing gloves.. The in-cabin TVs show feature films
such as ``Wag the Dog,'' ``Anastasia,'' and ``Out to Sea,'' which I
thought was damned big of Princess to run, considering that it was
filmed on a Holland America ship.
</P>
<P>
   There, too, are cruise-ship staples such as trivia games, the
Newlywed and Not So Newlywed Game, ``horse racing,'' and that
perennial favorite, bingo. And there occasionally is entertainment
linked to the ports being visited, such as a folkloric show in
Barcelona and a classical concert in Venice, complete with jugglers
and clowns all doing tricks for us. There is simulated golf, where
you play at the world's greatest courses, and a nine-hole putting
green. Also aboard: table tennis, volleyball, basketball, and a
giant chess board with huge chess pieces, and, yes, shuffleboard.
But, as ship historian Maxtone-Graham noted, there are also
unadvertised ``activities'' like reading in a deck chair until you
fall into a refreshing sleep.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Other features
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Princess also has a gym and health spa, beauty salon,
teenage center, child-care centers that the youngsters (and their
parents) really seemed to enjoy, a library, a fine arts gallery
(there is $3 million worth of art aboard), a writing room, a card
room, and four duty-free shops.
</P>
<P>
   So how hard was it to get around on a ship this size? Not very,
since most public areas fan out logically from the atrium and there
is a plethora of elevators and signs telling where everything is.
</P>
<P>
   As a directionally-impaired person who takes stairs for exercise
to counterbalance the many dining opportunities aboard, I found it
a bit confusing that the stairway amidships does not reach all
decks. But I finally figured things out and usually remembered to
climb the stairs fore and aft. Meanwhile, my only wait during the
voyage was at the two purser's desks, where some passengers seem to
turn buying stamps or cashing travelers' checks into an operation
more complex than a corporate merger.
</P>
<P>
   Because the ship was completed slightly behind schedule, the
first planned cruise was canceled and the Grand Princess went into
service after only a brief no-passenger sail. As a result, in the
first days of sailing there were occasional glitches and gremlins _
a hyperactive air conditioner here, a drippy faucet there. But, as
one mother tells her 5-year-old, ``Spit happens,'' and virtuallyall
those problems should be gone by now.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, it was smooth sailing, literally as well as
figuratively, because much of the time I would forget the ship was
in motion. You might say it was grand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
