<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, July 29:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments in Kenneth Starr's
investigation of the president: Monica Lewinsky has reached an
immunity deal.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TACTICS (Washington) _ Kenneth Starr is finally
hurrying, but Clinton has a new, specific reason for delay _
wanting Lewinsky to testify first so he had a chance of knowing
what she says. By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-SHOOTING (Washington) _ President Clinton and
congressional leaders honor the two slain policemen in the Capitol
Rotunda. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-SCENE (Washington) _ The thousands of citizens who lined
up to pay tribute to the policemen. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-NURSING (Washington) _ Federal investigators, at a
congressional hearing, document abuse and neglect of nursing home
patients, attribute deaths to lax enforcement by Federal and state
authorities. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   CUOMO-RACE (Washington) _ In an address to the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference, Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo
warns that the largely white and suburban Congress is fast losing
interest in programs for the inner cities. He says racism is at the
bottom of this neglect and asks the SCLC to start demonstrating for
money. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SWEEPSTAKES-ELDERLY-II (Undated) _ Second of two articles: As
the mailboxes of the elderly overflow with sweepstakes offers from
big-name American magazine publishers, a new class of con artist is
using the same promise of riches to bilk the elderly out of
hundreds of millions of dollars each year. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-ELECT (Phnom Penh) _ Hun Sen's ruling party claims a
landslide victory in parliamentary elections; the opposition
accuses him of widespread fraud. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   BURMA-DISSENT (Manila, Philippines) _ The U.S. joins with six
other nations in demanding that the army generals who run Burma end
their five-day standoff with that nation's Nobel Prize-winning
dissident leader, whose car has been surrounded by armed security
forces on a rural highway since last Friday. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-TIMOR (Dili, Indonesia) _ Indonesia begins withdrawing
combat troops from East Timor, but critics and residents remain
skeptical of the overall presence of more than 11,000 security
personnel who continue to patrol the territory.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POISONING (Tokyo) _ Police in Wakayama continue their
investigation into the mystery surrounding a mass food poisoning
during a local festival last Saturday. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-KOSOVO (dateline to kum) _ Developments in the conflict
between Serbian forces and ethnic Albanian rebels in Kosovo.
