<P>
   CAPITOL-SECURITY (Washington) _ Sen. John Warner, R-Va., who for
months was a lonely voice in calling for more state-of-the-art
security on Capitol Hill, is getting new support from colleagues
since two security guards were gunned down last week. Warner,
chairman of the Senate Rules panel, offers a beefed-up security
plan that would involve half public and half private funding. By
JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-VIOLENCE (Washington) _ Despite the uproar over school
shootings in Arkansas, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Mississippi and
Kentucky, gun-related deaths in schools have not risen dramatically
in the past six years, a criminal justice think tank reports. Its
message: School is really safer for kids than their home is. By DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-GOVERNERS (Washington) _ Leaders of the National
Governors' Association assess the nation's welfare system nearly
two years after President Clinton approved legislation that
overhauled it by forcing most welfare recipients to go to work,
cutting benefits and turning control of the program over to the
states. By NICOLE TSONG.
