<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSITY-RESEARCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITIES CRITICIZE FEDERAL CUTS IN RESEARCH SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARVY LIPMAN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Federal research grants to public colleges and
universities in New York, which make up more than half of the
schools' research money, last year fell to the lowest level since
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Private universities statewide also saw their federal funding
drop, reaching its second-lowest level of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening in New York is part of a national trend. In
1996 and 1997, the federal government doled out about 10 percent
less in research grants _ adjusted for inflation _ than it did at
its high point in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of those cuts reverberate far beyond the walls of
university labs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should any of us care about that?'' said Jack Wilson,
acting provost at Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute in Rensselaer,
N.Y. ``Because in the last 15, maybe 20 years, we've seen the
conversion of the U.S. economy away from heavier manufacturing
toward the information industries ... What comes out of research
labs is the next industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Being able to attract grants _ or more specifically, the faculty
who can win grants _ also affects students. For one thing, much of
the federal money is used to pay graduate assistants to work on
research projects. But researchers and university administrators
also argue that there are benefits for undergraduates, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are getting grants by definition have to be on the
cutting edge of their fields,'' said Stewart Tolnay, director of
the Center for Social and Demographic Analysis at the State
University of New York University at Albany. ``If your faculty are
successfully writing grants, that means they're well-informed and
up-to-date in their fields, and having well-informed professors
benefits undergraduates.''
</P>
<P>
   The cuts are the result of Congress' efforts to balance the
budget. With the exception of the National Institutes of Health,
virtually every federal agency that funds research has been forced
to reduce its support for such work over the past few years. The
National Science Foundation, the Defense Department and the
Department of Energy have all reduced by about 10 percent the
amount of research money they've put into universities in New York
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Balancing the budget is a virtue and makes good sense,'' said
Jerry Roschwalb, director of governmental relations for the
Washington-based National Association of State Universities and
Land Grant Colleges. ``But we are a cheap date. We're only about
$16 billion from the whole federal government, which is not a lot
of money when you're talking about a $1.7 trillion federal
budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Roschwalb argues that research grants are among the best
investments the federal government makes _ returning about $20 in
economic growth for every $1 spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could offer you the return on a business investment that
we can offer Congress as a return on research, you would steal the
money to invest. And nobody argues with us about that,'' he added.
``We had a study done on high-tech patents this year, and 80
percent of them referred to university basic research. If it wasn't
for university research, this stuff wouldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But basic research _ the kind of work that may solve a
fundamental scientific puzzle without leading directly to some new
device _ is what's suffering the most because of federal cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Why does that matter? ``Because that's where the Nobel prizes
come from,'' Roschwalb said. ``You've got two or three young guys
in a lab who want to do something a little bit different, who want
to gamble on something a little off the main track, a little more
innovative. That's what's lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Another result is that universities are in fierce competition
with one another for faculty who can bring in the grants.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to recruit faculty of the highest quality,'' said
Daniel Wulff, interim vice president for research at the State
University of New York at Albany. That can mean the university has
to come up with other money to spruce up its labs and equipment, so
top-notch researchers will want to join the faculty.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when many states are trying to hold down costs, that
can make things tough for state universities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
