<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6275 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEBALL-FAME-2TAKES-     07-28 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-FAME-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL GREAT FINALLY GETS THE HONOR HE DESERVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _20Immortality is running late only by human
standards _ slowed, no doubt, by rubber-neck traffic. Immortality
doesn't answer to clocks or calendars. Immortality tends to matters
on its own terms, in its own good timelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Immortality finally has gotten around to settling up with
Gorgeous George Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball Hall of Fame on Sunday provided a cozy and
comfortable place for Davis, a native of Cohoes, N.Y., who last
appeared in a major-league game in 1909. Davis didn't make it easy
for immortality to find him. He has spent nearly six decades in an
unmarked grave in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   That's right: One of the best all-around players of the turn of
the century gets a plaque in his honor in baseball's shrine before
he gets a headstone on his grave. If the juxtaposition seems out of
kilter, then you're starting to get a flavor of the paradoxical
life Davis either created for himself or had thrust upon him.
</P>
<P>
   Davis performed acts of heroism that had nothing to do with his
ability to catch or throw or hit a baseball, yet he spent his final
years in a mental hospital enveloped in a syphilis haze.
Contemporaries lauded Davis for his gentlemanly behavior on the
field, yet his attempt to break a contract nearly caused a war
between the American and National leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Davis spent the bulk of his 20 years in the major leagues in New
York and Chicago, playing a key role on two championship teams, yet
baseball quickly carried on as if he never existed.
</P>
<P>
   Even a seemingly cut-and-dry matter like marriage is a mystery
where Davis is involved. Or not involved. Some researchers say
Davis remained a bachelor until 1918, when he was nearly 50. Some
point to testimony from a 1909 court case that indicates Davis was
married during his playing days.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, nobody has found evidence that Davis left behind
any children. No relatives have come forward on Davis' behalf for
the induction ceremonies _ a strict departure from the Hall of Fame
norm.
</P>
<P>
   George Stacey Davis was born at 32 Sargent St. in Cohoes on Aug.
23, 1870. He was the fifth of seven children of immigrant parents.
Abram Davis was from Wales, Sarah Healy Davis from England. They
met as neighbors on Sargent Street and married in the 1850s.
</P>
<P>
   The Cohoes of George Davis' boyhood was full of possibilities.
Sitting just off the Hudson River, Cohoes had location, location,
location in its favor when it came to emerging as a hub of
industry. Abram Davis was a machinist. One of his boys went to work
in the textile mill at age 11, but George Davis had a different
kind of life in mind.
</P>
<P>
   He played outfield for a semi-pro Albany baseball team in 1889.
When the National League got raided by a rival league the next
year, Albany manager Tom York directed the Cleveland Spiders'
attention to a 5-foot-9 young man who could run, throw, catch and
switch-hit.
</P>
<P>
   The winter after the 1892 season, John Montgomery Ward left the
Brooklyn team to manage the New York Giants. One of Ward's first
moves was to trade one of the biggest stars of the 19th century,
catcher Buck Ewing, out of New York for Davis. It was a colossal
show of faith in Davis, because he was 22 and coming off a season
when he batted only .241 while shuttling between the outfield and
third base.
</P>
<P>
   Davis clearly took a liking to his new surroundings, as well as
the new rule that moved back the pitcher's mound from 50 feet to
its current distance of 60-feet-six-inches. He finished fourth in
the 1893 batting race (.355) and second in slugging percentage
(.554). He scored 112 runs and drove in 119. He whacked 27 triples
and finished in a fifth-place tie with 11 home runs. That began a
streak of nine consecutive seasons of hitting above .300.
</P>
<P>
   The streak ended in 1902. Davis slipped to .299.
</P>
<P>
   During that 10-year reign of terror at the plate, in the field
and on the basepaths, Davis batted .329 while averaging 91 runs
batted in, 91 runs scored and 39 stolen bases. He helped the Giants
upset the Baltimore Orioles in the 1894 equivalent of the World
Series. He had emerged as the best all-around shortstop in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Davis took the chance to become a full-time shortstop in 1897 as
his cue to act as if he had been born to play the position. He led
the league in putouts and double plays. He finished 10th in the
league in batting (.353), fifth in slugging (.509) and was one home
run short of tying for the league lead of 11. The modern-day record
for RBI in a season by a switch-hitter is 130, set by Mickey Mantle
during his Triple Crown and Most Valuable Player season of 1956 and
matched by Ken Caminiti during his 1996 MVP season.
</P>
<P>
   In 1897, Davis drove in 136 runs.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was a regular shortstop for 10 seasons. No shortstop
handled more chances per game or had a higher fielder percentage
during that time. Gorgeous George, they called him. The exhaustive
encyclopedia, Total Baseball, ranked Davis as the No. 3 player in
the league 1893, No. 2 in 1897, No.1 in 1899, No. 2 in 1900, No. 4
in 1901, No. 1 in 1905 (at age 35) and No. 5 in 1906.
</P>
<P>
   So what kind of player should Gorgeous George be compared to in
modern-day terms?
</P>
<P>
   Think Robin Yount, a member in good standing of the hallowed
3,000 Hit Club. A switch-hitting Yount, give or take a plus or
minus. Like Davis, Yount broke into the majors as a teen-ager. Like
Davis, Yount was one of the cornerstone offensive players on his
team. Like Davis, Yount, who will be eligible for the next Hall of
Fame vote, spent a chunk of a 20-year career (1974 to 1993) playing
somewhere other than shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Yount loses some ground to Davis on defense. While Yount ranked
fourth among the 1950-1993 shortstops in successful chances per
game (4.99), he was 33rd in fielding percentage (.964). Yount won
one Gold Glove before shoulder injuries forced him to move to the
outfield for his final nine seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, for his part, ranked fourth in fielding percentage (.940)
while handling more chances per game than anybody (5.84) in an age
of bumpy fields and gloves the size of, well, gloves. Winter
gloves, as opposed to modern-day monstrosities that just barely fit
into a Manhattan apartment.
</P>
<P>
   During his 10 seasons as a regular shortstop, Davis led the
league in chances per game four times and finished second three
times. He led the league in double plays four times and finished
second three times. He led in fielding percentage four times and
was second there seems to be a pattern here _ three times.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   In time, another pattern would emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Gorgeous George Davis didn't have even a shred of a clue how to
promote himself. The flashiest thing about him was his nickname.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1898, the Giants manager resigned. The manager was
Ewing, whom the Giants had traded seven years earlier to acquire
Davis. His successor: Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing didn't go quietly, 22-41 record or not, accusing Davis of
undermining the efforts of the manager.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ewing, players resented teammates he'd brought in
from Pittsburgh and Cincinnati. Ewing accused Davis of using a knee
injury as an excuse to miss a road trip and curry favor with the
owner. Why, Ewing knew for a fact that Davis had been out scouting
minor leaguers and ``has secured Taylor, a deaf-mute pitcher from
the Albany Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Luther ``Dummy'' Taylor joined the team that season and would
win 116 major-league games. His teammates eventually learned sign
language to communicate with Taylor, developing the basis for the
coaching signs used today.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy continued to brew during the offseason, when first
baseman Jack Doyle said, ``The New York team will never be
successful as long as George Davis is at the head of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants went 52-85 the next season under Davis. The only
bright light in that dark season was the emergence of a
20-year-old, 20-game winner named Christy Mathewson.
</P>
<P>
   When the Chicago White Sox offered a two-year deal that would
make Davis the highest-paid infielder in baseball, he jumped at the
chance to leave behind his troubles in New York. Davis made $4,000
with the White Sox in 1902 before attempting to break that is
accepted the Giants' offer of $6,300 to fill the hole he had left
at shortstop _ in the process violating a peace treaty the two
leagues recently had forged.
</P>
<P>
   Order was restored only after National League President Harry
Pulliam ordered Davis back to the White Sox after only four games
with the Giants. Davis sat out the rest of that season before
returning to the White Sox, and he was worth the wait. He still was
going strong in 1906, when he was the cleanup hitter on a
pennant-winning team.
</P>
<P>
   At 36, Davis batted .277, stole 27 bases and finished third in
the league with 80 RBI. ``Hitless Wonders'' that the White Sox
were, .230 team batting average and all, they entered the World
Series with the look of sacrificial lambs being led into slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The cross-town rival Cubs had won a record 116 games, and an
ailing Davis would miss the start of the series. He returned to the
lineup with the White Sox trailing, two games to one. He delivered
four hits, including three doubles, in 13 at-bats over the next
three games.
</P>
<P>
   Will Hitless Wonders never cease? The White Sox won all three
games to take the series. Though Davis had missed half the series,
he led both teams with six RBI.
</P>
<P>
   If Davis had gone out then, on top, maybe the Hall of Fame
couldn't have missed him and his .303 career average. Instead,
Davis hung around long enough for his average to fall to .295. More
than two and a half decades passed between the time Davis played
his final game and the Hall of Fame opened.
</P>
<P>
   By then, George Stacey Davis was out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   And probably out of his mind.
</P>
<P>
   His death, on Oct. 17, 1940, didn't even rate a newspaper
obituary. Davis had been admitted to Philadelphia General Hospital
six years earlier suffering generalized paralysis and mental
impairment. Doctors diagnosed him with paresis, a disease of the
brain caused by advanced syphilis. The disease is marked by
progressive dementia, with patients frequently experiencing
dramatic mood swings and delusions of grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Gorgeous George Davis spent the last six years of his
life. Within three weeks of his admission into the hospital, he was
transferred to a psychiatric facility. His wife, Jane Holden Davis,
had him buried at Fernwood Cemetery in a pine box the day after he
died. There were no pallbearers. The cost: $41.
</P>
<P>
   Gorgeous George Davis is in a better place now, a place where
people can remember him as one of the greatest baseball players
ever to wear spikes. He's even getting a headstone on his grave.
The Century Monument Co. in Rensselaer, N.Y., is donating a stone
at no cost, to be unveiled in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
