<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETS-RYAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PRIVATE RYAN' GIVES EXPERTS INSIGHT INTO SHELL SHOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ To steel himself for what he thought would be a
round of questions from veterans in his therapy group, Dr. Nick
Kanas went to see the new World War II film ``Saving Private
Ryan.'' He is glad he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand better, emotionally, what it was like. Watching
it, things came together for me emotionally that I had already come
to accept intellectually,'' said Kanas, a psychiatrist who holds
talk sessions with World War II and Korean War veterans at the
Veterans Administration hospital at Fort Miley.
</P>
<P>
   Kanas, a veteran of the Vietnam War, meets regularly with a
group of men in their 60s, 70s and 80s at the San Francisco
hospital. After seeing ``Saving Private Ryan,'' he said, ``I can
understand better why it's so hard for them to explain their
experiences to those who haven't been there. I've been to Normandy,
I've seen those beaches, but this, especially, drove it home.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frank Schoenfeld, director of the Post Traumatic Stress
Disorder department at Fort Miley, expects veterans seeing ``Saving
Private Ryan'' to have a hard time over the next few weeks as they
try to separate the present day from 50-year-old memories.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 400 post traumatic stress disorder cases at
Fort Miley, Schoenfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever an explicit film like `Platoon' or `Full Metal
Jacket' comes out, a film with any sense of accuracy to it, vets
will react strongly to the combat scenes,'' Schoenfeld said. ``I'm
expecting the same this time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' is a story about a unit, headed by Capt.
Miller (Tom Hanks), who survives the Normandy D-Day invasion only
to be assigned the task of locating a young private (Matt Damon)
who is the only surviving brother of four. The film begins with a
stirring, brutal take on the invasion.
</P>
<P>
   The Veterans Administration is setting up a hot line to deal
with anticipated response to ``Saving Private Ryan,'' and
Schoenfeld said, ``It will be interesting to see if we get any new
patients because of this _ people coming to us after going to the
film, people who say, `I'm having trouble. I didn't think I was
having any trouble with things like this, but ...'''
</P>
<P>
   Talk of post-traumatic stress disorder usually centers on
Vietnam veterans, Schoenfeld said, but veterans from World War II
and Korea are just as susceptible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any meaningful event can trigger a change,'' he said. ``An
argument with the boss, anything ... the symptoms of stress
disorder are remarkably tenacious. How strong it is depends a lot
on how things are going in one's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanas agreed, saying, ``Some event comes up _ retiring, a
medical procedure, flashbacks _ and it starts all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Though none of the dozen veterans in the group session Monday
had seen ``Saving Private Ryan,'' they found themselves talking
about it, about the spasms of gore, about the unrelenting scenes at
Omaha Beach on the Normandy coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very vivid,'' Kanas said. ``I can't imagine it not
bringing back memories.''
</P>
<P>
   The director of the film, Steven Spielberg, has said he would
consider ``Saving Private Ryan'' successful when ``people walking
past veterans' cemeteries ... spend a second thinking about who's
buried there.''
</P>
<P>
   The scenes that open and close the film _ an aging veteran
breaking down at a U.S. graveyard above Omaha Beach _ was actually
taken from Spielberg's memory of a trip to Normandy in 1972, when
he watched a veteran collapse before rows of graves in a cemetery
on the bluffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stopped in his tracks and his body began to shake,''
Spielberg, 51, said. ``He fell to his knees and began to sob. His
entire family surrounded him and began to comfort him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1521EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6438 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVESTING-THREE-AZR &LR;      07-28 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVESTING-THREE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY FIRMS WELCOME LITTLE, STEADY INVESTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN GILBERTSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - With a teacher's salary and a chunk of credit card
debt, Heather Baxter doesn't have much money to invest.
</P>
<P>
   But the 28-year-old Mesa, Ariz., woman wanted to begin saving
for retirement. She's afraid the State Retirement Plan won't be
enough to pay for travel and other retirement dreams.
</P>
<P>
   When she went to see a financial planner to discuss her options,
she didn't expect much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really afraid they'd say the minimum was $200 a paycheck
and I'd say, `Well then, I'm out of here,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Baxter was thrilled to learn she could get started for just $15
every other week. For the past year, the money has been deducted
from her paycheck and invested in mutual funds in a tax-sheltered
annuity, an insurance product for retirement savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel it at all,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A bare-bones budget doesn't mean no Wall Street in your diet.
Mutual funds, brokerages, publicly traded companies and others
offer programs ideal for investors on a shoestring.
</P>
<P>
   More and more people are seeking them out as they get the bug
after watching the stock market's spectacular run the past few
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to get in on the bandwagon,'' said Joanne Schwartz,
a certified financial planner and owner of JS Financial Concepts in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz and other planners advocate starting as early as
possible, even if it's on a small scale, to take advantage of
compounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like working out _ anything you do is beneficial,'' said
Christopher McCrossan, a senior financial adviser with American
Express Financial Advisors in Mesa, the planner Baxter went to see.
</P>
<P>
   Before you pull out your checkbook, however, there are a few
things to keep in mind. First, it's foolish to commit to regular
monthly investments if you're loaded up on debt and barely have
enough money to pay the bills. (Baxter has about $7,000 in credit
card debt, but is paying it off aggressively and has some savings
so she can afford the $15 investments.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had one or two clients who basically had so much credit
card debt that they couldn't afford $5 a year to invest,'' Schwartz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz turns such clients' attention to budgeting, credit card
consolidation and other moves to get their financial house in
order.
</P>
<P>
   McCrossan said he looks for ways to help clients free up enough
money to invest, such as paying their car insurance twice a year
instead of monthly, which usually comes with a convenience charge.
</P>
<P>
   Experts also like to see people have savings equal to three to
six months' living expenses for emergencies before they start
investing.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they suggest taking full advantage of 401(k) programs
and other employer-sponsored retirement savings plans before
branching out into other investments. The money comes right of your
paycheck and there's usually a company match based on your
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can put in as little as 1 percent of your salary,'' said
Chuck Carlson, a do-it-yourself investing expert who edits a
newsletter on buying stocks without a broker. ``That really is the
first place someone with limited money ought to be looking.''
</P>
<P>
   With those caveats, here's a sampling of some of the most
popular low-minimum investing options out there, for investors on
their own or with the help of a financial adviser.
</P>
<P>
   _Low minimum mutual funds. Many mutual funds let you get started
for as little as $50, provided you agree to invest that much on a
monthly basis. Strong Funds (800-359-3379; www.strong-funds.com),
for example, has an Automatic Investment Plan with a $50 monthly
minimum. The money is deducted from your bank account or, where
available, pay. It covers about 40 funds, from money market funds
to international growth funds.
</P>
<P>
   Strong introduced a program this year for beginning investors.
The centerpiece is the Strong Step 1 Money Fund, a money-market
fund. The minimum is $1,000 but that's waived if you commit to
invest $50 a month.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to building up their savings, investors get
educational materials to help them learn about investing, including
recommendations on how your investments should be divvied among
different categories based on your age, risk tolerance and other
factors.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum balance in the account is $20,000 to encourage
people to start diversifying into different types of investments.
</P>
<P>
   Other fund families that let you get started for $250 or less
include Invesco (800-525-8085), Neuberger &AMP; Berman (800-877-9700),
Pioneer (800-225-6292) and Franklin Templeton (800-342-5236).
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz likes the American Funds family (800-421-0180, Ext. 23;
www.americanfunds.com), which offers 28 funds through financial
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Her favorites are American's Washington Mutual Investors fund, a
conservative growth-and-income fund, and New Perspective fund, an
international growth fund. They allow a minimum investment of $50,
sometimes $25, if you agree to invest regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer mutual funds to (individual stocks) because you're
spreading your risk in a mutual fund,'' Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   The discount brokerage firm Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. recently began
offering an educational program for new investors in its four
Phoenix area offices. Investors should ask for a copy of Beginning
Investor _ Schwab Solutions. If you decide to open a Schwab
account, the minimum is $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   _Direct stock purchase plans and dividend reinvestment plans. If
there's stock-picking in your blood, you can start investing in
companies without a broker for as little as $50, according to Chuck
Carlson, editor of ``No-Load Stock Insider'' and ``DRIP Investor''
(219-852-3220; www.dripinvestor.com).
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 companies offer direct purchase plans, or no-load
stocks, as Carlson calls them. They include such household names as
Disney, McDonald's and Exxon. Not all have ultra-low minimums,
however. McDonald's requires $1,000 to start.
</P>
<P>
   For those with limited funds, Carlson likes Johnson Controls, a
building controls company (NYSE:JCI; $50 minimum, no fees); Becton,
Dickinson, a health care company (NYSE: BDX; $50 minimum if you
agree to invest regularly; 3 cent per share purchase fee); and oil
giant Exxon ($250 minimum, no fees).
</P>
<P>
   ``For $350 you can get started in three companies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He recommends beginning with three or four companies, adding
more after you've accumulated 25 to 50 shares in each company.
</P>
<P>
   _Low-cost investment plans. The National Association of
Investors Corp. (888-780-8400; www.betterinvesting.org), a
non-profit educational group that helps investment clubs and
individual investors, has a new stock service for members that
allows investments of as little as $10 excluding fees. Temper of
the Times Communications, which publishes the ``Moneypaper''
newsletter (914-381-5400; www.moneypaper.com) has a plan called the
Temper Enrollment Service, featuring more than 900 companies. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dawn Gilbertson may be reached at dawn.gilbertson(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
