<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO'S UNION SQUARE BECOMES HOT RETAIL AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER and WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An increase in activity among merchants
competing for coveted space in Union Square has made real estate
near this tiny plot of land more expensive than it has been in
decades, elevating San Francisco's retail center into a
sought-after address.
</P>
<P>
   ``Union Square has got to be the hottest retail shopping center
today,'' said Helen Bulwik, director of global retailing for Arthur
Andersen Consulting in San Francisco. ``The rental rates now are
extremely high, and the only retailers that can really afford to
take that kind of space ... are those comfortable with their
financial future.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of retailers _ including Neiman Marcus, Niketown,
Rockport, the Body Shop, Ultimo and Diesel _ have expanded into
nearby streets, making the area worthy of comparisons to Tokyo's
Ginza district or New York's Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   But Union Square rents aren't quite what they are in Tokyo or
New York, where rental costs are $500 to $700 per square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Rents for small shop fronts on Union Square _ measuring 1,000 to
2,000 square feet _ are about $300 per square foot, according to
Jill Paul, a broker with CB Richard Ellis. Spaces of 10,000 to
20,000 square feet on and near Union Square are going for about
$150 per square foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rents on the square are the highest in the city on a
per-square-foot basis,'' Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question the high cost of doing business is changing
the face of Union Square, but making space there even more of a
premium and pushing up rents in neighboring areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are looking at Union Square, but there's just
not a lot of space,'' said Ken Brownell, president of Blatteis
Realty Co. He described the market in the square as the tightest he
has seen in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Paul, who specializes in downtown properties, says competition
is great, especially for small spaces because retailers are
clamoring for a presence in Union Square.
</P>
<P>
   Even for the square itself _ an elevated park bounded by Geary,
Powell, Post and Stockton streets _ improvements are in the works.
A $15 million face lift is in the works for a park that many say
has gone to seed and has become a hangout for the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Union Square proprietors and civic groups contend the renovated
park _ which may end up looking like a low-rise Egyptian pyramid _
will be more attractive and safe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
