<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6451 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GHANA-AZR &LR;      07-28 2768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GHANA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
7,000 MILES NO BARRIER TO CHIEF LEADING TRIBE IN GHANA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NALERIGU, GHANA _ Sule Issifu, a prince of the Mamprusi Tribe,
had hoped to return to his West African birthplace and abdicate his
position as chief while his life back in America was on hold.
</P>
<P>
   But as in many royal families, politics intervened.
</P>
<P>
   What had seemed so simple a notion in Higley, a suburb in the
Phoenix area, was causing turmoil 7,000 miles away in this village
of mud and thatched-roof houses where Issifu was born 47 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tradition was at stake.
</P>
<P>
   As the eldest son of Mamprusi Chief Issifu Tampuri, Sule Issifu
had inherited the title of chief after his father's death last year
at 89. By this tradition, the younger Issifu was expected to rule
the Mamprusis as his beloved father had for more than half a
century. No one else would do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody said they wanted me,'' Sule Issifu (EEE-see-foo)
says with a sigh. ``Everybody likes me.`'
</P>
<P>
   Love had become an unfortunate burden. Family members agonized
over his intention to relinquish the title, highest rank in the
tribe except for the paramount chief, known as the Nayiri. Village
elders warned that abdication would send the line of succession to
another family. Outsiders waited to contest the title and buy the
privilege for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Pride was at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Issifu would have to demonstrate the wisdom and diplomacy his
father had taught him since birth. The next weeks would be a test
of how well he had learned those lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Not until he finally held the red cap and spear that signify
Mamprusi authority would it become clear he had mastered his
lessons. That day was still many months away.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Living in 2 worlds &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving Ghana 25 years ago for college in Portland, Ore.,
Issifu has been a man living comfortably in two worlds. His
birthright is the heritage of a village with a simple lifestyle and
citizens whose hands and kind faces eagerly welcome strangers of
all colors.
</P>
<P>
   The Mamprusis who inhabited this territory for centuries as
warriors are today a peace-loving tribe. The tender-hearted Issifu
has no wish to abandon his people.
</P>
<P>
   But the land of his birth is farther away now than it was when
he enrolled at Lewis &AMP; Clark College in 1973, farther both
geographically and culturally. Issifu has an American-born wife and
two daughters born and reared in the United States who explore the
world on their home computer and have unlimited opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tradition that called him back to Africa in January,
he could not ask his children to trade the life he and his wife,
Lydia, have made in America for life in a town just now entering
the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   In Nalerigu, there are no telephones, no running water, no
Internet. There are power poles but no power. Electrical lines
stretch across the village, waiting to be connected. Someday.
</P>
<P>
   Goats, sheep, chickens and pigs run along the dirt roads of the
village in the innocent days before they become the next night's
stew. Barefoot children chase after them, kicking rubber balls and
playing with such unconventional toys as used auto parts, bicycle
handlebars and discarded tuna cans.
</P>
<P>
   Their laughter is musical as they circle a towering kapok tree
outside the Issifu family compound. The majestic old tree serves as
a kind of community center where villagers stretch out on the
protruding roots to share news of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the real Africa,'' says Alhaji Alhussein Mahama,
Sule's best friend since high school.
</P>
<P>
   The men of Nalerigu farm one season a year, forced to idle their
fields during the dry spring because there is no irrigation system.
</P>
<P>
   Women keep house, cooking over wood fires outside their homes,
stirring huge pots of rice, mutton, beef, beans, yams and plantains
with wooden spoons as long as their arms.
</P>
<P>
   Water is toted from a reservoir a mile away. Making countless
trips each day, women ferry pots of water for cooking, bathing and
cleaning. They nurture large families while keeping immaculate
homes, constantly sweeping away debris from the dirt floors.
</P>
<P>
   Polygamy rules. Men have as many wives as they can afford.
Sule's father had five wives and 22 children. Mothers bear as many
as eight to 10 children. Child rearing demands the lion's share of
their time and sometimes saps their health.
</P>
<P>
   But with time has come progress. A bus depot in town connects
residents of Nalerigu (Nah-LAIR-ee-goo) with neighboring villages
and, ultimately, to the capital city of Accra on the Atlantic
coast. A beauty salon has opened.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's, the local watering hole, offers the coldest beers
and soft drinks in town _ slightly cooler than room temperature,
thanks to a generator-powered refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   There are promises that electricity will be connected next
month, though even Accra still suffers frequent blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   As pleasant and uncluttered as life is in Nalerigu, Sule and
Lydia want more for their daughters, Seiba, 11, and Aza, 8. The
girls are honor roll students who view a visit to Ghana like a
camping trip, bathing under buckets of water and trying out the
packed-earth latrine that their father, whom they affectionately
call Baba, has just had built.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia could be content living without amenities. It's the
children's future that concerns her. In Nalerigu, they would attend
school only through junior high. High school would mean boarding
school in Accra, more than a day away by car.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sacrifice neither she nor her husband is willing to make,
no matter how much they are pressed by tribal custom, family pride
and the entreaties of village elders. Seiba and Aza come first. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Being Americanized &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Married for 14 years now, Sule and Lydia met in college and fell
in love over his talent for making peanut butter soup.
</P>
<P>
   They had always known that one day Sule would be expected to
take his father's place among the quarter-million Mamprusis. But
the couple put thoughts of royalty out of mind as they made a home
and started a family.
</P>
<P>
   Sule has become Americanized. Though he finds peace and comfort
in the familiar surroundings of Nalerigu _ ``I feel at home; I feel
safer'' _ Western civilization has transformed him.
</P>
<P>
   Even in his birthplace, his role has changed. When he goes home
now, he no longer walks easily with boyhood friends. In his
presence, they bow or squat and address him as chief. He does not
spend leisurely hours at Christie's. Instead, he holds court while
someone fetches him a cool beer.
</P>
<P>
   His day begins with a bowl of oatmeal, a cup of Nescafe and the
sweet bread baked in town. Villagers with business to conduct begin
arriving early in the morning, squatting and whispering the
traditional greeting, ``Naaa, naaa.'' They clap their hands softly
and avert their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   After breakfast, Sule makes his rounds, meeting with elders and
greeting his people as he walks with an entourage. He might stop at
one of the schools in the village or drop by the police station.
</P>
<P>
   If his uncle, chief of a neighboring village, is visiting
Nalerigu, he will pay his respects. Guabligrana, 78, was a
decorated World War II soldier with the British army. He is adamant
that Sule must be chief.
</P>
<P>
   Family honor is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is for this house,'' Guabligrana said, declaring that his
nephew has the attributes to be a good chief, as his father had
before him. ``It is God who makes him that way.''
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Sule negotiated with his family to resolve the
dilemma of succession. His intention had been to accept the title
of Masu, or chief, then abdicate in favor of his uncle or a younger
brother. But when he arrived late in January to begin executing the
plan, his announcement was met with alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Family meetings ended in tears. Only Sule could be chief! His
brothers and sisters begged him not to abdicate, fearing loss of
the title from their clan. Their big brother must comply, even if
it meant ruling from across an ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Sule and his wife despaired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our plan would work,'' Lydia says. ``We never
thought it would come to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid rumors that she was encouraging her husband to abandon his
commitment, Lydia was dispatched to reassure the family that the
decision would be Sule's alone. She was supportive. But his nervous
siblings wanted to hear only one thing: Their brother would be
Masu.
</P>
<P>
   At last, bowing to pressure and bound by duty, Sule conceded,
agreeing to become chief, appoint a subchief and return to his home
in America to conduct a long-distance reign.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the coronation could take place. In a ceremony called an
inskinment, Sule, holding the temporary title of Gbangrana, would
don a dried goat skin, taken from an animal slaughtered days
earlier, to receive the spears and red cap that symbolize power.
</P>
<P>
   Coronation day would be celebrated with song and dance. Talking
drums would echo across the village.
</P>
<P>
   But the resolution of Sule's predicament would not come so
easily. Even in a small African village, bureaucracy rears its
head. Superstition plays a hand. Day after day, elders delayed
setting a date for the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   By tradition, inskinment can be held only on Saturdays and
Wednesdays, and never at the end of the month. By now, it was
nearly the end of February. The Council of Elders favored waiting
until another moon rose. The ceremony scheduled for Saturday was
postponed until Wednesday. Wednesday dawned, morning wore on. But
no word came that this would be Sule Issifu's coronation day.
</P>
<P>
   The spears had been prepared. the Gbangrana waited to don his
royal raiments. And still the council delayed. The Nayiri, the one
Mamprusi who rules above the Masu, was in failing health and
reluctant to appear weak before his people or to tempt fate by
rushing a ceremony before God willed it.
</P>
<P>
   Haste is an American attribute. Patience is the Mamprusi way.
</P>
<P>
   This was the dry season. The Harmattan, a dusty wind that blows
south from the Sahara, had filled the air over Nalerigu with a
choking sand ground to fine powder. It gave the sky the look of
haze and made waiting under the hot sun with temperatures
approaching 100 even more uncomfortable. It aggravated the
Gbangrana's allergies.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the family compound, the gnarled roots of the kapok tree
cradled the citizens of Nalerigu waiting for word that the
ceremonial drums would soon begin. But late on the last Wednesday
of the month, as sunset streamed through the old tree's leafy
branches, Sule Issifu was still not Masu.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Back to Arizona &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Issifus returned to Arizona in March with little resolved in
the matter of Masu vs. the Elders. Though disappointed, Sule
accepted the sensibilities of his people. His temper, which had
flared under the frustration of family politics, had cooled. He
shed his traditional Ghanaian garb, billowing cotton smock and
loose trousers, for his American T-shirts and blue jeans.
</P>
<P>
   While Sule returned to work in the human resources division of
the Arizona Department of Economic Security, Lydia went back to
running the family dairy farm.
</P>
<P>
   But Sule's thoughts remained 7,000 miles away in Nalerigu.
Despite the turmoil he left behind, he knew that his decision to
return to America was the right one. He and Lydia could do more for
his people here than in a village where his only income would be
from livestock and where he would lack the business contacts that
could help raise Nalerigu's standard of living.
</P>
<P>
   Through their Mamprusi Development Fund, a tax-deductible,
non-profit organization, they plan to court American business and
industry. Donations will finance the cleanup of the water supply,
expedite the connection of power lines, fund paving of dirt roads
and establish scholarships for promising students who can't afford
to pay for high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, we have to bring in some selected
development,'' Sule said, referring to light industry, craft work,
assembly of small products. ``You need capital and someone who can
go there. . . . Americans have always been generous. That helpful
spirit is still there.''
</P>
<P>
   Although optimistic, he sometimes feels overwhelmed by his
responsibilities. Nalerigu is not connected to Phoenix by phone or
fax. The nearest telephone is a village away.
</P>
<P>
   Saddened by the turmoil he left behind, he recognized that his
frustration was a product of his Americanization.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Western influence is taking over me,'' he said. ``I'm not
patient. That's what I'm losing more and more the longer I'm in the
states.''
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters was the Nayiri's failing health, which left
the octogenarian bedridden. Eager to be viewed as a strong leader,
he feared alarming his people with hints of mortality. Sule felt
sympathy for the man who holds such an esteemed position among the
Mamprusis.
</P>
<P>
   There had been speculation that the elders had postponed the
ceremony to assert their independence against pressure to hold
events on a fast-track Western timetable. They were said to be
disturbed by the invasion of a television film crew, reporters and
friends of the Issifu family from Eugene, Ore., and were
stonewalling in order to conduct their traditions their own way.
</P>
<P>
   Sule dismissed such talk. Although admitting he ``felt rotten
and tired and fed up with the whole thing,'' he also respects the
leaders of his village and said that there was nothing unusual
about the way events proceeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how they do it,'' he said of the system of installing
a new chief. ``They've had people stay there for months. . . . I
pushed as hard as I could, and then I remembered tradition.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Coronation day &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In June, the letter came.
</P>
<P>
   The Nayiri's personal message invited Sule to return to Nalerigu
to be installed as Masu. Coronation would take place July 1 or July
4. On June 24, Sule was on a British Airways flight bound for
Accra.
</P>
<P>
   Busy with several projects at DES, he said, ``I had no business
going to Ghana.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Nayiri had spoken.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew I had to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather in Nalerigu was cool, the savannah green and
beautiful. It was the beginning of the rainy season.
</P>
<P>
   His health improved, the Nayiri appeared hale and eager to
conduct the ceremony. Sule hoped it would take place July 1, a
Wednesday, but there was too much to be done. Prominent members of
the village had to be personally notified. Saturday would be
coronation day.
</P>
<P>
   At 10 a.m, the talking drums began pounding. At noon, the Nayiri
emerged from his palace, welcoming Sule to the center of the
compound where hundreds of villagers had gathered to bear witness.
Sule's assistant, the Wudana, carried the ceremonial spears.
</P>
<P>
   Sule and his brothers removed mourning caps they had worn since
their father's death and placed them in a basket. The period of
mourning was over.
</P>
<P>
   Once, twice, three times Sule squatted and rose as he donned the
royal smock and cap. The third time provoked an outburst of joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incredible,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Sule Issifu was Masu.
</P>
<P>
   Riding back to the family compound, exuberant family members
waved white ribbons tied to their wrists. Villagers dusted
themselves with white powder to demonstrate their happiness.
Talking drums bellowed.
</P>
<P>
   Sule, too, was excited, but maintained the composure expected of
a Mamprusi chief.
</P>
<P>
   Spirited dancing erupted at the compound, celebrating not only
the coronation of a chief but the Damba Festival, the Mamprusi new
year. For 10 days, there would be dancing from 8 p.m. to midnight.
On the 10th night, it would last till dawn.
</P>
<P>
   When the Masu was persuaded to dance, a hard rain followed, and
the people took it as a good omen. &QL; 
Long-distance rule
</P>
<P>
   Sule is home again, recovering from another bout of the malaria
that plagues him every time he visits Ghana. During the rainy
season, the air is thick with disease-bearing mosquitoes. But he is
recovering.
</P>
<P>
   In Nalerigu, his brother, Tampuri, is ruling as the Masu's
representative. Tampuri will telephone Sule once a week, trading
news for advice.
</P>
<P>
   If Sule's family ever doubted he would remain loyal and a vital
part of their lives, their fears were unfounded. He is a man who
lives in two worlds and loves both. His dedication is undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half after his father's death, Sule Issifu has
fulfilled his obligation to the citizens of Nalerigu.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted me as Masu and no one else, and that's how it
turned out'' he says. ``It worked out well.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
To contribute to the Mamprusi Development Fund, write P.O. Box
6991, Mesa, AZ 85206. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
