<SLUG> BC-GHANA-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF'S WIFE COMMITTED TO IMPROVING LIVES OF GHANAIAN WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GHANA, WEST AFRICA _ In the village of Nalerigu, women's work is
never done.
</P>
<P>
   Like most American wives and mothers, these women cook, clean
and rear a brood of children. But they do it without microwave
ovens, vacuum cleaners or day care.
</P>
<P>
   In a community where electricity and running water are only
promises, women's work means fetching drinking and bathing water
from a reservoir a mile away and cooking in huge pots outside their
front doors.
</P>
<P>
   Families are large. Abortion is illegal in Ghana, and
contraception is something that often must be practiced in secret.
For men, children bring status. A wife might slip off to the
missionary hospital outside town for a clandestine injection of
Depo-Provera, a Norplant patch or a supply of birth control pills.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, a local midwife says, ``Women work harder than men
and live longer.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the women whose lives American-born Lydia Issifu hopes
to change over the next several years as her husband, Sule, rules
as chief of the Mamprusi Tribe, whose capital is Nalerigu. Sule,
reared in Nalerigu and educated in the United States, inherited the
title when his father died last year.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, the family traveled back to host the final memorial
service for the old chief and to prepare for the succession of a
new one.
</P>
<P>
   Believing they can do more to help the citizens of Nalerigu from
America, the couple will preside over the Mamprusis from their home
in the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia will go to work in behalf of the women. Her priority is
education, the springboard to other opportunities. She said she
believes school is as important for girls as it is for boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you educate a man, you educate a man,'' she quotes an old
saying. ``When you educate a woman, you educate a village.''
</P>
<P>
   School is free through junior high. Those children who wish to
continue must pay tuition at the local secondary school or attend
boarding school in towns as far away as Ghana's capital of Accra.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a fierce determination to make progress. More and
more high school graduates are attending teacher-training schools,
then returning to the village to share their knowledge. Some
students go on to college either in Ghana or America, daring to
dream of opportunities across the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   While Sule works in human resources for Arizona, Lydia and her
brother run the family dairy farm at Higley, east of Phoenix. Hers
is a life Nalerigu women might envy, with her career, modern home
and husband all to herself. She does not condemn the practice of
polygamy but believes it is one more obstacle to equality.
</P>
<P>
   Each succeeding wife falls lower and lower in status. Sometimes,
wives squabble. It is the senior wife's duty to help select
subsequent ones; it is the husband's duty to keep them happy.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia and Sule say they will not try to change tradition but
will be role models.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just live by example,'' Sule says. ``I haven't married
more than one wife.''
</P>
<P>
   His one wife laughs and says that she will make sure things stay
that way.
</P>
<P>
   But women in Nalerigu face other problems. The only water source
is the reservoir formed by the Brimi River. With perfect posture
and an exquisite sense of balance practiced since childhood, women
transport huge earthenware jugs of water on their heads back to
common storage tanks in the village, making several trips a day.
</P>
<P>
   The water is used for cooking, drinking, bathing and washing
clothes and dishes. Adults tolerate it, but water-borne bacteria
often make children sick. A water purification program is on Sule's
priority list.
</P>
<P>
   Women have benefited from the services offered at a hospital
operated by American Baptist missionaries. Classes in nutrition and
prenatal care are available.
</P>
<P>
   While many mothers give birth with the aid of missionary doctors
and midwives, most deliver at home, assisted by traditional birth
attendants. Only an emergency, such as prolonged labor, would bring
them to the hospital
</P>
<P>
   If the woman is able to walk, she would make the 30-minute trip
on foot or by bicycle. If not, her husband would pedal to the
hospital and summon an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   Though most children in Nalerigu appear healthy and happy, some
suffer the plagues of malnutrition, malaria, measles, whooping
cough and tetanus.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of all children die in their first year, says
Martha Nabila, a midwife at the missionary hospital. Of 10 children
a woman might bear, only five or six will survive childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Most girls marry by age 18, some as young as 15, through
arranged marriages brokered between families.
</P>
<P>
   A girl might become the third or fourth wife to a much older man
or be given as a gift, sent to live with the prospective groom's
mother until she is old enough to be a wife. Only a strong-willed
young woman defies her family's choice of a husband. In shunning
marriage, she risks ostracism.
</P>
<P>
   Nabila says that she believes polygamy was once a satisfactory
practice, but that now, men are less able to support several wives,
and everyone suffers.
</P>
<P>
   Bearing many children is a status symbol for women as well as
men, Lydia &UR; says. A woman who appears infertile is the subject of
gossip. And a woman who is not a wife and mother has few
alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is hard for the women,'' says Nabila, whose own husband
abandoned her with four children. ``They work too much.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to improving education, Lydia &UR; also wants to promote
entrepreneurship, something some women already practice.
</P>
<P>
   There are market women, for example, who travel as far as Accra
to purchase wholesale commodities such as housewares, then sell
them in Nalerigu and surrounding villages. Profits are low.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a living,'' Lydia says. ``It's subsistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the wife of a chief has no official duties, Lydia is
committed to improving women's lot in Nalerigu.
</P>
<P>
   But without such basics as electricity and clean water, progress
is uncertain. Change will not come immediately; tradition is
entrenched. But Lydia looks ahead 10 or 20 years and is filled with
hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that life is going to be easier,'' she says. ``There
will be pipe-borne water coming into the households. There will be
electricity. . . . Over the next 20 years, women will have more
time and more ways to improve their income. They will send all
their kids to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I would like to see.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
