<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Tuesday, July 28, 1998     
 Editors     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim Spence at
202-298-6920. For questions about Houston Chronicle sports stories,
please call the Houston Chronicle Sports Department, 713-220-7896.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: CLINTON-INVESTIGATION; CAPITAL-SHOOTINGS;
POWERBALL-LOTTERY; BBN-ASTROS; FBN-McCOMBS; and BKO-WORLD.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INVESTIGATION (Washington) _ Former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky wins immunity from independent counsel Kenneth
Starr, her lawyers say, while the White House tries to decide
whether to appeal a ruling that Starr may interview close White
House aides. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-SECURITY (Washington) _ Sen. John Warner, R-Va., who for
months was a lonely voice in calling for more state-of-the-art
security on Capitol Hill, is getting new support from colleagues
since two security guards were gunned down last week. Warner,
chairman of the Senate Rules panel, offers a beefed-up security
plan that would involve half public and half private funding. By
JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-SHOOTINGS (Washington) _ Throngs of people join
President Clinton and members of Congress in honoring two slain
guards whose bodies are lying in state in the Capitol rotunda. The
officers, Jacob J. Chestnut and John Gibson, were shot dead last
week while trying to stop a gunman who invaded the building. By
GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-VIOLENCE (Washington) _ Despite the uproar over school
shootings in Arkansas, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Mississippi and
Kentucky, gun-related deaths in schools have not risen dramatically
in the past six years, a criminal justice think tank reports. Its
message: School is really safer for kids than their home is. By DAN
FREEDMAN. (For release 6 a.m. EDT Wednesday)
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-GOVERNERS (Washington) _ Leaders of the National
Governors' Association assess the nation's welfare system nearly
two years after President Clinton approved legislation that
overhauled it by forcing most welfare recipients to go to work,
cutting benefits and turning control of the program over to the
states. By NICOLE TSONG.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   POWERBALL-LOTTERY (Undated) _ Texans are sweltering in the
Louisiana border heat for a chance at the $250 million lottery,
asking themselves, ``Didn't we just have a world-record Powerball
jackpot?'' The answer is yes. The reason is that officials at the
multistate lottery upped the odds last November, which means fewer
jackpot winners, but more lotto frenzies. By RICHARD STEWART.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Republicans are finding that
lecturing voters about morality does not sell beyond the ranks of
the religious right. The question now is whether to keep it up or
drop the subject. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ Pitcher Sean Bergman will be shooting for
his 10th victory of the season as the Houston Astros try to make it
two in a row over the Florida Marlins. By CARLTON THOMPSON. (Game
time is 8 p.m. EDT)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-McCOMBS (Dallas) _ NFL owners approve Red McCombs of San
Antonio as the new owner of the Minnesota Vikings football
franchise. By DANNY ROBBINS.
</P>
<P>
   BKO-WORLD (Athens, Greece) _ An advance on the World Basketball
Championships, where a team of little-known Americans will try to
pull off an improbable run to a gold medal under the guidance of
Houston Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich. The tournament begins
Wednesday with the U.S. team facing Brazil. By EDDIE SEFKO.
</P>
