<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6512 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EAST-GERMANY-RESTAURA     07-28 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAST-GERMANY-RESTAURANTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORN AGAIN: REPLACING WURSTS FOR WHITE ASPARAGUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV.: A map locating Dresden is being sent to NYT graphics
clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling
212 556-4204.)  
 (HLW)  
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRESDEN, Germany _ This is what eating out in the monochromatic,
monolithic Communist state of East Germany and its capital, East
Berlin, used to be like:
</P>
<P>
   In Dresden, once such a picture of Baroque magnificence that art
historians unblushingly compared it to Venice and Florence, the
best meal in town was a watery, lackluster Hungarian goulash in a
dreary, Lubyanka-like restaurant. To cheer things up, a quartet of
Volkspolizei, or people's police, often stood along the walls,
fingering their Uzis, lower lips protruding in loathing for the
almost entirely foreign clientele.
</P>
<P>
   In East Berlin, which I visited several times in the 1970s and
1980s, a search for a gastronomically satisfying lunch was a search
for the imbiss, or snack bar, that sold the most distinguished
currywurst _ a grilled or fried sausage, sprinkled with curry
powder and slathered with paprika-spiked ketchup. For dinner, I
took the elevated train back to the bright lights, starched
tablecloths and sweet-and-sour bistros of West Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   And this is how things have changed on the restaurant scene,
every bit as quickly as they have changed on the political and
economic fronts:
</P>
<P>
   In Dresden, which is rapidly repairing the physical damage from
the hideous allied fire-bombing of 1945, if not the psychological
damage of the dismal decades that followed, the dining room of the
Buelow Residenz, a small hotel in a stunning canary-and-white
Baroque mansion, has won a richly deserved Michelin star for
cooking that would pass muster in Paris. The gun-toting cops are
long gone, replaced by shining crystal and fresh flowers.
</P>
<P>
   In eastern Berlin, one is spoiled for choice; indeed, many
knowing visitors turn their backs on the fading glamour of the
Kurfuerstendamm in the western part of town to stay and eat in
Mitte, the heart of the east. There, too, is a Michelin-starred
restaurant, called Vau, a handsome room with a modern barrel-vault
ceiling, sharp service, and fresh, light German cooking.
</P>
<P>
   By chance, my wife, Betsey, and I were in Berlin when the wall
came tumbling down in 1989, and this summer we made our second
extensive trip to the reborn East. Polluting smokestacks have been
capped, shrubbery and window boxes decorate once-barren houses,
potholes have been filled with a zeal that would thrill Alphonse
D'Amato, and if satisfying, occasionally brilliant meals are not
quite as omnipresent as scaffolds, cranes and backhoes, they are
widely available if you know where to look.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the chefs in eastern Germany's new restaurants came from
the West, lured by economic opportunity; others, having traveled
through western Europe since the wall came down, have emulated what
they saw and tasted there.
</P>
<P>
   A passion for seasonal specialties is one of the joys of eating
in Germany, and especially eastern Germany, where the grip of
tradition is far more tenacious than in the West. Only in northern
Italy, where everyone who can afford it gorges in season on white
truffles and floppy porcini mushrooms, is there a comparable
obsession with fleeting culinary pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   People overdose on goose on St. Martin's feast day, Nov. 11,
when the birds are at their fattest; on Germany's remarkably sweet
cherries in early summer; and on pfifferlinge, the pumpkin-colored
mushrooms that the French call chanterelles, a little later. But
this is nothing compared to the frenzied consumption of white
asparagus (spargel in German), whose season is limited by law to
the period from late April to June 24, to give the beds ample time
to regenerate.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans heap the earth around the spears of asparagus and
cut it in the pre-dawn hours, to protect it from the light that
would turn it green. All of which I thought a lot of nonsense until
we stumbled upon a little restaurant called Vogelherd outside a
village named Zerbst _ not far, incidentally, from the newly
restored Bauhaus architecture and design school in Dessau.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Vogelherd, kitschy in the manner of rural
Germany, owes nothing to the Bauhaus. But though we were late for
lunch, we were warmly greeted and offered a four-page menu of
asparagus specialties. In its way, we soon learned, this was a
sophisticated place, certainly from the drinker's point of view,
with elegant Rheingau rieslings from Robert Weil, grappas from Levi
and eaux-de-vies from Miclo. It was a bit like coming across Ridge
zinfandels on the Dakota plains.
</P>
<P>
   The asparagus, cut in the surrounding fields about six hours
before we ate them, were a revelation. Clearly, freshness is the
key to this game. Betsey ate them with brown butter; I chose
hollandaise sauce. Herby, sweet, just firm enough, the plump white
spears easily outdistanced in complexity and subtlety of flavor the
green asparagus I cut as a kid from my Aunt Peg's prized bed and
ate with melted butter. I can offer no more heartfelt praise.
</P>
<P>
   Betsey? She ate asparagus so often in the next week that I
started calling her Spargel Plenty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   We had several good meals in Dresden, none of them Hungarian,
including a superb after-opera supper at the Taschenbergpalais, a
rebuilt schloss in the center of town, whose cuisine Michelin
underrates. But the highlight was the Buelow Residenz, the domain
of Ralf J. Kutzner, a chef trained in western Germany, Hong Kong
and Britain, who decided five years ago to cast his lot with
Dresden when trees still grew in ruined buildings near the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I arrived with no staff, no suppliers, no menu, no wine list
and a month to go until opening,'' Kutzner said. ``When we drove
into town, at night, having just left London, my wife looked around
and asked me, `Are you sure?' My old colleagues weren't interested
in coming, so I had to train people. Now, they call from all over,
looking for jobs in reception or the kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Residenz is a residenz by chance. The Buelow family,
builders and real estate operators in Stuttgart, bought it for an
office in eastern Germany, but the city wanted to restore the
prewar residential character of the neighborhood, across the Elbe
River from the Opera House. Presto, change-o, the office building
became a hotel with a restaurant called Carrousel.
</P>
<P>
   A truck arrives from the Rungis market, just outside Paris,
twice a week, but just as he has trained staff members, Kutzner has
guided and encouraged local growers of vegetables and herbs. He
buys venison from Brandenburg, the state surrounding Berlin, and
hopes to add other regional suppliers soon.
</P>
<P>
   All is not perfect. On one of two nights we ate there, the staff
was overwhelmed by large parties, the service dragged, and my
wife's gimlet eye detected a tiny chip in one glass and a faded
bloom in one bouquet.
</P>
<P>
   But the Carrousel delivered the goods 95 percent of the time.
The English menu is in English, not some Graustarkian mutation, and
the staff, in a region where Russian is still the dominant foreign
language, handles French and English with aplomb. Yellow-lacquered
walls, Dresden china chandeliers in pink, white and green, an old
porcelain stove in a corner, service plates with wide green borders
_ the look of the place is a welcome in itself.
</P>
<P>
   Stefan Hermann, all of 29, runs the kitchen now, with Kutzner
occasionally looking over his shoulder. A protege of Harald
Wohlfart, the chef of the Schwarzwaldstube in the Black Forest,
which many consider the best restaurant in Germany, he sent out a
stream of delicious dishes. Almost all showed a rare gift for
combining delicate textures with robust flavors.
</P>
<P>
   There were soups like an emerald-green puree of watercress,
peppery yet soothing, with a quail egg and bits of roasted salmon
adding accents, and a clear gelee full of tomato flavor, neither
rubbery nor watery, with chunks of fresh tomato. That was Betsey's
favorite dish of the trip, not just the meal. The kidneys and
sweetbreads were crisp and untouched by the lingering flavor of
uric acid that so often mars this dish. I would also cast a vote
for a perfectly timed slab of roast turbot, a veritable steak from
the sea. And then there was Jell-O gone to heaven: a pyramid-shaped
gelatin dessert with peak-of-the-season cherries trapped inside,
the gelatin itself flavored with rum, port, cassis and red wine.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, understandably, since eastern Berlin is only a cab ride
from western Berlin, change in the old Prussian capital, soon to be
the seat of the national government again, has been more rapid than
elsewhere in eastern Germany. The star is Vau, just off the
magnificent square called the Gendarmenmarkt, which is dominated by
Schinkel's Schauspielhaus, one of the world's half-dozen greatest
neo-classic buildings, now a concert hall.
</P>
<P>
   Vau strikes a different note. Long, narrow, with bare wood
floors, banquettes and rows of Breuer chairs, it looks more formal
than it is. Not surprisingly, both the cooking and wine list show
Austrian influences; this is a new venture of Josef Viehhauser, the
Austrian chef and owner of the high-profile Le Canard in Hamburg.
We ate very well. A veal steak with bits of grilled asparagus and
seraphic homemade noodles took the prize, but only just. The
cheeses were in perfect condition, and a glass of Banyuls, a
fragrant red wine from the French-Spanish border country, which had
the richness of dried fruit, proved a perfect partner for rye bread
and Bleu de Bresse.
</P>
<P>
   People had said Vau was hot, hot, hot, and we went expecting to
find a roomful of rich, rich, rich people. Not at all. The crowd
was old and young, local and foreign, dressy and casual. The room
hummed contentedly. It was fun.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere at Maxwell, which occupies the courtyard and
ground floor of a restored brewery, has a similar quality, both
warmhearted and with-it. The restaurant's eclectic menu is executed
with panache.
</P>
<P>
   A first course of rare tuna with soy, coriander and sesame was
enlivened by crisp, bright-flavored vegetables, and a more Germanic
dish, boar with cabbage, wild mushrooms and sliced, pan-fried
dumplings, showed how modern technique can salvage onetime
favorites that overburden fragile modern digestive systems. The
meat, sliced thin, was chewy but full of rich, gamy flavor: pork
tenderloin with attitude, and no murky sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the clients at most of these places are visitors from
western Germany, westerners who have moved east and foreign
tourists. The prices are too steep for all but a few easterners.
Dinner for two with wine at Vau, whose prices are typical of the
best restaurants, costs $150 and up.
</P>
<P>
   My choice for a less expensive supper after the opera (or
anything else) would be Borchardt, a classic brasserie on the model
of Coupole in Paris or Balthazar in New York, though calmer than
the latter. The floor is tiled, the banquettes are raspberry-red
and the room is broken up by fat Corinthian columns.
</P>
<P>
   Delicious, unfussy food _ steaks, chops, Irish oysters and
premium quality seasonal specialties, from quail to strawberries _
is served with aristocratic wines at working folks' prices, such as
Ornellaia red from the Tuscan coast and Schloss Vollrads rieslings
from the Rheingau.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Gendarmenmarkt from Vau is a reincarnation of Lutter
&AMP; Wegner, which began life in a wine cellar in the East, moved to
the West after World War II and recently opened this branch, on the
site of the house of E.T.A. Hoffmann, the 19th-century artist,
writer and wastrel. Not without reason, the menu describes the
wiener schnitzel as ``our classic.'' You will find no better in
Vienna, and everyone sitting around us seemed to be eating it. The
frothy beet soup is good, too.
</P>
<P>
   There are many more tables to sample. You will find understated
Italian food at Cantamaggio, near the Volksbuehne theater;
Southeast Asian fare at Mao Thai near bustling Kaethe Kollwitz
Platz; innovative Middle Eastern dishes at Cafe Oren, right next to
the restored New Synagogue; and, I am told, good German cooking at
Kaiserstuben, opposite the Pergamon Museum, a 30-seater opened only
three months ago by a young partnership that makes a specialty of
brunch on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Still more, no doubt, are on the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
