<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6518 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AREA-CODE-BLUES-2TAKE     07-28 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AREA-CODE-BLUES-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEED TO ADD AREA CODES MAKES DIALING MORE COMPLEX 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Baltimore resident Joseph Kaelin wants to call
up his next-door neighbor, he must dial 10 digits _ the area code
plus the telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   If he mistakenly dials a ``1'' before the area code, his call
still will go through, and no long-distance charges will be
assessed.
</P>
<P>
   Now if Kaelin travels to Los Angeles next year, he'll need to
dial 11 digits (``1'' plus the area code and the number) if he's
staying along the coast, but only seven digits if he's downtown.
</P>
<P>
   And if he stops in Houston, he'll be back to punching 10 digits.
But if he tries to dial a ``1,'' he'll get a recording.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the traveler, it makes it absolutely insane,'' said
Kaelin, a Baltimore real estate agent who criticized Maryland's
overlay plan when it was being reviewed by regulators. ``The
frequent fliers of this country, what do they do?''
</P>
<P>
   This hodgepodge of local calling procedures _ more varied and
confusing than anything seen in this country in decades _ reflects
state regulators' attempts to cope with an explosion in demand for
telephone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   State officials are trying to accommodate an increasing need for
telephone numbers brought on by the burgeoning popularity of
technologies such as cellular telephones and pagers, while at the
same time setting aside millions of number combinations in the hope
of fostering local phone competition.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that area codes such as 713 and even the newer 281
in Houston are rapidly running out of numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Jan. 16, Houston callers will be required to dial the
area code and telephone number when making all local calls.
</P>
<P>
   The boundaries between 713 and 281, drawn just two years ago,
will disappear. And a third, as-yet-to-be-assigned area code will
be laid over the entire Houston metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas callers will begin 10-digit dialing Dec. 5, when the
dividing line between 214 and 972 is erased. Dallas will then get a
new, ``overlay'' area code next July.
</P>
<P>
   Houston first flirted with the notion of an ``overlay'' area
code three years ago, but regulators backed off in favor of the
temporary 281 geographic split when residents began to howl.
</P>
<P>
   Other communities pushed ahead and have become the nation's
telephone overlay guinea pigs. While their transitions to this new
way of dialing have gone relatively smoothly, they have experienced
some minor, albeit embarrassing, glitches.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, for instance, adopted a new 678 overlay area code last
January. Some pay telephone owners, however, failed to reprogram
their phones. When customers tried to make local calls within the
new area code, they found themselves getting charged $3 a pop
because the phones treated these as long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   Miami began requiring 10-digit dialing earlier this month, only
to have the burglar alarm companies begin to wail. Many of their
alarm systems couldn't dial numbers longer than seven digits, and
they had to beg for a 90-day reprieve. Georgia regulators gave
Atlanta security companies a six-month break, and then had to grant
them an additional six months.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Georgia Public Service Commission, which for months
preached to businesses and consumers about the need to prepare for
10-digit dialing, forgot to reprogram one of its own phone systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission sent the states down this
road three years ago, when it began rejecting proposals to allow
states to assign new area codes only to ``wireless'' technologies
such as cell phones and pagers.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC _ pointing to the Communications Act of 1934 _ has
concluded such programs ``discriminate'' against the wireless
technologies, since they alone would have to bear the stigma of an
unfamiliar area code and the expense of reprogramming for it.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Public Utility Commission favored such a plan to
relieve the number crunches in Houston and Dallas, but the FCC
denied its request. Only New York's technology-specific plan, which
was implemented in 1992, was grandfathered in.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut has asked the FCC to reconsider that ruling, and
Texas has joined in that request. But federal regulators have given
no indications of a change in direction.
</P>
<P>
   Critics ridicule the logic of the FCC decision. ``How can you
discriminate against a cell phone?'' Baltimore's Kaelin asked.
</P>
<P>
   But overlay plan supporters argue that technology-specific plans
merely delay the inevitable. New York, for instance, already has
plans for two new overlay plans because its ``wireless'' program
cannot keep up with demand.
</P>
<P>
   These newer technologies, however, account for only part of the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators, trying to offer consumers competition in their local
phone market, have been assigning millions of numbers _ in blocks
of 10,000 per prefix _ to companies hoping to offer local service.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this competition, however, still is theoretical. Ten
companies have been assigned telephone numbers in the Houston area,
but even regulators aren't sure how many of them actually are
providing service.
</P>
<P>
   Some states have implemented number-conservation programs _
divvying out numbers in batches of 1,000 rather than 10,000 _ but
those efforts have often been too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   Criticized for destroying residents' sense of a geographical
identity, overlay plans remain unpopular in many parts of the
country. Illinois is still hoping to avoid an overlay plan for
Chicago's northern suburbs scheduled to go into effect later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   California split itself into 25 different geographic area codes
before agreeing to create an overlay plan in the coastal portion of
Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Worried that ``11-digit dialing'' may be too grating for
Southern Californian ears, GTE California has come up with its own
description. ``We're calling it 1 plus 10,'' company spokeswoman
Julia Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Those communities that already have implemented overlay plans
argue they have received widespread public acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Public Service Commission, for instance, has logged
only four complaints since Miami's new area code took effect July
1, while Maryland, which began mandatory 10-digit dialing more than
a year ago, has received only 13.
</P>
<P>
   Critics argue that a lack of complaints filed with a
little-known state agency is not an accurate reflection of public
sentiment. And it's not likely to take into account the opinion of
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Self, president of Bethesda, Md.-based Market Dynamics,
tells the story of an old friend from out-of-town who came to visit
and got confused on the directions. She stood outside his office
for half an hour, trying to figure out how to use the pay phone.
</P>
<P>
   When the Miami area went to 10-digit dialing, the posh
Fontainebleau hotel on Miami Beach sent letters to guests and
placed new phone cards in their rooms. But visitors are calling the
front desk in ever greater numbers, trying to learn how to dial.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few that are a little frustrated, like all of
us,'' said hotel spokeswoman Lisa Cole.
</P>
<P>
   While callers are adjusting to dialing more digits, the newly
created overlay codes remain virtually unknown. In eastern
Maryland, Bell Atlantic has assigned only about 6,100 numbers in
the new 443 overlay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen one of those numbers yet,'' said Self, author
of the book ``Long Distance for Less.'' ``They're supposedly giving
them out, but I've never had one to dial. I've never seen one
advertised.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston and Dallas will go one step further by actually erasing
area code boundaries. With telephone experts already looking toward
the day when 12- or even 15-digit dialing will be required, the
idea is to conserve the dwindling pool of numbers as much as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``You delay the date, to the absolute maximum, when you're going
to need the next area code,'' said Bill Adair, a Southwestern Bell
employee who is Texas' number administrator and the industry's
point man on the area code change.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy, suggested by a Southwestern Bell customer, has
raised eyebrows around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why in God's name would they erase that?'' asked Mark Cooper,
director of research for the Consumer Federation of America and a
longtime critic of overlay plans. ``The (Public Utility) Commission
has approved this stuff?''
</P>
<P>
   To get the word out about the area code changes, Southwestern
Bell and local business boosters are considering taking out ads on
pizza boxes, on grocery store bags and in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   They're planning to hand out fliers at the state fair, rent
billboard space and possibly draw up materials for children to
color on at restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   They've even come up with a slogan: ``Use 10 Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the media blitz will come soon enough for Houston
companies and consumers to make the change smoothly remains to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gowen, vice president of Alarm Data Corp. in Beltsville,
Md., said it took his company two years to contact customers and
adjust all their security systems to enable them to dial 10 digits.
</P>
<P>
   Elevator repair companies also must take action, since many of
their emergency phones must be reprogrammed.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that work in the Houston area, however, was completed
when the city split into two area codes.
</P>
<P>
   Houston-based Crimefighters of Texas Security reprogrammed all
of its alarms at that time to handle 10 digits, to ensure that all
customers' alarms could signal the company's monitoring station in
Channelview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pain in the butt, but we did it,'' said Jim Cassidy,
the company's owner.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Maryland regulators, the Public Utility Commission of
Texas opted not to allow callers to dial ``1'' when making a local
call. Commissioners reasoned they wanted Houston and Dallas callers
to understand exactly when they were making a local call and when
they would be calling long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   The overlay plans in Houston and Dallas will make dialing in
those areas different from dialing in the rest of Texas. In cities
such as Austin and San Antonio, callers still will dial only seven
digits to make a local call.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to create some uniformity within Texas, the
commission is considering requiring phone companies to allow
10-digit local dialing everywhere in Texas. This means in
communities where only seven digits are required to place a local
call, callers used to dialing 10 digits will be able to dial the
area code plus the number and still have the local call go through.
</P>
<P>
   Adair holds no illusions Houston residents will enjoy the
upcoming changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The area code relief is painful no matter how you do it,''
Adair said. But he promises: ``It's not as bad as it sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
