<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6525 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLANTAINS-ART-3TAKES-     07-28 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANTAINS-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PEEL TELLS THE STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To many Americans raised on eating sweet, mushy
bananas, it is difficult to imagine one that does not taste sweet
and needs to be cooked. But the plantain, a tropical fruit related
to the banana and of near miraculous variability, is spilling over
from bodegas and flooding into supermarkets and restaurants all
over New York.
</P>
<P>
   It is becoming so pervasive that it seems poised to join the
list of mainstream ingredients that were exotic not so long ago,
like cilantro, jalapenos and lemon grass.
</P>
<P>
   The plantain is surfacing on menus where you would never expect
to see it. At Park View at the Boathouse in Central Park, plantain
chips cozy up to a grouper club sandwich. Clementine, a downtown
restaurant with an eclectic menu, sometimes runs as a special
grilled octopus with a spicy plantain caper salad, a witty play on
a French potato salad.
</P>
<P>
   And at the Terrace on West 119th Street, a busy green chili
Caesar salad is sprinkled with crunchy plantain croutons and tuna
tartar.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the plantain such an extraordinary fruit is that it
can be treated as both a fruit and a vegetable. In one dish, it can
be tender, succulent and faintly sweet; in the next, stiff, starchy
and nutty. It is whatever you want it to be and is tremendously
forgiving in a pan, which is why chefs love it so much.
</P>
<P>
   Its taste and texture all depend on its stage of ripeness. A
plantain looks much like a banana but is slightly larger with
angular, faceted sides (it is sometimes called platano macho, or
``macho banana,'' in Spanish).
</P>
<P>
   It is harvested green, when it is starchy and has a firmness
like that of a hard rubber ball. A green plantain is much like a
potato, with a high starch content and mealy texture. It may be
baked or boiled, but the flesh, a creamy peach color, is usually
thinly sliced and fried to make chips or cut into thick slices for
the flat, fritterlike snacks called tostones. And because the sugar
content is low, it doesn't burn but browns evenly and stays
crunchy.
</P>
<P>
   As the plantain ripens, it's peel yellows and softens slightly
as the starch begins converting to sugar. A yellow plantain, tender
and more succulent with a mild, vegetal sweetness, reacts well to
boiling and mashing, sauteeing and baking.
</P>
<P>
   If allowed to sit long enough, a plantain will shrivel and
blacken. Frankly, it will look rotten and hopeless and will attract
fruit flies like crazy, but the yellow flesh inside will be like a
sweet, fragrant flower, touched with acidity. It is best for sweet
plantain mash.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, chefs are known for seeking out new, exotic
ingredients, but there is more to the growing interest in the
plantain than mere fad value. For starters, a compelling change in
demographics.
</P>
<P>
   According to the City Planning Department, the majority of
immigrants between 1982 and 1989 arrived from Asia, the Caribbean
and Latin America _ countries where the plantain is a fundamental
element of the diet. And imports of plantains nationally have
jumped nearly 25 percent during the last nine years, according to
the United States Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
   George Contos, a partner in the American Banana Company Inc., in
Hunts Point, the Bronx, said that his company's sales of plantains
over the last five years have increased about 30 percent. ``When
you consider the fact that it is a specialty item,'' he said,
``it's pretty amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Growth of the plantain business is part of a larger development
in the produce business, Contos said. ``What were considered
Spanish items are gaining popularity on a broader population
level,'' he said. ``Things that were considered ethnic are becoming
mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   But why are so many upscale restaurants suddenly paying
attention to the plantain? Many chefs thank Douglas Rodriguez, the
chef at Patria in the Flatiron district. When he opened his
restaurant in 1994, he introduced what he calls nuevo Latino
cooking to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Plantains appear everywhere on his menu. Long strips of fried
plantain are stuck like tusks into a mound of plantains mashed
coarsely with sauteed onion and bacon _ an African preparation
called fufu _ covered in a confetti of salsa. Shredded plantain
forms a crust on mahi-mahi, and long silky slices of steamed sweet
plantain are used to line a mold of quinoa.
</P>
<P>
   Having grown up in Miami, the son of Cuban immigrants, Rodriguez
cannot remember a family meal without plantains. ``If my father
didn't have rice and plantains with dinner,'' he said, ``it
wouldn't be dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   They say in Cuba that when a foreigner blends into the culture,
he has become aplatanado, or ``going native like a plantain,''
which though not native to the island or the Caribbean, has adapted
naturally to the local habitat. The plantain actually originated in
Southeast Asia, but it is so adaptable that it is grown abundantly
in warm climates around the world.
</P>
<P>
   It is equally adaptable in the kitchen, where the starchy and
succulent fruit has become a significant part of cuisines
throughout the tropics. It is so pervasive, said Elizabeth
Schneider, the author of ``Uncommon Fruits and Vegetables''
(William Morrow, 1998), that ``you can tell where someone is from
by the way they prepare their plantains.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Caribbean and Latin America, the plantain _ which is
higher in potassium and vitamin C than a banana and much higher in
vitamin A _ belongs to a group of starchy vegetables called
viandas, or ``staples'' in Spanish. Along with the breadfruit, taro
and malanga, among others, it forms the base of most meals. Which
is why some call the plantain the potato of the tropics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   But as easy as it is to compare it to the potato _ whose
versatility translates into infinite permutations of dishes in
Western cooking _ the plantain is actually quite different. It is
less earthy and more succulent, so it must be treated carefully
when it is mixed with dishes like, say, a hamburger.
</P>
<P>
   ``They function in a way that is amenable to cross-cultural
cooking because you can use a variety of spices,'' said Katy
Sparks, the chef at Quilty's in SoHo. ``It's like a sponge
absorbing flavors, but it has its own integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   John Schenk, the chef at Clementine, sees it just this way. In
his plantain caper salad, the assertive flavors of coriander and
green curry are mellowed by cubes of rich plantain. It wouldn't
work with potatoes. ``With plantains,'' he said, ``it's less of a
glaring mix.''
</P>
<P>
   The plantain turns up often with seafood, a kind of
meat-and-potatoes kinship in South American cooking.
</P>
<P>
   At Park View at the Boathouse, for instance, a tuna tartar,
bound with mango, cucumber and a curry mayonnaise, is paired with
steamed and fried plantains, like toast points. At One 3 in
Greenwich Village, slender, salty plantain chips are piled atop a
tower of raw oysters.
</P>
<P>
   Some chefs stretch the plantain-seafood theme a little further.
Patricia Williams, the chef at the City Wine and Cigar Company in
TriBeCa, for instance, pickles plantains and serves them as a sort
of relish with sauteed halibut and avocado puree.
</P>
<P>
   But most chefs do not stray so far from tradition. There is no
need to, really. Most traditional dishes, when prepared well, are
incredibly good. Who doesn't love dishes with names like fufu,
mofongo and patacones?
</P>
<P>
   Tostones, made from green plantains, are thickly sliced, fried
and then smashed flat with a plate or meat pounder and fried again.
They are crisp and chewy, and they make smart vehicles for hors
d'oeuvres.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Flay, the chef at Mesa Grill in the Flatiron district,
treats his like blinis with Latin blood, spooning salmon tartar and
an avocado relish on top of the rugged-looking, golden disks. Each
bite is at once crisp, silky, starchy and clean.
</P>
<P>
   At Patria, a Colombian dish called patacones pisados is served
with chicken. Whole peeled green plantains are steamed and then
rolled like pie dough with a rolling pin and fried again. Patacones
pisados, which means ``stepped on plantains'' in Spanish, are
usually served in a flat long oval, like the sole of a shoe,
Rodriguez said. He has manicured them a bit, cutting them into neat
triangles.
</P>
<P>
   At many small Latin American restaurants around the city, you
will come across _ in addition to tostones and fried plantains _ a
dish called mofongo. Though it is made in what seems to be 1,000
different ways, in Rodriguez's version, green plantains are braised
until tender and then sauteed with loads of garlic and lemon or
lime juice.
</P>
<P>
   As they saute, the plantains are mashed and tossed, much like a
potato hash, eventually forming a great, fragrant ball.
</P>
<P>
   Most common of all, though, are paper-thin strips of green
plantain _ sometimes the length of the fruit, sometimes a
cross-section _ fried in oil and seasoned with salt. It is a dish
rooted in nearly every tropical culture in which plantains are
grown, including southern India.
</P>
<P>
   There, the chips may be seasoned with curry leaves, chilies or
mustard seeds, said Madhur Jaffrey, who has written several books
on Indian cooking. She is working on a new book, ``Madhur Jaffrey's
World Vegetarian,'' to be published by Clarkson Potter next year
and to include several plantain recipes, like an Indian dish of
yogurt with plantains and mango.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my old books, I think I avoided plantains because I thought
it would be hard for people to find,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But that is certainly no longer the case. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLANTAIN CHIPS, FUFU AND SALSA  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Douglas Rodriguez's ``Nuevo Latino'' (Ten Speed
Press, 1995) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 cups canola oil
</P>
<P>
   2 green plantains, peeled and thinly sliced lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1 large cucumber, washed
</P>
<P>
   2 small tomatoes, seeded and cut into {-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1{ jalapeno chilies, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 medium red onion, cut into {-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces bacon, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, cut into {-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   3 brown plantains, peeled and cut into 1-inch cubes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare plantain chips: In deep fryer or heavy saucepan, heat
canola oil to 350 degrees. Add half of green plantains, one slice
at a time, and fry until golden brown and crisp, about 3 to 4
minutes. Drain on paper towels, and sprinkle with salt and garlic
powder to taste. Repeat with remaining green plantains. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Prepare salsa: Peel cucumber. Finely dice the peel, and place
it in medium mixing bowl. Reserve rest of cucumber for another use.
To mixing bowl add tomatoes, jalapeno, cilantro, red onion, lemon
juice, vinegar and olive oil. Season to taste with salt and pepper;
set aside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Prepare fufu: In skillet over medium-high heat, fry bacon
until crisp, about 4 to 5 minutes. Transfer to plate lined with
paper towels. Lower heat to medium, and add onion. Saute until
translucent, about 2 minutes. Add to plate of bacon, and set aside.
Fill large pan halfway with water, and bring to boil over high
heat. Add brown plantain cubes, reduce heat and simmer until
plantains are soft, about 15 minutes. Drain plantains, and transfer
them to large bowl. Using potato masher or fork, mash the
plantains. Fold in the bacon and onion, and season to taste with
salt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve: Mound fufu in center of large serving plate. Spoon
salsa on top of fufu, and press fried plantains into sides of mound
so that they curve upward like antlers. Serve immediately. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 appetizer servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   PLANTAIN BAKED IN ITS SKIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Uncommon Fruits and Vegetables'' &QL; 
by Elizabeth Schneider (William Morrow, 1998) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   4 medium yellowish brown plantains
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons lime juice, more to taste
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon pure mild chili powder, more to taste
</P>
<P>
   2{ tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt.
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat oven to 375 degrees. Trim ends from plantains. Cut a
lengthwise slit in each plantain. Place plantains slit-side up on
roasting pan, and bake in oven until creamy and tender, about 30 to
40 minutes. Remove plantains from oven, and let them cool slightly.
Leave oven on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Peel plantains, and cut them into {-inch-thick diagonal
slices. Place in ovenproof serving dish. Sprinkle with lime juice
and chili powder, and dab with butter. Season with salt. Toss
gently. Return to oven, and heat through, about 10 minutes. Serve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   YOGURT WITH PLANTAIN AND MANGO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Madhur Jaffrey's World Vegetarian'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   to be published next year by Clarkson Potterindexed in main
story &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 25 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 medium yellow plantain, peeled and cut into }-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon yellow split peas (chana dal)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon whole brown mustard seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 hot, dried, red chilies, halved
</P>
<P>
   15 fresh curry leaves or basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 medium shallot, peeled and cut into fine slivers
</P>
<P>
   3 thin slices of fresh, peeled ginger cut into fine shreds
</P>
<P>
   1 cup }-inch diced mango. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place plantain in small pan. Cover with water, and bring to
boil. Cover, reduce heat to low and cook until plantain is tender,
about 10 to 15 minutes. Drain, and set aside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. In small bowl, beat yogurt with fork until smooth and creamy.
Slowly add 1 cup water and the salt. Stir to mix, and set aside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Put oil in small, deep frying pan, and set over medium heat.
When oil becomes hot, put in the split peas. Stir until peas just
start to turn reddish. Add mustard seeds. As soon as seeds begin to
pop, a matter of seconds, add red chilies. Stir once, and add curry
leaves. Stir again, and then add shallot and ginger. Reduce heat to
medium-low. Stir and fry shallot and ginger until golden, about 2
minutes. Add this to the yogurt, and stir to combine. Add diced
plantain and mango. Stir to mix. Serve at room temperature or cold
with steamed basmati rice. As you are eating, discard curry leaves
as you come across them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOSTONES WITH SALMON TARTARE AND AVOCADO-CHIPOTLE RELISH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Bobby Flay, the chef at Mesa Grill &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh sushi-quality salmon, cut into \-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   \ cup drained capers
</P>
<P>
   \ cup finely chopped scallions
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped cilantro, plus some leaves for
garnish
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons pureed canned chipotle peppers
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe Haas avocados, peeled and pitted
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lime juice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons creme fraiche or lightly whipped heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   3 cups peanut oil or canola oil
</P>
<P>
   2 green plantains, each sliced crosswise into 4 pieces and then
peeled
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare salmon tartare: In small mixing bowl, combine salmon,
mustard, capers, scallions, chopped cilantro, olive oil and 1
tablespoon of the chipotles. Mix well. Season to taste with salt
and pepper. Refrigerate until ready to serve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Prepare avocado-chipotle relish: In medium mixing bowl,
combine avocados, lime juice and remaining tablespoon of chipotles.
Mash with fork until blended but not quite smooth. Season to taste
with salt and pepper. Fold in creme fraiche until mixture has a
marbled appearance. Refrigerate until ready to serve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Prepare Tostones: In deep, heavy skillet, heat peanut oil to
325 degrees. Add half of the plantain quarters, and fry without
stirring until bottom halves are golden brown, about 2 minutes.
Turn quarters, and fry an additional 2 minutes. Remove, and drain
on paper towels. Repeat with remaining plantains. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. Increase temperature of oil to 375 degrees. Using meat
pounder or other heavy object, flatten each plantain slice until [
inch thick. Return tostones to skillet, and fry tostones until
golden-brown and crisp, about 1 minute a side. Drain on paper
towels, and sprinkle with kosher salt to taste. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. To serve, place each tostone in middle of a small plate, and
top with 1 heaping tablespoon of salmon tartare. Top salmon with 1
teaspoon Avocado-Chipotle Relish, and garnish with cilantro leaf.
Serve immediately. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 appetizer servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLANTAIN CAPER SALAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from John Schenk, the chef at Clementine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes, plus about 20 minutes' cooling time &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 head garlic, unpeeled and split
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon coriander seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   2 large yellow (still a little green) plantains
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons capers, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon green curry paste, available at Asian and Indian
markets
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   One-third teaspoon chopped thyme. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In medium nonreactive saucepan, combine 4 cups water with
vinegar, garlic, bay leaves, thyme sprigs, coriander, peppercorns
and salt. Bring to simmer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Trim ends from plantains, leaving rest of peels intact. Add
plantains to simmering liquid; cook until tender, about 20 minutes.
Remove from heat, and let cool in liquid. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Remove plantains from liquid; peel, and cut them into \-inch
cubes. In stainless-steel, glass or ceramic salad bowl, combine
plantains, capers and shallots. Stir to mix. In another bowl,
combine lemon juice, curry paste, olive oil and chopped thyme. Stir
until smooth. Add to plantains; stir to mix. Serve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
