<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6540 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MENUS-NYT &LR;      07-28 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MENUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MENU AS PUZZLE: ROLLING THE `EEL DICE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The day my friend ate a chicken foot from a dim sum
cart was the day she swore never to order anything unless she had
seen it on a menu first. ``If only it had been written down,'' she
kept saying. ``I never would have ordered it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily. Anyone who's been dining out at some of the
newest New York restaurants recently might have noticed that the
menu has become a rather puzzling document.
</P>
<P>
   Buttons of milkweed?
</P>
<P>
   Mint love letters?
</P>
<P>
   Hot eel dice?
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Granted, some of the items do speak for themselves even if they
don't sound particularly appetizing _ to me, at least. Beef cheek
ravioli with crushed squab liver sounds like something that should
be reported to the ASPCA. And I think the operative word in hot eel
dice is eel; hot or cold, sliced or diced, this creature is not
going into my mouth.
</P>
<P>
   But it does seem that the newest rage about town is a menu so
special, so exclusive, that even you, the special, exclusive diner
who is paying for the privilege, has no idea what you are about to
eat. If you're among friends, you can always barrage the waiter
with inquiries as to what exactly is happening inside the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   But what if you're with clients? Do you want to admit that you _
sophisticated diner that you are _ not only don't know that spruce
tips are buds harvested from the evergreen tree people put presents
under each December, but also that you're not all that interested
in widening your culinary horizons quite that far?
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the late 1990s, where the 1980s Menu as Treasure Hunt
(baby lettuce from Indiana, wild salmon from Canada, purple
potatoes from Maine) has given way to Menu as Rorschach Test: Does
``wilted lamb's-quarters'' refer to the animal after an
exceptionally hard day on the range? Or when you discover it's only
lettuce, does your misconception reveal more about your own day at
the office than you want your guests to know?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a little intimidation factor going on here,'' says
Clark Wolf, a food and restaurant consultant based in New York.
``In the 80's menus were about whimsy, which pedigreed ingredients
came from which side of the creek. In the 90s it's about obscurity.
There's such a manic race to imitate Jean-Georges and Gray Kunz.
And the irony is that at Jo Jo, Jean George's other restaurant, the
menu says Cod. Salmon. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Loffredo, an owner of Cena on East 22nd Street, home of
the spruce tips and the milkweed buttons, maintains that his chef,
Normand Laprise, wants only to expose customers to exciting new
ingredients. ``But,'' Loffredo admitted, ``there is another side to
the coin. I think to some degree restaurants now are trying to push
the shock factor. It's clearly a marketing decision. They want to
show how cutting edge they can make the menu, to tweak interest as
much as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Falcinelli, the chef at Moomba on Seventh Avenue South,
disagreed. ``The cooking world looks to New York to see what
ingredients we're using,'' he said. ``Farmers from Ohio or
Pennysylvania come to New York where someone will give something a
shot before anyone else tries it. It's good to educate people.
Chefs want to express what's on their minds. Sometimes it works,
sometimes it doesn't. But in New York, when you practice your
craft, you know you're where people appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Falcinelli's own menu is relatively straightforward, though he
calls cockles ``cockle clams.'' ``It's just to let people know that
cockles are like clams,'' he says. ``They're still bivalves.'' And
the ``natural lamb essence'' that accompanies the roasted rack of
Australian lamb is nothing more than a reduction. ``But when you
say reduction, people think it's thick or syrupy,'' he said. ``This
is just the juice cooked down to the pure essence of lamb flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Some chefs admit to extending their creativity past the bounds
of the kitchen. For his menu at Asia de Cuba on Madison Avenue,
Eric Basulto invented the word ``tunapica'' to describe his version
of tuna tartare. ``Picario is a simmered meat dish with capers,
olives, currants and almonds that is usually used for stuffing
empanadas,'' he said ``We've come up with tunapica to mean it's
tuna tartare made with picario ingredients.''
</P>
<P>
   At Babbo, a new restaurant on Waverly Place, the chef, Mario
Batali, says his mint love letters are ravioli folded in the shape
of a letter. ``I invented the name,'' he said. ``I love mint. It's
like a kiss. And it kind of makes sense. It's got a sweet little
story inside. But items like this on the menu also invite a
discussion between the service staff and the customer. Granted,
some people don't want an intellectual conversation about the
ingredients; they just want dinner. But the questions can bring
about an interesting conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Or stop one. When I called Chris Johnson, the manager of Bond
Street, which lists the hot eel dice in the sushi roll section of
the menu, I told him I assumed the eel was diced and served hot
inside the roll. Not exactly, he said. ``It is hot as in
temperature, but instead of putting the eel and avocado on the
inside, we top the roll with eel and sprinkle it with almonds. The
chef thinks they look like dice.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh.
</P>
<P>
   I think I'll stick with the Christmas tree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
