<SLUG> BC-CASINO-RESTAURANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODDS OF A GOOD MEAL IN LAS VEGAS ARE RISING  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jean-Georges Vongerichten and Charles Palmer, two top
New York chefs, have joined other prominent restaurateurs in in
responding to the lure of Las Vegas, Nev. Vongerichten of Jean
Georges, Vong and Jo Jo, and Palmer, of Aureole, the Lennox Room
and Alva, will be running restaurants in two new hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Vongerichten is opening Prime, a steakhouse, in the Bellagio
hotel that is to open on Oct. 17. Bellagio, which is owned by Steve
Wynn, will also have branches of Le Cirque 2000 and Osteria del
Circo from New York, both of which will be run by Marc Poidevin,
the chef de cuisine at Le Cirque 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer will open a branch of Aureole in the new Mandalay Bay
hotel that is planned for the spring; the restaurant will be
designed by Adam Tihany.
</P>
<P>
   These chefs are part of a second wave. They follow those already
established in Las Vegas like Wolfgang Puck, with Chinois and Spago
at Caesar's, Emeril Lagasse who has Emeril's New Orleans Fish House
in the MGM Grand, Jean-Louis Palladin, with Napa in the Rio Casino
and Hotel, and Mark Miller's Coyote Cafe, also in the MGM Grand.
</P>
<P>
   With all their trophy chefs, each of the new mega hotels in Las
Vegas are increasingly offering microcosms of the American dining
scene. And their customers never have to step out of the air
conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said he was persuaded to open a restaurant in Las Vegas
by the city's growing market for convention business, instead of
just gamblers, and by a contract that gave him full control of his
restaurants, which will include a wine bar and the Aureole Swan
Court, a smaller restaurant. Mandalay Bay will also have a China
Grill restaurant and cafe, and a House of Blues. The hotel, owned
by Circus Circus, is planning a high-end Italian restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   In a city already overrun with steakhouses, and where Smith &AMP;
Wollensky will open a place, Vongerichten's decision to open Prime
may seem surprising. He said the hotel offered him a choice between
fish or steak. ``I thought steak would be simpler for us,'' he
said. ``It's a new challenge but I'm doing it with eight different
kinds of potatoes and all kinds of sauces, so it will be totally
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellagio will also have a Petrossian boutique and a La Brea
Bakery from Los Angeles, as well as branches of Olives from Boston,
Aqua from San Francisco, and Picasso, a spinoff of Masa's, also
from San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Another hotel, the Venetian, which is being built on the site of
the Sands, has signed Joachim Splichal of Los Angeles to create
Patina-Pinot, Lagasse to open Delmonico's New Orleans Steak House
and Piero Selvaggio of Los Angeles for a branch of Valentino. Bill
Weidner, the president, said they are close to signing with Stephan
Pyles' Star Canyon from Dallas, and, from Paris, the venerable
Laduree patisserie.
</P>
<P>
   A contract with Nobu for an outpost in the Hard Rock Hotel is
under negotiation. And the Paris Las Vegas hotel being developed by
the Hilton Hotels Corp. has been talking to Alain Ducasse, the
Michelin-starred French chef.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
