<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6573 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT &LR;      07-28 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 WINE TALK: WHERE THE LISTS ARE LONG AND THE PRICES ARE LOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ To sports lovers, this Bergen County
town is strictly a stadium for football, an arena for basketball
and a track for horses, cheek by jowl in a former swamp known as
the Meadowlands. The real town, which few fans ever see, is a mile
or two west, a gritty enclave dominated by the roar of Route 17,
the old truck route that cuts through it. It is also an unlikely
mecca for wine lovers.
</P>
<P>
   Almost lost among the small factories and auto-body shops are
two restaurants _ Park and Orchard, and Sonoma Grill _ that just
happen to make East Rutherford the best place in New Jersey,
perhaps in the entire New York metropolitan area, to eat well and
drink truly exceptional wines at bargain prices.
</P>
<P>
   Both are owned and run by dedicated and knowledgeable wine
experts, a quality extremely rare in the restaurant business. These
men are in the business as much to indulge and communicate their
personal fascination with wine as they are to offer good food and
hospitality. The locations may not be chic and may even be out of
the way. But as they say in the Michelin red guide, both
restaurants are worth a detour.
</P>
<P>
   Park and Orchard, which is almost 20 years old, got its name
from its first location, the intersection of Park and Orchard
Streets, just a few blocks from the present site, a cavernous
former machine shop at 240 Hackensack St.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the restaurant was vegetarian, but eventually fish
was added to the menu, then poultry. There is still no red meat,
except for private parties.
</P>
<P>
   What there is plenty of is wine, and most but not all of it is
on the 126-page wine list. ``There is a lot more,'' said Buddy
Gebhardt, the owner, ``but I really don't see how I can fit it on
the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Gebhardt is a hopeless burgundy addict. Once he added $200,000
worth of new burgundies every year. No longer. ``I bought the 1990
Leroys,'' he said, referring to Domaine Leroy, the prestigious
burgundy house, ``but none since. The prices are too outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that his customers need worry; the selection is still
staggering. Some of the finest burgundies come from the Clos
Vougeot, and Park and Orchard offers 43, from the 1983 through 1990
vintages and from producers like Meo-Camuzet, Jean Grivot,
Mongeard-Mugneret, Daniel Rion and Georges Roumier.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 Clos Vougeot from Grivot is $83 at Park and Orchard,
the 1985 from Rion is $100 and the 1989 from Jacky Confuron is $75.
There is also a 1983 Clos de la Marechale from Faiveley, at $50; a
1985 Vosne-Romanee Les Brulees from Rene Engel, at $75; a 1983 Clos
de la Roche from Domaine Dujac, at $75, and a 1990 Morey-St.-Denis
Les Sorbets from Domaine Serveau, at $45.
</P>
<P>
   To the occasional drinker, these prices may seem high, but in
fact each of these wines could command $20 to $50 more a bottle in
some Manhattan restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   California wine fans are not slighted at Park and Orchard. Helen
Turley's 1996 Black Sears zinfandel is $65, the 1994 Pahlmeyer
merlot is $57 and the 1986 Diamond Creek Red Rock cabernet
sauvignon is $70. Gebhardt annotates each of his wine selections.
For the Diamond Creek, he wrote: ``For those of you who like
gigantic wines. You must call me hours in advance so I can decant
it.''
</P>
<P>
   John Foy, the owner of Sonoma Grill, has his own wine story to
tell. As a Peace Corps volunteer in Jamaica from 1969 to 1971, he
started experimenting with the island's wines. Later, as an
accountant in Belgium, he began to appreciate fine food and
eventually became a sous-chef at the ``21'' Club in New York. In
1976, he opened the Tarragon Tree in Meyersville, N.J., with his
brother Dennis; later, he opened Les Delices in Whippany, N.J.
Then, in 1992, he opened Sonoma Grill at 64 Hoboken Road.
</P>
<P>
   Foy's interest in wine extends well beyond his restaurant. He
publishes his own newsletter, John Foy's Wine Odyssey, and writes a
weekly wine column for The Bergen Record. His wine cellar may not
be as extensive as Park and Orchard's but he has a different
viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy has breadth,'' Foy said of his colleague a few blocks
away. ``I try for depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, his cabernet sauvignons include 13 vintages from
Stag's Leap Wine Cellars, 9 from Sterling Vineyards and 8 from
Beaulieu Vineyards Private Reserve. His Mondavi Reserve cabernets
go back to 1975, and his Heitz Cellars Martha's Vineyard cabernets
to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Sonoma Grill offers 10 wine tastings a year and twice-a-month
wine dinners. It is also noted for its sales. This summer, for
example, Foy is offering a 25 percent discount on all California
cabernets from the 1984 vintage and older. The same reduction
applies to burgundies from 1985 and older and Bordeaux from 1983
and older, with the exception of the 1982's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm already lower than anyone else on 1982,'' he said. ``I
can't go down any more. Our prices on mature wines, from 1990 and
earlier, are anywhere from a third to a half of prices on
comparable lists in New York. On younger wines, I'm 25 percent
lower.''
</P>
<P>
   Foy's customers prefer California cabernet and merlot. ``The
dividing line is clear,'' he said. ``The under-40 crowd drinks only
California. They'll pay $80 for a California wine and ignore a
better French wine at half the price. I'll say to a customer, `Try
this Pomerol,' and he'll wave it off, saying, `I don't know
anything about that stuff.' If I explain that it's 100 percent
merlot, I'll get: `Really? Maybe I'll try it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Both Park and Orchard and Sonoma Grill benefit from the crowds
at the Meadowlands, but neither owner thinks of his place as a
sports restaurant. Both have knowledgeable clients who come over
from New York because of the extensive wine lists and relatively
low prices, but neither caters only to wine sophisticates.
Gebhardt's wine list starts off with two pages of wines for $25 or
less, and both restaurants offer lots of wines by the glass.
</P>
<P>
   Park and Orchard's menu features lighter fare. Sonoma Grill
offers two menus, a modern American selection and one emphasizing
broiled meats. Park and Orchard's phone number is (201) 939-9292;
Sonoma Grill's is (201) 507-8989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
