NYT-07-28-98 1642EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6591 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIX-EN-PROVENCE-FEST-     07-28 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIX-EN-PROVENCE-FEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FESTIVAL THAT GIVES YOUNG ARTISTS A CHANCE TO GROW  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AIX-EN-PROVENCE, France _ The magnet of big names _ Peter Brook,
Claudio Abbado, Pierre Boulez and Pina Bausch among them _ drew
many visitors to Aix-en-Provence this month for France's best-known
summer opera festival. Once here, however, some operagoers wondered
whether they had landed by mistake at a youth jamboree. The veteran
stars were delighted. Things had gone according to plan.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1948 and floundering in the mid-1990s, the Aix
festival was reborn this year around the idea of giving young
singers and instrumentalists the chance to work with top
conductors, stage directors and soloists. To give structure to the
experiment, Stephane Lissner, the festival's director, created a
European Music Academy and invited 53 musicians under the age of 35
to attend its opening season.
</P>
<P>
   But the purpose was more practical than pedagogic. The academy
members were chosen both for their talent as musicians and their
lack of professional experience as performers. What they learned
from assorted maestros during long rehearsals in Aix was then put
to the test in recitals, concerts and opera productions. And they
performed before paying audiences that were not about to make
allowances for youth.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Lissner's long-term strategy of creating the
next generation of opera talent, the academy's two productions,
Purcell's ``Dido and Aeneas'' and Britten's ``Curlew River,'' were
well received by both public and critics. Indeed, if the youth of
the performers was evident in the events, which will end on July
31, it was through the verve and energy they brought to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had to learn to handle myself under a lot of
pressure,'' said Rinat Shaham, 25, an Israeli-born mezzo-soprano
who sang the role of Dido. ``Having the main role, I feel the show
rests on my shoulders. I'm expected to be excellent every time. And
the exposure is unbelievable. Basically everyone comes here _
directors, critics, conductors, a great audience.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 13 singers and 15 instrumentalists involved in the
academy's two operas this year, more experience lies ahead when the
two productions tour 16 European cities from February to May next
year. ``In some ways, meeting musicians from all over the world is
the best thing about this,'' said Marc Thayer, 27, an American
violinist who has played in the Miami-based New World Symphony for
the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Among the guides for these two operas were the American
conductor David Stern, the British tenor Robert Tear and the
Japanese actor Yoshi Oida, who belongs to Brook's Paris-based
experimental theater company and who directed ``Curlew River.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a desperately needed moment,'' explained Stern, 35,
who is music director for this year's academy. ``Too many kids come
out of conservatory without knowing what awaits them. This gives
them a chance to step back before they ply into a career.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight other singers participated in a workshop on Mozart's
``Zauberfloete,'' but again this was not an academic exercise.
Working with the veteran French soprano Regine Crespin, Stern and a
rising French director, Stephane Braunschweig, they have been
preparing the production of ``Die Zauberfloete'' that will be
presented at next year's festival. And to expose them to an
audience, several rehearsals have been open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Another group, with 12 young singers, formed the chorus in
Brook's production of ``Don Giovanni,'' and they will join a
five-nation tour of the opera from August through January. These
singers, all planning careers as soloists, have also learned the
individual roles in ``Don Giovanni'' in hope of taking over a
leading part when the production is revived here next year.
</P>
<P>
   Even five young composers were able to hear their new works,
commissioned by the academy, performed in concert.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if the academy did not become a sort of youth wing to the
main festival, it was because young people were everywhere. The two
casts for ``Don Giovanni'' comprised experienced singers, but there
was not a gray hair among them. Accompanying them in the pit were
musicians of the newly formed Mahler Chamber Orchestra, all between
the ages of 22 and 28. For Bartok's ``Bluebeard's Castle,'' which
was directed by Ms. Bausch, Boulez conducted the Gustav Mahler
Youth Orchestra, whose instrumentalists were even younger, between
16 and 24.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was Daniel Harding who best personified the festival's
spirit of bringing young and old together. A slightly built,
fair-haired Briton who looks even younger than his 22 years,
Harding shared the responsibility of conducting ``Don Giovanni''
with Abbado, more than 40 years his senior. And he held his own, in
the view of critics, precisely because he did not try to imitate
the maestro.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think Claudio would come along and tell me how to do
things, but he hasn't,'' Harding said. ``It's incredible how he can
be so open and flexible. The main differences are in tempi. Anyway,
it's not interesting to have a star conductor and a little person
who comes along to copy. You're better off with the real thing. If
they have me, better to let me do it my way.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, Abbado is famous for encouraging young musicians.
He founded both the Gustav Mahler Youth Orchestra and the Mahler
Chamber Orchestra and, in 1995, invited Harding to be his
assistant. By then, though, the young Oxford-born conductor had
already cut his teeth working with Simon Rattle and the City of
Birmingham Symphony Orchestra. He is now principal guest conductor
of the Trondheim Symphony Orchestra in Norway and next year will
become music director of the Deutsch Kammer Orchestra in Bremen.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, more even than being acclaimed after conducting ``Don
Giovanni,'' Harding considers his strongest experience this summer
to have been working with Brook during two months of rehearsals.
``I think we're all spoiled, me in particular,'' he said, ``that my
first outing into opera should involve learning Peter's theatrical
way of working. He would be there as a kind of guiding light for
everyone. It's very hard to be nervous working with Peter because
he always makes you feel so secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Other young performers also appreciated the opportunities
offered by the long rehearsal time. ``It was very rewarding working
with Yoshi Oida,'' said Michael Bennett, 32, a Briton whose
performance as the Madwoman in ``Curlew River'' was widely praised.
``He didn't want us to act. The Madwoman is a very traumatized
character. He made me believe I could convey this without showing
it to the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was also ``incredibly stimulating'' to be counseled
by Tear, who sang the Madwoman in Britten's first production of the
opera. ``Without knowing it, your standard is raised,'' Bennett
said. ``I hope that when this is over I will sit down and think
about all we have done here and let it feed through to my work from
now on. And, yes, I'd like to come back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1644EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
