<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      07-28 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORN CREPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The crepe's reputation has suffered lately. The crepe is widely
seen as old-fashioned, but the truth is that it has a lot going for
it, no matter what fashion may be dictating at the moment. It is
delicate in flavor and texture, so it allows the personality of the
filling to emerge cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   A blessing for the cook is that a crepe, unlike a tortilla, is
easily made from scratch. Tortillas involve rolling or pressing,
the kinds of activity that benefit from years of practice. Crepes
are quicker to make and more forgiving; most troubles can be fixed
by adjusting the amount of batter in the pan or thinning it with a
little water.
</P>
<P>
   This dish was inspired by one of my favorite enchilada recipes.
The wrap is a corn-flavor crepe. The filling is nothing more than
fresh corn, stripped from the cob and sauteed with onion, zucchini
and seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   But the true star of this dish is mole, a dazzling, nuanced
Mexican sauce that contains ground red chili, spices, Mexican
chocolate and a bit of vinegar (you'll find the chili and the
chocolate in stores selling Mexican or Southwestern ingredients).
</P>
<P>
   Ground chili is a natural thickener, so it binds the sauce and
gives it body. If you use a mild chili powder, which I call for,
you'll find the sauce hot but not at all fiery. The chocolate
further mellows the mole while adding complexity. Don't expect to
taste the chocolate, though; it disappears as it harmonizes with
the other ingredients. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CORN CREPES WITH RED CHILI MOLE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 15 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   One-thir cup cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   1\ cups milk
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   2 large or extra-large eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons melted and cooled butter, plus extra for cooking
the crepes
</P>
<P>
   \ cup raisins, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup pignoli nuts
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (about 2 ounces) grated goat cheddar or other cheddar
cheese
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons coriander seed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon anise seed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cumin seed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried Mexican oregano
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons canola or sunflower seed oil
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups minced onion
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup mild ground chili
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce Mexican chocolate, chopped
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon sherry vinegar, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced zucchini
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh corn kernels
</P>
<P>
   { cup creme fraiche or very lightly beaten heavy cream. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a medium bowl, combine flour, cornmeal, milk and {
teaspoon salt; blend well. Add the eggs and melted butter, and mix
until smooth. Place a 6- to 8-inch nonstick skillet over medium
heat. When it is hot enough for a drop of water to skitter over the
surface, add about { teaspoon butter. Ladle a scant \ cup batter
into the skillet, and swirl to form a thin layer; pour any excess
back into the bowl. When the top of the crepe is dry, after about 1
minute, turn, and cook the other side 15 to 30 seconds. The crepe
should brown only slightly; it should not be crisp. Put it on a
plate. Repeat the process, adding butter as needed. The cooked
crepes should make a stack of 12.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cover raisins with warm water, and set aside. Place a dry
skillet over medium heat. Put in pignoli nuts, and stir or shake
the pan until they begin to brown; transfer immediately to a small
bowl. Drain the raisins, and squeeze gently to remove excess
liquid. Add raisins to the bowl of pignoli nuts, along with cheese
and cilantro; set aside. In a dry skillet, combine coriander seed,
anise, cumin and oregano. Cook over medium heat, stirring, until
fragrant, about 2 minutes. Transfer to a spice grinder, and grind
to a powder; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. To prepare the mole, place a medium saucepan over medium-high
heat; add 3 tablespoons oil. When oil is hot, add { cup onion.
Saute, stirring, until it just begins to brown. Add 1 teaspoon
garlic, and stir for 1 minute. Stir in the reserved spice mix, and
remove from heat. Add chili powder and 1{ cups water. Return pan to
medium heat, and slowly bring to a boil, stirring frequently. Add
chocolate and 1 teaspoon salt. Reduce heat to low. Simmer,
stirring, for about 5 minutes. Add vinegar, adjust seasonings, and
keep warm until serving.
</P>
<P>
   4. Place a skillet over medium heat, and add the remaining 2
tablespoons oil. When oil is hot, add the remaining 1 cup onion,
and saute until onion is translucent. Add the remaining 1 teaspoon
garlic, zucchini and 1 tablespoon water. Saute until zucchini is
tender, about 5 minutes; add corn. Cook, stirring, about 5 minutes;
remove from heat. Stir in raisin-pignoli mixture.
</P>
<P>
   5. Heat the oven to 400 degrees. To assemble, place about 2
tablespoons of filling on one quadrant of a crepe. Flatten the
filling slightly, fold the crepe over, and place 1 tablespoon of
filling on the crepe covering the original portion of filling. Fold
again, and tuck a tablespoon of filling into the fold that was just
made. The finished crepe will be folded into quarters, with three
pockets of filling. Place the crepes on a baking sheet, and bake
until heated through, about 10 minutes. To serve, place two or
three crepes on each plate, and top with a spoonful of mole and a
little creme fraiche.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
