<HEADER>
A6622 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT &LR;      07-28 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thai Marketplace Replaces A Korean Restaurant
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bop, the little Korean restaurant that Brad Kelley
opened last December at 179 Prince St. (Thompson Street), was such
a success that he closed it a month ago. He knows what he's doing:
he is moving it to a bigger location at 325 Bowery (Second Street).
He has converted the Bop space into Kin Khao Market, a takeout
shop, food market and cafe specializing in the Southeast Asian
dishes served at Kin Khao, Kelley's Thai restaurant a block away on
Spring Street.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the heat, the Kin Khao Market can coax appetites with a
tangy green mango salad showered with toasted coconut, a
chili-flecked tuna salad with a whiff of lemon grass, and a Thai
beef salad refreshed with cucumbers. Salads are $5.50 to $7.95.
Curries, satays, steamed dumplings, Mongolian barbecue and
sandwiches like Thai grilled chicken are served at the counters at
lunchtime. In the afternoon, ingredients that are peeled, sliced
and ready to go into the wok are sold, with recipes and seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   Kin Khao Market will also cater.
</P>
<P>
   Thin Sardinian Bread
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The thinnest kind of flatbread, so fragile it is one
step from phyllo, is Sardinian carasau, or sheet-music bread, and
it is now available in packages (top, center). Triangular pane
carasau, made by a consortium of wheat growers on Sardinia, comes
plain, in whole wheat or sprinkled with olive oil and salt. Its
crispness is enhanced by a brief warming in an oven. Sardinians
serve it broken into pieces, which is the way you may find some of
the sheets in the box. A slightly thicker rectangular variety, pane
pistoccu, can be layered with tomato sauce and cheese and baked
like lasagna.
</P>
<P>
   Pane carasau is $3.50 to $4.50 for a 250-gram package (about
nine ounces) and $5.50 to $7 for 500 grams (17 ounces). Pane
pistoccu comes in a 500-gram box and is $4.75 to $5.50. Some stores
that have the breads are Todaro Brothers, 555 Second Ave. (30th
Street); Amish Market East, 240 E. 45th St.; Dean &AMP; DeLuca, 560
Broadway (Prince Street); A. Razzano Salumeria, 287 School St.,
Glen Cove, N.Y., and Wheat Fields, 82 Mill Hill Road, Woodstock,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Caramel Success
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico and South America, caramel is not always made by
cooking sugar. Often, the process is to heat cow or goat milk
slowly until it thickens to a sweetly concentrated, honey-colored
confection. Haagen-Dazs has borrowed from this recipe for a new
flavor of ice cream, dulce de leche, whose success has taken the
company a bit by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The caramel ice cream, which is aswirl with darker, slightly
more bitter caramel, was developed for the Argentine market, then
introduced last fall in parts of New York and other North American
cities that have large Hispanic populations. The flavor did so well
_ in Miami it outsold the company's vanilla ice cream _ that
Haagen-Dazs is now introducing it to broader markets around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go out on a limb and say it could be the most successful
new flavor introduction we have ever done,'' said Vivien Godfrey, a
vice president of Haagen-Dazs. ``It's flying off the shelves in
markets where there is no major Hispanic presence.''
</P>
<P>
   And no wonder. Dulce de leche is richly beguiling, and
unencumbered by distracting bits of candy or chunks of cookie. The
price is $3.50 to $4.25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
