<HEADLINE>
A MUSSEL DISH WITH ADVENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: recipes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a whole world of steamed mussels beyond white wine,
parsley and garlic. Don't misunderstand: you can't go wrong with
this traditional approach. But you can't go too far with it,
either.
</P>
<P>
   With favorites like mussels, a little adventure takes no more
effort than the tried-and-true. The basic trick is to use
distinctive Asian seasonings like ginger, soy or curry powder. And
to omit the cooking liquid, to make the sauce more intense. Mussels
generate so much good-tasting broth of their own during cooking
that additional liquid is superfluous. By relying only on the
mussels' natural juices, you can use fewer seasonings (and less of
them) to produce a flavorful sauce that is also less watery than
the usual one. These are mussels to eat on a flat plate, rather
than in a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, any mussel recipe will work equally well for
clams. If you're clam-minded rather than mussel-minded, you'd do
best to avoid steamers (which tend to be sandy) and instead go for
littlenecks _ small hard-shell clams, the kind served on the half
shell and used for good pasta with clam sauce. Figure on one and a
half to two pounds of clams for each pound of mussels, and you'll
need to strain the cooking liquid, since the shells may be sandy
even after washing.
</P>
<P>
   When cleaning mussels or hard-shell clams, discard any with
broken shells. Clams must be shut tight before cooking; mussels may
be open, but their shells should close when lightly tapped (if they
don't close, discard them). If the mussels have beards _ hairy
vegetative growth attached to the shell _ trim them off. Those
clams or mussels that remain closed after the majority have been
steamed open can be pried open with a knife (a butter knife works
fine) at the table.
</P>
<P>
   If you use soy, the sauce becomes a lovely shade of mahogany;
with curry, it's stunningly yellow. Either way, these are mussel
dishes that are better served with rice than with bread.
</P>
<P>
   STEAMED MUSSELS WITH SOY
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peanut or canola oil
</P>
<P>
   \ cup roughly chopped scallions
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon roughly chopped ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, lightly smashed
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds mussels (or 6 to 8 pounds hard-shell clams), well
washed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon soy sauce.
</P>
<P>
   1. Put oil in saucepan large enough for all of the mussels. Turn
heat to medium. One minute later, add scallions, ginger and garlic.
Cook, stirring occasionally, for about a minute.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add mussels, turn heat to high, and cover pot. Cook, shaking
pot occasionally, until all (or nearly all) of them open, about 10
minutes. Turn off heat.
</P>
<P>
   3. Scoop mussels into serving bowl. Add soy sauce to liquid, and
then pass liquid through a fine strainer (or a coarse strainer
lined with cheesecloth). Pour liquid over mussels, and serve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Variation: For Curried Steamed Mussels, substitute 2 tablespoons
butter for the oil. Substitute \ cup shallots for the scallions,
and omit the ginger and garlic. When shallots soften, sprinkle them
with 1 teaspoon curry powder, and cook, stirring, for another 30
seconds. Cook, and finish as above, substituting the juice of 1
lime for the soy sauce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
