<SLUG> BC-NEGOTIATOR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE NEGOTIATOR': WHEN A NICE GUY HOLDS SOMEONE HOSTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(th) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a twist on the Hitchcockian maxim, ``The Negotiator'' places
two extraordinary actors, Samuel L. Jackson and Kevin Spacey, in
the midst of surprisingly ordinary circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   And considering how well-known they are for delivering wildly
colorful dialogue with deadpan panache, it is no less unexpected to
find them cast as blandly nice guys. Though the film has its basis
in an actual event that took place in St. Louis, it takes on the
homogeneous look of many other thrillers in which an emergency
escalates into a paramilitary operation.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of close-ups, exaggeratedly tense moments and blue-lighted
nighttime scenes guarantee that ``The Negotiator'' will be right at
home on video some day.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, both Jackson and Spacey are cast as friendly,
pleasant family men and team players. Both also happen to be
tip-top hostage negotiators, well versed in the art of agreeing to
crazy demands so as to outsmart terrorists and persuade them to
surrender.
</P>
<P>
   What a high-concept turning of the tables it is, then, to find
Jackson's Danny Roman, a Chicago police officer, forced to become a
hostage-taker himself. An elaborate though predictable scheme has
Danny framed by other officers for stealing from the policemen's
disability fund. Under this pressure, he goes crazy-like-a-fox
berserk in order to prove his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   As directed with brisk, matter-of-fact momentum by F. Gary Gray
(``Set It Off''), ``The Negotiator'' has the unfortunate effect of
glamorizing Danny's gambit. Taking hostages turns him into a
powerful figure wielding great, dramatic influence on everyone
around him.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Jackson is also asked to deliver the
screenplay's typically flat dialogue by way of explaining himself,
as in: ``Put yourself in my position. What else could I do?''
Jackson is far too commanding and clever an actor to make his
character seem that uncomplicated, but the script doesn't leave
much to the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   The film's title really should have been plural, since the story
really concerns the two negotiators in an elaborate standoff.
Though they know each other only by reputation, Jackson's Danny
insists that Spacey's Chris Sabian be brought into the case.
(Explanation: ``When your friends betray you, sometimes the only
people you can trust are strangers.'')
</P>
<P>
   Like Jackson, Spacey cuts an impressively cryptic figure even
when dealing in platitudes, and the two stars do get to make the
sort of declarations that rarely crop up in everyday life. Like:
``We're gonna do it my way or I walk!'' Or: ``I'm reading your
eyes. The eyes can't lie.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's supporting cast includes a solid array of actors well
versed in the ways of police thrillers, including David Morse, John
Spencer, Ron Rifkin and J.T. Walsh. Walsh, who died earlier this
year, had the best cynical scowl in the business and is seen using
it with his trademark shrewdness one last time here.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the cast is Regina Taylor as the loving wife of Danny,
who is supposed to be a love-struck newlywed. ``The Negotiator'' is
so intent on domesticating its stars that it even shows Spacey
kidding with a cute little daughter and Jackson line-dancing at a
policemen's hoedown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Negotiator'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes profanity and violence.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE NEGOTIATOR'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by F. Gary Gray; written by James DeMonaco and Kevin
Fox; director of photography, Russell Carpenter; edited by
Christian Wagner; music by Graeme Revell; production designer,
Holger Gross; produced by David Hoberman and Arnon Milchan;
released by Regency Enterprises and Warner Brothers. Running time:
115 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Samuel L. Jackson (Danny Roman), Kevin Spacey (Chris
Sabian), David Morse (Commander Beck), Ron Rifkin (Commander
Frost), John Spencer (Chief Al Travis), J.T. Walsh (Inspector
Niebaum) and Regina Taylor (Karen Roman). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
