<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY PROVIDES SANCTUARY TO ENDANGERED GULF COAST DENIZENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RALPH WININGHAM  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ARANSAS, Texas _ Tony Amos somewhat resembles the biblical
figure Noah, although the ``ARK'' under Amos' care is a group of
land-bound tanks and cages rather than a seaworthy craft.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, the white-haired and bearded Amos climbs into his
pickup truck and scours 7.5 miles of beach for creatures native to
the Gulf Coast and returns to the Animal Rehabilitation Keep (ARK)
on the grounds of the University of Texas Marine Science Institute
at Port Aransas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really had a run on babies this year,'' Amos said as he
scurried about preparing to feed nearly 100 sick or injured sea
turtles and sea birds under his care. ``This operation has gotten
so large that we can't continue like we have for the past 20
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The ARK is run by university volunteers, mainly Amos, who
attempt to help Kemp's ridley, loggerhead, hawksbill and green sea
turtles, as well as various gulls, pelicans and other birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``These little babies attract the most attention,'' he said as
he held up a Kemp's ridley sea turtle that weighed about an ounce
and was no bigger than 2 inches across.
</P>
<P>
   About 3,000 of the endangered turtles are believed to exist, and
all of the other turtles and birds at ARK are listed by the U.S.
Fish and Wildlife Service as either endangered or threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have five of these ridleys now and could end up with about
a dozen. All of them are missing flippers, but we hope to be able
to release them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will keep seeing more of the baby ridleys through the
middle of August, and then we will see the young hawksbill in
September and October.''
</P>
<P>
   State and federal officials removed the turtle eggs last year
from nests dug by their mothers. Each nest can contain as many as
90 eggs, which are incubated away from the beach to save them from
predators.
</P>
<P>
   Amos said this breeding season he saw one of the females he
helped release 13 years ago return and create two separate nests.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is very rare. I saw her dig the nest and lay the eggs in
one nest and (during the same year) saw her returning to the water
from another nest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One had 90 eggs in it, and the other had 100.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 29 sea turtles and 245 birds were taken to Amos'
facility. More than 50 percent were returned to the wild, Amos
said, but the rest remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them are still here and others can't be released
because of the severity of their injuries,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Amos has been operating his rehabilitation facility, the only
one of its kind in the area, for 20 years. While the university
provides the facility for the rehabilitation center, all food,
medicine, equipment and other supplies must be purchased with
donations, Amos said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
