<SLUG> BC-OPIUM-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OPIUM: A HISTORY': ALL THE FACTS, AND THEN A BIT MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Opium is important and, in one or another of its derivatives and
preparations, has been for millenniums. It is mentioned by Homer,
who called it nepenthe; it was a major factor in the shaping of
19th- and 20th-century Chinese history; it contributed in its way
to the sensualism of Samuel Taylor Coleridge's poetry, and, of
course, it is an addictive commodity traded by vast networks of
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   In his sprawling study of opium and its role in human history,
Martin Booth, a British novelist and documentary filmmaker, covers
everything from opium's chemical composition and manner of
cultivation to the organization of contemporary international
criminal networks for its distribution and sale. He describes in
detail the arduous work of extracting it from the pods of a certain
species of poppy cultivated in Turkey, Iran, Afghanistan, India,
Myanmar and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   He recounts the story of a German pharmacist's assistant named
Friedrich Sertuerner who discovered its morphine derivative in the
19th century. He talks about famous addicts and infamous drug
dealers. He provides history of the Opium War by which the British
forced China to open ports to British trade and residents in 1842;
he talks about subjects as diverse as 19th-century Hong Kong opium
dens, the Hollywood drug scandals in the 1920s and the politics of
opium transport by the CI during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Booth in short has written a comprehensive survey based on a
prodigious and impressive amount of research. ``Opium'' in this
sense is a valuable work, a kind of book-length encyclopedia entry.
But despite its value, Booth's account presents some problems. He
uses no source notes, and that makes it impossible, without doing
considerable research, to assess some of the claims he makes.
</P>
<P>
   He does not help matters by frequently employing soggy
expressions like ``it was estimated'' and ``it has been suggested
that,'' but he rarely identifies those who are doing the estimating
or the suggesting.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Booth, who uses a very sober, judicious style, is
correct, for example, when he says that Benjamin Franklin was
``almost certainly addicted to opium in his declining years,'' or
that in the 19th century 90 percent of the adult population of two
coastal provinces of China were ``habituated,'' or that opium was
smuggled into the United States from Hong Kong in the hollowed-out
horns of imported cattle. (Hong Kong exported cattle to the United
States?) But he provides no sources for any of these interesting
statements.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Booth makes some claims, always without
substantiation, that, if true, would force considerable revisions
of history. He gives a brief account, for example, of the Chinese
Nationalist leader Chiang Kai-shek's shady dealings with the head
of the Shanghai underworld, Tu Yueh-sheng. That there was a
relationship between the two men is well-known. What is less well
known is Booth's assertion that ``Tu controlled opium and therefore
Chiang Kai-shek.'' Historians accept that the French police in the
foreign concession in Shanghai gave Tu the authority to control the
criminal underground, but the relationship between Tu and Chiang
has always seemed far murkier than Booth makes it appear.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas, Booth obviously exaggerates, as when he asserts
that New York City is ``in a virtual state of siege'' and that it
is being ``killed by heroin.'' He cites a 1971 article in Newsweek
to that effect, but then asserts on his own authority, ``The
situation is little changed today.''
</P>
<P>
   He writes, ``Americans consider drugs the greatest problem
facing their nation,'' which will come as news to most Americans.
Less credible and entirely unsubstantiated is Booth's remarkable
claim that the downing of Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie,
Scotland, in 1988 can be blamed on covert CIA drug shipments,
undertaken in a futile effort to gain influence over Middle East
terrorist organizations holding Americans hostage in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Booth gives a capsule history of the CIA's transport of opium
for the Hmong secret army in Laos in the 1960s, which is
well-known, but he later asserts, without documentation, that
without official Western promotion of the drug trade, ``it is
arguable whether or not the Golden Triangle and the Crescent would
be the major producers they are today.'' That almost meaningless
phrase ``it is arguable whether or not'' gives a gloss of
carefulness to what is actually a careless and certainly
unsubstantiated statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is even suggested,'' Booth writes, that ``the CIA has
reverted to its Southeast Asian practices of the 1960s and is
itself dealing in heroin as part of its Middle East strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Booth does not tell us who is suggesting this. He
argues that the CIA might be using drugs to pay bribes to Arab
governments so they will remain within the anti-Iraq alliance
created during the Persian Gulf war. If this is true, it would be
the story of the century, but Booth, with that phrase ``it is even
suggested,'' has certainly not demonstrated that it is true.
</P>
<P>
   In these instances, he does not so much practice journalistic
investigation as he passes along the various unconfirmed
allegations he has heard, especially when it comes to the nefarious
dealings of Western intelligence agencies.
</P>
<P>
   When Booth turns to other subjects _ and most of his book has to
do with other subjects _ he seems a far more reliable reporter. His
account of opium's use in medicine, the discovery of its active
properties, his appreciation of the paradox that Western
profiteering from the drug trade in China helped inflict the
scourge of addiction in the West: these and other subjects are
reliably and competently covered by Booth. It is too bad that his
dubious assertions undermine his believability.
</P>
<P>
   Publication notes:
</P>
<P>
   OPIUM: A HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   By Martin Booth
</P>
<P>
   381 pages. St. Martin's Press. $24.95
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
