</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: GLENN AND CRONKITE; LEFTISM ON FOX; MONDAY NIGHT
FOOTBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glenn's Show, And Cronkite's
</P>
<P>
   John Glenn's return trip to space has the ring of nostalgia for
a generation of Americans, and CNN will add to that flavor by
bringing Walter Cronkite back as a co-anchor for its coverage of
the event.
</P>
<P>
   The cable network announced Tuesday that Cronkite, who was
closely associated with the U.S. space program in his role as the
CBS News anchor in the 1960s, would join John Holliman in
presenting CNN's coverage of the launching of the space shuttle
Discovery on Oct. 29 and the planned landing Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite was in Florida in 1962 when Glenn became the first
American to orbit the Earth, and he said Tuesday that his memories
remained ``rather intense.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, technical circumstances for reporting were very
different. ``We had primitive quarters,'' Cronkite said. ``I was in
the back of a station wagon in a snake-infested field.'' And during
the network's minute-by-minute coverage, Cronkite said, ``We kept
track of where he was using this world chart that I unrolled like a
papyrus.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, he said, he recalled the national excitement
that built up before the launching. ``It was like the nation's
honor rested at the top of that rocket,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The excitement even got to the CBS anchor, who was famous for
his coolness under pressure. ``I do remember my unbridled
enthusiasm at the moment of takeoff, when I said, `Go, baby, go.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the U.S. space program was the biggest of stories a
television anchor could cover; today, Cronkite conceded, things are
different. Interest faded, just as he says he predicted it would 30
years ago, as the trips became less suspenseful and more routine.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought the space program today was where he might
have expected it to be 35 years ago, Cronkite said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have thought we'd be further along,'' Cronkite said.
``Doing things like erecting a space city. Of course, none of us
knew what we'd find when we landed on the moon. At the time, we
were all thinking in terms of moon colonies. I didn't think we'd
abandon that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Glenn's flight, Cronkite said suggestions that it was a
gimmick to reignite interest in the space program were unfair. He
said he believed it was a legitimate, serious scientific
examination related to aging and space travel.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, he is excited again about seeing Glenn take off. ``I
might be lured into saying `Go, baby, go' again.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Fox Populi
</P>
<P>
   Unexpected bedfellows: how did a radical leftist historian come
to have his main work purchased as a miniseries by the Fox network?
</P>
<P>
   Fox, is, after all, owned by Rupert Murdoch, who is not known
for making deals with left-wingers, unless they run China and it's
the only way to keep his satellite business solvent.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox did announce that it will present a 10-hour series based
on the book ``A People's History of the United States,'' by Howard
Zinn. The book, which was nominated for a National Book Award in
1981, chronicles American history from the point of view of blacks,
Indians, women and the disadvantaged.
</P>
<P>
   Zinn has also challenged U.S. participation in virtually every
war, and once wrote a play based on the early life of anarchist
Emma Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   What in this appeals to the Fox network? Apparently nothing.
It's Matt Damon and Ben Affleck that appeal to the network.
</P>
<P>
   Zinn's name was celebrated in their film ``Good Will Hunting''
when Matt Damon's genius character lauded the book. That mention
was noticed by Marci Pool, the Fox executive in charge of movies,
who got in touch with Damon and Affleck and asked if they would be
interested in bringing this project to television.
</P>
<P>
   They will, as executive producers. What exactly the project will
be is a little unclear, though it may not be precisely the vision
presented in Zinn's book.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not doing the book,'' said David Grant, president of the
Fox Television Studio. ``It's a dramatic work. It's not a political
piece. The book is really the inspiration for Matt and Ben to tell
stories.''
</P>
<P>
   As described by Fox, the miniseries is going to tell stories of
American history from a ``youth-oriented'' point of view. ``It's
history as it happened to ordinary people,'' Grant said. ``It's
populist in that sense.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Media Quarterbacking
</P>
<P>
   Most listeners scoffed when a top UPN network executive declared
Sunday that only 12 to 15 percent of men aged 18 to 49 watched
``Monday Night Football'' on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   UPN programming chief Tom Nunan, used the statistic to explain
why UPN had put together a lineup of male-oriented comedies for
Monday nights in the fall. But his audience, a convention of
television critics and reporters, dismissed his comment as some
sort of cockeyed spin on the Nielsen numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Now hear this, critics and sports fans: the numbers are correct.
Among 18-to-49-year-old men, only 12 percent, or about 7.3 million,
watched ``Monday Night Football'' last season, according to Nielsen
Media Research.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers look better for ABC and the National Football League
when you consider the share number, or percentage of sets in use.
Among men 18 to 49 who were watching television on Monday nights,
an average of 34 percent were watching football. (The same
percentage held for all men over 18.)
</P>
<P>
   But among younger men, the numbers are even lower: 10.8 percent
of men 18 to 34 watch ``Monday Night Football,'' with a 32 percent
share.
</P>
<P>
   As Nunan argued, that means plenty of young men, a group coveted
by advertisers, are available and might be lured to other programs
_ in UPN's case, ``Guys Like Us,'' a buddy comedy; ``DiResta,'' a
sitcom based on the real-life story of a New York City subway
policeman, John DiResta; ``Desmond Pfeiffer,'' a screwball spoof
about Abraham Lincoln, and the returning ``Malcolm &AMP; Eddie.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
