<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6753 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWINSKY-CIRCUS-NYTSF     07-28 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-CIRCUS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL'S ALLEGED PHILANDERING IS HILLARY'S PROBLEM, NOT STARR'S 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Central time zone, call CONNIE WHITE at
1-800-444-0267. Or fax her at (816) 822-1444.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Pacific or Mountain time zones or in Latin
America, call OLIVIA VASQUEZ at (310) 996-0075. Or fax her at (310)
996-0089.
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Watergate had its heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Glorified as their roles might have been in the book and movie
versions of ``All the President's Men,'' Bob Woodward and Carl
Bernstein and Ben Bradlee and even the shadowy Deep Throat were
crusaders for the truth. It seemed appropriate that dashing young
stars Robert Redford and Dustin Hoffman play the lead reporters in
the film.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, even Richard Nixon _ while no hero _ was an
undeniably fascinating and complex figure, worthy of a Greek
tragedy or at the very least an Oliver Stone film starring Anthony
Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no heroes in the Starr Wars saga. No one to cheer
for; no one who has emerged as the noble underdog or the innocent
victim or the champion of truth and justice and the American way.
</P>
<P>
   They're all kinda greasy. From Linda Tripp to Lucianne Goldberg
to Monica Lewinsky to Kenneth Starr to all the slick-talking
attorneys to the media pack hounding secretaries and bit players _
if you were related to any of these people, you wouldn't want to
invite them to the family reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton? He's an above-average president riding the rocket
ship of a booming economy _ and he's a haplessly horny buffoon in
his personal life, if all the stories (or even half the stories)
about him are to be believed. Trysting with a blowsy lounge singer,
trysting with a beauty queen, engaging in something with a chatty
intern who's only a few years older than his daughter _ why doesn't
the guy just get a BMW roadster, undergo liposuction, dye his hair
and acknowledge he's the Warren Beatty of modern politics?
</P>
<P>
   From the cold of January's winter to the dog days of late July _
that's how long it took for us to get to that teeny-weeny press
conference Tuesday afternoon, when the wonderfully named Plato
Cacheris said, ``We, as counsel for Monica Lewinsky, have reached
an agreement today that for her full and truthful testimony she
will receive transactional immunity in this case,'' and then walked
away as reporters yelled ``What's transactional immunity!''
</P>
<P>
   It means the kid can tell her version of the truth without going
to jail _ an agreement that should have been hammered out months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   This revelation led to yet another bizarre press conference,
starring Mike McCurry and that wacky band of White House beat
reporters. Like a lot of people who have plans to leave a job in
the near future, McCurry seemed relaxed, bordering on goofy at
times, as he fended off a barrage of questions.
</P>
<P>
   He scolded the press: ``I know you're all going to have to run
out and yak and yak and yak forever about this, but it's going to
be based on very few facts.''
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked if any ``world leaders'' had discussed the
investigation with Clinton, McCurry chuckled and said: ``The
foreign angle! Looking for that foreign angle! I can safely report
I'm not aware of any foreign angle on this story.''
</P>
<P>
   He chided Sam Donaldson for predicting the content of Lewinsky's
testimony: ``That is sheer speculation on your part, Sam. We've
established some time ago you have absolutely no Earthly idea what
she's going to testify to; you've conceded that point.''
</P>
<P>
   He even dropped a trivia-bombshell. Turns out Lewinsky once
interviewed for a job in the White House press office _ leading
McCurry to admit with a twinkle in his eye how grateful he is about
that hire not materializing.
</P>
<P>
   It was an excellent and entertaining performance. You almost
expected McCurry to come out for a curtain call. But as masterful
as McCurry was in conveying the message that the immunity agreement
is no big deal to the White House, he can't fit the role of hero in
this drama. Spin doctors can't be heroes; they're sidekicks at
best.
</P>
<P>
   Sidekicks to a president who treats the truth like kryptonite.
It's time for Clinton to testify, to provide the ``he said'' to
Monica's ``she said.'' Admit it, deny it, explain it, step up to
the plate and be a man about it.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anything Clinton says should destroy his presidency. I
may be the last person in America clinging to this belief _ but I
still wonder if Clinton and Lewinsky really did have relations. And
if they did, so what? Jabber all you want about ``suborning
perjury,'' there's nothing impeachable here. The president's
alleged philandering is Hillary's problem, not Ken Starr's.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) can be heard on the
``Media Creatures'' show, which airs daily in Chicago from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. on WMVP-AM (1000) and appears Tuesday and Thursday at
7:55 a.m. on WFLD-TV's ``Fox Thing in the Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A daily columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, Roeper has also
written for TV Guide, Spy, Playboy, Chicago magazine and many other
publications, and has appeared as a guest on ``Nightline'' and
``Oprah.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
