EVEN AS '90s REMAKE, `PARENT TRAP' IDEA WORKS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating: 3 Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; In a summer marked by the nuclear-powered
vulgarity of ``There's Something About Mary'' and the harrowing
brutality of ``Saving Private Ryan,'' Disney's almost
pathologically innocuous remake of ``The Parent Trap'' is sure to
seem like some kind of relief.
</P>
<P>
   And it is, to an extent. Thoroughly undemanding, yet made with
enormous care and commitment by director Nancy Meyers and her
producer husband, Charles Shyer, ``Parent Trap'' is a reassuring
re-enactment of the eternally popular 1961 family comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the parts that remind you of another deathless,
early-'60s movie: ``Psycho.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an iffy proposition back then that a mother and father
would split up upon the birth of their twins, each flee with one
infant to different sides of the continent and never let either
girl know of their other parent or sister's existence. Thirty-seven
years and quantum leaps in child-development studies later, such a
premise not only seems hard to buy, but downright appalling.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, oddly enough, this creepy idea prevents the movie from
wallowing in preteen empowerment pablum. Of course, Meyers and
Shyer refuse to address the queasy question in any direct way _
these are the folks who brought us those ``Father of the Bride''
remakes, and they appear to be constitutionally incapable of
visualizing anything that doesn't evoke (let alone challenge) a
sense of leisure-class comfort. But whenever the movie's mushy
romantics or repetitive, ``which-one-is-it-now'' twin jokes wear
thin, at least there's an interesting space for your mind to wander
to.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is not a movie meant to inspire thought. Like
David Swift's original, this ``Parent Trap'' is about feelings, and
darn powerful ones. The discovery of someone just like you, putting
a broken family back together, finding a dream dad/mom (well,
except for the total abandonment part) out of thin air _ these are
wish-fulfillment fantasies any child can take to heart.
</P>
<P>
   Shyer and Meyers have increased the geographical stakes here _
mom Elizabeth (Natasha Richardson) and her half, Annie, live in
England, while dad Nick (Dennis Quaid) and his daughter, Hallie,
own a Napa Valley winery _ but they're otherwise remarkably
faithful to Swift's original.
</P>
<P>
   The girls, played by Lindsay Lohan with state-of-the-art digital
assists Hayley Mills never dreamed of, accidentally meet at summer
camp, take an immediate dislike to one another, then are thrilled
to discover the truth. When summer ends, Hallie heads to London
with a newly minted accent, and Annie goes West with an
appropriately American tomboy 'do.
</P>
<P>
   Both exult in fooling the parents they've never known while just
dying over how cool they turn out to be (Elizabeth is an ultra-hip
wedding gown designer _ is such a job possible? _ and Nick is
something of a cowboy). But there's a hitch: Nick's being vamped by
an evil publicist (Elaine Hendrix), and if the second phase of the
grand plan _ getting the folks, whose reasons for breaking up in
the first place are never made clear, back together _ is going to
work, the girls better act quick. Warmth and farce ensue.
</P>
<P>
   Although her visual capabilities are generally those of an
interior decorator, Meyers uses computer technology to seamless,
though hardly eye-popping, effect whenever Lohan has to act with
herself. And the young actress does a terrific job, maintaining
energy and comic timing throughout what must have been a tedious
and demanding process. Quaid and Richardson are as likable as can
be, too, without getting too sappy about it. Lisa Ann Walter and
Simon Kunz provide a few laughs as enthusiastically supportive
servants.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, really pleasant family fun, fundamentally demented
as it may be. But maybe that's just the '90s talking. Perhaps the
upcoming remake of ``Psycho'' will seem like a story about an
especially close, mother-son relationship where the wacky high
jinks just got a little out of hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
