<SLUG> BC-WHITNEY-DIRECTOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR APPOINTED BY WHITNEY MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a three-month search for a new director, the
Whitney Museum of American Art has appointed Maxwell Anderson, the
director of the Art Gallery of Ontario. Anderson, who has spent
three years in that post, succeeds David Ross, who resigned in
March to become director of the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, 42, who begins his new job in September, has been
chosen to bring a more scholarly approach to exhibitions and
programs at the Whitney than Ross did, said Joel Ehrenkranz,
president of the board and chairman of the search committee that
selected Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for someone to bring a serious perspective to
our programs,'' Ehrenkranz said. ``Max understands the balance of
our programs, both historic and contemporary. I think what he will
bring is a scholarly understanding to the importance of
contemporary art.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson seems less likely to mount shows like ``Black Male:
Representations of Masculinity in Contemporary American Art'' or a
show devoted to the fashion photographer Richard Avedon,
exhibitions in 1994 that were attacked by critics as being trendy.
Earlier this month, the museum announced cancellation of ``The
Great American Nude,'' a show of visual and performance art, that
had been scheduled for December.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment comes three months after the Whitney unveiled a
$30 million renovation and expansion that includes new galleries,
the first dedicated to the permanent collection of the 67-year-old
museum. With these new quarters, Whitney officials say, they are
trying to balance the institution's reputation for venturesome
shows with a greater emphasis on art of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from a tradition of writing and thinking about American
identity,'' said Anderson, grandson of the playwright Maxwell
Anderson and son of Quentin Anderson, a professor of American
literature at Columbia University for nearly 40 years. ``At the
Whitney I am hoping to help define the character of American art in
a more international arena.''
</P>
<P>
   A native New Yorker, Anderson graduated from Dartmouth College
and earned a Ph.D. in fine arts from Harvard University. For six
years, until 1987, he worked in the department of Greek and Roman
art at the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   From 1987 to 1995, he was the director of the Michael C. Carlos
Museum at Emory University in Atlanta, where he oversaw the
museum's expansion by Michael Graves.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure at the Art Gallery of Ontario in Toronto,
Anderson increased its collections, expanded its special
exhibitions program and increased revenues significantly during a
period of government cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney appointment was voted by the board Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what his mission would be at the Whitney, Anderson said he
wanted to ``get great works of art in front of the public and help
them understand what they are seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   As for acquisitions, he said he wanted the Whitney to increase
its holdings of Abstract Expressionist masters while remaining open
to some risk-taking collecting of works by emerging artists. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
