<HEADER>
A6785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINCOLN-CENTER-FEST-N     07-28 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINCOLN-CENTER-FEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FESTIVAL RESULTS PLEASE LINCOLN CENTER OFFICIALS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Relieved that their third summer arts festival has
survived its pre-opening calamity _ the last-minute cancellation of
a centerpiece production of a revered 19-hour Chinese opera _
Lincoln Center officials began this week to assess the damage and
look ahead to the next two scheduled festivals and perhaps beyond.
</P>
<P>
   For the 20-day Lincoln Center Festival '98, which was perhaps
more notable for what was not performed than what was, the
experiment in luring younger audiences with unconventional works
from all over the world fell into a pattern established by the two
prior Lincoln Center Festivals: a mixed bag of critical successes
and flops and a decidedly last-minute audience, which sent
organizers into paroxysms of anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a nail-biter,'' Nathan Leventhal, the president of
Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts, said.
</P>
<P>
   In the delicate business of mixing adventurous but risky,
way-out offerings with bankable but predictable crowd-pleasers, the
1998 program balanced the lurid weirdness of a cybernetic (and
negatively reviewed) ``Faust'' from Barcelona with an elegantly
star-studded (and far better received) production of ``Twelfth
Night,'' programs dedicated to Leonard Bernstein, and two plays by
the Gesher Theater of Tel Aviv intended to draw New York's large
Jewish and Russian populations.
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal and Beverly Sills, the chairman, said that as a matter
of policy they would not disclose financial and attendance figures
for the festival, which ended on Sunday. But they said that the
majority of the 99 performances of 20 program events met or
exceeded their box office projections. They declined to say which
fell short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am one happy guy,'' Leventhal said in an interview. But he
acknowledged, ``I lost 10 years off my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Measured by the Mohawk index, it was a success, said Nigel
Redden, the festival's director, who was formally designated only
last month. ``I have not seen that many Mohawk haircuts ever at
Lincoln Center,'' said Redden. The successor to John Rockwell, who
returned to The New York Times as editor of the Arts and Leisure
section, Redden also serves as general manager of the Spoleto
Festival U.S.A. in Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the thwarted attraction _ ``The Peony Pavilion,'' a
400-year-old kunqu opera, abruptly bottled up in Shanghai _
remained unclear, along with Lincoln Center's chances of recouping
its investment in the opera of close to $400,000. That includes its
$180,000 share of the creation costs plus about $200,000 in labor
and travel expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll write it off for now,'' said Leventhal, citing expected
surpluses from other operations.
</P>
<P>
   Redden, who held cliffhanger, face-to-face talks with the
resistant director of the Shanghai Municipal Bureau of Culture
until the very eve of the opera's scheduled opening on July 7, said
he hoped it could be brought to New York next summer. Lincoln
Center's three co-producers of ``Peony Pavilion,'' arts festivals
in Paris, Hong Kong and Sydney, have their own performances
scheduled and are now expected to take the lead in negotiations
with the bureau's director, Ma Bomin.
</P>
<P>
   Faulting the production, which is directed by Chen Shi-Zheng,
for supposed elements of pornography, superstition and feudalism,
Ms. Bomin embargoed the company of 21 actors and 15 musicians,
although the set, costumes and props were released. Efforts to
reach accommodation failed and, Ms. Sills said, even a call by
Henry A. Kissinger to the mayor of Shanghai proved fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Peony Pavilion,'' rarely, if ever, performed in its
entirety in the last few centuries, was to have highlighted the
opening of the festival with episodes spread over the first six
nights. It was to have been repeated in a three-night marathon the
second week. Ticket holders were offered a refund or the chance to
exchange their seats for any other production. Nothing else was
substituted in the scheduled venue, the theater of the Fiorello H.
La Guardia High School of Music and Art and Performing Arts, and
two Lincoln Center symposiums on the opera were canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a disaster, no question about that,'' Ms. Sills said.
Still, ``it called attention to the fact that the festival was
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the more acclaimed highlights of the season were two
evocations of the Holocaust, the Gesher Theater's mock-circus
production of ``Adam Resurrected,'' and the Theatre de Complicite's
London production of ``The Street of Crocodiles,'' based on the
hallucinatory stories of a murdered writer, Bruno Schultz.
</P>
<P>
   Also well received were the Stuttgart Ballet's first
reappearance in New York in 19 years, the complete organ works of
Johann Sebastian Bach (although often played to moderate audiences
in Alice Tully Hall), and ``Patience and Sarah,'' the world
premiere of a folk opera about a pioneering lesbian couple.
</P>
<P>
   As in previous festivals, the New York Philharmonic drew often
disappointing crowds, perhaps because the orchestra performs
regularly at Lincoln Center. Still, as part of a politic effort to
include its constituents in its summer festival, the Philharmonic
has already been booked for next year's festival, organizers said.
In the same way, the festival underwrote part of Lincoln Center
Theater's production of ``Twelfth Night,'' which continues a
regular run now that the festival is over.
</P>
<P>
   Many critics assailed the American premiere of Krzysztof
Penderecki's oratorio ``Seven Gates of Jerusalem'' and the
cyberspace ``Faust,'' ``Faust, Version 3.0,'' by La Fura dels Baus.
The mixed-media Spanish production, performed in the New York State
Theater, was the first festival offering ever to bear a warning
label of unsuitability for minors. Leventhal insisted he enjoyed
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a vivid presentation,'' he said, adding, `I'm not
saying it was my favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's festival employed some new marketing tools,
including the sale of various ``passports'' for discounts and
better seating. One version, the ``Diplomat'' passport, which for
$100 offered access to prime full-price seats within 48 hours of a
performance, went so quickly that its sale was capped at 300, weeks
before the festival's opening.
</P>
<P>
   Although no figures were released, Leventhal said the festival
would be within budget this year, ``which was not the case last
year.'' Started on a budget of $8.5 million, of which $5.5 million
was to be raised from benefactors, the festival ballooned to
considerably above that, with some of the box office deficit later
offset by production savings. This year is expected to be closer to
the original figure.
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal and Ms. Sills said that although the board had only
authorized the festival through the 2000 season, they considered a
longer future likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has not been a chore to raise the money,'' Ms. Sills said.
``Here we have three or four of the most beautiful theaters in the
U.S. They should stay dark in the summer?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
