<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE CONTINUE PROBE OF FESTIVAL POISONINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Police in Wakayama continued Tuesday to investigate the
mystery surrounding a mass poisoning that left four people dead
Saturday after they had eaten at a festival.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Wakayama Prefecture police said although
investigators strongly believed that cyanide had been deliberately
introduced into curry at the festival, they could not rule out the
possibility that the food was accidentally tainted.
</P>
<P>
   The four victims died within hours after the curry had been
served. Forty-two others remained hospitalized. An additional 21
were treated at hospitals for symptoms of cyanide ingestion and
released.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the dead, Takatoshi Taninaka, 65, and Takaaki Tanaka, 53,
were officers in the community association that had organized the
festival. The other two fatalities were a 10-year-old boy and
16-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   In the late summer Japan comes alive with festivals, as city
dwellers return to their hometowns to celebrate Obon, a Buddhist
holiday that honors the spirits of dead ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   The Wakayama poisoning promises to put a damper on the season
this year, with some municipalities going so far as to cancel their
festival plans, according to the Japanese press.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although the apparent randomness of the incident recalled the
poison gas attack on the Tokyo subway system three years ago,
masterminded by the Aum Shinrikyo cult, the police spokesman said
the authorities did not suspect the involvement of any religious
group.
</P>
<P>
   Police have learned of disputes between the local community
association and other community associations, as well as within the
sponsoring association. But the spokesman said there did not appear
to be any conflict serious enough to lead to an act like poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   Police are grappling with odd strands of information. The curry
was made in two large pots in a resident's garage and a smaller pot
at another house before the festival, police said. The organizers
sampled the food at noon before taking it to the festival grounds.
</P>
<P>
   After people who had eaten the curry became violently ill, some
curry was left in the smaller pot and one of the large pots, but
there was no trace of cyanide in the leftover food. The other large
pot had been cleaned after the curry in it had been served.
</P>
<P>
   Police found traces of cyanide in a nearby sewer and have
speculated that it was, perhaps, washed out of the second large
pot.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, more than 100 small fish were found floating
dead in a stream near rice paddies in the festival area, and the
police are conducting autopsies on the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Cyanide is a deadly and fast-acting poison. Ingestion of a trace
causes extreme nausea in 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The festival poisoning was not the first incident of random
cyanide poisoning in Japan. In 1977 two high school students died
after having picked up a can of soda in a telephone booth and
sharing it. The soda was laced with cyanide. The case was not
solved.
</P>
<P>
   In several cases of attempted extortion cyanide has been found
injected in foods like chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most famous case of cyanide poisoning was in 1948,
when a man pretending to be a health officer killed 12 bank
employees while claiming to be checking for dysentery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1753EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
