<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6794 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERMAN-THEATER-REVIEW     07-28 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERMAN-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AN EVENING WITH JERRY HERMAN': NO-FRILLS SELF-TRIBUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jerry Herman has often said that one of the places he
is happiest is at the keyboard, and that, naturally, is where he
can be found throughout most of ``An Evening With Jerry Herman,''
the no-frills retrospective of his career as a Broadway composer
that opened Tuesday night at the Booth Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Joined by his friends Florence Lacey and Lee Roy Reams, who have
both appeared in his musicals, and playing many of his most famous
songs from ``Hello, Dolly!'' ``Mame,'' ``Milk and Honey'' and ``La
Cage Aux Folles,'' as well as several lesser-known numbers from
``Dear World,'' ``Mack and Mabel'' and ``The Grand Tour,'' Herman
spends an amiable couple of hours savoring his hits and mourning
his flops. The production is not unlike those award-show tributes _
including the mock-ups of the marquees from the old shows floating
down from the ceiling _ except in this case, the honoree is the
host of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   With the two men in tuxedos and Ms. Lacey wearing the kind of
form-fitting sequined cocktail dresses that once seemed fashionable
in the lobbies of the Fountainebleau or Eden Roc in Miami Beach,
the show is tailored to the specifications of another era in the
theater, the one during which Herman reigned as one of Broadway's
top tunesmiths. The era has passed, as the 66-year-old composer
keeps reminding us _ he hasn't had a new show on Broadway since the
Tony-winning ``La Cage'' opened in 1983 _ and much of ``An Evening
With Jerry Herman'' is bound up, a bit mustily, in memorializing
that period and the names that typified its glamour: Merman,
Channing, Merrick, Sardi.
</P>
<P>
   The evening evokes the age of the well-made song, a time when
``Broadway musical'' meant musical comedy and featured the sort of
character, comedy and statement songs at which Herman excelled,
numbers like ``Before the Parade Passes By'' and ``Bosom Buddies''
and ``If He Walked Into My Life.'' Throughout the show, Herman
tells brief tales about how this musical or that came into being,
and if these events hadn't really happened _ he says the producer
David Merrick hired him to write the score for ``Hello, Dolly!''
with the Winchellesque blessing ``Kid, the show is yours!'' _ they
certainly would have wound up as subjects of some Jerry Herman
Hey-world-get-outta-my-way-type production numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The revue, directed by Reams, is an outgrowth of a cabaret act
he devised with Herman at Rainbow and Stars in 1989 and that they
have intermittently taken on the road. It remains a cabaret act and
will probably be most affectionately embraced by people who enjoyed
Herman's musicals and maybe even have held on to the old vinyl cast
albums. His shows brimmed with goodwill toward the Broadway of
Berlin, Rodgers and Hammerstein, and I was hoping ``An Evening With
Jerry Herman'' would recapture some of his bountiful sense of _
well, to use two Jerry Herman-sounding words _ class and pizazz.
</P>
<P>
   It may have them for you, but I found the revue waxen on the big
stage, even a stage as intimate by Broadway standards as the
Booth's. The 28 songs, written from the 1960s to the early '80s,
show off Herman's considerable skills as a lyricist; the words mold
to the musical phrases like Saran Wrap. The show also reconfirms
his status as Broadway's leading proponent of carpe diem: Song
after song, from ``It's Today'' (``Mame'') to ``Hello, Dolly!'' to
``The Best of Times'' (``La Cage''), promises that ``this very
minute has history in it'' or ``Tomorrow will be brighter than the
good old days'' or pleads with us to ``hold this moment fast.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The sentiment may be paper thin, but it is genuine. Yet what
makes it hard to receive in the same spirit is Reams' underwhelming
presentation of the material. For example, his shuffle-and-swivel
choreography seems as out of style as a restaurant that still
serves salads of iceberg lettuce; it lends a worn-out air to the
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially unfortunate in a show in which the star
player continually draws attention to his feelings of not always
having been fully appreciated; after the phenomenal success of
``Hello, Dolly!'' and ``Mame'' in the '60s, Herman's next several
shows got disappointing receptions from critics and audiences, and
it wasn't until the blockbuster ``La Cage'' that the composer felt
a sense of popular redemption. He still appears hurt and angry at
the failure of ``Mack and Mabel,'' for example, and the weary tones
in which he describes his black decade, the '70s, puts an
unnecessary damper on things; every show, after all, can't be a
juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   Herman, Reams and Ms. Lacey take us chronologically through the
composer's work, and it's Ms. Lacey, the most accomplished stylist,
who has most of the memorable moments. Her renditions of ``I Don't
Want to Know'' (a personal manifesto in waltz tempo from ``Dear
World'') and ``I Belong Here'' (a soothing sigh from ``The Grand
Tour'') are delicate and touching, as is her smooth handling of
``Song on the Sand'' from ``La Cage.'' She's not much fun, though,
which makes her a mismatch for Reams, who is loosest in comic songs
like ``Penny in My Pocket,'' a number for the miserly Horace
Vandergelder that was cut from ``Hello, Dolly!'' (His piercing
tenor tends to overwhelm songs like ``It Only Takes a Moment'' that
cry out for a lighter touch.)
</P>
<P>
   In his 1996 memoir, ``Showtune,'' Herman wrote that illness, the
death of a lover and a nagging sense that his kind of music had
gone out of fashion were among the reasons he stopped writing after
``La Cage.'' In the intervening years, contemporaries like Stephen
Sondheim and John Kander and Fred Ebb continued to churn out
musicals; what seems apparent is that they had far greater
capacities for responding to changing musical tastes and, perhaps,
farther-reaching musical talents.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the evening, Herman plays a song that he says
has become a personal anthem: ``I'll Be Here Tomorrow,'' from ``The
Grand Tour.'' ``I'll be here tomorrow/Alive and well and
thriving,'' the lyric begins. That he articulates it with such
conviction will thrill his fans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
