<HEADER>
A6820 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      07-28 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; OFF THE BEATEN PATH &QL; 
 &UR; (North Point, $24)
</P>
<P>
   This is a collection of original short fiction created by some
of today's finest writers at the request of the Nature Conservancy.
Barbara Kingsolver tells in her introduction how it came about:
``In the hope of raising awareness, raising Cain, and raising money
with which to spare more wildlands from the blade, the editors
conceived this book. They called a dozen or so fiction writers and
issued an invitation: Visit one of the wild places the Conservancy
is working to protect (you get to choose which one), then go home
and write a story. The story need not be about anything that
happened during your visit, particularly. It need not even be about
the place you visited. Just see where the inspiration takes you.''
As Kingsolver notes,``this is not something we fiction writers hear
very often from editors and publishers,'' so most of them took the
bait. Included are Howard Norman, Jill McCorkle, Barry Lopez,
Gretel Ehrlich, Julia Alvarez, Rick Bass, Rita Mae Brown, David
James Duncan, Richard Bausch, Eric Lustbader, Larry Watson, Lee
Smith and Annie Proulx. Among the places that inspired them:
Montana's Blackfoot River, Alaska's Katmai Peninsula and the Ten
Sleep Preserve on the slopes of Wyoming's Bighorn Mountains. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MR. MIKE: THE LIFE AND WORK OF MICHAEL O'DONOGHUE &QL; 
 &UR; Dennis Perrin (Avon, $25)
</P>
<P>
   As deaths go, Michael O'Donoghue's was dramatic. On Nov. 8,
1994, he suffered a massive brain hemorrhage, a misfortune, writes
Perrin, that ``mirrored somewhat the anatomy of his jokes: a swift
buildup to a violent finish.'' And then there was the wake, which
``New York'' magazine described as ``the hippest party in New
York,'' attended by friends O'Donoghue had made at ``National
Lampoon'' and ``Saturday Night Live'' (and a few enemies as well,
most notably Lorne Michaels and Chevy Chase). O'Donoghue's comedy
was lacerating, aggressive and all-inclusive. His life didn't just
touch people, said one friend. It (begin itals) stabbed (end itals)
them. Perhaps it's normal that some parts of this biography are
seriously overwritten as Perrin attempts to convey the spirit of
his subject. In death as in life, O'Donoghue is hard to take, an
assessment that probably would delight him. As Perrin says, ``the
only boundaries he acknowledged were his own.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; A NEW KIND OF PARTY ANIMAL &QL; 
 &UR; Michele Mitchell (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23)
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who is 27 and the youngest person to have written for
the editorial page of The New York Times, paints a flattering
portrait of the 18-to-35 age group that is at the center of a
national marketing blitz, is a collective political wild card and
has its elders scratching their heads and wondering what this
younger generation really wants. When all the generational analysis
began, Mitchell was just starting a job as a press secretary on
Capitol Hill. ``We weren't the first to be dissected in an attempt
to figure out what we would do with the country when we took
over,'' she says, but still it was insulting and often downright
silly. They don't vote? They don't read? They don't seem to know
how to dress? In debunking those insinuations (made by no less than
``Time'' magazine), Mitchell focuses on six factors that set her
contemporaries apart: their lack of party affiliation, their
interest in a range of issues, their grassroots-based approach to
problem-solving, their lack of gender bias, their skepticism of
marketing and advertising, and their computer savvy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE 50-YEAR DASH &QL; 
 &UR; Bob Greene (Doubleday, $11.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not exactly a guidebook for being 50,'' writes Greene.
``It's more like a companion volume to take along on a trip. It's
about all the things that 50 is about _ family, career, body,
money, sex, mortality; friendship, regrets, fears, memories,
doubts, dreams; angers, clothes, resentments, houses, parents,
fantasies; children, food, love, bosses, doctors, rivalry;
yearnings, sleep, employees, shoes, medicine, backaches; hope,
cars, lust, embarrassments, heartaches, horizons.'' Think he's left
himself enough room to move? Just to be safe he goes a step farther
and tells us that 50 is the age at which we will want to buy
birdbaths for our yards. Is this stretching things a bit? We think
so, have for years, but people keep buying his books anyway. This
one is new in paperback. Read it fast _ 60 is just around the
corner, and we know Greene is watching. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; GOOD SCRIPTS, BAD SCRIPTS &QL; 
 &UR; Thomas Pope (Three Rivers, $14)
</P>
<P>
   As Pope was studying screenwriting (he has written screenplays
for ``The Lords of Discipline,'' ``Hammett'' and others) he
discovered that he learned as much from bad films as from good
ones. ``But when I asked why `The Jewel of the Nile' didn't work as
well as the original,'' he writes, ``why `Falling in Love' fell on
its face, why `Havana' was revolting, or why so many films simply
didn't work, all I got was a shrug and a smile.'' This book, he
says, is ``the Harvard Business School gone Hollywood,'' in which
he seeks to teach by example, good and bad. He discusses, among
others, ``The Abyss'' (that disaster of disaster films), ``Singin'
in the Rain,'' ``Pulp Fiction,'' ``The Usual Suspects,'' ``Fargo,''
``The Bonfire of the Vanities,'' ``Tender Mercies,'' ``The Day of
the Jackal,'' ``Chinatown'' and ``Groundhog Day.'' It's useful to
fledgling screenwriters, and entertaining to people who just like
to talk about movies. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
