<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-MSKUBE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Tuppers' expansion creates shortage of six-pack carriers
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 30: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the little things we take for granted. The ham can be smoky
and sweet, the potato salad perfect and the eggs deviled just
right, but there won't be a picnic unless someone can scare up some
plastic plates and forks. And some napkins.
</P>
<P>
   At the Old Dominion Brewery in Ashburn, Va., an unexpected
shortage of six-pack holders _ the cardboard contrivances for
carrying half a dozen bottles of beer _ has arisen. You never think
about these things. You wonder if the beer is available, if it can
be transported, if there's enough retail demand. But cardboard
holders?
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened after Tuppers' Hop Pocket Ale was
introduced to the Atlanta market two weeks ago and sold out within
days. At Harry's Farmers Market in Marietta, Ga., beer manager Juan
Viteri received 20 cases of Hop Pocket on a Thursday _ one of the
largest shipments in the area _ and by midday Saturday all but
three were gone.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside a once substantial display, Viteri sounded like
someone wondering how the snowman had melted away. ``You see
that,'' he said. ``It's all we got left.'' Even as he was saying
it, someone walked up and asked, ``Excuse me, but can you sell me
some of the Tuppers'?''
</P>
<P>
   Demand in Atlanta for Tuppers' Hop Pocket _ winner of the gold
medal for American-style pale ales last year at the Great American
Beer Festival _ surpassed all projections. ``We've already got 200
cases back-ordered, and that's probably shy of what we need,'' says
Peter Marte, president of Thunder Head Distribution Services.
``We've also got orders in Athens(Ga.) we're trying to fill.''
</P>
<P>
   For Old Dominion founder Jerry Bailey, whose following had been
largely confined to Northern Virginia, Maryland and the District of
Columbia, it's all come rather quickly. After the small craft
brewery shipped 1,000 cases of Hop Pocket to England _ where
national pride limits enthusiasm for an ale that's too assertively
American _ cardboard six-pack holders suddenly have become more
than incidental.
</P>
<P>
   ``That beer has moved faster than anything I've seen since
Sierra Nevada Celebration Ale _ and that's a seasonal beer,'' says
Andy Klubock, proprietor of the Taco Mac pubs in Sandy Springs and
Snellville, where Hop Pocket is sold on draft. ``Beers like this
aren't something you guzzle to get drunk. It just shows how
knowledgeable people in Atlanta are becoming about beer. They are
as knowledgeable here as they are in Boston, New York or Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   You'll notice he didn't say Seattle, San Francisco or Portland,
Ore., but he said more than anyone could have said only a few years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Better than respectable
</P>
<P>
   When you've done someone a disservice, better that you try to
rectify it than deny it. A few weeks ago, in another section of
this newspaper, I offered my impressions of the area's brewpubs. Of
John Harvard's Brew House in Buckhead I wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``Half a dozen or so `chain beers,' brewed to corporate recipe,
are on tap, most of them respectable, others quite commendable.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not what appeared in the paper. Somewhere in the
editing process the phrase ``others quite commendable'' was
deleted, leaving a reader to infer that certain of brewer Kurt
Harrison's beers were less than respectable.
</P>
<P>
   It was an innocent mistake, but one that should be acknowledged.
The fact is that Kurt Harrison and assistant Happy Harris brew
beers that are respectable and then some. I happen to think they
are better with ales than with lagers, but that's true of most
brewpubs. Harrison's Scottish Ale, as the article reported, won a
silver medal at the Great American Beer Festival, and his India
Pale Ale reproduces the original British style as well as any. I
admit a partiality to the more assertive Pacific Northwest style,
but Harrison's IPA is one any knowledgeable brewer would admire.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison also took exception to the phrase ``cookie-cutter
beers,'' made in reference to beers made according to corporate
guidelines. The truth is that those guidelines, established at the
company's Cambridge, Mass., headquarters, aren't as rigid as the
phrase would suggest.
</P>
<P>
   John Harvard's head brewer, Tim Morse (whose credentials include
several years at Anchor Brewing Co. in San Francisco), specifies
ranges within which certain styles should be brewed _ from
maltiness to hoppiness, for example _ but individual brewers are
allowed degrees of latitude. Palates might differ from city to
city. Still, there is a point beyond which a pale ale, say, is no
longer a pale ale but something else. You can't fault John
Harvard's for wanting a certain consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the article I said that John Harvard's brewers
``take their beer seriously.'' No retraction is in order there.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
