<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cartoon museum salutes Garfield
 &HT;    By Alan Patureau
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Garfield, the fat cat created by artist Jim Davis, is
celebrating his 20th birthday, prompting the International Museum
of Cartoon Art in Boca Raton, Fla., to stage an exhibition
featuring the feisty feline through Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   It's as good an excuse as any this summer to check out Boca, the
booming Palm Beach County resort that is steadily gaining a
reputation for brainy as well as beachy attractions.
</P>
<P>
   The 50,000-square-foot exhibit contains original comic strip
panels, sketchbooks, lithographs, animated TV films, books in two
dozen languages and Garfield toys, including the stick-on doll that
once graced car windows all over America (and is still hanging onto
some).
</P>
<P>
   ``With Davis' generous help, this show really captures the
development of Garfield from 1978 to the present,'' says museum
chairman Mort Walker, creator of the Beetle Bailey strip.
</P>
<P>
   In his early years, Garfield is seen walking on all fours, with
a smaller head and more stripes. Viewers can follow the evolution
of his sweet-and-sour personality, plus the introduction of owner
Jon, dog Odie and Pookie the teddy bear.
</P>
<P>
   Garfield's favorite themes are explored, such as overeating,
laziness, hating Mondays and loving lasagna. Davis' original
basement studio in Indiana is re-created, with his desk, lamp,
drawing board, brushes and a big poster of Raquel Welch. An award
room contains Garfield's three Emmy Awards, various cartooning
awards and a world map pinpointing the strip's growth to 2,500
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Cartoon buffs will also enjoy the permanent museum exhibits,
including the first ``Yellow Kid'' comics of 120 years ago, Walt
Disney's original 1926 storyboards of Mickey and Minnie Mouse,
editorial cartoons from around the world and the Cartoon Hall of
Fame, honoring 31 artists.
</P>
<P>
   Walker founded the museum in 1960 to preserve classic cartoons,
including his own. He moved it from Rye Brook, N.Y., to Boca Raton
in 1992 when the Florida city revitalized its aging downtown mall,
Mizner Park, and offered concessions to land a major anchor
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   -- When and where: The museum is open 10 a.m.-6 p.m.
Tuesdays-Saturdays, noon-6 p.m. Sundays; adults $6, children $3.
Call 561-391-2200. It's at 201 Plaza Real in Mizner Park, east of
I-95 on Federal Highway at Palmetto Park Road. Mizner Park, called
``the village within the city,'' has been expanded to 1 million
square feet, with shops, restaurants, a movie multiplex, tropical
park, fountains, offices and apartments. Try Max's Grille and
Coffee Shop, 404 Plaza Real, for sesame seared tuna, barbecue ribs
or turkey meatloaf.
</P>
<P>
   -- More fun: Boca Festival Days is being celebrated through Aug.
31, with golf and tennis tournaments, charity luncheons and what's
billed as Florida's largest wine-tasting party (145 varieties).
``Wine and All That Jazz'' will be staged at the posh Boca Raton
Resort &AMP; Club, 501 East Camino Real, at 6 p.m. Friday; admission
$25. Call the Chamber of Commerce, 561-395-4433.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
