<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Thomasville's big oak had a famous fan
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people draw celebrities like magnets. I spent a week in
Thomasville, Georgia once and the most famous person I met was a
well-regarded gentleman who sold peanuts on the main street.
</P>
<P>
   Now I hear from my friend Pat Gainey that Thomasville's
celebrated ancient oak tree is a natural attracter of the eminent
and celebrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your article about the old oak tree in Mobile(Ala.) reminded
me of one of Thomasville's landmarks, our vintage live oak tree,
corner of Monroe and Crawford streets,'' wrote Miss Gainey.
``Visitors to our town are always shown the oak. Each time I drive
by, I wonder how much longer its wide, low, heavy branches will
stay intact.''
</P>
<P>
   Ike comes calling
</P>
<P>
   Miss Gainey continues: ``One of the last visits President
Eisenhower made to Thomasville (about 1958) was a side trip to view
the big oak. After several days of hunting and golfing in the area,
Ike and his motorcade were departing to drive 25 miles to Moultrie,
Ga. and Spence Field, to board the plane for Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the locals lined the main thoroughfare to get a glimpse as
the president passed. Mrs. Rudolph Keyton and sister Janie Bett
Tharpe stood among the crowds along the route on the edge of town.
Mrs. Keyton's house was directly across from the big oak, and the
president walked up and down her front porch looking at the tree
and the wide spread of its branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This side trip to see the oak was unannounced, but if Mrs.
Keyton had stayed at home she could have stood beside Ike,
conversed with him and had an unusual experience. She was so
unhappy learning about this missed opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   There's more to Miss Gainey's report on the oak and its
celebrity fans.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise guests
</P>
<P>
   ``Another time when Ike was in the Thomasville area, we heard
that he was playing golf on a particular day. We have an excellent
18-hole golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The President usually came to hunt quail, deer, etc. But that
day he was rumored to be at the golf course, so we went to the Glen
Arven clubhouse hoping we would see him. There were Washington
reporters and cameramen outside, but no local people. We waited
awhile and were ready to leave, when one of the press told us to
wait, he was coming outside. To our surprise, the golfer who came
out was the Duke of Windsor!''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Gainey suggests that golf and shopping, perhaps more than
the oak, drew the Windsors, who often spent winters at the Baker
family estate in Leon County, Fla., just south of the state line.
They were often spotted downtown and at the country club, probably
because, as she explained, the townspeople didn't bother them.
</P>
<P>
   As polite as you and me
</P>
<P>
   ``Her father, leaving the Thomas Drugstore, automatically opened
the door for a lady _ who turned out to be the duchess. She
politely thanked him and went her way.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these memories,'' concludes Miss Gainey, ``because you
wrote about an oak tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomasville has always cherished her trees. But after
Hurricane Kate ripped through here in 1985, toppling trees on 80
houses, we've become a lot more nervous. Nevertheless, we love our
shade trees and I hope and pray we'll never have another
devastating storm like Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
