 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plenty of food sites to savor on the Net
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 30: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We have all become familiar with the warnings that have come
along with the burgeoning of the Internet _ take heed before giving
out personal information, don't become a Net addict, beware of
strangers, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes yet another, although far more benign, Internet worry.
Affected are those millions of folks who jealously guard a precious
hour or two a month when they can steal away to a favorite chair,
facing no distractions, with a favorite food magazine. Leafing
through the slick pages showing tantalizing food being prepared in
impossibly fabulous kitchens, by impossibly fabulous people in
exotic settings, can be a seductive escape from busy lives _ to say
nothing of the inspiration you can get for your own kitchen. The
problem may arise because the Internet presents too much of a good
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, only a handful of food magazines were being
published. Now it's hard to keep up with the proliferation of
gourmet and cooking publications that hit the newsstands every
month. Add to those print publications their Internet versions and
``webzines,'' which are found only on the World Wide Web, and there
are more food publications out there than you can possibly ever
read. So, with a warning to be selective, here are some Internet
addresses that, with a press of a button, will give you instant
access to hundreds and hundreds of food and gourmet magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Go to http://www.sapphireswan.com/webguide/wg/recipes.htm and
you'll have instant access to Gourmet Connections, Gourmet Fare,
Only Gourmet, Gourmand, Wine and Dine Connoisseur, StarChefs,
Virtual Gourmet, Wine and Dine, Diabetic Gourmet and even The
Hungover Gourmet. And that's just for starters.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the ``Mega-Guide'' to gourmet magazines at
http://www.netfinderusa
</P>
<P>
   .com/Magazines/cooking.htm, which makes the one just mentioned
look downright skimpy. And there's also
http://hearte.com/in/food.htm and
http://mecklenburg.net/news/magsFood.htm and
http://super.net.pkresource_list/FOOD.HTML and
http://www.ahandyguide.com/cat1/m/m911.htm and
http://hearte.com/in/food.htm and
http://www.excite.com/apple/guide/Lifestyle/Food_and_Drink/.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these sites, with surprisingly little duplication, has
hundreds of food-related magazines as well as the food sections of
a number of daily newspapers. All this competition has proved to be
a plus for the reader, as many of those we scanned had top-notch
photography, articles by first-rate food critics, tips, feedback,
interesting and informative features about food, travel and
entertaining and other slick content.
</P>
<P>
   Just promise us you won't try to read it all.
</P>
<P>
   We found this week's summer recipe on Gourmet Fare (http:
</P>
<P>
   //www.gourmetfaremagazine.com), an award-winning webzine
published in metro Atlanta (Roswell, Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
