<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Saving Private Ryan'' creates ``dialogue'' for America Online
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Veterans of the Second World War II and high school students
just learning about it are venturing onto America Online's Saving
Private Ryan area (Keyword: Saving Private Ryan) to remember,
exchange stories and just talk.
</P>
<P>
   AOL spokeswoman Janine Dunne says that since the area opened
Friday, more than10,000 messages have been posted. Dunne says the
only time there was such a large response to a topic was after the
death of Princess Diana.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Kornbluth, AOL's editorial content director, says the
outpouring of messages can be directly related to the movie's power
and the need to talk about the war and its aftermath in a different
way. He also says that AOL's infrastructure and technology make
this kind of dialog easier than it would be on the Web or other
online services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everytime on AOL we get real and deal with the struggle of
everyday life, there is just an outpouring of emotion on the
boards,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the messages are personal reactions to the movie
and heated debates about Matt Damon's acting ability, the most
interesting and moving posts are a spontaneous dialogue between
those old enough to recall the war in vivid detail and those who
are young enough to regard it as ancient history.
</P>
<P>
   Comments range from those of vets recalling their wartime
memories to amazed teens who now see ``grandpa's war'' in a new
light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you loved the movie, hated the movie, found it
overdone, inaccurate, too gory, etc., ``Saving Private Ryan'' did
exactly what a good movie should do ...i t created a dialogue,''
wrote one AOL member marvelling at the number of messages.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Saving Private Ryan'' message boards aren't the only place
where AOL members have gone en masse to express their opinions and
feelings. AOL has set up areas to talk about the Florida forrest
fires and Jonesboro, Ark., high school shootings and met with an
outpouring of emotional and heartfelt response. The combination of
AOL's screen names which protect the identity of the user (members
are warned not to post their names, addresses or any other specific
personal information) and the online service's technology that
makes chats and message boards easier to manipulate than those on
the Web are part of what makes AOL something akin to a national
watering hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm embarrassed that it takes a movie to make us realize what
it took to get this country where it is,'' wrote one AOL member.
``Sure we learned about the wars in history class, but I don't
think it ever soaked in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It brought back memories one tried to supress for 50 years,''
wrote another veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a Vietnam vet and the son of a WWII vet who was in the
invasion of Normandy, I can say I finally understand how and why my
father became the man he is,'' one AOL member writes. ``When I
asked him about the invasion, he said he left his soul on the
beach. After seeing 'Saving Private Ryan,' I know now what he
meant. I served in Vietnam and did see some action, but nothing
compared to the carnage and destruction of Normandy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kornbluth believes the ``Saving Private Ryan'' area is what
America Online is all about. ``To me we are an online 'service,'''
he said. ``The service aspect is hugely important to me and crucial
to what we do. After you check the stocks and look at your e-mail,
there is one other thing to do _ to share and feel. ``
</P>
<P>
   The boards are monitored, not censored. A teenager who doubted
the film's authenticity and touted Adolph Hitler as a great man,
received many responses _ some gentle and some passionate _
disagreeing with him. One member replied. ``Millions fought and
died 50 years ago so that you can voice that kind of opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the best example of how high emotions are running on
this topic come from a Vietnam vet who responded to a message from
a teenage girl: ``You said, 'I have so much respect for veterans
from the past wars, I only wish I could tell them all and hug them
and thank them.' Young lady, you just did. As a Vietnam vet I thank
you for your thoughts and believe me, your hugs felt good.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
