<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lemon Pie, Part Deux: New take on a pie classic
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 30: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, we ran an old favorite for many _ Eagle Brand Magic
Lemon Pie. The recipe came to us from Plennie Robinson of
Dawsonville, Georgia who had copied it straight from the ``Borden's
Eagle Brand Magic Recipes'' booklet published many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was exactly what Gwendolyn Connally was looking for. But
while the recipe has been used by many over the years, Borden has
revised it and renamed it Creamy Lemon Pie.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the revision? The cooking time in the original
recipe (which appeared in this column last week) is 15 minutes.
That's not long enough to bring the eggs in the filling to 160
degrees _ the safe temperature for eliminating risk of a food-borne
illness.
</P>
<P>
   Those using the original recipe should be aware that consuming
foods with uncooked or partially cooked eggs can be a health
hazard. To avoid that risk, Eagle Brand has created this new
recipe, which we share with you and Connally. It's still a yummy
summer treat.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Creamy
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 4 hours
</P>
<P>
   3egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   114-ounce can Eagle Brand Sweetened Condensed Milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Yellow food coloring, optional
</P>
<P>
   18- or 9-inch baked pie shell or graham cracker crumb crust
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream or topping, optional
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. In a medium bowl, beat egg yolks
with sweetened condensed milk and lemon juice. Add food coloring if
desired. Pour into prepared pie shell and bake for 30 minutes. Cool
at room temperature for 2 hours, then chill for at least two hours
more. Top with whipped cream or topping, if desired. Refrigerate
leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (graham cracker crust, without topping): 335
calories, 6 grams protein, 14 grams fat (percent calories from fat,
37), 48 grams carbohydrates, 97 milligrams cholesterol, 237
milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   REQUESTS
</P>
<P>
   -- Kathy Attaway of Augusta, Georgia hopes someone has a recipe
for Apricot Nut Bread that her mother made many years ago using a
biscuit mix and oats. It may have been published in a Bisquick
booklet in the late 1960s or early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests should be sent to Recipe Swap, Food
Department, Cox News Service, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
