<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    World War II documentry on PBS
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Wayne's ``War is swell'' film legacy is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Spielberg and Tom Hanks are seeing to that. And those
who've already seen Spielberg's ultraviolent ``Saving Private
Ryan'' are likely to have their interest in World War II piqued
further by tonight's PBS special ``Guts 'n' Glory: An 'American
Experience' Special'' (check local listings).
</P>
<P>
   The 150-minute show is actually two documentaries _ one on D-Day
(nominated for an Oscar in 1995) and another on the Battle of the
Bulge.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to retired Army Lt. Col. William Friedman recalling D-Day
and Allied troops landing on Normandy beaches amid heavy gunfire.
``Rank had nothing to do with anything on that beach ... Not by
unit, not by role, everybody individually ... did what they had to
do ... (Men) started yelling, 'Goddamit, get up, move in, you're
going to die anyway, move in and die!''
</P>
<P>
   You need more proof that war is hell? This documentary points
out that 60 percent of all allied equipment parachuted in was lost
and large numbers of troop transports overshot their drop zone by
miles.
</P>
<P>
   The second documentary chronicles the nearly two-month-long
Battle of the Bulge, the Nazi counterattack of 250,000 men across
an 85-mile-wide Allied front from Belgium to Luxembourg. Nearly
80,000 Americans were killed, wounded or captured (PBS notes the
battle is ``the single biggest and bloodiest American soldiers have
ever fought.'').
</P>
<P>
   Both stories are told through eye-witness accounts. And their
words shatter the legacy of Wayne's war movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't go away,'' one soldier says. ``It sleeps sometimes,
but then it awakens again ... It's an enormity of an experience.
And everything after that has been a footnote.''
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   UPN shows to premire late
</P>
<P>
   UPN strategy has always been to debut its fall shows early. Not
anymore. This year, the mini-network will launch its entire new
season in October. Thirteen shows will debut from Oct. 5 through
Oct. 14. Here's the rundown (All times are Eastern): On Oct. 5 _
``Guys Like Us'' at 8 p.m.; ``DiResta'' at 8:30 p.m.; ``The Secret
Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer'' at 9 p.m.; and ``Malcolm &AMP; Eddie'' at
9:30 p.m. On Oct 6 _ ``Moesha'' at 8 p.m.; ``Clueless'' at 8:30
p.m.; and ``Mercy Point'' at 9 p.m. On Oct. 7 _ ``Seven Days'' at 8
p.m. On Oct. 8 _ ``UPN's Thursday Night at the Movies'' at 8 p.m.
On Oct. 9 _ ``Legacy'' at 8 p.m. and ``Love Boat: The Next Wave''
at 9 p.m. On Oct. 14 _ ``Seven Days'' at 8 p.m. and ``Star Trek:
Voyager'' at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary . . .
</P>
<P>
   We hold these truths to be self evident: that ``Ally McBeal''
needs a diary. And come Nov. 1, America will have just that.
ReganBooks will publish ``Ally McBeal: The Diary'' with more than
250 photos from the show. A press release claims the book will
delve ``inside the mind ... the soul ... and the heart ... of Ally
McBeal.'' Truth is, it will be gleanings from show scripts and
penned by former Entertainment Weekly writer Tim Appelo.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
