<HEADER>
A6834 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDBOOKTAPES-AZR &LR;      07-28 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDBOOKTAPES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LISTEN AWAY THE MILES: BOOK TAPES FILL HOURS OF TRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (With Photo Illustration)  
 (With sidebar: KIDBOOKSIDE)  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picture it: Miles and miles of road ahead of you. You've just
started your trip and the wailing has begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we there yet?'' ``She hit me!'' ``Turn up the
air-conditioning!''
</P>
<P>
   Will your family survive the vacation trip?
</P>
<P>
   Put an end to the kids' backseat whining and bickering. Pass the
sodas and popcorn, then pop a cassette into the tape deck.
</P>
<P>
   A (begin itals) book (end itals) on tape, that is. They make
them for little people, too. Buy or rent a few before your next
trip. Splurge on separate tape recorders and earphones if you have
kids of different age levels to entertain. Before you know it,
you'll arrive safe and sane at your destination.
</P>
<P>
   Books on tape also make a nice variation to kids' bedtime
routines. Engaging for them, easy for you. Just turn on the tape
player, kiss them good night, and you can be out the door! Or
better yet, stay and listen with them.
</P>
<P>
   Listening Library produces unabridged audiobooks primarily for
children. For a free catalog, call 800-243-4504, or check its site
at www.listeninglib.com on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The Audio Partners Publishing Corp., also known as Audio
Editions, at 800-231-4261, also has an extended selection for kids
and parents. Its site is www.audiopartners.com on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some standout tapes for children: &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ARTHUR CHAPTER BOOKS: VOLUME 1 &QL; 
 &UR; Marc Brown (Listening Library, $15.95)
</P>
<P>
   Young kids love Arthur, who has his own PBS television show.
These tapes contain three stories: ``Arthur's Mystery Envelope,''
``Arthur and the Scare-Your-Pants-Off-Club,'' and ``Arthur Makes
the Team.'' Playing time: Two hours. For ages 4 to 8. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE SECRET GARDEN &QL; 
 &UR; Frances Hodgson Burnett (Audio Editions, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   This 1911 classic has served as the basis of several movies and
a Broadway musical. It is the story of an unloved and selfish child
named Mary, who discovers friendship and happiness by helping her
invalid cousin become strong. The children work together in their
secret garden, and nature's restorative touch heals them both.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Wanda McCaddon's British and Yorkshire accents perfectly
suit the characters in this absorbing tale. Playing time: Seven
hours, 45 minutes. For ages 7-12. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE ADVENTURES OF TOM SAWYER &QL; 
 &UR; Mark Twain (Audio Editions, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   We all know the story of Tom Sawyer, the scrappy kid who grew up
on the banks of the Mississippi. But voice-over actor Patrick
Fraley brings the lively dialogue to life in an amazing way. He has
created 36 ``voices'' for the wide range of Twain's characters,
reflecting various dialects, ages and sexes. You'd swear there was
a cast of thousands. It's almost like watching a play. Everyone in
the family will enjoy this one. Playing time: Seven hours, 42
minutes. For ages 8 and up. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MINUTE MYSTERIES &QL; 
 &UR; Patrick Fraley (Audio Editions, $11.95)
</P>
<P>
   For shorter attention spans, actor Joe Mantegna adopts the
``Dragnet'' persona of Lt. Harry Rhyne, who lays out the facts of
brain-teasing whodunits for the whole family to solve. A short jazz
riff gives you time to solve the crime. When you give up, the
lieutenant explains his dazzling detective work. Playing time: 80
minutes. For ages 10 and up. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE MIGHTY &QL; 
 &UR; Rodman Philbrick (Listening Library, $16.98)
</P>
<P>
   Max Kane is a troubled, lonely kid, teased all his life for
being dumb and slow. He meets Kevin, a small, physically disabled
kid with the brains of Einstein. Together, they become ``The
Mighty,'' an invincible force for justice.
</P>
<P>
   The story is the basis of a motion picture to be released this
fall starring Sharon Stone, Gena Rowlands and Harry Dean Stanton.
The audio book was declared a winner by our 12-year-old field
tester. Playing time: Three hours, 16 minutes. For ages 10 and up. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; REDWALL: BOOK 1, 2 AND 3 &QL; 
 &UR; Brian Jacques (Listening Library, $19.95 per book)
</P>
<P>
   This trilogy centers on the exploits of peace-loving mice who
must defend their home against Cluny, the Scourge and his army of
rats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Redwall: Book 1'' and ``Redwall-Complete Set'' won Audie
Awards for Best Children's production and Best Children's Title at
this year's BookExpo America Conference in Chicago. The first book
also was honored as an American Library Notable Recording. Playing
time: Three to five hours per book. For ages 10 and up. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; OUT OF THE DUST &QL; 
 &UR; Karen Hesse (Listening Library, $16.98)
</P>
<P>
   ``My father's digging his own grave, / he calls it a pond, / but
I know what he's up to. / He is rotting away, / like his father, /
ready to leave me behind in the dust. / Well, I'm leaving first.
(July 1935.)''
</P>
<P>
   Hesse's prose about a 14-year-old girl growing up in the
Oklahoma Dust Bowl during the Depression won the 1998 Newbery
Medal. This first-person story, written in free verse, is
particularly well suited for reading aloud, especially by the
authentic Oklahoma narrator Marika Mashburn.
</P>
<P>
   The protagonist, Billie Jo, is very much alone as she struggles
through traumas no child should have to face. Her mother dies in an
accident caused by her father, whose self-absorption alienates
Billie Jo. Ultimately, Billie Jo heals herself, then reunites with
her father. Playing time: Two hours, 9 minutes. For ages 10 and
up. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SEES BEHIND TREES &QL; 
 &UR; Joseph Bruchac (Listening Library, $16.98)
</P>
<P>
   A lilting flute begins the mystical story of Young Walnut, a
Native American boy who doesn't see very well. He's worried about
an upcoming feast, where he's supposed to shoot moss from the air
with his bow and arrow and earn his grown-up name.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has trouble seeing with his eyes, he's developed
another form of vision by using his other senses. This special
ability prompts a village elder to take him on a journey, where his
skills and wits are challenged in a difficult test. The story
transports kids to another culture. Playing time: Two hours, 29
minutes. For ages 10 and up. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TO KILL A MOCKINGBIRD &QL; 
 &UR; Harper Lee (Audio Editions, $34.95)
</P>
<P>
   Headed across country? This 10-hour reading of the
third-bestselling book of all time ought to get you there.
</P>
<P>
   Narrator Roses Prichard slips easily into the persona of Scout,
who observes her Southern hometown wrestle with the issue of a
black man who has been falsely accused. For ages 12 and up. &QL; 
(Beverly Medlyn can be reached at Bevmedlyn(at)aol.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
