A6837 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDBOOKSIDE-AZR &LR;      07-28 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDBOOKSIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUT SOME OOMPH INTO YOUR STORYTELLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Sidebar to KIDSTAPES)  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those four words put you and your children on a journey to
castles; kings and queens; fishing holes; gingerbread houses;
baseball fields; outer space; and dark, forbidding forests.
</P>
<P>
   How you tell the tale can make the difference between the
listeners' restless indifference and total enthrallment.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Fraley, a professional voice-over performer on cartoons
and radio and the father of four boys, shares his tips on ``How to
Read Aloud to Kids,'' published by Audio Partners. Patrick Fraley,
a professional voice-over performer on cartoons and radio and the
father of four boys, shares his tips on ``How to Read Aloud to
Kids,'' published by Audio Partners. His ideas and demonstrations
are worthy instruction for parents, teachers and librarians.
</P>
<P>
   The highlights:
</P>
<P>
   _ Use emphasis to enhance meaning. You can do this by making
words louder or softer in volume or higher or lower in pitch,
elongating or shortening pronunciation and pausing before or after
a word. Emphasize verbs to move along the action.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tempo sets the mood. A slow, soft voice aptly describes a
dark, spooky barn. A jaunty pace recounts how Peter Rabbit squeezed
through the gate just in the nick of time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Change your voice for various characters. Feel free to steal
voices from movie and cartoon characters. Practice talking like a
crafty elf, a wicked witch, a Southern belle or a grouchy old man.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make the story interactive by having kids assist you with
sound effects, like that made by a howling wind, a slammed door or
twittering birds. Ask older kids to recap the previous night's
episode before you read the next chapter.
</P>
<P>
   Fraley also addresses certain problems that may crop up during
read-aloud sessions.
</P>
<P>
   What if your 3-year-old grabs the book and wants to read it
herself? That's fine. Let her patter on about the pictures and
story, but don't let her go off into her own world. Be the kind of
listener you would like her to be _ one who is attentive and asks
questions.
</P>
<P>
   What if your kid wants to skip to the last page to find out what
happens? Knowing that Cinderella eventually marries the prince
doesn't ruin the story for adults, so why should it for kids? Flip
to the last page, then go back and pick up where you left off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pleasure to be gained lies in the activity _ don't be too
goal-oriented,'' Fraley says. ``Reading aloud is not about
finishing. That's just what happens when you get to the last
page.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
