   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SMALLBIZ _ About 13 million American businesses, including about
175 of the Fortune 500, are family controlled companies. But it is
often difficult to successfully keep family-owned businesses intact
as they pass from one generation to the next. Here's a look at a
few family-owned businesses in Austin that are struggling to
survive. (Tyson, Austin American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GM - GM and the UAW are on the verge of a settlement. The
sticking point is Dayton. Although local UAW officials say they
made ``extreme progress'' today in their talks with the automaker,
they still don't have a deal. GM reportedly has agreed to not close
or sell the Wisconsin Blvd brake plant until September 1999.
(Wagner, Dayton Daily News) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   POWERTEL _ WEST POINT, Ga. -based Powertel is a personal
communication services provider (PCS) that serves a 12 Southeast
states, a population of 24 million. The company has moved
agressively to offer wireless phone service its markets, building
cell towers in a frenzied pace. Allen E. Smith, president andchief
executive officer, said ``Powertel's strategy of quickly building
out an efficient, high quality contiguous network covering
metropolitan areas and connecting highway corridors proved to be
the right strategy'' (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8
p.m. ET.
</P>
