<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6865 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS &LR;      07-28 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANTANI RETAINS LEAD AS JULICH HANGS ON TO SECOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBERTVILLE, France _ Italian Marco Pantani barely missed
winning the race Tuesday but kept his overall lead. And American
Bobby Julich barely held on to second place.
</P>
<P>
   Which is to say that the Tour de France is in a precarious,
let's-shake-up-the-standings state as the race enters its third and
final week.
</P>
<P>
   There was a dubious consistency to one aspect of the
proceedings, however. The drug scandal that has plagued the Tour
since its start widened yet again Tuesday when a third team _
Bigmat _ was implicated as suspicious medication was seized from
its van.
</P>
<P>
   Top-ranked Festina has been banished, and the Dutch TVM team is
under investigation. Meanwhile, two former Festina cyclists,
Emmanuel Magnien and Gilles Bouvard, were released by police a day
after being held for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   On the roads, Jan Ullrich of Germany and Pantani rode in front
of the pack for the last 40 miles of the race, with Ullrich
finishing first in 5 hours 39 minutes 47 seconds. The win moved him
up a notch to third place, and it was almost, but not quite, enough
to knock Julich out of his spot.
</P>
<P>
   Julich led the sprint as the next pack raced in, 1 minute 49
seconds behind Ullrich. That was enough for Julich to keep his
tenuous hold on second, just 14 seconds ahead of Ullrich, last
year's champion.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani, who won the Tour of Italy last month, seems determined
to chalk up another major win and hold on to the yellow jersey he
wrested from Ullrich Monday. Indeed, it seems a fitting fashion
statement to go along with the trademark multicolored bandanna he
wears over his bald head.
</P>
<P>
   The 127-mile stage started in the town of Vizille in eastern
France, went north, and ended up in Albertville, where the 1992
Winter Olympics were held. In between were four climbs, then a trip
up and over the Col de la Madeline, called a ``beyond category''
climb, at 2,000 meters one of the steepest summits in the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it had everything that spectators relish about a
stage in the Alps _ the grimacing faces of riders as they push
their way up the mountains, the way they often stand up in their
seats for more power, the way they put on their caps and nylon
jackets to keep warm as they speed down the descents at speeds of
almost 60 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Frenchman Stephane Heulot, German Rolf Aldag, and Andrel
Teteriouk of Kazakhstan led the way up the mountains and built a
lead of six minutes on the pack. But it was too much too soon in
the Alps, and eventually, they were reeled in.
</P>
<P>
   On their way up the final climb, Ullrich and Pantani were intent
on showing their champion mettle. They surged away from the other
riders, building a lead of more than four minutes on a group of
pursuers that included Julich, 1996 Tour winner Bjarne Riis of
Denmark, and Jean-Cyril Robin of the US Postal Service team.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani seemed determined to show that his impressive win in the
rain Monday was no fluke, and Ullrich seemed just as determined to
show that he's still in the hunt. Up the mountain and down, Ullrich
led the way as Pantani followed on his wheel.
</P>
<P>
   And as the two headed into town, the end was as close to a photo
finish as a stage can get, with Ullrich and Pantani riding neck and
neck, or rather wheel and wheel, Ullrich lunging forward with his
bike just enough to get the win. It was so close, in fact, that the
two were given ``same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Ullrich could shake off Pantani at the finish, it's
not certain he can shake the yellow jersey off his back. After
surrendering to Pantani's power Monday, Ullrich said, ``I never
said I could win five Tours. I'll be happy just to be on the
podium.'' He might have to settle for that.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Hamilton of Brookline, Mass., finished with a pack 11
minutes behind the leaders and is now in 68th place overall.
</P>
<P>
   The race thinned some more Tuesday as six riders pulled out,
including Jan Svorada, winner of Stage 2. With the high attrition
rate _ of the 198 riders who started 17 days ago, 134 are left _
the American-based US Postal Service team might once again be in
the select company of finishing the race with its nine-rider team
intact. Last year it was one of three teams to get to Paris
undamaged; now just the Postal Service and the German Telekom team
still have all their original riders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
