<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6870 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROLLS-ROYCE-325&AMP;ADD-N     07-28 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROLLS-ROYCE-325&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BMW FORCES VW TO GIVE UP THE ROLLS-ROYCE NAME IN 2003 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ALAN COWELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Volkswagen AG suffered a humiliating setback Tuesday
when it was forced to agree to hand over the Rolls-Royce name in
2003 to BMW AG, the archrival it had faced down to acquire
Britain's luxury automaker from Vickers PLC in May.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts quickly declared BMW the real winner of the takeover
brawl over Rolls-Royce Motor Cars because the name is considered by
many to be Rolls-Royce's most valuable asset.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen had paid $780 million for Rolls-Royce Motor Cars,
known for its Rolls-Royce and Bentley cars, glowing with
hand-tooled leather and walnut, beloved by rock stars, royalty and
the rich.
</P>
<P>
   But when the deal was announced in May, one key element was
absent: Vickers did not own the rights to the Rolls-Royce name.
That license belonged to another company, Rolls-Royce PLC, an
aerospace concern with close ties to BMW and a marked preference
for BMW to become the custodian of Britain's most prestigious
automotive brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone clearly made a big mistake,'' said Hartmuth Hoen, an
analyst an Enskilda Securities in London. ``It's obviously a big
mess.''
</P>
<P>
   In the agreement announced in London on Tuesday, BMW said it had
acquired the Rolls-Royce name _ and the ``Spirit of Ecstasy''
emblem that adorns the hoods of Rolls-Royce cars _ from Rolls-Royce
PLC for $65 million, a sum regarded by many analysts as a steal.
``BMW is getting a lot and paying next to nothing,'' Hoen said.
</P>
<P>
   Ferdinand Piech, the chief executive of VW, and Bernd
Pischetsrieder, his counterpart at BMW, appeared together Tuesday
to announce the details of a deal that will allow Volkswagen to
maintain exclusive rights to the Rolls-Royce name until the end of
2002. Thereafter, BMW will acquire the rights to produce a new
Rolls-Royce and Volkswagen will maintain the right to build
Bentleys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went for a peaceful solution'' rather than a long legal
battle, Piech said. But he ruefully acknowledged that ``I would
have preferred to keep both brands.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the seesawing contest for Rolls-Royce, Volkswagen always
seemed ready to put up a higher financial stake, and many analysts
were puzzled by BMW's refusal to raise the ante.
</P>
<P>
   But BMW had two trump cards: its coziness with Rolls-Royce PLC _
the two companies already had a joint venture _ and a deal to
supply the engines for the Rolls-Royce Silver Seraph and the
Bentley Arnage. When Vickers agreed to sell Rolls-Royce Motor Cars
to Volkswagen, BMW said it would cancel the deal for V12 and V8
engines within a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volkswagen had a car but no engine,'' Hoen said. Since the
Volkswagen deal with Vickers closed earlier this month, analysts
said, BMW intensified the pressure. Under Tuesday's deal, BMW
withdrew its threat to cancel the engine deal and will continue to
supply engines to the Rolls-Royce plant at Crewe in northern
England until the end of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Then, BMW will ``take over the distribution of Rolls-Royce cars
and will continue the production of the Silver Seraph in
cooperation with the plants in Crewe and manufacture additional
Rolls-Royce automobiles in a newly built plant in Britain,'' a BMW
statement said. It did not say where the new plant would be.
</P>
<P>
   BMW already owns plants in Britain through its Rover subsidiary,
but Pischetsrieder indicated the new Rolls-Royces would not be
produced at those factories. Volkswagen will be left with the aging
plant in Crewe and the Bentley name.
</P>
<P>
   Bentleys account for 60 percent to 70 percent of Rolls-Royce
Motor Cars' sales. But ``the Rolls-Royce name is potentially more
valuable than Bentley because it is known better globally,'' said
Christopher Will, an analyst at Lehmann Brothers in London. He
predicted BMW would seek two markets, the United States and
Germany, where the Rolls-Royce has more cachet.
</P>
<P>
   ``BMW got the last laugh,'' Will said.
</P>
<P>
   The new deal _ splitting brands between rival auto producers _
will mean that Rolls-Royce and Bentley will be direct competitors,
produced by different companies, for the first time in most
Britons' memory.
</P>
<P>
   That sat uneasily with the union representatives of the 2,400
Rolls-Royce Motors Cars workers in Crewe. The agreement was
``absolutely disgraceful and nothing short of a betrayal of trust
by Volkswagen,'' the Amalgamated Engineering and Electrical Union
said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement had another long-term implication. Daimler-Benz
AG in Stuttgart announced Tuesday that it would develop its own
luxury car, the Maybach, its first such luxury automobile since the
600 Pullmann series was discontinued in 1981. Anyone looking to buy
a European luxury car in the next few years will, thus, one way or
the other, be buying German. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
