<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, July 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Temperatures soared to a record 112 degrees at The Dalles in
eastern Oregon on Monday as an intense heat wave gripped the
interior Northwest. On Wednesday, heat will build across the
region, but a bevy of scattered thunderstorms will erupt as an
upper-level low presses inland from the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   With hot air near the surface and high-altitude cold air
associated with the lofty low, the atmosphere will become very
unstable, heightening the risk that a few of the storms may
approach severe levels in east Oregon and east Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Powerful wind gusts called microbursts are possible as
concentrated, intense downdrafts of air within storms spread
rapidly outward upon impact with the ground. Hail is also possible.
</P>
<P>
   Afternoon thunderstorms will blossom again over the central and
southern Rockies as the uneven heating of mountains and valleys
promotes vigorously rising currents of moist air. Farther east,
clusters of showers and thunderstorms will develop and roam across
parts of Kansas and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   To the south, Dallas will notch its 24th consecutive day with
triple-digit temperatures and warm air aloft will continue to act
as a lid and suppress the formation of drought-breaking
thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, scattered showers and thunderstorms will develop in
the very warm and humid air mass covering the Southeast. In New
England, a few potent thunderstorms will attend an arriving cool
front. The concentration of showers and thunderstorms will steadily
thin out along the front across the Middle Atlantic and upper Ohio
Valley states.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: DOOMED DARBY
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Darby weakened Tuesday as it passed over cool seas
while moving west toward Hawaii. The cool waters provide a natural
shield against the full fury of eastern Pacific storms. Only a few
storms that approach Hawaii rapidly from the south can deliver a
major blow (such as Iniki in 1992). The fortress of cool water is
due, in part, to high evaporation rates induced by intense tropical
sunshine. During evaporation, salt is left behind, and with little
rain for dilution, increasingly salty water becomes dense and
sinks, allowing cooler water from the depths to rise to the
surface. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
