<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOCK-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE TAME CAN SUDDENLY SEEM WILD  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With art, there are three forms of shock: the shock
of recognition, the shock at something merely appalling and the
shock of the new. At the Bonnard show at the Modern the other day,
the big landscapes and especially the pictures of Marthe, Bonnard's
wife, looked less pretty, more audacious than I'd recalled (I'm
talking about a certain simmering, subterranean emotion and
weirdness of drawing).
</P>
<P>
   Bonnard's pictures are best when they're biggest, and when the
colors buzz, and these paintings suddenly seemed wild in a way that
was mildly shocking.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a bad feeling. One critic of the Bonnard show attacked
him as a piddler (and the people who like him as complacent or
blind), and I wondered whether the critic's unusual peevishness
didn't perhaps also reflect an agitation that can be linked, at
least subconsciously, with shock.
</P>
<P>
   It's rare to feel really shocked by anything in art now, shock
having been the aim of so much of what's on view for so long that
it has become a cliche, which poses the obvious problem that
cliches by their nature aren't shocking. Bonnard did not aim to
shock, of course; maybe that's why he can.
</P>
<P>
   It happens that a few days after seeing Bonnard I went to ``Pop
Surrealism'' at the Aldrich Museum of Contemporary Art in
Ridgefield, Conn., much of which involves surreal or grotesque
images, what might be called hard-core Pop irony and violent riffs
on the human body _ supposedly shocking stuff, though all
hard-boiled art veterans, mimicking Sam Spade, have perfected a
reaction of indifference. Fortunately the crime scene is the Venice
Biennale, and we're sipping Bellinis at Harry's Bar.
</P>
<P>
   This topic comes to mind having lately run across a remark by
Charles Rosen, the pianist, in a little book he wrote a few years
ago, ``The Frontiers of Meaning.'' He recalls his nauseated
response as a boy to Bartok's Fifth String Quartet.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen demonstrates how we may actually be sickened when
something is truly unfamiliar to us, when it thwarts our
expectations, which is what the Bartok quartet did to him.
</P>
<P>
   True shock, in other words, isn't specifically about grotesque
or horrific or risque effects. It's about incomprehension, the
reverse also being the case: we obviously feel most comfortable
with art that conforms to what's already familiar to us.
</P>
<P>
   But expectations and tastes evolve. The art historian Leo
Steinberg famously noted that resistance to modern painting
originally derived not from what painters put into their pictures
but from what they left out, meaning that abstraction shocked
people at first because it lacked recognizable images. Then viewers
gradually accustomed themselves to judging art on the basis of pure
forms and expressive brushwork _ until Abstract Expressionism
became so widely accepted that Pop seemed shocking.
</P>
<P>
   Its shock had to do not just with the return of images (a
certain brand of imagery, anyway) but with the absence of visible
touch in the works of painters like Lichtenstein, Warhol and
Rosenquist, touch having become what people had learned to equate
with art.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen cites Wordsworth's axiom that an original poet ``must
himself create the taste by which he is to be relished,'' which is
undeniably true, although we have often misconstrued this idea,
mistaking tastelessness for originality. Invention, though it
sometimes shocks us by seeming tasteless, mostly assumes, as with
Bonnard, subtler.
</P>
<P>
   I liked ``Pop Surrealism,'' but not because it affronted my
taste, which is almost impossible to do at this point. My reaction
involved the way the best work looked oddly beautiful. It seemed
obsessively well made _ intricately painted, drawn and put together
_ and the clash of refined technique with sometimes gross or banal
imagery heightened a sense of a strange new elegance.
</P>
<P>
   Having seen this sort of work fairly often in recent years, I
felt that perhaps, almost surreptitiously, my perception of what is
beautiful had gradually been altered.
</P>
<P>
   But then I wondered: maybe I'm only reacting positively to a
kind of refinement that recapitulates what I already prize in art.
Could it be that the art in ``Pop Surrealism'' that outwardly seems
shocking is actually more conventional than Bonnard, who to his
critics seems almost pathologically safe?
</P>
<P>
   Now I'm not sure. Surprise or shock is tricky to decipher.
``This is the legacy of Romanticism,'' Rosen writes, ``and critics
who would like to maintain or return to absolute standards have
been protesting it without much success for almost two centuries.
Whether there is, in fact, anything constant or invariant about
esthetic appreciation is irrelevant _ even if there is, it must be
on a level of such generality that it can never help us in any
given instance.''
</P>
<P>
   I recall there was a Harvard professor decades ago who tried,
without success, to quantify beauty in art mathematically.
Standardless, some people today defensively embrace whatever is new
(and disdain what isn't), fearing that otherwise they may miss what
turns out, in retrospect, to be significant. Not wanting to be
remembered like the Paris critics who hated Impressionism, they opt
for a kind of critical limbo.
</P>
<P>
   I'd say we worry too much about being correct in our reactions.
Being right is a matter for pedants and historians. Of course,
knowledge and experience help when they don't lead to rigid
opinions, as they often do; they sharpen awareness.
</P>
<P>
   But art, by its nature, demands simply that we be open to what
we see and feel, that we keep looking. In return we may
occasionally have the disturbing pleasure of a certain
indeterminate shock in front of something even as familiar and
deceptively tame as Bonnard's pictures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
