<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MORALITY WARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republicans are discovering that
pious lectures about declining public moral values do not sell well
among voters who consider themselves independent or undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that people are not inclined to look on
politicians as paragons of virtue who know best how others should
behave in private life. Preachers belong in churches, not in
legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   The House GOP leadership made a political mistake recently by
capitulating to pressure from the religious right, which demanded
that the party devote more attention to a moral crusade against
homosexuality, abortion and other conservative social causes. The
religious right exerts so much influence now over the GOP that
conservative lawmakers rushed to denounce gays and push for new
gay-bashing and anti-abortion measures.
</P>
<P>
   But the political backlash was swift, demonstrating that many
Americans are more tolerant of homosexuality and personal privacy
freedoms than religious conservatives are. A new poll by the
Republican Leadership Council, a group of GOP moderates, confirms
the findings of previous surveys that so-called moral issues turn
off independent and undecided voters.
</P>
<P>
   Only 20 percent of registered independents and swing voters
approved of the party's opposition to gay rights and abortion in
all circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN poll in early July said 59 percent of Americans disapprove
of active homosexuality. But that does not mean most voters would
endorse efforts to discriminate against gays and lesbians or would
support politicians who arrogantly pass judgment on other
individuals' private lives.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Republicans have been persistent in their efforts
to chip away at the legality of abortion, trying to slip inventive
restrictions into unrelated legislation at every opportunity. But
the issue of gay rights has been relatively dormant until recently,
when religious right leaders threatened to turn their backs on the
GOP if its officials did not give a higher priority to their
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The religious right was upset that GOP leaders had not protested
immediately when President Clinton issued an executive order in May
to assure equal opportunities for gay federal employees.
</P>
<P>
   After the threat, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss,
jumped in with both feet. He attacked homosexuals as sinful and
compared them to kleptomaniacs, sex addicts or alcoholics who
indulge in bad behavior that they should be able to control. He
also vowed not to allow a Senate vote this year on the nomination
of James Hormel to be U.S. ambassador to Luxembourg. Hormel would
have been the nation's first openly gay ambassador if confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   This official ratification of its views in turn encouraged the
Christian Coalition to take out full-page advertisements in major
newspapers across the country contending that homosexuality is
voluntary, self-destructive behavior that can be cured by faith in
God. The ad urges gays to ``recognize their sin and repent.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads' assertion is contrary to majority scientific opinion,
which does not view homosexuality as an illness to be easily
remedied by merely finding God and changing one's ways. There is no
real consensus as to the cause of homosexuality, but many experts
believe it has a genetic basis over which a person has little
control.
</P>
<P>
   The ads' underlying purpose seemed to be to frame a new
political crusade that would seek this fall to label any candidate
who defended gay rights as immoral and approving of sin.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Rights Campaign, the nation's largest gay rights
group, countered with its own commercials attacking the religious
right as mistaken and prejudiced. The ads say, ``Some in this
country are selling a myth that gay Americans are not people of
faith ... they are those who want to claim God and the Bible for
their own narrow vision of this nation.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's press secretary, Mike McCurry, noting the
sudden re-emergence of homosexuality as an issue, said, ``I don't
know whether Republicans think gay-bashing is good politics. There
are some who apparently act like they believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, congressional Republicans are divided about whether
picking on gays is good politics. They must ultimately choose
between appealing to mainstream voters they need to lure into their
party and pandering to a narrow group they already have.
</P>
<P>
   It is exclusive politics versus inclusive politics, and the
answer should be clear that attracting more voters is better than
attracting fewer. In any case, it is wrong to be mean-spirited
about gay rights. Homosexuals have a right to be treated fairly
like anyone else, and their private sexual preference is none of
our business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
