u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURTLE-WOMAN-ART-NYT &LR;      07-28 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURTLE-WOMAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN MAKES SURE TURTLES KEEP THEIR BREEDING GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain, Germany)  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALYAN, Turkey _ On many nights this summer, a mysterious and
wondrous spectacle has been unfolding on the beach of this
Mediterranean town.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning soon after dark, dozens of giant loggerhead turtles,
some a century old or older, emerge from the waves, lumber up the
sand, dig 3-foot-deep holes and deposit 100 or more eggs before
returning to the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from the shoreline, a British-born woman who has made
Turkey her home sits contentedly in a house made largely of
driftwood. Without her, the sea turtles might have lost their
breeding ground here, one of the most important in this part of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, June Haimoff, spent many summers abard a boat
sailing in the Aegean before settling in a shack on the sand bar
here in 1975. Before long she saw her first breeding sea turtle,
and slowly she came to realize that the Dalyan beach was a vital
part of the turtles' world. When she learned that a Turkish-German
consortium was planning to build a hotel on the beach, she flew
into action.
</P>
<P>
   Sea turtles time their egg-laying so that 60 days later when the
eggs hatch, a full moon will be shining. The hatchlings follow the
glare of the moon to find the sea, which is to be their home.
Lights from a hotel would almost surely disorient them and lead
many to die within hours of their birth.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Haimoff, who when asked her age said only that she was born
in the 1920s, began by collecting signatures and contacting
environmentalists in Germany. Before long an international campaign
was under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a question of either being for the turtles, who need
this beach for survival, or for people who are just looking for
someplace hot for a week so they can go back like lobsters to
Bremen or Dusseldorf,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental consciousness was very low in Turkey during the
1980s, and there was not yet a government agency to defend nature
and wildlife. Many people in Dalyan became angry at Ms. Haimoff for
blocking what they saw as a money-making project. At one point they
accused her of being a Greek spy.
</P>
<P>
   But as it turned out, a combination of factors led to a
trail-blazing victory for Ms. Haimoff and the turtles. German
campaigners brought public pressure to bear on the German company
that was building the hotel. At the same time, management of the
family-owned Turkish partner company, Kavala Holding, passed to a
young man, Osman Kavala, who considers himself a conservationist.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started construction, hardly anyone in Turkey knew
about sea turtles coming to this beach,'' Kavala said in an
interview. ``After we found out what the situation was, we tried to
modify the project and turn it into a kind of environmental hotel.
But after a while it became clear that the only solution was to
abandon the project altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   As the developers were changing their position, the Turkish
government began to focus on the issue. In 1987 the prime minister
at the time, Turgut Ozal, came here and proclaimed the beach a
``specially protected area.'' As he was departing, several people
in the crowd pointed to Ms. Haimoff and shouted that she was the
``turtle woman.'' He stopped, shook her hand and told her: ``Thank
you. We need people like you.''
</P>
<P>
   With backing at such a high level, public officials began to
take the turtles and their defenders seriously. Today the Dalyan
beach is closed between dusk and dawn, and large signs list rules
that daytime visitors must follow.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Haimoff's success helped inspire Turkey's fledgling
environmental movement. But many environmentalists say that the
government pays only lip service to their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In a new brochure, one environmental coalition asserts that
controls at Dalyan and other beaches where turtles lay eggs are too
loose, and that waterfront development is racing out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there remains almost no coastal area still in its natural
state, neither for nesting of marine turtles nor for use by
tourists and ourselves,'' the brochure says. ``Existing and planned
construction has already exceeded the carrying capacity of our
coasts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1848EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6879 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWERBALL-WARNING-BOS     07-28 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERBALL-WARNING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIAL WARNS ABOUT OVERINDULGENCE IN POWERBALL BETTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As dreamers in 20 states and the District of Columbia lined up
Tuesday for an infinitesimal chance at the richest jackpot in the
history of jackpots, the man New Hampshire puts in charge of
selling tickets issued a surprisingly frank warning: Don't waste
your money.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Wisler, executive director of the New Hampshire Lottery,
warned residents not to spend beyond their means on a lottery they
have virtually no chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a better chance of throwing a quarter over their
shoulder into a glass on the sidewalk from the top of the Empire
State Building,'' Wisler said of Wednesday's $250 million Powerball
jackpot. The odds of winning are one in 80.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   While the stratospheric odds of playing the lottery are hardly a
secret, gambling experts said it was unusual for the leader of a
lottery to warn participants about the dangers of careless
wagering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a welcome sign,'' said Marvin Steinberg, a vice president
of the National Council on Compulsive Gambling. ``It wasn't long
ago that lottery directors would tell you that the lottery isn't
gambling, the lottery is entertainment. Lottery is gambling and
it's often entertaining to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay James, chairwoman of the National Gambling Impact Study
Commission, said states are becoming increasingly dependent on
lottery revenue and are devising creative new games to entice
people to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``His effort to make sure people understand exactly what the
odds are can be nothing but applauded,'' James said. ``I suspect,
however, that in the midst of the frenzy that's going on right now
that message might not get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bingo!
</P>
<P>
   Even as Wisler was telling reporters that buying 50 to 100
tickets is not going to increase a player's chances by very much,
he was predicting record sales that would eclipse last week's $6.5
million _ more money than the New Hampshire lottery took in over
the entire three years from 1968 through 1970.
</P>
<P>
   And in gasoline stations, convenience stores, liquor stores, and
newstands around Rhode Island, New Hampshire, and Connecticut _ the
three New England states to participate in Powerball _ proprietors
reported that lines are long, hopes are high, and tempers in some
cases are frayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's hoping,'' said Harvey Goldberg, owner of Stateline
Tobacco Store in Tiverton, R.I., just over the Massachusetts line.
``It's like going to the circus. A few people get ticked off
because the line is long. But it's a party atmosphere. And I
haven't seen anybody playing irresponsibly.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisler, the New Hampshire lottery chief, said he has never
before called a press conference to issue a word of caution to
lottery players on the eve of such a big jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   But he said state government has a special responsibility to
their taxpaying customers that private retailers don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine the maker of Beanie Babies saying to their
customers, `Go out and just buy one or two, but don't buy a bunch
more?' '' he asked. ``But anybody standing in line for a couple
hundred tickets isn't going to do much to improve their chances
when we're talking about 80 million to one.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisler said the average lottery bet this week has been about $5,
a wager slightly more modest than what Susan Glegg, assistant
manager at J.B. Liquors in Woonsocket, R.I., has witnessed from
behind her busy counter Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see people spending $20 to $50,'' Glegg said. ``That's very
common. We did have someone come in and put $20 worth of quarters
on the counter and it makes you wonder where the money is coming
from.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Scanlan, executive director of the Massachusetts
Council on Compulsive Gambling, said there is a growing number of
casino and lottery executives who are recognizing the need to make
sure the glittering attraction of spectacular prizes does not blind
participants to the dangers of excessive gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a sign of the times,'' Scanlan said. ``It's really
coming to this and I'm thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Scanlan said her office recently fielded a call from a woman who
was in tears at a nearby supermarket. She had spent her family's
grocery money on lottery tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the jackpot gets higher, more people who have an impulse
problem want to play,'' said Steinberg, who is also director of the
Connecticut Council of Problem Gambling. ``Maybe you and I can
withstand the hype and walk into a store and not buy a Powerball
ticket, but the next guy is drawn into it like a magnet. I know
people who are spending thousands of dollars a week on the lottery
regularly.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said 16 percent of the callers to a gambling hot line
in Connecticut have trouble controlling their wagers on the
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   While many proprietors of stores selling lottery tickets in
Rhode Island and New Hampshire near the Massachusetts border
reported record sales and well-behaved customers, tensions were
tighter elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In Greenwich, Conn., state troopers have been stationed to keep
order in lines of 500 people with waits of up to 10 hours. At one
exit on the New York-Connecticut border, more than 150 people
abandoned their cars on the highway shoulder to walk to a rest area
lottery outlet. In Stamford, Conn., police were called to stores
when customers waiting to buy Powerball tickets refused to leave at
closing time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
