<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-DRUMMER-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROUGH HIS HANDS, THE HEALING POWER OF RHYTHM 
</HEADLINE>
   Adam Shatz, editor of Lingua Franca Book Review, writes about
jazz.  
 (bl)  
 By ADAM SHATZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the percussionist Leon Parker isn't practicing
on his West African shakers and his Tibetan singing bowl at his
apartment in the Park Slope section of Brooklyn, he passes the time
browsing at a nearby Barnes &AMP; Noble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to surround myself with knowledge,'' Parker explained,
waving his hand like a baton at the stacks from his seat in the
bookstore's cafe. So what had he been reading lately? ``Oh, that's
a secret,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Upon further nudging, he disclosed: ``OK, Quentin Crisp's
`Resident Alien.' Crisp is not really an American, and he's not
really an Englishman. He's a gay Englishman living in New York, so
his perspective is right on. He doesn't belong to any of the
fashions we have in America _ black or white, man or woman. And to
be an artist, you've got to be willing not to belong.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not immediately clear what Parker, 32, would have in common
with Crisp, the androgynous British performance artist and writer.
Where Crisp has spent half a century on the margins of respectable
society, Parker's resume suggests the irresistible rise of an
insider. In barely a decade, Parker has gone from stints with the
pianist Kenny Barron to a chair in the pianist Jacky Terrasson's
fine trio to a major label contract.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Parker's enthusiasm for Crisp says a lot about the
drummer. Like Crisp, Parker is a romantic loner with a dread of
other people's expectations. In conversation, as in his music, free
association is his way of keeping his listeners on edge. His sound
is one of the most recognizable and unusual in jazz _ light and
airy, yet as visceral as the kettle drummers in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Like his hero, the drummer Roy Haynes, Parker is a natural
storyteller; like Ed Blackwell, another drummer, he has a love of
polyrhythmic subplots. And though he can swing hard, he prefers the
shadings of timbre and texture to the forward drive of modern jazz
drumming.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early '90s, Parker has been smuggling some fairly
unorthodox ideas into the mainstream. While playing in Barron's
trio, for example, he pared his drum set down to a lone ride
cymbal. Some people thought he'd lost his mind, but he figured:
``Why wouldn't it work? When you listen to Billy Higgins or Ben
Riley, what do you hear? You hear a cymbal.'' So Parker threw out
his snare drum and floor tom and just played cymbal.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Parker is bidding farewell to straight-ahead jazz
and reinventing himself as a world-music percussionist. ``Jazz has
become a marketing term that has nothing to do with what the music
is about,'' he said, echoing the complaints of many younger players
like the clarinetist Don Byron and the pianist Rodney Kendrick. On
his new album, ``Awakening,'' Parker plays a variety of African,
Latin and Asian hand drums, with scarcely a nod to traditional jazz
drumming. He canceled all of his jazz gigs for the summer,
including his appearances with Terrasson.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz fans may regret Parker's departure from jazz. But Parker
said he doesn't have a choice: ``I have to be a monk now. I have to
withdraw from the world in order to get in touch with whatever this
power is.''
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds vaguely New Age, it's no accident. Parker sees
himself as a spiritual messenger who communicates in rhythm. A
handsome, bearded man who often covers his meticulously shaved head
with a knit cap, Parker looks at once earthy and urbane in his
beige moccasins and khakis. He speaks volubly of ``using organic
sound for healing purposes,'' and likens the proliferation of the
drum machine since the early '80s to ``a nuclear bomb.'' (``I
couldn't understand how everyone could walk around as if nothing
had happened,'' he said.)
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with Parker's vision, ``Awakening'' offers a serene
balm for the spiritually and rhythmically impoverished. No longer
is Parker trying to juggle the worlds of jazz drumming and ethnic
percussion, as he did on his first two albums.
</P>
<P>
   Like the late-'60s work of Pharaoh Sanders and Don Cherry, much
of ``Awakening'' is third-world pastoral music, evoking rivers and
forests more than skyscrapers and alleyways. The songs, which bear
titles like ``Mother Earth'' and ``Peaceful Dream,'' are
sun-drenched collages of percussion, wordless vocals and reeds. If
the minimalist composer Steve Reich had soul, his works for
percussion would probably sound like Parker's.
</P>
<P>
   Some jazz listeners will be mystified by the music's dreamy,
uneventful mood, but dancers will have no trouble understanding
Parker's intentions. With its dense layerings of African, Cuban,
Brazilian and Afro-American syncopation, ``Awakening'' clearly
aspires to be heard on the dance floor rather than in the jazz
club.
</P>
<P>
   Like most self-styled healers, Parker has his own image of Eden,
and it looks a lot like his childhood in Greenburg, a small town in
Westchester County. ``Greenburg was one of the first integrated
school districts in the country, so it was like a utopia
socially,'' he recalled. ``Since then it's gone downhill like the
rest of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker's mother, a former jazz and rhythm-and-blues singer,
nurtured his interest in music. His father, who is part Cherokee,
taught him, as he put it, ``how to live in accordance with nature,
as the Native Americans did.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who is mainly self-taught, began drumming with kitchen
utensils at the age of 3. As a teen-ager, he played in jazz
ensembles and pop cover bands and went out at night to hear funk,
rap and Latin music. Coming home, he would often stay up all night
``because there was too much good music on the radio.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Parker came to New York City. Fordham University
offered him a scholarship to study religion and philosophy, but he
decided to enroll in the pianist Barry Harris' Jazz Cultural
Theater, a workshop for young musicians on Eighth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd go there and wait three hours for your five minutes to
play,'' he said. ``It had an old, grungy, dirty jazz feel to it,
and it was really beautiful.'' He paid his rent by drumming in the
Mighty Zippers, a band led by the former Woody Herman tenor
saxophonist Carmine Leggio that played at black social events in
Westchester County. Soon he was jamming regularly at Augie's, a
Columbia University haunt, with the alto saxophonist Jesse Davis
and the organist Larry Goldings.
</P>
<P>
   But, not for the last time, he became fed up with the jazz
scene. ``The black musicians were thinking Art Blakey; the white
musicians were thinking Bill Evans, and it felt old,'' he recalled.
With his wife, Lisa, a flutist, he ``ran away'' to Europe in the
spring of 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In Barcelona, he went to a pawnshop and traded his drum set for
a djembe, a West African hand drum; he and Lisa traveled through
Spain, Portugal and France for a year, performing duets in the open
air.
</P>
<P>
   Back in New York a few years later, Parker was introduced to
Terrasson, the French-American pianist, and the Nigerian-German
bassist Ugonna Okegwo. They hit it off instantly and began playing
together at Bradley's. Bop, French Impressionism, funk, Afro-Latin
_ the Terrasson trio ranged across all these styles, becoming one
of the most inventive live acts in jazz. Terrasson says that after
playing with Parker, who has an affinity for shifting tempos, he
felt ``as if I'd only been making love in one position.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker has a theory about his rapport with Terrasson and Okegwo:
``Jacky and Ugonna are both mixed, and I'm mixed in my mentality,
so we don't think black or white; we're thinking as artists.''
</P>
<P>
   On his albums, Parker has surrounded himself with a remarkably
diverse group of musicians. The group on ``Awakening'' features,
among others, Lisa Parker, who is Anglo-German (she and Parker are
now divorced); the Puerto Rican percussionists Adam Cruz and his
father, Ray; the Brazilian vocalist Rita Silva; the black American
reedmen Steve Wilson and Sam Newsome, and the French-American
percussionist and vocalist Natalie Cushman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a completely international ensemble, and that's the
beauty of it,'' Parker said. Nor is the lineup just a matter of
pride; it's a full-blown program. His objective, he said, is ``to
bring people together.''
</P>
<P>
   Strangely enough, though, the man who wants to bring people
together now prefers to dispense with his band. Parker has recently
embarked on a career as a solo percussionist. Next spring, he hopes
to have a monthlong engagement at the Knitting Factory in Tribeca.
By playing solo, he believes, he can commune with a larger
ensemble, namely the audience.
</P>
<P>
   In his festively didactic concerts, Parker assumes the
ceremonial airs of a tribal leader, imploring his audience to form
an impromptu percussion chorus. Besides drumming and singing,
Parker makes what he calls ``body sounds'' by rapping on his chest
and thigh; he also creates rhythmic patterns out of grunts, huffs,
yelps and pants.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, he's staking a claim to the territory mapped out
by Bobby McFerrin and Savion Glover. It's the kind of performance
art that works best in theaters, schools and small avant-garde
clubs where people aren't hovering over drinks and chatting with
their companions. Parker declares the jazz club ``almost
obsolete.''
</P>
<P>
   But it won't be easy for him to leave behind his jazz roots
altogether. While world-beat percussion covers a broader musical
terrain than jazz, solo instrumentalists are a hard sell. Jeff
Levenson, an executive at Columbia, Parker's label, commented:
``Leon is exploring where to go next, and it could be in the
direction of dance or visual art. The question is whether he can
harness his own creative spirit and give it an expression that
enables his fans to feel fulfilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker is confident, though, that fans will come around to his
new concept. Cosmic forces, he said, are on his side: ``We've used
up all that outside kind of stimulus _ the drum machine, the
computer. So we're turning inward, to our bodies and our voices.
It's just a natural inclination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
