<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SCENE-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS PAY TRIBUTE TO SLAIN OFFICERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Mass.)  (Eds: With CAPITOL-SHOOTING) 
(mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With their clunky strollers and squirming children,
in their sneakers and shorts and visors, the visitors from
Cleveland and Chicago, Puerto Rico and Washington itself, came to
the Capitol Tuesday eager to whisper their thank yous to two police
officers they never met.
</P>
<P>
   Not a week goes by that some police officer somewhere is not
felled by a bullet. Murder is routine in this country. And so,
generally, is the numb response. But this is different, the
visitors said. This is not some drug-laced street corner; this is
the Capitol, the frontline of Democracy, a place free of ordinary
menace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the nation's capitol,'' said Laurie Waller, 33, as she
headed for the back of the line with her 1-year-old in a stroller
and her 8-year-old walking alongside. ``This building means freedom
for the rest of us. It means the United States, and these men were
guarding it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a symbol of Democracy,'' said Steve Giblin, a visitor
from Cleveland who came here with his wife and four children before
heading home.
</P>
<P>
   The sentiment was echoed up and down the line Tuesday, as
thousands of tourists and Washington neighbors waited outside to
sign a condolence book and pay their respects to the two slain
officers, Jacob J. Chestnut and John Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   One boy traded a visit to the Air and Space Museum to stand
under the hot sun in front of the Capitol for what seemed like
forever to him. A South Carolina mother rounded up her three
children to show them that Americans can act with dignity, not just
hatred. And hundreds of police officers, from states as near as New
Jersey and as far as Minnesota, waited patiently, their hats tucked
under their arms, to offer a slow, measured salute to two slain
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Others simply said they sought to freeze a memory _ a pastel
blue sky, twin flag-draped coffins under a frescoed ceiling, the
sharp click of a uniformed officers' heels on the floor of the
rotunda _ a sliver of history to carry home with their T-shirts and
baseball caps.
</P>
<P>
   For the thousands who showed up here Tuesday, waiting up to two
hours in a line that snaked from the Capitol doors to the corner of
the street, the deaths of the two Capitol Hill police officers
stirred complicated feelings of loss, patriotism and gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the usually bustling rotunda, visitors walked solemnly in
a circle around the coffins, mixing in with staff members, police
officers and members of Congress. They clutched at their cameras
while their children looked on uncomfortably, squinting up at the
oversized historical paintings, stealing quick glimpses at the two
coffins at the center of the room.
</P>
<P>
   Parents said they wanted their children to come away with a
sense of respect for police officers and to witness the pomp and
circumstance of a nation paying them tribute.
</P>
<P>
   Trisha Colella, a 45-year-old Boston homemaker, said she
``thought long and hard'' about whether to bring her 10-year-old
daughter, Stephanie, to file past the coffins. She decided yes,
``to show her this is the U.S. government and we don't stop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an experience she'll take with her for the rest of her
life,'' she said. ``Hopefully, she won't see it this way again.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Among a public grown used to playground shootings and gunplay,
Friday's act by a gunman prompted few calls for a lockdown of the
Capitol or even for heightened security.
</P>
<P>
   A few visitors did turn their sights on guns, saying there are
too many floating around the country. ``What more can you do, and
how much more tax dollars can you spend?'' asked Angela Frazier,
33, a Washington native who stood with a bottle of water and a
white umbrella to block the midday sun. ``Maybe the right to bear
arms should be for law enforcement, and not civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Frazier, who lives nearby, said she was drawn here for a
personal, none- too-common reason. As a teen-ager, she and her
friends used to gather on the Capitol grounds to ``make out'' with
their boyfriends, ``and the officers were always nice and
helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   A few steps away from her, Burnice Kearney, 59, who worked for
the Parks Department, said he came with his wife as a gesture of
solidarity with the fallen officers' families. ``I felt it was
something we had to do,'' said Kearney, who gripped a bouquet of
flowers. ``It will give us a sense of satisfaction to know that we
did what we could.''
</P>
<P>
   As the children scrambled around the grounds or sat wearily on
benches, their backpacks slung next to them, they talked about how
the Capitol seemed quieter than the rest of Washington. One woman
set up a table with small paper cups to dispense water. At least
one person fainted from heatstroke.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Colella said she was touched to see that the government had
planned such a noble ceremony for two of its guardians. It was a
fitting gesture, she said, for a building that belonged just as
much to them as to the senators and representatives who are elected
to serve there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be a president to deserve the respect the
rotunda offers,'' she said, swiping tears as she spoke. ``They did
their jobs and gave their lives for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
