<SLUG> BC-BKC-BOSCOL-MAGLOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON COLLEGE LOSES MAGLOS TO GREEK TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The upcoming basketball season was already shaping up
as a tough one for Boston College, but it got exponentially tougher
Tuesday when Kostas Maglos confirmed he was signing a three-year,
$1.35 million contract to play in his native Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Maglos, 22, an athletic 6-foot-10-inch forward/center from
Athens, said Tuesday he was not coming back to BC after signing for
$450,000 annually with Panathinaikos, the reigning Greek club
champion, which won a bidding war with another Athens-based team,
AEK, for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard decision,'' said Maglos in a telephone interview
from in Athens, where he had returned for the summer to try out for
the national team. ``I was ready to come back (to BC). I had said
no to both of those teams, but then Panathinaikos just made a
better offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Maglos averaged 13.3 points and 6.7 rebounds per game on a BC
team that went 15-16 overall and 6-12 in Big East last season. He
was projected to be the focal point of BC's young squad as its only
senior. Now sophomore Kenny Harley (4.5 points, 3.5 rebounds per
game) ranks as BC's leading returning scorer and rebounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you notice the improvement he made in a year's time, he
certainly had the chance to come back and be one of the better big
men in the league,'' said disappointed BC coach Al Skinner, who was
in Canada on a recruiting trip. ``He had a great opportunity to
really solidify his game and continue his improvement and maybe
become a first-round (NBA) pick. All I can do now is wish him
nothing but the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Maglos said he spurned earlier offers this year from both Greek
teams, including a $1 million proposal last summer from AEK. But
when Panathinaikos, which was unable to sign a player it had
coveted, came back and upped the ante by offering guaranteed money
in the first two years, Maglos reconsidered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great offer,'' said Maglos, who indicated he had
every intention of returning to BC after taking two summer school
courses. ``So it would be crazy for me not to take the money and
stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   Panathinaikos made an offer he couldn't refuse. It was an offer
that allowed Maglos to earn a huge sum and enabled him to remain
home with his widowed mother, Maria, and his older brother,
Manolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if he had a good feel of what could happen for
him here,'' Skinner said, ``but I also think his mother wanted him
home and that had a little bit to do with it. I guess the money got
to the point where they thought it was a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that it's not a lot of money, but it's all
relative,'' he added. ``For an average individual, it's a lot of
money. For an NBA basketball player, it's not a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Maglos said he called Skinner Monday and informed him of his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, they wanted me back,'' he said. ``I feel bad
because I know they were counting on me, but this was different. It
was my life and it was my decision. I just really want to thank
them for everything they did because without them, I wouldn't have
been able to get this money. It was the best experience for me. I
want to thank the college and the coaches and the team. I'm going
to miss them a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Maglos becomes the sixth player from last year's team to leave
the program. Seniors Mickey Curley, Duane Woodward, and Antonio
Granger graduated, sophomore Damien Foster transferred to the
Univeristy of Buffalo, and freshman guard Javier Rodriguez, a
native of Vitoria, Spain, turned pro with his hometown club team.
</P>
<P>
   BC returns six players, including three walk-ons, and will add
five freshmen and one transfer who sat out last season to fill out
a roster that now numbers 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
