<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-RETIREES-RECRUIT-365&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIRED PROGRAMMERS WILL BE RECRUITED TO TACKLE `YEAR 2000' BUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the request of the White House, two senior
citizens' groups have agreed to recruit retired computer
programmers to go back to work finding ``year 2000'' bugs in old
computer systems, the head of the President's Council on Year 2000
Conversion announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Retired Persons will conduct an
``aggressive outreach campaign,'' assisted by the National Council
of Senior Citizens, said John Koskinen, who was appointed by
President Clinton in February to lead the federal effort to
minimize disruptions to the government and the economy from the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Many computers record the date as a 2-digit number and will
recognize the day after Dec. 31, 1999, as Jan. 1, 1900. The
resolution of this problem will involve the reviewing of millions
and millions of lines of computer programs, and finding all the
places where date information is stored. Some of the programs were
written decades ago, some in computer languages no longer widely
used.
</P>
<P>
   AARP spokesman Ted Bobrow said, ``Many people think you have to
be 20-something to understand this stuff, but there are people
who've been working on it for 30 or 40 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Some industries are having trouble finding the programmers they
need for the job. Koskinen on Tuesday launched a public campaign to
improve awareness of the problem and unveiled a web page
(http://www.y2k.gov) with a job bank maintained by the Labor
Department, for potential employers and employees to register.
</P>
<P>
   AARP staff member Deborah Russell said ``The money is good, and
it's an opportunity to go back into the workforce for a finite
amount of time, an opportunity to be useful, to make a
difference.'' She said people who had programmed in early computer
languages like COBOL and FORTRAN were in high demand.
</P>
<P>
   Kosikinen also said that a bill would be introduced in Congress
on Wednesday to make it easier for companies to share Y2K fixes
without fear of liability suits if the fixes cause new problems.
The bill would make companies liable only if they knew the
information was false or had reckless disregard for its accuracy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the federal government itself, Koskinen said, there has been
some progress, but it will not be clear how much until later this
year. ``We have a lot of work under way; we've got people all
around the country focused on this problem,'' said Koskinen, a
former deputy director of the Office of Management and Budget. ``I
think it's too early to say there are going to be major problems,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the federal government was doing better than most small
companies, but not as well as some big ones.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to trying to get the federal government's own
computers fixed, he said, ``we're also engaged in a campaign to
encourage information sharing about solutions. It's clear that if
every organization in every country dealing with this issue has to
reinvent the wheel, there's not enough time left to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said that programmers were making progress with
software, but that sometimes the problem was not in computers but
in microchips that are parts of other machines. ``Increasingly,
people are focusing on what I've called growth industry of the
problem: embedded chips or integrated circuits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen was reluctant to discuss how many systems have actually
been fixed. ``We're moving through the proselytizing and organizing
phase,'' he said. But he added, ``We're running out of time for
people to be organized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
