<SLUG> BC-US-GREECE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEKS OFFER APOLOGY TO US OVER OFFICIAL'S REMARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Greek government tried to calm tensions with
Washington Tuesday by dismissing the blistering words of the Greek
foreign minister against President Clinton as ``a parenthesis that
has already closed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration quickly accepted what amounted to an
apology and said normal relations would resume. But observers who
follow Greece say that heated exchanges between the NATO allies the
past few days signaled frustration with a stalled peace process
between Turkey and Greece over the divided island of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   The contretemps between the United States and Greece started
over a single word. White House spokesman Michael D.McCurry called
the Cyprus disagreement a ``conflict'' instead of an ``invasion,''
the term the United States has used in the past to describe the
situation on the Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
   Greece interpreted the change as a deliberate softening of the
US position. Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos accused Clinton of
``gross lies'' and suggested that Greek-Americans donate money to
Greece's defense budget instead of to US political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting angrily, the Clinton administration canceled a trip to
Greece by Thomas Miller, the new US special coordinator for Cyprus.
Speaking to reporters Monday, State Department spokesman James P.
Rubin said, ``When friends disagree and allies disagree, they
should share their concerns privately rather than resort to these
kind of insulting and spurious public criticisms.''
</P>
<P>
   That the administration has been unable to help restart the
stalled Cyprus peace process may have contributed to frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a lot of anxiety and anger at the Americans, who
may have promised more than they could deliver,'' said Eileen
Babbitt, a professor of international politics at the Fletcher
School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University. Babbitt has worked
on a project attempting to resolve the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Tozun Bahcheli, a professor of political science at Kings
College in Ontario and author of an upcoming book on Cyprus, said,
``Pangalos is a loose cannon,'' and he thinks ``he does a lot of
harm to Greece's image.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bahcheli added that, ``US diplomacy has not been successful
in narrowing the gaps (on Cyprus), so there's frustration on the
part of the Greeks.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, former governor Michael Dukakis, who follows events
in his ancestral homeland, said Pangalos is a smart politician who
sometimes ``lets things fly'' when speaking in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that it means that the US-Greek friendship is in
jeopardy, and it certainly does not mean that Greek-Americans will
not be actively involved in politics here,'' Dukakis said. He said
that both Greece and Turkey have expressed disappointment as
mediation efforts by the United States and the UN have failed to
achieve a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   To raise the profile of the Cyprus talks, Clinton last year
assigned one of his top negotiators, Richard Holbrooke, to shuttle
among Turkey, Greece, and Cyprus. He also named a blunt-talking
career diplomat, R. Nicholas Burns of Wellesley, Mass., ambassador
to Greece. Clinton has nominated Holbrooke as ambassador to the
United Nations, where the negotiator promised to continue working
for peace in the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of continuing tensions in the region, the government
in Athens said Tuesday that Greek coast guard ships fired warning
shots Monday at Turkish fishing boats within Greek waters of the
Aegean Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Greek authorities warned about 10 fishing boats to leave but
only half of them complied, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to calm the rhetorical jabs at Washington Tuesday, Prime
Minister Costas Simitis held a meeting about US-Greek relations
with several of his top aides. ``Greek-American relations are
good,'' spokesman Dimitri Reppas said later. ``An annoyance was
created on both sides. We believe this is a parenthesis that has
already closed.''
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official familiar with Greece accepted the
unofficial apology, saying, ``Now that we've made our views clear,
we believe it makes sense for both sides to limit themselves to
private discussions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
