<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR SEEKS TO BOOST SECURITY AT U.S. CAPITOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John Warner, who for months was a lone voice
in calling for more security on Capitol Hill, is getting new
support from colleagues since two security guards were gunned down
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, R-Va., said the Senate Rules Committee would meet
Wednesday to consider enhanced security measures that would be paid
for with public funds and private donations. The senator said he
hoped the private support would blunt criticism about cost.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, who heads the Rules Committee that oversees Capitol
security, envisions funneling visitors to the U.S. Capitol from an
underground center that could hold 30,000 people. The visitors
could see educational films and artifacts and would pass through
state-of-the-art security devices before entering the building that
houses the House and Senate chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take the level of security up to the next notch,''
Warner said in an interview, adding he intends to tap the military,
Secret Service and crime laboratories to determine just how to do
that.
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate floor Tuesday, Warner announced he was asking for
an additional $14 million that would beef up security and could go
toward the visitors center. If approved, that would be added to the
$20 million the Senate appropriated in April for improved security.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a gunman burst into the Capitol and fatally shot two
Capitol Police officers, Jacob J. Chestnut and John Gibson. The
coffins of the slain officers lay in state in the grand Rotunda
Tuesday during an emotional ceremony attended by President Clinton
and members of Congress, while thousands of people gathered outside
to pay tribute.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect in the shootings, Russell Eugene Weston Jr., who
relatives say is a paranoid schizophrenic, remained hospitalized
with gunshot wounds at a Washington hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Warner said the ``tragic circumstances'' have given new momentum
to a proposal for a visitors center that he introduced in November
with Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Senate
Minority Leader Thomas A. Daschle, D-S.D. The the proposal
languished amid concern over the cost, estimated at $125 million.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings were the first in the Capitol since 1954, when
Puerto Rican nationalists fired shots from the House gallery onto
the floor, wounding five members of Congress. In 1983, a bomb
exploded outside a Senate office, but no one was wounded.
</P>
<P>
   After the bombing, the Capitol Police asked for sniper stations
in the ceilings of both the House and Senate and called for a tall
fence around the complex, but both ideas were rejected.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of last week's shootings, lawmakers appeared to
be giving a fresh look at efforts to bolster security.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rod Grams, R-Minn., who has led a crusade to reopen
Pennsylvania Avenue in front of the White House after it was closed
in 1995 as a security measure, said he doubted such a Capitol
visitors center would prevent the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only would have happened farther out,'' Grams said.
</P>
<P>
   But Grams said such a center had merit because it ``could add
convenience for tourists and give them a place to get out of the
rain and the sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said ``the visitors center might be
good rather than having all kinds of screening at every door.''
Tourists to the historic building now pass through four Capitol
entrances by walking through a metal detector and placing
belongings on an X-ray machine, much like those in airports.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Larry E. Craig, R-Idaho, said a visitors center was worth
considering, but he added it could never guarantee safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can not create a fool-proof system in a society in which
there are violent people,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., the assistant majority leader, said
he did not want to see Capitol Hill blocked off from public access,
adding he ``hates'' to see how traffic is detoured away from
Pennsylvania Avenue in front of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton agreed to closing a two-block stretch of Pennsylvania
Avenue to vehicular traffic in the aftermath of the truck bomb
explosion at the federal building in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grams said the president overreacted because several security
breaches that happened around the White House were not related to
automotive traffic on Pennsylvania Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   There have been several security breaches at the White House in
recent years. In 1994, Francisco Martin Duran fired shots from a
semiautomatic rifle at the White House but was tackled before he
could reload. Also that year, an unlicensed pilot named Frank
Eugene Corder flew over the White House and crashed on the lawn
south of the Executive Mansion, killing himself.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles said a Capitol visitors center would be a good
alternative to other proposals such as installing a fence around
the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the fact that constituents walk in,'' Nickles said.
``We don't want to eliminate that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. William V. Roth Jr., R-Del., cautioned against a
knee-jerk reaction to last week's violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should jump at it at this time,'' Roth said.
``This is the people's building and we ought to keep it open.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., said he did not see how a visitors'
center ``would substantially change the security equation,'' and
said Congress must keep in mind what kinds of signals any walling
off of the Capitol might send.
</P>
<P>
   ``Substantively and symbolically, it says something about what
kind of society we live in,'' Graham said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
