<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-RYAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGER CHICO RYAN, 50; PLAYED BASS FOR SHA NA NA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Chico Ryan sang ``Teenager in Love,'' his bandmates handed
him a hanky as he wailed his way through the kitschy '50s pop
lament. His histrionics usually elicited more laughs than tears.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Ryan, who sang and played bass with the mock '50s rock act
Sha Na Na for 25 years, died Sunday at Mediplex of Beverly (Mass.).
He was 50.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of Sha Na Na, Mr. Ryan toured the world. He also
appeared in the classic musical ``Grease'' with John Travolta and
Olivia Newton-John. He and his bandmates appeared in the film as
the band Johnny Casino and the Gamblers. Earlier this year, they
traveled to Los Angeles, where they performed at a party
celebrating the 20th anniversary re-release of the film.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Ryan's real name was David-Allen Ryan. He was raised in
Arlington, Mass. He attended Boston University and graduated from
Emerson College.
</P>
<P>
   As a youth he played with the Minutemen from Arlington. During
his college years, he performed with the Rockin' Ramrods, a local
rock band that performed regularly at the Surf Ballroom in
Nantasket Beach, outside of Boston. The Ramrods released an album
under the name Puff and once toured with the Rolling Stones.
</P>
<P>
   He then fronted his own band, Rainface, before joining the
Happenings, an act based in New Jersey that recorded the top 10
hits ``See You in September'' and a rock update of the Gershwin
classic ``I've Got Rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   As a member of Sha Na Na, he performed satirical versions of the
the hits of the '50s while decked out in a gold lame costume or
black leather jacket. The band hosted a syndicated TV show from
1976 to 1981.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Susan (Patience); a daughter, Kimberley, of
Wenham, Mass.; his mother, Marie (Mahoney) Ryan of Arlington; a
brother, Peter, of Lowell, Mass.; and a sister, Pamela, of Holyoke,
Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
