</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EATON CHALLENGING WHEELER, THOMAS FOR TACKLE JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I._ If anything, Chad Eaton used to be the guy who
could provide a bit of comic relief.
</P>
<P>
   He was the guy who two years ago once asked the media who had
won the Patriots' game from the day before. Those were the days
when Eaton was on the practice squad, and he wasn't required to
dress for the games. So he'd stay home and watch the ``X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, the tattooed Eaton is still a hoot, but he's
showing his serious sides as well, playing well enough to be
pushing both Mark Wheeler and Henry Thomas for a starting tackle
job.
</P>
<P>
   And he's taking that very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not coming in hoping I'll be a role player,'' said
Wheeler. ``No way. I want to play. And the coaches are telling me
every day I'm competing for a starting job.''
</P>
<P>
   He's come a long way since the days when Parcells got him off
the scrap heap in Cleveland, where former Patriots assistant Bill
Belichick first noticed him. Back then he was just a crazy kid from
Washington State University who used to be reprimanded for hitting
Drew Bledsoe at WSU practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of myself back then I didn't have the
confidence,'' Eaton said. ``I had the size and the strength. I
didn't have the ability to take the next step. The coaches are
giving me a chance. Being on a practice squad two years ago and now
competing for a starting job, that's a big step for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, everyone knows I'm in the mix. The guys in front of me
know that. They're going to play the best guys. We have five
preseason games, and the best guys are going to play. Whoever plays
best is who will open against Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   His adrenaline seems to flow a little harder than most. He has a
side of him that other players don't have, and he uses those
intangibles to motivate himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do I say this?'' he said. ``The edge I have on them is
that I love camp. I love going out there. Right now I have a quad
bruise the size of Texas on my left leg. I couldn't even get into
my car last night. The coach says, `what are you on? What are you
doing?' That's what I'm all about. I'm not going to take any time
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have guys here ... they have a little nick here and a
little nick there, and ... this isn't college any more. You come
out and you play. If you're gonna be on the sideline, I don't even
want you on my team. It gets to the point where I care about
playing. I mean, Ted Johnson has a full blown hamstring, Ted
doesn't stop. He's going to make the team. He doesn't have to be
out there, but he loves to play. We have guys who sit on the
sidelines. You have to be tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more encouraging when you're nicked up. Right now my leg
hurts, my hands are swollen. It's bad, but you actually start
liking it after awhile. The offensive line, they're hurting. so
when I look into (center) Dave's (Wohlabaugh's) eyes and he's a
little sore, that's my edge. That's what makes me go harder.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Patriots came out with no pads in both sessions Monday
after a long scrimmage Sunday, Eaton was miffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was actually mad that we didn't have the pads on today,'' he
said. ``I kind of miss the days with Bill (Parcells) when we used
to go out and beat the crap out of each other and being all bloody
and seeing who's standing at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always be the last man standing at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   He played in the scrimmage Sunday after coaches advised him
against it. ``I was out there for 12 or 13 snaps,'' he said.. ``I
shouldn't have been out there. I worked on my reads and just to
help out the defense. I was trying to be a leader on the white team
with Zo (Scott Zolak), but it didn't work out. We lost.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows going from the practice squad, to backup work a year
ago, to starter is a long road. So he's realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely a run-stopper,'' he said. ``I'm not focusing on
a pass rush. I just want to be out there first and second down _ if
I emerge as a pass rusher, great. My game is strength and shutting
down the run. Centers aren't going to beat me. I'm quick enough
where if I get my hands on them _ I just need to make sure Ted
Johnson doesn't have a center on him so he can make the play.''
</P>
<P>
   He's trying to change how he perceives the coaches view him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I hear is that they think that I feel that being a
second-string player is OK,'' he said. ``Usually practice squad
guys don't make it as starting players. Who makes it as a starter
from practice squad? I was on the practice squad in Cleveland and
New England. The coaches might say he wasn't a big-time draft
choice, so he doesn't want it. Why do they think that? I don't
know. I think the frame of mind is changing. Bobby Grier came up to
me saying, `start thinking of yourself as a starter' and that's
what I'm doing. I have it written on my wrist bands: stay low and
start. I write that every day.''
</P>
<P>
   He is serious, but in a funny way. He has removed some of his
tattoos. He no longer bleaches his hair. The only discolored part
of him now are the bruises on his body. And they feel good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
