u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAILWIND-COX     07-28 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAILWIND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investagator thinks public discussion of Tailwind, recognition
of veterans important
 &HT;    By Ron Martz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the Pentagon's lead investigators on the
Tailwind-CNN controversy said Tuesday that the public debate over
the secret mission may bring long-overdue recognition to veterans
of covert military operations in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Tailwind veterans, who have been hesitant to speak about their
behind-the-lines operations even decades after the fact, came
forward to publicly protest what they feel was an unfair
characterization of them as possible war criminals, said Charles
Cragin, Acting Assistant Secretary of Defense for Reserve Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given their training, given their background, understanding
what they did and how they did it, you can appreciate their
reticence to engage in public discussion. This instance cast such
an aspersion on their heroism and essentially branded them, if
true, as war criminals, they coalesced because of the nature of the
accusations,'' said Cragin, a Navy veteran and former judge.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN special report last month charged that Operation Tailwind
targeted American defectors in Laos in September 1970 and used the
deadly nerve gas Sarin during the mission.
</P>
<P>
   Following an outcry from veterans and an internal CNN
investigation, the network retracted the story and apologized to
Operation Tailwind participants. In addition, CNN is negotiating
financial settlements with several veterans of the mission
mentioned in the report. Retired Adm. Thomas Moorer, cited in the
CNN report as one of the key sources, has already reached a
financial settlement with the network.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's own investigation, during which Cragin
interviewed several key team members, found no evidence to support
the CNN allegations, Cragin said.
</P>
<P>
   Cragin, in Atlanta to address a conference on assistance for
families of military reservists called to active duty, said
Secretary of Defense William Cohen has ordered a further
investigation into whether additional recognition is due the 13
Americans who participated in Operation Tailwind.
</P>
<P>
   All were wounded during the four-day battle in Laos which Cragin
said produced the single largest intelligence document cache of the
Vietnam war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just so impressed with the heroism of this group of men
and they probably never got the recognition they deserved because
of the secret nature of the operations that they were employed
in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   CNN producers April Oliver and Jack Smith, fired for their role
in the show, charged that the Pentagon used undue influence on the
network and veterans to disparage the story.
</P>
<P>
   But Cragin said the facts, culled from three different sets of
military documents, did not support the CNN thesis and that he saw
no undue influence being exerted on anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had such pressure been brought to bear, I would have been
aware of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
