<SLUG> BC-GOLF-NOTEBOOK29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golf Notebook: Pepper loses track of Pak
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why no angry reaction from Dottie Pepper after three-putting the
18th hole at the Giant Eagle Classic Sunday, allowing a third win
in four events for the amazing Se Ri Pak? Pepper, it turns out,
despite missing a 4-footer for birdie, thought she had tied Pak at
14-under par and was headed for a playoff. Pepper walked off the
green and asked her caddie, John Killeen, why he was removing his
bib. ``We're going back to the tee, aren't we?'' Pepper said.
``No,'' the caddie said. Watching up ahead as she played the 18th,
Pepper was unaware Pak had two-putted for birdie and finished at
15-under.
</P>
<P>
   Can Nicklaus avoid hip surgery?
</P>
<P>
   His closing 67 at Riviera notwithstanding, Jack Nicklaus might
be on a collision course with hip-replacement surgery. After
finishing at 8-over-par 292, Nicklaus, 58, declared it his last
tournament of the year and said he will start an aggressive program
with his longtime physical therapist, Pete Egoscue, to strengthen
his legs and mid-section to aid mobility in the left hip. Is that
realistic? Probably not. Cartilage in Nicklaus' hip basically has
been ground away over the years, leaving minimal cushioning. In
other words, it's bone against bone. ``I decided long ago that my
first option was exercise,'' said Nicklaus, who just ended a streak
of 154 majors in a row. ``If it works, great. If not, then at least
I'll be in good condition when I have an operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip shots
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Billy Andrade seemed to be crawling out of his
year-long slump with a tie for 14th at Hartford July 5, but he took
a step backward last week by missing the cut at another favorite
event, the CVS Charity Classic in Sutton, Mass. Although Andrade
began the year strongly with a tie for sixth at Phoenix Jan. 25, he
has missed the cut in 10 of 19 events and is 104th on the money
list at $177,083. A strong iron player normally, Andrade is ranked
155th in greens in regulation. ... Georgia Tech's Matt Kuchar will
spend 13 days with his family in New Hampshire after finishing play
Aug. 2 in the Palmer Cup, where his partner at St. Andrews will be
Tech teammate Bryce Molder. Kuchar has yet to say whether he will
defend at the U.S. Amateur at Oak Hill in Rochester, N.Y., Aug.
24-30. ... Father Peter Kuchar might have turned off at least one
agency in the pro talks that germinated after Matt contended at the
U.S. Open. While speaking about endorsement contracts for Matt,
Peter, according to one agent, said he wanted some deals, too. ...
Don't push Golf Channel commentator Doug Tewell, 49, to the Senior
Tour just yet. He's enjoying one of the most efficient seasons on
the PGA Tour. With a tie for fourth at Hartford and a tie for sixth
at Hilton Head, he's earned $192,087 in nine events _ $21,343 per
week. ... Peachtree City's Franklin Langham has recovered
impressively after missing five straight cuts in the spring.
Although disappointed to have lost his Sunday lead at the Deposit
Guaranty on the way to a runner-up finish, the former Georgia
player should retain his PGA Tour card; he stands 101st with
$184,765. ... Ben Wright, 65, whose sexist comments about the LPGA
Tour forced his suspension by CBS-TV two years ago, will be back on
the air in September as a regular contributor to a syndicated show,
``Golf 2000 with Peter Jacobsen.'' The two-minute segment will be
called ``Quite Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
