A6903 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NELSON-INJURY-COX     07-28 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NELSON-INJURY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nelson facing an uncertain future
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Such is the fragility of life on the Senior PGA Tour.
A week ago 50-year-old Larry Nelson of Marietta, Ga. had earned
more than $1 million in 1998 and was pondering a U.S. Senior Open
title to accompany his three PGA Tour majors. Now Nelson is
uncertain about when he can compete again and what the long-term
future might hold.
</P>
<P>
   Test results in Orlando this week revealed a herniated disk in
Nelson's neck that will keep him off the Senior Tour for at least
five weeks and could require surgery. Nelson had to withdraw from
the U.S. Senior Open last week when pain in his neck and shoulder
sapped his right arm of strength to compete. On Monday, he
underwent an MRI ordered by his Orlando orthopedic surgeon, Dr.
Norton Baker, and was told of a protruding disk that appears to be
pressing on a nerve.
</P>
<P>
   One minute, Nelson's big concerns were drives in the fairway and
greens in regulation. Now, he's at his Atlanta Country Club home
wearing a cervical collar for two weeks, gulping cortisone pills to
reduce the inflammation and hoping that an exercise and
strengthening program can alleviate the problem without an
operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that I never have to have the surgery and I just
have to cut back my schedule,'' Nelson said Tuesday, ``but surgery
is possible. It's something I'm not really going to know for two or
three weeks. ... There is a slim chance that it could be
career-threatening, or career-ending, only in the sense that I
wouldn't be able to play as much as I want to play. But it's not
like I wouldn't ever play again.''
</P>
<P>
   From the conversation with Baker, a 25-year friend, Nelson said,
``I could tell it was going to take a while and that he was
concerned. He said he didn't want to operate on my neck because the
neck is never the same. He said it definitely would be my last
resort.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, a two-time winner this year with $1,087,753 earned,
said, ``My right arm was like a noodle'' before his first round
Thursday at Riviera. He withdrew after eight holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nerves tell the arm to work,'' he said, ``and they had no
comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson is encouraged that the medication already has eased some
pain, but he realizes that a longtime problem is unlikely to be
solved overnight. He was introduced to a rigorous exercise program
four years ago by physical therapist Kelly Blackburn and might have
stretched himself too far in recent months. The U.S. Senior Open
was his ninth event in 10 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember when I didn't have pain in my right side and
shoulder,'' he said. ``Your body just gets to a point where it
says, `I don't want to do it anymore.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A two-time PGA champion, Nelson will withdraw from the event at
Sahalee Country Club in Redmond, Wash., in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
