<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S ECONOMIC INDICATORS ARE IMPROVING, NEMTSOV SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MICHAEL WINES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ An architect of Russia's fiscal recovery strategy
allowed Tuesday that foreign investors need some good news to stem
renewed fears that the government is losing control of its
financial destiny, a belief that has driven stock and bond markets
to near-record lows this week.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov, said some of
the economy's key indicators are beginning to tick upward, and he
added that the government will soon begin to issue regular and
detailed economic reports to investors that would prove his point.
</P>
<P>
   Nemtsov said the markets' steep slide has been due mostly to a
``public relations problem'' caused by a vacuum of reliable
information about the course of Russia's fiscal recovery.
</P>
<P>
   But the rate of tax collections, a crucial indicator of the
government's progress toward solvency, will show a modest increase
in July, he said. And the government will issue new policies late
this week aimed at stabilizing the value of the ruble and laying
out its plans for issuing new debt, he added.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, he stressed that the government will fight any
drop in the value of the ruble in relation to other currencies.
Devaluation would raise prices domestically and slash the value of
foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no devaluation,'' he said, adding confidently,
if jokingly, that ``devaluation will happen with other governments,
not ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's financial markets have been on a stomach-churning ride
since May, when it became clear that the government was headed
toward insolvency unless international lending agencies stepped in
to bolster currency reserves and calm investors who were pulling
their money out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund voted on July 13 to immediately
add $4.8 billion to Russia's gold and currency reserves after
President Boris Yeltsin decreed a sweeping overhaul of the
country's tax and spending policies.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF and other lending agencies have promised to increase
that package to a total of $22.6 billion if the government actually
carries out its new policies.
</P>
<P>
   In the days after that announcement, Russia's stock market leapt
by more than 25 percent and short-term interest rates dropped from
as much as 150 percent to 50 percent. But little has happened since
then, in part because Russia's Parliament _ a stumbling block to
full implementation of the reforms _ will not take up some of the
most important economic changes until the middle of next month.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the stock market has given up all its gains.
The price of one much-watched government bond _ a repackaged
version of international debt run up by the old Soviet Union _ has
hit record lows.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday the rate on the Russian version of an American
treasury bill neared 80 percent, up some 30 points from a few weeks
ago. Russian blue-chip stocks regained about five percent of their
value Tuesday, following six straight days of losses that had
sliced some 25 percent from the most popular index of the market's
value.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nemtsov said Tuesday that investors are overlooking promising
aspects of the Russian economy, including industrial sectors like
automobile production, which are registering large gains in output
and a threefold reduction in strikes.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that the government is drafting new plans to sell
off vast chunks of state-owned companies, from oil to
telecommunications, in a way that will encourage competition and
net the government a healthy profit.
</P>
<P>
   Nemtsov noted in particular the government decision this week to
sell nearly a seventh of its 41 percent stake in Gazprom, a
natural-gas monopoly that is Russia's largest company. Investors
have reacted skeptically to that decision, noting that Gazprom
shares have fallen more than a third in the last two weeks and that
a decision to sell now would amount to a fire sale.
</P>
<P>
   But Nemtsov said Tuesday that it generally makes sound economic
sense to shed state interests in private companies, and he said
that the government would not sell part of its Gazprom stake until
the stock price had recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Russia needs _ what the government needs _ is a very
transparent policy to explain to everyone what is happening'' on
economic issues in the executive branch and the Parliament, he
said. The government hopes to begin issuing weekly reports on key
economic issues, including statistics on tax collection, currency
issues and market activity.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Blitzer, a leading analyst of Russian economic issues,
said he agreed that foreign investors have overreacted lately to
the dearth of good news about the Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the sentiment is negative and the market's sort of
lost confidence in the government and in a whole string of positive
actions the government's taking _ selling off part of Gazprom,
cracking down on tax evasion, and so on,'' said Blitzer, director
of emerging market research at the investment firm of Donaldson
Lufkin and Jenrette. ``The government hasn't done a very good job
of getting its information across.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
