<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITIZENS-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIZENS FINANCIAL EARNINGS RISE 11 PERCENT IN QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Citizens Financial Group Inc., the third largest bank in
Massachusetts and New England, said earnings in the just-ended
quarter were up 11 percent on last year's levels but down slightly
compared with the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Providence, R.I. bank reported higher expenses as well as
increased sales of investment products.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens, whose Massachusetts franchise is Citizens Bank of
Massachusetts, said net income for the three months ending in June,
the company's second fiscal quarter, rose to $50 million from $45.1
million a year ago. The number was 8 percent below last quarter's
record earnings of $54.3 million, in part due to a higher tax
bracket, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens, a large community bank with 274 branches throughout
four New England states, has been spending heavily on hiring,
compensation, and benefits after buying Connecticut-based Bank of
New Haven last August. Non-interest expense rose 15 percent
year-on-year to $125.5 million, an amount roughly flat on the
previous quarter's level.
</P>
<P>
   Noninterest income, from sales of investment products and
motgages and from trust operations, was $50.4 million, up 27
percent on a year ago but down 6 percent on the previous quarter,
mainly due to flat Treasury bill prices. Net interest income, or
earnings from loans, leases and other bank mainstays, was up 6.2
percent year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens, with $17 billion in assets, is majority owned by
Edinburgh-based Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, which has 76.5
percent. Bank of Ireland holds the remainder.
</P>
</TEXT>
