<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MASSACHUSETTS BUDGET UP $1 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When he was lieutenant governor, Paul Cellucci vowed to
reorganize government and slash the number of jobs by 7,500, saving
more than $650 million. But a new state budget, expected to be
signed Thursday by now Acting Governor Cellucci, will increase
state spending by $1 billion over last year's total and the number
of state jobs will have risen by almost 700 people.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from the $19.5 billion budget are earlier plans to
eliminate the Commonwealth's multiple correction agencies for a
savings of $10 million and merge the state's 20 human services
agencies into four, for a savings of $127 million. Another $15
million that was to be saved by privatizing the management of two
higher education institutions is also absent from the budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's very little appetite in this building for that kind of
initiative without a fiscal crisis behind it,'' said Charles D.
Baker, secretary of administration and finance, blaming the
Democratic-controlled Legislature. ``You need the sword of Damocles
ready to fall.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci and former governor William F. Weld were supposed
to wield that sword. With great fanfare 2 1/2 years ago, the two
unveiled proposals to eliminate five cabinet secretaries, kill 76
state agencies and 263 boards, and reduce the Commonwealth's
workforce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lieutenant Governor Paul Cellucci heard loud and clear from
the citizens of Massachusetts: State government is too large, too
costly and too intrusive,'' said a 1996 Weld-Cellucci report that
took state government to task for duplicative efforts, burdensome
regulations, and too many hassles.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the proposals have largely gone unrealized, and the
number of executive department workers has actually increased by
698 people since that time. In January 1996, there were 54,238
workers in the executive department of state government. Currently,
there are 54,936 employees, according to the Office of
Administration and Finance. The bulk of the additional hires _ 397
_ are working in a new state prison.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials decided last year to change course and
stop asking the Legislature to pass all of their ``reinventing
government'' proposals. Instead, officials decided to pick off and
push small pieces from their report.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Cellucci said he understands that big
ideas take time to become law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it sometimes takes more than one year or two years to
get major proposals through,'' Cellucci said. ``I think welfare
reform was an example of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci and Weld fought and lost for a welfare overhaul in
1994, then they campaigned before the voters to change the welfare
laws and were finally successful in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But in ticking off the issues he would keep fighting for, if
elected, Cellucci talked about an income tax cut, the death
penalty, and teacher testing legislation. He never mentioned any of
his proposals to downsize state government.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the $1 billion increase in state spending that
Cellucci will authorize Thursday represents a 7 percent growth rate
compared to the 2.3 percent inflation rate. Of his five
reorganization proposals he resubmitted this year, three were
relegated to studies and two were adopted by the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   But while many of the proposals from the 117-page report have
disappeared, the philosophy behind it has not. As Cellucci signed a
historic $770 million tax cut bill last Tuesday, he reminded his
audience of the importance of fiscal prudence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the government's money, as Bill Weld used to remind
us all the time,'' Cellucci said. ``It's the taxpayers' money.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the administration's ideas require legislative approval,
a major stumbling block with a Democratic-controlled Legislature
concerned about preserving jobs in an election year and currying
favor with the labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   But one item could have been put into place with a stroke of a
pen, said State Treasurer Joseph D. Malone, who is running for
governor against Cellucci in the Republican primary. In their
report, Weld and Cellucci said they would have executive agencies
manage their organizations with 5 percent less over two years _
which Malone calculates would have saved about $85 million.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Cellucci added $102 million in his budget proposal for
executive agency operations, Malone said. ``Paul Cellucci is more
interested in reinflating government than reinventing government,''
said Malone. ``If he had any spirit of reinvention he's certainly
lost it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, a spokesman for the office of administration and
finance rejected Malone's contention as ``categorically false.''
Spokesman Joe Landolfi said Cellucci's budget proposed a 3.4
percent increase over last year, with the bulk of the money going
for health care, education reform, and money for cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, the downsizing effort has accomplished this: Five
Cabinet secretaries were eliminated, though four of the five
survived under new titles; a few agencies were merged; the county
system of government is gradually being abolished; several toll
gates on the Massachusetts Turnpike were torn down; and the
20,000-page Code of Massachusetts Regulations dating back to 1907
has been rewritten.
</P>
<P>
   ``That plan was ill-received in the state Legislature and to a
large degree disappeared from sight,'' said Cam Huff, a senior
research associate at the Massachusetts Taxpayers Foundation, a
government watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   David Tuerck, executive director of the Beacon Hill Institute, a
conservative think tank, said it was the so-called Pacheco bill
that derailed many of the initiatives, virtually preventing the
privatization of all government services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the opportunity for downsizing would have come from
privatizing government services,'' Tuerck said.
</P>
<P>
   But Malone says Cellucci should have launched a campaign to tout
the downsizing initiatives that have worked, and urged voters to
tell the Legislature to do more.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just didn't have the kind of passion and follow-through and
conviction to get the job done,'' Malone said. ``He buckled to the
liberal spenders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
