<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ABORTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIAL SUGGESTS MEXICO OPEN DEBATE ON ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In its push to create a more democratic society,
this country of 96 million people has tackled a number of defining
issues over the last several years such as multiparty elections, a
weak and often corrupt criminal justice system, and the yawning gap
between rich and poor.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes perhaps the most sensitive topic of them all:
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   During a women's health conference here 12 days ago, Juan Ramon
de la Fuente, the country's secretary of health, surprised people
on both sides of the issue by saying that it is time for Mexico to
open a national debate on legalizing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue should be reviewed (and) debated, with objectivity
and seriousnes,'' de la Fuente said. ``All points of view should be
heard respectfully. We need to be tolerant, not just in talk but in
practice, accepting from the outset that there will be different
positions.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that abortion has been mentioned
publicly. The subject is broached regularly by politicians,
religious leaders, and activists on both sides of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   What makes de la Fuente's remarks notable, specialists here
agree, is that they come from the government's highest ranking
health official, also a highly regarded doctor appointed by
President Ernesto Zedillo, who has remained silent on the issue.
Other colleagues in the ruling party Cabinet have supported de la
Fuente's call that the Mexican Congress should consider the outcome
of the abortion debate, including possible legislation legalizing
the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The initial reaction to de la Fuente's comments from some
leaders in the Catholic Church, which staunchly opposes abortion,
has been remarkably positive. One Cardinal, Juan Sandoval Iniguez
of Guadalajara, said late last week that the church would
countenance debate as long as the discussion were honest and
without a predetermined agenda to alter abortion's illegal status.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to raise the discussion,'' Sandoval Iniguez told a
Mexico City daily. ``We are in a democratic society, but this has
to be done with principles and values.''
</P>
<P>
   As in other predominately Catholic Latin American countries,
abortion is illegal in Mexico, except in cases where the mother's
life is at risk or the pregnancy is the result of rape or incest.
Under provisions of most Mexican states, both the woman who
receives an illegal abortion and the person who performs it can be
imprisoned from 6 months to 8 years.
</P>
<P>
   Such strict laws have led to an increasing number of underground
abortions and abortion-related deaths and injuries, say
legalization supporters. One leading women's health group estimates
that 1,500 women in Mexico die annually from such procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a woman decides to have an abortion, it's usually for a
grave reason, not for pleasure,'' said Guadalupe Salas y
Villagomez, a specialist on Mexican abortion laws and coordinator
for the Demographics of Mexican Society, a nongovernment
organization. ``Now we're seeing it as a public health issue,
because women are the nucleus of the family and because
complications can lead to death or to longer and more expensive
hospital stays.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Institutional Ruling Party and those who oppose
any new debate on abortion offer a number of theories to explain de
la Fuente's pronouncement.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional leaders of both the center-right and center-left
parties say the Institutional Ruling Party is merely raising the
abortion controversy to distract voters from other serious issues
such as severe budget cuts, the stalemate with rebels in the
southern state of Chiapas, and the government's request that
taxpayers bail out a bankrupt government lending agency. Cynics
call it a ploy to attract more support and votes from women to the
Institutional Ruling Party.
</P>
<P>
   Others say de la Fuente's statement reflects the growing
pressure on the government by international business firms, such as
pharmaceutical companies that favor legalized abortion to create a
market for drugs like the ``morning after pill.''
</P>
<P>
   And a few even point to the mounting political influence from
Washington, where the Clinton Administration vetoed a bill last
spring that would have prevented family planning organizations from
lobbying to overturn abortion prohibitions in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three things that make this a new and dangerous
chapter in the abortion discussion,'' said Jorge Serrano Limon,
national president of Mexico's Pro-Life Committee. ``First, you
have the secretary of health stating his opinion on this. Then you
have a congress dominated by the (center-left) party. And you have
the president of the United States pressuring Mexico to legalize
abortion. Together these things make us worry very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Smith, a religion professor at Ripon College in Wisconsin
who specializes in Latin America, says abortion discussions, such
as those seen recently in Argentina and Brazil, will become more
common as these countries open up their political systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the result of the redemocratization of these
societies, especially as more women influence politics and as more
parties try to increase the popular vote,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of Mexico City, however, it remains unclear how
comfortable residents are to talk about such a sensitive issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have trouble communicating with my children about things
like sex before marriage and diseases,'' said Adriana Montoya, a
45-year-old department store clerk and mother of three teenagers.
``Abortion brings up all kinds of questions about God, love, and
money. I don't know how I feel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
