<HEADLINE>
FLAGSTAFF RESTAURANT FILLS A KNEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ I was biding my time up here, enjoying the
cool weather between the Arizona Cardinals football team's
two-a-day practices, and decided to get a bite to eat downtown.
</P>
<P>
   With its big front windows and rustic brick-wall interior, the
Mountain Oasis looked like a relaxing place for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   I had no idea . . .
</P>
<P>
   In addition to lots of plants, a hipper-than-thou wait staff and
a vaguely New Agey menu _ I had lemon tahini dressing on my salad,
if that tells you anything _ the Mountain Oasis offers a great
idea:
</P>
<P>
   Massage.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch and a massage _ I know how that sounds, but this wasn't of
the ``gentleman's lunch'' variety that you find at strip clubs (or
so I have heard).
</P>
<P>
   This was all on the up and up. Dean Davidson, a licensed massage
therapist, sets up shop every Tuesday and Thursday, right in one of
the front windows. ``Shop'' in this case being one of those massage
chairs you lean into face first, with a hole in the pad where you
place your face.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, that hole is there so that you can breathe while
you're getting your massage. But in this case, it's also handy
because it blocks your view of the rest of the restaurant, whose
customers can watch Davidson knead your back and shoulders while
they munch their lunches. I don't mind being gawked at, but I
didn't want to watch it happen.
</P>
<P>
   At least that was my thinking when I entered. As I watched a
woman get a massage, I also watched the three people sitting at a
table 2 or 3 feet away watching her, too.
</P>
<P>
   Except that they didn't, much. Oh, sure, there was the
occasional glance, but no elbow-in-the-ribs, ``Look what he's doing
now!'' gawking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are a bit reluctant to sit too closely'' at
first, Davidson said. ``I get some people who have a troubled look
on their face. There may be an initial reaction, but it kind of
dissipates. It becomes normal.''
</P>
<P>
   That's even more true for the person getting the massage. I paid
the $15 fee, which gets you about a half-hour of tugging and
rubbing (purely for research purposes, you understand).
</P>
<P>
   At first, I felt a little conspicuous. After all, it's not just
the customers at the Mountain Oasis who can see you. Anyone walking
down the sidewalk out front gets a good look through the window,
too.
</P>
<P>
   But after about five minutes, I couldn't have cared less who was
watching. Davidson tugged and stretched my muscles, often to the
point of pain. Yet when he let go . . . ahhh. I could have been
naked and slobbering in a lawn chair in front of my in-laws, and it
wouldn't have mattered.
</P>
<P>
   Even the occasional ``BLT and a gyro!'' shouted by an overly
eager waiter failed to break the spell.
</P>
<P>
   Many clients start out a little agitated, Davidson said, but the
feeling passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, I can feel the shift,'' he said. ``That's the
whole point.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson has been massaging customers at Mountain Oasis for two
years, he explained as he moved his Isuzu Trooper in an attempt to
stave off a parking ticket. Before that, he massaged in a
health-food store for three years. He started in a Wild Oats
grocery store in Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to bring massage out into the open, and make it
available to literally anyone walking by,'' he said, as many people
did just that. ``I love working in the window.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, he's a good fit. Forgive the unfair stereotyping, but
dressed in a distressed denim shirt, Dockers khakis held up by a
woven-rope belt and brown walking shoes, Davidson looked the part
of a massage advocate. His longish gray-brown hair furthers the
impression.
</P>
<P>
   But if he's serious about bringing massage to the masses,
shouldn't Davidson take his show on the road? Isn't giving massages
in a place like Mountain Oasis just preaching to the choir?
</P>
<P>
   Yep. And that's why he's planning to set up his massage chair in
a city park, once he takes care of the needed permits.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson's on to something big here. I love his attitude _ with
it, massage could catch on everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   I say we start with newsrooms. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
