<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEEPSTAKES-ELDERLY-II-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEEPSTAKES: CON ARTISTS STEAL PAGE FROM PUBLISHERS' PLAYBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also sidebar, SWEEPSTAKES-ELDERLY-II-TIPS; second of two
stories: SWEEPSTAKES-ELDERLY-I moved yesterday; for repeats, call
212-556-1927.) 
) 
(bl) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the mailboxes of Americans overflow with sweepstakes offers
from big-name magazine publishers, a new class of con artist is
using the same promise of riches to bilk the elderly out of
hundreds of millions of dollars each year.
</P>
<P>
   These schemes often tailor their solicitations to sound like the
authentic contests, promising sweepstakes prizes, discounted
vacations and extravagant gifts. But the authorities say the
promises are empty, and often so are the pockets of the victims at
the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Most often the victims are elderly, and their losses can be
devastating. A retired dean of women at the University of
Massachusetts lost $80,000 to a con man who convinced her that she
had won the American Family Publishers sweepstakes and that Ed
McMahon would deliver her prize. A former businessman in North
Dakota paid hundreds of thousands of dollars for promised prizes he
never received.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest-growing swindles are telemarketing schemes. Armed
with lists of people known to play legitimate sweepstakes, the
fraudulent telemarketers tell their targets, or marks, that they
have won a valuable prize and then try to persuade the marks to pay
phony fees and taxes _ sometimes amounting to thousands of dollars
_ in order to collect.
</P>
<P>
   These schemes are increasingly popular in Canada, where
cross-border fraud has become a thriving industry, even as U.S.
authorities have made inroads against telemarketing crime.
</P>
<P>
   Targeting primarily Americans, fraudulent telemarketers in
Canadian cities exploit the jurisdictional differences that arise
when criminals are in one country and victims in another, while
also benefiting from weak laws and light sentences.
</P>
<P>
   One Canadian telemarketer under indictment in Seattle grossed
$70 million a year, and some authorities estimate that consumers
lose hundred of millions of dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why sell drugs and risk a huge sentence, when you can make all
kinds of money in telemarketing with less risk and a kiss if you
get caught?'' said Barry Elliott, the head of the Ontario
Provincial Police's national telemarketing fraud task force,
Operation Phonebusters.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts are under way on both sides of the border to deal with
these problems. After President Clinton and Prime Minister Jean
Chretien discussed the issue last year, a U.S.-Canadian task force
was formed. But progress in coordinating investigations and
strengthening Canadian laws has been slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen people across the continent saying, `We're
getting out of this business,''' said Jonathan Rusch, special
counsel at the Justice Department in Washington and co-chairman of
the task force. ``They have switched schemes and moved their
operations, but they have not stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   The target of choice is the elderly, who often have more assets
to steal and can be more susceptible to the blandishments and false
friendship of smooth-talking hucksters. Sometimes, too, the elderly
are reluctant to report losses because they are embarrassed or fear
family members will have them declared incompetent. Operation
Phonebuster records show that more than 70 percent of the Americans
victimized by Canadians are over 60 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Telemarketing fraud describes any crime in which a telephone is
used to deprive victims of money or property or to misrepresent the
value of goods or services being sold.
</P>
<P>
   Fraudulent telemarketers play off the popularity of legitimate
sweepstakes and contests, often incorporating them into their cons,
but they differ in critical ways. Most significantly, the
fraudulent operations promise big prizes to try to get money in
advance from ``winners,'' which is illegal. The promised prizes or
gifts are never delivered. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While there are countless schemes and variations, following are
the five basic scams, according to law-enforcement officials and
consumer advocates:
</P>
<P>
   _ Prize or sweepstakes frauds, the most common type in the
United States last year, according to the National Fraud
Information Center in Washington. People are guaranteed a prize or
gift, but the caller requires money up front, saying it is needed
to cover shipping costs, taxes or processing fees. Once a mark
makes the first payment, con artists make repeated calls seeking
more money by claiming that the value of the award has increased.
Some schemes send trinkets, but most never send anything.
</P>
<P>
   _ Advance-fee loan or credit card schemes, most often directed
at people with financial problems. Callers offer loans or credit
cards but require payments in advance. Borrowers never receive
loans; people offered credit cards get only a standard application
form.
</P>
<P>
   _ Investment schemes. Victims are sold securities or goods that
appear to offer high profit, but often the products don't exist or
are almost worthless. Because returns on legitimate investments may
not be realized for long periods, these schemes can go undetected
for months.
</P>
<P>
   _ Foreign lottery scams. People are offered a chance to
``invest'' individually or as part of a club in tickets for
well-known foreign lotteries, such as the Irish Sweepstakes.
Victims are often deceived about the chances of winning.
</P>
<P>
   _ Recovery rooms. In perhaps the most insidious scheme, callers
claiming to be lawyers or government officials promise to help
people who have lost money to scams recover the losses _ for an
advance fee. The callers may be the same people who defrauded the
victim initially, or they may have bought names of victims from
other telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
