<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOU </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO DO WHEN YOU WIN THE POWERBALL 
</HEADLINE>
 WON-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CLAY THOMPSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Ok, let's say for the sake of argument that you defy
the 80.1-million-to-1 odds and win the $250 million Powerball
jackpot tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Someone has to win it sooner or later, so let's assume
it's you.
</P>
<P>
   If you opted for the cash payout, you just won, depending on
your state's tax rate, roughly $132 million, after state and
federal taxes, or, if you took the annuity, about $6.7 million a
year for 25 years, again after taxes. Quit whining about the taxes.
You paid $1 for a ticket and now, by the random grace of some
numbered balls, you are as rich as sin.
</P>
<P>
   What are you going to do now?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, don't lose your ticket. The lottery office isn't
going to be open until Thursday morning and, knowing you, a lot
could happen to that ticket in the meantime. Don't go showing it
off to the neighbors, and for heaven's sake, don't let the dog
anywhere near it. Seal it in a baggie and put it in the freezer. Go
to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Next, first thing Thursday morning, get the ticket out of the
freezer, double check the numbers, kiss the ticket, dance around
the kitchen laughing hysterically, and then put it back in the
freezer. Call in sick. Have some coffee. Then get on the phone and
find the best tax lawyer/investment counselor/money manager you
can. Ask them what to do. Then do whatever you want. You're rich.
</P>
<P>
   Ok, next: Move. You're rich. You can afford to live somewhere
lse, preferably some place with better weather and no state income
tax. You can always come back to visit. In your private jet.
</P>
<P>
   Do you tell anyone that you won? You don't have to. Your
anonymity can be arranged.
</P>
<P>
   You realize, of course, that within one hour of your name being
made public you are going to have blood kin you never knew existed.
Plus, every television, radio or newspaper reporter and
photographer in a 300-mile radius is going to be camped on your
lawn.
</P>
<P>
   As fair and responsible members of the press, they are going pry
into every nook and cranny of your life, including that little
incident in the sixth grade, and - this is guaranteed - they are
going to hate you. They are going to hate you because you are
undeservingly rich and they aren't. In fact, you haven't even won
yet and they already hate you because you might win and they won't.
</P>
<P>
   So, best keep a lid on it. Besides, being anonymous offers more
possibilities for fun. Take $10,000 - what's 10 grand to you, big
shot? - go to the mall, stop the first person who strikes your
fancy, say, `Here's $10,000,'' and walk away. That would be
extremely cool.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, you really should give away a fair amount of
money - 10 percent at least. It's the decent thing to do and you
know it. Just write out a check to your favorite charity, walk into
their office and hand it to the receptionist and walk out.
</P>
<P>
   You could give it all away. That would be something. You could
just give it all away to set an example for the rest of us about
charity and rejecting the culture of materialism. Of course, the
rest of us would think you were an idiot.
</P>
<P>
   This also would be extremely cool: Assuming you have enough,
secretly buy up controlling interest in your company, keep going to
work as if nothing had happened and wait patiently for some SOB to
cross you. Then have them fired.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you do, don't do anything trashy. If you're going to
buy a new car or jewelry or a house, buy something tasteful. On the
other hand, if you bought something trashy, it would make the rest
of us feel somewhat better. We could sniff and tsk, tsk and assure
each other that if we had won, we would have had better taste.
</P>
<P>
   An acquintance said that if he won, he would fill a big garbage
can with $100 bills, pour it out on his bed and roll around in it
naked. This, while not trashy, is not an image one cares to dwell
on.
</P>
<P>
   Just remember, money can't buy happiness, although for $133
million you could buy some really major giggles. The history of
lotteries is full of people whose lives were ruined by wealth, who
died broke and disillusioned.
</P>
<P>
   So if you spend your millions foolishly and have only grief and
unhappiness to show for it, don't come crying around to us with
your sad story. We already hate you. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
