<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6931 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWEEPSTAKES-ELDERLY-I     07-28 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEEPSTAKES-ELDERLY-II-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: other telemarketers.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In recent years, the Federal Trade Commission and other federal
and state agencies have brought hundreds of civil and criminal
fraud cases against operators of direct-mail and telemarketing
schemes disguised as legitimate sweepstakes and contests.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the biggest civil cases, a Southern California firm,
Direct American Marketers Inc., sought bankruptcy protection last
year after a Missouri judge ordered it to pay $8.6 million for
misleading consumers. The company was accused in several states of
mailing authentic-looking checks for $7,500 and urging people to
call a 900 number for details on how to collect the money.
</P>
<P>
   The small print on the back said the average call would cost
$30; some people paid as much as $400. In exchange, most people
received a check for $1. In Missouri alone, the company pocketed
$4.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Until the mid-1990s, most telemarketing frauds in the United
States were run out of boiler rooms where 20 or 30 people made
calls simultaneously. Often a single operation took tens of
millions of dollars a year from thousands of victims.
</P>
<P>
   Investigating and prosecuting were difficult because victims
were usually far apart and because many were elderly and reluctant
or unable to testify. Authorities knew where the boiler rooms were
and what they were doing, but efforts to attack them were
ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Two undercover operations developed new tools to counter those
problems. The first was Operation Disconnect, in which FBI agent,
Timothy Healy posed as a salesman with an automatic dialing machine
supposedly capable of placing 12,000 calls a day.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the machine gave him access to top-level fraudulent
telemarketers, Healy gathered evidence on their operations from
1991 to 1993. The result was 300 convictions in 15 cities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next came Operation Senior Sentinel, which capitalized on con
artists' penchant for going after the same victims repeatedly. The
FBI and Justice Department, with help from the American Association
of Retired Persons, identified elderly people who had been victims
of previous schemes and recorded their calls from telemarketers.
The investigation was coordinated with state and local authorities
across the country and has led to 1,000 convictions since the end
of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Today's swindlers are more likely to set up smaller operations
in hotel rooms or apartments. Such operations are called ``rip and
tears'' because they can be dismantled and moved quickly, and
operators rely on cell phones to make detection tougher.
</P>
<P>
   THE REFUGE: North of the Border, A Homegrown Industry &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only a few American telemarketers sought refuge in Canada after
the crackdown. Most of the fraudulent operators in Canada,
authorities say, are homegrown. And telemarketing fraud aimed at
Americans has risen steadily since late 1995. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Police say at least 50 rooms are operating in Toronto, 30 in
Montreal and 20 to 30 in Vancouver. There also are countless
smaller rip-and-tear operators. Montreal police said they know of
200 active mail drops used by telemarketers in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Even though police may log dozens of complaints about a
telemarketing operation, stopping one is difficult, particularly
when the victims are across the border, as half the victims of
Canadian telemarketing fraud are, according to police data.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials in both countries say their cooperation is
improving, but investigations and prosecutions involving two
jurisdictions still are slow and complex. Formal approval for
investigations commonly takes six months. If charges are filed,
extraditing Canadians to the United States, where the victims are
and the sentences are tougher, takes time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fraud on this scale involves levels of planning and
coordination. An operation needs a large number of telephone lines
or cell phones, a script, people to place calls and a list of
potential victims. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The appetite for victims is insatiable. Even a small operation
makes thousands of calls a day. The highest prices are paid for
``suckers lists,'' which carry names and phone numbers of people
who have lost money before. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The demand for names spawned a cottage industry of
semi-legitimate businesses known as ``lead companies'' that provide
names and phone numbers of people who have bought goods through
legitimate sweepstakes. The lists can be bought from sweepstakes
companies and direct-mail businesses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Police said some lead companies also buy names of victims from
fraudulent telemarketers, so the telemarketers collect twice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the companies also run phony sweepstakes, offering a
vacation or car to people who send in entries, unwittingly
providing telemarketers their name, address and phone number. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Prices can go up to $3 a name for previous victims on a
suckers list,'' said Laurier Quesnel, a police sergeant who heads a
14-member telemarketing fraud unit in Montreal. ``When we go into a
boiler room, we find boxes and boxes of lead names.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most lead companies are in the United States. Police on both
sides of the border say they have difficulty cracking down on them
because the owners claim to have no knowledge of what is done with
the lists they sell.
</P>
<P>
   THE PITCH: Painting a Picture And Picking a Pocket
</P>
<P>
   The heart of telemarketing fraud is the pitch. The callers learn
by example and through trial and error how to create fantasies and
instill trust in their victims. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're doing as a salesman, what we are doing, is
painting a picture,'' one telemarketer said in a conversation
recorded by the FBI. ``Soon as they pick up the phone, and I get on
the phone with them, my hand is on the way. My hand goes, two hands
go, through the phone. One hand goes up the wall and starts
painting pictures, the other hand is in their checkbook and writing
it out.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6932 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWEEPSTAKES-ELDERLY-I     07-28 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEEPSTAKES-ELDERLY-II-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: it out.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some con artists spend weeks setting up victims for big losses.
They call two or three times a day to gossip. One in Toronto sent
an elderly woman a new puppy after her dog died, police said.
Sometimes theirs is the only voice an elderly person living alone
hears on a regular basis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We targeted people who were homebound,'' one explained at a
sentencing hearing in California. ``It was kind of like
entertainment for the homebound.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And they often do their homework. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helen Cole, a retired dean of women at the University of
Massachusetts, found herself tricked by a man who identified
himself as Richard. He knew many details of her life, including
which charities she supported and how much she loved the
university. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard claimed falsely that he was from American Family
Publishers, the big sweepstakes company, and that she had won $2
million. Another $2 million, he said, would go to the university to
endow a scholarship in her name. He said that he and Ed McMahon, a
representative of the real sweepstakes, would deliver the money.
But first Mrs. Cole, an 88-year-old widow, would have to send
$20,000 for a bond to cover taxes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I said I couldn't come up with that much, he said he was
willing to help pay for the bond because he would get a bonus,''
she said. ``He said he discussed it with his wife and they would
take out a second mortgage on their home to pay half the bond. I
sent him my $10,000.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cole ultimately sent Richard $80,000 over several months,
cashing in her stocks and other investments. He stopped calling
only after she told him she had run out of money. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I was a gullible fool,'' Mrs. Cole said. ``But this
guy, he was so persuasive.''
</P>
<P>
   In dozens of interviews in Canada and the United States, victims
and the police marveled at the smoothness of the telemarketers'
pitches. Relatives said they were unable to convince victims that
they were being conned.
</P>
<P>
   Police said elderly victims often ignore hard evidence. Since
September 1995, for example, Montreal police have intercepted and
returned $7.5 million in courier mail deliveries to known
telemarketing mail drops and rooms, most of it from Americans. But
victims are not always grateful. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't believe us,'' Quesnel said. ``The telemarketer is a
lot more convincing than we are on the phone. We returned one check
six times to the same person.''
</P>
<P>
   THE MARK: Twice Bitten, But No Less Shy
</P>
<P>
   In March 1996, Leo Flaming, a wealthy retired lumber man from
West Fargo, N.D., began getting calls from two men who said they
were from Montreal and specialized in selling unclaimed estates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said there was a $16 million estate,'' Flaming, 83, said
in an interview. ``They said in Canada people leave an estate and
if no one claims it they put it on the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Flaming said he was told he could pay $500,000 and the estate
would be converted into certified checks with $16 million that
would send him certified checks worth $16 million. ``I said I
wasn't interested,'' he said. ``It sounded too good. Two weeks
later they called back. I said no. They called every day and I did
some research and finally I sent them a check.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flaming said he and a business partner put up the $500,000 and
mailed it to Montego Bay, Jamaica. For two weeks, he said, the
callers offered excuses for delays in sending him the $16 million.
Then there was silence.
</P>
<P>
   Flaming said he hired a lawyer and a private investigator, but
no one could locate the men. A later police inquiry discovered that
the check had been cashed at a currency exchange in Montreal. The
callers had strung Flaming along only until the check cleared.
</P>
<P>
   After that experience, Flaming said, he was bombarded with
similar schemes. ``Once they got my name, boy did I get telephone
calls,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Flaming said he rebuffed all callers except one. He sent $10,000
to a woman in Montreal who said he had won a lottery. He also sent
her an airplane ticket so she could deliver his winnings in person,
but he and his wife were left standing at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``She seemed like a very nice girl over the phone,'' he
explained. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flaming insisted that he lost only $260,000 in the schemes and
that he participated in no others. But an investigation by the FBI
determined that Flaming lost far more money. Because he had waited
nearly a year to complain, the trail was cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flaming has now expended somewhere in the vicinity of $700,000
to $800,000 and will take no advice from anyone regarding this
matter,'' the FBI report said.
</P>
<P>
   In June, a worker at the Federal Express plant in Memphis
telephoned Operation Phonebusters in Canada. She said a man named
Flaming was sending a package to a known fraudulent telemarketing
operation in Montreal. The package was returned to him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
