</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEEPSTAKES-ELDERLY-II-TIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIFFERENCES BETWEEN LEGAL TELEMARKETING AND SCAMS: A PRIMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sidebar with SWEEPSTAKES-ELDERLY-II) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following are tips from government agencies and nonprofit
organizations on how to distinguish legitimate telemarketing calls
from scams:
</P>
<P>
   _ If you have really won a prize, you do not have to send money
in advance or provide your credit card number to receive it.
</P>
<P>
   _ You do not have to call to claim a prize. Legitimate companies
notify you in writing.
</P>
<P>
   _ You do not have to buy anything to enter a legitimate contest.
</P>
<P>
   _ In most jurisdictions, it is illegal to request a fee in
advance to obtain a loan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask for information in writing. Wait at least 24 hours to
evaluate a proposal. Discuss it with other people.
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Retired Persons has developed
programs to help its members protect themselves from fraud. The
organization found that a key difference between victims and those
who avoid the scams is the ability to simply hang up. It stresses
the need to plan ahead and know what to say when a stranger calls,
because the longer a person stays on the line, the greater the
chance they will become a victim.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission, which enforces telemarketing
rules, offers two free booklets, `Tips Sheet' and `Bookmark,' that
contain advice and information about consumer rights under
telemarketing laws. Write to the FTC Public Reference Branch, Room
130, 6th Street and Pennsylvania Avenue NW, Washington, D.C. 20580.
The commission also has a web site at www.ftc.gov.
</P>
<P>
   People who think they have been victimized can call their state
attorney general's office. They also can seek help from the
National Fraud Information Center, a nonprofit organization
affiliated with the National Consumers League. The toll-free number
is 800-876-7060. The web site is www.fraud.org.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Phonebusters is a task force set up by the Ontario
Provincial Police in Canada to combat telemarketing fraud. It
collects data on specific companies and pitches and shares it with
law-enforcement officials in Canada and the United States. The
toll-free number, which can be used from the United States, is
888-495-8501. The web site is www.gov.on.ca/phonebusters.
</P>
</TEXT>
