<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURNED-BOY-SUSPECT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE ATTORNEY SAYS `TERRIFIED' TEXAS TEEN DID NOT BURN BOY, 8  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAUL McKAY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONROE, Texas _ The teen-ager accused of dousing an 8-year-old
East Texas boy with gasoline and setting him on fire on his
birthday denies any involvement in the offense and was
``terrified'' into giving an incriminating statement, the youth's
defense attorney said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer William E. ``Bill'' Hall said 13-year-old Don Wilburn
Collins _ whose request for release from detention was denied by a
judge Tuesday _ may have been pressured into telling investigators
he was present on June 28 when Robert Middleton was splashed with
gasoline and burned over 99 percent of his body in the rural
Splendora-area subdivision where the boys were neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County investigators maintain that Collins _ who is
in custody in the juvenile justice system on allegations of
aggravated assault and injury to a child _ gave a statement when he
was taken into custody July 2 in which he admitted being present
when Robert was burned. Investigators have said he blamed another
boy who lives near the neighborhood northwest of Splendora for the
assault.
</P>
<P>
   Splendora is about 30 miles north of downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, however, said Collins was ``scared to death'' and
``terrified'' into giving the incriminating statement shortly after
he was picked up by police and taken into custody at gunpoint while
television news crews hovered around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a gangbusters arrest,'' Hall said. ``Guns were pulled
on him The media was there. It's entirely conceivable to me how,
after he was snatched up that way, that adults could get him to say
anything they wanted him to say. It's obvious to me that the
investigators had already made up their minds that he had done
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``He denies any involvement whatsoever,'' Hall said of Collins.
``He was terrified when he gave the statement. It's quite possible
he told (investigators) what they wanted to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   According to court papers, Robert _ who is in critical condition
at the Shriners Burns Hospital-Galveston where he is being treated
_ told his mother and two nurses that ``Don did it'' before
sheriff's investigators obtained a warrant and took Collins into
custody.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Robert's sensitive condition, investigators say they
have not been able to obtain a detailed statement from him as to
what exactly did happen to him on the wooded trail where he was
burned a short distance from his home.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was living with relatives next door to the Middleton
family at the time of the episode. Court documents allege that
Collins had threatened to hurt Robert on the day of the burning
because Robert, who was celebrating his eighth birthday, reported
to his father that Collins had stolen his fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of Collins _ who have maintained since his arrest that
the teen-ager is innocent _ say his mother died several years ago.
His father has not been identified.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Green, a Conroe lawyer who has been appointed by
juvenile Judge Mason Martin as Collins' temporary guardian,
declined comment about the teen Tuesday after Judge Mason Martin
ordered a psychological evaluation on the teen-ager and scheduled
another detention hearing for Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Collins wept Tuesday after Martin refused to release him.
Prosecutor Bill Pattillo told the judge that the teen would be a
flight risk and argued that further detention would be in Collins'
best interest because threats have been made on his life.
</P>
<P>
   Pattillo also cited the seriousness of the offense as reason
enough to keep Collins in the county's juvenile detention center, a
lockup in which he has been held since his arrest earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
   But Hall urged Martin to release the youth to the custody of an
uncle, noting that ``a 13-year-old boy can't go far on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge gave no reason for not releasing him at this time,
and I don't want to be putting words in the judge's mouth,'' Hall
said. ``But it's my understanding that he's not even going to
consider releasing him until a psychological evaluation can be
done, and I can't argue with that. I think it's important that we
get a psychological evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was obviously disappointed that he couldn't be released
today so that he can be with people he loves. But I'm optimistic
he's going to be released soon. Arrangements have been made for him
to be taken to a safe place within the county's jurisdiction if he
is released.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been discussed and tentatively arranged.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
