<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: BUSINESS AIR FARES LEVEL OFF; CLAIM FREQUENT-FLIER
MILES; DISNEY SHIP SETS SAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: Also moved in ``t'' category.) 
(mk) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't look now, but typical business air fares finally appear to
be holding steady. The reasons why are a matter of some dispute.
But after having to contend with steadily rising fares from 1995
through 1997, as the airline industry struggled to return to
financial health after its $14 billion hemorrhage in the first half
of the decade, business travelers are likely to welcome any
leveling off, whatever the reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent evidence of stability is contained in the
American Express domestic air fare index, which shows that from
October 1997 through May of this year, typical one-way business
fares rose only 1 percent, to $452. In contrast, those fares
climbed 16 percent in 1997 over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   In its first-ever domestic air fare report, released a week ago,
the Air Transport Association found that average ticket prices
overall (that is, business and leisure fares combined) increased
last month only 2.2 percent over fares in June 1997. So far this
year, the association added, average fares remained relatively
unchanged, increasing only 1.7 percent for a 1,000-mile one-way
trip, to $141.80 from $139.38.
</P>
<P>
   In an obvious dig at American Express, which has compiled its
fares index for eight years, the association said its report ``is
based on actual prices paid by the vast majority of the flying
public,'' rather than relying ``on estimates or only on tickets
purchased by customers of a particular company or on a limited
number of routes.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Abernathy, manager of public affairs for American
Express, shrugged off the implied criticism. ``In all the years
we've put out the index, we haven't heard a word out of them,'' she
said of the association.
</P>
<P>
   Differences aside, there is general agreement that stable fares
are not the result of a single event, but a combination of factors.
Corporate travel managers cite the success of negotiated discount
fares and corporate policies that impose restrictions on everything
from what carriers to fly to flight times to routes and even to
preferred airports. But the main reason, many business travelers
say, is that the airlines are almost certainly responding to
election-year pressures from Washington, which is hinting that it
may reregulate some air fares.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that pricing suddenly stopped escalating, that's
suspicious,'' said James Haynes, president of the Atlanta-based
Commercial Travelers Association.
</P>
<P>
   The carriers have another explanation, obviously, including
lower-priced aviation fuel, improved productivity, lower interest
rates for leases on planes and, of course, competition.
</P>
<P>
   Airline Update
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, members of the frequent-flier programs of AMR's
American Airlines and US Airways can begin claiming awards for
travel on either airline. And at a date to be announced ``in the
near future,'' the carriers said Tuesday, members of both carriers'
programs will be able to combine miles from each program in order
to claim awards on either airline.
</P>
<P>
   Because of hot temperatures in many cities, Delta Air Lines will
not check live animals as baggage through Sept. 15. Passengers who
had planned to fly with their pets during that period can cancel
their reservations without penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Third Time Around
</P>
<P>
   Although it's too late to book passage on Thursday's maiden
voyage of the Disney Magic, Walt Disney Co.'s twice-delayed ship,
the company said limited berths were still available for most of
the Magic's cruises in August. For September and later, there is
ample space on the ship's weekly sailings from Port Canaveral, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   All sailings include three or four days at Walt Disney World
Resort followed by a three- or four-day Bahamas cruise.
</P>
</TEXT>
