<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6947 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-DNC-LADN     07-28 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-DNC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNC PANEL GETS ROYAL TREATMENT IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 
(Col., Pa., Mass., Minn., La., Fla. ATTN) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: This story will be UPDATED with new developments later
tonight.) 
(Moving in the ``a'' national news file and in the ``n'' California
news file.) 
By RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As a pointed reminder of California's role in
electing presidents, the city gave each member of the Democratic
Party convention site selection committee Tuesday a Los Angeles
Kings jersey _ emblazoned with a large ``54.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's 54 as in 54 electoral votes _ 20 percent of what's
needed to win,'' City Council President John Ferraro told the
committee, which is visiting to decide whether Los Angeles will
host the Democratic National Convention in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   These not-so-subtle reminders of California's political clout
were coupled with pleas and promises of what the city can offer and
its historical ties to the Democratic Party. They include the
President John F. Kennedy's nomination during the 1960 Los Angeles
convention and the state's support for President Clinton in the
last two elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were there for you then; we're here for you now,'' an
announcer intoned in a special video presentation designed to show
off the Staples Center sports arena, which is under construction
downtown and would be the convention site.
</P>
<P>
   The Staples Center, owned by developer Ed Roski and Denver oil
billionaire Philip Anschutz, is scheduled to open in 1999 as the
permanent home of the Lakers and Clippers professional basketball
teams and the Kings hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members were presented with tickets to the first
Lakers home game scheduled for Nov. 4, 1999, in a show of
confidence about the opening of the $300 million arena.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Leiwecke, president of the Kings, said the developers stood
ready to make changes in the Center to help win the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the type of event we built this for,'' Leiwecke said.
``It is the home of the Kings, the Lakers and the Clippers. But it
is also to be part of the community and to have events that involve
the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The building, with its 160 luxury suites and 32 guest suites,
could be used to help bring in money for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's tour of Los Angeles began with a three-course
breakfast at the Convention Center, during which the city made its
formal bid setting out what it offers in terms of facilities, hotel
rooms, transportation, security and communications facilities.
</P>
<P>
   It cited the 93,000 hotel rooms available in the Los Angeles
area, enough space for each state delegation in the Convention
Center. The proposal also cited the city's ability to shift work
hours to ease traffic and provide the latest technology for
broadcast and other productions.
</P>
<P>
   The city also offered to provide gavel-to-gavel coverage of the
convention on its cable station as well as full-time security.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members held closed sessions in the afternoon to
question city officials and others about specific concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, it was a day of entertainment and sales pitches.
</P>
<P>
   At the breakfast, that began when a wall of white balloons was
exploded as the door to the Convention Center hall as trumpeters
blared a fanfare, the committee members saw a stuntwoman dressed in
a white angel's costume descend some 60 feet from the ceiling as
other ``angels'' distributed a copy of a CD-ROM with the formal
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   After the morning presentation that included walking through the
Convention Center facility next to the Staples Center site, the
committee was taken to the Central Library where groups of cheering
children lined the entranceway to greet them as two Chinese dragons
and a Chinese band played.
</P>
<P>
   The committee was reminded of the diversity of Los Angeles and
how it has served to adopt new comers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my council district, there are 250,000 people,'' Councilman
Mike Hernandez said. ``Yet, there are 85 different ethnic groups.
You should bring the convention here because this city represents
what America will look like in the 21st Century.''
</P>
<P>
   Several committee members said they were impressed with what
they saw and heard, but were withholding judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Seven cities are bidding for the convention, which local
officials have estimated could bring in $160 million and 30,000
visitors. Other cities include Philadelphia, Boston, Minneapolis,
New Orleans, Miami and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The day's activities ended a tour of the new Getty Center with
its views of the city from the ocean to downtown and an evening
reception at Mayor Richard Riordan's private residence in
Brentwood.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan, a Republican, said the bid to host the convention has
wide support as he promised a city willing and able to provide for
the Democratic Party's needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles is the city that is the crossroads to the world,''
Riordan said. ``We will be the capitol city of the next
millenium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
