r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NURSINGHOME-NEGLECT-S     07-28 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSINGHOME-NEGLECT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOCKING NEGLECT REPORTED IN CALIFORNIA NURSING HOMES 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ Witnesses recited a litany of abuses at California
nursing homes Monday at a Senate hearing, telling of malnutrition,
bone-deep bed sores and other symptoms of severe neglect.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The panel, headed by Iowa Republican Charles Grassley, also
released a General Accounting Office report finding that one-third
of California's nursing homes had ``serious or potentially
life-threatening care problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we had the problem licked'' after legislation was
enacted 12 years ago to remedy such problems, said Grassley.
</P>
<P>
   ``To imagine that these things are going on today in one or more
nursing homes in the state of California is simply intolerable,''
he said. ``We will not stand for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Grassley indicated, however, that he is not seeking new
legislation but rather stronger enforcement of existing
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings by the Senate Special Committee on Aging, scheduled
through Tuesday, were upstaged last week after President Clinton
announced a set of 14 reform proposals that emphasized stepped-up
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The industry, as well as the state's health director, reacted
with both skepticism about the GAO figures and promises to rid the
state of negligent facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't quibble at all with the desire and the obligation to
get rid of bad facilities,'' said Paul Willging, executive vice
president of the American Health Care Association, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   But Willging said accepted government surveying methods put the
number of nursing homes posing ``an immediate and serious jeopardy
to residents'' at 1 percent nationwide, with an additional 5
percent of homes providing ``substandard'' care.
</P>
<P>
   California Health Director Kim Belshe took strong issue with the
hearing, refusing to send state officials to testify. In a letter
to the committee, Belshe said the panel had unfairly singled out
California and had already drawn conclusions ``to which we take
considerable exception.''
</P>
<P>
   Belshe said that many nursing home problems are created by
federal regulations, some of which she called ``seriously flawed.''
Belshe also questioned the credibility of some witnesses, saying
they ``appear to have their own agendas,'' and she concluded that
Grassley's panel ``does not appear to be genuinely interested in
exploring the critical issues associated with the system of nursing
home oversight.''
</P>
<P>
   The witnesses _ nursing home residents, their relatives and
staff _ told the Senate committee of terrible neglect at several
California nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Malnutrition, dehydration, filthy rooms and beds, and unanswered
calls for assistance were common at several homes, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   John Davis, a nursing home resident from Santa Cruz, Calif.,
complained of conditions in several homes in his videotaped
testimony, but the names of the facilities were edited out by the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses also said that care tended to be worse for Medicare
and Medicaid residents than for private payers. And they noted that
substandard facilities seem to know when state inspectors are
coming because they suddenly intensify efforts to clean rooms and
bathe patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I visited my husband every day but two in the two months he
was in this facility,'' said Ellen Curzon of Lakeside, Calif. ``In
61/2 weeks, he lost 35 pounds, developed decubitus ulcers on the
buttocks and became so dehydrated he flinched when touched . . .
Every single day, I had to literally hunt for someone to change
him.'' Curzon is suing the facility, which she did not name.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report said that despite federal and state regulations,
``certain California nursing homes have not been and currently are
not sufficiently monitored to guarantee the safety and welfare of
their residents.''
</P>
<P>
   The report did not name the facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO used data from federal surveys and state complaint
investigations on 1,370 California nursing homes. Of these, 407, or
nearly one in three were cited by state surveyors as having
``serious or potentially life-threatening care problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded that surveyors frequently miss problems and
that those homes that are identified are not sufficiently
penalized. The GAO said federal regulators ``took a lenient
stance'' toward facilities showing violations, and said the state
Department of Health Services normally grants a facility a 30- to
45-day grace period to remedy violations except in extreme cases.
</P>
<P>
   Belshe said in a statement that many of the reforms proposed by
the Clinton administration ``are identical to California policies
that are already in effect.''
</P>
<P>
   These include criminal background checks of nursing home
employees, immediate fines on nursing homes that commit serious
violations and staggered inspections so that operators do not know
when inspectors are coming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
