<HEADER>
A6952 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOVRACE-ABORTION-SFCH     07-28 1518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVRACE-ABORTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LUNGREN AND DAVIS, ABORTION STANCE IS CLEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLA MARINUCCI  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California's two major gubernatorial candidates,
Democrat Gray Davis and Republican Dan Lungren, don't agree on much
when it comes to taxes, tobacco, guns or the environment. But even
though both are Catholic, it is the emotional issue of abortion on
which they are most dramatically divided.
</P>
<P>
   In the nation's most populous state _ one of just 15 remaining
that provide state funding for abortion in most cases _ such clear
definition has prompted forces on both sides to proclaim the
California's governor's race to be the nation's premier
battleground over abortion and reproductive rights.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the pro-choice lieutenant governor, has said that
abortion must remain a private decision between ``a woman, her
physician and her God.''
</P>
<P>
   Lungren, the anti-abortion state attorney general, has cited his
status as a practicing Catholic, saying he believes in ``the
sanctity of innocent life and its protection as a matter of
societal good.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis pledges to maintain state financing for abortion and
family planning services for California women, particularly
military women and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren opposes legalized abortion except in cases of rape,
incest or when the life of the mother is at stake. He has said he
will veto state-financed abortions for Medi-Cal recipients and
oppose birth control services to minors. He supports parental
consent laws, and a ban of late-term abortions, except when the
mother's life is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Both pro-choice and anti-abortion lobbies are keenly aware of
the high stakes involved in the election, and they intend to pump
both money and manpower to influence the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``California is ground zero,'' said Tanya Zumach, the Northern
California director for CARAL, the state arm of the National
Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League. ``If we can't hold
the line here, there's no hope elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis also has the endorsement of feminist icon Gloria Steinem,
who founded the nonpartisan Voters for Choice, and Harriet Stinson,
founder of California Republicans for Choice, who predicts that GOP
women will desert the party in droves over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But Lungren's anti-abortion supporters are saying just the
opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan Lungren has a very solid record on life issues, . . . and
we have the greatest confidence that will not change,'' said Jan
Carroll, a legislative analyst for National Right to Life and
California Right to Life, organizations that have both endorsed
Lungren and are working for his election, she said.
</P>
<P>
   With polls showing that two-thirds of all Californians support
current abortion laws _ or would liberalize them _ Davis has wasted
no time addressing abortion as a campaign issue. His web page
 &LR; (www.gray-davis.com) &LR;  includes a link to related ``women's
rights'' issues, detailing his positions on family planning and
contraceptive funding, child care, child support, abortion and sex
education.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren, too, has a record on those issues, dating back to his
days in Congress. He argues he is firmly ``in the mainstream'' on
such matters as late-term abortion and parental consent, but he
faces a challenge in satisfying both the GOP's staunch
anti-abortion conservatives and moderate GOP women on this
high-profile issue.
</P>
<P>
   That may be one reason he appears markedly less than eager to
put such topics at the front and center in his campaign. His web
page  &LR; (www.lungrenforgovernor.org) &LR;  contains no mention of abortion
or reproductive health issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a defining issue,'' said Lungren campaign manager
Dave Puglia. ``Davis wants to . . . ignore the issues the voters
care most about.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Puglia has protested when reporters use the term
``anti-abortion'' to describe Lungren, saying ``it's too large a
blanket,'' and does not accurately reflect the candidate's
position, which allows for some exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lungren has never shied from questions about abortion _
neither does he appear to relish them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the area of abortion, I don't bring it up,'' he told a
Chronicle editorial board in June. ``I respond to it when it's
brought up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lungren argues that the governor's ability to directly effect
abortion issues is restricted to just three areas: parental
consent, late-term abortions and taxpayer funding of abortions. ``I
would try to be a leader in all three of those areas,'' he said.
``Outside of that, the governor has no real role to play in
influencing the question of abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   But those on both sides disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very important position,'' said anti-abortion
spokeswoman Carroll. ``The governor signs bills and makes
appointments to all areas that are important (in family planning
and abortion). ... There are many ways that an agenda can be
advanced.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has budget power . . . and veto power,'' agreed Zumach,
``which is really important to funding for contraception, sex
education, abortion care and health care,'' she said. ``He also has
the power to appoint California Supreme Court justices.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who has been involved in pro-choice legislation for
decades, boasts of a ``near-perfect'' rating with California NOW
and the League of Women Voters on women's issues.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' campaign manager Garry South charges that Lungren is
already ``running'' from ``a whole continuum of reproductive issues
_ from adoption assistance, foster home assistance and abortion to
contraception.''
</P>
<P>
   He argued that Lungren was the California co-chairman of the
Republican Party platform committee in 1996, helping to write the
plank calling for appointing judges who ``respect the sanctity of
innocent human life'' _ the kind of ``litmus test'' opposed by
pro-choice advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as a member of Congress, Lungren in 1987 co-sponsored
the Human Life Amendment, an attempt to amend the Constitution to
ban abortion, and also cast votes to restrict or cut abortion, even
in cases of rape, incest or life endangerment. ``He voted for a
bill in 1988 which would have repudiated Roe v. Wade,'' South
charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can try to gussy it up, but are you for a woman's right to
choose or are you not?'' he said. ``He is not.''
</P>
<P>
   Lungren himself has called some of those votes merely
procedural, but his spokesman, Bob Brown, said he has never wavered
from his basic beliefs. ``Dan Lungren is pro-life _ and has always
been pro-life. He has said it is drawn from his belief in the
sanctity of life, being raised Catholic,'' he said. ``He has been
consistent on that from Day One.''
</P>
<P>
   Lungren ``doesn't have a litmus test on the issues regarding
judges,'' Brown argues.
</P>
<P>
   Some women's groups have charged that as state attorney general,
Lungren has not been aggressive in protecting clinics from violent
anti-abortion activists.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown said Lungren has stood up for women's rights, for
example, prosecuting a number of doctors accused of injuring women
in botched abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from abortion issues, the vast number of voters could be
far more affected by the next governor's profound influence on
family planning and reproductive health services issues.
</P>
<P>
   California's governor oversees the State Department of Health's
Office of Family Planning, which budgets $82 million to fund
contraceptives, pregnancy testing, sex education, health
examinations for nearly 600,000 low-income women and girls in
California _ a fifth of them 19 or younger.
</P>
<P>
   The state also grants money to clinics that perform abortions,
such as the Planned Parenthood Association. And under Governor Pete
Wilson, the state's Expanded Teen Counseling Program provides
family planning and counseling to more than 350,000 youth
statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the candidates have differed markedly on their views of
such services.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren has previously stated his opposition to the distribution
of condoms and birth control to teenagers, and has said his
policies regarding the State Office of Family Planning will mirror
those of his mentor, Governor George Deukmejian. The GOP governor
slashed the Office of Family Planning funding by two-thirds _ but
was forced to restore the cuts after widespread protests.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who was then the state controller, took the same stand
then as he does today: that basic quality-of-life issues are at
stake in providing services to poor women and teenagers who cannot
afford such health care. He argues that for every dollar spent in
family planning and the prevention of adolescent births, the state
saves $12 in health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren, who has said his own budget decisions will be made on
an individual basis, said that while he respects his opponents, he
will firmly disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are coming from a set of values that are to be respected
and to be joined in mutual and respectful debate,'' Lungren told
The Chronicle in June. ``But if you start equating life with
dollars, I think you run us in the wrong direction, and you truly
go to what people would call a materialistic society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1919EDT &QL; 
