<HEADER>
A6954 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-49ERS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-28 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUBBS CATCHES A BREAK AS THE NEW MIDDLE MAN  
BY GARY SWAN
</HEADLINE>
   Chronicle Staff Writer  
    STOCKTON, Calif. _ Sometimes it's the little things that make a
difference when a player moves from one team to another.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask linebacker Winfred Tubbs, for example, what it's like being
a 49er after four years with the Saints, and he pauses only briefly
to talk of the winning and losing and cuts to what matters during
two-a-day practices in broiling weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am in training camp and they're giving me days off,''
Tubbs said, referring to the occasional afternoons when players are
told to take a break and the holiday given all players and coaches
Monday. ``Other training camps I've been in, it doesn't matter
what's wrong with you, they never give you a day off. Here they
seem to know you don't make our playoff run in July. They save you
so there's still spring in your legs come November.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs was receptive to the 49ers' offer that arrived literally
at the stroke of midnight as the free-agency signing period opened
in February. The team needed to replace middle linebacker Gary
Plummer, a vital cog in the No.1-ranked 1997 defense. The Saints
did not want to lose a player who set the team record with 160
tackles last season, but they did not match the 49ers' offer of
$14.25 million over five years with an added $4 million to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs does not expect the same numbers with the 49ers. One guy
makes that many tackles only on bad teams, he said, although Ken
Norton Jr., who holds the 49ers' record with 165 tackles in 1996
and also had a team-high 138 tackles last season, might argue the
point. Defensive schemes differ from team to team, and the 49ers
like to funnel the ballcarrier to Norton.
</P>
<P>
   As the inside linebacker, Tubbs inherits much of Plummer's
coach-on-the-field duties. When he sees the offense approach the
line in certain telltale formations, he will have to bark commands
for the defensive line and the other linebackers to adjust their
coverages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy I'm replacing should also be a Hall of Famer, so I
have a lot of pressure on me,'' Tubbs said. ``If I don't come up
and play just as well or better than Gary Plummer, the guys are
going to look down upon me, and the coaches are going to say `We
wasted our money.'''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer was 37 last season, and 12 years of pro football had
taken a toll on his body. He rarely practiced during the week and
would trudge out to the field with bandages from head to toe that
made him resemble the pictures of Confederate soldiers coming home
from the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   With Tubbs, 27, the 49ers' defense gets much younger and
quicker. Tubbs probably will not be replaced with a defensive back
on every passing down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been associated with a superstar team like this
before,'' he said. ``It's amazing to look around here. You've got
people here who are the best ever at their positions. The
quarterback, the receiver, the safeties, the linebackers, it seems
like I've got to just sit back and watch everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs is smart, as anyone filling Plummer's position has to be.
He has already bonded with Tim McDonald, a locker-room leader. And
what he likes so far is the way the 49ers make training camp more
of a mental challenge than a physical one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches know your physical talent already. How tough you
are,'' he said. ``So they watch for a guy who is less talented, and
if he uses proper technique, he can beat out guys who are tougher
or with more talent. The difference is the mental aspect. And they
know that here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim McDonald told me, `Once you come here, it's hard to leave
here.' This type of training camp as opposed to a training camp
where every day you hit, hit, hit and all they care about is how
tough you are. In comparison to this where there isn't much hitting
and a lot of classroom stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs said he can fill Plummer's role all the way to the point
of being the sidekick to Norton during endless streams of practice
banter, which can become nasty at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked a lot in New Orleans, too,'' Tubbs said. ``And
Kenny, he's the kind of guy who talks a lot and backs it up. So I
have no complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
