<HEADER>
A6956 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RAIDERS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-28 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAIDERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENTOR SHAW, PUPIL ALLEN CONTINUE TO CROSS PATHS  
BY RON KROICHICK
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Eric Allen sat in his living room, a talented
athlete prone to mischief. He was 16 years old at the time. His
talent would land him a college scholarship, as long as the
mischief subsided.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Shaw also sat in Allen's living room on that long-ago
day. Shaw was an assistant coach at Arizona State. He had come to
his own hometown, San Diego, to meet with Allen, his mother and his
brother.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw arrived with a straightforward message: Stay out of trouble
and go to class. Satisfy these modest requirements and the
scholarship belonged to Allen, plain and simple.
</P>
<P>
   Allen listened.
</P>
<P>
   Here they stand, 16 years later, student and teacher once again.
Shaw now is the defensive coordinator of the Raiders, the man
trying to retrieve respect for Oakland's wayward defense.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, the starting right cornerback, qualifies as one of Shaw's
prized pupils. He was the team's most significant acquisition of
the offseason, arriving from New Orleans for a fourth-round draft
choice.
</P>
<P>
   But there are meaningful stories beyond the semantics. There is
history at work here _ a long relationship between Shaw, the
mentor, and Allen, the star athlete who nearly fumbled his future.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw encouraged Allen to resist the easy option of staying home
and going to junior college. Shaw talked of improving in school,
attending a four-year college, opening up a whole new world.
</P>
<P>
   He seldom talked about football, something Allen remembers to
this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That last year in high school, Willie was integral in helping
me see past tomorrow,'' Allen said Monday at training camp in Napa.
``That's very difficult for a 16-year-old guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just like any teenager growing up in the inner city.
There were a lot of temptations. I wasn't always on the straight
and narrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen grew up in rugged southeast San Diego, near Shaw's alma
mater, Lincoln High School. (Running backs Marcus Allen and Terrell
Davis also are Lincoln alums.) Eric Allen's mother taught at
Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   But trouble surfaced before Allen ever reached high school. He
was expelled from junior high for fighting. His mother ultimately
put Allen on a bus and sent him to Point Loma High School, about 10
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   There, Allen resuscitated his grades and excelled in football
and baseball. One of his Point Loma baseball teammates was David
Wells, who pitched a perfect game for the New York Yankees earlier
this season.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Allen straightened out his act. He earned that
scholarship, starred at ASU and climbed into the NFL. Along the
way, he never forgot the role Shaw played in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie's a teacher at heart,'' Allen said. ``That's what I
like about him the most. He not only wants you to succeed on the
football field, he wants you to learn things that can help you in
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a role model for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, 54, was Allen's position coach last season in New Orleans.
So it was no great surprise when the Raiders, acting largely on
Shaw's recommendation, traded for Allen on Mar. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's presence also helped when Allen initially refused to
report to the Raiders, because he did not consider them Super Bowl
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Allen later backtracked. He said he was angry with the Saints,
who had promised to confer with him before they completed a trade.
Allen, 32, signed a new contract and officially joined the Raiders
on Apr. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Raiders are counting on Allen to revitalize their
secondary. He brings along six Pro Bowl berths, 39 career
interceptions and a sparkling reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric's a pro,'' Shaw said. ``He brings his lunch pail, and he
comes to work every day. You can tell the young guys there's
someone to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   The mantle has been passed. Now it's Allen's turn to be the role
model.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
