<HEADER>
A6959 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCK-GUYGROUPS-TEX     07-28 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-GUYGROUPS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKSTREET BOYS ARE THE FIRST IN A NEW WAVE OF GUY GROUPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALYSON WARD and ROB McDONALD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're young, they're cute, they can dance _ and sometimes they
can even sing.
</P>
<P>
   Boy groups are big again (shades of New Kids on the Block!),
with young fans _ male and female _ buying records and tossing
teddy bears at No Mercy, 'N Sync, Five and the Backstreet Boys.
</P>
<P>
   How big is the trend? They're bringing back Menudo. Consider
yourselves warned.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Backstreet Boys
</P>
<P>
   The gimmick: In concert, they pick out several girls to serenade
at once.
</P>
<P>
   The boys: Nick Carter, the youngest, blondest and most popular;
Kevin Richardson, the oldest and the serious one; Alexander James
``A.J.'' McLean, the wild man; Howard ``Howie D.'' Dorough; Brian
``B-Rok'' Littrell.
</P>
<P>
   The merchandise: T-shirts, posters, baseball caps _ plus the
boys have their faces on throw pillows.
</P>
<P>
   The music: Bubblegum R&AMP;B.
</P>
<P>
   Hit songs: ``As Long as You Love Me'' and ``Quit Playin' Games
(With My Heart).''
</P>
<P>
   On tour: They play Starplex in Dallas on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Official story: Took their name from the landmark Backstreet
Market in Orlando, Fla. Formed in the early 1990s and first hit it
big in Britain. Their self-titled debut album was ignored in the
United States until it became a hit in most other English-speaking
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Distinguishing characteristic: Frankly, we get them mixed up
with 'N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Five
</P>
<P>
   The gimmick: The male Spice Girls!
</P>
<P>
   The boys: Sean Colon, the serious one; Scott Robinson, the baby
and the gabby one; Richard Neville, the soft-spoken one; ``Abs''
Breen, the romantic; ``J'' Brown, the oldest at 21 and the
prankster.
</P>
<P>
   The merchandise: Selling like crazy in England, but so far
there's not much available here. But fans are asking for it, so
prepare to be inundated.
</P>
<P>
   The music: Hip-hop/dance with an English flair.
</P>
<P>
   Hit song: ``When the Lights Go Out.''
</P>
<P>
   On tour: A U.S. tour starts in late August.
</P>
<P>
   Official story: Formed in Britain by Bob and Chris Herbert, the
father-and-son duo behind the Spice Girls. They auditioned 3,000
boys for a male version of Sporty, Scary, et. al.
</P>
<P>
   Distinguishing characteristic: They reject the ``boy band''
label. Says Abs: ``We're too real for that. We're not about to
start wearing matching silky shirts and being told what to say.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync
</P>
<P>
   The gimmick: justiN, chriS, joeY, lansteN, j.C. ... did you
catch that? The boys combined the last letters of their first names
to come up with 'N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   The boys: James Lance ``Lansten'' Bass, the shy one; Joshua
Scott ``JC'' Chasez, the jock; Joseph ``Joey'' Anthony Fatone Jr.,
the flirty one who's been in ``Matinee'' and ``seaQuest DSV'';
Christopher ``Chris'' Alan Kirkpatrick, the oldest and the
prankster; Justin Randall Timberlake, the youngest.
</P>
<P>
   The merchandise: Had their own special on the Disney Channel
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The music: Pop/R&AMP;B/dance.
</P>
<P>
   Hit song: ``Tearing Up My Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   On tour: In June, they'll play Six Flags Over Texas and the KISS
Party '98. On Aug. 17, they'll perform for the Miss Teen USA
pageant on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Official story: If Five is from the United Kingdom, 'N Sync is
from the Magic Kingdom. Timberlake and Chasez met on the set of
``The Mickey Mouse Club'' and, inspired by crowd reactions to their
dance moves, recruited the others.
</P>
<P>
   Distinguishing characteristic: Two blond heartthrobs, instead of
the traditional one.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   No Mercy
</P>
<P>
   The gimmick: Twins from Cuba!
</P>
<P>
   The boys: Marty Cintron, Ariel Hernandez and Gabriel Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   The merchandise: T-shirts and key chains galore.
</P>
<P>
   The music: Pop/soul with a Latin twist.
</P>
<P>
   Hit songs: ``Where Do You Go'' and ``Kiss You All Over.''
</P>
<P>
   On tour: Not right now; too busy working on an album.
</P>
<P>
   Official story: Cintron performed on the streets of South Beach
in Miami, where he caught the attention of a European producer who
asked if he had any friends who could sing. Cintron brought in the
twins and they were whisked to Germany to record.
</P>
<P>
   Distinguishing characteristic: Um ... there are only three of
them.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   A boy group time line
</P>
<P>
   1977: Producer Edgardo Diaz comes up with the idea for Menudo.
As performers age, they are replaced with younger versions. All
told, there were 33 members of Menudo. Six former members have
reunited this summer for an international tour: El Reencuentro _
The Reunion.
</P>
<P>
   1981: New Edition is formed by producer Maurice Starr, who
envisions an '80s version of the Jacksons. Before dissolving in
1989, the collection launches the careers of Bobby Brown, Johnny
Gill, Bell Biv Devoe and Ralph Tresvant.
</P>
<P>
   1986: Maurice Starr tries it again with New Kids on the Block, a
white version of New Edition. He meets Donnie Wahlberg, who
recruits some of his friends. By 1993, Starr is no longer managing
the band. They change their name to New Kids, then to NKOTB. They
disband by 1995.
</P>
<P>
   1990: Oklahoma City band Color Me Badd is discovered by Robert
Bell of Kool and the Gang. The group is quiet after ``Now and
Forever'' is released in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   1994: All-4-One forms. They haven't released an album since
1995, but have appeared on the soundtracks of ``Space Jam'' and
``The Hunchback of Notre Dame.'' A new album, ``My Brother's
Keeper,'' should be in stores Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The boy group rules
</P>
<P>
   Like the Mighty Morphin Power Rangers, each member needs an
over-simplified personality: ``The shy one,'' ``the flirt,'' ``the
wild one,'' etc.
</P>
<P>
   Someone in the group must have some acting experience, so he can
ham it up for the close-ups.
</P>
<P>
   One guy should have a name made of two letters or less, such as
T.J., J.C. or just J.
</P>
<P>
   There must be a maestro who orchestrated the group's shtick.
</P>
<P>
   During the band's strongest love ballad, a girl must be pulled
on stage and serenaded. (Don't just pick the good-looking girls, or
you'll risk the wrath of parents.)
</P>
<P>
   Keep the lone bad boy in check. New Kids on the Block allowed
Donnie Wahlberg to lose it. He set a fire in a hotel and attacked
someone on an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
