<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-GOVERNORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNORS PRAISE WELFARE OVERHAUL TWO YEARS AGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Nearly two years after Congress passed legislation
overhauling the nation's welfare system, leaders of the National
Governors' Association (NGA) on Tuesday voiced bipartisan support
for the measure and praised state efforts to reduce welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people receiving such aid has dropped 27 percent
since 1996 to 9 million, according to the Department of Health and
Human Services. When Congress passed the welfare bill on Aug. 1,
1996, 12.4 million people were receiving cash assistance. The
number had peaked at 14.4 million in March 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Voinovich, R-Ohio, president of the NGA, said at a
news conference here that the measure ``far exceeded our
expectations.'' He criticized people who said state control over
welfare would result in a ``race to the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The critics have been wrong,'' he said. ``We have been, in
fact, witnessing a race to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   The flexibility that the federal government gave to the states
makes the decrease in welfare rolls possible, Voinovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Thomas R. Carper, D-Del., NGA vice president, said the drop
is also due in large part to the booming economy. ``Whoever decided
to launch welfare reform in the midst of the longest economic
expansion that I can remember in my life, that was a smart
person,'' Carper said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress changed the face of welfare two years ago when it ended
the 61-year-old practice of giving federal funds to all those
eligible. Instead, the government gave states overall control of
welfare and provided them with lump sums of money, called block
grants.
</P>
<P>
   The government also required the states to limit the time a
person can be on welfare to five years and to put half of those
then receiving the aid into the job market by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, states are now devising new methods to get welfare
recipients into jobs, Voinovich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new system has allowed states to create a new culture for
treating welfare recipients not as numbers but as individuals,'' he
said. ``It has allowed us to say to people, `We respect you.'''
</P>
<P>
   According to Voinovich, states are spending more on child care,
transportation to get people to work and efforts to make jobs more
attractive to those on welfare. Twenty-two states have already
implemented programs that help people find jobs, he added.
</P>
<P>
   According to NGA figures, 32 states currently have or plan to
devise strategies to check on individuals who leave welfare to see
whether they really have jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Carper warned that welfare problems are not over. If anything,
he said, ``the opposite should be suggested. ... A lot of people
have drug and alcohol addiction problems. We still have some tough
customers out there to help get off of welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   He advocated assessing which programs work now while the economy
is strong instead of waiting for a recession when more people will
be out of jobs. ``It is incumbent upon (the governors) to use this
period of time wisely,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
