A6961 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-GROENING-465&AMP;ADD-S     07-28 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GROENING-465&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROENING HAS A HAND IN FOX'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ ``The Simpsons'' perks along merrily to the
delight of Fox and the show's creator, Matt Groening, who can see
``no end in sight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``King of the Hill'' is an established hit, too, and will move
to new Tuesday quarters in the fall. And within a year, it's
conceivable that Fox will have four animated shows and one
claymation-type production on the air.
</P>
<P>
   These shows are joys for their creators and their networks. For
one thing, cartoon characters are permitted a loutishness _ see
``South Park'' on Comedy Central _ that would amount to
broadcasting felonies if they were human.
</P>
<P>
   Also, cartoon characters seldom ask to have their contracts
ripped up and renegotiated. Or ask networks to grease their
four-fingered hands with fat production deals. Or demand on-set
trailers equipped with hot and cold running sycophants and personal
trainers.
</P>
<P>
   No, Homer Simpson is the same unadorned, beer-swilling slug we
met a decade ago. He's an unwitting, penniless prisoner of his own
little ``Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Groening himself is about to capitalize on the animation surge
he launched. He's readying for Fox a midseason show set in the year
2999 called ``Futurama.''
</P>
<P>
   During a session at the TV press tour, Groening said he wanted
to indulge his notion that ``it would be really neat to take some
of the conventions of science fiction and have fun with them in a
`Simpsons'-style way.''
</P>
<P>
   Groening's vision of the future apparently doesn't involve a
Zen-like quest for harmonic convergence, backed by a benign
military federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love `Star Wars' and `Star Trek' and all the variations on
them,'' he said. ``However, I wanted to do a TV show in which the
problems of the universe are not solved by militarism guided by New
Age spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought, `Let's try something different.' It's not a
knock. It's not a knock on the optimism of those shows. I just have
a slightly more subversive take, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   You can expect disembodied heads in jars. Aliens commingling
with earthlings. ``Dick Clark's Rockin' New Year's Eve 3000.'' A
popular TV show called ``The Mass Hypnosis Hour.'' And bumptious
robots.
</P>
<P>
   Groening said the show's main characters will be Fry, ``a guy
from our time who has a tragic mishap'' and regains consciousness a
thousand years into the future; Leela, a female alien who sweeps
her hair onto her forehead to disguise the fact that she has only
one eye; and Bender, a kleptomaniacal robot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the standout character right now on this show,'' Groening
said. ``He's our robotic Homer Simpson. He's just totally corrupt _
lovably corrupt, a la Homer. Loves his vices. I think he's the
first robot in science fiction who shoplifts.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Groening said he and his production team have been patching
``Futurama'' together for three years. It doesn't yet have an air
date or time period on Fox, though 8:30 p.m. Sundays, after ``The
Simpsons,'' and 8:30 p.m. Tuesdays, after ``King of the Hill,'' are
surely prospective slots.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``The Simpsons,'' Groening is promising a 1998-99 season
``as good as any we've ever done, or better.''
</P>
<P>
   In one episode, he said, ``keeping a secret proves difficult for
Homer when he lands a personal assistant job working for Alec
Baldwin and Kim Basinger.'' In another, ``Homer raises a lobster _
you know, he goes to the store and he wants a lobster. It's too
expensive, so he gets a baby lobster to raise it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ned Flanders will suffer a midlife crisis and go to Las Vegas
with Homer, where they'll waken one morning in the company of two
cocktail waitresses. There will be ``our obligatory Jerry Springer
appearance,'' and a show in which Homer tries to become a more
adept inventor than Thomas Edison.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that will not happen, Groening said, is a crossover
episode between ``The Simpsons'' and ``Futurama.''
</P>
<P>
   ```Futurama' is real,'' he said. ``The Simpsons are fictional.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Simpsons don't have their place in the world of
2999.
</P>
<P>
   ```The Simpsons' is still on a thousand years from now,''
Groening said. ``With original episodes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
