</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: N.Y. GOVERNOR'S ARTS AWARDS; MACNALLY PLAY GOES
FORWARD; ARSON CAUSE OF WOLFE HOME DESTRUCTION; BLUES SINGER
ESCAPES BURNING HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.C., Calif.) (rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Actor James Earl Jones, artist Ellsworth Kelly and
musician Tito Puente are to receive 1998 Governor's Arts Awards,
which celebrate outstanding individuals and organizations in their
field. Others to be honored when Gov. George Pataki, his wife,
Libby, and Earle Mack, chairman of the New York State Council on
the Arts, take part in ceremonies on Oct. 5 at the Vivian Beaumont
Theater at Lincoln Center are: Marian and Andrew Heiskell, 1717
Cedar Arts Center, Albany Symphony Orchestra, Brooklyn Children's
Museum, Dance Theater Workshop, George Eastman House, Munson
Williams Proctor Institute, North Country Public Radio and
Playwrights Horizons. As a tribute to the 150th anniversary of the
Women's Rights Convention in Seneca Falls, the Governor's
Commission Honoring the Achievements of Women will also present
special citations to dancer and choreographer Judith Jamison,
artistic director of the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater;
composer and conductor Tania Leon, and singer and arts
administrator Beverly Sills.
</P>
<P>
   Aftermath
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Terrence McNally's play ``Corpus Christi'' is to
begin previews on Sept. 22 at Manhattan Theater Club and have its
official opening on Oct. 13. Last spring, when the play about a gay
Jesus-like figure attracted protests from a Roman Catholic civil
rights group and bomb threats, the club removed it from its fall
schedule, citing security concerns. Then, as outraged artists
accused the theater of being intimidated into self-censorship,
``Corpus Christi'' was reinstated. In a gesture of support for
``Corpus Christi,'' South African playwright Athol Fugard removed
his play ``The Captain's Tiger'' from the theater's schedule. It is
back on, and is to begin previews on Dec. 15 and open on Jan. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Homeless
</P>
<P>
   Arson is cited as the cause of the fire that gutted the boyhood
home of Thomas Wolfe in Asheville, N.C., on Friday. Harley Shuford
of the Buncombe County Arson Task Force said it appeared that
someone hurled something through a dining room window to ignite the
blaze. The 1883 Queen Anne-style Victorian house was the setting
for Wolfe's 1929 novel ``Look Homeward, Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   Safe and Sound
</P>
<P>
   Grammy Award-winning blues singer and guitarist John Lee Hooker
escaped with his life and his guitars when fire destroyed the roof
of his home in Los Altos, Calif. The blaze, which began in the
bedroom of one of Hooker's housemates on Sunday night, caused about
$400,000 in damage to the $1.5 million, eight-bedroom home. Hooker
has recorded more than 100 albums, including ``The Healer,'' a
winner of a Grammy in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
