<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6968 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WB-SFCHRON &LR;      07-28 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WB-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN VIEWERS LIFT THE WB TO GLORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The wheel of fortune used to crank around one
gear notch at a time. Now it's spinning crazily. Take the WB: a
joke of a TV network one day, a perfect business model the next.
</P>
<P>
   The WB was where embarrassingly bad shows played in obscurity
until they were mercifully extinguished. Then ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer'' came along. And ``Dawson's Creek.'' And, quietly,
``Seventh Heaven.'' And, in the fall, the can't-miss ``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Simple. The WB got lucky. Teenagers found it. In May,
advertisers were lining up to plunk down as much as $285,000 for a
30-second spot on ``Dawson's Creek,'' dwarfing the commercial cost
on the higher-rated but older-skewing ``60 Minutes.'' You're old,
you're chopped meat.
</P>
<P>
   In three more years, the WB might even turn a profit. But while
the WB is rising from the launching pad, the rival UPN is taking a
decidedly different tack to assure its own survival.
</P>
<P>
   The battle between these fifth and sixth networks is a
reflection of all of television today. One seeks to be a
``narrowcaster,'' the other a broadcaster. Right now, the smart
money seems to be on the ``narrowcaster'' approach.
</P>
<P>
   The WB is ``narrowcasting'' to viewers 12 to 34 years old,
locking that demographic in its sights and firing programs at it.
UPN is pursuing a more traditional broadcasting model, trying to
program for a middle American audience between 20 and 50 years old
_ more or less the same 18-to-49 demographic that, say, NBC
targets.
</P>
<P>
   There are spills. The WB doesn't exactly instruct 40-year-olds
not to trespass, and UPN isn't checking IDs to keep 13-year-olds
away. But the two struggling networks are definitely exploring
divergent paths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any broadcast network that adopts a narrowcast model is
ultimately doomed to failure,'' UPN President Dean Valentine told
the press in Pasadena last weekend. ``I don't believe in it as a
business model. I don't believe in it as a social model.''
</P>
<P>
   A social model? Valentine apparently meant the further
fragmentation of the TV audience, the prospect of programming that
speaks only to the experiences and desires of narrow bands of the
national population, the loss of one more unifying thread in
American life.
</P>
<P>
   There's life yet, Valentine said, in UPN's ``umbrella strategy''
of reaching the broadest possible cross-section of adult,
middle-class Americans. Steven Spielberg just proved it, he said.
```Saving Private Ryan' opened to $30 million in business this
weekend, and I hazard to say they weren't 16-year-olds who were
going to it,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Saving Private Ryan'' didn't depend on selling 30-second
spots to ad agencies craving the attention of young consumers.
Jamie Kellner, the WB's chief executive officer, and Garth Ancier,
its entertainment president, say even the big networks must learn
to narrow their aim.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at some of the most competitive marketing areas _
sneakers, the movies, fast food, beverages, computers _ all these
really hot marketing areas, they tend to be very focused on younger
people today,'' Kellner said. ``I think it's the battleground, in
effect, for the future of marketing in our country _ to attack
these younger demographics.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the idea of being able to focus advertisements toward
gigantic groups of people is almost over, in my opinion. The future
of our business is going to be very targeted. All the networks will
eventually select certain targets, and try to attack those targets,
and be very specific toward those groups of people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The major networks, Ancier said, are already ``starting to
become self-defined.'' Fox skews younger than NBC. NBC skews
younger than CBS. ABC _ well, one day ABC will know what it is.
(That's me, not Ancier, picking on ABC.) Anyway, Ancier continued,
programming is tailored accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps us tremendously on the program side,'' Ancier said,
``because we know that show isn't for us, this show is for us. Our
casts should be in this age range, not in that age range. It says
you don't do your shows with Ted Danson, you do them with Joshua
Jackson, or Sarah Michelle Gellar.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellner and Ancier make a persuasive case. And certainly the WB
is projecting a consistent, well-defined image while UPN has no
persona at all, except maybe what remains of its ``Star Trek:
Voyager'' sci-fi infatuation.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  But the Kellner-Ancier model, attractive as it seems, is
ultimately devastating. If not to commerce, to the social weal and
to television's brittle veneer of art.
</P>
<P>
   If TV entertainment is to serve any larger purpose than to
massage the brain between commercials, it should be akin to the old
theatrical aspiration of broadening our humanity and deepening our
understanding of what's called, for lack of a better term, the
human condition.
</P>
<P>
   When a Garth Ancier says that ``our casts should be in this age
range,'' he's already cheated that goal, wittingly or not.
</P>
<P>
   Is the best TV show one that simply regurgitates anyone's own
demographic perspective on the world, turning the rest of the
species into nonentities, bit players or generational enemies? No
wonder so much television drama has turned weary and angst-ridden;
angst is a natural byproduct of self-obsession.
</P>
<P>
   So the WB, with its top-hatted frog mascot prancing ahead of it,
is on a parade route toward prosperity. Smart business plan. But
one more gulp of poison for an increasingly fractious, selfish and
myopic society.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
