<HEADER>
A6974 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-MEMORIAL-CO     07-28 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-MEMORIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    NATION'S LEADERS SAY FAREWELL IN THE U.S. CAPITOL TO TWO SLAIN
OFFICERS WHO PROTECTED THEM
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They filed in silently Tuesday, the senators and
representatives, the members of the president's cabinet, and
finally President Clinton himself, filling in the space between the
rows of uniformed Capitol Police and the caskets that held the
bodies of two fallen officers.
</P>
<P>
   Last to enter were the widows, the children and the
grandchildren, taking seats beneath the soaring Rotunda in the
Capitol where the men that they loved had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this room there are murals, pictures, statues of the great
men and women in our country's history,'' said Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. ``Today we honor two men that should
rightly be recognized in this hall of heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men _ Capitol Police officers Jacob ``J.J.'' Chestnut
and John Gibson _ died Friday from gunshots allegedly delivered by
a delusional gunman just one floor below the Rotunda where Congress
convened in silence Tuesday to hear the United States' top leaders
pay tribute to the officers' sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story of what they did here on Friday in the line of duty
is already a legend,'' Clinton said. ``And we thank their families
for enduring the pain and extra burden of joining us here today,
for they remind us that what makes our democracy strong is not only
what Congress may enact or a president may achieve...
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the countless individual citizens who live our ideals
out every day, the innumerable acts of heroism that go unnoticed,''
Clinton said, ``it is the quiet courage and uncommon bravery of
Americans like J.J. Chestnut and John Gibson....''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Rotunda was closed Tuesday for the congressional
memorial, long lines formed outside the Capitol as people waited in
a baking sun to spend a minute or two passing the officers'
flag-draped coffins. A group of about 30 bagpipers from different
law enforcement agencies gathered on the Capitol's east lawn in the
early afternoon, sending their mournful music across an abnormally
quiet plaza toward the building where their brethren lay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their devotion to duty, their sacrifice to defend freedom,
their commitment of their life, both on a daily basis and at the
crisis that occurred on Friday, has in fact reminded millions and
millions of people that, while this is the center of freedom in the
world, and this building is the centerpiece of freedom in our
constitutional system, it only lasts as long as there is courage,''
said House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore also spoke of the symbolism of the
Capitol:
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we honor two watchmen who guarded not just a building
but an ideal,'' he said, ``men who lived and labored not only to
keep our democracy free from harm, but to keep it free and open to
all our people.''
</P>
<P>
   The dead officers' commander, Capitol Police Chief Gary Abrecht,
defiantly promised that the Capitol would remain open to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that there are those who seek to disrupt the
national legislative process or come here to commit acts of
violence,'' Abrecht said. ``It is important that those individuals
understand that there are other officers like J.J. and John who are
determined to fill the breach and hold tight the thin blue line
which protects our congressional community and allows the public to
safely visit their seat of government.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
