<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-NURSING-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT CALLED LENIENT TOWARD ERRANT NURSING HOMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., La., Iowa, Maine)  (mk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly one-third of the nursing homes in California
have been cited for violations that cause death or life-threatening
harm to patients, but the federal government ``generally took a
lenient stance toward many of these homes,'' congressional
investigators said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the General Accounting Office said that
federal officials had been extremely reluctant to take action, even
against nursing homes repeatedly cited for serious violations of
federal health and safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homes can repeatedly harm residents without facing
sanctions,'' William Scanlon, director of health care studies at
the accounting office, told the Senate Special Committee on Aging
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO investigation focused on California. But Charlene
Harrington, a professor of nursing at the University of California
at San Francisco, said that ``California is symptomatic of all the
states,'' and that it was actually better than many other states in
detecting substandard care.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Breaux, D-La., the ranking Democrat on the committee,
said, ``Other states probably have similar problems.''
</P>
<P>
   After listening to eight hours of testimony over two days, Sen.
Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, the committee chairman, said that the
federal Health Care Financing Administration, which regulates
nursing homes, ``has been comatose for too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Scanlon said that nursing home residents in California ``were
left sitting in urine and feces for long periods of time.'' Some
patients were allowed to waste away with no medical attention, he
said, while others had bedsores so bad that they infected the
surrounding tissue and exposed the underlying bone.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley said that a lawyer for one California nursing home had
apparently tried to intimidate a witness who testified before the
committee on Monday. The lawyer sent the woman a letter saying she
faced ``various forms of liability'' because her prepared testimony
included inaccurate statements about conditions at the home where
her mother was a patient in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, the lawyer, Dan Woods, from the firm of
White &AMP; Case, said, ``It was not our intent to intimidate any
witness.'' He said that he just wanted to make sure that the woman
testified truthfully.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley said the situation in California was ``horrifying _ the
equivalent of a national scandal.'' It was, he said, all the more
remarkable because Congress in 1987 passed a law that set
stringent, extremely detailed standards for nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Toby Edelman, a lawyer at the National Senior Citizens Law
Center, said: ``The federal enforcement system now in place looks
very much like the system that Congress repudiated in 1987, when it
enacted the nursing home reform law. Compliance with the new
standards remains largely a voluntary matter. Nursing homes are
nearly always given an opportunity to correct deficiencies before
they can be sanctioned for providing poor care.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating Tuesday's hearing, President Clinton last week
announced steps to crack down on nursing homes that violate federal
health and safety standards. But experts told Congress Tuesday that
the administration had done nothing to address one of the biggest
problems: a shortage of nursing assistants and other personnel at
many homes.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO examined the quality of care at 1,370 California nursing
homes inspected from 1995 to 1998. It found that 30 percent of the
homes had committed violations that caused death or
life-threatening harm to patients, or had understated the amount of
poor care by falsifying medical records.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thirty-three percent of the homes had violations that harmed
patients without threatening their lives, and 35 percent had
deficiencies that could harm patients if not corrected, Scanlon
said. Only 2 percent of the homes had no violations or minimal
deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   Scanlon said the nursing homes continued receiving Medicare and
Medicaid payments after they had been cited for serious violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Health Care Financing Administration has authority to
terminate a home from participation in Medicare and Medicaid,''
Scanlon said. ``But termination rarely occurs and is not as final
as the term implies.'' Of the 1,370 nursing homes, he said, 16 have
been terminated at some time since 1995, but 14 of the 16 were
reinstated. Since their reinstatement, Scanlon said, six of the 14
homes have been cited for new violations that harmed patients.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, said federal officials had imposed
``rather puny penalties'' on nursing homes. ``This lack of
enforcement sends a very troubling signal to unscrupulous providers
of care,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
