<SLUG> BC-POWERPLANT-EXPLOSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER PLANT BLASTS INJURE 17 IN INDIANA 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMMOND, Ind. _ Two explosions within seconds ripped through a
power plant Tuesday, injuring 17 people, four of whom suffered
critical burns.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe a cleaning crew inside the State Line Power
Plant, a coal-burning plant owned by the Southern Energy Corp., may
have sparked fumes inside one of the plant's giant coal bunkers
shortly before 8 a.m. Seconds later a transformer ignited, sending
flames and clouds of smoke high into the air.
</P>
<P>
   About 120 workers were inside the plant when the explosions
occurred. Three employees were trapped on the roof, but
firefighters doused enough of the fire to allow the workers to
escape through the building.
</P>
<P>
   Although an investigation was incomplete, fire officials said a
spark from the cleaning crew, which was vacuuming coal dust in the
plant in a routine cleaning procedure, probably ignited the highly
flammable dust.
</P>
<P>
   After the initial explosion, employees trying to escape opened a
set of doors, creating a back draft that helped spread the fire,
said Jim Walsko, a spokesman for the Hammond Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   The plant, which sells power to Commonwealth Edison, the main
source of electric power in the Chicago area, is on the shore of
Lake Michigan just across the Indiana state line from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Plant officials could not say when it would be back in
operation, but Commonwealth Edison said that the plant was one of
its smallest suppliers and that its customers would not be
affected.
</P>
</TEXT>
