<SLUG> BC-IMMUNITY-LEWINSKY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL GIVES LEWINSKY `BLANK CHECK' IN AVOIDING PROSECUTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The rare immunity deal between Monica Lewinsky and
independent counsel Kenneth Starr gives the former intern a free
pass from prosecution as long as she tells the truth to a grand
jury investigating President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's pledge to give Lewinsky ``transactional immunity''
provides broader protection than the more common ``use immunity''
prosecutors give witnesses for testifying in criminal cases. Under
the deal, Starr, who made the same pledge to Lewinsky's mother,
Marcia Lewis, will be barred from prosecuting Lewinsky for matters
discussed in her testimony before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Use immunity would have prevented Starr from using her
grand-jury testimony _ or any evidence derived from it _ as part of
a prosecution of Lewinsky, a former White House intern. Starr would
still have been free to bring Lewinsky up on charges based on
evidence he could collect independently of her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But with transactional immunity, the independent counsel has
given Lewinsky, who faced potential charges of perjury and
obstruction of justice, a ``blank check'' that enables her to avoid
prosecution, said Houston defense attorney Kent Schaffer. All
Lewinsky has to say is ``Bill did it'' to hold up her end of the
bargain, Schaffer said.
</P>
<P>
   The breadth of the immunity deal depends on how broadly her
seasoned Washington attorneys, Plato Cacheris, Jacob Stein and
Nathaniel Speights, defined ``transaction'' in their agreement with
the independent counsel, said former federal prosecutor John G.
Douglass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Presumably, her lawyers have defined it very broadly,'' said
Douglass, who teaches law at the University of Richmond. ``Their
aim would be to protect her from prosecution for perjury ... or
obstruction.''
</P>
<P>
   But the agreement with Starr makes Lewinsky's grand jury
testimony less credible because she now has the ``ultimate bias''
against Clinton, said Schaffer, who is president of the Texas
Criminal Defense Lawyers Association. Starr, in effect, has told
Lewinsky, ``You will never go to jail, you will never be
prosecuted; now, what do you want to say?,'' Schaffer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to cross-examine that witness,'' the lawyer said.
``I don't know what stronger incentive you can give somebody to
lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky testified under oath in Paula Jones' since-dismissed
sexual harassment case against Clinton that she had no sexual
relationship with the president. However, Lewinsky allegedly
contradicted her sworn testimony when she said she and the
president had been intimate, a contradiction that her former friend
Linda Tripp secretly recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky also allegedly urged Tripp to mislead investigators if
they asked about Tripp's claim that Clinton had made unwelcome
sexual advances toward Kathleen Willey, who was seeking a job in
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
