A6989 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWERTEL-COX     07-28 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERTEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Powertel becomes player in 'mobile data' serviceBy Michael E.
Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The big winners usually have a way to break out of the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   That is true of the wireless phone market as much as it is for
the Peachtree Road Race _ to win means breaking away, by either
crossing the finish line first or catching the eyes and wallets of
more consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta may be one of the nation's hottest wireless
markets, with more than 20 percent of residents using the service.
But with six companies in the race, each must find a distinct
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has its brand name. So does BellSouth. AirTouch
Communications has aggressive marketing. Southern seems to rely on
its identity as a utility icon. Nextel markets its ability to
provide either phone or two-way radio communication.
</P>
<P>
   Powertel, an ambitious upstart out of West Point, Ga., surged
into the market late last year and has hammered several themes: No
contracts, clear rate schedules and cutting edge technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just at the very start of mobile data right now,'' said
Allen E. Smith, company president and chief executive officer.
Analysts say wireless use could double in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which started in 1990 selling analog cellular
service, now has licenses to provide digital wireless to areas in
the Southeast with a population of 24.3 million. Powertel has
raised about $1.3 billion from investors including Ericsson and
South Carolina Electric and Gas Co. Each of its 1,000 cell sites
can cost up to $300,000. And the company plans to build 500 cell
sites more by year's end, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues last year were $79 million with a $135 million loss _
and it will be some time before the company, which has 1,300
employees, can turn investment into profit. Tuesday, the stock
closed at 17 9/16, up 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   When Powertel paid GTE nearly $200 million for its wireless
license in metro Atlanta, some skeptics scoffed. Cam Lanier,
Powertel's chairman, obviously wanted to make a regional splash so
the company could be sold to some national player. Now, Powertel
thinks of itself as hunter _ not prey. ``There is not an
acquisition on the plate today, but we need to be in position so
that when opportunity presents itself, we can take advantage,''
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The company will not say how many subscribers it has, but says
its average customer spends nearly $60 per month _ well above the
cellular industry average. Demand for wireless will keep growing,
Smith said. ``The more it becomes an integral part of your life,
the more you will use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Aiming for a particular customer _ the professional who needs
connections to data and the Internet _ the company in the next few
months will offer two-way data links. Connection speeds may not be
stellar, but Powertel says velocity will improve.
</P>
<P>
   Powertel uses a wireless standard known as GSM, for global
system for mobile communication. Other Atlanta providers use other
standards, like the time division multiple access _ TDMA _ used by
BellSouth. GSM allows Powertel to deliver a cutting-edge data
service, Smith said. ``This standard was developed for data.''
</P>
<P>
   Powertel users can receive e-mail on their phones, they can
receive and reply to pages. They have voice mail and caller ID, and
they get their first minute free _ key to avoiding expense of
taking unwanted calls. A user can receive notification that a fax
has been sent, type in a fax number and have the fax sent.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these features are available from other providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data market has never evolved or been a big piece of the
market,'' said Tim Birmingham, marketing director for Nextel in the
Southeast. ``It's a very small niche.''
</P>
<P>
   Nextel uses a Motorola technology, similar to GSM and will be
able to _ eventually _ deliver similar features, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Battcher of BellSouth Mobility said the market and not the
technology is key.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the gee-whiz stuff is great, but it affects very few
customers.'' BellSouth marketing often pounds the company's
extensive wireless coverage _ a weakness for Powertel. ``We are not
rushing to offer new features that customers aren't asking for yet.
</P>
<P>
   Powertel's service area now includes 26 metropolitan areas with
a population of 10.5 million. In metro Atlanta, Powertel has been
steadily expanding service toward Peachtree City and Griffin in the
south, toward Canton and Lake Lanier to the north. This fall it
plans to offer service to Chattanooga, Nashville, Louisville and
Charlotte .
</P>
<P>
   Powertel offers five basic rate plans. For $20 a month, a user
gets 100 minutes of air time and pays per minute after that. For
$40, a user gets 400 minutes and heavier users can pick more
expensive plans. Users who roam outside the Powertel service can
connect to other GSM providers and pay 50 cents a minute for
airtime and 25 cents a minute for long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
