u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-ANIMAS-NAT     07-28 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-ANIMAS-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        CLINTON ADMINISTRATION WANTS TO RENEGOTIATE ANIMAS LA PLATA
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Elliot Zaret  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 28 -- A month after Sen. Ben Nighthorse
Campbell said a presidential veto threat effectively killed the
Animas La Plata water project, the White House wants to ``enter
into a good faith dialogue'' with two Indian tribes, an
administration official told a House panel Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Ute Indian Tribal leaders said it may be too late to
renegotiate the proposed $300 million plan to divert the Animas and
La Plata Rivers in southwestern Colorado and northern New Mexico to
two Ute Indian tribes to resolve water rights issues remaining from
an 1868 treaty with the tribes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their good faith doesn't hold water,'' said Judy Knight-Frank,
Chairwoman of the Ute Mountain Ute Tribe, one of the two tribes
involved in the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The tribes have been mulling over filing suit, something
Campbell has encouraged, as a breach to the treaty. Without the new
water supply, the tribes say their health will be endangered and
economic growth stunted.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Ute Settlement Act Amendments of 1998, sponsored by
Campbell in the Senate and Rep. Scott McInnis, R-Pueblo, in the
House, would build a reservoir and pumping plant on the Animas
River near Durango, along with other features for municipal and
industrial water supplies. It would serve Ute tribes and other
communities in southern Colorado and northern New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The scaled-down version -- known as ``Animas La Plata Lite'' --
would cost approximately $300 million, far less than the original
$754 million project which Congress passed in 1988. But
environmental groups have attacked the plan as just the first step
in an attempt to reinstate the original, larger plan.
</P>
<P>
   Eluid Martinez, commissioner of the Interior Department's Bureau
of Reclamation, said that the Clinton Administration opposes the
current plan, and opposes efforts to scrap the whole plan and start
over. Martinez wouldn't say how the plan could be changed to
satisfy the President, only that such details could come in the
next ``30 or 60 days.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. Roy Romer, D-Colo., who helped negotiate the
settlement, said that it is crucial for the administration to come
to Colorado no later than August with a list of specific changes
they want to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot start from square one again,'' said Romer. ``Too
much time has been lost and we've discussed all the alternatives...
We need some decisions to be made here.''
</P>
<P>
   A Campbell spokesman said that as long as the administration
opposes the deal, the Senator considers it dead. But McInnis said
he plans to continue to push for the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not dead -- of course there's hope for it,'' said
McInnis. ``It's going to be built.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
