r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-`PARENTTRAP'-FILM-REV     07-28 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`PARENTTRAP'-FILM-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMAKE OF `PARENT TRAP' DOESN'T DOUBLE YOUR PLEASURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First, the good news: ``The Parent Trap'' is the first Disney
remake in recent memory that doesn't cheapen its source material.
That's a rarity these days, when ``update'' usually means adding
jokes about crotch injuries and passing gas. The new ``Parent
Trap'' is just as sweet as the 1961 original _ maybe even sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   But it's still a dark sweetness. Both movies are romantic
comedies that take off from a tragic premise _ namely, that a young
couple gets married in a fever, quickly has twin girls, then splits
up, each taking one of the twins with no plans for the girls to
ever see each other again. Even in 1961, this was cruel; in the
'90s, when no one has to explain the terms ``deadbeat dad'' or
``parental abduction,'' it's almost sadistic.
</P>
<P>
   If director Nancy Meyers was going after a realistic update,
both girls would have been in therapy faster than you could say
``child abandonment.'' At least Meyers and her co-writers have the
sense to include a child's-eye lecture about the importance of
fathers.
</P>
<P>
   As for originality _ put aside the occasional cell phone or
alt-rock song, and the new ``Parent Trap'' isn't just a remake;
it's a Xerox. Not only does it follow the original virtually scene
for scene, it lifts some lines verbatim _ and not always the best
lines, either. That it took three writers is baffling.
</P>
<P>
   Meyers and husband/co-writer Charles Shyer are so close to the
material they even name Hallie and Annie _ the two girls who meet
at summer camp, realize they're twins, and then plan to reunite
their parents _ after their own daughters, who have small roles in
the film. Brian Keith may have been in the original, but this one's
the real family affair.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first time Meyers and Shyer have visited such
territory _ they gave us 1984's ``Irreconcilable Differences,'' a
movie in which 10-year-old Drew Barrymore sued her parents for
divorce. (Even though Meyers and Shyer are by all accounts happily
married, one could be forgiven for thinking that they have, you
know, ``issues.'')
</P>
<P>
   Although Meyers is a veteran of nearly two decades of film work,
this is her first time behind the camera. Her pacing is better than
the original, but her biggest success is the performance she gets
out of Lindsay Lohan, who plays the twins.
</P>
<P>
   Lohan's no rookie, either; she's been acting since she was 3,
and she gives one of the most refreshing, unaffected kid
performances to come along in a while. She's natural and unenamored
of her own freckle-faced cuteness, no easy feat considering the
movie's tendency to play cute.
</P>
<P>
   And how nice it is to see a movie in which Dennis Quaid smiles.
Quaid, who plays the girls' father, has sulked through much of the
'90s, sometimes successfully (1993's ``Flesh and Bone''), sometimes
not (last year's ridiculous ``SwitchBack''). He seems relieved to
be playing a good-natured hunk again, and he delivers his most
relaxed performance since 1987's ``The Big Easy.''
</P>
<P>
   As the girls' mother, Natasha Richardson gives a performance
that's perfectly nice _ and that's just the problem. She's neither
impish nor feisty enough to do some of the things she does to
sabotage her ex's romance with a gold-digging publicist (Elaine
Hendrix, in a deliciously comic performance). Richardson has the
biggest shoes to fill here _ Maureen O'Hara, an actress few can
match for backbone and spirit, was the best thing about the
original. (She was so feisty that she even popped Brian Keith in
the eye, a scene that Meyers has wisely chosen to delete.)
</P>
<P>
   As sweet as it is, ``The Parent Trap'' is too derivative to
merit a wholehearted recommendation. But several preview-goers said
they enjoyed the movie BECAUSE it sticks so closely to the
original. Seems a little odd, when it's so easy to rent the real
McCoy. And it's too bad _ if it had tried a little harder, we
really could have had something special here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Parent Trap'' is rated PG for slapstick, two or three
questionable words and some relatively heavy kissing scenes. It's
still family entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Film: ``The Parent Trap'' Director: Nancy Meyers Featuring:
Lindsay Lohan, Dennis Quaid, Natasha Richardson Length: 124 min.
Rated: PG Rating: 2 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
