<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6993 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     07-28 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOY COMES FROM JUST WINGING IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The road to wisdom is a difficult one. The path is rugged,
filled with giant potholes. There are unexpected detours and
inexplicable U-turns. The few maps available are written in crayon,
on a paper towel, under water. Following the traffic can result in
a foolish mistake but, hey, at least you've got company.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder, then, that so many people just give up and
settle for something less than true enlightenment? I think not.
There is much joy to be found in other areas of life. I know
because there I was, and there I would have remained if I hadn't
been issued a particular challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge? Find the restaurant that has the best chicken
wings in the Metroplex. The prize? A pack of Tums. So it's not a
Good Will Hunting type of exercise. I'm no good at complex math
equations but chicken wings, yes, that's something I can do.
</P>
<P>
   So off we went, me and Honey Bunny, in search of the ultimate
hot wing. Every week, we tried a different restaurant. The Chinese
place scored a lot of points with its spicy sesame wings, but we
couldn't stop there. The barbecue place had this
finger-lickin'-good sauce, but the chicken was tough. We searched
from Chez Sammie's, where the poultry was covered in slimy peanut
oil, to KFC, which earned an honorable mention. Still, there was no
clear winner.
</P>
<P>
   Discouraged but determined, I was drinking another bottle of
Pepto Bismol when my husband commented, ``I've heard that Hooters
has good wings.''
</P>
<P>
   I sputtered and pink stuff came flying out of my nose.
``Hooters! You have got to be kidding. I'm not going near that
place. Don't they exploit the wait staff and make them wear
revealing clothes?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh I don't know about that,'' he said. ``I've only heard about
the chicken wings. They've won several national awards with their
recipe.''
</P>
<P>
   How he managed to avoid the bolt of lightning that came through
the kitchen is beyond me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called Hooters for goodness sakes. Do they serve owl
there?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the founders was named Hooter.''
</P>
<P>
   He's good, isn't he?
</P>
<P>
   I let curiosity smother indignation and agreed to try the world
famous Hooters cuisine. But I insisted that the children accompany
us and wear their T-shirts that say ``I love my Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   The waitress came over as soon as we were seated. She looked
like a model for Victoria's Secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, where are your hooters?'' my youngest son instantly asked
her in a loud voice. My husband stared at the table, but I saw the
smile torturing his pressed lips. The four guys at the adjacent
table roared. I pointed to a small, fake owl on the wall and my son
said, ``That's a hooter? That's sorry. I thought hooters were
big.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, much as I hate to admit it, those were some awesome
chicken wings. They won the contest hands down.
</P>
<P>
   On the way home, my son said, ``I wish I could work there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is that, son?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, they had 20 televisions! I could watch sports all day.''
</P>
<P>
   You know, true enlightenment is highly overrated.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. Contact her at (817) 548-5564. Write in care of
the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington, TX
76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
