<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS COULD BE AT TURNING POINT IN CLINTON STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH   AND CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Monica S. Lewinsky's immunity deal with independent
counsel Kenneth W. Starr could prompt Democrats to put new pressure
on President Clinton to tell everything about his alleged sexual
relationship with the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Some party members are worried further delay by Clinton could
mean the issue will explode as they head into the fall elections.
But others said Tuesday they will continue their strategy of
criticizing Starr's methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats are running as far away from the president on this
as they can,'' said political analyst Stuart Rothenberg, who
follows many congressional races around the country. ``They want
him to deal with this, and they don't want to be anywhere near him
when he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon E. Panetta, Clinton's former chief of staff, said on CNN
that Clinton ``owes an explanation ... to the American people. In
the end, I think that will save his presidency.'' Panettta said
Lewinsky's agreement with Starr showed ``this has reached a crucial
stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic consultants interviewed Tuesday said the party is not
concerned if the case comes down to ``he said, she said.'' But some
Democrats are concerned Starr could have independent evidence that
would corroborate allegations that Clinton had an affair with
Lewinsky and urged her to lie about it. Clinton has sworn in an
affidavit he did not have an affair with Lewinsky and he has denied
telling her to lie.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, as members of Congress left a memorial service for two
slain Capitol Police officers, some Massachusetts Democrats were
not running away from Clinton. ``As a prosecutor, I always had a
concern about immunized testimony because it does go to the
question of credibility,'' said Representative William Delahunt,
referring to Starr's agreement with Lewinsky for complete immunity
from prosecution in exchange for her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the public is interested in a $40 million
investigation about consensual sex between adults,'' said
Representative Martin Meehan.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the question of whether Clinton had an affair with
Lewinsky has come up in only a few congressional campaigns. But
that could change, especially if Clinton does not follow through on
his promise to speak ``sooner rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
   House minority leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri, who is
preparing to challenge Vice President Al Gore for the Democratic
presidential nomination in 2000, has called on Clinton to make good
on his promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always believed that Bill Clinton would do as he has
said he would, and would get all the necessary information to the
independent counsel,'' Gephardt said recently. This comment has
been interpreted by some analysts in the last few days as a party
message to the president.
</P>
<P>
   In the worst-case scenario for Democrats, Starr could deliver
his report on the investigation to Congress before the November
elections, and Congress could start impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   If the White House continues its strategy of continued legal
appeals and delaying of the investigation, it could play into the
hands of Republicans who want to turn the case into a broader
campaign issue of whether Democrats can be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton holding record-high approval ratings throughout the
year, many Democrats hoped nothing would happen to damage his
standing. But there have also been signs throughout the year that
Democrats wished he would tell everything as soon as possible.
Former top Clinton aides George Stephanopoulos and Panetta have
urged Clinton to speak up, and White House press secretary Michael
McCurry has mused aloud that Clinton would have talked more if the
matter could have been explained easily.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic consultant Mark Mellman said, ``The level of anxiety
has throughout this whole episode exceeded the level of damage.''
For Democrats to become deeply concerned, he said, there would have
to be overwhelming, independent corroboration of wrongdoing by the
president, not just an alleged sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Tuesday's development about an immunity agreement, some
Democratic leaders said they still think the matter will die down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another television story,'' said Anne Pedersen,
acting chairwoman of the Iowa Democratic Party. ``People are not
tuned in to it. It does not affect their lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
