<HEADLINE>
DOW DROPS 93.46 POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SHARON R. KING    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although investors might not think so, Tuesday's
stock market performance might not even race the pulse of some
die-hard roller coaster aficionados.
</P>
<P>
   But it probably came close.
</P>
<P>
   There were twists and turns and wild gyrations, as continuing
concerns about corporate profits, Asia's financial crisis and the
specter of political upheaval in Washington pushed stocks lower. At
one point, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 212.15 points,
before bargain hunters ratcheted it upward to trim its loss to
93.46 points.
</P>
<P>
   The blue chip index closed at 8,934.78, erasing Monday's 90.88
gain. J.P. Morgan, United Technologies and Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. led
the declines, a 1.04 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the persistent concerns about Asia and corporate
profits was news that former White House intern Monica Lewinsky had
received immunity from prosecution, paving the way for her to
testify before a grand jury seeking to determine whether President
Clinton tried to obstruct justice to hide any relationship with
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a very high run-up, and there's some uncertainty
about the sustainability of earnings,'' said Shannon Reid, a
portfolio manager for the Evergreen Select Strategic Growth fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are more willing to pay up for predictability of
earnings vs. earnings growth, which is what you see at the end of a
cycle,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Asian markets were mixed Tuesday. Japan's benchmark Nikkei 225
index rose 170.18 points, recouping less than half of Monday's
417.53 point loss. Analysts predict Japan's fundamental economic
situation will take at least 12 months to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't read this as indicative of an uptrend,'' said Dan
Seto, a senior economist at Nikko Securities International.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot of skepticism that this new leadership
will shift to anything aggressive'' to spur the Japanese economy,
he said. ``Therefore, the other Asian markets will have limited
upside.''
</P>
<P>
   In domestic markets, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index, fell
17.03 points to 1,130.24, a 1.5 percent decline. The Nasdaq
composite index suffered even steeper declines, falling 36.73
points, or nearly 2 percent, to 1,896.53. Microsoft, Worldcom and
MCI led the declines.
</P>
<P>
   All of these factors still leave investors searching for clues
to determine whether corporate profit growth will improve in the
second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Based on earnings for the 385 member companies of the S&AMP;P 500
that have reported thus far, earnings are expected to grow by about
4 percent in the second quarter. That is slightly above the first
quarter's 3.8 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts now forecast growth to improve in the third quarter, up
7.6 percent. They are looking for even stronger earnings growth in
the fourth quarter, up 14.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Chuck Hill, head of research at First Call Corp., cautions
investors to realize that analysts have already begun making
substantial downward revisions in their third quarter forecasts.
Those changes, at a sharper than usual pace, are a signal that
analysts believe the impact of Asia's woes have not yet entirely
filtered through the domestic market, he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
