<HEADLINE>
FRANCE JOURNAL: VOLCANO SPEWS FAKE FIRE AND REAL IRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV.: a map for use with this story is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
(HLW) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST.-OURS, France _ Louis XIV built Versailles. President
Francois Mitterrand rebuilt the Louvre. Now his predecessor, former
President Valery Giscard d'Estaing, plans to build his own
monument.
</P>
<P>
   A volcano.
</P>
<P>
   Volcanoes used to erupt here in Giscard d'Estaing's home region
of Auvergne until 5,000 years ago, leaving a mountainous landscape
of cinder cones, lava fields and basalt that is best known for the
pure mineral water it produces.
</P>
<P>
   Vulcania, the name of the former president's pet project, will
be a theme park, one costing $87 million, mostly in public funds.
It will have simulated fumaroles (the volcanic vent), steaming lava
flows and temblors, on a site where real lava buried a valley
27,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nature never seems quite good enough for the French, as anybody
knows who has seen what they put plants through in a formal garden.
</P>
<P>
   So two years from now, if all goes according to schedule, the
Puy de Dome, the biggest extinct volcano in the area, will be
mirrored in miniature by a striking metallic cone that will be the
centerpiece of the theme park being built at 3,000 feet altitude
here on the grounds of a former arms depot.
</P>
<P>
   The cone's interior copper lining will reflect bursts of light
simulating eruptions. Most of the exhibits will be below ground _
long walkways through basaltic columns, dial-a-blast consoles that
will show digital simulations of Mt.-St.-Helens-style explosive
eruptions, and auditoriums presenting real-time data on discoveries
on other active volcanic locales, even ones on Mars or the moons of
Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 feet below the surface, rumblings will issue from
a pit that will be the mirror image of the metallic cone. On a
recent day, giant Volvo trucks and shovels were busily digging the
pit out of the solid lava on the construction site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the project to be on time,'' Giscard d'Estaing,
president of the Regional Council of Auvergne, the elected body
that commissioned it, told workers celebrating the first
anniversary of construction work. ``If I understand correctly,
you're not going to take any vacation this summer,'' since there
are ``only two years left before we present this project to the
Auvergnat people.''
</P>
<P>
   Vulcania? Megalomania, environmental groups and other opponents
reply. The fracas has sent pyroclastic flows of controversy
sweeping over Auvergne regularly since Giscard d'Estaing first
broached the idea in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But after a decision this spring by the Council of State, the
country's highest administrative court, struck down the last of a
series of suits by environmentalists and other opponents of the
project, Vulcania now seems unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   Giscard d'Estaing, now 72, looking fit, patrician and pleased in
his office in Clermont-Ferrand, the somewhat down-at-the-heels
regional capital, said in an interview that the project would give
the area a forward-looking image and bring in 500,000 tourists a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are our assets here?'' he asked. ``We have the
countryside, which is superb. We have beautiful Romanesque churches
and medieval castles, but nothing like the chateaus of the Loire
that would attract visitors and make people want to stay.'' If the
unique volcanic landscape doesn't, the theme park will, since it is
meant to take an entire day to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a center about the study of volcanic activity, and
it will change the way people in this region, intelligent but
isolated and somewhat backward-looking, look on life,'' Giscard
d'Estaing said. ``It's a qualitative leap forward.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Vulcania's opponents, Daniele Auroi, a member of the
environmentalist Greens party and a deputy mayor in
Clermont-Ferrand, dismissed the park's scientific ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a Disneyland,'' she said. ``No research will take
place here at all. It'll be Giscard's monument to himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The park and the planned superhighway the former president
succeeded in getting to go with it, she said, would bring an
environmentalist's nightmare of cars and tourists and cheap hotels
and McDonald's restaurants, harming a preserve of natural beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people want to learn about volcanoes, all they have to do
is come to the Puy de Dome to see one,'' she said. ``And 400,000
visitors a year already do that. Vulcania could drive people like
that away.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Auroi and other opponents collected 15,000 signatures
against the project, but the Regional Council, controlled by
Giscard d'Estaing's conservative majority, has commissioned polls
that showed that 72 percent to 86 percent of voters approve.
</P>
<P>
   The futuristic design would fit in with the natural
surroundings, he said, and the council chose one of Europe's best
known architects, Hans Hollein, of Vienna, to come up with it.
European Union rural development funds will provide $12.5 million
for the project, and the French government $4.6 million more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was inspired by Jules Verne's ``Journey to the Center of the
Earth,'' Dante's ``Inferno,'' and the landscape, among many other
things,'' said Hollein, visiting the site with Giscard d'Estaing.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking his feet in the porous decayed basalt that overlays the
location, the designer of the exhibit, Rainer Verbizh, like Hollein
an Austrian, commented: ``In Germany or France, a project like this
would get talked to death. But the French have their Sun Kings, and
their projects get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Simone Shinkaretzky, a local summer resident, said she thought
the former president, who was in office from 1974 to 1981, should
pay no attention to his hecklers. ``They made fun of Louis XIV
while he was building Versailles, too,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
