<HEADER>
A7003 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BENOIT-JACQUOT-FILMS-     07-28 1395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENOIT-JACQUOT-FILMS-ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ANALYST OF PASSION, AND PARIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Leslie Camhi writes frequently about film, art and contemporary
culture for the Village Voice . )  
(rl) 
 By LESLIE CAMHI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Benoit Jacquot is not about to turn out
autobiography. ``I'm not interested in recounting my life through
my films,'' the famously reticent French director said recently.
``I'd rather they teach me something about my life.''
</P>
<P>
   His presence in his work is close to transparent: a finely tuned
eye and intelligence, focused on the intricate, oblique
entanglements of human beings. Inspired by the sensual, emotional
immediacy of actors, he also partakes in his films of an analyst's
measured distance and reserve. His characters, veiled in silence or
adept in miscommunication, rarely say what they're thinking. And
while Jacquot is not the product of a tell-all society, he also
remains largely faithful to a city, Paris, and a set of
psychological concerns that differentiate his work from recent
French films set in the provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers can see Jacquot's analytical mind at work in ``Seventh
Heaven,'' a 1997 film that opened in New York on Friday. Subtle,
cryptic and funny, it explores a modern triangle among a wife, her
husband and her therapist. Mathilde, a young woman, neglects her
job and suffers from frigidity, fainting spells and bouts of
kleptomania. When an enigmatic hypnotist cures her of these ills,
her husband, Nico, begins to shirk his work as a surgeon and his
conjugal duties. A poignant survey of the shifting grounds of
marital power, this comedy of the unconscious is also a compendium
of Parisian neuroses and pleasures, from adultery to
psychoanalysis.
</P>
<P>
   Jacquot, 51, is as contradictory and recondite as his oeuvre.
Tall and angular, with elegant manners, a foxlike face and a gaze
that nails its object, he can seem in conversation at once
surprisingly self-effacing and rather wearied by the limits of
language. He has set two films (one recent, one to come) in the
18th century, and that age of enlightened libertinage probably
appeals to him, for despite his crow's-feet, he reminds an
interviewer of an oddly amiable Marquis de Sade _ fundamentally
chilly but as mirthful as a schoolboy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Parisian by birth and by existence,'' as he puts it, Jacquot
grew up on the films of the French New Wave, assisted the great
writer and director Marguerite Duras when he was in his early 20s
and began his own career as the director of abstruse, rigidly
stylized dramas amid the theoretical ferment of Paris in the 1970s.
``I don't like my early films,'' he admitted. ``I have a hard time
seeing them and acknowledging them as my own. When I made my first
film, `The Musician Killer,' in 1975, it seemed like my last; while
15 years later, with `The Disenchanted,' I felt that I was
beginning my career anew.''
</P>
<P>
   That lyrical, deeply moving film, which was shown this spring at
Film Forum in New York, stars Judith Godreche as a 17-year-old high
school student who lives with her mysteriously paralyzed mother and
her little brother in a once-grand apartment. The film traces her
encounters over the course of three days with several men: her
handsome, arrogant boyfriend; Chan, a Chinese friend and fellow
student; Alphonse, an older writer whom she meets by chance, and
``the uncle,'' a cultivated and insidious retired doctor who
supports her impecunious household.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Disenchanted'' moves across Paris with the exactitude of
an anatomist palpating a body, revealing the city's lush little
islands, afternoon dance clubs, high-rise workers' housing and
gracious bourgeois apartments. It's also a remarkably tender
vivisection that all but exposes the beating heart of a young
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship to Paris is extremely precise in all of
Benoit's films,'' said prolific French producer Philippe
Carcassonne, Jacquot's frequent collaborator. ``We are working
right now on `Pas de Scandale,' to be shot this fall. Benoit has
already indicated the two or three avenues where we are to look for
the main character's apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacquot's later films have all focused on the mystery of women's
identities and desires, set against the exigencies (material,
social, psychological and physical) that circumscribe them.
``Marianne'' (1994), an adaptation of Marivaux's novel ``La Vie de
Marianne,'' stars Virginie Ledoyen as the 18th-century heroine of
indeterminate origins who moves uncertainly through an often
predatory world of servants, tradespeople and aristocrats.
</P>
<P>
   Ledoyen also stars in ``A Single Girl'' (1995), which was well
received in the United States two years ago. Filmed for the most
part in real time, it follows a young woman through an early hour
of a gray Parisian morning as she meets her unemployed boyfriend in
a cafe, tells him she's pregnant and begins her first day of work
as a room-service waitress, delivering breakfast in a four-star
hotel. There she navigates a maze of bosses, co-workers and a
multitude of strangers with whom she shares unwanted moments of
intimacy; all the while, her secret is privately at work within
her. This small, dazzling film tells almost no story; instead, it
focuses with the intensity of a lover's gaze upon the riddle of
another's existence.
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration for ``Seventh Heaven'' was double. Jacquot wrote
the script with Jerome Beaujour for Sandrine Kiberlain and Vincent
Lindon, the two French stars who play the married couple and who
are, in fact, husband and wife. ``I could only have made this film
with a couple who live together,'' Jacquot said. ``It's fiction,
but it also has a documentary aspect, in the way that George
Cukor's films play off the real-life couple of Katharine Hepburn
and Spencer Tracy.''
</P>
<P>
   That the film has the lightness of a 1930's domestic comedy is
all the more striking when one considers its second source of
inspiration: Lacanian psychoanalysis. In 1974, Jacquot directed the
only televised interview with Jacques Lacan, the highly celebrated
and controversial Parisian psychoanalyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had read Lacan's work, and it moved me very deeply,''
Jacquot said. ``Before him, psychoanalysts tended to write of the
unconscious as if they themselves had none. For me, he was a
brilliant model of someone who could be at once extremely rigorous
and precise, and yet open to the effects of the unconscious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He also had a remarkable sense of comedy; he was extremely
adept in the art of surprise,'' Jacquot continued. ``And surprise
is our only real proof of the unconscious.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an art that, as a director, Jacquot takes pains to
cultivate. His preparatory work with actors is lengthy but oblique;
he never rehearses, and all his films are shot using very few
takes. ``The films always spill over the idea I had of them,'' he
said. ``They lead me, together with the cast and crew, elsewhere.
Otherwise, they're just illustration.''
</P>
<P>
   In relation to his work, he attempts to preserve something of
the analyst's fertile silence and enigmatic power.
</P>
<P>
   Kiberlain's troubling and touching performance as Mathilde in
``Seventh Heaven'' required her to feign fainting, hypnosis and
(discretely) orgasm. ``If there's a rapport between hypnosis and
acting, it has to do with the sense of surrender,'' Kiberlain said.
``When Benoit would tell me, now you faint, I didn't have the
faintest idea of how to go about it. But you just let go, you fall.
There has to be a great deal of confidence between actor and
director for that to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacquot enjoys the reputation of a director who is highly
respected by actors. Lindon concurs. ``It's because he loves
actors, listens to them, respects them, and because the actors in
his films are always good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What is it about women that so interests Jacquot?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born a man,'' Jacquot said, ``and women are the part of
humanity that is at once familiar and very, very strange to me.
It's difficult for a man to ask the question, what is a man. It's
as if the question just doesn't arise. Or as if we already know the
response, and it's not necessarily amusing. But a woman can ask
herself the question, what is a woman? I try to respond to that
question with the female characters I invent and the actresses I
film. And they always lead me to further questions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
