</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KALABINSKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACEK KALABINSKI, 59, POLISH JOURNALIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jacek Kalabinski, a Polish journalist and former opposition
figure who worked in the United States since fleeing his native
land in 1983, died on Friday at his home in Rockville, Md. He was
59.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Kalabinski was the Washington-based correspondent of the Warsaw
daily Rzezcpospolita (The Republic). He previously worked for Radio
Free Europe/Radio Liberty as a program editor in New York and as a
senior correspondent in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A 1961 journalism graduate of the University of Warsaw, he did
postgraduate work at the Ecole Nationale des Sciences Politiques in
Paris and as a journalism fellow at Stanford University. He started
his career in the 1960s working as a reporter and editor in Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, he became a news editor for Polish Radio, and from 1973
to 1981 he was a foreign-affairs commentator for the Polish
National Radio network. After the imposition of martial law in
Poland, he was dismissed as ``unfit to serve in a militarized unit
of Polish Radio and Television.''
</P>
<P>
   He had become the president of the Warsaw chapter of the Polish
Journalists' Association in 1981. The association was shut down by
the government the following year. He then was foreign editor of a
Warsaw Catholic monthly and of Poland's largest uncensored
underground weekly, Tygodnik Mazowsze. By then in hiding and on an
arrest list, he wrote under the pen name Cassandra.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his arrival in this country, he was named a visiting fellow
at Yale University. His Op-Ed articles on Central Europe and the
Soviet Union soon appeared in The New York Times and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   A linguist, he also accompanied Lech Walesa to Capitol Hill when
Walesa, the chairman of Solidarity, Nobel laureate and Poland's
future president, addressed Congress in November 1989. To the
audience, his voice, a radio-trained baritone, became Walesa's,
rendering the speech into idiomatic English as the visitor asked
for support in efforts to make Poland ``the America of the East.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalabinski's survivors include his wife, Barbara; a daughter,
Marta, 14; and his mother, Maria Kalabinska, of Warsaw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
