<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7010 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMMUNITY-0729     07-28 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMMUNITY-0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LEWINSKY GRANTED RARE 'TRANSACTIONAL' IMMUNITY FOR TESTIMONY
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Monica Lewinsky has bargained away her Fifth
Amendment right to remain silent in exchange for transactional
immunity, a form of blanket protection so comprehensive it's rarely
granted by prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The deal guarantees that Lewinsky won't go to jail in connection
with her alleged White House tryst, regardless of any evidence that
might arise against her.
</P>
<P>
   In agreeing to grant her such immunity, independent counsel
Kenneth Starr has sacrificed his chance to catch a little fish in
order to have a crack at the big one: President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''Transactional immunity means basically that he's promised that
there'll be no prosecution of her whatsoever, under any
circumstances, in connection with events coming out of this whole
transaction,'' said Thomas C. Green, an attorney with the
Washington firm of Sidley &AMP; Austin who has defended several targets
of independent counsel inquiries. ''It's something that can be
bargained for, and it would be an exceptional circumstance.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, for her part, promised her ''full and truthful''
testimony, in the words of her attorney, Plato Cacheris, who
announced the immunity deal Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That means Lewinsky must answer any and all questions Starr
might raise when he hauls her before the grand jury probing
allegations that Clinton had a sexual relationship with the former
White House intern and later urged her to lie about it, charges
Clinton has denied.
</P>
<P>
   She will not have the option of hiding behind the Fifth
Amendment, which protects citizens from self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   If there's no prospect they're going to be prosecuted, in
essence, there's no possibility of self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there are no consequences to your testifying against
yourself, then you cannot keep your mouth shut,'' said Frank
Schuchat, an attorney with the Denver law firm Holme, Roberts &AMP;
Owen.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's why immunity is given,'' explained James S. Blumstein,
professor of law at Vanderbilt University in Nashville. ''You have
no absolute rights to remain silent if the government says it will
not prosecute you.''
</P>
<P>
   When Starr interrogates Lewinsky before the grand jury,
Blumstein said, ''they will undoubtedly have in their possession
something that would incriminate her.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky has stated in a sworn affidavit that she had no sexual
relationship with Clinton, a position she contradicted in taped
telephone conversations she had with former Pentagon co-worker,
Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement reached Tuesday, Lewinsky could testify as
to whether her earlier affidavit was truthful, without fear of
being indicted for perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses also forfeit their Fifth Amendment rights in exchange
for a more limited, and more widely extended, form of protection
known as ''use immunity.'' Under that form of protection,
prosecutors may not use anything a witness says to prosecute them,
or to seek evidence to prosecute them, though the person can still
be prosecuted if evidence surfaces independently that they have
committed a crime.
</P>
<P>
   ''A grant of 'use immunity' is not an absolute guarantee that
you will not be prosecuted,'' Green, the Washington lawyer, said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
