</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SATELLITE-FOUND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE MISSING, SPACECRAFT EQUIPPED TO STUDY SUN IS FOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Skedded earlier as SCI-LOST-SATELLITE.) 
(th) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Astronomers have located the missing SOHO
spacecraft, which suddenly went silent a month ago while observing
the Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph Gurman, the NASA project scientist for the joint
U.S.-European Solar and Heliospheric Observatory (SOHO) project,
said Tuesday that space agency officials still hoped to regain
control of the scientific observatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a little better off today than we were a week ago,'' he
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   NASA and the European Space Agency announced that ground-based
radio telescopes situated thousands of miles apart were able to
find the $1 billion satellite last Thursday by sending radar
signals into the area of space where the craft should have been.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the National Astronomy and Ionosphere Center in
Arecibo, Puerto Rico, used their radio telescope, which is 990 feet
in diameter, to transmit radar signals toward SOHO's location,
almost a million miles from Earth. NASA's 230-foot Deep Space
Network dish in Goldstone, Calif., picked up signals reflecting off
the satellite and was able to track it for more than an hour,
scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   The spacecraft is very close to its original position and is
turning slowly at a rate of about one revolution per minute,
scientists said. This slow spin rate is encouraging, they added,
suggesting that minimal structural damage has occurred to the
craft. SOHO is equipped with special instruments to study sunlight
at different wavelengths and to analyze particles and magnetic
fields generated by the Sun.
</P>
<P>
   The spacecraft orbits the Sun at a point between Earth and the
Sun where the gravity of each body cancels out that of the other
and keeps the craft in a stable spot.
</P>
<P>
   SOHO was launched on Dec. 2, 1995, and was designed to stay
operational for at least two years. Scientists had hoped to
continue the mission into the next century as the Sun goes through
a period of maximum activity.
</P>
<P>
   Radio contact with the spacecraft was lost on June 24 when it
was given erroneous computer instructions, causing the craft's
solar power panels to switch positions away from the Sun. Deprived
of sunlight, the satellite lost power and stopped responding to
orders from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Gurman, working at NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center in
Greenbelt, Md., where SOHO is controlled, said engineers hope
further radar observations will refine the craft's position and
give more precise information on SOHO's orientation and spin. There
is a possibility that the craft will slowly align its solar panels
with the Sun over the next few weeks and get enough power to allow
it to respond to commands, he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
