<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7013 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SUBPOENA-HNS &LR;      07-28 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SUBPOENA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MAY BE LATEST PRESIDENT TO PROVIDE TESTIMONY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, if independent counsel Kenneth
Starr has his way, would become the first U.S. chief executive to
testify in a criminal proceeding in which he is the target.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton _ no stranger to providing testimony _ would merely
be the latest in a long, recent string of presidents who have
either provided documents to a court or sworn to tell the truth,
the whole truth and nothing but the truth.
</P>
<P>
   President Nixon, even during the height of Watergate, was never
subpoenaed to testify. However, Nixon _ after losing a historic
Supreme Court battle _ was compelled to surrender his recordings of
White House conversations to special prosecutor Leon Jaworski as
part of the investigation of the president and his men.
</P>
<P>
   President Reagan, under investigation in the Iran-Contra
scandal, provided written answers under oath to independent counsel
Lawrence Walsh's questions. Reagan, a target of Walsh's
investigation, was not indicted in the investigation of the
diversion to Nicaraguan rebels of funds from the sale of U.S. arms
to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   One president even appeared as a witness for the prosecution.
Gerald Ford testified against Lynette ``Squeaky'' Fromme, who had
tried to assassinate him on Sept. 5, 1975, in Sacramento, Calif.
Fromme, a follower of Charles Manson, was convicted and sentenced
to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   President Jimmy Carter, his peanut business under federal
investigation for alleged financial misdeeds, answered questions
under oath from special prosecutor Paul Curran in 1979. The
investigation revealed no wrongdoing by the president.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century, President Thomas Jefferson was subpoenaed
to provide documents in the 1807 treason trial of his former vice
president Aaron Burr, accused of scheming to convince some states
to secede from the Union. Burr was acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has testified three times since taking office in January
1993.
</P>
<P>
   He gave videotaped testimony in the trial of James and Susan
McDougal, his former partners in the failed Whitewater land deal.
Clinton also answered questions under oath from former Whitewater
independent counsel Robert Fiske.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the president provided a sworn deposition in a
since-dismissed lawsuit brought by Paula Jones, alleging that
Clinton, while governor of Arkansas, made unwelcome sexual advances
toward the state employee in a Little Rock, Ark., hotel room. The
truthfulness of Clinton's testimony during that deposition, in
which he denied having had a sexual relationship with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky, is part of Starr's wide-ranging
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton may have the Constitution on his side if Starr
persists with his effort to force the president to answer questions
regarding an alleged cover-up of his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution is silent on whether a sitting president can be
subpoenaed. However, the Constitution does state that a president
can be removed from office by impeachment in the House of
Representatives followed by conviction in the Senate for ``treason,
bribery, or other high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   The carefully delineated impeachment process might bar the use
of any other procedure, such as criminal prosecution, for
preventing the president from performing his duties, David Crump, a
University of Houston law professor, said.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional separation of powers between the judicial and
executive branches could prevent courts from ordering the president
to testify. Allowing the federal judiciary to compel presidential
testimony would enable judges hostile to the president to harass
the chief executive by frivolously calling him to testify, Crump
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is the commander in chief, the leader of the
free world, and he has scheduling responsibilities that are
dramatic and awesome,'' Crump added. ``Subpoenas could be used to
harass the president.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Jonathan Turley, a George Washington University law
professor, said a president has ``no greater rights or privileges
than an ordinary citizen'' subpoenaed to appear before a grand
jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The subpoena was not served upon the president of the United
States,'' Turley noted. ``The subpoena was served upon a citizen,
William Jefferson Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The professor predicted that federal courts ``would make fast
work'' of a White House effort to challenge the subpoena on
constitutional grounds, saying judges would be loath to place the
president beyond their judicial authority. ``The likelihood that
the president could quash the subpoena ranks with an asteroid
hit,'' Turley said.
</P>
<P>
   American University law professor Thomas Sargentich, however,
sees shades of gray in the subpoena dispute. Courts have yet to
decide whether a sitting president can be indicted for a crime, and
just as much uncertainty exists as to whether a chief executive can
be subpoenaed to testify in a criminal investigation that could
lead to his indictment, Sargentich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what exactly a court would do,'' the professor
added. ``To subpoena a sitting president is an aggressive action
that hasn't been done before, but we know that Ken Starr is willing
to break precedent.''
</P>
<P>
   The subpoena has been a tool Starr has wielded often in trying
to uncover whether Clinton obstructed the investigation of his
relationship with Lewinsky. The independent counsel has
successfully sought to compel the testimony of Secret Service
agents who guard the president and of Bruce Lindsey, the deputy
White House counsel and a long-time Clinton friend.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr's effort to compel Clinton's testimony could set the
stage for a major constitutional challenge not seen since the
Supreme Court ruled 8-0 on July 24, 1974, that Nixon must surrender
his tapes. Shortly after complying with the court order, Nixon
resigned on Aug. 9, 1974.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
