</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONICA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A moment of Monica, a full day of 'coverage'
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``This is clearly the endgame. There's a sprint to the finish,''
announced Wolf Blitzer, CNN's guy at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   That sprint turned out to be a walk. Didn't matter: On Tuesday,
TV finally got the summer replacement series it's been waiting,
waiting, waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's cameras quickly left Blitzer for the Washington office
building where Monica Lewinsky was expected to meet her lawyers.
When she finally arrived, CNN caught her stepping down a narrow
path cleared through a herd of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   That's all CNN needed: the 10-second walk would be replayed all
day, eventually unreeled in slow motion and stretched into a more
profound 20 seconds, like a Sam Peckinpah death scene.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as is often the case in these media-made events, TV seemed
in disagreement with itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't exactly ax murder,'' allowed CNN legal analyst
Greta van Susteren.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't judge anyone until the final report comes in,'' added
Michael Weisskopf, a reporter CNN recruited from Time magazine to
speculate on events about which he didn't think anyone should
speculate. ``This is only the seventh inning.''
</P>
<P>
   So TV focused on the seventh-inning stretch. CNBC aimed its
cameras unblinkingly at the media waiting for Lewinsky's attorneys
to announce the immunity deal everyone had been reporting all day.
CNBC was covering a news conference that was not yet a news
conference _ these days, a sort of scoop.
</P>
<P>
   We saw a reporter ... turn to her right! Another reporter ...
shifted weight from his right foot to his left! Still another did
... nothing! Just nothing. Nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polls show this (the Lewinsky story) has been irritating to
the American public,'' mused CNBC ``Power Lunch'' anchor Bill
Griffeth. ``They'd rather this story go away.''
</P>
<P>
   CNBC then ran its own tape of Lewinsky walking from a car into
her lawyers' building.
</P>
<P>
   Now that CNN and CNBC had prepped us with their exhaustive
pre-news conference coverage (``Making sausages isn't always
pretty,'' CNN's Frank Sesno said as cameras caught reporters
laughing cynically after Lewinsky's walk), the broadcast networks
stepped in for live reports.
</P>
<P>
   The news conference was this: Lewinsky lawyer Plato Cacheris
taking maybe 20 seconds to say his client had been given
transactional immunity. He didn't take questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does transactional mean?'' a reporter yelled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look it up in the dictionary,'' another reporter advised.
</P>
<P>
   More sausages.
</P>
<P>
   ``In case you missed it, here was the sum total of today's
streetside press conference,'' NBC's Brian Williams said with a
hint of irony. NBC then reran the full 20-second drama of a lawyer
in a pinstripe suit making a statement and walking away.
</P>
<P>
   CBS' Dan Rather was shorter on irony, longer on acting
straight-shootin' dude. ``A huge coup for her attorneys, bad news
for President Clinton,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even Rather couldn't resist. ``Let me put `if' in italics,''
he said, by way of jumping into the day's speculative pool.
</P>
<P>
   So what did we learn from Tuesday's breathless coverage?
</P>
<P>
   We learned that in covering an event, TV doesn't even need an
event anymore. That it can replace real drama with speculation
about drama yet to come. And that it's not above chastising itself
for doing what it's doing _ and then doing it some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later, this matter will come to some kind of end,''
White House press secretary Mike McCurry said at his own news
conference, before sighing for all of us, ``One would hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera is a television critic for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
