<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7022 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMAS-LAWYERS-BOS &LR;      07-28 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMAS-LAWYERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK LAWYERS NOT LIKELY TO WARM TO THOMAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clarence Thomas, as the second black justice in the history of
the US Supreme Court, should be enjoying a hero's welcome Wednesday
when he is scheduled to appear in Memphis before the country's
largest association of black lawyers and judges, the National Bar
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, his appearance has already reignited the long-running
firefight that pits him against nearly the entire leadership of the
civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have the tensions that boiled over when he was named to
succeed Thurgood Marshall not abated, they have hardened into
bitterness and suspicion. Thomas has made it clear that he has no
use for mainstream civil rights thinking. And, in turn, a movement
built largely on judicial action has no patience for the country's
highest ranking black judge.
</P>
<P>
   Even Thomas's decision to show up Wednesday is viewed as a
gesture of defiance. His invitation to speak this spring was
quickly disowned and denounced by much of the association's
membership. But Thomas simply ignored efforts to get him to cancel
his appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Association officials deny that they are attempting to silence
Thomas out of disagreement. But they argue that the panel that
invited him had no right to do so, and say Thomas should have taken
the hint.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had thousands of speakers who represent every point of
view in the political spectrum,'' said A.J. Cooper, a bar
association board member who supported Thomas seven years ago and
opposes him now. ``We have a right to decide who we want to speak
to us and who we don't. If someone else doesn't like it that's
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said, and many association members agree with him, that
Thomas has sold out the fundamental values of the civil rights
movement. But the justice and his supporters would argue that many
of the legal tools the civil rights movement used have become
dated, even counterproductive. Thomas has drawn criticism from
black liberals for nearly 20 years, but shows no inclination to
change his views.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who supported him by and large are dissapointed that he
led them to believe he was going to be a justice who would listen
seriosuly to concerns about minorities and women and poor people in
America,'' said Harvard Law professor Charles J. Ogletree Jr., who
was among those who thought Thomas should steer clear of the bar
association event. Ogletree was an opponent of Thomas's nomination
to the high court.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ... said Thurgood Marshall was a hero,'' Ogletree said.
``He led many to believe he would at least respect the precedental
value of decisions of affirmative action and other issues. He has
dissapointed people who were among his staunch supporters.''
</P>
<P>
   But Yale Law Professor Stephen L. Carter, who had been a clerk
for Thurgood Marshall, said Thomas has been been attacked for
deviating from orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I don't agree with everything he says by a long shot, I
think the notion that we should try to screen for the correct black
position is really dangerous,'' Carter said. ``We should embrace
diversity within the community as much as as we embrace it
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaints against Thomas center around his views on voting
rights, affirmative action, and prisoner rights.
</P>
<P>
   In one ruling often pointed to by critics, he voted to reject an
affirmative action policy at the University of Texas Law School.
The retired chief judge of the 3rd US Circuit Court of Appeals in
Philadelphia, A. Leon Higginbotham argued that the Hopwood v. Texas
decision helped lay the groundwork for the abolition of the
affirmative action efforts in the University of California system.
</P>
<P>
   Association members also feel stung by the fact that the group
endorsed Thomas when he was nominated for the court in 1991 after
being persuaded that that he would eventually ``come around'' to
embrace affirmative action, minority-influenced voting districts
and other civil rights stands.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Thomas has sided with the conservative wing on the
court and joined the slim court majority that has consistently
voted to weaken all those measures. Those votes are viewed by
opponents as not merely differences of opinion, but as acts of
betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a struggle,'' said Ronald Walters, a political
science professor at the University of Maryland. ``As a community
we're faced with a question: Do we go along with him simply because
he's going to be here, or do we fight for our legacy? Most of us
have decided to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose Sanders is an attorney and civil rights activist in Selma,
Alabama, home of some of the most dramatic and pivotal protests of
the 1960s. She argues that the voting rights gains of that era have
been eroded as a direct result of Thomas' actions. She said a plan
that could have led to the election of more black judges in Alabama
was recently scrapped because of fears that it would not pass
Supreme Court muster.
</P>
<P>
   Carter notes that Thomas's battles with civil rights activists
date back to his stint as head of the federal Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission. Even then, as a rising black star in the
Reagan administration, he was viewed with suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite apart from the the issues there's some personal stuff
here, too,'' Carter said. ``There are a lot of people who have
positions silmilar to his on affirmative action who don't generate
the same level of outrage.''
</P>
<P>
   After it became clear that Thomas would proceed with plans to
speak to the association, Ogletree and Higginbotham offered to host
a panel on Marshall's legacy, to be held immediately after Thomas'
speech. That invitation was quickly accepted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
