</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Jones needs to grow up
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know what Andruw Jones needs? He needs a good spanking from
my grandmother back in Indiana. If not that, he needs somebody who
is big and bad inside the Atlanta Braves clubhouse to shout in his
ears so often that he either gets the message about hustling at all
times or requires a hearing aid before his 22nd birthday.
</P>
<P>
   That somebody has to be a player. It can't be a coach or even
manager Bobby Cox. But there is no such player in sight for this
team whose strength overall is its weakness, in this case.
</P>
<P>
   You see, the Braves are huge on professionalism. In fact, with
Tom Glavine leading the way, they've won more games than anybody
during this decade by featuring players who haven't needed to be
told by anybody to give their best every second. They've just done
it.
</P>
<P>
   Well, until now. In case you haven't noticed, the Braves are
being held hostage by a highly talented guy who has these spurts of
indifference on the field. Although something must be done about
Jones' growing problem, the options aren't good for Braves
officials.
</P>
<P>
   They could ship Jones back to the minors, but they won't, and
they shouldn't. It isn't practical at this point. Two seasons ago,
Jones became better than Mickey Mantle during a World Series Game,
and Jones often flashes the skills of Willie Mays during his second
full season in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to the next option: They could trade Jones, say,
before Friday's deadline for as much as they can get. It also would
be foolish. In spite of Jones' shaky attitude toward the game at
times, he remains a cheap and worthy commodity for the Braves as a
player with less than three years of experience. The only reason
why you would trade somebody as young and as promising as Jones
would be if he were a bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   Jones isn't a bad guy. Take it from Cox, who said Tuesday from
the visiting clubhouse at Cinergy Field in Cincinnati, where the
Braves are playing the Reds, ``I like Andruw, and we talk all the
time. In fact, I probably talk to Andruw more than I talk to
anybody on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, but many of those chats between Cox and Jones haven't
resembled those between Barney and Baby Bop. Cox said, ``If this
were somebody with less talent than Andruw, he would have been gone
(from this organization) about two or three years ago. You just
can't tolerate somebody giving less than 100 percent, and when you
have a team like this that features a good work ethic, somebody who
doesn't really sticks out.''
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, Cox has employed everything shy of capital punishment
to get Jones to resemble his peers on the Braves. Cox even tried
baseball's Bataan Death March last week by yanking a nonchalant
Jones from the outfield before the end of an inning and making him
jog toward the dugout in embarrassment before a packed house at
Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. Four days later in Pittsburgh, Jones loafed after a
ball that shot by him for an inside-the-park home run. Although Cox
defended Jones' effort on the play, it is difficult for the rest of
us to give somebody with Jones' recent past the benefit of the
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The answer here is simple: Andruw Jones has to grow up, and the
impetus has to come from Andruw Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore's column appears in the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tlmajc(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
