<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURMA-DISSENT-280&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYANMAR UNDER FOREIGN PRESSURE FOR STANDOFF WITH DISSIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines _ The United States joined with six other
nations Tuesday in demanding that the army generals who run
Myanmar, formerly called Burma, end their five-day standoff with
the leader of that country's democratic opposition, whose car has
been surrounded by armed security forces on a rural highway since
last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition leader, Daw Aung San Suu Kyi, was stopped about
30 miles outside Yangon, formerly called Rangoon, the capital of
Myanmar, as she drove to a meeting with supporters. Her party won
an overwhelming majority in a national election in 1990, but the
military junta refused to turn over power to a civilian government.
</P>
<P>
   Suu Kyi, who won the 1991 Nobel Peace Prize for her campaign to
bring democracy to Myanmar, has refused to budge from her white
sedan, which was reported on Tuesday to have been surrounded by
soldiers and police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and the foreign ministers
of six countries who are here for a meeting of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations _ Australia, Canada, Japan, New Zealand,
South Korea and Austria, representing the European Union _ met on
Tuesday with the Myanmar foreign minister to insist that the junta
end the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats said that the seven nations had urged the
Myanmar government to allow the U.S. and Japanese ambassadors in
Yangon to go to see Suu Kyi on the roadside and to serve as
mediators in the dispute. They said there was no immediate response
to the proposal from the junta, which calls itself the State Peace
and Development Council.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition leader was freed from house arrest in 1995 after
nearly six years of confinement.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Aung San Suu Kyi should be able to travel freely in her own
country,'' Albright said at a news conference here after meeting
with Myanmar Foreign Minister U Ohn Gyaw. ``We hope very much that
there will be a resolution to the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   When she was U.S. delegate to the United Nations, Albright met
with Suu Kyi in Yangon, and she continues to correspond with the
dissident leader. Albright said the United States had received
encouraging reports on Suu Kyi's condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is still with her car,'' the secretary said on Tuesday.
``She has enough food and water and medical attention, and her
health is OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, it is usually kind of a normal practice for countries
to allow their citizens to travel freely within them and to be able
to meet with whomever they want. I think this is an international
norm that many countries obviously support.''
</P>
<P>
   During this week's meetings in Manila, Albright has repeatedly
singled out the Myanmar junta for criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Monday she warned in a speech that Myanmar, which joined the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations last year, had reached ``a
moment of truth'' and that the nation faced ``a social breakdown or
explosion'' after decades of repression. She said the United States
held the junta directly responsible for Suu Kyi's welfare.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued in Yangon, Suu Kyi's political party, the
National League for Democracy, said she had been visited on the
road Tuesday by her doctors. The statement gave no details on the
doctors' findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The provisions in the car _ water and edibles _ are nearly
exhausted,'' the party said. ``Before her health conditions fail,''
it said, she and her two drivers ``should be allowed to proceed on
their journey.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time in the last month that Suu Kyi, the
Oxford-educated daughter of Myanmar's national independence hero, U
Aung San, has been stopped as she tried to travel outside Yangon to
meet with members of her party.
</P>
<P>
   The protest by the United States may mean less to the Myanmar
junta than the criticism offered by the governments of Japan and
South Korea, which have much closer economic and diplomatic ties
with Myanmar. The United States has relatively little economic
leverage left, since it has already imposed severe economic
sanctions on Myanmar as a result of its human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   The junta responded to the international criticism on Tuesday,
issuing a statement in Manila in which it insisted that Suu Kyi had
provoked this week's standoff by failing to give the military
notice of her travel plans.
</P>
<P>
   Her car was stopped about 30 miles south of Yangon to prevent an
``untoward incident from occurring which could affect the peace,
tranquillity and security,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   It accused her of trying to create ``a political issue'' by
staging the incident during this week's meeting of foreign
ministers from the Association of Southeast Asian Nations and other
countries with an interest in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Her car was stopped, the junta suggested, for her own
protection. ``Myanmar authorities,'' it said, ``have always
provided her with meticulous security measures at her request to
ward off any untoward foul play which could impinge on her security
and safety.''
</P>
</TEXT>
