<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-DOGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Animal deaths prompt Delta, American to refuse pets
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Five guard dogs, en route from Atlanta to South
Carolina for training, died from heat-related stress after
thunderstorms kept their Delta Air Lines flight grounded on a
broiling Hartsfield runway for more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The June incident, now under investigation by federal
authorities, has prompted Atlanta-based Delta to join American
Airlines in banning animals from the cargo holds of U.S. passenger
flights through Sept. 15. The carriers cite the deadly heat wave
that's gripping most of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want another animal fatality,'' said Delta spokesman
Bill Berry. ``It will probably be an inconvenience to some people,
but the pet owner, the animal lover, will see this is the best
approach to take.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture is investigating Delta for
possible violations of the Animal Welfare Act in connection with
the dogs' deaths. The airline paid for the animals' autopsies,
which determined they died after being subjected to heat stress in
the non-air-conditioned cargo hold, Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   The Animal Welfare Act, among other things, is designed to
prevent animal injury during air shipments. The USDA requires that
animals not be exposed to more than 85 degrees for more than four
hours, or less than 45 degrees for more than 45 minutes, prior to
boarding. There are no specific temperature requirements once the
animals are on board, ``but there's a requirement that they handle
these (animals) in a way that doesn't allow them to expire,'' said
USDA spokesman Steve Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA has investigated hundreds of animal welfare complaints
involving U.S. airlines in the past 10 years. American Airlines and
Delta recently settled cases with the department. In 1994, Delta
was fined $140,000 after 32 puppies died when a two-hour weather
delay created unbearable conditions in a cargo hold.
</P>
<P>
   Under Delta's new policy, passengers cannot check animals as
baggage through Sept. 15, though if their pet fits in an under-seat
carrier, they can bring it aboard with an advance reservation and a
$60 fee, Berry said. Passengers can also ship their animals on a
Delta Air Cargo flight, if the temperature is below 85 degrees at
the airports where the plane will depart, connect and land.
</P>
<P>
   Delta passengers who are in the middle of a trip with animals
will be allowed to check them on the return flight if the 85 degree
benchmark isn't exceeded; passengers affected by the embargo can
re-book or receive refunds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
