<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GTE-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC-GTE DEAL DRIVES DOWN TELECOMMUNICATIONS STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It isn't often that a merger announcement drives down the prices
of stocks across an industry. But it happened Tuesday, as investors
absorbed the news that Bell Atlantic was paying $53 billion in
stock for the GTE Corp. in a deal structured as a merger of equals.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day's trading, the Bell Atlantic-GTE
combination looked more like the pin that burst the
telecommunications stock bubble than a go-go megamerger. The group,
which had traded at a price-earnings multiple of 27 earlier this
year, was down to a below-market multiple of 21 Tuesday. Months of
merger hype and investor hopes went pop. Like that.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the eight stocks that make up the Standard &AMP; Poor's
telephone index fell Tuesday. The only stock in the group that rose
was US West, which inched ahead 6.25 cents, to $53.75. To be sure,
most stocks were hurt in a weak overall market, but the deal helped
drive the telecommunications index down almost 3 percent to around
613.82. That was well down from its April high of 658.29.
</P>
<P>
   Most distressing, especially to investors who had bought GTE
shares on takeover hopes, was the action in those shares. They
opened at $51.75, down $4 from Monday's close, but rallied to close
at $53.0625, down $2.6875 on the day. Shares in acquirer Bell
Atlantic fell 68.75 cents, or 1.5 percent, to $44.3125.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the deal were not exactly generous to investors.
Instead of getting a premium to the market price for their stock,
as expected, GTE holders got a discount. Bell Atlantic agreed to
hand over 1.22 of its shares for each GTE share. That translated to
$54.90 a share, below the $55.75 price of GTE stock the day before
the deal was announced.
</P>
<P>
   It is typical in a takeover for an acquirer's shares to decline.
But the drop in GTE's stock was puzzling to investors who were
positive on the deal. Ray McCaffrey, portfolio manager and analyst
at Pilgrim Baxter Value Investors, who owns the stock for his
clients, said, ``There's no dilution in the deal, it's accretive to
both companies' earnings, and it gives them a chance to be one of
the survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   What was behind GTE's dismal stock performance?
</P>
<P>
   Money managers gave several explanations. Mario Gabelli, a money
manager and telecommunications stock fan, said that although the
deal would create a company with a strong balance sheet and
financial muscle, it fell far short of what is required nowadays
for companies hoping to compete worldwide with giants like Deutsche
Telekom, France Telecom and British Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal solves some minor issues,'' Gabelli said. ``But it
doesn't address the globalization of the telecom market. It is
still landlocked, still parochial. They need to accelerate the pace
to create a global alliance.'' Gabelli suggested that a logical
partner for an American company would be British Telecom. ``You
can't draw a Maginot Line at the borders of your country and say
you are going to compete on a global basis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Why did the deal wreak havoc on the entire telecommunications
sector? One reason may be a growing belief among investors that the
Bell Atlantic-GTE deal would result in increased scrutiny by
regulators on previously announced deals that are not yet closed.
Ameritech stock, for instance, fell almost 5 percent Tuesday on
fears that its acquisition by SBC Communications, announced in May,
would not pass regulatory muster.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to regulatory fears is the fact that there is little in
the deal that brings more competition to the local service market.
With $110 billion in revenues, local phone service is the biggest
telecommunications market. In exchange for letting some of these
mergers go through, Federal regulators may insist on prying open
those markets to competition, perhaps by requiring a regional
company like Bell Atlantic to offer competitors the chance to lease
the last mile of cable that goes into people's homes for a
reasonable rate.
</P>
<P>
   If the Federal Communications Commission were to release the
grip that regional Bell companies currently have on local service
markets, the impact on all the companies, including GTE, would be
great. Local service generated 28 percent of GTE's revenues last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The tremors that the deal sent through the entire
telecommunications sector Tuesday led some market watchers to
wonder whether the merger signaled a turning point in
telecommunications valuations. GTE was a well-known takeover
candidate, after all; its stock traded as high as $62 in April on
the assumption that it would be bought. At that level, optimistic
investors seemed to think the company could fetch $65 a share in a
buyout, or even more.
</P>
<P>
   For GTE shareholders to accept the equivalent of less than $55 a
share for their stock means that valuations of other companies in
the business, especially the regional Bell operating companies,
will almost certainly be ratcheted down.
</P>
<P>
   So says Tom Burnett, director of Merger Insight, an
institutional investor advisory firm in New York. ``Most people are
surprised that GTE accepted this'' offer, said Burnett.
``Underneath it says to me, `We couldn't get the stock back to $65
or $70 on its own, so we decided to join up with these guys.'''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Burnett said, investors Tuesday were busy
reconfiguring values in the industry. ``Reality is very often
different from the hopes and prayers that go into pre-announcement
trading,'' he said. ``The hopes that GTE is a $70 stock have been
dashed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
