<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7030 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-ROTUNDA-BOS &LR;      07-28 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-ROTUNDA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERS EULOGIZE SLAIN OFFICERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two police officers who considered themselves
ordinary men were hailed by President Clinton Tuesday as
extraordinary symbols of ``quiet courage and uncommon bravery'' as
they were honored in ``the hall of heroes'' at the US Capitol, the
building they died defending.
</P>
<P>
   In a ceremony fraught with emotion, the grieving families of
Detective John M. Gibson and Private First Class Jacob J. Chestnut
sat before their flag-draped caskets in the majestic Rotunda as
Clinton and congressional leaders extended the nation's sympathy
and gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitol Police officers were shot to death last Friday as
they protected hundreds of tourists and congressional workers from
a gunman who broke into the building, apparently firing
indiscriminately.
</P>
<P>
   ``In passing, your husbands and fathers brought together this
nation,'' said House Speaker Newt Gingrich of Georgia. ``Their
devotion to duty, sacrifice to defend freedom and commitment to
life has reminded millions and millions of people that while this
building is the center of freedom in the world, it only lasts as
long as there is courage.''
</P>
<P>
   As the officers' widows fought back tears, they were surrounded,
in a striking display of support and unity, by Hillary Rodham
Clinton, Vice President Al Gore, former Senate Majority Leader Bob
Dole, several Cabinet members, US Supreme Court Justice Antonin
Scalia, the 535-member Congress and hundreds of police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone but the officers' immediate families remained standing
throughout the 45-minute service, a moving gesture of respect.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut, 58, and Gibson, 42, were the first individuals other
than unknown soldiers of war to lie in state in the Capitol Rotunda
who were not widely recognized figures. Flanked by white-gloved
honor guards, their caskets lay on the marble floor where the
coffins of eight presidents have rested.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the near-anonymity of the officers, several leaders
said, that made them powerful symbols of the risks that law
enforcement officers brave daily across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fitting that we gather here to honor these two American
heroes in this hallowed chamber that has known so many heroes, in
this Capitol they gave their lives to defend,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In honoring them, Clinton added, ``We honor also the hundreds of
thousands of other officers who stand ready to do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   An overflow crowd of thousands listened silently and bowed their
heads outside the Capitol while the voices of Clinton and the other
dignitaries boomed through loudspeakers. Even scores of tired
children showed remarkable restraint in the 90-degree heat, staring
quietly at the Capitol steps.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the officers' families squeezed together near a bust of
the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and a portrait depicting the
signing of the Declaration of Independence. As their eyes glistened
with tears, many of the mourners glanced at the Rotunda's frescoed
dome ceiling, towering nearly 10 stories above them.
</P>
<P>
   The dome is topped by the Statue of Freedom, one of the most
prominent sights on the Washington skyline. ``The monument for
these two heroes is the monument of freedom that is exemplified by
this building,'' said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   In a private moment afterward, the Clintons and some lawmakers
met with the officers' families. Gibson is a Waltham, Mass. native
whose wife, Evelyn, is the niece of Representative J. Joseph
Moakley, Democrat of South Boston. The couple has three children,
Kristen, John and Daniel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very brave and very courageous, but clearly they are
just really hurting,'' Senator John F. Kerry said after meeting
with the Gibson family.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said the Gibsons are ``very grateful for all the support
they have gotten. They really feel the sense of shared grief, and
they are very grateful for everybody's reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut's wife, Wen Ling, attended the ceremony with their
three children, Joseph, Janece and Janet, and his two children from
a previous marriage, Karen and William.
</P>
<P>
   Both officers will be buried in Arlington National Cemetery
after separate funerals Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect in the shooting, Russell Eugene Weston Jr.,
underwent surgery Tuesday for his wounds and was in stable
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday's ceremonies, members of the House and Senate
paid a private tribute to the officers. Many hugged Representative
Tom DeLay of Texas, the House majority whip, whose office Gibson
was assigned to protect when he died. Friends and foes alike hugged
DeLay, from Senator Bob Smith, a New Hampshire Republican, to
Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was kind of staggered by it all,'' Kerry said of the
shootings. ``There is a pall over the whole place.''
</P>
<P>
   The memorial service was part of a day-long tribute to the
officers, as their caskets lay in the Rotunda for 11 hours and were
viewed by thousands of lawmakers, congressional workers and others.
</P>
<P>
   Heads bowed, the mourners slowly circled the caskets in a
clockwise procession of grief, the rhythm of their footsteps
piercing the eerie stillness. Some crossed themselves, others
cried, and nearly all moved through in reverent silence.
</P>
<P>
   Among them strode other ordinary men and women, like Gibson and
Chestnut, who keep the Capitol going every day: apron-clad cooks,
subway drivers, switchboard operators and many others.
</P>
<P>
   They were joined by police delegations from around the country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe correspondent Estella Duran contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
