<HEADLINE>
GAILEY UNLEASHES THE HITTING IN COWBOYS PRACTICE
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Cowboys coach Chan Gailey ended Tuesday's
practice with a goal-line session featuring live hitting. It turned
a typical, mundane, technique-oriented workout into something
exciting.
</P>
<P>
   The lively drill was topped off by a quarterback sneak for a
touchdown by Troy Aikman. The sight of ravaging defenders piling on
the $50-million man in a training-camp practice had many onlookers
gasping. It's a good bet Aikman had never participated in a live
quarterback sneak in his entire career.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman didn't mind, saying ``I scored. They can't hurt me.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive lineman Chad Hennings jabbed, ``He should be a
fullback; he weighs 235 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to another example of Camp Chan.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey is proving to be a Jimmy Johnson-like psychologist. He
said the snippets of ``live'' hitting, compared to the daily doses
of full contact at past Cowboys camps, are by design. He said it
ensures high quality and enthusiastic contact when the players
finally get an opportunity to let go.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes that ``chomping at the bit'' premise holds true when
the Cowboys meet Seattle in their preseason opener Friday night at
Texas Stadium. MILLS: SLOWER BUT SMARTER
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys veteran receiver Ernie Mills calls them the good old
days. He watches Jimmy Oliver, Billy Davis and Stepfret Williams
run in practice and remembers the days when he could run fast and
free.
</P>
<P>
   A torn anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee, sustained in
the 1996 Super Bowl, changed all of that. Now, the eight-year
veteran Mills gets by on guile and savvy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that's why they call you a veteran,'' said Mills, 29.
``I have to learn different things to get open. It takes a while to
learn some things. Now, I can run routes without having a marked
field, because I've been running routes for a long time. I just got
a better feel for the game. I know when the quarterback is getting
ready to throw the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills, who said he was smaller when he was faster, has turned to
the weight room to add strength and bulk. He also said he's a film
guy now.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came into the league, if you cut on a film, it was a
struggle for me to stay awake,'' Mills said. ``Now, I watch and
study defensive backs.'' GONZALEZ ENDORSEMENT
</P>
<P>
   The release of former TCU quarterback Max Knake was an
endorsement of sorts for rookie free-agent Danny Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Cowboys brought in Josh LaRocca to compete for the
third quarterback spot, Gailey said he likes what he has seen in
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a strong arm and good knowledge of the game,'' Gailey
said. OFFICIALS IN CAMP
</P>
<P>
   Three NFL referees were at practice Tuesday to work with the
Cowboys on rules interpretations. The officials will stay until
tomorrow, when they will conduct a presentation about rules changes
in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Their presence was met with approval from Gailey, who said he
told the officials to tell players when they have committed a
penalty and why, while telling the players not to be shy about
asking for clarifications and interpretations from the officials.
MAKING YOU GO HMMM
</P>
<P>
   Following the morning practice, receivers Michael Irvin and
Billy Davis stayed late to catch passes from quarterbacks Jason
Garrett and LaRocca, while the team's corps of young receivers
traipsed off to the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   If Irvin or Davis need extra practice, how about Macey Brooks,
who has struggled. Or Jeff Ogden, who has missed several days of
practice due to injury. Or Stepfret Williams, who is fighting for a
starting job. Or roster long shots Michael Hicks and Taj Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think the Cowboys' coaching staff didn't notice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
