<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7034 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TACTICS-NYT &LR;      07-28 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TACTICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CLINTON WILL BENEFIT IF LEWINSKY TESTIFIES FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-LEWINSKY-CHRONO) 
(bl) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Monica Lewinsky's decision to cooperate with
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr added fresh legal urgency to the
political strategy of delay that President Clinton has pursued over
the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Clinton and his lawyers have waged in a political war
of attrition against Starr. Delay worked in the president's favor
because in the protracted fights over executive privilege,
attorney-client privilege, and whether the Secret Service should be
allowed to testify before Starr's grand jury, the Independent
Counsel was portrayed as partisan and overzealous.
</P>
<P>
   Even as his lawyers lost many of the legal rounds they fought
against Starr, the president's approval ratings soared and Starr's
plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   Back in January, the president said he wanted to tell the
American people the full story sooner rather than later. Then his
lawyers said that Starr's tactics made further statements from the
president, beyond his initial denial of a sexual relationship with
Ms. Lewinsky, too perilous. Then, as they threw roadblocks in front
of Starr, Clinton's defenders complained that Starr's investigation
was taking longer than it took the United States to win World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is a more tangible legal reason for Clinton to try to
seek more time before he decides whether to give testimony to Starr
and comply with the subpoena he has received from the independent
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   With prosecution of Ms. Lewinsky all but impossible (she would
only be vulnerable to prosecution only if she lies to the grand
jury), the president himself appears to be the main target of
Starr's expanded, six-month probe of an alleged affair between the
president and the former intern. So Clinton would almost certainly
benefit from having Ms. Lewinsky's version of events be given to
Starr before his, hoping to learn what she said either through
contacts between his lawyers and hers, or from leaks in the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would prefer to go in to testify knowing what has gone on
before,'' said Lawrence Barcella, a former Justice Department
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's agreement with Starr creates the potential for a
``he said/she said legal confrontation'' in which Ms. Lewinsky
would be the lead witness against the president. Ms. Lewinsky has
agreed to tell Starr that she did have a sexual relationship with
Clinton, according to lawyers familiar with her talks with Starr,
while the president has denied any relationship. Since Clinton
swore, in the Paula Jones sexual harassment suit, that they had not
had sex, Ms. Lewinsky's assertions could make the president
vulnerable to a perjury charge.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing the details of Ms. Lewinsky's testimony could help the
president develop specific rebuttals and question her credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's immunity agreement with Starr significantly
complicates the most important decision the president must reach in
coming days, whether to comply with the subpoena he received from
Starr, the first summons to a sitting president to appear before a
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   With Ms. Lewinsky's deal and his own legal jeopardy heightened,
many lawyers would normally advise someone in Clinton's place to
avoid testifying altogether, either by moving to quash the subpoena
or by citing the constitutional right against self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton is no ordinary witness. Every legal decision he
considers is freighted with political consequence. Whatever the
Constitution says, the American public often views citing the Fifth
Amendment as an admission of guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, in criminal cases, targets are not summoned before
grand juries. ``An individual who is invited to appear before a
grand jury knowing that he is a target is normally advised that to
do so would not be in his best interest,'' explained Richard Ben
Veniste, a former Watergate prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the president's advisers believe he must eventually
testify. But in negotiating with Starr over the terms of any
presidential testimony, a process that is itself almost guaranteed
to win further delay, almost all of Clinton's advisers agree that
Ms. Lewinsky's testimony should come first, according to several
lawyers close to his defense team.
</P>
<P>
   The details and scope of Ms. Lewinsky's testimony could become
known to Clinton's lawyers through the press.
</P>
<P>
   A second way Clinton's lawyers could learn about Ms. Lewinsky's
testimony is through the lawyers' network. Several of the lawyers
representing witnesses in the investigation share information and
there is nothing that legally prohibits a witness from discussing
his or her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Although the deal Ms. Lewinsky's new legal team struck with
Starr makes such behind-the-scenes cooperation and coordination
much more unlikely, it is not out of the question. Ms. Lewinsky's
lawyers are friendly with the president's team. Plato Cacheris, for
example, is so chummy with Robert Bennett, one of the president's
lawyers, that he has helped him shop for a nattier wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   With Starr quickening the pace of his investigation and reaching
a culmination point, many House Republicans are on edge. The
president's strong political standing is one worry. Another is that
Starr, even with Ms. Lewinsky's cooperation, will wind up where he
began: with an investigation focused on the president's private
life.
</P>
<P>
   As the president proceeds with caution and deliberation,
balancing his political interests against his legal ones, so, too,
is the man who may have to act on Starr's findings, House Judiciary
Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, who would guide any impeachment inquiry, has indicated no
eagerness to receive a report from Starr. In an interview late last
week Hyde's counsel, Chicago lawyer David Schippers, said ``God
forbid it comes over.''
</P>
<P>
   Schippers, 68, is a seasoned prosecutor and a lifelong Democrat
who has known Hyde for years. Last winter, he agreed to move to
Washington and handle any impeachment investigation that Starr's
probe might trigger. He has put together a hand-picked team of
eight lawyers and investigators, many of whom he worked with in
Chicago. One is his son.
</P>
<P>
   Last January, Hyde said his committee would need more than
evidence of an illicit affair to begin impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't impeach him for a peccadillo,'' Hyde said in a
television interview.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
