   By Michael Paulson. (story will move in the ``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) Microsoft Corp. denied it
committed any antitrust violations and countersued 20 states that
had charged the software giant with anti-competitive behavior. The
company said the states unconstitutionally undermined its software
property rights. It filed a formal denial to allegations in
antitrust lawsuits by 20 states and the U.S. Justice Department.
The company has been accused of trying to crush competition for the
Internet browser market to protect its virtual monopoly for
operating systems. In its counterclaim, Microsoft said that the
states were seeking ``to impose state-law restrictions on and
thereby impair Microsoft's rights under the Copyright Act and the
Constitution.'' The company also denied allegations contained in
the Justice Department's complaint that it asked Netscape
Communications Corp. executives to illegally divide the market for
Internet browsers. (summary from wires.)
