<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GTE-BELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS, INVESTORS CAUTIOUS ON BELL   ATLANTIC-GTE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Corp. says its $52.07 billion buyout of GTE Corp.
will create a hot player in the telecommunications market, but the
deal got a cool reception Tuesday on Wall Street and in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, if completed, would create the nation's largest
telephone company, with over 250,000 employees in 40 states and $53
billion in revenue _ more than AT&AMP;T's 1997 revenue of $51.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner was the takeover announced, however, than some critics
questioned whether it would benefit consumers under the a two-year
old federal law intended to spur competition in the
telecommunicaitons industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger makes sense for the companies involved, but the
benefits to the marketplace are less clear,'' said Jeffrey Kagan,
an Atlanta telecommunications analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators, whose approval will be needed for the deal
to happen, remained noncommittal while investors dumped shares of
both GTE and Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the parties will demonstrate how this merger advances
the pro-competitive thrust of the Telecommunications Act,'' William
E. Kennard, chairman of the Federal Communications Commission, said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic's stock fell 11/16 to close at 44 5/16. Shares of
GTE, of Stamford, Conn., fell 2 11/16 to 53 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the merger announcement, five GTE shareholders
filed separate civil suits in New York State Supreme Court in
Manhattan claiming they should receive more for their shares. Bell
Atlantic headquartersa are in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Bell Atlantic will exchange 1.22 shares for
each share of GTE. Based on Bell Atlantic's closing price, that
works out to $54.06 a share for GTE, or a total of $52.07 billion.
Bell Atlantic will also assume $14.1 billion in GTE debt.
</P>
<P>
   Executives defended the deal at a news conference in New York.
Pairing GTE, the nation's largest independent phone company with
Bell Atlantic, which dominates the local telephone market between
Maine and Virginia, is ``a merger of equals in every way,'' said
Raymond W. Smith, Bell Atlantic's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The merged companies _ which will get a new corporate name _
will be run by Bell Atlantic president Ivan Seidenberg, who will be
president and co-chief executive with Charles R. Lee, GTE's
chairman, who will remain chairman and co-chief executive. He will
become sole CEO in three years and succeed Lee as chairman in
mid-2004. Smith will retire next year.
</P>
<P>
   The deal faces close scrutiny in many circles, starting with
investors, concerned about the finanical terms of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``GTE has never been for sale, '' said Lee, adding that the
terms are ``appropriate,'' and that shareholders will see
significant value in the combination in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees with him. Some institutional shareholders
maintain the deal for GTE is too low and does not include the kind
of a price premium found in other megamergers. Several Wall Street
analysts questioned whether the merger terms would change if GTE's
stock price drops.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic and GTE management ``will have an uphill battle
convincing GTE shareholders that there are enough strategic and
operational positives to the deal,'' said Scott Wright,
telecommunications analyst at Fahnestock &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said he doubted another company would offer a
significantly higher price, but noted that Bell Atlantic could
modify the financial terms of agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Bell Atlantic-GTE merger, which company officials said will
take 12 to 18 months to complete, has also raised questions over
whether the mammoth company will bring long distance competition to
the marketplace. With GTE, a small but but growing provider of long
distance services spread out in the 28 states, a major goal is to
reach the lucrative 13-state Northest region and the District of
Columbia that Bell Atlantic services, where 30 percent of all long
distance calls are made.
</P>
<P>
   But under the Telecommunications Act of 1996, Bell Atlantic must
first open up its local telephone markets, known as the local loop,
to competitors in the Northeast. It hopes to fulfill the
requirements in New York by year end with Massachusetts in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bell Atlantic does not have any state approvals, the
federal regulators including the Department of Justice should
withhold their approval of the merger, said Congressman Edward J.
Markey, (D-Mass). the ranking Democrat on the House
Telecommunications, Trade, and Consumer Protection subcommittee.
``This merger should not happen until all local loops are in Bell
Atlantic's region are open,'' said Markey. ``That should give
tremendous an incentive to other regions to get their regional
phone companies to open their markets. It would be a big mistake if
the Justice Department approved this kind of merger absent
conclusive evidence that these local loops were irrevocably open.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcement was the fourth in a series of
consolidations through mergers and acquistions in the
telecommunications industry this year. All have the stated goal of
offering customers a combination of services, including local and
long distance, high-speed Internet access and wireless
communicaitons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
