u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-MARTIN-NYT &LR;      07-28 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MARTIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM MCCHESNEY MARTIN JR., LONGTIME FED CHAIRMAN, DIES AT 91 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  (rl) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   William McChesney Martin Jr., the chairman of the Federal
Reserve for 19 years spanning five administrations, from that of
Harry S. Truman to Richard Nixon, died on Monday at his home in
Washington. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a plain-spoken Democrat from Missouri, detested
inflation. He once said that the role of the Federal Reserve was
``to take away the punch bowl just when the party gets going.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he was criticized alternately for making credit too
easy and too tight, Martin was known as an honest, responsible man
who often stood up against the political pressures of the executive
and legislative branches. And he retained the confidence of five
presidents, even when he opposed them.
</P>
<P>
   Martin set the course of the nation's monetary policy during an
economic golden age. His tenure included the nation's longest
economic expansion, from 1961 to 1969. That growth period ended
when the central bank was forced to begin raising interest rates to
fight the rising inflation that was caused by government spending
during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his most controversial moves, in December 1965, Martin
voted to raise the discount rate _ the rate at which commercial
banks borrow from the Fed _ despite President Lyndon Johnson's
objections. After the vote, he was summoned to Johnson's ranch. He
soon emerged to say that the meeting had changed neither man's
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Martin often verbally battled with his most bitter critic, Rep.
Wright Patman, a Democrat from Texas, for whom interest rates could
never be low enough. But he largely avoided public squabbles and
had a knack for stating his gloomy predictions in a pleasant way.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of one economic slump, Martin warned Congress that
you can't ``spend yourself prosperous.''
</P>
<P>
   Another time, he remarked, ``A perpetual deficit is the road to
undermining any currency.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement Tuesday, Alan Greenspan, the current
chairman of the Federal Reserve, said that Martin had set a
``masterful example.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Crucially, Chairman Martin moved the Federal Reserve from
being an adjunct of the Treasury Department to the independent
status we know today,'' Greenspan's statement said.
</P>
<P>
   In private, Martin was known as a relaxed, friendly man who had
an engaging, boyish grin. He was an avid tennis player who often
played on a court across the street from the headquarters of the
Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   His father, a prominent banker in St. Louis, had helped
President Woodrow Wilson draft the Federal Reserve Act, which
created the central bank in 1913. Later, his father served as
president of the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis, and Martin
followed, working in his younger years as an examiner at that same
bank.
</P>
<P>
   After a move to New York, Martin, at age 31, became the first
paid president of the New York Stock Exchange, a position that
earned him the nickname of ``boy wonder of Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1941, he left his $48,000-a-year job at the exchange to serve
in World War II, where he began earning a salary of $21 a month. He
rose to the rank of colonel, serving in several key wartime
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Martin became chairman of the Export-Import Bank
and then served as assistant secretary of the Treasury under
President Truman, a fellow Missourian.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's 19-year chairmanship of the Fed under both Democratic
and Republican presidents was longer than the term of any other
chairman so far.
</P>
<P>
   When President Truman interviewed him about taking the
chairmanship, Truman recalled that he had bought some Liberty Bonds
in the First World War that had later declined in value. ``You
wouldn't ever let that happen again, would you?'' the president
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Martin replied that he wouldn't want it to happen, but unless
the Administration followed responsible fiscal and monetary
policies, it probably would happen again.
</P>
<P>
   President Kennedy had told Martin in 1961 that most of the
Kennedy advisers wanted a new Fed chairman and questioned him
closely about whether he intended to ``flaunt'' the independence of
the Fed. In the end, Kennedy asked him to stay on and explained
that he did so because ``responsible men'' were not easy to find.
</P>
<P>
   A similar conversation occurred early in President Johnson's
administration, with the President telling Martin that he wanted
low interest rates all the time. The chairman replied that he would
have to get another man to achieve that.
</P>
<P>
   Martin stepped down from the central bank in January 1970. He
then served on the board of directors for many corporations and
nonprofit organizations, including IBM, American Express and the
National Geographic Society. For many years, he worked as a lawyer
for Riggs National Bank in Washington. He also served as president
of the National Tennis Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Cynthia Davis Martin, and their
three children, Diana Martin of Washington, Cynthia Martin Ghenea
of Portland, Maine, and William McChesney Martin III of Cambridge,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The New York Times in 1985, Martin said
there was much double-talk in most discussions about monetary
policy, which ranks as one of Washington's most arcane subjects.
</P>
<P>
   When he took office, Martin said, he had told himself: ``My
gracious, here I am the new chairman of the Fed and I'm doing my
best _ I'm not the brightest fellow in the world, but I'm working
hard on this _ and I haven't the faintest idea of how you figure
the money supply. Yet everybody thinks I have it at my fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't really know what the money supply is now, even
today,'' Martin continued. ``They print some figures _ I'm not
trying to make fun of it _ but a lot of it is just almost
superstition.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
