<HEADER>
A7047 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-IMMU     07-28 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-IMMUNITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY'S IMMUNITY BROADER THAN THAT OF WATERGATE FIGURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-TACTICS, CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-LEWINSKY-CHRONO) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not all immunity is equal.
</P>
<P>
   Having been granted what lawyers call transactional immunity,
Monica Lewinsky is off the hook as long as she tells the truth.
</P>
<P>
   With transactional immunity, which prosecutors give only when
they want someone's testimony very badly, she cannot be prosecuted
for the wrongdoing she testifies about. To put it another way, not
only is she safe from being incriminated by her own words, but from
the words of others.
</P>
<P>
   That last point is crucial in understanding the difference
between transactional immunity and the more common use immunity.
</P>
<P>
   When granted use immunity, a witness may not be incriminated by
his or her own testimony, nor are prosecutors supposed to use that
testimony to gather other evidence against the witness.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors can and do use other avenues to gather evidence
against witnesses who have use immunity. A quarter-century ago,
more than two dozen witnesses were granted use immunity so they
would testify before a Senate committee investigating the Watergate
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most important witnesses, John Dean, President
Richard Nixon's White House counsel, and Jeb Stuart Magruder,
deputy director of the Nixon re-election committee, then pleaded
guilty to obstruction of justice. Prosecutors had gathered plenty
of evidence against them before their Senate testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, two important figures in the Iran-Contra scandal,
Lt. Col. Oliver North and Vice Adm. John Poindexter, fared better.
They were granted use immunity for their congressional testimony,
and they were later convicted in court _ on evidence not gleaned
from that congressional testimony, the prosecution maintained.
</P>
<P>
   But an appeals court threw out the convictions, holding that
even though the defendants' congressional testimony had not been
used at trial, it still might have tainted the recollections of
other witnesses who had seen the defendants on television.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7049 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROBE-LEWINSKY-BOS &LR;      07-28 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROBE-LEWINSKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY TO TESTIFY FREE OF THREAT OF PROSECUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr granted former
White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky the broadest possible form of
prosecutorial immunity Tuesday, paving the way for Lewinsky to
appear before a federal grand jury as the star witness in the case
against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, as counsel for Monica Lewinsky, have reached an agreement
today that for full and truthful testimony, she will receive
transactional immunity in this case,'' said Plato Cacheris, one of
her three lawyers. Flanked by attorneys Jacob Stein and Nathaniel
Speights, Cacheris then walked away from the horde of reporters and
cameramen in silence.
</P>
<P>
   That one sentence, spoken in a soft tone, roared through the
corridors of power here Tuesday with a force unseen since the first
days of the Lewinsky investigation in January.
</P>
<P>
   The grant of immunity virtually assures Starr that Lewinsky will
testify, as she reportedly offered in January, that she engaged in
a sexual relationship with Clinton in 1996 and 1997 _ in direct
contradiction to the president's sworn deposition in the Paula
Jones sexual harassment suit.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal sources have also hinted that Lewinsky will provide
incriminating information beyond the nature of her relationship
with Clinton but short of explicitly saying that the president
pressured her to lie. Other legal analysts speculated that the
breadth and depth of the immunity offered by Starr indicates that
Lewinsky may be prepared to testify to instances in which Clinton
attempted to obstruct justice in the Jones suit.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's mother, Marcia Lewis, received the same grant of
immunity Tuesday in her own deal with Starr, according to her
lawyer, Billy Martin. Lewis had testified before the grand jury on
Feb. 10 and 11 before leaving the courthouse in an apparent
emotional state. She has not returned since.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's lawyers, realizing some of the worst fears of the
White House in the six-month investigation, stood on the mobbed
sidewalk outside their downtown office building Tuesday afternoon
to announce the long-awaited deal. Clinton aides immediately
reacted with an outer calm that belied what some officials
privately described as inner frustration throughout the West Wing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was called and informed of the deal Tuesday morning by
his personal attorney, David Kendall. Asked about the president's
reaction, White House spokesman Michael McCurry said, ``I think
that he's pleased that things are working out for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Told by a reporter that Clinton's reaction indicated sympathy
for Lewinsky, McCurry added, ``He is a human being. I don't think
that would be a surprise to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   With the so-called transactional immunity, Lewinsky can no
longer be prosecuted for any matters in the case in which she
supplies testimony. The grant is more far-reaching than the more
common form of judicial or use immunity, in which witnesses cannot
be prosecuted based on their own testimony, but are still subject
to prosecution using outside evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transactional immunity means they agree not to prosecute you
for whatever transactions are covered by your testimony,'' said
Robert Luskin, a prominent Washington defense attorney. ``It is a
promise for non-prosecution. They are saying under no circumstances
will we prosecute you, whereas with judicial immunity they are
saying they won't use what you say to prosecute you.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal was struck Tuesday morning, just a day after Lewinsky
met with prosecutors from Starr's office in a five hour, covert
meeting in New York City to discuss the details of her possible
testimony should she be granted immunity. It serves as the single
most dramatic develepment in the case that has plagued the Clinton
adminstration since the third week of January.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, White House aides have repeatedly dismissed questions
about the Lewinsky probe by saying that both Clinton and Lewinsky,
in respective sworn statements, have denied any sexual
relationship. Lewinsky was captured on secret tape recordings
bragging to colleague Linda Tripp of a lengthy sexual affair with
Clinton, one in which, she said, they met regularly in the Oval
Office and often exchanged telephone calls and gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton supporters said that if Lewinsky only testifies to a
sexual relationship with the president, the simple perjury
allegation stemming from the dismissed Paula Jones suit will not
ignite any outrage among the congressional Republicans who would
ultimately decide his fate _ a sentiment echoed for weeks on
Capitol Hill. Still, there appeared to be a new strain of anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's serious she is preparing to testify in contradiction to
her previous testimony and in contradiction to the president,''
said Lanny Davis, Clinton's former spokesman on legal issues. ``But
I don't believe this story affects the outcome if that's all she's
got.''
</P>
<P>
   Still unclear is the status of negotations between Kendall &UR;  &LR; and
Starr over the subpoena that was issued to Clinton two weeks ago.
The two continued to negotiate over such issues as whether Clinton
would be able to testify on videotape, from the White House, in the
presence of an attorney. Normally, grand jury testimony is given at
the US District Court with no attorney present.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he will testify,'' one Clinton ally said Tuesday,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``He doesn't have any choice.
People are about to get angry at him because he is allowing this
thing to continue and is distracted from the business of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Jones deposition, Clinton said in what was reported to be
a voice so quiet and halting that his own lawyer asked him to speak
up, ``I have never had sexual relations with Monica Lewinsky. I've
never had an affair with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, in an East Room appearance in January, Clinton said
more emphatically, ``I did not have sexual relations with that
woman _ Miss Lewinsky. I never told anybody to lie.''
</P>
<P>
   There were widespread indications from White House officials
that Clinton may try to hold off on testifying until September,
after he returns from an overseas trip to Ireland and Russia that
is expected to be triumphant.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, analysts said, Starr may not dare to file a
report to the Congress on the allegations with only two months
remaining until the November midterm elections. Many senior
Republicans have privately indicated to Starr that if he cannot
send them a report by August 1, to wait until after the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have speculated that Clinton would prefer to
testify after Lewinsky, rather than before, though that point
seemed to be growing moot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has no advantage in time,'' said Jonathan
Turley, a George Washington University law professor who has filed
court briefs in support of Starr. ``If he testifies before Monica
Lewinsky, he may be called back to respond to inconsistencies
afterwards. The benefit of timing this testimony will be marginal
at best.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry declined to speculate on the timing of Clinton's
testimony, but said, ``I think he's eager to see it resolved, and I
think that, as you know, we're reager to see that Mr. Starr and Mr.
Kendall make whatever conclusion of their discussions they make.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Clinton's schedule, McCurry added, ``He's going to be a
busy guy. He's the president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
