<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATION PAYS TRIBUTE TO SLAIN OFFICERS IN TOUCHING CEREMONIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In simple, touching ceremonies beneath the grand
dome of the U.S. Capitol, President Clinton, lawmakers, police and
the public paid tribute Tuesday to the two officers killed last
week during a bloody shootout in the halls of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Both before and after the formal eulogies, thousands of mourners
filed solemnly past the flag-draped coffins of Detective John
Gibson and Officer Jacob J. Chestnut resting side-by-side at the
center of majestic Capitol Rotunda. A four-man police honor guard
stood watch over their fallen partners.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers and tourists from across the nation mingled with
politicians and Capitol Hill staff in a common show of grief and
respect. Many stood for hours in a line that began forming before
dawn.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, calling Gibson and Chestnut ``quiet men of
uncommon bravery,'' said it was fitting that the two be recognized
with a special service in the Rotunda, where 27 other Americans
have been honored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we mourn their loss and we celebrate their lives. Our
words are such poor replacements for the joys of family and
friends, the turning of seasons, the rhythms of normal life that
should rightfully be theirs,'' Clinton said to the Gibson and
Chestnut families who sat to his right and left.
</P>
<P>
   ``They loved justice. They did mercy. Now and forever, they walk
humbly with their God.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, 42, and Chestnut, 58, will be buried later this week at
Arlington National Cemetery. They were the first police officers to
lie in honor in the Rotunda, and Chestnut was the first black man
to be so honored.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday, only presidents, members of Congress, military
commanders and unknown soldiers from the major conflicts in this
century had been given such a service in the great hall separating
the House and Senate chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on behalf of the police force charged with protecting
the Capitol community, Chief Gary L. Abrecht praised the two
officers for ``selflessly'' sacrificing their lives ``so that
others might live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not have asked any more of them. They would not have
given any less for us,'' he said, as some police officers in the
packed hall wiped tears from their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``While what we say here will soon be forgotten, the memory of
the heroic actions of Officer Jacob Chestnut and Detective John
Gibson will become as timeless as the building in which they
died,'' Abrecht added.
</P>
<P>
   Before they spoke, Clinton and Abrecht joined Senate and House
leaders in placing large wreaths next to the caskets, which rested
beneath the huge Capitol dome. As they moved the flowers into
place, the mid-afternoon sun streamed through the windows overhead,
bathing the Gibson and Chestnut families for a few minutes in a
brilliant light.
</P>
<P>
   The sun also glinted off the black-taped badges of hundreds of
Capitol police officers, who squeezed into the Rotunda beside
members of the Senate and House, and Cabinet officials, including
Attorney General Janet Reno and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin.
Vice President Al Gore, Supreme Court Justice Antonin Scalia, FBI
Director Louis Freeh and former Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole
also attended the service.
</P>
<P>
   Before the eulogies, Senate and House members also participated
in a private viewing of the caskets. They stood in silence six and
eight deep around a roped perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Off to the side, House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., House
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., and House Majority Whip Tom
DeLay, R-Texas, formed a receiving line as lawmakers filed out of
the grand hall and into nearby rooms to offer condolences to the
Gibson and Chestnut families. Many paused to hug DeLay, his wife,
Christine, and daughter Danielle Ferro.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, assigned to the Capitol's protective detail, had been
DeLay's personal bodyguard. He was posted inside a doorway to
DeLay's suite of offices when the suspect in the shooting, Russell
Weston Jr., burst through after allegedly shooting Chestnut with a
.38-caliber pistol. Gibson is credited with bringing Weston down
with three shots as he took fire himself at point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
   Weston, 41, has been charged with one count of murdering a
federal police officer and could get the death penalty. More
charges are expected to be filed against him. The suspect, who has
a history of mental illness, underwent another round of surgery
Tuesday at a local hospital. He was still listed in stable
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut and Gibson were the first members of the Capitol Police
force to die while on duty protecting lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   As they filed solemnly passed the caskets, some tourists bowed
their heads in silent prayer. Police officers saluted, and some
members of Congress placed their hands over blue ribbons worn over
their hearts in memory of the slain officers.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said that it was
``only right'' that the two officers be honored under the Capitol
dome where so many ``heroes of our history'' have been eulogized.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two men have proven that they are the very best of us
because they have paid the ultimate sacrifice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The House, for the second day, remained in recess as a tribute
to Gibson and Chestnut. And though the Senate continued to debate
various bills, members still took time to praise the two officers
for their sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., also raised the possibility of shifting
$14 million in already-appropriated funds to the Capitol
architect's office to be used in beefing up security. He said it
could include construction of an underground visitors center, which
would be used to control access to the Capitol grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Rules Committee also said it may consider a
resolution this week naming the ground-floor entrance near where
the shootings occurred after the two slain police officers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
