<HEADLINE>
NHL REFEREE STEWART RECOVERING FROM CANCER SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Colorful National Hockey League referee Paul Stewart, a native
of Boston, is recovering from colon cancer surgery. Stewart
underwent an operation last month at New England Baptist Hospital
and is receiving chemotherapy halfway through 12 weeks of
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors expect Stewart, 43, to make a full recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last year has been a roller-coaster ride,'' said Stewart,
who in the past 12 months has gotten married, become the father of
a son, and is building a house. ``In the last year, I've had the
biggest thrill of my life and the biggest shock of my life. (Being
diagnosed with cancer) was a shock. It was worse than a Terry
O'Reilly punch.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who is very active in the local community, has been an
NHL referee since March 27, 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are very optimistic,'' he said. ``The doctors tell me I
am cancer-free and that I am responding well to the chemo. I have a
5-month-old and I intend to be around for his education. And I
think I still have a lot of games left in me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have spoken with Paul and he is very upbeat,'' Bryan Lewis,
the NHL's director of officiating, said in a statement. ``His
recovery is our first concern. The thoughts of all the NHL referees
and linesmen are with Paul and his family and we wish him well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 2030EDT &QL; 
