<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-CHRONO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONICA LEWINSKY: CHRONOLOGY OF A SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-TACTICS, CLINTON-LEWINSKY-CHRONO) 
(bl) c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   June 1995 _ Monica Lewinsky begins work at the White House as an
unpaid intern.
</P>
<P>
   April 17, 1996 _ Ms. Lewinsky moves to the Pentagon as a
confidential aide to an assistant secretary of defense for public
affairs and becomes friends with Linda Tripp, who had formerly
worked as secretary to White House counsel Bernard Nussbaum.
</P>
<P>
   Fall 1997 _ Ms. Tripp begins secretly taping telephone
conversations in which Ms. Lewinsky says she had an affair with
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 7, 1998 _ In an affidavit in the Paula Jones sexual
misconduct case, Ms. Lewinsky denies that she had a sexual
relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 12 _ Ms. Tripp tells prosecutors for the independent
counsel Kenneth Starr that she has a tape on which Ms. Lewinsky
says that Clinton's friend Vernon Jordan encouraged her to deny
having an affair.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 17 _ The president is questioned for six hours by lawyers
for Mrs. Jones. He is asked about Ms. Lewinsky and denies that he
had a sexual relationship with her.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 21 _ News accounts first appear of the alleged affair
between the president and Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 29 _ After inconclusive discussions between Ms. Lewinsky's
lawyer, William Ginsburg, and Starr's prosecutors, negotiations on
an immunity deal protecting Ms. Lewinsky from prosecution for
perjury appear stalled.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 10-11 _ Ms. Lewinsky's mother, Marcia Lewis, testifies for
more than six hours over two days and leaves the U.S. District
Court in Washington looking physically shaken and emotionally
distraught.
</P>
<P>
   March 5 _ Ginsburg argues before a federal district judge in
Washington that Starr's office had made, then retracted, a firm
offer of immunity for Ms. Lewinsky in return for her full
testimony. Starr denies making such a deal.
</P>
<P>
   April 1 _ A federal district court judge in Arkansas throws out
Mrs. Jones' sexual harassment civil lawsuit. Mrs. Jones' lawyers
later appeal the decision.
</P>
<P>
   April 29 _ A federal district judge rules that Ms. Lewinsky did
not have an agreement with the independent counsel that would give
her immunity from testifying.
</P>
<P>
   May 11 _ The Lewinsky family hires Judy Smith, a veteran media
relations specialist.
</P>
<P>
   May 28 _ In a Los Angeles FBI office, Ms. Lewinsky gives
handwriting, fingerprint and voice samples.
</P>
<P>
   June 2 _ Ms. Lewinsky dismisses Ginsburg and hires Jacob Stein
and Plato Cacheris. One week later the new lawyers discuss possible
immunity for Ms. Lewinsky with independent counsel prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   June 11 _ Ms. Lewinsky flies to California to spend time with
her father, signaling that no agreement is near on possible
immunity.
</P>
<P>
   July 28 _ Lawyers for Ms. Lewinsky broker an immunity deal with
Starr in which she promises ``full and truthful testimony'' in
exchange for a sweeping grant of immunity from Federal prosecutors.
Her mother, Ms. Lewis, also is given immunity.
</P>
</TEXT>
