<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves waives lineman Davis
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUWANEE, Ga. _ The Atlanta Falcons waived defensive lineman
Nathan Davis on Tuesday after he tried to make a return to
football.
</P>
<P>
   Davis showed up at camp at 8 a.m., but was told by coach Dan
Reeves that he would be cut. The 6-foot-5, 326-pound Davis, a
second-round pick in 1997, apparently walked into the locker room
and was asked by equipment manager Brian Boigner to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who could not be reached for comment, quit Friday, on the
second day of training camp, after telling Reeves, ``My heart
wasn't in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons put Davis on the ``reserve/left squad'' list, which
means he had five days to return or not be eligible to play this
fall. Had he not returned, he would have owed the Falcons
two-thirds of the $662,000 signing bonus that was included in his
three-year, $1.74 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Teams rarely pursue the return of signing bonuses in such
situations, but Reeves said he thinks that it was Davis' motivation
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he felt like he made a hasty decision,'' Reeves said.
``In my opinion, it wasn't because he wanted to play football. I
think it was strictly ... knowing he had an obligation to live up
to when he signed the contract, and, if he didn't (live up to
them), basically he had to give the money back.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis will be on waivers for 24 hours. If no other team claims
him, he will count $245,700 against the Falcons' salary cap this
year _ the $220,700 pro-rated portion of his signing bonus, plus a
$25,000 offseason workout bonus he earned. The final $220,700 will
count next year. If he is claimed, all of his remaining signing
bonus and the workout bonus _ a total of $466,400 _ will count
against this year's cap.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' agent, Nate Lampley, said Davis made one mistake after
another, including rejecting the Falcons' request last winter to
attend the weight-loss clinic at Duke University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does he have the talent to play at a high level in the NFL? Of
course,'' Lampley said. ``There's a lot of guys out there with
`potential' on their tombstones.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
