<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-BOXING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boxer aims for the fearless
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ebo Elder used to hear the roar of an engine when he
was a top young supercross rider. Now the 139-pound boxer hears
only the roar of a crowd, but his detour onto dirt tracks helps him
get his motor running in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to not fear anything to race motorcycles
competitively,'' said Elder, 19, of Newnan, Ga. ``If you can fly
through the air 60 mph on a dirtbike, you can go against another
human competitor easily.''
</P>
<P>
   The light welterweight was scheduled to meet Canada's Michael
Strange in a Goodwill Games quarterfinal bout late Tuesday night at
the Theater at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Elder started racing motorcycles when he was 10, attained a No.
5 ranking in supercross, and quit when he was 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing has always been a serious thing; motocross was more of
a fun thing for a young guy to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was also more dangerous, which contributed to his decision to
leave the sport.
</P>
<P>
   He retired uninjured, but with a new name. His given name is
Eben, which announcers couldn't say right.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad just came up with Ebo spur of the moment around when Bo
Jackson was so big,'' Elder said. ``It's kind of catchy; people
remember it once they get it in their head.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Elder also gave his son a love for boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had this dream of being the best boxer in the world since
I was 3 years old,'' said Elder, who trains at Biggs Morrison
Boxing in Atlanta. ``My dad, before I was born, prayed to have a
son he could teach boxing to and take what he had done further.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, who is still his coach, won the Southeastern
Championships. ``He was the toughest guy in town,'' Elder said of
his father. Elder fights left-handed, but plays ping-pong and bowls
with his right. Being quasi-ambidextrous, Elder said, helps because
his jabs and hooks are more powerful. While he trains for Sydney,
he's working full-time for his father's construction company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a tough road is better than having it easy,'' Elder
said. ``Working a 9- or 10-hour day, going to the gym, getting home
late and getting up early _ if you can do that, you can win a
five-round fight any day.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
