<SLUG> BC-NFL-MEETING29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cleveland franchise may cost $1 billion
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The NFL on Tuesday all but assured a record price tag
for a professional sports franchise in fine-tuning the process for
selecting the owner of the resurrected Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Several owners said the franchise fee might approach $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do the math,'' Dallas owner Jerry Jones said. ``With the
kind of revenues that team is going to generate, I'm not ruling
anything out.''
</P>
<P>
   San Diego owner Alex Spanos said: ``I still think ($1 billion)
is fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue announced after the four-hour
meeting that candidates will make presentations at a league meeting
Aug. 19. ``We will focus on quality and character and planning at
that meeting,'' Tagliabue said.
</P>
<P>
   Six groups have announced their intentions to seek the team _
Larry and Charles Dolman, Richard Jacobs, Bart Wolstein, Howard
Milstein, Al Lerner and Thomas Murdough. The commissioner also said
that some interested parties prefer to remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Grubman, a managing director for Goldman Sachs, the
investment-brokerage group handling the bid, said his firm is
recruiting potential owners.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the bid process were not divulged, but Tagliabue said
it will be ``in phases.'' The list of candidates will be narrowed
in August, and Tagliabue said the league is on schedule to select
an owner in September.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing red
</P>
<P>
   Red McCombs, a billionaire businessman from San Antonio, was
unanimously approved here Tuesday as the new owner of the Minnesota
Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his promises to keep the team in place, the outspoken
McCombs did not rule out the possibility that the franchise might
someday relocate if it is not supported to his satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Following a quick vote, McCombs met the media and stressed
several times the need to sell out the Metrodome regularly.
``That's the only way you get the home-court advantage,'' said
McCombs, former owner of the NBA's Denver Nuggets and San Antonio
Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   McCombs has championed San Antonio's efforts to land an NFL
team. Asked if that might factor into his future plans for the
Vikings, he issued a poorly veiled threat to Minnesota fans. ``They
should be concerned about that,'' he said. ``I don't expect that
issue to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocking stuffers
</P>
<P>
   The owners approved a plan for stocking the roster of the new
Browns, and it's similar to the one used for Carolina and
Jacksonville. The club will have the initial selection in the 1999
draft, but unlike the Jaguars and Panthers, the Browns will not
have multiple choices in the first round. The club will be allowed
a total of 28 picks in the 1999 and 2000 drafts, but Cleveland will
forfeit its additional choices the second year if it makes the
playoffs in its inaugural season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
