<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC NOTEBOOK: Gamecocks' QB cleared for camp
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM _ South Carolina quarterback Anthony Wright, just
nine months removed from a potentially career-ending knee injury,
has been cleared to participate in next month's preseason camp.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, a 6-foot-2, 192-pound senior from Vanceboro, N.C., tore
two ligaments in his right knee, as well as the hamstring in the
leg, in the Gamecocks' 22-7 loss at Tennessee Nov. 1. Wright
suffered the injury while being tackled by Vols middle linebacker
Al Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm probably 90 to 95 percent,'' Wright said on the
opening day of the SEC Football Media Days. ``One thing I'm lacking
is strength. I can cut on it and I can run on it, but it's just not
as strong as the other leg.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Wright and promising backup Phil Petty have been
ruled off-limits for contact by South Carolina coach Brad Scott. In
fact, Scott says Wright won't be hit until the Gamecocks'
season-opener against Ball State in Columbia Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about his condition at this point,'' Scott said.
``At the time of his injury, I think it was the opinion of the
medical people that he'd never play football again. But I expect
him to be back at 100 percent when camp opens in August.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright threw for 1,685 yards and 18 touchdowns with only five
interceptions in nine games last season before the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Mealey Ailing
</P>
<P>
   Departed LSU star Cecil ``The Diesel'' Collins isn't the only
tailback that had Tigers coach Gerry DiNardo on edge this summer.
</P>
<P>
   While Collins was dismissed from the team following his arrest
earlier this month, junior Rondell Mealey, second on the team last
season with 664 rushing yards, underwent surgery on his right foot
after spring practice. Mealey had a pin removed from the foot last
week and has started running again. ``Hopefully, he'll be ready for
the first game, Sept. 12 against Arkansas State,'' DiNardo said.
</P>
<P>
   OId Friends
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State running back James Johnson, one of the
league's most underrated players after finishing fourth last season
with 1,069 rushing yards and 12 touchdowns, says he believes
Tennessee won't lose much with new quarterback Tee Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson should know. The pair were boyhood friends, living just
five houses apart in Mobile, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always telling me he wanted to play quarterback,''
Johnson said. ``I told him that he needed to be a running back. I'm
glad he didn't listen to me.
</P>
<P>
   First Commitment
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln County High defensive end Shedrick Wynn became Georgia's
first commitment after picking the Bulldogs over Louisville, South
Carolina, Clemson, Tennessee and Georgia Tech. Wynn, the cousin of
former Bulldogs RB Garrison Hearst, had 76 tackles and 11 sacks for
Lincoln County as a junior.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
