<SLUG> BC-TYSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nevada dismayed by Tyson's hearing
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ The head of Nevada boxing expressed
disappointment in the decision by New Jersey athletic officials to
hold a licensing hearing today for deposed heavyweight Mike Tyson.
Nevada is the state that revoked Tyson's boxing license for at
least one year last July after the former champion twice bit
Evander Holyfield in their title fight in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Ratner, executive director of the Nevada Athletic
Commission, said he does not want to ``prejudge'' New Jersey
officials until after they reach their decision whether to license
Tyson. But Ratner added, ``I never thought another state would even
go this far (and have a hearing). I thought all states would honor
our disciplinary action.''
</P>
<P>
   The recently passed Professional Boxing Safety Act asks states
to abide by each other's medical suspensions, but the act is not
binding. It also does not refer to suspensions or license
revocations for non-medical reasons, such as Tyson's. ``Legally,
the state of New Jersey is completely in the right (to consider
licensing Tyson),'' Ratner said. ``But whether they're operating
within the spirit of the law is another matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is expected to regain the license, and he might fight
before the end of the year, pending the resolution of contractual
problems with promoter Don King, whom he is suing for $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The boxer will appear with his attorneys and advisers before New
Jersey commissioner Larry Hazzard and three board members. Tyson is
expected to make a statement and answer questions from officials,
who have 45 days to render a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Commission spokeswoman Rhonda Utley Herring said Tyson's
``character, honesty, integrity and responsibility'' will be
considered. Herring reiterated that New Jersey was not legally
bound by Tyson's situation in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Finkel, one of Tyson's new advisers, was quoted last week
as saying he thought Tyson would not regain his license in Nevada.
On Tuesday, Finkel claimed he was misquoted, saying, ``I believe
Nevada would've licensed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Why apply in New Jersey?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's changed a lot of things,'' Finkel said. ``He's gotten rid
of his promoter and his managers. He wants a new start in a
different state.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly ...
</P>
<P>
   Tyson has agreed to play himself in the film ``Black and
White,'' the New York Daily News reported. Set in New York, the
script involves white prep school students who have a ``reckless
infatuation with black hip-hop life,'' director James Toback said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
