<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-ELECT-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONGMAN'S PARTY CLAIMS VICTORY IN CAMBODIAN VOTE
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ Post-election battle lines began forming
in Cambodia on Tuesday with the dominant party of the incumbent
strongman, Hun Sen, claiming victory and his two opposition rivals
crying fraud and threatening to block the formation of a new
government.
</P>
<P>
   With only a tiny fraction of the vote count released, the
country appeared to be entering a tense and possibly chaotic period
of protests and maneuvering by all sides, including the two main
opposition candidates, Prince Norodom Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy.
</P>
<P>
   International observers, who said they visited about 20 percent
of polling places, declared that the voting on Sunday and the
counting on Monday appeared to have been largely acceptable. But
critics, including some foreign diplomats, charged that the
monitoring was belated and thin and that the count remained open to
manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   Most projections on Tuesday indicated that Hun Sen had won the
vote, Cambodia's first parliamentary election in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Such a victory would crown a single-minded effort by Hun Sen,
including a coup a year ago that ousted Ranariddh, then his
co-premier, and a later campaign of intimidation in which more than
100 political opponents were killed, according to U.N. officials.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hun Sen claimed victory, even by his party's own
estimate, he had not won enough votes to take power without forming
a coalition with either the prince or Sam Rainsy.
</P>
<P>
   The two opposition leaders, normally political enemies, joined
forces on Tuesday to protest the claim of Hun Sen's party, the
Cambodian People's Party, to have won from 65 to 67 of the 122
seats in Parliament, based on the party's own estimate. The party
projected that the prince's royalist party would win 42 to 45 seats
and that Sam Rainsy's party would win 13 seats, not enough to allow
them to form a coalition of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The party's projection suggested a more powerful victory for Hun
Sen than that of an independent poll-watch group, called the
Committee for Free and Fair elections.
</P>
<P>
   The prince and Sam Rainsy said they would boycott the new
assembly, which would make it impossible for Hun Sen to form a
coalition and reach the two-thirds majority of 81 votes that is
needed to create a new government.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stole our vote, and we will disagree with whatever their
result,'' Sam Rainsy said. ``We are going to protest in all legal
and peaceful ways against this unfair election. So we lodge
complaints, we will write petitions, and, why not, organize all
kinds of protest.''
</P>
<P>
   If a government cannot be formed, an official of the ruling
party said on Tuesday that Hun Sen would continue in his current
role as leader. Official preliminary results are not expected until
Saturday and the final official results will only be announced at
the end of next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any declaration of victory is premature,'' said Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, who is in the Philippines for a regional
conference. ``The only people who deserve congratulations are the
people who voted.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Solarz, who heads an American observer delegation here,
said the allegations of fraud were premature, and he went so far as
to suggest that the election might become known as ``the miracle on
the Mekong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They do not have the right to expect that their allegations
will be accepted in the absence of credible evidence indicating
that they are true,'' he told a news conference. ``At the moment we
are not convinced that the concerns they have expressed justify the
conclusions they have reached.''
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, the two opposition leaders complained of
``missing ballots, polling station workers marking ballots for
voters, purposeful miscounting of ballots, threats to observers,
insufficient party agents and observers allowed to watch the
counting, improper moving of ballots at night and unexplained
delays in reporting results.''
</P>
<P>
   The Committee for Free and Fair Elections countered with a
statement saying, ``Problems and irregularities were mainly
isolated and did not represent a prevailing trend.'' The group's
director, Thun Saray, said, ``They can't reject the result just
because they lose. I worry, but perhaps they are just saying this
now and will accept later.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The main observer mission, called the Joint International
Observer Group, which is a U.N. umbrella organization that has
coordinated almost 500 monitors here from more than 20 nations,
offered an upbeat assessment early on Tuesday. That judgment was
criticized by a number of diplomats as being premature and
incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the impression of the JIOG that what could be observed
by us on polling day and counting day was a process which was free
and fair to an extent that enabled it to reflect in a credible way
the will of the Cambodian people,'' the group said. ``In the end,
efforts to intimidate sections of the Cambodian population appear
not to have significantly influenced the climate of polling day
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of this assessment said it discounted the weeks and
months of intimidation that had preceded the vote, the
near-monopoly of the ruling party of radio and television and the
oppressive influence on voters of the ruling party's control of
Cambodia's military, police and government administration.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the critics questioned the effectiveness of the
observer process itself. The 500 international observers, working
in teams of two, could visit only a small fraction of the 11,699
voting precincts and could be effective only when they were
actively watching the count, these critics said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the voting and counting procedures generally appeared
to be open and fair and the ballot boxes to be secure and well
guarded, there were also many opportunities for fraud. Visits to a
dozen counting stations on Monday found instances of incorrect
votes being read out and valid votes for opposition parties being
set aside as incorrectly marked. Armed men were observed outside
one polling station in violation of election rules.
</P>
<P>
   The ballot boxes, with multiple locks and seals, were mostly
held overnight from Sunday to Monday in well-guarded, well-lit
municipal buildings. But some international observers interviewed
on Monday said they had not actually spent the night with the
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   More worrisome to critics was the nationwide vote count that is
now being tabulated at the Phnom Penh headquarters of the National
Election Commission. Like other government agencies, it is
dominated by members of Hun Sen's party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
