u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDERMOTT-BOEHNER-SPI     07-28 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDERMOTT-BOEHNER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE THROWS OUT SUIT AGAINST MCDERMOTT IN TAPE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With harsh words for both sides, a federal judge
Tuesday dismissed a lawsuit against Rep. Jim McDermott, saying
McDermott's alleged role in leaking an illegally recorded phone
conversation among Republican leaders was protected by the First
Amendment to the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott, who has declined to say what part he played in
providing tapes of the call to newspapers, remains under
investigation by the Justice Department in the incident.
</P>
<P>
   In dismissing the lawsuit, U.S. District Judge Thomas Hogan was
particularly critical of McDermott. He said the Seattle Democrat's
alleged actions, although legal, were troubling, and that his
successful legal arguments undermine the nation's anti-wiretapping
laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unfortunate that a United States representative, who had
chosen a position that supposedly illuminated him as a beacon of
ethical behavior, should so eagerly seek to capitalize on the
skullduggery of would-be party operatives to win petty, partisan
victories in the press,'' Hogan wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan, who was appointed to the federal bench in 1982 by
President Reagan, was clearly impatient with both sides in the
case, which was brought against McDermott by House Republican
Conference Chairman John Boehner, R-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case arises out of the unfortunate acrimony, absence of
civility and shortage of honor that pervades the partisan sniping
between some members of Congress and their supporters,'' Hogan
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The case stems from a Dec. 21, 1996, conference call between
Boehner, House Speaker Newt Gingrich, and other Republican leaders
discussing how to respond to an ethics committee ruling against
Gingrich. Boehner, who was vacationing in Florida at the time,
participated in the conversation from a cellular telephone. The
call was intercepted on a police scanner and taped by a Florida
couple active in Democratic politics.
</P>
<P>
   The couple eventually provided the tape to McDermott, who was
then the ranking Democrat on the House ethics committee. Two days
later a story relying on the tape appeared on the front page of The
New York Times. The newspaper said it had obtained the tape from a
Democrat hostile to Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida couple, Alice and John Martin, pleaded guilty to
unlawful interception of Boehner's phone call, and each was fined
$500.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott declined requests for an interview Tuesday, and his
attorneys could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Boehner said he was disappointed, and would consider an filing
an appeal of the legal case or a complaint against McDermott to the
House ethics committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Mr. McDermott acted unethically in this case is no longer
in doubt,'' Boehner said. ``We will continue to pursue justice in
this case, and we will insist that Mr. McDermott be held fully
accountable for his reprehensible, cynical and unethical actions.''
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Hogan held that McDermott's free speech rights,
protected by the Constitution, outweigh Boehner's right to privacy,
protected by the Electronic Communications Privacy Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First Amendment prevents the government from punishing the
disclosure of truthful, lawfully obtained information of public
significance,'' Hogan ruled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First Amendment is largely blind to motives ... and it
offers protection not only to the noble, but also to the ignoble,''
Hogan wrote. ``Thus, Rep. McDermott's actions are protected under
the Amendment, and the court must grant his motion to dismiss.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan noted that the Electronic Communications Privacy Act makes
it illegal to disclose the contents of an illegally tape recorded
telephone call, but not to be the recipient of such a disclosure.
He ruled that once McDermott had legally obtained the tape
recording, his alleged disclosure of the tape was an act of free
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan was clearly uncomfortable with his own conclusions, saying
that the effect of First Amendment protections on cellular
telephone privacy laws are ``illogical,'' and saying that
McDermott's successful legal arguments ``lay siege to the
protections against illicit wiretapping.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(McDermott's) theory is a slippery one, as it not only
defends, but even encourages, the circumnavigation of wiretap
statutes, which are designed to prevent the disclosure of private
conversations,'' Hogan wrote. ``Under (McDermott's) theory, the
state has no means to prevent disclosure of private information,
because criminals like the Martins can literally launder illegally
intercepted information.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan went on to say that the sentence imposed on the Martins
was ``almost laughable'' and that because of the ``loophole''
exploited by McDermott ``the effect of the (Electronic
Communications Privacy) statute is diluted into nothingness.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hogan had only minimal sympathy for Boehner's plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The circumstances of the present case suggest that the
government interest in protecting the privacy of this particular
plaintiff (Boehner), in this particular situation, is diminished,''
Hogan said. ``(Boehner) seeks less to strike a blow for his
personal privacy rights than he does to fire a salvo in the
partisan battle between rival groups in the House of
Representatives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
