<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7073 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-NYT &LR;      07-28 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LEWINSKY, PRESSURES MAY BE ALMOST OVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-TACTICS, CLINTON-LEWINSKY-CHRONO,
CLINTON-LEWINSKY-IMMUNITY) 
(bl) 
 By TIM WEINER   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The agreement struck Tuesday between former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky and Kenneth Starr begins to resolve an
ordeal that thrust Ms. Lewinsky into the crucible of celebrity and
``made her a lot tougher,'' according to a friend.
</P>
<P>
   The friend, who dined with Ms. Lewinsky a few days ago and asked
that his name not be disclosed ``because I don't want to be
subpoenaed by Ken Starr,'' added:
</P>
<P>
   ``From knowing her and talking to her, I know she has handled
all this with with a shocking amount of grace and dignity, a lot of
humor _ and a great deal of pain.'' That pain made her stronger, he
said, and more determined to put an end to the uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   And it appears to have shifted her legal stance. After months of
stalemate with Starr, she dismissed her lawyer, William Ginsburg,
whose experience was in malpractice law, not high-stakes political
chess. She retained two criminal defense lawyers well-versed in
Washington's ways and received the services of a skilled publicist.
</P>
<P>
   Several people close to Ms. Lewinsky said Tuesday that her new
lawyers, Plato Cacheris and Jacob Stein, broke the impasse by
seeing eye-to-eye and talking man-to-man with Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday also saw resolution for Marcia Lewis, Ms. Lewinsky's
mother, who suffered a severe anxiety attack when called before the
grand jury to testify about her daughter in February. She also
received immunity Tuesday, presumably in exchange for testimony
about what her daughter told her about her relationship with
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky is now free from the threat of prison, if she
testifies truthfully about that relationship. Whether she will ever
be free of the experience of being transformed into a hunted animal
and a hot property is another question.
</P>
<P>
   She was betrayed by a confidante, Linda Tripp, who took tapes of
her intimate conversations to Starr. ``The betrayal of Linda Tripp
_ that was devastating,'' the friend of Ms. Lewinsky said. ``To be
betrayed by a friend, that was a tremendous hurt, and a tremendous
lesson. Now, the hardest part is that she has to go on with her
life.''
</P>
<P>
   She was stalked by the million-footed beast of the broadcast
media in her beauty salon. She was advised by Ginsburg to pose for
Vanity Fair, and consented, coyly clutching a fan-dancer's plumage
of fuchsia feathers to her breast.
</P>
<P>
   Her e-mail messages and telephone conversations have been
presented in the press as circumstantial evidence that Ms. Lewinsky
had some form of sexual relationship with Clinton, something she
and the president have denied under oath.
</P>
<P>
   She was threatened by prosecutors with spending the best years
of her life in a jail cell unless she testified again, under oath,
about her connection to the president. And she has agonized,
according to members of her family and friends, about spending the
rest of her life as the punchline to an unending off-color joke.
</P>
<P>
   The media have seized the story of her life. Presumably, she
would like her life back. The price is her testimony. ``She is
finally going to tell her story,'' said another family friend.
``She has always wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   As yet another family friend put it: ``She does not want to be a
joke. She does not want to be a punchline. My hope is she can get
on with her life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
