<HEADER>
A7080 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALCONS-ROOKIES-COX     07-28 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-ROOKIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons rookies realizing there's plenty to learn
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons' rookies see bigger and faster players
when they stare across the line in Suwanee this week. They expected
that. What's surprising is how the pro game is so much more mental
and technical.
</P>
<P>
   A few of them, including linebacker Keith Brooking, receiver
Jammi German and right tackle Ephraim Salaam, are learning faster
than the other draft picks and free agents. But even they struggle.
Sometimes badly.
</P>
<P>
   Brooking lined up with the first team during a goal-line defense
drill, and Salaam and Bob Hallen were working in backup roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's faster than college,'' said Salaam, a seventh-round draft
choice from San Diego State. He was talking about both team speed
and the learning curve. ``The faster you can assimilate
information, the better off you are,'' the 6-foot-7, 300-pound
Salaam said. ``We put in five or six new plays every night. We
can't go on instinct yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snap counts and other stuff _ that's all running through your
head. The more time you spend studying, the better you'll be. I
study from about 10 to 11:30 (p.m.), after meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, that's not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys hold 10 times more than in college,'' Brooking said.
``When the refs were here, I was asking, `Is this a hold?' and `Is
that a hold?', and they were pretty much telling me they weren't
going to call it in games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are kind of running together. Man, they're throwing a
lot at us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons expect their class of nine draft choices and nine
undrafted free agents to contribute. They just don't know how much.
</P>
<P>
   Salaam, Brooking and Hallen, who is working at guard and center,
appear to have the inside track on getting playing time. German, a
third-round pick, and punt returner/receiver Tim Dwight, a
fourth-round pick, may also make the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Brooking) is working through a lot, but a guy that works that
hard is going to improve,'' coach Dan Reeves said. ``Jammi is a
natural; he does things you don't teach, as far as making
adjustments and feeling where people are.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've probably put Tim in too many places (receiver, punt
returner, kick returner), but you can see the explosion. He really
uses his hands well, and he's a bigger target than he looks (5-8,
182), because he extends. Ephraim is very smart, has good foot
quickness and recovers extremely well.''
</P>
<P>
   Each rookie spends extra time on certain things, some off the
field. Salaam eats; coaches want him to add 10-15 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   German is learning to get free at the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to work on shaking off the line, because they play a
lot of press coverage in the NFL,'' he said. ``If you get too
caught up thinking about getting off the line, you forget the
play.''
</P>
<P>
   The other draft choices, fourth-round safety Omar Brown,
sixth-round cornerback Elijah Williams, seventh-round running back
Ken Oxendine and seventh-round defensive tackle Henry Slay have
more ground to make up.
</P>
<P>
   A few undrafted college players are making impressions,
including 6-6, 320-pound right tackle Jose Portilla of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jose is a big guy that moves a lot better than his size,''
Reeves said. ``But third(-string) guys work mostly against other
third-group guys. A lot will depend on how they look against better
players.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
