u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWERBALL-LOTTERY-HNS     07-28 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERBALL-LOTTERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWERBALL FEVER SWEEPS TEXAS AS LOTTERY PLAYERS DRIVE TO LOUISIANA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (see optional trims) 
 
By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOOMEY, La. _ Texans sweltering in the Louisiana border heat for
a chance at a $250 million lottery are asking themselves, ``Didn't
we just have a world-record Powerball jackpot?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, of course, is yes.
</P>
<P>
   It all comes down to math, said Doug Orr, of the Multistate
Lottery Association, which runs Powerball games in 20 states and
the District of Columbia. ``People told us they wanted bigger
jackpots, so in November, we changed the number matrix.''
</P>
<P>
   The result has been fewer but bigger jackpot winners, and much
more lotto frenzy. In Connecticut, New Yorkers are standing in line
for nine hours to buy chances at the $250 million, Orr said.
</P>
<P>
   The prize _ enough to buy, say the Minnesota Vikings football
team, or five houses as costly as computer billionaire Bill Gates'
new abode, or maybe a different $250,000 limo or sports car every
day for almost three years _ is enough to lure plenty of Texans to
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Trucker Dave Loupo drove a jet fuel truck all day Monday, but
decided he could put in a couple of hundred more miles from his
Houston home to pick up tickets for himself, his boss and some
friends. ``All day long I just kept thinking, that's a quarter of a
billion dollars!'' he said. ``That is just a powerful lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I won,'' he said, ``neither I nor anybody in my whole
family _ both sides _ would ever want for anything again. And a lot
of people in Houston would never want for anything again.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Louisiana Lottery Association reported that
1,800 Powerball tickets were being sold in the state every minute.
</P>
<P>
   A peek at Powerball outlets near the Texas border showed why.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had people sleeping in the parking lot last night so they
could be first in line,'' said the manager of Tobacco Plus, in the
tiny town of Toomey, four miles inside the Louisiana state line on
Interstate 10. By early afternoon Tuesday, a line snaked out of the
little convenience store and gas station, went down the side of the
store and out into the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all those in lines at outlets near the state line were
from Texas, but not all.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Bureau drove a couple of hundred miles from the Baton
Rouge area after hearing about the big crowds near the state line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought some tickets last Friday over near home and there
wasn't any lines,'' he said. ``I thought it would be luckier to
come over here. There's more luck where there's more people buying
tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Butler, who traveled from Houston with her twin, Jan
Fontenot, said she's sure her luck will be good. ``I had a dream
about a green alligator,'' she said. ``That must mean luck.''
</P>
<P>
   It will take phenomenal luck to win the big prize. Statisticians
say the 1 in 80 million chance of picking the correct six numbers
to win is about as easy as guessing President Bill Clinton's
personal telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   According to ``The Book of Risks'' by Larry Laudan, a former
philosophy professor at the University of Hawaii, a person is 40
times as likely to get killed falling out of bed or being killed by
an animal, and a thousand times as likely to die of complications
from surgery as they are to win the Powerball.
</P>
<P>
   The odds against winning the Powerball are more than five times
as steep as winning the Texas lottery jackpot _ which is a mere $4
million Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, $4 million isn't something to sniff at. That would buy 33
new Porsche 911 turbos and plenty of gas to drive to Louisiana to
buy Powerball tickets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The odds of winning the big Texas jackpot, which has been as
high as $77.1 million, are only 15.8 million to 1.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Powerball so much harder to win _ and thus
provides the big jackpots _ is the special sixth number that gives
the game its name.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, lottery players pick six numbers from 1 to 50. The
numbers can come in any order.
</P>
<P>
   In the Powerball, players pick five numbers from 1 to 49. They
then pick a special powerball number from 1 to 42. The number drawn
for the powerball can also appear as one of the regular five
numbers, but one of the regular five numbers on a player's ticket
cannot be used for the powerball number.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Overall, there's a 1 in 35 chance that a $1 Powerball ticket
will win at least something. A correct powerball wins $3. Five
correct regular numbers without the powerball wins $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Half of the money players put into the Powerball is used in
prizes. Another 30 percent goes to the state of Louisiana and the
rest goes to pay for running the game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Powerball officials aren't yet predicting how big the jackpot
could be Saturday if nobody chooses the numbers drawn at Powerball
headquarters in West Des Moines, Iowa, at 9:59 p.m., CDT,
Wednesday. It would probably reach $350 million to $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   There is only a 15 percent chance of the jackpot not being won
Wednesday night, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Texas, the Powerball jackpot can be paid out over 25 years.
Most Texans who crossed into Louisiana on Tuesday were buying the
cash option, however, which instantly pays about half of the
jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   For the cash option, after taxes, that would mean a check for
almost $84 million. That's not the advertised $250 million, but it
is enough to buy a new Harley Davidson Electra Glide Ultra Classic
motorcycle for yourself and for almost 4,000 close friends.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Toomey's Abear's Grocery (phonetically spelled for Texans who
couldn't properly pronounce Hebert), a Powerball player who called
himself simply ``R.K.'' (``in case I win``) was philosophical about
his chances. Last week he bought 50 tickets and won $103. Tuesday
he was planning to put all of his winnings and $15 more into a
chance at the big prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it's all a dream,'' he said, as he stood near the end of
a two-hour line. ``It's as American as apple pie. It's a chance to
just sit on the porch in a rocking chair. Well, two or three
porches.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Powerball outlets are allowed to sell the tickets from
5 a.m. to midnight every day of the week. The lines, retailers
report, will only get longer before sales on the $250 million
drawing stop at 9 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Texans who don't want to face the long lines in Louisiana do
have an alternative, though. New Mexico sells Powerball tickets as
well, and it's only 645 miles from Houston to Carlsbad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
