<HEADER>
A7088 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRICE-MARKETPLACE-ART     07-28 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRICE-MARKETPLACE-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: HIS FUNDS STRUGGLING, PRICE DEPARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ever since Michael Price sold the management company
of the Mutual Series funds to the Franklin Templeton Group for a
small fortune two years ago, the funds have labored under a cloud
of uncertainty. Shareholders have nervously awaited the day Price
would give up stock-picking and fly off to his vacation home in
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   That cloud has darkened considerably over the last year, as
Price stepped away from full-time involvement in the funds,
splitting his portfolio management duties among a team of seven
analysts. Under that diffuse management structure, the largest
Mutual Series portfolios turned in relatively poor performances,
dropping to the bottom ranks of groups of similar funds and leading
disappointed investors to begin withdrawing their money.
</P>
<P>
   Price cleared the air Tuesday, announcing that he would step
down as chief executive of the group, effective Nov. 1, taking
advantage of an option outlined in his contract that allowed him to
depart on the second anniversary of the company's sale.
</P>
<P>
   In his place, he split his executive and portfolio management
roles at the fund group between two longtime aides: Robert
Friedman, who was named chief investment officer, and Peter
Langerman, currently chief operating officer, who will take over as
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Their first order of business, Friedman said Tuesday, would be
``to address the causes of the recent underperformance.''
</P>
<P>
   Certain things will not change at the funds, which will continue
to follow a value investing style, seeking out beaten-down stocks
that have been all but abandoned on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   With Price remaining as chairman of the fund management company,
Franklin Mutual Advisers, and of the funds themselves, the funds
also will continue to have access to a hard-nosed manager who made
a practice of squeezing corporate executives to improve their
performance or put their companies up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   But the reins are likely to be tightened on certain aspects of
the fund company's collegial team approach, which has been
emphasized in advertisements and marketing material in the two
years since the acquisition by Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months, Price said, the company will give
certain managers more authority over individual funds, rather than
continue a wholesale team approach.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, said Friedman, the funds, several of which have
become indistinguishable in objective and portfolio holdings over
the years, will become more focused, and investment ideas will be
screened more carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``There definitely have been stocks put into our portfolios over
the past year that will not be allowed to go into the portfolio in
the ensuing years,'' said Friedman. ``There have been too many
names in the portfolios. Now we will say if you want to put that
one in, let's take out something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Price said his departure was not prompted by the funds' recent
underperformance. ``There just comes a time when you go,'' he said.
``The guys who I've brought into the business are champing at the
bit to run it. I don't think it makes sense to sit there when over
the last year or two they are doing more and more.''
</P>
<P>
   And while he acknowledged that recent performance has lagged, he
said that his style has always underperformed in bull markets. In
the two years ended June 30, the three largest Mutual Series funds
ranked in the bottom quarter of their peer group of funds that
invest for growth and income, according to Lipper Analytical
Services.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the recent downturn has left at risk even Price's long-term
record, built up in the 23 years since he joined the firm and was
taken under the wing of Max Heine, one of Wall Street's best-known
proponents of the value style of investing.
</P>
<P>
   According to Morningstar Inc.'s measures of performance through
June 30, the Mutual Shares fund, the largest of Price's funds, with
$10.8 billion in assets, trailed the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index in
every time period from one month to 15 years. Similar results have
ensued for the Mutual Qualified fund, with $6.7 billion in assets,
and the Mutual Beacon fund, with $7.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Price and his funds have taken some hard knocks in recent
months. Sunbeam Corp., in which Price invested in 1990 while the
company was mired in bankruptcy, suffered an embarrassing downturn
in earnings, followed by the very public firing of its much-touted
chief executive, Al Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   The Mutual Series funds also recently took a big stake in shares
of Oxford Health Plans, whose troubles earning profits on its
managed care business have caused the stock to continue to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there have been big winners in recent years, most
notably Chase Manhattan, which under pressure from Price merged
with Chemical Bank in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That is what attracted the attention of Franklin two years ago.
Best known for its bond funds and its international portfolios,
Franklin lacked a stable of strong domestic equity funds.
</P>
<P>
   Just how sought-after it considered Price was demonstrated in
the $550 million in cash and $70 million in stock that it offered
for Price's firm, Heine Securities. In addition, Price had the
ability to earn incentive payments of up to $192 million if his
company met certain revenue targets. Earlier this year, Franklin
said that Price had already earned $64 million of that amount.
</P>
<P>
   After the sale, cash flooded into the funds, as Franklin began
introducing them to the thousands of brokers at Wall Street's major
brokerage firms who sell the other Franklin Templeton funds. Before
the sale, the Mutual Series funds had been sold directly to
investors, without a sales charge.
</P>
<P>
   But after adding $3.8 billion in net new investments to its six
funds last year, several of the funds more recently have begun to
experience withdrawals, according to AMG Data Services, which
tracks fund flows. Mutual Beacon lost $194 million to withdrawals
over the last five months, while Mutual Qualified saw $71 million
flow out over three months and Mutual Shares lost $3 million in
June.
</P>
<P>
   While declining to comment on specific figures, Price said,
``The outflows have not been significant.'' And, he added,
investors should remain patient. ``I don't view these things in
short time periods. Over the long term, our funds will compound
investors' money in the mid-teens, like they've always done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7090 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-STRIKE-ART-NYT &LR;      07-28 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM, UAW REACH AGREEMENT TO END 8-WEEK STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(th) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ General Motors and the United Automobile Workers
union agreed Tuesday to end a nearly eight-week strike at two auto
parts factories here that has shut down GM assembly plants across
North America, pushed hundreds of thousands of workers into
temporary unemployment and slowed economic growth across the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's settlement, which is subject to ratification votes on
Wednesday morning by workers at both factories, settles a wide
range of local issues at the two factories and at several other GM
factories where workers had threatened strikes.
</P>
<P>
   But the pact did not directly address national issues like GM's
push to open new factories overseas or its effort to shrink its
work force in the United States through attrition.
</P>
<P>
   The pact includes a promise by both sides' leaders to hold
regularly scheduled meetings, as a way to rebuild their
relationship and head off further confrontations. But company and
union officials already meet periodically, and have been unable to
bridge disagreements that produce several factory-level strikes
almost every year.
</P>
<P>
   GM promised not to sell or close before January, 2000, either a
struck speedometer and spark plug factory here or a pair of brake
factories in Dayton, Ohio, where workers have also threatened a
strike this summer.
</P>
<P>
   GM also agreed to invest $180 million in new equipment at the
other struck factory here, which makes auto body parts, in exchange
for work rule changes, notably a 15 percent increase in the number
of parts that some workers are required to make before stopping
work.
</P>
<P>
   The broad outlines of Tuesday's settlement, which was reached at
3:05 p.m. and announced at 4:30, began to emerge in the first week
of talks. The strike lasted as long as it did partly because of the
two sides' mutual mistrust and partly because GM raised the stakes
by suing the UAW for the first time since 1937, contending that the
strikes here violated the company's national agreement, which runs
until September, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   GM withdrew its lawsuit Tuesday, along with a grievance in which
an arbitrator had been expected to rule as soon as Wednesday. While
UAW leaders insisted at a press conference late Tuesday afternoon
that they had not been intimidated by GM's legal offensive, a UAW
official who insisted on anonymity said that the union had become
worried that it might lose and stepped up the pace of settlement
negotiations on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If the threat of litigation deters the UAW from further strikes
until the national agreement expires, this summer's strikes can be
counted as a small but costly victory for GM. But GM was fortunate
in that its case was assigned to a conservative federal judge who
repeatedly prevented the union from stalling during the
arbitration, and the company might not be so fortunate in future
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Each side's gains in the current strike were offset by enormous
losses. Wall Street analysts estimate that GM suffered after-tax
losses of $3 billion from the strike, and suffered a drop in sales
of about $12 billion, the heaviest losses ever incurred by an
American company during a strike, at least before adjusting for
inflation. The UAW's 200,000 members lost paychecks totaling about
$1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   GM can recoup as much as half of the lost profits by running its
factories around the clock for months to restock dealerships picked
bare of popular models. UAW workers will earn ample overtime in the
coming weeks, although not enough to balance the paychecks foregone
during the strike.
</P>
<P>
   There will be four separate votes on ratification, as each of
the two struck factories will hold separate votes for assembly line
workers and for skilled craftsmen, like electricians.
</P>
<P>
   Agreements to end other recent strikes at GM factories have been
easily approved and UAW officials expected that Tuesday night's
pact would also pass, although they predicted some grumbling among
workers facing higher production quotas.
</P>
<P>
   In a provision that is likely to raise eyebrows on Wall Street
but improve the odds of ratification, GM will give a week's pay to
all striking and laid-off workers who missed a week of holiday pay
early this month because of the strike. GM said that the payments
to more than 100,000 workers would not affect its earnings because
it would use money previously earmarked for joint training programs
with the union.
</P>
<P>
   If ratified, Tuesday's accord would allow more than a hundred GM
assembly plants and parts factories across the nation to clank back
into production over the next week, with production resuming at the
struck factories by Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   GM would recall 189,000 workers that it has temporarily laid off
across North America, while its suppliers would bring back tens of
thousands of workers that they have also pushed into unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Restarting the world's largest manufacturing system will be a
formidable task. With the strike costing $75 million a day, GM is
likely to undertake a massive airlift of auto parts to assembly
plants as soon as the two struck factories here reopen, said
Michael Robinet, the managing director of CSM Forecasting, an auto
production consulting firm in Farmington Hills, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes by 9,200 workers here lasted so long partly because
both sides came to see them as struggles over principles _ indeed,
Donald Hackworth, GM's group vice president for North American car
operations, even said early this month that the cost of the strikes
could not be justified in financial terms.
</P>
<P>
   But the strikes also dragged on longer than anyone expected
because both sides kept raising the stakes, bringing up new issues
or making new threats in the mistaken belief that the other side
would quickly back down. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
