<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7091 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTNEY-COX     07-28 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTNEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A house near Penny Lane shares memories of ex-Beatle
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIVERPOOL, England _ Paul McCartney's yesterday is here today.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning today, visitors will be allowed to explore the modest
government housing unit where the former Beatle spent his years as
a teenager and began life as a rock 'n' roll icon.
</P>
<P>
   McCartney and John Lennon often slipped away from school to idle
away their afternoons in the tiny front parlor picking at their
guitars by the coal-fueled heater. Here they scratched out early
tunes such as ``I Saw Her Standing There'' and ``Love Me Do,'' the
song that launched the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was still living in the house when the Beatles found
worldwide fame,'' McCartney wrote in a guidebook prepared for the
house. ``My memories of the house are closely connected with those
times.''
</P>
<P>
   McCartney was 13 when his family moved into the 3-year-old house
at 20 Forthlin Road, not far from the shops and stores of Penny
Lane. It was 1955 _ the year before McCartney's mother, Mary, died
of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   He remained there with his father, Jim, and brother, Michael,
until 1964, the year of the group's American debut, when
Beatle-crazed fans forced the McCartneys to flee in the middle of
the night.
</P>
<P>
   The National Trust bought the two-story council house in 1995
for $91,000 from the woman who moved in after the McCartneys.
</P>
<P>
   In selecting furniture, decorations and other artifacts, the
trust sought to re-create the aura of living in a government-owned
council house during the 1950s and early '60s. There are period
furniture pieces and appliances _ including a small TV bought in
the '50s from future Beatles manager Brian Epstein's music store.
</P>
<P>
   The painting scheme _ a buttery ``corporation cream'' and deep
maroon _ is authentic. Even the flowers bordering the rectangle of
grass in front of the house were selected to match what the
McCartneys had planted.
</P>
<P>
   Black-and-white photographs taken by Paul's brother Michael
connect the rooms to his family's daily life there. Among these is
a famous photo of McCartney climbing up a drainpipe to the back
restroom window.
</P>
<P>
   McCartney's tiny linoleum-floored bedroom, where he slept until
the Beatles made it big, overlooks the front garden and quiet
street. It is in this spare room that he listened to American
rhythm and blues greats Fats Domino and Little Richard on a
Phillips radio that Jim McCartney rigged for his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are familiar things for many people; perhaps reminding
them of somewhere they had been, maybe their grandmothers' homes,''
said Sarah Collins, a spokeswoman for the National Trust. ``It's
meant to be an evocation of what went on here.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the judgment of the National Trust, what went on in these
cramped quarters was important. This marks the first time that the
trust, which is most often associated with palaces and castles,
acquired a house connected to a living person, and it is the most
modern property in the organization's inventory. ``I don't think
anybody could argue about the impact of the Beatles to popular
culture in the 20th century,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   And people in Liverpool, a faded port city of 500,000, aren't
arguing with the impact, or at least the potential impact, of the
Beatles on the local economy. Of the 800,000 tourists who visit
Liverpool each year, about 500,000 come because of the Beatles,
according to the Merseyside Tourism and Conference Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   McCartney's house is only the latest addition to the collection
of Beatles attractions that have sprung up here in recent years.
The city seems to be shedding its ambivalence about its most famous
sons who left at the first opportunity, and in the minds of some
failed to look back often enough.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, there was little evidence that the Beatles had
ever existed here. Now, signs of the Fab Four are here, there and
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of years ago, the city began to recognize the tourism
potential and began to develop an infrastructure to support it,''
said Keith Davis of the Tourism bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Liverpool officials are eager to bring people here with the
sizzle of the Beatles and then hook them on the city's history,
fine collection of architecturally interesting buildings and
attractions such as the nearby walled city of Chester. ``Liverpool
is a brand name across the world because of the Beatles, and we
need to find ways to leverage that,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The leveraging is well under way. For a sample _ a big sample _
take a Magical Mystery Tour bus to 59 Beatles sites, including the
Strawberry Field orphanage and the early homes of all four Beatles,
such as No. 9 Newcastle Road, where Lennon lived with his mother,
Julia.
</P>
<P>
   On Mathew Street, where the Beatles debuted in the Cavern
nightclub, you can buy a pint at the Abbey Road bar or get a
``Lennon Burger,'' with fried onions and tomatoes for about $2.50.
The Cavern, the cellar of an old fruit warehouse that was nearly
demolished in the 1970s, has recently reopened. Around the old
nightclub, the city has developed Cavern Walks shopping arcade.
There's the Cavern Pub and Cavern Wall of Fame, which bears the
names of 1,801 acts that appeared there between 1957 and 1973.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the Beatles' Story at the Albert Docks, which
for an admission charge of about $7.50 per adult offers an
underground walking tour that progresses through the stages in the
careers of the four Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   While it is expected to bring only 11,000 paid visitors a year,
the McCartney house will lend an air of dignity to the legacy here.
Moreover, it is creating a nice spate of publicity, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for the neighbors on Forthlin Road, the prospect of a fresh
wave of Beatlemania is a bit unnerving. On Tuesday, a number of
cars and vans bearing what appeared to be peering tourists stopped
in at the house and began videotaping people standing outside. A
mother holding her pigtailed daughter's hand complained to a
National Trust official about the danger of the traffic to the
children.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Gledhill, who lives next door, is annoyed. ``It's already
like living in a fishbowl,'' he said. ``This is hyped up out of all
proportion. I feel like packing up.''
</P>
<P>
   For McCartney's part, he expressed some pride at the house's
recognition. ``My dear mother Mary had great aspirations for our
family and was very proud and pleased when we moved in,'' he wrote
in a good-luck letter to the Trust. ``Because of its modern design,
it was a house that attracted the admiration of visitors, as I hope
it will now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
