<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7095 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALLBIZ-COX     07-28 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALLBIZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Solid planning keeps business going through generations
 &HT;    By Kim Tyson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Bea McQueen and her late husband Joe built their
IEC Corp. over the past 43 years into an international,
multimillion-dollar company by producing industrial devices used in
everything from oil rigs to food conveyor belts.
</P>
<P>
   Now 81, one of Bea's biggest jobs is helping ensure IEC remains
controlled by her family.
</P>
<P>
   About 13 million American businesses, including about 175 of the
Fortune 500, are family-controlled companies, according to one
book, ``Wars of Succession: The Blessings, Curses and Lessons That
Family-Owned Firms Offer Anyone in Business.'' They aren't all
mom-and-pop stores either: Companies like Ford Motor Co., Marriott
Hotels, and Wal-Mart Stores Inc. all started as family-owned
companies.
</P>
<P>
   But it is often difficult to successfully keep family-owned
businesses intact as they pass from one generation to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Only 30 percent of all businesses survive the transfer to a
second generation of family ownership and only 13 percent survive
to a third generation, according to ``Wars of Succession.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred McNair, president of McNairs Appliance Inc., says good
estate planning has helped the company as it begins the transfer to
its fourth generation of McNair ownership. The company has grown
into a $14 million business _ the 57th largest appliance dealer in
the country _ since it was started in 1939 by Fred McNair's
grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have spent a lot of money with accountants and tax
lawyers,'' McNair says. ``It takes literally years to move some of
these assets out of the estate. Luckily we started a long time
ago.'' Through family limited partnerships, planned gifts, and
generation skipping trusts, the McNair family istrying to soften
some of the tax bite that can hit a company after its founder dies.
</P>
<P>
   The National Federation of Independent Business, which
represents 600,000 business owners, has been lobbying for changes
in ``death taxes,'' which can take up to a 55 percent tax bite out
of the value of a business when it is transferred after the death
of the owner.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Congress increased the tax exemption from $600,000 to
$1 million on family-owned businesses being transferred to heirs.
The ``unified tax credit'' is being phased in over 10 years. The
NFIB is still pushing for full repeal ofdeath taxes on family-owned
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   While tax issues can be onerous, keeping harmony in the family
while balancing everyone's ownership interest in the company is
equally difficult, McNair says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've done it legal, but also as equitably as we
could,'' he says, adding that his 25-year-old son, Adam, has said
he wants to pursue a career with the company. He also has two other
children. ``You don't want to make a family member mad and break up
a family relationship. That's the ticklish part.''
</P>
<P>
   At IEC, Bea McQueen says she and her husband began working with
estate planning consultants 10 years ago on a succession plan for
their company. It wasn't easy, she says, especially since her
husband disliked even discussing the topic.
</P>
<P>
   Joe McQueen died in November 1996 of cancer. He built a company
known for producing highly reliable slip rings _ electro-mechanical
devices that allows the transfer of power between a moving object
and a stationary object. IEC products have been used in everything
from giant conveyor belts to warning devices used by the U.S.
military.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978 Bea took the helm of the company when her husband
decided he would rather spend more time on their ranch. Bea, then
61, diversified the business into new industries and oversaw its
growth into a company with $3 million in sales in 1997. Last fall,
she received a lifetime achievement award from the Texas Women's
Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Bea spends only a few days a week in IEC's offices.
Her son-in-law, John Paul Hudson, took over as president in 1994.
``(Joe McQueen) had the philosophy that he would never sell the
company. It would continue to be a part of the family,'' Hudson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the McNairs, the McQueens have tried to ensure that IEC
will stay in the family by setting up trusts that allow for its
stock ownership to proceed to the grandchildren. Such trusts allow
for the company to avoid a second set of taxes by skipping the
second generation of ownership.
</P>
<P>
   McQueen says she took out an insurance policy on herself that
would be used to pay off the the company's federal estate taxes
when she dies. (The National Federation of Independent Business
estimates that 68 percent of family business owners take out
insurance for this reason).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, family members are learning the ropes of the
business. Hudson has been with the company since the early 1970s.
Grandson Casey, 18, worked this summer in its machine shop, and
26-year-old daughter Heather has been producing the company's next
catalog of products.
</P>
<P>
   ``(John Paul) has got a sharp brain,'' Bea McQueen says. ``He's
a good leader. Right behind him are his daughter and son. It will
be carried on because they are both interested. We will make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Tyson writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
