NYT-07-28-98 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7097 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSEUM-DIRECTORS-$ADV     07-28 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-DIRECTORS-$ADV02-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS ART MUSEUMS THRIVE, THEIR DIRECTORS DECAMP  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Tenn., Texas, Mich., Mo., Ill., N.Y., Pa., Calif.)   Deborah Solomon's ``Utopia Parkway: The Life and Work of Joseph
Cornell'' will be issued in paperback next month.  
 (af)  
 By DEBORAH SOLOMON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   E.A. Carmean Jr. is one of the most respected museum men in
America, but these days you won't find him anywhere near a museum.
It took him three decades to rise to the upper echelon of his
profession and all of three minutes to bow out: he recently quit
his job as the director of the Memphis Brooks Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Once he went to board meetings. Now he goes to Bible classes. At
54, he has decided to become an Episcopal priest.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain his decision, Carmean, who still lives in
Memphis, chuckled softly and told a joke. What's the difference
between a church and a museum? ``In church you have bread and
wine,'' he said, ``whereas at museum openings you have bread and
wine and cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, what led him to leave? ``The pressure on museum
directors is nonstop,'' he said. ``The minute you close one
blockbuster, you have to open another one. Museums are competing
with one another for attention, jumping up and down and screaming,
`Look at me, look at me!' If I ever organize a show again, at least
I'll have God on my side!''
</P>
<P>
   Attendance at American art museums is skyrocketing, but upstairs
in the director's office, the desk chair is often unoccupied and an
eerie silence prevails. At last count, there were about 20 openings
for directors at prominent museums, and trustees are insisting,
with only partial exaggeration, that they can't find anyone for the
job.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, all kinds of institutions, from the Ivy League to
major league baseball, are having a hard time filling top
positions. All around, the theme is the same: money and marketing
are stripping jobs of their character and driving visionaries away.
The help-wanted problem is particularly acute at museums, where
directors are departing with a new haste as stranded trustees
consider alternate models of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   If you're thinking of becoming a museum director, this is an
excellent time to apply. The vacancy rate is the highest it has
been in 15 years, according to Mimi Gaudieri, the executive
director of the Association of American Museums.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have never been so many openings at bigger institutions
especially,'' she noted. They include the Whitney Museum of
American Art, the Dallas Museum of Art, the Detroit Institute of
Arts, the St. Louis Art Museum and, most confoundingly, the Kimbell
Art Museum in Fort Worth, where trustees have been trying since
January to fill what might seem like a plum job.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimbell claims a $200 million endowment, the largest of any
art museum in this country except the Getty, and can promise its
future director the chance to work in a stylish building designed
by Louis Kahn, care for a collection laden with Old Masters and
earn a salary said to be in the $400,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   One person who won't be applying is Kevin E. Consey, who, just
this summer, at age 46, gave up the directorship of Chicago's
Museum of Contemporary Art. ``Wild horses and pots of gold couldn't
get me to take another museum job,'' he said cheerfully on his last
day of work, adding that he plans to go to business school and
teach arts administration. ``I can't wait to get out of here. I've
got to clear my brain. I'm just going to take some time and go
surfing, which will be hard to do on Lake Michigan.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Tucker, 58, the outgoing director of the New Museum of
Contemporary Art in New York, similarly harbors no interest in
applying for another directorship. ``Why would I?'' she asked in a
startled voice. ``To direct an institution nowadays you have to be
an opportunist. You have to use every social situation you get to
think about fund-raising and social contacts. Sorry, but the
cocktail-party conversation is not my preferred mode of thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Koshalek, 56, the director of the Museum of Contemporary
Art in Los Angeles, plans on stepping down next year. ``I don't
think I'll miss being a director,'' he said with undisguised
pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   What, exactly, is a museum director, and what does he or she do?
For most of us, the job title still conjures a genteel vision _ an
image of someone who is poised and cultivated, who spends his days
conferring with curators, acquiring masterpieces for the collection
and charming wads of dough out of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   We imagine someone who, if asked, could easily instruct us in
the esthetic significance of Rodin bronzes or Chinese scroll
paintings, and who is equally adept at making toasts. We imagine
this person vacations in Tuscany.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 20 years, however, the classic image of the
director-connoisseur has gone the way of monocles and white gloves.
Directors have begun to sound like desperadoes. Their time is spent
courting socialites and odd-duck widows, while pining for the
corporate handout bonanza of the 80s. Money is harder to drum up,
though trustees are more demanding and seem to prize profits over
the ideal of civic service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most trustees aren't in it for the love of art,'' said Robert
T. Buck, the former director of the Brooklyn Museum of Art and a
current director of the Marlborough Gallery in New York. ``At board
meetings, they go over the financial reports and then look at you
with disappointed faces. I felt like the board was playing Pin the
Tail on the Donkey and I was chosen to be the donkey.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   To run a cultural institution is, in some ways, to be a cloven
creature _ half head-in-the-clouds dreamer, half bottom-line
bookkeeper _ and it might seem logical to split the job in two.
That's how it works in the performing arts, where an artistic
director and a general manager tend to reign in tandem.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the partnerships have been fabled, like that of Lincoln
Kirstein and George Balanchine, who founded the New York City
Ballet in 1948. Kirstein, who ran the money end of things, kept an
address book stocked with the names of Astors, Warburgs and other
philanthropists, leaving Balanchine free to obsess over dance
steps.
</P>
<P>
   Could it work in the museum world? A few museums have
experimented with the two-headed model, only to conclude that one
head is better than two. The Metropolitan Museum of Art, after 20
years of leadership by a director as well as a salaried president
whose authority was exactly equal, is scrapping the system next
spring and reverting to one-man rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dual leadership doesn't solve any problems,'' said Philippe de
Montebello, the Met's longtime director. ``A director needs a
vision that informs everything from his aura when he walks in the
door to how he looks at a work of art to the attitude of the
guards, and a vision cannot be divided in two.''
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Museum of Art, after splitting its top job
between a director and a CEO for 14 years, similarly decided to
recombine the posts in 1996. ``Double leadership makes more sense
for the performing arts,'' said Anne d'Harnoncourt, the museum's
director. ``A conductor, choreographer or stage director is an
artist who has to spend all his time with the product, the
performance. That isn't the case with museum directors. We're not
artists. We don't have to paint the pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves one lone big-city museum to endorse the merits of
dual leadership: the Los Angeles County Museum of Art. It added a
paid president to its staff in 1995, after the director, Michael
Shapiro, bolted from his job almost as soon as he unpacked, serving
for just a year.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, new paradigms of leadership are emerging. Foremost
among them is the Friendly Manager _ a director with a warm
handshake who is happy to devote endless hours to administrative
details while leaving all esthetic decisions to a team of ace
curators. Glenn D. Lowry typifies the breed. He joined the Museum
of Modern Art in New York in 1995, and in some ways he was an odd
choice: an Islamicist by training to preside over a museum that
owns more than 100,000 works of art, not one of which is Islamic.
</P>
<P>
   Lowry, who is 43, previously ran the Art Gallery of Ontario,
where he completed a $58 million building project; he's now
overseeing an elaborate expansion at the Modern.
</P>
<P>
   The current expand-or-die mentality has surely found its most
formidable champion in Thomas Krens of the Solomon R. Guggenheim
Museum, another archetypal 90s director. Call him the
Charlemagne-boss, conquering lands far and wide.
</P>
<P>
   The Guggenheim's new annex in Bilbao, Spain, is one of the
wonders of the nonancient world, and architecture critics have
praised it extravagantly. Still, the museum's curatorial objectives
remain hazy, and no one is sure what will fill the building over
time. Maybe paintings after all.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, will Krens last long enough to decide? Much like
that of college presidents, the tenure of directors is shrinking.
Directors used to serve for two or three decades; now they clear
out after an average of seven years. Their photographs appear with
increasing frequency in trade magazines like Art News, accompanied
by reports of the latest career jumps _ David Ross, for instance
(who just went from the Whitney to the San Francisco Museum of
Modern Art), or Samuel Sachs II (who left Detroit for the Frick
Collection).
</P>
<P>
   Such museum-hoppers stand in contrast to the slow-creeping
stewards of the past, most notably Alfred H. Barr Jr., the founding
director of the Museum of Modern Art. Dismissed from his job in
1943, after supporting, among other things, an unpopular exhibition
of paintings by a retired slipper manufacturer named Morris
Hirshfield, Barr refused to go away; he moved into a tiny cubicle
in the museum's library and stuck around for another two decades,
writing his scholarly books.
</P>
<P>
   Unwilling to bodily eject him, trustees gave up and left him on
the payroll. As Margaret Barr, his wife, once explained: ``Of
course Alfred would not leave. It was his museum. The museum was
his mistress.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, directors are more fickle. At a time when society
places a high premium on personal fulfillment and encourages
fantasies of starting over _ if you dislike your job, your spouse
or your nose, you can get a new one _ directors seem as willing as
anyone to switch careers.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of Charles S. Moffett, who, at 52, is known in
the museum world as an authority on French Impressionism. He served
as a curator at various first-tier institutions before being tapped
for his dream job: the director of the Phillips Collection in
Washington, one of the most enchanting small museums in this
country. Yet last April, six years after he arrived, he resigned.
He switched into the auction business, becoming a vice president of
Sotheby's in New York.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
