<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nigerian writer trapped in U.S. by INS red tape
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobel laureate Wole Soyinka fled his native Nigeria in 1994 to
escape imprisonment. Now, though it is certainly no prison, he
feels confined to the United States, unable to leave for fear he
will not be allowed to re-enter the country.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Soyinka _ a playwright who lectures at Emory
University in Atlanta and who won the 1986 Nobel Prize for
literature _ declined last week to attend a human rights conference
he had been scheduled to address in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Soyinka has opposed a succession of Nigerian military
dictatorships. In 1994, he was charged with treason by the
government of Gen. Sani Abacha and made a harrowing escape from his
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Another dissident writer, Ken Saro-Wiwa, was executed by
Abacha's government in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Abacha died in June. His successor, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar,
has promised to bring democracy to Nigeria next year.
</P>
<P>
   Soyinka came to the United States on an exchange program
administered by the U.S. Information Agency.
</P>
<P>
   He has applied for permanent residency. But those applications
take time. In the interim, he has been living in the U.S. on what
is called ``advance parole,'' a yearlong dispensation which allows
him to to leave and re-enter the country without a visa.
</P>
<P>
   That expired July 8. Despite Soyinka's application for renewal,
it has not been renewed.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to get comments from the Immigration and Naturalization
Service failed. Officials in Washington referred questions to
officials in Atlanta, who did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Lelia Crawford, director for international
student and scholar programs at Emory, the hang-up is that, under
the rules of the USIA exchange program, Soyinka must return home
for two years if Nigeria needs his skills _ and both theater and
education are on a list of skills Nigeria says it needs _ before he
can be eligible for permanent residency.
</P>
<P>
   The INS has approved Soyinka's request to stay in this country,
based on a provision of the law that applies to Nobel Prize winners
and other people of high achievement, Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   But the INS cannot proceed until Soyinka fulfills his USIA
requirement. That requirement can be waived if Soyinka demonstrates
a well-founded fear of persecution if he returns home, said Stanley
Colvin, assistant general counsel for USIA.
</P>
<P>
   Colvin said he was not familiar with Soyinka's case but was
speaking only about the legal requirements. He said applications
for waivers based on fear of prosecution are turned over to the
State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford said she plans to submit such proof _ newspaper
clippings, mostly _ to USIA today.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Soyinka, who has on occasion criticized the State
Department, hopes to be able to resume his international travel
schedule. And he is aghast that no accommodation could be made for
him to travel to the Ottawa conference even for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm trying to reassure myself that it's a genuine
bureaucratic snarl,'' he said. ``I'm trying not to have a
conspiracy mentality right now. It's very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
