<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7100 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSEUM-DIRECTORS-$ADV     07-28 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-DIRECTORS-$ADV02-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: New York.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To ask why he left his museum job is to hear a familiar litany
of complaints. ``I was spending all my time raising money,''
Moffett said with a sigh. ``I knew that if I lost contact with
works of art, I would dry up and turn to dust and blow away. The
job at Sotheby's has given me an opportunity to go back to art and
connoisseurship.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the salary issue. Most art museum directors do
not earn whopping incomes _ the median salary last year was
$110,250, according to a survey by the directors' association _ and
while Moffett declined to specify what Sotheby's was paying him, he
did remark, somewhat jokingly: ``Auction houses have a bonus plan,
and there's a possibility for reward at the end of the year. At the
Phillips Collection, I only received Christmas cards from the
trustees.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, it was considered taboo for a museum director
to cross over into the auction field. To sell art was to sell out.
Auction houses, unlike museums, cater to a tiny coterie of people
(tycoons, heiresses, art dealers, etc.) who buy and sell Picassos
and Dubuffets for business or sport. Not even the perkiest
auctioneer at Sotheby's or Christie's could pretend that they play
any role in educating a large public in the higher rewards of art.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, these days, defections to the auction houses and Manhattan
galleries are increasingly common (they include Richard E.
Oldenburg, formerly of the Modern), and no one raises an eyebrow.
Perhaps that's because museums are no longer viewed as castles of
purity and scholarship, towering above the world of commerce.
Rather, they're seen as businesses of sorts governed by practical
imperatives, and the prestige of museum directors has been
tarnished in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the throngs pouring into the latest shows of Picasso
or Degas or Bonnard might seem to suggest that museums are
flourishing. And, in many ways, they are. It is not Pollyanna-ish
to speak of the present as a golden age for the American museum.
</P>
<P>
   More people than ever are seeing more ambitious exhibitions; the
complaint that a mass art audience dilutes the quality of shows is
a pious fiction, embraced mainly by cranks. The mobbed Cezanne show
seen in Philadelphia in 1996, to cite an obvious example, proved
that art addicts and the general public can inhabit the same
heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the museum boom has come at a high price. Bigger
shows demand bigger budgets, and the need for directors who excel
at raising money is driving a generation of esteemed art historians
right out the door. This poses a real danger to museums,
particularly the new or newly expanded ones, which might never have
the chance to define themselves _ to establish why they matter _
without able leadership, the sort of leadership now being shunned.
</P>
<P>
   Who will guide our museums into the 21st century? True, there
are a few newcomers _ like Robert Fitzpatrick, who has just been
named director of Chicago's Museum of Contemporary Art. At 58, he
has never worked in a museum before, and he claims unusual
credentials: dean of the School of the Arts at Columbia University
and, before that, president and chief executive of Euro Disney
outside Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his vision for the museum, Fitzpatrick questioned
the necessity of having a vision at all. ``I'm not going to sit
here like some kind of French intellectual and say, `Here is the
way I see the universe.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he then articulated a vision of sorts. ``What
Disney gave me,'' he said, ``was an enormous respect for what
Disney calls the `guests.' There's a difference between a client, a
customer and a guest. When you go to a Disney theme park you feel
truly welcome. We have five young curators at this museum, and this
summer I'm having them work as guards at the museum for a day or
two. I want them to experience how visitors enter a gallery, to
think, `How can we make this museum a pleasant, welcoming
experience?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the museum specializes in contemporary art, much of
which _ Bruce Nauman's shrieking videos, Cindy Sherman's
photographs of rotting food, Sue Williams' plastic puddle of vomit
_ might not seem to lend itself to the museum's new hospitality
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind. Told that he seemed uncommonly upbeat for an art
museum director, Fitzpatrick explained, ``Well, I've only been here
for three days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
