<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO U.S. OFFICIALS DETAINED IN CHIAPAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Pro-government Indians detained the assistant
United States army attache and an American army sergeant for nearly
five hours on Monday in a conflict-ridden village in Chiapas state,
a spokesman for the United States embassy said Tuesday. The two
diplomats were released unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Thomas Gillen and Sgt. Elizabeth Krug, both assigned to the
military attache's office in the embassy here, were stopped by
villagers in the mountain hamlet of Los Platanos. The Indians
blocked the road with rocks to keep them from leaving after the
Americans refused to allow a search of their vehicle, citing their
immunities as diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin said in Washington that
the officials' Chiapas visit was ``part of their regular and normal
duties'' to report on political events in Mexico. Several shooting
incidents have occurred recently in the hamlet.
</P>
<P>
   Chiapas state police and government officials stepped in to
persuade the villagers to let the diplomats go.
</P>
<P>
   The government has mounted a campaign among its followers to
blame foreigners for the crisis in Chiapas, where pro-government
groups are squared off against Zapatista rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
