<HEADER>
A7108 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-ART-2     07-28 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-ART-260&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA REDUCING FORCES IN EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: a map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, Indonesia _ Indonesia began withdrawing 1,000 combat
troops from East Timor on Tuesday, but critics and residents
remained skeptical about the more than 11,000 troops and police
officers who will continue to patrol the territory.
</P>
<P>
   The highly publicized withdrawal is an attempt to demonstrate
Jakarta's commitment to a peaceful resolution of the fate of the
former Portuguese colony, which Indonesia invaded in 1975 and
annexed in 1976. Since then, the disputed territory has been the
scene of fierce fighting between security forces and separatists,
that along with disease and starvation, has left an estimated
200,000 people dead.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1976, the Indonesian military has been accused of repeated
human rights abuses against the people of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, 398 departing troops, representing the elite Special
Forces and the Strategic Reserves Command, boarded a vessel docked
in the harbor here in the capital while several hundred residents
watched from behind an iron fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are removing the combat troops because the number of rebels
in the jungle is getting smaller,'' said the military's information
officer, Capt. Tri Yoga Budi, who estimated the current number of
rebels at fewer than 200.
</P>
<P>
   While the threat from rebels seeking independence for the area
may have been reduced, the decision to pull out the combat troops
is believed to have more to do with the talks between Indonesia and
Portugal planned for Aug. 4 and 5 in New York under the auspices of
the United Nations secretary general.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Requests for demilitarization have also come from Jamsheed
Marker, the United Nations' special envoy for East Timor who
recently visited the territory, and from the Roman Catholic bishop
for the territory, Carlos Ximenes Belo, who has repeatedly called
for freedom of movement on the tiny island 1,300 miles east of
Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as there are soldiers there will be threats,'' said
Manuel Carrascalao, a founding member of the Movement for the
Reconciliation and Unity of the East Timorese People.
</P>
<P>
   Residents and activists said security officials were still
stopping East Timorese at random and that the military retained a
presence in each of the villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The soldiers are repressive as usual,'' said Anis Neves from
the local Rights Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   He questioned the need to keep on so many troops if so few
rebels remained to pose a threat.
</P>
<P>
   The official answer is that the troops will be employed in the
territory's ``development.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The soldiers help the farmers with planting, some help teach
and others are involved with development activities,'' said Lt.
Col. Saragi, who like many Indonesians uses only one name.
</P>
<P>
   Carrascalao said only a complete withdrawal of troops would lead
to peace and confidence-building in East Timor, where 85 percent of
the population of 850,000 is Catholic in predominantly Muslim
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The East Timorese don't have a problem with religious
differences or with the Indonesians,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we do have a problem with ABRI,'' he said, using the
initials for the Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
   Carrascalao called the troop withdrawal a ``charade'' staged for
the outside world at a time when the new administration under
President B.J. Habibie has offered the territory a degree of
autonomy in return for international recognition of East Timor as a
part of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations still recognizes Lisbon as the administrative
authority over the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Jakarta's officials have ruled out the possibility of a
referendum on East Timor's fate, asserting that a vote on whether
to integrate with Indonesia or become independent would separate
the people of East Timor and possibly lead to a civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have never been any problems solved by referendum,''
said Abilio Soares, governor of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We prefer dialogue as a means of bringing about a better
future for the people of East Timor,' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
