<HEADLINE>
LIGHTING OUT FOR THE TERRITORY, THIS TIME IN 3-D  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARK TWAIN'S AMERICA IN 3-D &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An Imax film at Sony Theaters Lincoln Square in Manhattan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Narrated by Anne Bancroft &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Stephen Low &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G 47 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Low tries to fit the life of Samuel L. Clemens (1835-1910) into
the sweep of American history, a tall order for a 47-minute film.
But then this is a tall movie, projected onto a eight-story-high
screen with figures floating and leaping out at one through a 3-D
headset.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the enlivening effects, an earnest and rather plodding
narrative only grazes highlights from the author's boyhood on the
Mississippi, his riverboat-piloting days and Civil War experiences,
his career as a reporter and writer, and his later days as a
humorist and public figure. (Sadly, his rapier wit is reduced to a
few ponderous chuckles.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-7 The headsets are a bit of a load for the youngest
children, but they will enjoy the 3-D sights. The story, however,
will be confusing and boring. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 8-12 They, too, will like the effects. They might also have
appreciated a livelier, more imaginative historical account. The
wooden tone of this one may turn off brighter and more restless
children, even in 47 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND UP They are way beyond this sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   Peter M. Nichols &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE PARENT TRAP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Quaid, Natasha Richardson, Lindsay Lohan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Nancy Meyers &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG 128 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Disney has freshened up its 1961 classic about twins separated
more or less at birth who meet at summer camp and scheme to bring
their divorced parents back together. Ms. Lohan, a freckle-faced
redhead, plays both twins, as Hayley Mills did in the original.
</P>
<P>
   The poor-little-rich-girls story is even more improbable now,
because divorce and child-custody questions are so common. But it's
still a rosy fairy tale, and the 90s touches include blue
fingernail polish, a Napa Valley vineyard and the Concorde. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Some lusty kissing and a reference to sex. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY One mild instance, and an innocent use of the term
``F-word.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-5 The practical jokes and slapstick will make them laugh,
although they may not understand much of the plot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-11 Girls will beg to see it again. Most boys will
probably feel like the poor little guy who got on the wrong bus and
ended up at the all-girls' camp. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND UP Fans of the original film may want to see it for
nostalgia's sake. Others will be too hip for this kind of &QL; 
material.
</P>
<P>
   Jan BenzeL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THERE'S SOMETHING ABOUT MARY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cameron Diaz, Ben Stiller, Matt Dillon, Chris Elliott &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Peter and Bobby Farrelly &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 105 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe, but in high school in the middle 80s there
was this gorgeous girl named Mary (Ms. Diaz) who was so nice she
actually asked the very uncool Ted (Stiller) to go to the prom with
her. Thirteen years later, Ted has lost touch with Mary, but he's
still in love so he hires Healy (Dillon), a private eye, to find
her.
</P>
<P>
   The trail leads to Miami, where Mary is a doctor and as
good-hearted as ever. Problem is, everybody in South Florida is
also in love with her, and that soon includes Healy, who schemes
and lies for her affections. This being a concoction of the
Farrelly brothers (``Dumb and Dumber,'' ``Kingpin''), get set for
gross occurrences and riotous complications. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Ted gets banged around but gamely carries on through
slapstick scuffles and situations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX There is a glimpse of male genitals, and another scene
depicts masturbation, though not explicitly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY In a raucous movie, everybody, including sweet Mary,
has a dirty mouth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 10 Older children in this group would find much to
laugh at, but the obscenities and gross-outs make the film
unsuitable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-13 Parents should consider the language and other
crudities that have earned the film its R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP For teen-agers nothing in the film is all that
objectionable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter M. Nichols &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAFIA! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jay Mohr, Billy Burke, Lloyd Bridges, Christina Applegate &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jim Abrahams &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 86 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abrahams' spoof of Mafia movies touches all bases from Francis
Ford Coppola's ``Godfather'' to Martin Scorsese's ``Goodfellas''
and ``Casino.'' Flashbacks allude to tough but funny times in the
old country and on New York's Lower East Side.
</P>
<P>
   Years later at the mob's gaming tables in Las Vegas, the
spenders keep emptying their pockets. ``The smart ones just send us
the money and save the air fare,'' says the family scion, Anthony
Cortino (Mohr). ``It's the whole Sicilian thing, isn't it?''
complains the Waspy pacifist Diane (Ms. Applegate), Anthony's
girlfriend. ``I'll always be the Protestant chick who never killed
anyone.'' Instead she becomes president of the United States. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Killings, car explosions and such are strictly
comical. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX There are lewd references and sight gags with tongues and
breasts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY A moderate number of obscenities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-9 No. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-12 They'll burst their seams laughing at the silly
business and there's nothing too offensive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP No problem. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter M. Nichols &QL;
</P>
