<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-275&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ULLRICH, A TASTE OF VICTORY, AND DEFEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SAMUEL ABT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBERTVILLE, France _ Jan Ullrich is a great Tour de France
rider, as he proved Tuesday by storming away from all but one rival
to win the demanding second of three daily stages in the Alps. It
was exactly the sort of dominating performance that could be
expected of a man defending his championship in the tour.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Ullrich, the ride Tuesday followed a rare off
day in cold rain, a day in which he lost 8 minutes 57 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Equally unfortunate for Ullrich was that the one rival who
managed to stay with him up and over the fearsome Madeleine Peak
was Marco Pantani, the very man Ullrich lost both the 8:57 and the
leader's yellow jersey to on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   So Ullrich, a German who leads the Telekom team, moved up from
fourth place over all to third and almost to second, but did not go
far toward winning the world's greatest bicycle race for the second
successive year.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani, on the other hand, moved close to victory. By finishing
second in a sprint finish Tuesday, he widened his leadership to
5:42 over the American Bobby Julich and by 5:56 over Ullrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tour de France is lost,'' Ullrich conceded after the 16th
of 21 stages. ``But my victory today was extremely important for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich continued by praising Pantani's victory Monday as
``incredible,'' considering the daylong cold rain that crushed
Ullrich, a notorious summer soldier and sunshine patriot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never expected him to race so well after the hard last week
he had in the Giro,'' Ullrich said, referring to Pantani's victory
last month in the three-week Giro d'Italia. ``There's no doubt that
he's the best mountain climber in the world.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With one day left in the Alps, where the Italian leader of
Mercatone Uno has been outstanding, Pantani's big obstacle is a
32-mile individual race against the clock on Saturday. Although
such time trialing is not Pantani's strength, he is unlikely to
lose a lead of over five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That gap was obviously on Ullrich's mind when he accelerated
away from a group of leaders with 9 miles to go on the Madeleine
climb, 13 miles long with a grade of 7.6 percent. It is rated
beyond category in difficulty and followed four less demanding
climbs during the 127-mile trip from Vizelle to Albertville.
</P>
<P>
   Only Pantani was willing or able to follow him. As the overnight
second- and third-place riders _ Julich and Fernando Escartin, a
Spaniard with Kelme _ watched, Ullrich did all the work in the lead
position. He was looking back constantly to see where the others
were.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Pantani, they were soon out of sight. Within a few
kilometers, the pair caught and left behind three riders from an
early breakaway and then passed over the peak, 2:06 ahead, or
enough to allow Ullrich to rise from fourth to second place.
</P>
<P>
   Although the sun was out and the temperature balmy, the German
did not repeat his error Monday, when he failed to bundle up
adequately against the frigid wind on the descent. Then he wore
only a lightweight jacket over his yellow jersey; Tuesday he donned
a heavier one. Pantani, more a traditionalist, jammed some
newspaper pages into his jersey.
</P>
<P>
   At speeds up to 52 mph on the broadly curving 25-mile descent
into Albertville, the two did their best to maintain their lead.
Ullrich did about 75 percent of the work from the first attack
until Pantani began taking his turn at the head, allowing his
companion to rest in his slipstream.
</P>
<P>
   They even jawed at each other as they rode side by side at one
point, with Ullrich appearing to berate Pantani for lack of
cooperation. The new man in the yellow jersey had much to gain by
widening their lead. Even if it helped the German move up in the
standing, he would gain no time on Pantani, but the Italian would
gain on everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   Behind them, Julich was riding with eight teammates and rivals,
intent on guarding second place and slicing away at the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a very good day today,'' Julich, the rider for
Cofidis from Glenwood Springs, Colo., said later. ``I was suffering
on the climbs and afraid of being dropped. But the cheering from
the crowd kept pushing me on. I kept cramping badly in the last
descent and could barely push the pedals for about five
kilometers.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ullrich and Pantani approached the finish, they broke into an
unlikely sprint, the great puncher against the great climber.
Neither one is Mario Cipollini, the king of the sprinters, but
Ullrich was first by a few inches. In four stages in the Pyrenees
and the Alps, Pantani has won twice and finished second twice.
</P>
<P>
   Julich finished third, 1:49 later, or enough to keep second
place, with Escartin fourth and Axel Merckx, a Belgian with Polti,
fifth. Escartin dropped from third place over all to fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The American was typically upbeat afterward. ``The race isn't
over until the time trial,'' Julich said. ``Never say die.''
</P>
<P>
   He was talking about winning this 85th Tour, not about holding
on to second place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ullrich lost nine minutes yesterday and gained back two
today,'' Julich said. ``Next time, maybe it will be Bobby Julich's
time.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
