<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7121 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-TRIBUNAL-2TAKES-     07-28 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-TRIBUNAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANDMARK BOSNIA RAPE TRIAL: A LEGAL MORASS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands _ She is known as Witness A in the
courtroom, but what happened to her is no longer a secret.
</P>
<P>
   She lived in the Lasva River valley, once a peaceful part of
central Bosnia. A Muslim, she was married with two children. One
day in 1993, a Bosnian Croat soldier ordered her to strip naked as
he interrogated her. He rubbed his knife over her thigh and
stomach, then raped her. Next he locked her in a house where, for
about two months, he and some fellow soldiers raped her again and
again.
</P>
<P>
   The court documents describing these events do not say if
Witness A became pregnant. But she suffered shock and depression,
according to the evidence of a doctor and a psychologist. In her
testimony she talked about nightmares, nervous skin rashes and
stomach pains.
</P>
<P>
   This month, after eight days of hearings, the judges at the
court investigating war crimes in the former Yugoslavia seemed
ready to give their verdict in the case of one of four indicted
soldiers. It was meant to set an early precedent in the tribunal's
first trial charging rape as a war crime.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of the verdict, the startled courtroom heard a
bitter fight among lawyers over procedures. And there was a murmur
when the defense said the rape victim could not be trusted as a
witness because she had had memory problems and had misidentified
the accused. The defense demanded that the victim's testimony be
annulled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a new trial,'' said Luka Misetic, the Chicago lawyer
defending Anto Furundzija, a soldier charged with aiding and
abetting the crime. The lawyer said the woman had been treated for
post-traumatic stress syndrome, but the prosecution had hidden this
fact and was guilty of misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   While the treatment grew out of the crime, the three-judge panel
conceded that the prosecution had indeed made some procedural
errors. As a result, they ruled, the trial would have to reopen,
meaning that witnesses and the victim can be called to testify
again.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than providing an early precedent, the case is
highlighting some of the problems involved in punishing wartime
crimes against women.
</P>
<P>
   And it has raised such crucial questions as where the balance
lies between the right of the accused to a fair and public trial
and the right of the victim to privacy.
</P>
<P>
   As it is shaping up so far, the trial is a setback to the
prosecution, because it has been ordered to hand over medical
documents about the victim that it wanted to keep private.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing rape cases to the tribunal was expected to be
straightforward, given the widespread abuse of women in the Balkan
war. The lowest estimates hold that 20,000 women were raped, most
of them Muslims. Much of the evidence was collected by women. They
set out to demonstrate that sexual assault in Bosnia was systematic
and used as a weapon of war.
</P>
<P>
   It was the outcry over the use of mass rape as a weapon to
impregnate women and to ``humiliate, shame, degrade and terrify''
an entire ethnic group, as one U.N. report put it, that gave sexual
crimes their first foothold in international humanitarian law. And
the outcry led this U.N. tribunal to include sexual assault in its
statutes as a crime against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   But as the case of Witness A has now shown, trying rape at a war
crimes tribunal has its own pitfalls. Other trials that include
sexual assault among a list of charges are under way, but this case
revolves around rape only and serves as a stark example.
</P>
<P>
   For one, to protect the victim, most of the proceedings were
held behind closed doors. The indictment, often an immense
document, in this case is less than four pages long and full of
deletions. It does say that Anto Furundzija, 29, was a commander of
the Jokers, a paramilitary unit that took part in a Croatian
campaign to drive Muslims out of the area. The unit operated from a
bungalow near Vitez in central Bosnia. There, the indictment says,
Furundzija and another soldier, nicknamed Cicko, first interrogated
the Muslim woman in May 1993.
</P>
<P>
   When Cicko beat her and then raped her, Furundzija was present
and did nothing to stop this, the indictment says. Therefore he is
charged with aiding and abetting the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Furundzija, who pleaded not guilty, was arrested last December
by Dutch NATO forces. Complicating the case is that the three
people indicted on charges of rape are still at large and possibly
abroad and the tribunal has no police force to track them down.
Their names have not been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Little else has been disclosed about the case involving Witness
A. At the tribunal's special sex-crime unit, officials say they go
to great lengths to protect a victim's identity and, if necessary,
that of other witnesses. They argue that abused women have suffered
enough and may become outcasts if their plight is known to family
and friends. For the same reason, prosecutors say they do not
reveal details of a victim's mental or physical problems resulting
from the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A rape trial at the tribunal is different from trials in many
other courts. There is no jury to decide the case, but instead a
panel of three judges. And the tribunal's rules of evidence say
that the victim's testimony need not be corroborated. Because the
rape happened during a war, in most situations the defendant cannot
claim there was consent.
</P>
<P>
   It is such limits that infuriate Misetic, the defense lawyer. He
insists that his client was not in the room during the first rape
and that the troubled victim was manipulated into naming him by
others who wanted to settle scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's on the money in the case of the physical perpetrators,''
he said in an interview outside the court, ``but when it comes to
Furundzija she is inconsistent and confused.''
</P>
<P>
   Could the trauma be used against a victim, he was asked, when
the trauma was caused by the crime in question? ``I'm not slamming
the victim for having problems,'' Misetic said. ``But people who
suffer a trauma often have memory troubles and are open to
suggestion.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was unacceptable that the prosecution had held back a
statement from a psychologist, saying the victim had been treated
at a women's counseling center and had shown symptoms of
post-traumatic stress syndrome. He said he had learned this only
during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Hollis, the prosecutor, who is on loan from the U.S.s
military, dismissed those arguments. The defense was duly informed
of the victim's counseling and heard a physician and the victim
herself testify about her symptoms, she said. Ms. Hollis added that
the psychologist's statement was not disclosed because ``it would
be a gross invasion of privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Adding a label of post-traumatic stress syndrome does not
change the picture,'' Ms. Hollis said. Victims of rape and sexual
assault experience trauma and many seek counseling, she added.
``Such psychological counseling does not affect a person's
credibility or memory.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 14, during one of the trial's rare public sessions, the
courtroom was tense and more observers than usual sat in the public
gallery. The accused, Furundzija, dressed in a dark gray suit, did
not move or look sideways.
</P>
<P>
   The presiding judge, Florence Mumba, a jurist from Zambia,
overruled the prosecutor's argument for privacy and ordered that
all relevant medical documents be handed over to the defense. And
she ordered the trial to be reopened. It may resume in September.
</P>
<P>
   One troubling aspect of this turn of events is that the rape
victim, whose whereabouts are secret, will almost certainly be
called to The Hague again to go through adversarial
cross-examination. Attorneys dealing with sex crimes here call this
``re-traumatizing the witness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is shocking,'' said one tribunal official. ``Of course
the rights of the accused must be protected. But the witness must
not be made to suffer over and over again. It's what rape victims
call feeling raped again in court.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
