<HEADLINE>
DUTCH TEAM IS SUBJECTED TO A DRUG SEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SAMUEL ABT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBERTVILLE, France _ The doping scandal enveloping the Tour de
France intensified Tuesday when police officers, seeking illegal
performance-enhancing drugs, searched the hotel of the Dutch TVM
team and took away four riders for questioning and blood tests.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the riders were identified as Jeroen Blijlevens and Bart
Voskamp. The team's assistant coach, Hendrik Redant, also left with
police. He was first questioned last week, when two officials of
the team were held in judicial custody.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, a third team became embroiled in the
controversy when the van belonging to the Big Mat-Auber team was
stopped on a highway near Albertville, the end of the daily stage
in the race, for what was termed a routine inspection. More than
100 medical substances were reported to have been found and sent to
a laboratory in Lyons for identification.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Jacques Henry, the assistant coach of the Big Mat team,
which is based in France, said: ``We're not concerned. Most of it
was simply recovery medication'' like glucose.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the development cast a cloud over yet another team
after the inquiry into TVM and the earlier expulsion of the entire
Festina team.
</P>
<P>
   In the TVM case, about 20 police officers entered the Hotel
Million here and searched the riders' rooms. Police also searched
cars and the team bus. They confiscated three suitcases, a sports
bag and a large plastic bag. The contents were not immediately
identified.
</P>
<P>
   Two officials of the TVM team _ Cees Priem, the coach, and Andre
Mihailov, the team doctor _ were taken into custody last week in
the Pyrenees and transferred to the French city of Rheims on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A TVM team car carrying what was described as a large amount of
illegal drugs was seized in Rheims in March, and two team mechanics
were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   All nine of the Festina riders in the Tour were expelled after
the team's coach, Bruno Roussel, was arrested and admitted through
his lawyer that he had supplied riders with drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the nine have since admitted using such drugs as EPO, an
artificial hormone, which is illegal in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Roussel was released from jail Tuesday, pending further charges
and possible trial for violating French laws against supplying
drugs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
