<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7130 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-WORLD-BLINEBURYCO     07-28 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-WORLD-BLINEBURYCOL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   Team of dreamers &QL; 
a refreshing change
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATHENS, Greece _ Shuffling through the Grand Casino in Monte Carlo
like day-trippers who had been bused in from across the border,
they were anything but celebrities among the royalty and the
moneyed elite.
</P>
<P>
   Strolling along the Via Veneto in Rome, they were just another
dozen in the summer tourist flock, drawing no stares or comparisons
to the Sistine Chapel ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Settled in now at a seaside resort on the outskirts of
democracy's birthplace, there is no mob scene in the hotel lobby.
No hungry hordes of autograph seekers. No throngs of pushy media.
No personal bodyguards. No limos.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the Dream Team. Just a collection of real dreamers
who will start to work today to fulfill an obligation for their
country and a dozen fantasies for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who ever would have believed it?'' said the basketball gypsy,
the only man in history to play for all three NBA franchises in
Texas. ``David Wood pulling on a jersey to play for the ol' USA.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never even dreamed of this,'' said Jason Sasser, Texas Tech,
class of '96. ``I thought trying to win a gold medal for America
was, frankly, beyond my level of ability.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, it would have been if the locked-out NBA players
had not used the World Championship of Basketball as a misguided
bargaining chip in their labor war with team owners.
</P>
<P>
   Stroke of luck for players
</P>
<P>
   So instead of a ``Who's Who'' list of slam-dunking talent, the
disappointed Greek organizers get a ``Who's He?'' American team
made up of Continental Basketball Association scrappers, undrafted
collegians and overseas exiles, coached, so fittingly, by the
Rockets' Rudy Tomjanovich, patron saint of the underdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you don't get an almost-guaranteed gold medal this
way,'' Rudy T said. ``But you know, this just might be more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention refreshing. Rather than bringing in a roster of
NBA Godzillas to stomp on the world as if it were a movie set of
Manhattan, the ol' USA will have to fight, hustle and labor against
a lineup of challenging competitors from Australia, Russia,
Yugoslavia, Lithuania and Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of this being a 12-day window to flex, pose and sell
souvenir NBA T-shirts and jerseys to every man, woman and child on
the planet, the World Championship turns back into an
honest-to-goodness tournament where almost anybody can win.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe without the Dream Team likes of Grant Hill, Tim Duncan and
Gary Payton, it's not sexy enough for NBC and TNT, which pulled the
plug on plans to air all of the games live in the United States.
The real dreamers have been relegated to appearances on ESPN2,
sandwiched between a couple of ``World's Strongest Men'' shows.
</P>
<P>
   But with players such as Wood and Sasser and Jimmy King and
Michael Hawkins and the rest, those viewers who tune in will see
guys playing for patriotic pride and maybe another chance at an NBA
life instead of multimillionaires playing to get one more
endorsement contract.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: The Dream Team concept had become old and
heavy-handed. When Magic Johnson, Larry Bird, Michael Jordan and
Charles Barkley led the original bunch to a staggering gold-medal
performance in 1992 at the Barcelona Olympics, the point had been
proved: We bad.
</P>
<P>
   Dream Team wore out welcome
</P>
<P>
   But Dream Team II in Toronto in 1994 gave us just
crotch-grabbing and trash-talking, and by the time Dream Team III
hit Atlanta in 1996, the world applauded politely and yawned. They
were exhibitions, and we have seen enough.
</P>
<P>
   Let the NBA go back to the task of repairing its product, which
suffers in personality and quality of play. Let FIBA, the
international basketball federation, fight its political battles
within the Olympic movement in another way.
</P>
<P>
   And let's go back to using these international tournaments as a
test track, a proving ground for young and hungry American talent.
Can't win that way? Check out the U.S. gold medal won last week at
the Goodwill Games by a bunch of college kids against some of the
same national teams that will play here. It was much harder than
any won by a Dream Team but much more satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   For the past three weeks, this bunch has traveled on first-class
flights, stayed at four-star hotels, trained in Monaco and Italy,
dined on crisp Greek salad and fresh shrimp while overlooking the
Aegean, lived a fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll bust their butts trying,'' Rudy T said.
</P>
<P>
   Not a Dream Team, just dreamers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
