<SLUG> BC-POWERBALL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWERBALL IS SAID TO HURT REGULAR STATE LOTTERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Conn., Ohio, Calif., Ariz., La., N.M., Texas,
Del., Ind.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Powerball, the pastime of multimillionaire wannabes, was created
to enable small states to sell tickets for potentially huge lottery
jackpots. But as its prizes and popularity have soared, Powerball
has become a concern to lotteries in some states where sales appear
to be lagging as bettors defect across state lines, lottery
officials in several states said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With longer odds than the individual state lotteries and usually
a larger number of players, Powerball jackpots start higher _ at
$10 million _ and can climb quickly to more than $100 million,
making local jackpots in the tens of millions sound puny by
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   The current Powerball bonanza is at a record $250 million, and
thousands of ticket-hungry dreamers from the New York region
continued to swarm Tuesday across the border into Connecticut, one
of 20 states where Powerball tickets are sold. The pilgrimage was
repeated across the country: from California into Arizona, from
Texas into Louisiana or New Mexico, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   While some lines to purchase Powerball tickets have stretched
for hours in Delaware and Indiana, lottery officials in New Jersey
and Ohio said there had been a recent slump in their states' ticket
sales. This, despite the fact that New Jersey's Pick-6 jackpot was
more than $21 million on Tuesday and that Ohio's Super Lotto
jackpot is $20 million for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a $21 million jackpot last night and sales were down
about 10 percent compared to the same jackpot in November,'' said
Holly Behr, a spokeswoman for the New Jersey Lottery Commission.
``We believe some of that decrease is probably due to Powerball.''
New Jersey, which previously declined to join Powerball, is now
rethinking that decision, Ms. Behr said.
</P>
<P>
   Any state can join the game, said Charles Strutt, the executive
director of the Multi-State Lottery Association, which runs
Powerball. ``Pretty much they say, `Hey, we'd like to join.' We
say, `OK' It's a simple process,'' he said. ``I frankly don't
understand why more states don't join. I think they just don't
understand the benefits of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   For ever $1 Powerball ticket, the state where it is sold keeps
50 cents, Strutt said, and the other 50 cents pays the prizes.
Because Powerball is run from the association's offices in West Des
Moines, Iowa, the states also save money by sharing operating
costs. Tickets are printed on the same machines used for local
lottery games and some states also pool resources for Powerball
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   But many larger states, including New York and New Jersey,
declined to join Powerball, confident that they could sell enough
of their own state lottery tickets. In lotto lingo, a multistate
game like Powerball gives states with small populations access to
the kind of ``large player base'' that allows bigger states to
generate multi-million dollar jackpots on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have had to create what we already have,'' said Stephen
Dolan, a spokesman for New York state Lotto. ``This week is an
exception. But you know a month from now, if you check the
Powerball and you check the New York Lotto jackpots, we're able to
do just as well. We're able to offer just New Yorkers what these
states had to band together in order to produce.''
</P>
<P>
   New York state lottery officials had been concerned about the
impact of Powerball, Dolan said, and had been carefully monitoring
ticket sales. So far, however, they have detected little change in
the numbers. The New York Lotto jackpot this week is $40 million
and so far sales have remained strong, Dolan said.
</P>
<P>
   New York officials scrutinized sales for last week's $25 million
jackpot when the Powerball jackpot was $185 million, he said, and
concluded there had been no decline. ``It was surprising to us as
well because we know about all of the cross-border traffic,'' Dolan
said. ``All the publicity and the hype surrounding Powerball is
stimulating demand for all lottery products.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is not happening this week in Connecticut. Missy
Simard, a spokeswoman for the Connecticut Lottery Corp., said sales
for the state's other games were down this week, although overall
sales were up. ``People are pumping so much into Powerball,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
