<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-OUTLOOK-NYT &LR;      07-28 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: WHAT'S GOOD FOR GENERAL MOTORS? BETTER LABOR RELATIONS
WOULD HELP 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related GM-STRIKE, GM-WORKERS) 
(HLW) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ Like estranged spouses who reluctantly realize
they have little choice but to live together again, the General
Motors Corp. and the United Automobile Workers union have ended
their quarrel here but remain trapped in a tattered relationship.
</P>
<P>
   GM factories are generally the least efficient in the industry,
partly because labor and management so deeply distrust each other.
The factories tend to have the least flexible work rules of the Big
Three auto makers, forbidding assembly line workers, for example,
from performing other tasks when the line stops. Workers fear there
would be unreasonable demands from foremen if the work rules did
not exist.
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing element of the settlement today is a
provision calling for the leaders of the two sides to meet
periodically to discuss their differences. In a sign of how poorly
GM and the UAW get along, this was hailed as an important
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps one of the very good things that might come out of
what has been a very difficult and very intractable situation,''
said Gerald A. Knechtel, GM vice president for North American
personnel, ``is a constructive focus by both of us to work very
hard to avoid these kinds of situations in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, though, that company and union leaders have been
quietly meeting for a long time _ and have nothing more to show for
it than 16 factory-level strikes over the last five years. Indeed,
in separate news conferences, each side's top negotiators first
mentioned the plans for future meetings but within minutes were
questioning the other's trustworthiness and ability to keep
promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good way to start building that trust level is to start
keeping commitments,'' said Stephen P. Yokich, president of the
UAW.
</P>
<P>
   GM's strategy in the strikes at two factories here in Flint also
seems like the least likely approach to produce a lasting
improvement in the relationship. The company put a weekly recorded
message on a toll-free number, called by many UAW workers, that
strongly criticized the competence of union leaders. GM also sued
the union for the first time since 1937 and insisted on binding
arbitration of a claim that the union could not strike over
investment issues, yet the final settlement today dealt with some
of the same factory investment disputes that GM had said it would
not discuss.
</P>
<P>
   A senior UAW negotiator, who insisted on anonymity, said on
Tuesday night: ``The only way GM will change is if the players
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Making GM factories more efficient is critical if the company is
to address its main problem, a long slide in market share, from 50
percent in the 1970s to 31 percent now. Each lost percentage point
means about $3 billion in lost sales, several hundred million
dollars in lost profits and about 6,000 more factory workers GM no
longer needs.
</P>
<P>
   In private, the two sides seldom have had anything good to say
about each other. GM officials accuse the union of dogmatically
defending even the most outdated practices, like a work rule that
has allowed some auto parts workers here to collect a full day's
pay for a half day's work. Union officials accuse GM of repeatedly
breaking promises to protect jobs and invest more money in new
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The accord on Tuesday did not affect staffing and investment
disputes at any factories other than the two struck factories and
three others here and in Ohio and Indiana where there were strike
threats. The only way to address the company's broad problems is
through its three-year national agreement with the union, which
next comes up for renewal in September 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW is so unhappy with GM that some local leaders were
planning even before the settlement on Tuesday to start urging
members this fall to begin saving for a strike during contract
talks next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll be real tough _ as soon as this is over, the UAW
members of GM need to start preparing,'' said Joseph Lovvorn, the
chairman of a 3,000-member local union unit that makes parts in
Athens, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Labor relations are not always this bad in the auto industry.
The Chrysler Corp. has had only a few strikes over the last decade,
and the Ford Motor Co. has not had one since 1986. Ford views its
cordial relations with the union as a competitive advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW cooperated last year with Ford in the closing of an
unprofitable car factory in Lorain, Ohio. Ford transferred 1,000
Lorain workers to a highly profitable factory in Louisville, Ky.,
agreeing to pay them $45,000 each to move. It cost $45 million but
avoided a costly strike.
</P>
<P>
   Closing factories is always expensive for Detroit auto makers
because their contracts with the UAW require that workers continue
to draw 95 percent of their pay even when idled. Workers also have
the right to turn down transfers to other factories more than 50
miles away. Because of strike threats by the UAW, GM has had a
harder time than its rivals in trying to close factories and move
workers; indeed, even as GM executives have been talking lately
about closing more factories, they still have not followed through
on plans announced in 1992 to close some particularly unprofitable
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Chrysler both entrust labor relations to top executives
who report directly to the chief executive officer, while General
Motors' top labor executive is buried three layers lower in the
management of the world's largest auto maker. Partly because of
close relations between Ford executives and union leaders, the
union negotiated national agreements first with Ford in 1993 and
1996 and then demanded that GM and Chrysler accept the same
pattern. Ford has used both opportunities to put GM at a
disadvantage, by negotiating lower wages for newly hired workers at
a time when Ford is hiring thousands of workers and GM is hiring
almost none.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Chrysler also make a point of removing factory managers
who cannot get along with workers, while GM tends to transfer them.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with dozens of auto workers around the nation, a
consistent theme is that GM allows less worker involvement in how
its factories are run than do Ford and Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
   Nihla M. Hall is married to a striking GM worker here and has a
brother who works for Ford and a daughter who works for Chrysler.
The consensus in the family, she said, is that Ford and Chrysler
``treat their people a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers on the picket line understand the long-term problem and
many wish their union and GM could get along better. ``A separation
like this gives you a lot of time to think,'' said Geno Gomez, an
assembly line worker who toted a green strike placard on Sunday in
front of a struck auto body parts factory here. ``GM and the UAW
are going to have to get their marriage back on track and run their
house together.''
</P>
<P>
   Some labor experts have suggested that GM try to break the UAW
someday, using replacement workers. But that would be extremely
difficult, given that GM has 200,000 workers at more than 100
factories. The strikes here have shown that closing even a couple
of factories can cripple production across North America.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at rival auto makers believe the deal announced today
will make no difference to GM's competitiveness because its
relationship with workers and the union remain so poisoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think,'' said a top executive from another auto maker
who insisted on anonymity, ``it'll change a thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
