<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7133 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIEWPOINTS-DANCE-ART-     07-28 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIEWPOINTS-DANCE-ART-$ADV02-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPENSING WITH DOGMA IN THE EDUCATION OF ACTORS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Ky., N.Y., Mass., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2) 
(Rachel Shteir is working on a book, ``Striptease: Grit, Glamour
and the Grind'')  
 (af) 
By RACHEL SHTEIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the first Viewpoints conference, held earlier this year at
New York University, about two dozen young actors jogged onto a
tiny stage. ``Go!'' ordered the instructor, Barney O'Hanlon, who
was teaching a specific Viewpoints technique.
</P>
<P>
   The actors formed a line and paired off, lunging toward each
other like cartoon city dwellers about to collide. ``Stop!''
O'Hanlon yelled. The pairs of actors paused, noses inches away.
Each pair then quickly turned a near-collision into a confrontation
imagined out of daily life: a man made a woman drop her groceries;
two long-lost friends met; in a schoolyard, a bully hovered
menacingly over a nerd.
</P>
<P>
   Invented in the 1970s by two dance choreographers, Mary Overlie
and Wendell Beavers, Viewpoints has recently become part of the
contentious debate currently going on in America about actor
training.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Konstantin Stanislavsky's Moscow Art Theater visited
the United States in 1923, actor training in this country has
focused mainly on naturalism on the stage. The most extreme form _
and the most influential _ has been the Method, Lee Strasberg's
idiosyncratic interpretation of Stanislavsky's theories emphasizing
psychological realism.
</P>
<P>
   But by the 1960s, theater artists who felt constrained by the
Method were searching for non-naturalistic ways to approach acting.
</P>
<P>
   Inspiration has come from many directions. Television and film
acting breaks down continuity into staccato moments on camera. The
stylized traditions of Japanese and Indonesian theater, for
example, have allowed performers to explore the use of puppetry and
masks.
</P>
<P>
   Artists like the director and designer Julie Taymor, who employ
a variety of ethnic theatrical styles, have helped popularize
non-Western movement and performance techniques. The American
director Robert Wilson's works, in which movement and sometimes
fragmented text are slowed or speeded up, have influenced a
generation of performers. And the self-conscious ironies of gay
theater have long since entered the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that in the last few years, naturalism has
sometimes seemed unequal to the task of portraying characters on
stage. And there is renewed interest now in discovering ways to
train actors that go beyond the Method.
</P>
<P>
   Some people in the theater believe the itch to explore is a
reaction to the longtime dominance of the intense, psychologically
based style preached by Strasberg, who died in 1982. Others argue
that these alternative theories merely reinterpret the Method for a
new generation.
</P>
<P>
   Viewpoints is worlds away from the self-referential style that
Strasberg expounded. Focusing on formal elements, like movement and
space, Viewpoints is both a compositional tool and a series of
actor exercises. Its most recognizable style comes from what its
advocates call ``sampling.''
</P>
<P>
   In this context, the word, borrowed from computerized digital
technology and used by rap music, means the free juggling of
incongruous dramatic techniques, arcane literary sources, news
articles _ almost any artifact from the culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a post-modern way to train actors,'' said Anne Bogart,
the director who has used Viewpoints in work as diverse as Bertolt
Brecht's ``Baal,'' Rodgers and Hammerstein's ``South Pacific'' and
Tennessee Williams' ``Streetcar Named Desire.'' In ``Streetcar,''
Ms. Bogart cast 8 Stanleys and 12 Blanches _ one of whom was a man.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Culture of Desire,'' another theatrical collage, this time
about Andy Warhol, Ms. Bogart stitches together words and texts
from Warhol interviews and writings, Dante's ``Inferno'' and French
literary theory. The production begins previews on Aug. 28 at New
York Theater Workshop in the East Village.
</P>
<P>
   Many directors maintain that Viewpoints is a long-overdue
correction to what they call the American theater's indifference to
staging. ``Historically, where you stand on stage has generally
been related to where you're going to fix the highball,'' said Jon
Jory, the artistic director of the Actors Theater of Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in part because of its emphasis on movement, Viewpoints
is creating excitement. Last year, when New York University was
planning the first Viewpoints conference, about 80 people were
expected. A month before the conference was to begin, registration
had soared to 400.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, theories like Viewpoints are gaining
currency as actors demand a variety of approaches. The biggest bete
noir seems to be that of sticking too rigidly to any one theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whereas 10 years ago, students wanted to learn one method,''
said Michael Kahn, the director of the drama division at the
Juilliard School, ``today there is no gospel.''
</P>
<P>
   True, there have always been iconoclastic acting teachers. In a
class at the H.B. Studio in Greenwich Village, Uta Hagen watched
her toy poodle lick a morsel of brie from her fingers as she
emphasized that she has never been in the service of any one
theory. ``The point is to bring a human being on stage _ electric,
alive, human,'' declared the actress who played Ophelia in Eva Le
Gallienne's ``Hamlet'' in 1937.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hagen's point of view seems increasingly popular as teachers
of acting agree that more options are better.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long time coming. In the 1940s, Strasberg
developed the Method at the famously exclusive Actors Studio _ a
kind of members-only club that emerged from the ashes of the Group
Theater, the revered Depression-era rep company.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1940s and 50s, the heyday of stage naturalism and
playwrights like Arthur Miller and Tennessee Williams, the Method
pushed actors to exploit their inner lives as material for the
characters they played, and it inspired a lot of grittily dazzling
theater and film. Perhaps it was no accident that audiences were
becoming interested in Freud's theories at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   But there were complaints that the Method ignored Shakespeare
and movement and too often collapsed into tic-filled performances
that were more appropriate to an analyst's couch than the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was terrible _ a tyranny,'' said Robert Brustein, the
artistic director of the American Repertory Theater in Cambridge,
Mass., and a longtime critic of the Method. Brustein even wrote a
play, recently produced at ART, excoriating Strasberg.
</P>
<P>
   Acting programs today are reflecting the changes that are under
way in the profession. Until recently, training had been split into
two static categories.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatory and university programs offer regular classes and
semesters that can take two or three years and cost up to $100,000;
graduation means a degree and a union card.
</P>
<P>
   Private studios, on the other hand, for about $5,000 a year,
provide a narrower range of courses, but appeal because the
teachers are often living links _ however distant _ to the hallowed
Group Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Today, American conservatories and studios alike are trying to
create new theatrical languages, said Jory in Louisville, who
characterized the time as ``the most exciting period in acting in
35 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Given all of this activity, what is an actor to do?
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Dundas-Lowe, who received good reviews last season in
New York in the nihilistic English comedy ``Shopping and ...'' by
Mark Ravenhill, is pragmatic. ``It's really about anything that
works,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry Jones, a Tony Award winner who starred in Tina Howe's
play ``Pride's Crossing'' last season at Lincoln Center, emphasized
the importance of working with actors from many backgrounds. ``I
learn from my peers more than from any one technique,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As more actors seek a variety of influences, the Method may well
become less central to American acting. In fact, two of the most
popular new approaches to actor training _ Viewpoints and a
technique created by the playwright David Mamet known as Practical
Esthetics _ are cool frontal attacks on Strasberg's concepts.
</P>
<P>
   Mamet himself is so opposed to actor training that in his book
for performers published last year, ``True and False: Heresy and
Common Sense for the Actor,'' he called such training ``nonsense''
and those who teach it ``charlatans.'' Mamet declined to be
interviewed for this article.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright's dislike of actor training programs may be
extreme. However, there is no doubt that actor training in America
has changed because the theater has also. Opportunities to polish
skills in repertory are dwindling. At the same time, tuition costs
of MFA programs are spiraling.
</P>
<P>
   The director JoAnne Akalaitis, who teaches at the Juilliard
School, complains that by the time acting students graduate, ``they
are saddled with enormous debt and have to do boring television
work.''
</P>
<P>
   In the opinion of Melissa Smith, director of the actor training
program at the American Conservatory Theater in San Francisco, such
problems are also forcing acting programs to become more flexible.
``People who are going to work in film, television and theater are
looking for a range of ideas about training,'' she said. ``After
all, the Group is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, the Moscow Art Theater, which inspired the
formation of the Group Theater during its 1923 visit to New York,
celebrated its 100th anniversary with the troupe's first trip to
the United States since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   One stop was the Actors Studio, where Studio members and Moscow
Art Theater representatives held a summit on the future of acting.
The actresses Lee Grant and Estelle Parsons, now artistic director
of the Studio; the director Arthur Penn, its president, and Anatoly
Smeliansky, the literary manager of the Moscow Art Theater, agreed
that Stanislavsky's tradition has lived on in America through
teaching.
</P>
<P>
   After the Group Theater fell apart in the late 1930s, its
members began to teach. And as the last of these masters die _
Sanford Meisner and Robert Lewis both last year _ Ms. Parsons
worries that the Group's ideas will vanish. ``That's the problem in
the American theater _ we don't record the way we train actors, so
we can't reproduce it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some studios tried to solve that problem by relying on
theatrical dynasties. In the late 1960's, Strasberg set up the
Strasberg Institute as a two-year training program where he could
disseminate on a more regular basis what he taught informally at
the Actors Studio. After his death, his third wife, the actress
Anna Strasberg, took over.
</P>
<P>
   ``People from around the world want to come to hear what Lee had
to say,'' said Mrs. Strasberg, who teaches a class in directing at
the institute. ``Why change what we do?''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But other studios are leaving the old acting gurus behind. Since
the death in 1992 of Stella Adler, a former Group member, the
studio she founded in 1949 has broadened its focus. ``We're hiring
teachers who never trained with Stella,'' said Tom Oppenheim,
Adler's grandson and the studio's artistic director.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar way, the financially ailing Actors Studio is
throwing open its doors. Four years ago, it joined forces with the
New School for Social Research to create a three-year MFA program.
The idea, said Penn, was to give the Studio a regular income while
providing a place to teach for its members, who are scattered all
over the country.
</P>
<P>
   Those associated with the program stress that the Studio is just
part of the picture. ``We teach Stanislavsky's legacy,'' said Sam
Schacht, the director of acting. Penn said the program has gone to
considerable lengths to address complaints about Strasberg's
limitations, adding classes in movement, voice, text analysis and
theatrical styles.
</P>
<P>
   But some who believe the Method has had more influence than it
should on American acting have sought alternatives. ``In general,
American actor training has put too much focus on emotional
authenticity,'' said the playwright Tony Kushner, about the
Method's emphasis on emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, after spending a year at the Neighborhood
Playhouse studying with Sanford Meisner, David Mamet began to teach
a method of acting at New York University with the actor William H.
Macy that they called Practical Esthetics. They wanted a place
where they could teach without the kind of mystery that has
surrounded the Method, Macy said.
</P>
<P>
   Out of these classes grew the Atlantic Theater Company School,
which offered part-time instruction until 1996, when a two-year
program was established several blocks west of where the company
performs in the Chelsea neighborhood of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way that Mamet boils down American naturalistic
dramaturgy to spare, tough-guy talk, so Practical Esthetics
condenses naturalistic acting into a blunter, street-wise style in
which emotion itself seems excessive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to not feel the lines, you have to just say
them,'' said Scott Zigler, who directed ``The Old Neighborhood,''
Mamet's recent, critically well-received play on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Although the author has subsequently distanced himself from his
own acting technique by attacking actor training in general, the
faculty at the Atlantic Theater Company School remains faithful to
his original vision: the actor's job on stage is to concern himself
with the action of the character, not to become the character.
Practical Esthetics, whose alumni include Felicity Huffman, Kristen
Johnston and Macy, is highly popular among young actors.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCann, who played Deeny, a stoic Mametian heroine in ``The
Old Neighborhood,'' and who teaches acting at the school, said that
Practical Esthetics does not lend itself to categorizing. ``It's
just about good acting,'' she said. But others argue that actors
trained in the theory have a very specific look on stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's confrontational,'' said Jory, likening it to ``lawyers in
a criminal case pursuing the witness.'' Indeed, some critics argue
that Practical Esthetics works best on the tightly wound dialogues
in Mamet's plays.
</P>
<P>
   According to Brustein, whose ART in Cambridge originally
produced ``The Old Neighborhood'': ``David doesn't believe in
characterization or interpretation. His approach is basically,
`Read my lines.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At the NYU conference on Viewpoints, the issue of what it is
exactly arose again and again, with anxious panelists arguing that
it is a method, a compositional tool or an approach to actor
training. Heated disagreements erupted over whether it could work
with classical theatrical texts. There was even debate on how many
Viewpoints exist (some said 12; others 9; still another faction
said 6).
</P>
<P>
   It was, recalled Una Chaudhuri, the chairwoman of the NYU
undergraduate drama department, which sponsored the conference,
strangely reminiscent of the quarrelsome debates that erupted over
the Method in the middle of this century.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Viewpoints is taught widely at universities around the
country, as well as at the Saratoga International Theater Institute
(SITI) _ the actor-training program that Ms. Bogart founded five
years ago with the Japanese director Tadashi Suzuki.
</P>
<P>
   Some theater critics are skeptical of its results. In a 1995
review of ``Small Lives/Big Dreams,'' Ms. Bogart's adaptation of
five Chekhov plays, Ben Brantley wrote in The New York Times: ``The
approach is, finally, reductionist, turning all dialogue into a
homogenized series of epitaphs for an age.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Ms. Bogart believes that Viewpoints is an ideal
tool for creating theatrical irony, which, in terms of describing
contemporary life, gives it an edge that psychologically based
training lacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are living in a fragmented world and so our actor training
has to be fragmented,'' Ms. Bogart says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
