<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7150 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GTE-BELL-ATLANTIC-600     07-28 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GTE-BELL-ATLANTIC-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC, GTE AGREE TO MERGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Corp., the nation's largest local phone company,
announced its $52.9 billion acquisition of GTE Corp. Tuesday, but
critical questions began to mount about its structure and
significance to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   A major theme coming from the companies Tuesday was that the
deal would be a true merger of equals, despite its financial setup
as Bell Atlantic's acquisition of GTE.
</P>
<P>
   That is a fairly standard thing for companies in takeovers to
say, but in the case of Bell Atlantic and GTE the facts actually do
appear to support the assertion.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bell Atlantic's shareholders would own most of the
combined carrier, each company would appoint an equal number of
directors. Ivan Seidenberg, who is scheduled to be promoted from
chief executive of Bell Atlantic to chairman on Jan. 1, agreed to
wait until 2004 to become chairman of the combined company.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Charles Lee, GTE's chairman, would hold the top job.
Seidenberg would share the post of chief executive with Lee until
2002, when Seidenberg would take over the entire job.
</P>
<P>
   Reinforcing the concept of a merger of equals, GTE agreed that
its shareholders would not receive a premium for their stock.
</P>
<P>
   The companies agreed that GTE's shareholders would receive 1.22
shares of Bell Atlantic for each GTE share. Based on Bell
Atlantic's closing share price Monday of $45, that made the deal
worth $54.90 for each share of GTE.
</P>
<P>
   GTE's shares closed Monday at $55.75.
</P>
<P>
   The companies pointed out that the ratio of 1.22 accurately
reflected the comparative valuation that the market had placed on
the two companies. As part of their negotiations the companies
produced a chart showing that over the year ended July 17, GTE's
shares traded at an average price 1.19 times that of Bell
Atlantic's. Over the final month of that period the ratio was 1.22.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic would also assume GTE's debt of about $18 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said shareholders of both companies would realize
a premium as the combined entity accelerated its growth of revenue
and earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, the Northeast's dominant local phone company, has
been itching to get into the markets for long-distance calling and
advanced data services, where GTE is growing quickly. GTE has
wanted to expand geographically beyond its local telephone base,
which is highly rural.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that Bell Atlantic had challenges, and
the biggest challenge was our revenue growth,'' Seidenberg said
Tuesday in a joint interview with Lee at Bell Atlantic's New York
City headquarters. (Last year Bell Atlantic posted a 3.6 percent
gain in revenue over 1996, while GTE's sales grew by 9 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   ``What you do in this transaction is address the No. 1 issue
that we have in terms of accelerating the growth of our company,''
Seidenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said: ``Our biggest challenge was to get a big urban center
that served Fortune 500 companies. There is no company better in
the world to do that than Bell Atlantic.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies said the deal would allow them to save $2 billion
in annual costs and generate an additional $2 billion in annual
revenue within three years. That would help the combined company,
which would take a new name that has not been determined, to
consistently increase its annual per-share earnings by 15 percent
after three years, Lee and Seidenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street was not happy with the deal, with many analysts
and investors saying GTE's shareholders deserved a premium.
</P>
<P>
   GTE's shares fell $2.6875, to $53.625, on the New York Stock
Exchange while Bell Atlantic's shares lost 68.75 cents, closing at
$44.3125.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Eric Strumingher, a telecommunications analyst at Paine Webber,
said he had upgraded his recommendation for GTE stock to a buy, but
that did not mean he was thrilled with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``GTE gives its equity away at a discount and the larger
company, Bell Atlantic, can't even keep management control in order
to do it,'' he said. ``It's not a beautiful deal for that reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Mahoney, manager of the AIM Global Telecommunications
Fund, which owns 675,000 shares of GTE and 350,000 shares of Bell
Atlantic, said, ``I think Bell Atlantic is getting a steal on
this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The cynic in me says that it's because Chuck Lee wanted to
preserve his job as chairman,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee denied that, but the perception that his job was a key part
of the negotiations was widespread on Wall Street. In fact, people
close to the negotiations said GTE had been approached about a
possible merger by BellSouth Corp., and that one reason that deal
did not happen was that Lee and F. Duane Ackerman, BellSouth's
chairman, disagreed on who would run the company.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth was also approached about a possible merger by SBC
Communications Inc., but similar issues arose between Ackerman and
Edward Whitacre Jr., SBC's chairman, according to people close to
the talks. SBC ended up agreeing to acquire Ameritech Corp. earlier
this year for $62 billion after Richard Notebaert, Ameritech's
chairman, agreed to cede authority to Whitacre.
</P>
<P>
   The low price for GTE's shares fueled speculation that an
unsolicited bidder for GTE, perhaps BellSouth, could emerge. To
help thwart that possibility, Bell Atlantic and GTE agreed on a
breakup fee of around $1.85 billion and exchanged options to buy 10
percent of each other's outstanding stock at pre-deal prices.
</P>
<P>
   The exercise of the options would dilute the shares of any other
company that tried to bid for GTE and could scuttle another
company's ability to use the pooling of interests method of merger
accounting. Pooling allows an acquirer to avoid taking charges
against future earnings to cover the difference between what it
pays and the acquired company's assessed value.
</P>
<P>
   Washington politicians also expressed wariness, fearing that the
Telecommunications Act of 1996 had not produced the broad
competition that its backers promised.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate antitrust subcommittee's ranking Democrat, Sen. Herb
Kohl of Wisconsin, said that since the act became law, ``we have
had lots of consolidation but not a whole lot of competition. If
this trend continues unabated, you can be sure that next year
Congress will consider cracking open the Telecom Act like a raw egg
_ that is, if the Telecom Act still matters.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
