<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 7/28/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- July 28, 1998 -- RAP-PRODUCER, 7-28 -- Chris
Schwartz, rap music producer and high school dropout. Schwartz, 37,
is certainly doing something right. Operating out of Conshohocken,
Pa., Ruffhouse Records, which he and his partner, Joe Nicolo,
founded nine years ago with $400, has been home to some of the
biggest names in hip-hop: Kriss Kross, Cypress Hill, and the
Fugees. The Fugees' ``The Score,'' with sales of 17 million copies,
is the all-time best-selling album by a rap group. Schwartz is now
a millionaire. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) GREENWICH, Conn. -- July 28, 1998 -- POWERBALL, 7-28 --
Ticket-hungry New Yorkers swell the line of people outside the ZYM
Stationery Store in Greenwich on Tuesday to buy Powerball tickets.
The current Powerball bonanza is at a record $250 million. (Chester
Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- July 28, 1998 -- CAPITOL-SHOOTING-3, 7-28
-- Police officers from across the United States are among those
paying tribute Tuesday in the Capitol Rotunda to Officer Jacob
Chestnut and Detective John Gibson of the Capitol Police. ``The
spirit of freedom is in this room because of these two men,'' says
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott. Clinton, Lott, House Speaker
Newt Gingrich and Capitol Police Chief Gary Abrecht reverently laid
large floral wreaths at the flag-draped coffins of Jacob Chestnut
and John Gibson. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- July 28, 1998 -- SCHOLARSHIPS-EDUC, 7-28 --
Sparlha Swaby, center, whose financial aid at Stanford University
was cut because of outside scholarships, meets recently with
Michael Mallory of the Ron Brown Scholars program and Brown's
widow, Alma. ``I was just really, really angry,'' says Ms. Swaby, a
normally upbeat 18-year-old from Oyster Bay, N.Y., who will enter
her sophomore year at Stanford in the fall. ``I thought I would get
the excess money. That's the reason I put in so much work trying to
get scholarships my senior year in high school.'' (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SHORT HILL, N.J. -- July 28, 1998 -- PRICE-MARKETPLACE,
7-28 -- Franklin Mutual Series Fund manager Michael Price outside
his offices in Short Hills. Price announced Tuesday that he would
step down as chief executive of the group, effective Nov. 1. In his
place, he split his executive and portfolio management roles at the
fund group between two longtime aides - Robert Friedman, who was
named chief investment officer, and Peter Langerman, currently
chief operating officer, who will take over as chief executive.
(Jonathan Levine/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LOS ANGELES -- July 28, 1998 -- DEMS-CONVENTION, 7-28 --
Los Angeles wants the Democratic Party's national convention in
2000 in the City of Angels, and Krista Miller performs at a
breakfast Tuesday for members of the party's site-selection
committee. Winning a national political convention for the first
time since John Kennedy was nominated here in 1960 would amount to
a kind of massive international coming-out party for a city that
has largely rebounded from the economic, natural and social
disasters of the early '90s. (Jill Connelly/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) STURGEON BAY, Wis. -- July 28, 1998 --
LITTLELEAGUE-RAGE, 7-28 -- After umpire Clayton Haen had refused to
call a balk in a Little League game, he was punched squarely in the
face by Thomas Torstenson, the father of one of the players. ``You
can't call it if you don't see it,'' says Haen. ``Besides, this is
Little League!'' If Torstenson, a 46-year-old carpenter, is
convicted of substantial battery, a felony, he could serve up to
two years in prison. (Jeffrey Davis/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEWTON, Mass. -- July 28, 1998 -- TAINTED-BLOOD-II-BOS,
7-28 -- Liz Kaplan should not be alive. As an infant she developed
a rare cancerous tumor within her pelvis. She survived surgery,
chemotherapy, and more surgery only to discover in 1985 that she
had been transfused with HIV-infected blood. Twenty-five patients
received the same blood, and today all but two of them are dead.
``I feel very sad that they all died,'' she says. ``It's very
strange to feel I am connected to all these dead babies, but I am.
So maybe part of them is in me.'' (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WESTPORT, Mass. -- July 28, 1998 -- TAINTED-BLOOD-I-BOS,
7-28 -- Liza Davis and James Blackledge stand in the dunes of
Horseneck Beach. Blackledge's son Matthew, who died of HIV tainted
blood transfusion, spent many happy hours on the beach. By the time
doctors discovered that the blood was tainted, 15 patients had
become infected and were already dead. A lawsuit filed in 1988 on
behalf of Matthew generated a $500,000 settlement from Boston's
Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, where the blood originated. ``It was
horrifying,'' Blackledge says. ``You realize you cannot save your
kid.'' (Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- July 28, 1998 -- CLINTON-STARR, 7-28 --
Monica Lewinsky's attorneys, from left, Plato Cacheris, Nathaniel
Speights and Billy Martin (attorney for Monica's mother, Marcia
Lewis) meet reporters outside Cacheris' Washington office Tuesday.
The former White House intern was granted total immunity in return
for her complete testimony in the sex-and-perjury probe targetting
President Clinton. ``We as counsel for Monica Lewinsky have reached
an agreement today that for her full and truthful testimony she
will receive transactional immunity in this case,'' says Cacheris.
(Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- July 28, 1998 -- CAPITOL-SHOOTING-2, 7-28
-- Evelyn Gibson, widow of slain Capitol Police officer John
Gibson, holds her daughter Kristen's hand during the tribute to
Gibson and Jacob Chestnut at the Rotunda on Tuesday. In exceptional
homage, President Clinton and congressional leaders paid tribute
today at the caskets of the two officers slain defending the
historic building they were sworn to protect. (Justin Lane/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- July 28, 1998 -- CAPITOL-SHOOTING-1, 7-28
-- In exceptional homage, President Clinton and congressional
leaders paid tribute Tuesday in the stately Rotunda at the caskets
of the two Capitol Police officers slain defending the historic
building they were sworn to protect. ``The spirit of freedom is in
this room because of these two men,'' says Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott. Clinton, Lott, House Speaker Newt Gingrich and Capitol
Police Chief Gary Abrecht reverently laid large floral wreaths at
the flag-draped coffins of Jacob Chestnut and John Gibson. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- July 28, 1998 -- HERMAN-THEATER-REVIEW, 7-28
-- Jerry Herman, left, with his friends Lee Roy Reams and Florence
Lacey in the show ``An Evening With Jerry Herman'' at the Booth
Theater. Herman spends an amiable couple of hours savoring his hits
and mourning his flops. The production is not unlike those
award-show tributes - including the mock-ups of the marquees from
the old shows floating down from the ceiling - except in this case,
the honoree is the host of his own party. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- July 28, 1998 -- WHITNEY-DIRECTOR, 7-28 --
After a three-month search for a new director, the Whitney Museum
of American Art has appointed Maxwell Anderson, 42. Anderson, who
has spent three years as director of the Art Gallery of Ontario,
succeeds David Ross, who resigned in March to become director of
the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- July 27, 1998 -- SWEEPSTAKES-ELDERLY-I-3, 7-27
-- Millions of offers of sweepstakes are sent through the mail each
year, with the envelopes usually designed to create the impression
that the recipient is, if not already a winner, then a finalist.
(New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- July 28, 1998 -- MCCOURT-BOOK-2-B&AMP;W, 7-28 --
Brothers Frank, left, and Malachy McCourt performing at the Village
Gate in 1984. ``I had a murderous rage in my heart of Limerick, the
humiliation of coming out of the slums,'' Malachy says of his
hometown in Ireland, the setting of his brother Frank McCourt's
Pulitzer Prize-winning memoir, ``Angela's Ashes.'' But these are
good days for Malachy, 66, whose own memoir, ``A Monk Swimming,''
has spent six weeks on the New York Times best-seller list. (Keith
Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- July 28, 1998 -- MCCOURT-BOOK-1, 7-28 -- ``I
had a murderous rage in my heart of Limerick, the humiliation of
coming out of the slums,'' Malachy McCourt says of his hometown in
Ireland, the setting of his brother Frank McCourt's Pulitzer
Prize-winning memoir, ``Angela's Ashes.'' But these are good days
for Malachy, 66, whose own memoir, ``A Monk Swimming,'' has spent
six weeks on the New York Times best-seller list. ``They say what I
did was ego-driven and name-dropping,'' he says. ``Damn right it
is. Who am I going to write about? People I didn't meet?'' (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- July 28, 1998 -- PLANTAINS-2, 7-28 --
Plantain chips, fu fu and salsa, a traditional dish, is among the
plantain specialties prepared by Douglas Rodriguez at Manhattan's
Patria. Growing up in Miami, the son of Cuban immigrants, Rodriguez
cannot remember a family meal without plantains. ``If my father
didn't have rice and plantains with dinner,'' he says, ``it
wouldn't be dinner.'' (Boyd Hagen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- July 28, 1998 -- PLANTAINS-1, 7-28 -- The
plantain, a tropical fruit related to the banana and of near
miraculous variability, is spilling over from bodegas and flooding
into supermarkets and restaurants. Plantains are green when picked,
turn yellow and then brown. (Boyd Hagen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- July 28, 1998 -- WINE-TALK, 7-28
-- Standing in their restaurant's wine cellar, John Foy, right, the
owner of the Sonoma Grill, and Buddy Gebhardt, the owner of the
Park and Orchard hold bottles that appear on their well-chosen wine
lists at reasonable prices. Gebhardt, who is a hopeless Burgundy
addict, once he added $200,000 worth of new Burgundies every year.
Foy's interest in wine extends to his own newsletter, John Foy's
Wine Odyssey, and to a weekly wine column in The Bergen Record.
(Frank C. Dougherty/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- July 28, 1998 -- BERRIES, 7-28 --
Gooseberries, top, and strawberries, are just two kinds of berries
available during July and August. With so many ripe and delicious
varieties of berries peaking, its a great time for those who love
mixed a berry desserts. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. -- July 27, 1998 -- GLF-PAK, 7-27 --
Se Ri-pak, left, walks with her father, Joon Chul, through the
press center at the JAL Big Apple Classic tournament earlier this
year. Se Ri, a 20-year-old rookie on the Ladies Professional Golf
Association Tour, has become a star on the world stage. Last Sunday
she won her fourth victory of the season and third in the last four
weeks, giving her a tour-best $768,211 in earnings. (Chang W.
Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
