<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7170 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-WORKERS-NYT &LR;      07-28 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-WORKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST WORKERS EMBRACE GM SETTLEMENT, BUT MANY WORRY ABOUT THE
FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related GM-STRIKE, GM-OUTLOOK) 
(HLW) 
 By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ Along the road leading into the sprawling General
Motors metal fabricating plant here, where the first of two strikes
that eventually paralyzed the company began on June 5, picketing
workers embraced news of a tentative agreement with shouts, tears
and a few two-step dance moves.
</P>
<P>
   It was a moment hoped for so long that striking workers outside
the plant, and a nearby parts plant, sought to savor it by
extending their normal two-hour picket line rotations.
</P>
<P>
   Workers were joined by their spouses, local business owners,
city and county politicians and others who wanted to be on hand for
the end of ``The Big One,'' as many here referred to the 53-day
dispute, the costliest strike against General Motors in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over!'' Craig Layman shouted as he and other pickets
outside one of the gates of the Delphi East instrument-parts
factory complex received word that an agreement had been reached.
As a part of the tentative agreement, General Motors agreed not to
sell the plant before December 1999 where Layman, 40, has worked
for 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Few battles between General Motors and the union have lasted
longer, been as bitter or wrought as much financial damage as the
walkouts at the metal factory and the Delphi East complex. The two
strikes have cost GM an estimated $2.2 billion in profit, shuttered
27 of its 29 North American assembly plants and put approximately
190,000 employees temporarily out of work.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, some workers said they expected labor relations to
fray even further once the company's national contract with the
United Automobile Workers expired.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, just the mention of those coming negotiations seemed to
temper today's jubilation, for many already think that they will
have to pick up their picket signs once more against General
Motors. Indeed, the company had asked for an agreement barring the
UAW from striking at other troubled factories.
</P>
<P>
   But the union agreed to a no-strike clause only for a factory in
Dayton, Ohio, which the company promised not to sell until at least
January 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little hard to be too excited,'' said Kendall Martin, a
27-year employee at the metal plant. ``I don't think I'll relax
until next year, when we've got a national agreement. ``Then it'll
really be over.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said that one of the first things he intended to do after
he returned to work was to begin putting away ``a few thousand'' to
weather another long strike. ``We're going to have to be back out
here, and next time GM is going to be more prepared to stay out
even longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Roe, 56, also said he believed another battle loomed. For
30 years, he said, he has watched General Motors promise
investments to his union and then turn around and break such
promises. But this time Roe will not be around to see what happens
to the promises made here Tuesday or the outcome of the national
talks. He said he would retire the day after he reported back to
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for the younger workers; they need to get back to
work. But I've been through too much of this,'' he said, standing
outside the metal factory as he and others huddled around a tiny
television set watching the union's news conference. ``General
Motors used to provide a good, easy living. Now it's too much
stress and too much worry. You can't count on a future anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratification votes were scheduled here Wednesday morning, though
both top UAW officials and striking workers like Layman called the
meetings ``a small formality.''
</P>
<P>
   While many of his co-workers had used their time off to complete
projects around the house, golf and spend time with their families,
Layman said he could concentrate on nothing but the escalating
tensions between the company and the union.
</P>
<P>
   When he was not walking the picket line, Layman, and his wife
and two children sat outside the suburban hotel where top
negotiators were meeting, snapping pictures and searching for signs
that progress was being made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd do it all over again if I had to,'' he said on his way to
the hotel one last time, hoping for a chance to personally thank
top UAW leaders. ``What we did was historic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
