<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASSENGER-ARRESTED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Passenger arrested after allegedly becomming abusive
 &HT;    By Lou Grieco
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ What authorities say started with a fondled
breast and a demand for more vodka ended Monday night with an
emergency landing at Dayton International Airport and a Michigan
man in Montgomery County (Ohio) Jail.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Kuchukian, 39, of Royal Oaks, Mich., was arrested after the
landing about 10 p.m. Kuchukian was one of 160 passengers on Spirit
Airlines Flight 632 from Tampa to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and local authorities said no charges were filed Tuesday
against Kuchukian. But airport spokesman John Sears said the FBI
was investigating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right about over Kentucky, the gentleman decided he wanted
additional alcohol,'' Sears said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in two years that a reported unruly
passenger caused an emergency landing in Dayton. Richard Josephson
of Wilmington, Del., pleaded guilty in December to endangering the
safety of an aircraft, by making a false bomb threat. He was
sentenced to six months in prison and forced to pay $40,653 in
restitution.
</P>
<P>
   Unruly passengers are an increasing problem, with 296 reports in
1994 and 921 in 1997, the Federal Aviation Administration told
Congress last month. For the first three months of 1998, there were
258 reports.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchukian wanted more alcohol, but flight attendants had cut
Kuchukian off after he touched the breast of a female passenger
next to him, according to Dayton police. Kuchukian responded by
threatening to turn on his laptop computer, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Use of laptops is barred because they can interfere with
airplanes' instruments and gauges, Sears said.
</P>
<P>
   After the threat, the flight attendants went to the captain, who
left the cockpit to speak to Kuchukian, police said. The laptop was
on, and Kuchukian said he would disrupt the aircraft's
communications. The captain then returned to the cockpit, declared
an emergency landing and contacted Dayton International Airport
authorities, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchukian then tried to force his way past flight attendants to
enter the cockpit, police said.
</P>
<P>
   After the landing, airport police arrested him and took him to
their holding cell. Since he was initially cooperative, they
removed his handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchukian later beat on the cell door, demanding to smoke,
police said. After a warning, police entered the cell to recuff
him, and scuffled with him.
</P>
<P>
   One officer suffered a sprained wrist, Sears said.
</P>
<P>
   After Kuchukian complained of chest pain, he was treated at Good
Samaritan Hospital and Health Center and released, police said. He
was then taken to jail.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Greico writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
