u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROBE-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      07-28 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROBE-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A VULNERABLE CLINTON, FAMILIAR GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton Conundrum was on full display in the
capital Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At one moment lawyers for Monical S. Lewinsky were announcing
that the one-time White House intern was being granted the broadest
form of immunity for her testimony, bringing the investigation that
threatens the president and the presidency one step closer to its
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   A moment later Bill Clinton was in the Capitol Rotunda, at the
symbolic center of American national life, presiding with gravity
and sensitivity at the memorial service for the two Capitol guards
who stood and died for freedom.
</P>
<P>
   And there, during the blink of an hour in one of the most torrid
and tense days of the Clinton presidency, was a vivid portrait of
the unusual, unconventional, and enigmatic role that the 42nd
president of the United States plays in a nation whose politics
more than ever seem like theater.
</P>
<P>
   For President Clinton is at once the most vulnerable and most
indispensable figures in American life.
</P>
<P>
   Few modern presidents _ perhaps John F. Kennedy, perhaps Ronald
W. Reagan _ have so effortlessly spoken for the American people at
times of tragedy and triumph.
</P>
<P>
   And yet few modern presidents _ perhaps only Richard M. Nixon _
have ever had an administration so constantly under attack, so
constantly at the verge of disintegration, so constantly in the
position of mounting a counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the case of Nixon, where petty political crimes
intermingled with historic constitutional questions, the Clinton
presidency is being assailed by a combination of possible sexual
dalliances combined with more serious allegations of obstruction of
justice _ charges that even some of the president's most dedicated
opponents are troubled about pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   The president's political destiny may be determined by Congress,
and so it was fitting that on a day of national loss and personal
challenge the president traveled the 16 longest blocks in American
political life, from the White House to the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   In a setting of remorse and remembrance, under the gravest
personal political pressures, President Clinton Tuesday nonetheless
captured the senselessness of the two guards' deaths _ and the
hopelessness Americans feel when confronting the violence that
pockmarks our national life. ``We thank their families for enduring
the pain and extra burden of joining us here today,'' the president
said, his eyes overflowing with feeling, ``for they remind us that
what makes our democracy strong is not only what Congress may enact
or a president may achieve; even more, it is the countless
individual citizens who live our ideals out every day, the
innumerable acts of heroism that go unnoticed, and especially, it
is the quiet courage and uncommon bravery of Americans like J.J.
Chestnut and John Gibson.''
</P>
<P>
   In that short passage were the moral and political touchstones
of the moment _ the grief of the families, the American creed of
democracy and freedom, the signature American idea of the
individual and the modern ideological conviction that the people,
and not the government, are what make the country strong. No one
could say it better and, in a parade of speakers that included
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, House Speaker Newt Gingrich and
Vice President Al Gore, no one did.
</P>
<P>
   At times like these, when even passersby on Washington streets
sense that historic events are unfolding, the strange echoes
between Clinton's predicament and Nixon's _ and the similarities
between his seldom less-than-astonishing political gifts and those
of Kennedy and Reagan _ seem vivid.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon was criticized, in turn, for his ``Vietnamization'' policy
designed to end American involvement in Southeast Asia; for his
invasion of Cambodia; for his economic policies, which included
wage and price controls; and for the entire tragic cycle of
Watergate, from break-in to coverup to stonewall. Clinton began his
presidency in controversy, from his mishandled effort to end
discrimination against gays in the military to botched nominations,
from an economic stimulus package that failed to a comprehensive
overhaul of the health system that also failed.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy and Reagan epitomized the power of the word in politics,
of knowing what to say and exactly how to say it. One was able to
mobilize the nation for the space race; the other to lead the
nation in mourning when the space shuttle Challenger exploded on
live television on an unforgettable morning. Clinton has perfect
political pitch, and his ability to anticipate the wrinkles of
public opinion has given him astonishing public-approval ratings
even as his Republican opposition and the political establishment
were ready to count him out.
</P>
<P>
   Now, once again, Clinton is struggling for survival in an
atmosphere of almost unbearable pressure on the president, the
presidency, and the political system.
</P>
<P>
   And even as Clinton recedes into lame-duck status, as the
presidency recedes from the center of American life and as politics
takes a secondary role in the nation, a constitutional drama is
unfolding in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It involves high principles and trivial charges _ and enduring
questions or private behavior and public morality. At stake is the
midterm congressional election, the credibility of the Republican
Congress, and the historical legacy of Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Many decisions beckon in the next week or so, most of them to be
made on behalf of a onetime University of Arkansas professor of
constitutional law by some of the priciest lawyers in the nation.
In the space of only a few days, independent counsel Kenneth W.
Starr issued a subpoena for Clinton to testify, won a victory on
attorney-client privilege, granted immunity to Lewinsky, and put
the White House on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the White House has found itself during most of the
last six years. Yet Clinton, more vulnerable than ever, is in a
strangely familiar position. For this is a man whose road to the
Democratic nomination and passage through the presidency has been,
from the start, a counteroffensive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David M. Shribman is chief of The Boston Globe Washington
bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
