r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     07-28 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREET &AMP; SMITH'S TOPS THE LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best sports magazine on the market is not Sports
Illustrated, a venerable institution that's been around since 1954
and has its own cover jinx.
</P>
<P>
   It is not ESPN The Magazine, either, the precocious offspring of
the cable network that has a hip-hop take on sports, complete with
migraine-inducing graphics and colors.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it dated The Sporting News, any of the dozen or so
annuals which flood the market each season, and certainly not any
of the fantasy magazines aimed at stataholics.
</P>
<P>
   The best sports magazine actually happens to be a four-month-old
magazine the everyday sports fan is likely to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   Its name is Street &AMP; Smith's Sports Business Journal, and its
50-plus pages each week provides an extensive education on the
size, shape and growing nature of sports' financial underbelly.
</P>
<P>
   The average fan cares most about the Dodgers and Angels standing
in the pennant race, Michael Jordan's plans for 1998, and what NFL
games are on television each Sunday. After 25 years in the business
of covering sports, I've learned Joe Fan is liable to tune out
whenever stories include more dollars signs and legalese than bunts
and punts.
</P>
<P>
   But considering the way owners keep digging deeper into the
pocket of fans, the way corporations are investing in franchises,
and the way players keep turning their heels on fans, the Journal
should fall into the must read category.
</P>
<P>
   Consider some of these headlines and news items culled from the
first 12 issues of Street &AMP; Smith's Sports Business Journal:
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Murdoch plans to spinoff part of his News Corp. empire,
including its cable TV unit and the Dodgers, and take 20 percent of
it public.
</P>
<P>
   Disney, owner of the Ducks, Angels, ABC and ESPN, is facing
shareholder discontent over the way its sports units are dragging
down its stock price.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Chargers will spend $200,000 in an effort to
market NFL-less Los Angeles and bring some ticket buyers south.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire stands to make $200,000 from a ticket incentive in
his contract if the Cardinals break 3 million in attendance. That
doesn't make him greedy; 3 million fans will generate $2.5 million
in revenue for the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Thomas is considering taking himself public -- part of his
salary and endorsements -- meaning a fan could buy shares of The
Big Hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The laws the NBA players are using in bargaining with David
Stern were created to protect coal miners.
</P>
<P>
   And so on.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal's birth can be traced to a former publisher of the
Wall Street Journal, Ray Shaw, who went about his retirement buying
up small newspapers and business journals. In the process, he
bought the Street &AMP; Smith line, heretofore best known for its
baseball and football annuals. Shaw's son, Whitney, thought there
was a place for a sports business journal in addition to the other
S&AMP;S titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sports industry is a $324 billion industry,'' said John
Genzale, the Journal's editor. ``To put it in perspective, the
automotive industry in America is an $80 billion business. When
you're dealing with an industry that big, there are literally
thousands of stories to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports has always been about business, Genzale says, but that
fact has only been grudgingly accentuated in the last two decades.
Journal research indicated a lot of information was going
unreported because of a basic fact of sports life for newspaper:
Its readers prefer box scores to stock tickers.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers attempt to cover this field, but it's a delicate
balance. Spend too much time writing about stadium economics or the
terms being discussed in the NBA lockout, and the reader very
likely will tune out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to recall what (the late) Jack Kent Cooke said when
asked why he doesn't spend more on marketing,'' said Genzale. ``He
said `I fill the stadium every week. What do I need marketing for?'
Things have changed since owners cared only about gate receipts and
television money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you have corporations investing, and teams are vitally
involved in stadium signage, merchandising and maxing out their
concessions, and it impacts the cost of tickets and whether
stadiums are built and whether a franchise is likely to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are aiming the magazine at anyone who makes a buck and
spends a buck in sports. It's the same concept for the Wall Street
Journal in business and Variety in entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Between stories about stadium financing and corporate
investment, the Journal puts some information into fan-friendly
formats. A weekly feature called The List, for example, recently
broke down what it costs a fan to park, buy a program and dinner --
a dog, beer and soda -- at each major league park (it's $17 for a
Dodgers game, $20.75 for an Angels game).
</P>
<P>
   Another showed what the most and least expensive tickets were in
each sport. The average ticket price for a Pittsburgh Penguins
hockey game is $56, $52 to see the Redskins and $51 to watch the
Raiders' Commitment to Excellence. You can catch a Twins game for
$8, and the Clippers for $24, the best bargain in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no concept of what a billion dollars is, nor what it
can do, and I'm sure most fans feel the same way. These are
staggering numbers,'' said Genzale.
</P>
<P>
   ``But fans are still the substance of the money. Without them,
there are no sports. So we try to explain where the money comes
from, and whether a team can create the revenue to justify a $300
million stadium, and what exactly it will cost the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   You can also find out the names of the agents for each NFL and
NBA first round pick, the impact McGwire has on road attendance,
the 21 new stadiums scheduled to open between today and 2002, and
that the Dodgers have had only a .2 percent fluctuation in
attendance over the last 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   All that may not hold the same thrill as watching Mark McGwire
hit 62 home runs, but it's nice to know someone is watching our
sports bottom line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7186 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-FRENCH-COLUMN-LAD     07-28 1554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRENCH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSPIRACY THEORIES FLY IN BRAZIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Angry Brazilians continue to seek for answers 2{ weeks after
their team's collapse in the World Cup final, and some of what
they're coming up with is fantastic.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the talk concerns Ronaldo, the wunderkind striker whose
disappearance in the title match set the tone for the 3-0 loss to
France on July 12. What, all wonder, is wrong with the ``world's
greatest player''?
</P>
<P>
   Or is something far more nefarious at work, some sort of
conspiracy that prevented Brazil from winning its fifth World Cup
title? Were the French promised the crown? Did Brazil trade victory
for something more? What role did Nike, or FIFA, play, and what
might all this mean for 2002?
</P>
<P>
   These are sticky questions, on the surface ridiculous, but
stranger things have occurred in this sport; nothing can be
discounted. Not even the simplest, and likeliest, explanation: That
Ronaldo suffered a seizure of some sort, tried to play anyway, and
struggled, as did his teammates, against a superior team.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't wash in Rio.
</P>
<P>
   Something more must be at stake ``This is going down as one of
the eternal mysteries in football history,` one Brazilian scribe
declared and the search has centered on Ronaldo, who has admitted
that he suffered a seizure before the match after denying so
earlier. Whether it was epilepsy, an allergic reaction, severe
stress or something else hasn't been determined, but what appears
clear is that the 21-year-old forward was in no shape to play.
</P>
<P>
   That he did Coach Mario Zagallo, dismissed Monday, first said
his other players ``panicked'' when Ronaldo wasn't on the original
starting lineup, then that Ronaldo demanded to play has been
ascribed to Brazilian corporate sponsor Nike (wanted to unleash a
new shoe in the wake of Brazil's expected triumph) or to the CBF,
the governing body for soccer in Brazil (forced him to play).
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what occurred in the hours before the final has had fans
in an uproar, the team's doctor before a review board and Ronaldo
defending his mental health.
</P>
<P>
   When Ronaldo was left off the roster, it was because of an
``injured ankle.'' Then it was his knee. Then it was a stomach
ache. Then something else. When he did take the field, he looked
like a zombie.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo, twice the world player of the year, says he was fine
until mid-afternoon the day of the final. ``Before the game I had
lunch, returned to my room, shaved and laid down to watch
television,'' he told Brazil's Globo television network. ``Then I
started shaking all over. I had a convulsion. I don't remember
anything else other than waking up with pain all over my body. It
was as if someone had beaten me.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor told me I wouldn't be able to play. I said that I
had to. ... I know a lot of people were expecting much more of me,
but I did the best I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Some suggested a row with his girlfriend, Susanna Werner (who
got nearly as much World Cup air time as her boyfriend), caused the
convulsions; others thought he might have been poisoned.
</P>
<P>
   And still others believe Brazil allowed France to hoist the
trophy in exchange for the 2002 World Cup, which according to this
line of thought the Brazilians would host when FIFA takes it away
from South Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   As farfetched as that one sounds, it just might be possible.
South Korea, in particular, is struggling with the demands of the
World Cup in the wake of the Asian financial crisis. It doesn't
have the money needed to improve stadia or build infrastructure,
and there has been speculation it would resign, or be replaced, as
host.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Koreans asked for a three-month postponement of
the tournament, to September 2002, because it realized, suddenly,
that the scheduled summer dates conflict with their rainy season.
Most believe cash, not weather, is behind it.
</P>
<P>
   England has made it clear it would step in to host, and its
facilities are certainly in better shape than Brazil's. But the
Koreans insist they'll be ready the Japanese claim they're raring
to go and FIFA has shown no signs it will take any action soon.
</P>
<P>
   So, could it be that Brazil's loss was just that, a loss? Was it
just not their night?
</P>
<P>
   Someone has to take the blame, and so far that someone is
Ronaldo. ``The problem,'' he said, ``was that the team played
poorly, and they found an excuse in me for the defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they found lots of excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ALL-STARS?
</P>
<P>
   The fans voted for Major League Soccer's All-Star Game starters,
so there's not much sense in questioning the choices, although
Preki? Alexi Lalas? Tab Ramos? It's the national team, really, that
will take on the World All-Stars on Sunday in Orlando: Only Tony
Meola and John Harkes, of the starters, weren't in France.
</P>
<P>
   The World team, with Jorge Campos in goal and Jan Eriksson and
Geoff Aunger in defense, has some questionable selections as well,
and why did Coach Octavio Zambrano include San Jose's Richard Gough
on his bench rather than the Galaxy's Martin Machon?
</P>
<P>
   The two most exciting selections are on the U.S. bench:
Colorado's Ross Paule, who has emerged as a force in midfield this
season, and D.C.'s Ben Olsen, a future World Cup star and the
rookie-of-the-year favorite. What they have in common: Both left
college a year early to turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   CORNER KICKS
</P>
<P>
   Americans are on the move in Germany. Defender David Regis, the
Frenchman naturalized just before the World Cup, is leaving the
Bundesliga after one season to play for Metz, the French
runners-up. Jovan Kirovski, who hasn't evolved as hoped for at
Borussia Dortmund, has been loaned to fellow German club Fortuna
Cologne; and then there's Frankie Hejduk, whose World Cup
performance paid off with a Bayer Leverkusen contract. Lots of
movement in Holland, too: World Cup alternates Gregg Berhalter
(Sparta Rotterdam to Cambuur Leeuwarden) and John O'Brien (Ajax
Amsterdam to FC Utrecht, a loan), both defenders, also have new
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Claudio Reyna, the most important player at VfL Wolfsburg last
season, isn't guaranteed a starting job by the German club this
season. Coach Wolfgang Wolf, apparently concerned with how Reyna
deals with physical play, has given the playmaker job to Ghanian
Charles Akonnor; Reyna is battling three players for a spot in the
first 11.
</P>
<P>
   Reyna and Hejduk are the only Americans in the Bundesliga, but
there are five ``Amis'' in 2Bundesliga, the second division:
Kirovski, Michael Mason (St. Pauli), Matthew Okoh (SpVgg
Unterhaching), John van Buskirk (FKC Uerdingen) and David Wagner
(Guetersloh).
</P>
<P>
   Lotta big names on the move in Mexico, too, including the
Tricolor's (and Necaxa's) striking tandem, Luis Hernandez and
Cuauhtemoc Blanco. Hernandez transfered to Monterrey and Blanco to
America in the annual ``draft.'' Other big transfers: Ricardo
Pelaez (America to Guadalajara), Luis Garcia (Atlante to
Guadalajara), Pavel Pardo (Atlas to UAG) and Braulio Luna (Pumas to
America).
</P>
<P>
   Sigi Schmid named five of his UCLA players to the U.S. Under-20
team that will attempt next month to qualify for the FIFA World
Youth Championships next April in Nigeria. Bruin goalkeeper Nick
Rimando, defender Carlos Bocanegra, midfielder Shaun Tsakiris and
forward McKinley Tennyson will be joined by recruit Ryan Futagaki
(Fountain Valley HS) in the Aug. 5-9 CONCACAF tournament in
Trinidad &AMP; Tobago. The Americans, Canada, Costa Rica and the hosts
are fighting for two berths. Others on the 18-man roster include
Maryland-bound Dan Califf (Orange HS), Indiana sweeper Nick Garcia,
and MLS youngsters Jamar Beasley (New England), Nino DaSilva
(Kansas City) and Tim Howard (New York/New Jersey).
</P>
<P>
   Schmid, who enters his 19th season this fall in Westwood (he's
305-59-33 with three NCAA titles, including last year's), wants to
consider John Thorrington
</P>
<P>
   (Manchester United) and Jacob Lisek
</P>
<P>
   (Fortuna Duesseldorf) for Nigeria, if he can. Both grew up in
the United States, but Thorrington was born in England and Lisek in
Poland, and neither have citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Burn may be faltering in MLS, but they're still on
target to repeat as U.S. Open Cup champs. The Burn takes on Chicago
and Columbus faces New York/New Jersey in a semifinal doubleheader
Monday night in New Orleans with the winners advancing to the final
Aug. 26 in Virginia Beach, Va. The Open Cup has been contested
since 1914 it's the United States' oldest soccer trophy but tight
schedules have persuaded the Galaxy to skip it in each of the
club's three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad &AMP; Tobago looks ready to wrest the Caribbean title from
Jamaica; it should get the chance Friday in the Shell Cup final.
Columbus' Stern John
</P>
<P>
   guided T&AMP;T into today's semifinal against Haiti, scoring both
goals to beat Martinique, 2-1, then getting four more in an 8-0
romp over Dominica. The Jamaicans take on Antigua and Barbuda
today.
</P>
<P>
   European club champ Real Madrid has a new coach, another one,
after Jose Antonio Camacho resigned after just 22 days on the job.
Guus Hiddink, the Netherlands' World Cup coach, will guide the
Spanish power, which won the European title in May, then dumped
coach Jupp Heynckes. Hiddink was hired after Nevio Scalaturned down
the post.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
