<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7187 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DON-GIOVANNI-OPERA-$A     07-28 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DON-GIOVANNI-OPERA-$ADV02-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE NURTURING OF NATURE, THE FRENCH WAY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2.) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AIX-EN-PROVENCE, France _ The twin colonnades of plane trees
that line the Cours Mirabeau in this ancient French city to the
south are not there by accident.
</P>
<P>
   Some human eye devised the spacings, guided the beginnings, then
let nature take its course. The hand of man is everywhere to be
observed on France's natural beauties. Nature is to be revered, but
it is also to be improved on.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a bad way to look at the Peter Brook production of
``Don Giovanni'' that played at the Festival Internationale d'Art
Lyrique here this summer. Brook offered not much of a production at
all: a few benches on the big courtyard stage of the Archbishop's
Palace, the Don in a vanilla suit and Panama hat, his colleagues in
street clothes and party dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Mozart was treated exceptionally well: not with visual
effects or theatrical coups that drew the audience into the events
but by an attempt to look at the opera's people from the inside
out. Brook, returning to the medium after years of boycott,
carefully prepared his young cast members to follow their own
natures, and seldom has the swollen rhetoric of opera been more
effectively curbed. So articulately demonstrative were the
recitatives that the non-Italian-speaker could follow every nuance
without the need of words.
</P>
<P>
   Brook's singers, uniformly good at a recent performance, were
none very old. Equally young were the musicians of the Mahler
Chamber Orchestra, who seemed mesmerized by their distinguished
conductor, Claudio Abbado. Roberto Scaltriti's tall good lucks and
firm baritone promised a very workable Don for the future. Nicola
Ulivieri, a thinking man's Leporello, avoided buffoonery.
</P>
<P>
   I liked the Donna Anna, Monica Colonna, for her intensity. Donna
Elvira's cold fury seemed to emanate as much from the natural
personality of the singer (Veronique Gens) as from the nature of
the role. Alessandro Guerzoni's Commendatore substituted
considerable, if light-voiced, dignity for the usual cavernous
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Tarver, a young American singing Don Ottavio, negotiated
the rigors of ``Il mio tesoro'' with understandable caution but
allowed ``Dalla sua pace'' to emanate with cool beauty. This is a
nice Mozart voice, fastidious and elegant. Nathan Berg and Catrin
Wyn Davies were the attractive Masetto and Zerlina.
</P>
<P>
   Brook's ``Don Giovanni'' did have a few tricks up its sleeve.
The orchestra rose for the finale, and members stamped their feet
as the Commendatore's ghost knocked for admission. At the
concluding sextet, the Don reappeared, now a disembodied observer
removed from life. The touches were all nice, but it was the
exercise of believable human discourse through artifice that made
the difference. The people who planted those trees would
understand.
</P>
<P>
   The Aix festival, which ended on Friday, was at once 50 years
old this summer and brand new. Its early postwar seasons served to
reacquaint culture-minded summer residents with the operas of
Mozart, and every June and July, Parisians descended from the
north, giving these events a cachet competitive with that of
Salzburg or Glyndebourne.
</P>
<P>
   But festivals multiplied and found new themes, and in recent
years Aix has faded. The city, whose project the festival largely
was, lost heart. Then Stephane Lissner arrived, a couple of years
ago, with restoratives. In Paris, Lissner had practiced similar
first aid on the Theatre du Chatelet, spending lavishly on
distinctive projects.
</P>
<P>
   He could. To his good fortune, Lissner became the handy cultural
weapon with which Jacques Chirac, then the mayor of Paris, thumped
political rivals in the national government, which owned and
operated the competing Paris Opera. When Chirac became president,
his good will toward his protege survived.
</P>
<P>
   The government and, to a lesser degree, the city and the region
are now the major players at Aix, and one-half of the festival's
$10 million budget will be subsidized (the rest to come from ticket
sales).
</P>
<P>
   Last year's lull (there were two operas in concert) was used to
build and rebuild: new studios and production plants, an overhaul
at the Archbishop's Palace (the scene this summer of Bartok's
``Bluebeard's Castle'' and Monteverdi's ``Orfeo'') and the
beginnings of work on other spaces.
</P>
<P>
   New to the festival was a kind of postgraduate school where
young professionals, recruited worldwide, learned by doing. They
were in good part responsible for the smaller productions of
``Curlew River'' and ``Dido and Aeneas'' in another nearby
courtyard theater, at Hotel Maynier d'Oppede.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The two operas, along with ``Don Giovanni,'' are to tour Europe
and Japan now that the festival has closed. At their courtyard
space, a raised rectangle of flagstones, a small fountain in its
middle, served as a stage, with amphitheaterlike seating on three
sides. Four big plane trees provided shelter.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits and disadvantages of youth were represented in both
pieces. Purcell's magnificent torso of an opera was prepared by
David Stern, a young American conductor, and its attractive crew of
singers was maneuvered by Marcel Bozonnet (director) and Caroline
Marcade (choreographer).
</P>
<P>
   No one except perhaps Andrew Rupp, as Aeneas, had the
ingredients for international success, but at the new Aix, ensemble
skill was more to the point.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these voices were in surprisingly poor health. Sandrine
Rondot labored uncomfortably as Belinda. Depending on your point of
view, matching Myriam Boucris' damaged technique to the part of the
Sorceress was either apt casting or poor judgment.
</P>
<P>
   I hope it is not a comment on the pushiness of the opera world
these days that a singer can have so many troubles at such an early
age. English diction from the international cast was cloudy at
best, Rupp being the exception. But since the French in general
don't like to speak English or listen to it, I guess it didn't
matter much.
</P>
<P>
   Rinat Shaham sang Dido with taste. Youth gave her music an
attractive bloom; it also largely disconnected her from Dido's
sufferings. At the moment, Ms. Shaham imitates the tragic heroine
well. Perhaps with a little more living, she will become one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curlew River'' shared the virtues of Aix's ``Dido'' and
largely avoided it problems. The conversational tone of Britten's
piece was particularly helped by the nearness of the performers.
Written for the church but inspired by Noh plays, ``Curlew River''
is less an opera than an lllustrated homily, a parable set to music
revealing God's mercy to those in pain.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is a ferry crossing. A child's death is remembered. A
Madwoman is reconciled to its loss and is healed. ``Curlew River''
is framed by plainchant as processional and recessional and modal
scales carry Britten farther from major and minor than he was used
to going.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshi Oida's direction was reticent, and Michael Bennett,
playing the Madwoman in Britten's all-male cast, touched his
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Purcell and Britten, separated by 300 years, have much in
common. Both love uneven phrase lengths that surprise and delight.
Both are descriptive composers: Britten with his delicate arpeggio
river swells, Purcell with his cave of witches and echo effects.
Britten's tiny instrumental ensemble, led again by Stern, was a
constant wonder of discreet and suggestive coloration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bluebeard's Castle,'' here conducted by Pierre Boulez and
splendidly sung by the Hungarian bass Laszlo Polgar, has never been
much of an opera to look at, so Aix hired the choreographer Pina
Bausch, who had done an earlier dance production of the work, seen
at the Brooklyn Academy of Music in 1984, to be its eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Dialogue became dancing images, repeated and multiplied.
Obsessions and fears could be looked at. Ms. Bausch got her quota
of boos at the end, but this simply showed an audience that was
paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, indeed, added much to these events, being silent,
attentive and, if not always knowledgeable, at least eager to know.
People make festivals, and these people had evidently made an
effort to be where they were and knew precisely why they had come.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
