<HEADER>
A7190 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-nfl-HNS &LR;      07-28 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-nfl-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Owners OK McCombs' acquisition of Vikings
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DANNY ROBBINS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
GRAPEVINE _ Red McCombs was approved as owner of the Minnesota
Vikings on Tuesday, gaining admission to a club he had sought to
join for more than 30 years. But the San Antonio businessman made
it clear his heart remains well south of Mankato, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   McCombs reiterated his view that there is no reason to move the
Vikings _ ``a Minnesota institution,'' he said _ but he indicated
he hopes to see improved attendance as well as progress in dealing
with, as he put it, the team's ``facility problem.'' He also said
he has not abandoned his dream of seeing an NFL team in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   In short, McCombs wasn't in the club long before he was talking
like a member.
</P>
<P>
   McCombs, who is paying a reported $250 million for the Vikings,
was approved unanimously by NFL owners meeting at the Dallas-Fort
Worth Airport Hyatt. The vote became basically a rubber stamp after
McCombs won the unanimous approval of the NFL's finance committee
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Tuesday vote, McCombs greeted Dallas Cowboys owner
Jerry Jones, a key supporter, with a hug and ``Hail to the chief.''
After the vote, McCombs and his associates entered the owners'
meeting room to loud applause.
</P>
<P>
   McCombs, who made his fortune primarily through his auto
dealerships, previously owned the Denver Nuggets and San Antonio
Spurs of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Author Tom Clancy originally had outbid McCombs for the Vikings
and was in line to buy the team before failing to appear before the
finance committee in May.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the owners laid the groundwork for stocking the
new Cleveland Browns, which will enter the league as an expansion
team in 1999. The Browns will receive at least 30 veteran players
from other teams and gain 14 extra draft picks in their first two
years of operation, NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue announced. At
least seven groups are bidding to own the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   McCombs' chief business associate, Gary Woods, cited three
factors for the relative ease with which McCombs was approved as
owner of the Vikings: single ownership, a background in sports and
sound financing.
</P>
<P>
   McCombs is expected to close the deal and assume control of the
team by the middle of August.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, president of McCombs Enterprises, smiled when asked where
McCombs, 70, gets his energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Genes,'' he said. ``Retirement is not in his vocabulary.
Vacation is not in his vocabulary. Anything he has ever done for
fun has always involved working. He combines the two. To him, this
is a challenge, fun, but also a business.''
</P>
<P>
   McCombs has tried to become an NFL owner since 1962, with most
of his efforts focused on getting a team for San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, he said he was excited about ``being a part of
Minnesota'' but acknowledged his primary wish is to see the NFL
come to his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (buying the Vikings) is a dream for me,'' he said, ``but
if I could wave a wand and create anything I wanted and had one
choice _ the choice of owning a team outside of San Antonio or
having the power to see that San Antonio had a team and that I
would not be involved in it at all _ I would definitely choose the
latter. It would not even be a choice, because I think the fans of
San Antonio, Austin and South Texas dearly expect and deserve to
have a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that was not an issue here. The issue here was a team for
sale in Minneapolis, and that team has a storied tradition in the
state of Minnesota. I can do the hypothetical, but the hypothetical
didn't come to pass. Having said that, as I said hello to (Buffalo
Bills owner) Ralph Wilson in the lobby last night, his first
comment was, `Well, I guess now you won't be calling me to see if
I'm interested in moving my team to San Antonio,' and I said,
`Well, don't bet on it, because San Antonio still doesn't have the
team.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the people in Minnesota should be interested in the
fact that a guy from Texas who for years has supported the program
to get a team in San Antonio now owns their team. They should be
concerned about that. I don't expect that issue to go away. But I
will do everything I can to see that the Vikings are competitive in
Minnesota, and I fully expect them to be. Having said that, I will
still work within the league to see if there is any way San Antonio
could have an NFL team.''
</P>
<P>
   McCombs' ownership and a vacant Alamodome could hover over a
franchise with lagging attendance and a stadium, the Metrodome,
that is less than optimal as a revenue producer even when full.
</P>
<P>
   McCombs sounded like an NBA owner when he spoke of the Vikings
regaining their ``home-court advantage,'' but the message won't
need translation in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say, `Well, this guy just paid a lot of money. What he
really wants to do is increase revenue,''' he said. ``That's true.
I do want to increase revenue. But it is a very, very solid fact:
Home-court advantage comes from the players knowing in advance that
there's standing room only, that their extended families are going
to be watching them and that everybody in the stands loves them and
hates the opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vikings have not had that advantage for several years. It
will be my job to see that they get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the stadium issue, he said: ``The facility problem for
the Vikings is very real. I think every person in Minnesota is
aware of it. That's ongoing. We will be trying to find ways to
relieve that problem, still working within the framework of
Minnesota. We don't have any answers yet, but obviously that is a
problem that has to be addressed. We will be talking to members of
the (Metropolitan) Sports Commission. They know far more about this
than we do. And I suspect the people of Minnesota will address this
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, McCombs and Woods will evaluate the team's
front-office personnel, the first step in putting their stamp on
the team. Woods said he would go to Minneapolis immediately.
McCombs is expected to arrive Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been involved with many companies other than sports
(franchises),'' McCombs said. ``We always find, in taking over any
company, there are assets we were not aware of, and they are always
people. To us, organization from a team aspect is just as important
as the team on the field. We have to be sure we have everybody in
the Vikings organization that has a passion for his or her job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
