<HEADER>
A7191 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCLC-RESIGNATION-COX     07-28 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCLC-RESIGNATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women's rift spurs founder to quit board
 &HT;    By Kimberly H. Byrd
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three days into the 41st annual Southern Christian
Leadership Conference convention and still there has been no public
mention of the rift with the women's division.
</P>
<P>
   But the board has met privately on four occasions. During one of
those meetings, Evelyn Lowery, founder of SCLC/WOMEN, resigned from
SCLC board, said Chairman Claud Young. But he refused to accept her
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an angry outburst,'' Young said Tuesday afternoon
following an awards luncheon. ``So I left the door open to set up a
means of working together.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowery, who apparently has left Washington, did not return phone
calls to her home in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks before the convention, which began Saturday with the
installation of Martin Luther King III as president, SCLC was
caught up in a controversy when it was reported that the board had
voted 10-9 in April to sever ties with SCLC/WOMEN.
</P>
<P>
   King, who voted in favor of the move, said the intent of the
board's vote was to restructure the organization so that SCLC/WOMEN
would function as a department, rather than a separate entity.
Additionally, Young said, there was a need to build in some
``accountability.'' Some board members have said privately that it
has been difficult to merge the two groups because Lowery's
husband, the Rev. Joseph Lowery, had been president of SCLC for 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue started before Martin,'' Young said. ``We've just
got to have one organization.''
</P>
<P>
   When Evelyn Lowery established the women's group in 1979, it was
set up as a department of SCLC. It was incorporated 10 years later
to secure a grant but never returned to its original setup.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Tuesday what role, if any, Lowery will play
within SCLC/WOMEN, but one board member noted that she had retired
from the presidency of the group months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
