<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNION, GM REACH PACT TO END STRIKES AT 2 PLANTS
</P>
<P>
   General Motors and the United Automobile Workers union agreed to
end nearly eight weeks of strikes at two auto parts plants in
Flint, Mich., that had shut down car assembly plants across North
America, pushed hundreds of thousands of workers into temporary
unemployment and slowed the nation's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, which must be approved by workers at both
factories, settles a wide range of local issues at the two
factories and at several other GM factories where workers had
threatened strikes. But it did not address any national issues,
such as GM's push to open new factories overseas or its effort to
reduce its work force in the United States through attrition.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ COMPOSITE INDEX FALLS 1.9 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 36.73 points, or 1.9 percent, to
1,896.53. The Dow Jones industrial average, which was down 212.15
points before bargain hunters trimmed the loss, closed at 8,934.78.
The market declines were caused by continuing concerns about
corporate profits, Asia's financial crisis and the specter of
political upheaval in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond rose to 5.74 percent,
from 5.71 percent.
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL PROGRAMS VULNERABLE
</P>
<P>
   A serious security flaw has been discovered in e-mail programs
from Microsoft and Netscape Communications that could permit a
malicious person to send a message containing a virus that could
crash a computer, destroy or even steal data.
</P>
<P>
   BMW ACQUIRES ROLLS-ROYCE NAME
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen was forced to agree to hand over the Rolls-Royce name
to BMW in 2003. Volkswagen and BMW had competed for the British
luxury car company with Volkswagen agreeing to pay $780 million for
Rolls-Royce Motor Cars. But analysts now say BMW appears to be the
real winner because the name is considered by many to be
Rolls-Royce's most valuable asset.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE APPROVES A CREDIT UNION BILL
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed a bill that would help credit unions compete
with banks for customers. The House had approved a similar measure
in April. If approved, the legislation would override a Supreme
Court ruling by letting federally chartered credit unions continue
to include more than one group in their memberships.
</P>
<P>
   WORKERS STOP REOPENING OF A PLANT
</P>
<P>
   South Korean workers blocked an attempt by Hyundai Motor to
reopen factories that had been closed for more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT CALLS CASE `GROUNDLESS'
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft called the government's antitrust case against it
``completely groundless'' and offered a glimpse of the legal
strategy it will pursue in its first court filing in its defense.
Both sides are scrambling to take depositions from potential
witnesses. Bill Gates, the chairman and co-founder of Microsoft,
plans to testify by videotape in the case, which is scheduled to
begin on Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA SEEN AS ASIA'S GROWTH ENGINE
</P>
<P>
   James Harmon, the chairman of the Export-Import Bank, a U.S.
government agency, said he wants China to become its largest
recipient of loans to buy American products and equipment. His
statement reflects the new emphasis the United States is placing on
China as an economic engine for Asia.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERS STILL CONFIDENT
</P>
<P>
   Consumer confidence in the U.S. economy stuck close to a 30-year
high in July, supported by a combination of benign inflation and an
unemployment rate near a three-decade low. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
