<HEADLINE>
CENDANT CHAIRMAN, 9 OTHERS STEP DOWN AFTER ACCOUNTING FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After weeks of intensifying pressure from an accounting scandal,
Walter Forbes, the chairman of Cendant Corp., resigned Tuesday,
saying that his departure would help the company ``focus all of its
attention and resources on restoring the faith of its shareholders,
its customers and its people.''
</P>
<P>
   The board immediately elected Henry Silverman, the company's
chief executive, to the additional post of chairman of Cendant, a
direct marketer and franchiser, which owns brands that include
Century 21 real estate, Avis car rentals, and Howard Johnson and
Ramada Inn motels.
</P>
<P>
   The company was formed in December from the merger of HFS Inc.,
led by Silverman, and CUC International, led by Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   His resignation comes 14 weeks after Cendant announced that
serious ``accounting irregularities'' had been uncovered at
businesses that had formerly been part of CUC International.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who will get a severance package worth more than $35
million, insisted Tuesday night that he had ``absolutely no
knowledge'' of those problems and that ``the actions of a few have
profoundly hurt us all.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' resignation was announced after a six-hour board meeting
at the New York City offices of the company's law firm, Skadden,
Arps, Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Forbes, E. Kirk Shelton, the former president of
CUC and seven other former CUC directors on the Cendant board also
resigned. A ninth ex-CUC director, current audit committee chairman
Frederick Green, announced he would leave the board by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Those departures will reduce Cendant's unwieldy 28-member board
to 18. The board also eliminated rules adopted as part of the
merger that required an 80 percent majority for key board action,
including the removal of the top executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter Forbes' decision and the corporate governance changes
approved today end any uncertainty about the future direction and
leadership of Cendant,'' Silverman said. ``That uncertainty was a
serious impediment to conducting our business and the process of
restoring trust in our company.''
</P>
<P>
   The resignations came after representatives of Arthur Andersen
and Deloitte &AMP; Touche gave the board a long and sobering account of
the magnitude and mechanics of the deceptive accounting practices
under investigation at the former CUC operations.
</P>
<P>
   The board is still waiting for Deloitte &AMP; Touche's formal audit
of its restated financial results for the last three years, and
Arthur Andersen's full report on who was responsible for the
apparent fraud, which may mean that more than 60 percent of CUC's
1997 profits were fictitious.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of those accounting irregularities caused
Cendant's stock to fall 46 percent on April 16 and caused a
firestorm of alarm among shareholders, employees and franchise
customers. More than 55 shareholder lawsuits have been filed.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' resignation was announced after the market had closed.
Shares of Cendant rose $1.25 Tuesday, to $17, on earlier reports
affirming the company's estimates of the financial damage caused by
the accounting irregularities.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Forbes, according to people formerly associated with HFS, began
negotiating the terms of his possible resignation early this month.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement approved by the board Tuesday preserves Forbes'
severance package, which the company valued at $35 million. In
addition, the company agreed not to sue Forbes, provided he is not
found to have been involved in any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Compensation Resource Group, executive compensation consultants
based in Pasadena, Calif., estimated that the stock options
available to Forbes under the severance package increased the value
of his severance arrangement to $44 million. The company announced
that it would record a one-time expense of approximately 3 cents a
share in the third quarter to cover the expense of the severance
package.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the company warned Wall Street that its
revised operating profits would be affected considerably more than
it had estimated in April, but the auditors Tuesday reassured the
board that no additional surprises are likely to hit the company's
financial statements as result of the continuing investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also confirmed that it is meeting regularly with
federal prosecutors in Newark, N.J., who are investigating the
case, and with lawyers from the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Cendant has disclosed that the accounting problems under
investigation affected not only the shopping-club membership
program at CUC, as it had reported in April, but also ``all the
major business units of CUC,'' extending back to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Revised financial statements for Cendant are expected by early
August, which will allow the company to move toward completion of
its pending acquisition of American Bankers Insurance Group. That
acquisition is subject to regulatory approval, and regulators
cannot review the deal without valid financial statements and a
corporate management team that can withstand scrutiny. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
