<HEADLINE>
HERMOSILLO CONTINUES QUEST FOR GOAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ As Carlos Hermosillo continues his quest for
a Major League Soccer goal _ an interminable wait, it seems -- Los
Angeles Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano is trying his hardest to be
patient.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy, but the rewards, should they arrive, could be
handsome. The 33-year-old Mexican striker scored 275 goals in 457
games south of the border; once he finds the net for the Galaxy,
the logic goes, the floodgates should open.
</P>
<P>
   He'll get another chance to start the deluge this evening, when
the Galaxy (16-5, 46 points visits the Dallas Burn (10-11, 22), a
matchup that -- if the previous meetings are any indication --
could provide Hermosillo the perfect opportunity to score. The
Burn, which snapped a nine-game regulation winless streak on
Saturday, has surrendered 12 goals in two games against the Galaxy,
eight in the last one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time he steps on the field, it's a new opportunity for
him,'' says Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano, whose worries concerning
the lumbering center forward aren't solely about production.
``Every opportunity is an important opportunity for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo, a pure goalscorer, has five assists, but no goals,
in seven games since joining the Galaxy in early June, and he has
found it difficult to fit into L.A.'s fluid attacking scheme
involving Cobi Jones, Mauricio Cienfuegos, Welton, Martin Machon,
Clint Mathis and Ezra Hendrickson.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy, Zambrano says, is in a transitionary phase, trying
to redefine itself with Hermosillo, toil that would be made easier
by a few goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether the transition proves to be fruitful or not remains to
be seen,'' says Zambrano. ``I always think a player like Carlos can
add to a team. At the same time, we need to make sure the things
that were working in the past don't get completely erased. ...
We're not used to dealing with a true striker. We've never really
had one. There are pluses and minuses that come with that. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can talk about disappointment yet. It's too
early to evaluate. More time has to pass. Now it's a matter of
giving him the confidence to perform, be patient and do his best,
and eventually that will translate into goals.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how Hermosillo, acquired primarily as a box-office draw,
sees things. He's still coming to terms with the faster-paced, more
physical American game and continues to work on his fitness, which
lagged during nearly two months of inactivity before joining the
Galaxy; he says he's not frustrated -- Zambrano says he is _ just a
little anxious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone with my experience realizes that sometimes the goals
don't fall,'' he said Tuesday. ``I'm very confident that when I
score my first, a bunch of others will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   He also had his first on Saturday, a miskicked roller that
sneaked into D.C. United's net but was disallowed because of an
offside call. Tonight, he'll try to do it right. He'd better soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, coaches get judged by results and
goalscorers get judged by goals. We have to think the time is now
for him to perform. We have to believe that the next games will be
the ones where we see who Carlos Hermosillo is. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The time will come when we look back and evaluate what Carlos
has contributed. It it is deemed a positive (contribution), we'll
definitely continue on the road we've set for ourselves. If not,
something has to change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
