<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: `XANAX. JUST DO IT.' 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Remember that old slogan for Bufferin asking ``Why
trade a headache for an upset stomach?'' A new survey on a hot
trend in advertising _ aiming sales pitches for prescription drugs
directly at users rather than at doctors _ indicates that consumers
may be pondering a similar question today.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the results of the survey, which was sponsored by
Prevention magazine, are generally favorable toward what is known
as direct-to-consumer advertising. Such ads are appearing virtually
everywhere since the Food and Drug Administration decided in August
to relax rules governing prescription drug ads on television.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also some cautionary aspects to the survey data.
For one, consumers say they worry whether these ads diminish
prescription drugs by likening them to heavily advertised packaged
goods. And the ads seem to get subpar grades for usefulness and
clarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line shows the consumer is benefiting,'' said
Stephen Giannetti, the New York-based associate publisher of
Prevention, published by Rodale Press Inc. ``But this is still in
its early stages, and it's too soon to tell what may happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The findings of the survey, conducted nationally among 1,200
adults in March and April by Princeton Survey Research Associates,
are to be presented at a luncheon Wednesday afternoon in midtown
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Direct-to-consumer advertising is beneficial, Giannetti said in
a telephone interview Tuesday, primarily because ``it's encouraging
a dialogue between doctor and patient.'' Indeed, the survey found
that 33 percent of those who have seen such ads have spoken to
their doctors about an advertised drug. Of those consumers, 28
percent asked for prescriptions _ and 80 percent of such requests
were granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about empowering people with information,'' Giannetti
said, ``which they're thirsting for because they're a little
disenchanted with the health care system.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before self-medication and self-care were in vogue,
Prevention had advocated that consumers take control of their
health care regimen and familiarize themselves with data on drugs,
nutrition, diet and exercise. In fact, 74 percent of the survey
respondents agreed strongly or mostly with the statement that
direct-to-consumer drug ads ``allow people to become more involved
with their health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Direct advertising has increased substantially since the
regulations were eased. Consumers are now being bombarded by slick
campaigns hawking medications like Allegra, Prozac, Valtrex and
Zocor. Until recently, those products had been advertised almost
solely to physicians. But to be aimed directly at consumers, the
FDA has declared, TV commercials must include some information
about the potential risks associated with the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Slaughter, market research director for Prevention at the
Rodale headquarters in Emmaus, Pa., said that means ``the
advertising includes what are essentially reasons not to buy the
product at the same time you're being sold the product.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When have we ever seen that before?'' he asked, adding, ``It's
a whole new genre of advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey shows that those who are taking medicines they see
being advertised say the ads make them feel better about the drugs,
make them more likely to take the drugs and remind them to have
their prescriptions refilled. Yet 61 percent of the respondents
agreed strongly or mostly with the statement that such ads
``confuse people about the risks and benefits'' of prescription
medicines _ just shy of the 67 percent who said they agreed
strongly or mostly with the statement that such ads ``educate
people about the risks and benefits'' of prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   That can be seen in another part of the survey showing that
respondents _ ``even those suffering from the conditions the
products are intended to treat,'' Slaughter said _ often were
unaware of that information. For instance, 59 percent of the
intended audience for Imitrex said they did not know it was meant
to treat migraine headaches, even after seeing ads for that brand;
the figure for Pravachol, a drug for high cholesterol, was 79
percent. And 55 percent said they agreed strongly or mostly with
the statement that direct-to-consumer ads make prescription drugs
``seem harmless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a legitimate concern,'' Slaughter said, ``that if we
start advertising this like corn flakes, does it trivialize
medicine?''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it seems as if it will be a mighty long time
before consumers see ads carrying catchy slogans like ``Xanax, just
do it'' or watch cute lizards disparaging frogs that croak
``Cla-ri-tin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
