u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-WORLD-U.S.-HNS &LR;      07-28 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-WORLD-U.S.-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
U.S. swaggers into opener
<TEXT>
<P>
   Team members confident; Rudy T remains cautious
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATHENS, Greece _ Fifteen nations will send out their best players
today as the FIBA World Championship of Basketball begins.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the United States, which has none of its top
400 players on the roster of 12 brave men led by Rudy Tomjanovich.
But what the team of non-NBA players has is one of the same
admirable qualities Dream Teams before it also shared _ an
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's not the same swagger Michael Jordan, Charles Barkley,
Shaquille O'Neal and others had in the past two Olympics or at the
'94 World Championship. But this team of little-known players knows
how to act the part of the big bully on the basketball block.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team opens the tournament today against Brazil at 9:30
a.m. CDT. It will be the first of three preliminary-round games
against the other three teams in the group.
</P>
<P>
   And the Americans expect nothing but good things in the opening
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't go 3-0, it's going to be an embarrassment to
ourselves and our country,'' starting power forward David Wood said
Tuesday after the team's final practice before the tourney. ``They
are all good teams. But we have the tradition. It would be like the
Celtics or the Lakers not making the playoffs in the '80s.''
</P>
<P>
   First-round success is critical for the United States or any
team that hopes to contend for a medal in this 12-day tournament.
The field will be pared to the top three teams in each of the four
groups after preliminary play. Records will be carried over into
the second round, which will trim four teams from medal contention.
</P>
<P>
   Teams are seeded after the second round, and an eight-team,
single-elimination tournament begins.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team is considered a gold-medal contender. But with a
relatively easy group that includes Lithuania and South Korea in
addition to Brazil, going 3-0 would seem a realistic goal in the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to finish first in our group after the first three
games and get in a rhythm for the whole tournament,'' Wendell
Alexis said. ``Especially playing three nights in a row. You want
to be at your best for three nights in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a disappointment (going anything less than 3-0),
because I think we're the best of the four teams. But that doesn't
mean anything if you get on the court and don't execute. If the
other team gets confidence, it can get very difficult. You can't
lighten up on anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But you can't go 3-0 until you are 1-0. That's a point
Tomjanovich has stressed to his team during the days leading to the
World Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's monumental that we get off to a good start,''
Tomjanovich said. ``But things happen. If we did come out and lose,
we'd just have to come out and tighten up some more and make sure
we don't lose again. But we're trying to win every game. That's why
you compete. You have to give respect to your opponent, but you
have to compete very hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this team, we're playing to win. Nobody expects us to
win. And those kind of challenges are great. I don't know what's
going to happen with this team, but I do know that I have a bunch
of hungry, proud players who look at this opportunity as something
that most people don't get a chance to experience. Emotionally, I'm
going to be so much more involved in this thing because of how hard
these guys have worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich's team is made up of players who have been
basketball nomads, moving from Continental Basketball Association
teams to European clubs to South America. One of them, Duke's
Trajan Langdon, is a collegiate star. But he also is one of the
players trying to prove himself because two years ago he was a
member of the U.S. junior team that was a disappointment in the
FIBA age-group tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worn the USA jersey two other times, before my freshman
year and after my freshman year,'' Langdon said. ``And after my
freshman year was the junior world championships here in Athens and
we just had a really bad showing. We went 4-4, and it was kind of
embarrassing the way we performed as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, obviously, back here in Athens for the World Championship
to represent the USA at a time when the NBA players decided not to
come, it's exciting. Throwing on the jersey, I'll probably have
chills going onto the court.''
</P>
<P>
   As will many of the U.S. players. Before one of the exhibition
games leading to the tournament, Jimmy Oliver had his wife
videotape him while he was putting on the uniform in the hotel
room. It was something he wanted to remember for the rest of his
life.
</P>
<P>
   First up is Brazil, which is not considered a medal threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've looked at their roster, and they've got a 7-footer
(Josuel dos Santos) who had some good games at the Goodwill
Games,'' said the 6-9 Wood, who could be matched up against the
260-pound Brazilian. ``And they've got a few other guys who can
score. Any professional team in this tournament can beat any other
team if the favored team plays terrible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned a little more after we played Italy. I thought
we could get into people defensively and control the game
defensively, but the Italians didn't seem to have much trouble with
our defense. We're going to have some really hard, tough games, and
it'll boil down to how well we execute in the last five or six
minutes of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are cautious, but they also are confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not afraid of anybody,'' point guard Michael Hawkins
said. ``We fear no team when we step on the court. We're coming out
to win every game. That's our goal for these next three games, and
I think we're going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   With that attitude, at least the Americans sound like a Dream
Team, even if that's the only resemblance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
