<HEADER>
A7209 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAP-PRODUCER-PROFILE-     07-28 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAP-PRODUCER-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIP-HOP STYLE: IT'S A WAY TO RUN A COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rl) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It would be easier for Chris Schwartz, rap producer
and high school dropout, to reveal the secrets of his success if
his cellular phone would stop ringing. Or if he would stop
answering it. Not that he's not apologetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I REALLY am sorry,'' Schwartz says; then, to a distressed
artist on the other end of the line one suspects is singer Lauryn
Hill, about to come out with her first solo album:
</P>
<P>
   ``No, he didn't say you were going to look like an icon; he's
afraid that's what people are going to THINK.''
</P>
<P>
   Pause. ``I think it's very roots, very cool, everybody digs
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pause. ``You just have to look where he is in the corporate
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Where is Schwartz, CEO and co-founder of Ruffhouse Records, in
the corporate culture?
</P>
<P>
   Hard to say.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion is taking place in the Manhattan offices of Sony
(which owns Columbia Records, which distributes Ruffhouse), but
Schwartz's phone style, which is more colorful and direct than his
interview style, leans toward the street: ``Yo, man,'' or ``Dude, I
know nothing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, as this is the music business, maybe street talk is
the correct corporate style.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, Schwartz, 37, is certainly doing something right.
Operating out of Conshohocken, Pa., Ruffhouse Records, which
Schwartz and his partner, Joe Nicolo, founded nine years ago with
$400, has been home to some of the biggest names in hip-hop: Kriss
Kross, Cypress Hill and the Fugees. The Fugees' ``The Score,'' with
sales of 17 million copies, is the all-time best-selling album by a
rap group. Schwartz is now a millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Schwartz special, however, is his salesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   He began his career managing Philadelphia gangsta rapper
Schoolly D, one of the first rap artists to cross over to a
mainstream audience. Schwartz also claims to have been the first
producer to take to the streets to sell his records, giving records
and stickers to club deejays and teen-agers rather than depending
on radio play.
</P>
<P>
   The tactics proved a little aggressive for New York _ last
winter, the leader of one of Ruffhouse's promotional street gangs
was arrested on charges that he was illegally posting stickers for
the group Sporty Thiev$. Columbia Records executives were publicly
displeased, and Schwartz is enough of a corporate creature to
decline to discuss the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Schwartz consider the subject of his race important.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if you're black or white,'' Schwartz says.
``What's important is to sign the right people, to get your stuff
out there. I do that. I make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoolly D is recalling how he hooked up with Schwartz: ``You
know West Philly? It's a black neighborhood. When Chris called, I
thought he was a black dude pretending to be white. It was rap, it
was hip-hop, I didn't know anybody white who was even remotely
interested. This is '84, '85, it's a black thing, yada, yada, yada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warren, my attorney at the time, never told me Chris was
white. I'm in the shower, Chris is ringing my bell, I go
downstairs, say, `Who are you?' I let him in. I'm just sitting
there in my towel. We start talking, we start laughing. Anybody who
can make me laugh is all right with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Schoolly D have a given name he uses?
</P>
<P>
   ``Only around my mother,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times is somewhat like one's mother.
</P>
<P>
   No response.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 30 or 40 guys around us, we were the only two who had the
killer look in our eyes,'' Schoolly D says regarding the old days.
``Everybody else just wanted drugs or they were chick hounds,
typical rock 'n' roll. When it was time to be real and the smoke
cleared, he was standing over there and I was standing over here.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps there is a gene for salesmen. This seems to be the case
with Schwartz. He was born in Devon, Pa., his father was a
furniture salesman, and all but one of Schwartz's nine brothers and
sisters would grow up and go into sales. Schwartz dropped out of
school in the 10th grade and joined the Navy at 17. He also formed
a band, which set up on the deck of an aircraft carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were like the warm-up act for the Blue Angels,'' Schwartz
says.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz worked as a musician, then hooked up with Schoolly D.
Schwartz persuaded the owners of a small record company in New
Jersey to produce records on credit _ a move that was particularly
impressive because the company produced children's records, and
Schoolly D, a gangsta rapper, was not producing material that was
Disneyesque.
</P>
<P>
   Ruffhouse was created in 1989. Cypress Hill, a Los Angeles group
that championed marijuana, was the label's first success, with a
debut album that was on the Billboard charts for more than 100
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a more alternative following than core hip-hop, and
we took advantage of that,'' Schwartz says. ``We put them on the
cover of High Times magazine. But our promotions are always
changing. When you sell a record, you are vying for a slice of a
kid's awareness. With all the media glut, it's hard to hold
somebody's attention.''
</P>
<P>
   What does Schwartz believe it takes to be a good salesman?
</P>
<P>
   His answer puts the street talk in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be able to read people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
