r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GODZILLA-HOME-VIDEO-L     07-28 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GODZILLA-HOME-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GODZILLA' HOPING TO ROAR LOUDER ON HOME VIDEO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- ``Godzilla,'' who promised far more than he
delivered in the box office or at the cash register, will hit home
video shelves in early November amid moderately sunny forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Sony executives believe the video version of ``Godzilla,'' which
grossed a disappointing $135 million domestically, will outsell the
estimated 8 million copies of ``Air Force One'' the company sold
last year. With a suggested price of $14.95, gross revenues from
video could top the domestic box office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grossing $135 million is nothing to sneeze at,'' said analyst
Barbara McNamara of Alexander and Associates. ``I expect (the
video) to do respectably.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, video chains like Blockbuster may wonder about the appeal
of ``Godzilla.'' The movie's downbeat results were blamed by
Carmike Cinemas and Hershey Foods, a major ``Godzilla'' partner,
for holding down profits during the fiscal second quarter. And
analysts believe slow movement of ``Godzilla'' merchandise hurt toy
sales, although toy retailers didn't single out the giant lizard
for any fiscal woes.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's timing of the announcement also reflects the fact that
the film has virtually disappeared from multiplexes. Usually,
studios wait until after Labor Day to announce video plans for
major summer films in order to maximize the box-office potential.
</P>
<P>
   Duracell and Dreyer's Ice Cream will launch tie-in promotions
for the video this fall, and TV ads are designed to make more than
1.2 billion consumer impressions.
</P>
<P>
   Sony executives also have predicted that a simultaneous release
of ``Godzilla'' in the DVD format, priced at $24.95 with
documentary footage and background commentary, will top 400,000
copies in sales.
</P>
<P>
   The record for video sales of live-action films is estimated to
be 20 million copies by ``Independence Day,'' although ``Titanic''
may beat that when it arrives in stores Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
