<HEADLINE>
NO RACISM IN PROBLEMS WITH SOX, VAUGHN SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Mo Vaughn said Tuesday that his problems with
the Red Sox are not racial in nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a racial thing,'' said Vaughn, contradicting
assertions made by guest Ken Ford on WBZ-TV in Boston Sunday night
that the club had conveyed the message, ``OK, black boy, you can go
out and play but keep your mouth shut,'' to the first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   On the same program, ``Sports Final,'' Channel 4's Steve Burton
said Vaughn informed him that general manager Dan Duquette asked
Vaughn point-blank whether he used drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Tuesday if Duquette ever asked him about drug use, Vaughn
said, ``A couple of years ago, when I had an irregular heartbeat in
spring training, Dan said it must have something to do with
substance abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   As to his other assertion that the Red Sox had him followed by a
private investigator, Vaughn offered no specifics but said he was
certain it was true. ``I can't tell you how I know,'' he said,
``but that's a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with both Channel 4 and the Globe, Duquette denied
that the Red Sox had ever had Vaughn followed by a private
investigator or that the club had ever accused him of drug use. The
club did ask Vaughn to submit to an alcohol evaluation this past
spring, which he refused.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was booed throughout last weekend at Fenway Park after he
told a Toronto reporter that he wanted to play for the Blue Jays
next season. By the end of the weekend, however, the boos were
mixed with cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt relief to get away from Boston for the next two
weeks while the Red Sox play 12 games in four cities, Vaughn said,
``It's really a relief just to play, man. I'm glad we won three out
of four.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who had at least one hit in all four games of the Blue
Jays series, said he did not speak with Duquette last weekend.
``What's he going to say?'' Vaughn said.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was asked if he thought there was a chance he would be
traded before Friday's deadline. ``I have no idea,'' he said. ``I
don't worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was learned Tuesday that within the last couple of weeks, the
Red Sox had internal discussions about trading Vaughn to the
Chicago White Sox for Frank Thomas, the first baseman who is having
an off season (.257 average). What is not known is whether the Red
Sox approached the White Sox about such a deal. Duquette, who
remained back in Boston when the team went on the road, said last
week it was ``doubtful'' he would trade Vaughn before Friday's
deadline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
