A7216 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION     07-28 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY AGREES TO TESTIFY IN CLINTON INVESTIGATION AFTER RECEIVING
IMMUNITY DEAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Monica Lewinsky was granted immunity from
prosecution Tuesday after she agreed to tell a federal grand jury
that she and President Clinton engaged in sex at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The former White House intern, who previously denied under oath
having an affair with the president, also will testify, sources
said, that Clinton suggested they both deny the relationship was
sexual.
</P>
<P>
   A day after a five-hour session in New York with prosecutors
from independent counsel Kenneth Starr's office, Lewinsky met with
her attorneys in Washington on Tuesday and signed the agreement
that puts her in a position to pit her word against the
president's.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's lawyers announced that she was being granted full
immunity in return for cooperating in Starr's investigation. The
immunity deal also extends to Lewinsky's mother, Marcia Lewis, who
reportedly talked by telephone with her 25-year-old daughter about
the relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, as counsel for Monica Lewinsky, have reached an agreement
today that, for her full and truthful testimony, she will receive
transactional immunity in this case,'' attorney Plato Cacheris told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Transactional immunity is a rarely granted guarantee that a
witness will not be prosecuted for any crime related to the matter
under investigation. However, the immunity can be withdrawn and the
witness could face perjury charges if a prosecutor can prove the
witness lied while testifying.
</P>
<P>
   Citing two unnamed attorneys familiar with the case, The New
York Times reported Lewinsky is prepared to testify that in late
December the president told her he planned to lie under oath when
asked if they engaged in sex and that if they both denied it, no
one would know the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky also is prepared to say Clinton urged her to tell
investigators that her visits to the White House were not to see
him but to chat with Betty Currie, the president's private
secretary, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's immunity deal was announced nine weeks to the day
after Cacheris and lawyer Jake Stein joined Lewinsky's legal team.
Since then, the two lawyers and defense lawyer Nathaniel Speights
revived talks with Starr that had broken down after he rejected an
immunity deal _ somewhat similar to Tuesday's agreement _ brokered
by former Lewinsky attorney William Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   A break in the apparent impasse came last week, according to The
Associated Press, which quoted unnamed sources saying that Stein
received a telephone call from Starr saying he was reluctant to
indict Lewinsky and that they should cut a deal before it was too
late.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers wanted immunity for Lewinsky because of the legal
trouble posed by an affidavit, or sworn statement, she provided to
lawyers in Paula Jones' sexual harassment lawsuit. In that
document, Lewinsky denied having sex with Clinton. Telling grand
jurors something different would mean one version was perjury,
which is a felony.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's immunity-for-testimony deal increases the pressure on
Clinton _ who has denied having sex with the former aide or urging
anyone to lie _ as he mulls how to respond to a subpoena to appear
before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to downplay this latest development in the six-month
sex-and-perjury investigation, White House spokesman Mike McCurry
said the president ``is pleased that things are working out'' for
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Brushing aside assertions that Lewinsky's impending grand jury
testimony would contradict Clinton's statements, McCurry said that
under the agreement ``she's going to give complete and truthful
testimony, and if she does, that should present no problem to the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the situation is working out for the president,
McCurry replied: ``It will eventually ... because sooner or later,
this matter will come to some kind of end. And it would help.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said the president and White House lawyers had not
decided yet whether to ask the Supreme Court to overturn a federal
appeals court ruling issued Monday compelling Deputy White House
Counsel Bruce Lindsey, Clinton's longtime friend and confidant, to
cooperate with Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said Clinton also talked with his private lawyer, David
Kendall, about the subpoena from Starr seeking the president's
testimony before the grand jury. Later, Kendall and representatives
from Starr's office were seen entering the federal courthouse for a
meeting with U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson, who is
overseeing the grand jury being used by Starr in the Lewinsky case.
The lawyers left an hour later without commenting.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton could challenge Starr's subpoena, it appeared that
the president was prepared to provide testimony for grand jurors if
he could do it without a history-making trip to the federal
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, grand jurors were hearing testimony from Secret
Service officers and from Linda Tripp, whose secret tape recordings
of conversations with Lewinsky triggered Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement read by her spokesman, Tripp said she was
encouraged by the deal worked out to secure testimony from
Lewinsky. ``It now appears that Monica Lewinsky is prepared to tell
at least a portion of the truth,'' Tripp said. ``I encourage her
and all other witnesses not only to tell the truth but to tell the
whole truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's tapes reportedly caught Lewinsky describing an 18-month
sexual affair with Clinton and efforts by the president and his
associates to keep it from becoming a part of Jones' lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
