<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTE IS BIG WIN FOR CREDIT UNIONS  
 BY PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - CREDIT   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
The U.S. Senate gave a big boost to credit unions yesterday in
their battle to reverse a U.S. Supreme Court decision that severely
restricts their ability to add new members.
<TEXT>
<P>
   By a 92-to-6 vote, the Senate passed a bill that would let
credit unions add members from outside groups so long as they come
from organizations with fewer than 3,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The motion follows a 411-to-8 vote by the House in April to
overturn the Supreme Court decision that banned federally chartered
credit unions from including more than one group in their
membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an overwhelming victory for consumers and credit
unions who serve them,'' said David Chatfield, president of the
California Credit Union League, which represents more than 600
credit unions serving close to 8 million California members.
</P>
<P>
   Once differences between the Senate and House bills are ironed
out and the resulting bill is signed by the president in an
estimated four to six weeks, Chatfield said, ``Credit unions once
again will be able to serve businesses too small to have credit
unions of their own as they had been able to do before being
stopped by lawsuits by banking associations.''
</P>
<P>
   The California Credit Union League estimates that the ban on
adding members has kept 1,000 consumers a day from joining their
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area institutions that have been hit particularly hard
include Embarcadero Federal Credit Union in San Francisco and New
World Federal Credit Union in the East Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Although the nation's 11,500 nonprofit credit unions have
presented themselves as David-fighting-Goliath banks, the banking
industry has cried foul because credit unions compete with them for
the same customers but pay no corporate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credit unions have a tax subsidy exceeding $1 billion a
year,'' noted Bill McQuillan, president of the Independent Bankers
Association of America. ``A hot dog vendor in any ball park pays
more in federal taxes than the entire credit union industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1934 federal act that established credit unions limited
their membership to ``groups having a common bond of occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, the National Credit Union Administration interpreted
this to mean that credit unions could have several groups of
employees so long as each group had its own common bond.
</P>
<P>
   After credit unions proceeded to add millions of new members,
some banks and the American Bankers Association filed suit in 1990
claiming that the NCUA violated the original Federal Credit Union
Act. The banks won their suit on appeal in 1996, and this past
February, the Supreme Court upheld the bankers.
</P>
<P>
   But in an election year, politicians including California
Senators Dianne Feinstein and Barbara Boxer have overwhelmingly
backed the credit unions.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the legislation passed by the Senate yesterday
faces a few hurdles. It lacks a House provision favored by Clinton
that would require credit unions to follow some of the same
fair-lending rules required of banks. That difference between the
two bills needs to be resolved before it is sent to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything in the Senate bill was good news to credit
unions. Patelco Credit Union chief executive Ed Callahn said he
opposed a provision that sets a cap of 12.25 percent of credit
union assets that can be lent to businesses. But he said that,
overall, the bill was good for U.S. credit unions and their 72
million members.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
