<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THIS WAY LIES MADNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By FRANK RICH   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Capitol police officers Jacob Chestnut and John Gibson had
hardly been declared dead when Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., sent
out a press release arguing that tighter gun control could have
prevented the tragedy. Not missing a beat, Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott was soon arguing that a $125 million bunker-barricade
camouflaged as a visitors' center would repel future assailants.
</P>
<P>
   But in a city where most politicians are so ignorant about
mental illness that they still think that Whitewater, not the
disease of depression, drove Vincent Foster to suicide, no one said
the obvious: It is the gaping cracks in American mental-health
care, not in Capitol security or gun-control laws, that most
clearly delivered Russell Weston Jr. to his rendezvous with
history.
</P>
<P>
   Weston's paranoid schizophrenia surfaced long ago. Yet, as The
New York Times reported, this now 41-year-old man ``received no
regular psychiatric treatment or medication over the last two
decades and (his) family seemed to understand little about how to
seek help for him.'' This is hardly an anomaly.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. E. Fuller Torrey, a psychiatrist who campaigns for better
mental-health care through the Treatment Advocacy Center in
Arlington, Va., says that of the 2 to 2.5 million Americans with
schizophrenia, ``40 percent are not receiving treatment on any
given day.'' Cases like Weston's _ in which a mental patient eludes
follow-up care and medication after a hospital release _ number
``in the hundreds of thousands.''
</P>
<P>
   How does this happen? Nearly as heartbreaking as the preventable
murders of officers Chestnut and Gibson is the plight of Weston's
family. They obviously love their child; they knew he was sick;
they wanted to get him help. But, as Russell Sr. said: ``He was a
grown man. We couldn't hold him down and force the pills into
him.''
</P>
<P>
   A comprehensive system of mental-health services, including
support for parents with sick adult children who refuse treatment,
doesn't exist. If it had, the Westons might have had more success
in rescuing their son _ as might the equally loving family of
Michael Laudor, the Yale Law School prodigy charged last month with
murdering his fiancee.
</P>
<P>
   That safety-net system doesn't exist because mental illness is
still in our culture's shadows _ stigmatized, misunderstood and
therefore the beggar of American health care. Though Weston's home
state of Montana offers particularly skimpy services, the national
baseline is ``not high,'' says Torrey. Poorly covered by health
insurance and spottily served by overcrowded and underfinanced
public institutions, mental illness is ``the last discrimination,''
as Michael Faenza of the National Mental Health Association puts
it, even though we now have the science to treat mental illness at
a success rate comparable to physical illness.
</P>
<P>
   It's not only politicians who are complicit in this
discrimination. The media sometimes compound the ignorance that
feeds it. Too many commentators look at Weston's symptoms _ such as
his paranoid delusions about the CIA _ and lump him in with
gun-toting, anti-government ideologues, making no distinction
between the clinically ill and political extremists.
</P>
<P>
   A Time reporter, on the hapless CNN show ``Newsstand,''
expressed surprise that Weston would so easily be diagnosed as a
paranoid schizophrenic given that he had no previous ``episodes of
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the majority of those ill with paranoid schizophrenia
are not violent, and the disease has no ideology. As Sylvia Nasar's
new book, ``A Beautiful Mind,'' documents, many of Weston's oddest
symptoms (including the conviction he was being beamed encrypted
messages) also characterized the paranoid schizophrenia of John
Nash, the brilliant, nonviolent Princeton mathematician who won the
Nobel Prize in Economics in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1835, one of the first patients at Washington's
government Hospital for the Insane _ as St. Elizabeth's Hospital
was then known _ was Richard Lawrence, a pistol-armed man who tried
and failed to assassinate Andrew Jackson in the Capitol's Rotunda.
He was pronounced not guilty by reason of insanity in a trial whose
jury deliberations took five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   More than a century and a half of medical and economic advances
later, what kind of progress is it that we still so often fail to
treat the mentally ill until after tragedy strikes?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 2221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7221 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-STRIKE-1STLD-WRITE     07-28 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM, UAW REACH AGREEMENT TO END 8-WEEK STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Subs for changes throughout. Adds new 1,000-word 2NDTAKE.) 
(See also GM-OUTLOOK, GM-WORKERS.) 
(ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ General Motors and the United Automobile Workers
agreed Tuesday to end the nearly eight-week strike at two auto
parts factories here, a dispute that has shut down GM assembly
plants across North America, pushed hundreds of thousands of
workers into temporary unemployment and slowed the nation's
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, which is subject to ratification votes Wednesday
morning by workers at both factories, settles a wide range of local
issues at the two factories and at several other GM factories where
workers had threatened to strike.
</P>
<P>
   But the agreement does not directly address national issues that
the union had publicly declared to be driving the strike, such as
GM's push to open new factories overseas or its effort to shrink
its U.S. work force through attrition. These issues can only be
changed through GM's national agreement with the UAW, which expires
in September 1999 and was not changed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement deals with a series of narrow issues. GM promises
not to sell or close before January 2000 either a speedometer and
spark plug factory on strike here or two brake factories in Dayton,
Ohio, where workers had threatened a strike this summer.
</P>
<P>
   GM also agrees to invest $180 million in new equipment at the
other factory on strike here, which makes auto body parts. In
exchange, the automaker gets changes in work rules, notably a 15
percent increase in the number of parts that some welders are
required to make before stopping work.
</P>
<P>
   In February, GM canceled its plans to invest the $180 million
because workers were drawing eight hours pay for four to six hours
of work and were resisting increases in production quotas.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement includes a somewhat surprising element, a promise
by both sides' leaders to have regular meetings as a way to rebuild
their relationship and head off further confrontations. But company
and union officials already meet periodically and have been unable
to bridge disagreements that produce several factory-level strikes
almost every year.
</P>
<P>
   Each side suffered enormous losses. Analysts estimate that GM
lost $3 billion after taxes and saw its sales drop by $12 billion,
the heaviest losses ever incurred by an American company during a
strike, at least before adjusting for inflation. The UAW's 200,000
members lost paychecks totaling $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   GM can recover as much as half of the lost profits by running
its factories around the clock for months to make up for lost
production. UAW workers will earn ample overtime in the coming
weeks, although not enough to balance the paychecks lost during the
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of GM had been rising for the last few days on optimism
about an end to the strike. They rose $1.125 Tuesday, to $74.25,
the highest since their $75.25 price when the dispute began on June
5.
</P>
<P>
   The broad outlines of Tuesday's settlement began to emerge in
the first week of talks. The strike lasted so long partly because
the two sides mistrusted each other and partly because GM raised
the stakes by suing the UAW for the first time since 1937,
contending that the strikes violated the national agreement.
</P>
<P>
   GM withdrew its lawsuit Tuesday, along with a grievance in which
an arbitrator had been expected to rule as soon as Wednesday. While
UAW leaders insisted at a news conference Tuesday afternoon that
they had not been intimidated by GM's legal offensive, a UAW
official who insisted on anonymity said that the union had become
worried that it might lose and stepped up talks on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If the threat of litigation deters the UAW from further strikes
until the national agreement expires, this summer's strikes can be
counted as a small but costly victory for GM. But GM was fortunate
in that its case was assigned to a conservative federal judge who
repeatedly prevented the union from stalling during arbitration,
and the company might not be so fortunate in the future.
</P>
<P>
   But some Wall Street analysts said that the company's losses far
exceeded its gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``This seems like it's just exactly the way it was before,''
said Michael Ward, an auto analyst at Paine Webber. ``I think the
market expected GM to deliver a knockout blow, and they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be four separate votes on ratification; each of the
factories on strike will hold separate votes for assembly line
workers and for skilled craftsmen like electricians. Agreements to
end other recent strikes at GM factories have been easily approved,
and UAW officials expected that Tuesday's agreement would also
pass, although they predicted some grumbling among workers facing
higher production quotas.
</P>
<P>
   In a provision that is likely to raise eyebrows on Wall Street
but improve the odds of ratification, GM will give a week's pay,
about $800, to all striking and laid-off workers who missed a week
of holiday pay early this month because of the strike.
</P>
<P>
   If ratified, Tuesday's accord would allow more than a hundred GM
assembly plants and parts factories nationwide to resume production
over the next week, with the factories on strike going back to work
by Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   GM would recall 189,000 workers that it temporarily laid off
across North America, while its suppliers would bring back tens of
thousands of workers who had been pushed into unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   GM desperately needs to restock its dealerships, many of which
have been picked bare of popular models during the strike. Ronald
Zarrella, GM's group vice president for sales and marketing, warned
earlier this month that GM could lose thousands of customers, never
to return, if it did not settle the strike by mid-July.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   GM's greatest asset has been the millions of Americans who keep
coming back to its dealerships every several years for a new car.
But once these customers try rival brands, they seldom come back,
which is why GM's market share has shrunk from 50 percent in the
late 1970s to 31 percent this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Restarting the world's largest manufacturing system will be a
formidable task. With the strike costing $75 million a day, GM is
likely to undertake a huge airlift of auto parts to assembly plants
as soon as the two factories here reopen, said Michael Robinet, the
managing director of CSM Forecasting, an auto production consulting
firm in Farmington Hills, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes here were particularly acrimonious because both
sides came to see them as struggles over principles. Indeed, Donald
Hackworth, GM's group vice president for North American car
operations, even said early this month that the cost of the strikes
could not be justified financially. Both sides kept raising the
stakes, bringing up new issues or making new threats in the
mistaken belief that the other side would quickly back down.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning, GM executives saw the strikes as a challenge
to their right as managers to decide which factories deserved new
investments and which did not. Union leaders viewed the strikes as
necessary to hold GM to past announcements of investment plans,
notably the $180 million.
</P>
<P>
   GM's decision to remove parts-making equipment from one of the
factories over Memorial Day weekend, fearing a strike, not only
prompted the walkouts but also caused the union's rank and file to
worry that their livelihoods were being threatened, making a
compromise even more difficult. GM returned the equipment on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As the strikes wore on, the UAW began publicly depicting them as
a struggle over whether the world's largest company would remain
committed to investing in its home market or would pursue fatter
profits in foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   But the final settlement here did not address GM's plans to
build assembly plants in Argentina, Brazil, China, Poland and
Thailand, as well as auto parts factories in dozens of countries.
</P>
<P>
   GM has been refurbishing factories in the United States but
seldom building new ones, mainly because its steadily falling
market share has already left it with too many inefficient
factories.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, GM aggravated workers' fears about job losses by
talking publicly about possible factory closings after the strike.
Richard Shoemaker, the UAW's vice president for GM issues, said
Tuesday afternoon that GM officials had not even mentioned the
possibility of factory closings during negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker and Gerald Knechtel, GM's vice president for North
American personnel, said in separate news conferences Tuesday that
there had been no changes in the national agreement, particularly
in the sections dealing with how quickly GM can reduce its work
force.
</P>
<P>
   So even if GM chooses to eliminate unprofitable car models and
close factories _ a decision that GM's board will consider Monday _
it will have to continue paying any workers for whom there are no
longer jobs. This makes it unlikely that GM will embark on an
ambitious reorganization, although it might make a few small moves.
</P>
<P>
   GM began calling for arbitration on June 23, contending that the
strikes here violated the company's national agreement with the
union. The national agreement only allows factory-level strikes
over increases in assembly line speed, subcontracting and health
and safety issues.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW had cited all these issues here but also demanded that
GM invest more money here and guarantee that jobs be preserved _
the same demands that the union has made in more than a dozen other
local strikes over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   When the UAW balked early this month at prompt arbitration, GM
filed suit and won a federal court order requiring that both sides
proceed without delay. UAW leaders concluded on Saturday, the last
of four days of testimony in the arbitration case, that there was
at least a chance that the arbitrator might issue a
precedent-setting decision barring investment issues from
discussion in future factory-level strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's agreement covers the two factories on strike here as
well as a car assembly plant here and parts factories in
Indianapolis and Dayton, Ohio, where workers had also threatened
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement did not include the Saturn factory in Spring
Hill, Tenn., the Corvette factory in Bowling Green, Ky., or a sport
utility vehicle factory in Janesville, Wis., where workers have
also asked permission from the UAW's national leadership to strike.
These factories are unlikely to receive that permission any time
soon.
</P>
<P>
   During the strikes here, GM has lost the production of nearly
500,000 vehicles, the equivalent of four full weeks of production,
and could lose an additional 100,000 or more vehicles as factories
gradually reopen when they receive fresh shipments of parts.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes would have been even costlier had they not included
GM's regularly scheduled summer shutdown over the first two weeks
of July, when all GM factories are closed anyway. By comparison, a
1996 strike at the two brake factories in Dayton, Ohio, lasted only
17 days but prevented GM from producing 180,000 cars and light
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Ballew, who was the Federal Reserve's expert on the auto
industry for many years and who is now the chief economist at J.D.
Power &AMP; Associates, said that the current strike slowed economic
growth by half a percentage point in the second quarter and by an
additional eight-tenths of one percent in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But once GM has finished converting factories to the 1999 model
year over the next couple months, it is likely to run many assembly
plants around the clock, which could increase the nation's economic
output this winter. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
