<HEADER>
A7223 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOLARSHIPS-EDUC-ART     07-28 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOLARSHIPS-EDUC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGES RECHECKING THEIR SCHOLARSHIP MATH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.H., Va., Conn.)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By IAN ZACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sparlha Swaby gleefully pumped her fists last year when she won
two prestigious national scholarships worth a total of $12,000 for
college. But her delight turned to dismay when Stanford University,
upon learning of the awards, took away more than $11,000 from
grants it had promised her.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Swaby's net gain for her efforts was less than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just really, really angry,'' said the normally upbeat
18-year-old from Oyster Bay, N.Y., who will enter her sophomore
year at Stanford in the fall. ``I thought I would get the excess
money. That's the reason I put in so much work trying to get
scholarships my senior year in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Swaby still received a generous Stanford grant, the
university's refusal to use her outside academic prizes to reduce
thousands of dollars in student loans illustrates a long-simmering
debate between families and private scholarship donors on one side
and colleges on the other. Many colleges will reduce some of their
own grants to students who win outside merit-based scholarships,
arguing that it helps them spread around financial aid to the
neediest. The question is just how much of a reduction is fair and
just.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in response to complaints from donors that their gifts are
not making much difference and to criticism that some colleges use
generous national scholarships to shore up their own financial aid
accounts, some colleges appear to be moving toward letting students
keep more of the outside scholarships they win.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, for example, recently announced that it was doing away
with its policy of drastically reducing university grants to offset
any outside awards. Following suit, Williams College and Columbia
University have said they will permit students to keep their
university aid and to apply the outside scholarships first toward
reducing student loans and then federal work-study obligations.
Both Dartmouth College and Yale University say they are looking
more closely at the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finding that we're attracting such outstanding students
that there's a lot more money they're bringing in and we feel we
should allow students to keep more of that,'' said Karl
Furstenberg, Dartmouth's dean of admissions and financial aid. He
added that contributing to the decision was the college's growing
endowment, fed by a booming stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Scholarships have grown, both in number and demand, as families
seek ways to offset costs and reduce college loans, education
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take away an award of almost any size, students feel
the pinch,'' said William Nelsen, president of the Citizen
Scholarship Foundation of America, the nation's largest private,
nonprofit scholarship organization. Moreover, he said, donors are
increasingly vigilant about their gifts. ``When they began to
realize that their work did not really result in a gain for the
local student, we heard about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is nearly impossible to arrive at a precise tally for the
amount of outside scholarships awarded each year because countless
local church and civic groups, like Rotary and Lions clubs, offer
scholarships in every community in the country. But the figure is
at least in the tens of millions of dollars and growing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   The Citizens Scholarship Foundation, for instance, plans to
award 88,000 scholarships worth about $80 million this fiscal year,
up from 49,000 scholarships worth about $58 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation runs the grass-roots Dollars for Scholars
program, which has 780 chapters in the United States that award
scholarships of $500 to $3,000 to high school seniors. The
foundation also manages the scholarship programs of nearly 200
corporations, including Chrysler, CBS and Pepsico. The corporations
alone will give away more than $40 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   About three years ago, after donors large and small complained
that their scholarships were disappearing into financial-aid black
holes, the foundation began requiring colleges to sign a pledge
that they would use at least $1,000 of the awards to reduce student
loans and work-study aid rather than reduce a university
scholarship by a similar amount. About 320 colleges have signed the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Others have refused. In the Byzantine world of college financial
aid, every college has its own method and rationale for dealing
with outside awards. Some institutions, like Rhodes College in
Tennessee, DePauw University in Indiana and Bucknell University in
Pennsylvania, say they allow students to keep 100 percent of
outside scholarships, although those who receive federal aid, like
a Stafford Loan, cannot under federal law keep other scholarships
that exceed their financial needs. Students who do not receive any
financial aid can keep any outside scholarships they earn, no
matter what college they attend.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of many public colleges, the University of Virginia does
not have a formula but lets students on financial aid keep a large
proportion of merit scholarships. ``Some agencies will come to us
and say, Before we make this award to this student, tell us what
you are going to do with it,'' said James Ramsey Jr., a longtime
financial aid official at Virginia. ``If they don't like the
answer, they just might not award it to the student who's coming
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Federation of Teachers of New York City, which awards
about 250 scholarships each year totaling more than $1 million to
city students, says it has waged a 20-year battle with colleges
over their use of the scholarships. ``With the cost going up so
much, shortchanging these students with a partial award is hard on
these kids,'' said the union's scholarships director, Jeffrey
Huart, who called the policies ``ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   The union keeps a list of about a dozen institutions it
considers less than generous. The list reads like a who's who of
America's most prestigious universities: Brown, Dartmouth,
Princeton, Yale, the University of Chicago, Georgetown, Duke.
</P>
<P>
   At these institutions, students usually receive a preliminary
financial aid award when they are accepted, but colleges often
reduce the award after students report additional income, including
scholarships.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
