<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOLARSHIPS-EDUC-ART     07-28 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOLARSHIPS-EDUC-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: including scholarships. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvard University, for instance, subjects all outside
scholarships to a ``60-40 split.'' For a student who receives a
$3,000 merit scholarship, the university will deduct 60 percent, or
$1,800, from its own scholarship award and use $1,200 to reduce the
student's loan or work study-aid, usually referred to as ``self
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Princeton, Yale and Brown use the first $500 from any outside
scholarship to reduce ``self-help'' aid, then employ a 50-50 split.
</P>
<P>
   ``These local groups that are having these bake sales and
holding these lotteries, if they knew where their dollars were
going, if they knew that 50 percent wasn't going to the kid, they'd
be real ticked off,'' said Michael Mallory, director of the Ron
Brown Scholars program, the most lucrative scholarship in the
country for black students.
</P>
<P>
   Mallory was beside himself when he learned how the Ron Brown
scholarships were used at some institutions last year to reduce a
large share of university scholarship awards. Some of the student
recipients, he said, come from poor backgrounds and could not
afford simple necessities like a winter coat or health insurance,
even after receiving the $10,000-a-year scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents should know that they should always wait to get
initial letters from institutions before they notify them of
outside scholarships,'' Mallory advised. ``Then they can compare.''
</P>
<P>
   The elite colleges defend their methods, noting that unlike most
other colleges, they practice ``need blind'' admissions, meaning
they admit students regardless of whether they can pay and provide
tens of millions of dollars a year in university grants to offset
the cost of tuition. Outside scholarships, they say, help them
spread out aid to students who may need it more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we feel we're a little unfairly compared to other
schools because we are meeting full need,'' said Donald Routh,
Yale's director of financial aid. But he said the university was
looking at a possible change in policy because of critics like the
United Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   While some education experts counsel families to shop around for
the best deal, others caution that academic rigor _ and not a few
thousand dollars in scholarships _ should determine college choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think to borrow ten to twelve thousand dollars to fund a
Dartmouth education is a good investment that we know repays itself
many times over in the course of a lifetime,'' said Furstenberg,
the college's financial aid director, noting that consumers gladly
plunk down more for a luxury automobile. ``To single out education
seems a bit odd to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
