<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7236 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYMINGTON-DEBT-AZR &LR;      07-28 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYMINGTON-DEBT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER ARIZONA GOV. SYMINGTON ASKS REPAYMENT ORDER BE OVERTURNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Former Arizona Gov. Fife Symington has asked a
superior court to overturn a judgment that ordered him to repay
$8.8 million he used to develop a downtown Phoenix property.
</P>
<P>
   Symington borrowed the money in the late 1980s to build the
Mercado shopping complex at Seventh and Van Buren streets and did
not repay the money when the project failed. In 1995, Symington
sought refuge from the debt in U.S. Bankruptcy court, shortly after
the pension funds obtained the $8.8 million judgment.
</P>
<P>
   In a motion filed last week in Maricopa County Superior Court,
Symington claimed that pension funds that loaned him the money had
concealed vital information from the court that could have reduced
the size of the judgment.
</P>
<P>
   The pension funds pursued Symington into Bankruptcy Court to
keep the debt from being erased, and that case is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   With interest on the judgment, Symington now owes the pension
funds more than $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   All his other debts have since been discharged by the bankruptcy
court.
</P>
<P>
   To block discharge of Symington's Mercado debt, the pension
funds must prove that the former governor defrauded them by lying
about his financial condition when he landed the loan in the late
1980s. Symington personally guaranteed the loan, which went into
default.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy dispute could go to trial late this year.
</P>
<P>
   The new battle in superior court is a sidelight to the
bankruptcy case, but it is important to Symington.
</P>
<P>
   If the 1995 judgment is vacated, the amount Symington owes the
pension funds would again be open to legal debate. A vacated
judgment could reduce the sum he owes the pension funds if the
bankruptcy court refuses to erase the debt completely.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Manning, attorney for the pension funds, predicted the
ex-governor's debt would be reduced by no more than one third if he
prevails in the motion he filed last week.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, that would leave Symington owing more than $10 million
to the pension funds.
</P>
<P>
   Manning called Symington's latest filing ``another delaying
tactic, an act of pathetic desperation. It'll cost the pension
funds more money and more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shull, Symington's attorney, countered that the action
``isn't a delay tactic at all.'' He said Symington ``has been
regularly asking the court to set this case for trial. It is they
who keep asking for more time.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
