<SLUG> BC-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROTHERS GROW NEW VISION`S REVENUE TO $200 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
 VISION-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JANE LARSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Jason Boreyko was carrying bags and driving golf carts
at a Phoenix resort when he asked for a 25-cent-an-hour raise and
was turned down.
</P>
<P>
   B.K. Boreyko worked his share of nights and weekends as a
wedding photographer, then got ``a real job'' in direct-mail
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Both were frustrated with long hours and low wages. So the
brothers, who got their start packing boxes for their father's
Amway business, turned back to their roots: network marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the prime aspects of network marketing is
self-development. I'm a prime example,'' Jason said. ``I couldn't
get a 25-cent raise, but the hotel's reservations manager now runs
my convention department.''
</P>
<P>
   Schooled by their parents' years in Amway and Matol Botanical
International distributorships, the Boreykos started New Vision
International Inc., which sells nutritional and other products
through a national network of independent distributors. Since its
founding in 1995, the company has grown so rapidly that this year
it earned the Boreykos recognition as Emerging Entrepreneurs of the
Year in the annual competition sponsored by Ernst &AMP; Young
accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   New Vision is already working out of its third building, having
outgrown 2,000-square-foot and 9,000-square-foot locations in the
Phoenix area. The company moved to Tempe, Ariz., last fall after
pouring $5 million into renovating and equipping a vacant furniture
store.
</P>
<P>
   The company ships 7,000 to 10,000 packages per shift, filling
three tractor-trailers daily for U.S. Postal Service delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers' growing interest in alternative medicines and in
home-based businesses have helped fuel their success, the Boreykos
say.
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneur of the Year judges first were impressed by the
company's growth, to nearly $190 million in sales in two years,
said Quinn Williams, a Phoenix lawyer who headed the selection
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second was their personal commitment and vision to create
a company focused on helping others,'' a vision the brothers are
able to communicate to their distributors and customers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   New Vision distributors sell 32 products across four product
lines: nutritional supplements, sports supplements, diet aids and
skin-care products.
</P>
<P>
   The products are made according to the company's proprietary
formulations and under a private label by four manufacturers, B.K.
said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has 700,000 customers who, following a Price
Club-like philosophy, are referred to as ``members'' and allowed to
buy products at wholesale prices. California, Arizona, Washington,
Texas and Florida are the biggest states for New Vision sales,
although 40 percent of its orders come from east of the
Mississippi, B.K. said.
</P>
<P>
   Of its customers, about 35,000 have part-time, home-based
businesses selling New Vision products, he says. The company soon
will go national with an infomercial promoting network marketing
and New Vision's potential as a home-based business.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest things that affects a family's life is that
they're able to have common goals. Even if it's little kids helping
out doing mailings to their downline members, the family can get
together as a group and go in the same direction. And that's unique
in today's society,'' B.K. said.
</P>
<P>
   The Boreyko family's solidarity, though, was tested more than
once in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Dorothy fell ill with a brain tumor, and the search for
treatment failed to save her life and bankrupted the family. Later
that year, Matol Botanical filed for bankruptcy reorganization,
leaving distributors without paychecks and others in the network
turning to the Boreykos to start something new.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad had 27 years invested into his network. . . . He's
thinking his whole life's work is going to unravel because of bad
decisions at corporate. And he told Jason and me, `I got you this
far. You take it the rest of the way,' '' B.K. recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The odds were against them, Jason says, because running a
company takes quite different skills from selling products.
</P>
<P>
   But the brothers, their two sisters and father kicked in to
start New Vision. B.K. took the name from a Sunday sermon. The
family developed the health and fitness focus from their mother's
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Her favorite saying, ``Dream big dreams. Small ones have no
magic,'' has become their motto.
</P>
<P>
   Whether New Vision-type products would have helped Dorothy
Boreyko is a question the family can't answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to think about it too much. . . . Cancer is a weird
thing,'' B.K. said.
</P>
<P>
   New Vision catalogs note that its statements about products
influencing everything from mood swings to athletic performance
have not been evaluated by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration.
The FDA doesn't regulate the nutrition industry, but the Boreykos
admit they've benefited from Congress' 1994 act lifting
restrictions on companies' claims.
</P>
<P>
   The company is debt-free, Jason said. His parents' experience
taught him the importance of not accumulating debt, something New
Vision tries to instill in its distributors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   New Vision's growth has not come without problems. For a year
callers were greeted with busy signals from a phone system that
couldn't handle the high volume of calls and had to be continually
upgraded. Early on, New Vision also outsourced its computer
services, but when sales hit $500,000 and the contractor couldn't
keep up, Jason scrambled to find a location and equipment to take
the service in-house.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 United Parcel Service strike nearly paralyzed the
company, leaving about 40,000 boxes sitting in Kentucky and costing
the company a couple million dollars to ship duplicate orders.
</P>
<P>
   Competition looms, too, from network-marketing rivals and local
health-food stores.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers wonder whether New Vision can sustain its growth.
But the brothers say they've brought in an experienced management
team to help carry out their vision. They added operations in
Canada this year and plan to move into the Mexico and South America
markets in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The company's in-house research-and-development department is
constantly looking for new studies and research on health
discoveries, B.K. said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to empower people with knowledge on why they need to
take these supplements, rather than just hyping them on the
benefits. Because if you teach a person why they need to take an
antioxidant, they're going to take it for the rest of their life,''
he said. ``And that really is the key to our long-term growth and
stability.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
NEW VISION INTERNATIONAL &QC; 
_Headquarters: 1920 E. Broadway Road, Tempe, AZ 85282
</P>
<P>
   _Management: B.K. and Jason Boreyko, co-chief executive officers
</P>
<P>
   _Year founded: 1995
</P>
<P>
   _Business: Network marketing of nutritional and other products
</P>
<P>
   _Employees: 250
</P>
<P>
   _Annual revenue: $200 million
</P>
<P>
   _Internet address: www.new-vision-intl.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jane Larson can be reached at 444-8280 or jane.larson(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
