<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT COMFORT LEVEL, COWBOYS' '97 ROOKIES EXPECT MORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The thing to remember about an NFL rookie
is that he's really just a college kid a few months removed from
being a Big Man On Campus.
</P>
<P>
   Drop him into his first pro training camp with a group of
skeptical veterans and he's probably going to feel a lot like a
college freshman: uncertain, uncomfortable, a bit out of place. Not
only does he not know the plays, he doesn't know the players.
</P>
<P>
   His performance can suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Cowboys second-year players say, that one year of
experience makes all the difference in the world of pro football.
And that offers hope for a team looking to build a foundation for
the future. The Cowboys draftees and rookie free-agent class of
1997, featuring starters Dexter Coakley and Richie Cunningham, met
or exceeded expectations of most observers last season, and class
members say they should be even better in 1998 with a year of games
behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tremendous amount of pressure is relieved off of you in your
second year,'' said tight end David LaFleur, the former Louisiana
State star who was the Cowboys' top draft choice last year. ``In
your second year, you know what to expect. You're more relaxed.
You're not all wigged out about what camp's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Cowboys' second-year players will be counted on to
take on more prominent roles this season. LaFleur will start at
tight end. Place kicker Cunningham and punter Toby Gowin are
expected to duplicate their success of last year. Coakley has all
his physical assets plus a year's experience at outside linebacker.
Reserves such as defensive backs Kevin Mathis and Omar Stoutmire,
defensive tackle Antonio Anderson, wide receiver Macey Brooks and
fullback Nicky Sualua are expected to improve and provide quality
depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a pretty good group last year,'' LaFleur said.
``Everybody pretty much stood up and contributed. Hopefully, we'll
grow together. We've got a great nucleus. We've got a great veteran
group with three Super Bowl rings, and they're going to be around a
long time, but obviously you've got to start building for the
future some time. Hopefully, we can stick together and bring more
championships to Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   LaFleur says his rookie NFL camp and his freshman college camp
were his two worst, and for some of the same reasons. Not all those
reasons are related to football technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot like college,'' LaFleur said of a rookie's camp
life. ``You get an empty feeling sometimes. You're back in a dorm
room _ and a dorm room's not the most glorious place to be. It can
get awfully lonely if you're just practicing and coming back to the
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Wheaton, a second-year cornerback from Oregon, agrees.
``The first year you come in, you don't know the guys so you keep
to yourself,'' Wheaton said. ``You can feel kind of lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, he says, things change.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the season goes along, (the veterans) take you under their
wing,'' Wheaton said. ``The second season you're a lot more
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the personal side of a rookie's life, there is the
football element. There, too, major leaps forward can be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a huge difference from last year just by my first two
weeks in camp,'' said Anderson, a fourth-round pick in 1997 from
Syracuse. ``You get a full off-season. You get to watch more film.
Leon Lett's back this year, and I get to work with him and Chad
(Hennings). Those guys have been instrumental. And Coach (Jim)
Bates, the technique he's gone over with me has helped
tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coaches expect significant improvement from second-year
players, offensive line coach Hudson Houck said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One more year of experience, it's a big difference,'' Houck
said. ``It's having that many more snaps knowing what to expect,
and knowing what our coaching philosophy is. It's knowing the
techniques and knowing the people around them.''
</P>
<P>
   Houck said a player's ``surroundings are a factor. Just where
they're living,'' he said. ``Their personal life.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important, he said, are ``the surroundings of the
football team: who's playing on the right and who's playing on the
left side of them. The more you know what your job is the more
aggressively you can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham said that despite their success last season, 1997's
rookies can't take it easy this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't become complacent,'' Cunningham said. ``You can't
think that just because it's your second year you can take it easy.
If we don't do our jobs, they'll find someone else to come in and
do them.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, for one, said he's not going to let that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little rap on me saying I faded toward the end of last
year, and I want to show the coaches I won't fade out,'' Anderson
said. ``I want to show them that I'll play the whole 16 games like
I did at the beginning of the season. I wasn't as prepared as I
should have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's rookies say they share something more than a work
ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we feed off each other,'' Wheaton said. ``We see each
other doing good, and we want to do good, too. We take pride in the
'97 group and just feel we have something to prove.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
