<SLUG> BC-TEN-LAVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAVER IS CONSCIOUS, IN SERIOUS CONDITION AFTER STROKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SUSAN B. ADAMS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rod Laver, the only tennis player to twice win the four Grand
Slam tournaments in one year, was conscious and off the critical
list Tuesday, a day after he had a stroke while being interviewed
for a television show about the century's greatest athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Laver, who turns 60 on Aug. 9, was in serious condition in the
intensive care unit at UCLA Medical Center in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely not paralyzed,'' Dr. Neil Martin, co-director
of the hospital's stroke center, told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   But, Martin said, Laver ``is not entirely out of the woods
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Laver was still having some difficulty speaking and had some
problems with his right arm and right leg. He will probably remain
in the hospital for a week to 10 days, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   An ESPN spokesman, Rob Tobias, told The Associated Press that
Laver had sustained the stroke Monday afternoon during an interview
at the Westwood Marquis Hotel, only a few blocks from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A dynamic, left-handed redhead, Laver not only won two Grand
Slams, but also inspired players like John McEnroe, Martina
Navratilova and Pete Sampras. Laver epitomized the all-court attack
that brought Australians to the forefront of the game in the 1940s
and '50s, but he also integrated heavy topspin to create a style
uniquely his own. After Laver, topspin became an elemental part of
the world-class game, practiced most notably by Bjorn Borg.
</P>
<P>
   Laver's formidable combination of power and spin, as well as his
foot speed and desire, more than offset his modest size. He was the
world's No. 1-ranked player in 1961, 1962, 1968 and 1969, and was
inducted into the International Tennis Hall of Fame in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Laver won the coveted All-England singles crown four times and
was a finalist six years, including four straight (1959-62), before
being banned for five years when he turned professional.
Professionals were not allowed to play against amateurs until 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his return to Wimbledon, Laver won the singles title in
1968 and '69. By advancing to the fourth round in 1970, he set a
Wimbledon record for men by winning 31 consecutive matches from
1960 to 1970. Borg topped that record in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Laver won 11 major singles titles, which places him in second
place with Borg and Sampras on the men's career list, behind Roy
Emerson with 12.
</P>
<P>
   Laver's total of 20 major titles in singles, doubles and mixed
are fifth behind Emerson (28), John Newcombe (25), Frank Sedgman
(22) and Bill Tilden (21). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
