<HEADER>
A7245 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOVERNOR-MILLER-COX     07-28 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVERNOR-MILLER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miller to become professor at UGA
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Following in the footsteps of other Georgia
elected officials, Gov. Zell Miller will move from the political to
the educational realm when he returns to his alma mater, the
University of Georgia, as a chaired professor in the Institute of
Higher Education after his terms ends in January.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who earned both a bachelor's and a master's degree at
Georgia in the 1950s, will be the first holder of the Philip H.
Alston Jr. Chair, UGA officials said Tuesday. Emory University and
Young Harris College also have announced that Miller will teach at
their schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that when the history of Georgia, and maybe American
education, is written, there will be few American governors who've
had as profound an effect on schools and learning as Zell Miller,''
said Rep. Louise McBee (D-Athens). ``What a wonderful thing it is
for students to have the privilege of learning from a practitioner
and a scholar with four books. He'll be a real asset to the
university.''
</P>
<P>
   UGA President Michael Adams will make a formal announcement
about the appointment today at a 10 a.m. ceremony, which will be
attended by Miller, McBee, state officials and Alston family
members. Miller was on campus Tuesday for a closed reception with
Adams and other officials.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Bentley, Miller's press secretary, said the governor would
not comment Tuesday on the appointment. It is unclear how Miller
will split his time between the three schools.
</P>
<P>
   Elkin Goddard Alston gave the university $1 million to fund the
chair in honor of her late husband, a UGA alumnus, prominent
Atlanta civic and business leader and a partner in the law firm of
Alston &AMP; Bird.
</P>
<P>
   A 1932 graduate of the university, Philip Alston earned a law
degree from Emory and further studied at Harvard before joining
Alston, Miller &AMP; Gaines, founded by his father and uncle. Alston
served as U.S. ambassador to Australia during the Carter
administration and on the state Board of Regents. He died in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Among politicians-turned-part-time-professors, Miller joins the
likes of Sen. Sam Nunn (D-Ga.), who began teaching at Georgia Tech
after resigning from the U.S. Senate, and President Jimmy Carter,
who began teaching at Emory University after leaving the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. David Boren (D-Okla.) became president of the University of
Oklahoma after resigning from the U.S. Senate, while former
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander briefly served as president of the
University of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year or so, UGA has seen an influx of former state
government employees into its work force.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are Hank Huckabee, former director of the state
Office of Planning and Budget and of Georgia State University's
Georgia Fiscal Research Program. He is now the director of UGA's
Carl Vinson Institute of Government, where former state Department
of Family and Children Services Director Michael Thurmond is on
leave from a one-year appointment as a distinguished practitioner.
</P>
<P>
   Also on staff at the Institute of Government are Steve Wrigley,
who worked as executive secretary in Miller's office; Grady
Cornish, who worked in the secretary of state's office; and Larry
Gess, a former Office of Planning and Budget employee who worked
with Huckabee at Georgia State.
</P>
<P>
   At UGA, Miller is expected to teach political science and to
work with graduates and undergraduates in the Institute of Higher
Education and the Franklin College of Arts and Sciences. He briefly
taught history and political science at UGA and Young Harris
College before launching his political career decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Miller came to UGA intending to study law but was, he has said,
``mesmerized'' by history professor E. Merton Coulter, who
supervised Miller's master's degree in history. UGA officials said
that one of the governor's most prized possessions is a letter from
Coulter telling Miller that he expected him to some day be governor
of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
