<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-TENNIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IVANISEVIC SINKS FURTHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)(WILL BE UPDATED) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Goran Ivanisevic doesn't handle disappointment
well. Three weeks ago he lost the Wimbledon final and mused about
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   So one only wonders what dark emotional depths the Croation was
exploring Tuesday afternoon after a straight-sets loss to France's
Guillame Raoux at the Mercedes-Benz Cup.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, all anyone could do was wonder, because Ivanisevic the
Irritable wasn't talking after Raoux ousted him 6-4, 6-4 in a
first-round match at Los Angeles Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe Ivanisevic had already said it all DURING the match,
when he held an impromptu debate with umpire Bjorn Bork, muttered
to linesmen and on one occasion slammed his racket into the
sea-blue Pacific Pave.
</P>
<P>
   What was clear is that Ivanisevic had barely touched a racket
since Pete Sampras beat him in England, an event so devastating
that the Croat said afterward, ``I cannot cheer anybody now. I can
only kill myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Only his game was dead Tuesday, to the delight of Raoux, who
registered the tournament's second upset of the day by knocking off
the No. 3 seed. Sixth-seed Wayne Ferreira of South Africa also
lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't look like someone who practiced hard for three
weeks,'' said Raoux, who beat Ivanisevic for the first time in
three tries. ``It was very tough for him to lose the (Wimbledon)
final. Maybe he's still thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic never had control of his game, or his emotions, and
his vaunted serve was erratic. His 14 aces were offset by eight
points lost on double faults in the second set, including three
straight in the third game (which he won anyway).
</P>
<P>
   It was during that marathon game, which went to deuce five
times, that Ivanisevic began to unravel. He kicked the ball after
squandering the advantage the second time, and after the third lost
opportunity he sat on the net post and chatted with Bork, while
Raoux waited patiently at his end of the court.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion ended after Ivanisevic grabbed a bottle of water,
opened it and handed it to the umpire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting for his mistakes,'' Raoux said. Of Ivanisevic's
antics, he said, ``It's part of the game. I don't care. I just
concentrate on my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic, ranked 17th in the world, was scheduled to play an
evening doubles match, paired with Paul Kilderry against Doug Flach
and Michael Tebbutt.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Henman of England, a Wimbledon semifinalist, was only the
third seeded player to win this week. The No. 2 seed easily
defeated Grant Stafford of South Africa 6-3, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   With seeded players falling, and two having dropped out with
injury (Sampras and Thomas Enqvist), Henman's first L.A. appearance
might become a memorable one. He's not assuming anything, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are very good (seeded) players that have lost.... Those
are so-called upsets, but when you've got (Andre) Agassi and
(Patrick) Rafter in the draw, that shows the depth of men's
tennis,'' Henman said.
</P>
<P>
   In other matches Tuesday: Sargis Sargsian of Armenia defeated
Ferreira 6-1, 6-2; eighth seed Vincent Spadea of Chicago defeated
Marcos Ondruska of South Africa 2-6, 6-3, 6-3; Manhattan Beach's
Jeff Tarango defeated Mexico's Alejandro Hernandez 6-2, 6-2, and
Santa Monica's Michael Joyce defeated Australian Michael Tebbutt
7-5, 2-6, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   In the late match, No. 1 seed Patrick Rafter of Australia was
scheduled to play Ramon Delgado of Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, Australian Sandon Stolle (subbing for injured No. 4
seed Thomas Enqvist) defeated 17-year-old Taylor Dent of Newport
Beach 6-3, 6-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
