<SLUG> BC-BOX-GOODWILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TEAM SURPRISES CUBAN BOXERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In terms of the U.S. Boxing team, youth and
inexperience, like ignorance, is bliss _ at least as it pertains to
having to face the Cuban boxing team, traditionally one of the
toughest in international competition.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest upset of the Goodwill Games quarterfinals was turned
in early in the evening Tuesday by Roberto Benitez, a 17-year-old
New York native who had fought just five times internationally.
Behind a point in the final round of his 112-pound bout, Benitez
overtook Manual Mantilla, the world champion from Cuba, by 12-8.
</P>
<P>
   It raised the Americans' record against Cuba to 3-1 for the day,
far beyond expectations for a squad which failed to win a medal in
the last world championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proving to the world,'' said Benitez.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez said he regretted being caught in reckless exchanges
with Mantilla, but they also gave him confidence. `'I was thinking,
wow, here I am 17 years old and just taking it to him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez tied Mantilla at 8-8 with a looping left, then surprised
him with a series of rights to take a 10-8 lead with a minute left.
A fatigued Mantilla dropped his hands, and Benitez drilled him with
two more lefts before the final bell sounded.
</P>
<P>
   The most stunning upset of the afternoon session was pulled off
by the youngest member of the U.S. team, Ricardo Williams Jr. of
Cincinnati, who recently turned 17. Williams defeated Damian
Echemendia, 24, of Cuba by 6-2 in a 139-pound bout. Earlier in the
afternoon, Teaunce Shepherd, 20, of Marquette, Mich., beat
Rudinelson Bell of Cuba, 16-3, in the 125-pound division.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Cubans' veil of invincibility had been lifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a long camp and they cried a lot, but it's working,''
said Al Mitchell, who is listed as adviser to the U.S. team. ``It's
a young team and we're pushing them right out into the fire. We've
got a good group of young guys. Half of the team is under 19 years
old.''
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd dropped Bell with a left hand in the third round,
igniting the pro-U.S. crowd and lighting a fuse for his teammates.
But Anthony Stewart of Chicago could not help the U.S. team get an
afternoon sweep as he lost, 7-2, to Israel Alvarez of Cuba in a
178-pound bout.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who was the 1996 U.S. Olympic boxing coach, was
ebullient over the performance of his team and its future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the right time to be meeting the Russians and the
Cubans,'' Mitchell said Tuesday of his youngsters. ``The experience
they're getting here at these matches is going to help them get
ready for the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   During the quarterfinals on Monday, the U.S. team didn't fare as
well against the Cubans, posing an 0-2 mark. But Benitez, Williams
and Shepherd made amends Tuesday, taking their fights right to
their Cuban opponents, frequently beating them to the punch and
establishing their jabs.
</P>
<P>
   Echemendia, who is vastly more experienced than Williams, is
probably the most technically sound boxer on the Cuban team. He won
an amateur world championship in the 139-pound weight class in
1993. If Williams was afraid, it didn't show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coach had been telling us in training camp that you have
to take the Cubans' heart,'' said Williams, who is making his debut
in international competition after an intense four-week training
camp in Colorado Springs, Colo., and Lake Placid, N.Y. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
