<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-PHONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICAN PHONE WORKERS VOTE TO END STRIKE, WITH GOAL UNMET 
 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico, _ Telephone workers here voted Tuesday to
end their 41-day strike, with their goal of halting the
government's sale of the Puerto Rico Telephone Company unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   After a tentative agreement was negotiated on Friday, the 6,400
workers voted for the settlement by an overwhelming majority, union
leaders said. The workers are expected to return to their jobs on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The strike interrupted telephone service to 300,000 homes on
this island of 3.7 million residents, and strike-related vandalism
caused an estimated $10 million in damage to telephone company
installations. But the strike by two unions did not stop the sale,
which the unions feared would cause layoffs or force the government
to hold a referendum on the deal. In the end, the unions succeeded
only in protecting themselves from legal action by the company, and
gaining the support of many Puerto Ricans who saw the state-owned
utility as a symbol of national pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ended the strike, but the struggle against the sale
continues,'' said Jose Juan Hernandez, president of the Independent
Telephone Workers Union, the larger of two unions, representing
4,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said the unions will continue to fight the sale
through protests, a court battle and by lobbying Federal
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The strike began on June 18, when the proposed sale of the
telephone company to a consortium led by the GTE Corp., based in
Stamford, Conn., was still awaiting approval by the island's
legislature. The legislature has since approved the measure, which
was signed into law by Gov. Pedro Rossello. The deal must still be
approved by the Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The high point of the strike was a 48-hour general strike by
tens of thousands of workers from more than 50 unions who walked
off their jobs on July 7 to support the 6,400 telephone strikers.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders said they created an environment that forced GTE
to better its original offer. During the strike, Spain's Telefonica
Internacional S.A. put in a counteroffer for the telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to that bid, GTE increased its offer to $2.01 billion
from $1.85 billion. The company also agreed not to dismiss current
employees without just cause and pledged not to increase local
calling rates. The government said it had accepted GTE's new bid on
July 22.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, strikers will receive a letter of
reprimand that is to be removed from their personnel files after
six months.
</P>
<P>
   The government pledged not to take any legal action against the
unions for the strike but said it would press criminal cases
against workers involved in sabotage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
