<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GENERAL MANAGER PUTS FEATHER IN GIANTS CAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ For the first time since Ernie Accorsi succeeded
George Young as the New York Giants' general manager on Jan. 8, he
had a chance to catch his breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the agent finally called me back,'' Accorsi said, ``we
got it done.''
</P>
<P>
   With the signing of Joe Jurevicius (pronounced Jur-a-vicious) to
a three-year $1.4 million contract, all the Giants' draft choices
were signed and in training camp at the State University of New
York at Albany. Even better, the Giants were about $1.4 million
under the National Football League's salary cap of $52.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``George used to tell me, `The cap is the first thing I think of
when I wake up and the last thing I think of before I go to bed,'''
Accorsi said. ``And I would ask him, `When do you sleep?'''
</P>
<P>
   At least Accorsi can sleep knowing that all his players are
signed, which isn't true of every NFL team. In too many other
years, that wasn't true of the Giants either. Young endured long,
bitter holdouts with Lawrence Taylor, Phil Simms and Carl Banks.
</P>
<P>
   As the Giants prepare to defend the National Conference East
title, Accorsi is the big change from last year to this.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to be under the cap,'' he said, ``because you never
know when you'll need to use that money.''
</P>
<P>
   The new general manager was sitting in his second-floor office
in the recreation and conference center just up the grassy slope
from the football fields where the Giants were perspiring. But he
doesn't consider the team's restored stature to be a burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the team did last year made it better for me,'' he said.
``It made it more acceptable that we had the right people here. I
don't mean me. I mean everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all those right people, the most important is Jim Fassel,
knighted as pro football's coach of the year following the Giants'
10-5-1 season that was dimmed by the 23-22 playoff loss to the
Minnesota Vikings. Fassel, who had been hired by Young, is working
with Accorsi, who was Young's assistant for four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here, Ernie was the only person I didn't know,''
said Fassel, who had been a Giants assistant coach in 1991 and
1992. ``I figured Ernie was the heir apparent to George, but I
wondered, `What if our personalities clash?' But they don't. We're
always on the same page. Our philosophy is the same.''
</P>
<P>
   And what is that philosophy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Build through the draft,'' Fassel said. ``Sign your good young
players. The coach coaches the team. We talk two or three times a
day and Ernie has told me, `If things get rough, I'll be right
behind you.'''
</P>
<P>
   With the usual divisional rivals plus visits by the Super Bowl
champion Denver Broncos, the Packers and the Chiefs as well as
visits to San Francisco and Tampa Bay, things could get rough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ernie knows what to expect,'' said Wellington Mara, the
Giants' co-owner. ``He's paid his dues. Before he came to us, he
was the Colts' general manager for two years and the Browns'
general manager for seven years. He knows the league. He knows the
collective bargaining agreement. He knows the cap. And he
communicates well. He makes it his business to be sure I'm
informed.''
</P>
<P>
   Informed about what?
</P>
<P>
   ``About everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Rooney, now in his 14th season as the Giants' director of
pro personnel, described how Accorsi and Young have different
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ernie is more open initially,'' Rooney said, ``while George is
the elephant in the trees; he takes the measure of the man before
he commits.''
</P>
<P>
   But in evaluating scouting reports, Rooney considered them alike
as general managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They defer to the information,'' he said. ``They trust you.
They ask the right questions, such as an injury or a character
situation in a player's background.''
</P>
<P>
   Accorsi is still asking Young questions.
</P>
<P>
   For quite a while, negotiations with Jurevicius stalled because
the wide receiver's agent, Neil Cornrich, refused to return
Accorsi's phone calls. Finally, last Friday, Cornrich phoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I gave him our offer,'' Accorsi said, ``I called George
to ask his advice. In one word with decibels that got louder and
louder, George said: `Sit. Sit. Sit. Sit. Sit.'''
</P>
<P>
   After Jurevicius agreed, Accorsi phoned Young to tell him.
</P>
<P>
   ``All George said,'' he recalled with a laugh, ``was, `See.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 2257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
