<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves notebook: Martinez looking for more work
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ It has been 57 days since Dennis Martinez caught
Juan Marichal, and he came to the park Tuesday, as he has every
day, hoping this would be the game he becomes baseball's leading
Latin American game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday wasn't the day. Martinez pitched three innings and gave
up two hits and one run, raising his ERA to 4.61.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day is a chance,'' Martinez said, ``but at the same
time, as it gets longer, when I haven't had a chance to pitch for a
week or eight or nine days, I feel like, what am I going to the
ballpark for? I've been in that situation off and on and I feel
sometimes I'm not there. I'm just here for the sake of being here.
I want to be here to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   As the bullpen has solidified in recent weeks, Martinez's
opportunities have become more sporadic, even though his
performance has remained statistically consistent. Over his past 25
appearances, his ERA is 3.12, including Saturday's ludicrous
two-run inside-the-park homer by Turner Ward in Pittsburgh. Stuck
at 243 career wins, he has worked just 6 1/3 innings this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had a chance to do it consistently because everybody
in the bullpen is doing great, which is fine,'' he said. ``But I
feel like I got put in a situation where sometimes, there is no
need to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the reason is Rudy Seanez, who has gone from the last
man in the bullpen to taking over the right-handed set-up role.
Martinez most frequently finds work when a starter lasts just five
or six innings, which isn't happening often.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying my best to help them in the bullpen,'' said
Martinez (2-4). ``But I still believe I can start. I can help some
other clubs that need one.''
</P>
<P>
   The art of the deal
</P>
<P>
   General manager John Schuerholz is known for waiting until the
last hours before the trade deadline, but the longer this week
goes, the suspicion grows hat the Braves can't get what they want.
Schuerholz has not been able to make a late July trade since 1995
(Mike Stanton to Boston) and has rarely had to deal from this
position _ highly specified needs (lefty set-up man and closer) in
a seller's market.
</P>
<P>
   Danny &AMP; Walt
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Danny Bautista was hobbled but available Tuesday
night while shortstop Walt Weiss is greatly improved but on the
bench. Bautista sustained a Grade 1 sprain to his left ankle when
chasing down a Guillermo Garcia double Monday night and would not
have been able to start if the Reds sent out a left-handed pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss missed his 11th game of the last 12 Tuesday while resting
his left quadriceps. And while Cox could not commit to playing him
before this road trip ends Thursday afternoon, Weiss has begun
limited sprinting and is expected to be near 100 percent when the
club returns home.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones is hitting just .246 since the All-Star break, but
in his first 18 games, he also had five doubles and six stolen
bases. ... Andres Galarraga began play with a .297 average, the
lowest it has been since April 27th, when he was batting .292. ...
Chipper Jones entered Tuesday's game hitting exactly .320 from both
sides of the plate. But he was out for extra batting practice at 2
p.m., honing his left-handed swing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
