<SLUG> BC-BRAVES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millwood folds early in debacle
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Kevin Millwood was poorly treated again Tuesday
night. If an 11-game winner can have a crisis, Millwood sniffs one.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds dropped the Braves 13-1 on the merits of a four-run
second inning. Millwood was lifted by manager Bobby Cox after three
innings, having yielded five runs (four earned runs, including a
Sean Casey home run) on five hits. The night marked Millwood's
third start in his last six that he failed to reach the fourth
inning and upped his ERA to 4.39.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of crises, Mark Wohlers saw his first action in six
days and the results were mixed. He pitched a scoreless seventh but
then stumbled in the eighth, giving up a walk to Eddie Taubensee, a
single to Pokey Reese and back-to-back walks to Melvin Nieves,
Reggie Sanders and Barry Larkin. The Reds scored five times, the
second on a passed ball that almost went over catcher Javy Lopez's
head, the last three after Russ Springer relieved him.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds used a three-hit, one-error second inning for a 4-1
lead, though the trouble was all Millwood's. After Dmitri Young
opened the inning with a walk, Millwood had Willie Greene, Bret
Boone and Taubensee all in 1-2 counts but could retire none of
them. Greene and Boone both singled to load the bases before
Millwood allowed Young to score on a wild pitch before Taubensee
doubled over Ryan Klesko's head.
</P>
<P>
   Reese next grounded to shortstop and while Ozzie Guillen was
playing deep and conceding the run, Greene scored to make it 3-1
and Reggie Sanders' sacrifice fly, for what should have been the
third out, brought in Taubensee.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves went out 1-0 when Barry Larkin couldn't handle
Young's relay throw following a Lopez double.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
