</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MCCALL-DONATIONS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW FIRMS THAT GOT CONTRACTS GIVE TO COMPTROLLER'S CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
   (rl) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The legal contracts were potentially among the most
lucrative ever granted by New York state, offering the dizzying
prospect of tens of millions of dollars in fees. Fourteen law firms
sought the work last year from the state comptroller, H. Carl
McCall, and he retained three, deeming them the most qualified.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the three firms have distinguished themselves in
another way: they have become major financial benefactors of
McCall's re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The three firms and their lawyers gave a total of more than
$165,000 to McCall, one of the state's most powerful Democrats, in
the seven months after he chose them in June 1997, according to
disclosure records. Those donations represented more than 10
percent of the campaign money he collected in that period.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers did more than write checks. At two of the firms,
they also organized fund-raisers for McCall that generated hundreds
of thousands of dollars in additional contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller retained the firms, all of which have close ties
to the Democratic Party, to represent the huge state pension fund
in class-action securities litigation. The job is so potentially
profitable because the firms could reap enormous contingency fees
from the lawsuits that they file on behalf of the $105 billion
fund, which is controlled by McCall and has extensive stock
holdings. Typically, such fees can run as high as 30 percent of the
damages awarded in the cases.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, McCall said that campaign contributions and
political connections had nothing to do with the decision to retain
the three firms. But he also acknowledged that the money
represented what he termed an ``appearance problem.'' He added,
though, that lawyers in his office selected the firms after
rigorously reviewing the qualifications of the 14 that applied,
emphasizing that he merely approved the choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing inappropriate about the money that has been
given to me,'' he said. ``It's all within the rules. The lawyers in
my office who made the recommendations to me had absolutely no
knowledge of who gave me money or wanted to give me money.''
</P>
<P>
   The firms denied that their contributions were linked to
McCall's decision to retain them for the pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are unrelated,'' said Leonard Barrack, a senior partner
at one firm. Barrack, of Barrack, Rodos &AMP; Bacine of Philadelphia,
was named finance chairman of the Democratic National Committee
last February. He is charged with overseeing the party's
fund-raising across the country.
</P>
<P>
   While the three firms have experience in class-action securities
cases and the comptroller described them as the best of the
applicant pool, his office has declined to reveal the names of the
11 firms that were passed over, even though most state agencies
routinely release such information and state law generally requires
it.
</P>
<P>
   McCall has collected nearly $5 million for his re-election
campaign, among the highest totals for candidates for statewide
office this year, and he has $3.5 million in the bank. He is facing
a little-known Republican, Bruce A. Blakeman, a Nassau County
legislator who entered the race in early June and has just begun
raising money.
</P>
<P>
   Like Barrack, Rodos, the two other firms that McCall selected
are no strangers to Democratic politics. Trial lawyers have long
been influential in the party because they are among its largest
donors. But most of the donors from the three firms had not
contributed to McCall's campaign before June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Melvyn Weiss, a senior partner at another of the three firms,
Milberg, Weiss, Bershad, Hynes &AMP; Lerach of Manhattan, was vice
chairman of the New York delegation to the Democratic National
Convention in 1996, and gave a party for delegates at the state
Democratic convention in May.
</P>
<P>
   The third firm is Bernstein, Litowitz, Berger &AMP; Grossmann, one
of whose partners, Max Berger, has also been a big contributor to
Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign contributions by lawyers to elected officials who
control legal contracts have come under growing scrutiny in recent
years, and some lawyers' groups are considering banning the
practice, known as ``pay to play.'' If they do, the groups would be
following the lead of the bond industry, which tightly restricts
political giving.
</P>
<P>
   Asserting that he was concerned about ethics in government,
McCall said he favored a law barring donors who do business with
the state from contributing to candidates for state office. But he
said that until such a ban exists, he would not unilaterally stop
collecting such money.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time that this happens, there is going to be an appearance
problem,'' he said, contending that all prominent state officials
face similar situations. ``That is why we have to change the
rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The retainer arrangements with the three firms do not include a
fixed duration, so it appears that the comptroller can dismiss any
firm at will. Each firm signs a new contract with the office when
he asks it to pursue a lawsuit. The comptroller has discretion in
choosing which firms get cases, said Steven Greenberg, his
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Barrack, Rodos has received one case, and Bernstein, Litowitz
has received two. Milberg, Weiss has not yet received one. Because
no cases are completed, none of the firms has been paid fees so
far.
</P>
<P>
   For the firms, being selected was a coup because of changes in
1995 in Federal law involving class-action securities lawsuits.
Under the new rules, the parties with the biggest financial
interest at stake in a class-action suit are supposed to become the
lead plaintiff, meaning their lawyers handle the case for all the
participants in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   When the New York state pension fund joins a class-action
lawsuit, its stock holdings in the company being sued are often so
large that it is in a position to become the lead plaintiff. The
lawyers for the lead plaintiff earn their fees from the entire
class-action award, not just the part that goes to the lead
plaintiff.
</P>
<P>
   Taking note of the new rules, the comptroller's office decided
for the first time last year to retain lawyers that specialize in
class-action securities lawsuits, the reason it chose the three
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers typically file class-action securities lawsuits on
behalf of the shareholders in a company after the price of its
stock has plunged. The lawyers often charge that the change in the
price is due to some wrongdoing by the company, like fraud, and
demand that shareholders be compensated for their losses.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, these suits fail to garner any money. But if they are
successful, the damages can run to tens or hundreds of millions of
dollars, depending on the losses to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   About a month after his firm was selected in June 1997, Barrack
gave $28,000, the legal limit, to the McCall campaign, according to
disclosure records. Barrack's wife, Lynne, also gave $28,000. In
the last five years, Barrack, his wife and his firm have given more
than $500,000 to Democratic committees and candidates on the
Federal level, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Barrack said he contributed to McCall because he wanted him to
run for governor. At the time of the contributions in July 1997,
McCall was considering entering the gubernatorial race, but a month
later, he decided to run for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is a very important state, and I was encouraging him
to do that,'' Barrack said.
</P>
<P>
   Barrack, Rodos and its lawyers have given a total of $110,000 to
McCall's campaign, including $84,000 after being retained. Earlier
this year, the campaign returned $7,000 that was over the legal
limit.
</P>
<P>
   Berger of Bernstein, Litowitz said members of his firm
contributed $43,050 to the McCall campaign in the seven months
after June 1997 to show their gratitude for McCall's decision to
criticize Texaco at a time the firm was representing Texaco workers
in a lawsuit over hiring and promotion practices.
</P>
<P>
   The McCall campaign collected most of the money at a fund-raiser
at the Harvard Club that Berger sponsored in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a quid pro quo,'' Berger said. ``We thought what he
did was really extraordinary, to come out as a large institutional
investor in Texaco and speak out against workplace
discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers at Milberg, Weiss gave $11,000 to the McCall campaign in
June 1997, soon after the firm was selected. Weiss, the senior
partner at the firm, later was co-chairman of a large McCall
fund-raiser at the Pierre Hotel in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a big supporter of Democrats, and I have been for a long
time,'' Weiss said. ``Carl was our only incumbent at the state
level, and I felt that it was an important race for our party.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the money that the three firms and their lawyers
gave in the seven months after they were retained, Bernstein,
Litowitz contributed $5,000 to the McCall campaign in June.
</P>
<P>
   The contracts with the firms became an issue in July in
litigation that the state pension fund has joined against the
Cendant Corp., which owns such brands as Avis car rentals and
Howard Johnson hotels.
</P>
<P>
   The fund has formed an alliance with the pension funds of
California and New York City, and that alliance is seeking to
become lead plaintiff in a class-action lawsuit against Cendant.
The other funds have agreed that Barrack, Rodos and Bernstein,
Litowitz will represent the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer who has brought his own lawsuit against Cendant said
the pension funds should be disqualified from becoming lead
plaintiff because the campaign contributions from Bernstein,
Litowitz to McCall called into question whether the funds could
insure that the lawyers would receive the lowest possible fees.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Howard Sirota, said he had not been aware of the
contributions from Barrack, Rodos and Milberg, Weiss to McCall.
When told of them, Sirota said: ``There is more here than I knew
about, and there is clearly at this point a lot of fire, not just
smoke. These numbers are staggering.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall's aides refused to say what percentage of any damage
award in the Cendant case would be paid to the two firms. But they
stressed that the fees were on a sliding scale, with the firms
receiving far less if the case is settled quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Cendant's market value dropped $14 billion in the spring after
accounting irregularities were discovered at CUC, a discount
shopping club business that had merged with HFS Inc. to form
Cendant. Cendant's chairman, Walter Forbes, resigned Tuesday after
coming under fire for the irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action lawsuit to recover some of the shareholder
losses could lead to damages in the hundreds of millions of
dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
