<SLUG> BC-BBO-MOST-VALUABLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SLUGGING IT OUT FOR MVP 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ There is excitement here, not electricity. What you
feel is the excitement of a novelty, not the electricity of a
pennant race, where every at-bat is crucial, every pitch matters,
every run is precious.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals players don't sit nervously in the dugout watching the
scoreboard. They sit and watch Mark McGwire hit towering home runs
at a record-setting pace.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere surrounding Busch Stadium is as festive as a
state fair. Fans come from far and near to witness McGwire's
startling exhibition of strength and hand-eye coordination as he
chases Roger Maris' single-season home run record.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Tuesday night's game with Milwaukee, McGwire led a
four-player race with 44 home runs. Sammy Sosa of the Cubs, with
two home runs on Monday, had 40, as did Ken Griffey Jr. of Seattle.
Greg Vaughn of San Diego had 37.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the difficult task of determining who should be the
National League's most valuable player: McGwire, who has created a
national sensation with his towering blasts; or Sosa who is trying
to carry his club to the playoffs, possibly a pennant, or Vaughn,
the power player on a first-place team?
</P>
<P>
   As St. Louis returned to Busch Stadium on Tuesday night for a
homestand, McGwire contemplated an award he has not won. ``I truly
believe that MVP should go to a position player,'' he said. ``It
should be the guy who has the best overall year, numbers-wise, no
matter if his team is in last place or is in first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Before this series my vote was cast: Sammy Sosa should be the
MVP, hands down. McGwire has 44 home runs on a losing team. Sosa
has 40 home runs and is propelling his team to the playoffs,
possibly a pennant. For Sosa there is more at stake than a home run
chase. He doesn't have the luxury of swinging from his heels every
time at bat. There are runs to drive in, games to win.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's game, Sosa said: ``I'm not looking for the
record. I'm not looking to chase nobody. I'm just trying to go out
there, do my job every day and win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Sosa hit a crucial home run against New York, then on
Monday he hit two more _ including a grand slam _ to help Chicago
keep pace in the division race. If the award is being given in the
spirit of Roger Maris, whose record is being chased, Sosa is the
MVP. Maris not only broke Babe Ruth's single-season record, but he
also did it in the context of helping his Yankees win a pennant.
</P>
<P>
   No one escapes pressure in this scenario; it just comes from
different directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're on a team with good players surrounding you it could
make things a little easier, but it could make things difficult,''
McGwire said. ``Sosa is playing on a great team, but he has a lot
of pressure because a lot of people are looking at him. The
pressure may be greater on him.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a different kind of pressure on McGwire. He is like the
carnival strongman who comes to work each day with thousands of
paying customers expecting to see him perform feats of strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people are talking about, the home run hitting, I don't
have any control over it,'' McGwire said. ``I only have control
over swinging the bat. If I get a hit, I'm excited. But I can't
control whether or not it's going to go out of the ball park.
That's a difficult thing to do. The whole weekend in Colorado
people were saying, `Come on, Mark, hit one out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although Vaughn is having a terrific season, his team leads its
division by 13 games. If Chicago makes the playoffs and Sosa keeps
up the pace, he should be rewarded for performing under the
pressure of a pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   As for McGwire, it's clear after walking around St. Louis, whose
playoff hopes are buried, that he is more or less performing a
civic duty. Even he admitted that ``when you're playing on a team
that hasn't been consistently winning all year, it's tough to come
to the ball park every day knowing that you don't know how your
team is going to play.''
</P>
<P>
   So if Sosa keeps up his pace and McGwire keeps up his, MVP
voters will be forced to make a sophisticated decision and a
critical distinction between who helped baseball and who helped his
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at it this way,'' McGwire said. ``It's not easy to play
consistently well over a whole year on a winning team; it's not
easy to play consistently well the whole year on a losing team.
There's so much pressure to deal with on both sides of this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what,'' he added, ``it's going to be a tough
task for the voters.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
