<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORTALS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTALS: DOORMEN OF THE INTERNET  
 BY JON SWARTZ 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - PORTALS   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
There's a new fad in the Internet market, and it sounds
supiciously like a real estate mantra: location, location,
location.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Major online services like Netscape and Yahoo are constructing
gated communities on their virtual real estate, and they want
consumers and advertisers to become permanent residents.
</P>
<P>
   These mega-sites, called portals, are ``doorways'' to the rest
of the Internet. They aim to be the first place Web surfers go
online, and the home base for all their Internet activities.
Vendors contend that they are the most efficient way to corral Web
users and generate revenues.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, portals offer a single convenient stop on the
Internet from which they can converse (e-mail, chat rooms and
instant messaging), shop (e-commerce), get up-to-the-minute
information (news, weather and stock quotes), look for information
(search engine, directories) and download free software.
</P>
<P>
   Once the portals hook Web surfers, the logic goes, advertisers
and content providers will flock to them with cash to buy space on
their sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is a scarce resource in our economy, and portals solve
that,'' Infoseek CEO Harry Motro said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Excite co-founder Joe Kraus said many of the 100 million-plus
consumers online want a convenient, easy-to-use site where they can
get news and information and ``there is no reason to go
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He said users choose a virtual home base through brand-name
recognition and then ``stick with it if they feel comfortable with
a personalized community.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he said you can expect to see a lot of advertising
from online companies attempting to create a brand image, and a
myriad of free online services from vendors in an all-out effort to
keep customers.
</P>
<P>
   The potential payoff is astronomical: Net advertising is
expected to hit $7.7 billion by the year 2002 and e-commerce sales
could balloon to $37.5 billion this year, according to market
researcher Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, portals have taken the Internet industry by
storm. They are changing the way companies design their sites and
how consumers surf the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Portals are a recognition that search engines alone are not
the end-all for the mass market to view the Web,'' said Barry
Schuler, president of AOL Interactive Services. ``The common view a
few years ago was that people would (sign up with) an ISP, choose a
browser and then do all their own searching. Aggregators like AOL
supposedly were dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That view was wrong,'' he said. ``The Internet experience is
all about creating a brand name to attract an audience and building
loyalty so they stick.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Internet has gone portal, Wall Street has bought into the
craze.
</P>
<P>
   A recent run up in online stocks has much to do with the new
strategy, according to industry observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows the Net will be big, and what they want is a
piece of the action,'' said analyst Jim Balderston of Zona Research
Inc. in Redwood City. ``But many would rather invest in a company
they understand, like a Yahoo, which is selling road maps to the
Net, than a router or hub company that is laying the cement for the
information superhighway.''
</P>
<P>
   Major media companies are scrambling to get into the portal
business. Many have either invested in Internet companies (NBC sunk
a substantial amount of money into Cnet, while Disney bought nearly
half of Infoseek) or attempted buyouts (AT&AMP;T Corp. offered $30
billion for AOL, while Zapata Corp. bid $1.7 billion for Excite.)
</P>
<P>
   The frenzied market reaction has resulted in stratospheric
market caps among the swelling ranks of portal players.
</P>
<P>
   _AOL's $25 billion market evaluation dwarfs Caterpillar Inc.,
Eastman Kodak Co. and J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. Not coincidentally, AOL is
credited with originating the concept in mid-1997 after its
subscriber revenues started drying up when it switched to flat-fee
pricing.
</P>
<P>
   To supplement its subscription and advertising income, the
company began striking million-dollar deals with retailers to carve
out real estate on its site. Amazon.com, a popular Web-based
bookseller, paid AOL $19 million over three years to be the
principal book retailer on aol.com, AOL's Web site. And
1-800-FLOWERS agreed to pay AOL $25 million over four years to be
displayed on the service.
</P>
<P>
   Such practices have become the industry norm.
</P>
<P>
   _Yahoo, at $9 billion, is worth more on paper than Union
Carbide, the 13th-largest chemical-maker. ``Chief Yahoos'' David
Filo and Jerry Yang, who co-founded the Santa Clara company in
1994, are billionaires despite dental-floss-thin profits.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the company's success is due to its widespread
brand-name recognition and its decision early on to layer a wide
variety of content on its popular search engine _ a strategy that
was parroted by its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Portals) are an extension of what we have always done,'' Yang
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our approach is to aggregate everything and anything
possible,'' company CEO Tim Koogle said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Netscape Communications Corp. yesterday became the latest
company to polish its portal plan. It unveiled My Netscape, a
personalized front page that combines news, browser, e-mail and
software applications.
</P>
<P>
   _Microsoft is readying a mega-portal site, code named
``Microsoft Start,'' that will showcase all its online properties _
from auto and travel services to news content, free e-mail, instant
messaging and an online directory.
</P>
<P>
   _Infoseek _ once given up for dead as a hopeless also-ran to
Yahoo and Excite _ has combined services with Disney to ``offer a
major media portal play,'' Motro said.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney-Infoseek partnership includes deals for exclusive
content from ABC News, ESPN and Disney. ``You can't be a me-too
service and expect to survive,'' Motro said. ``All of our content
is ours and no one else's.''
</P>
<P>
   _HotBot, the San Francisco-based search engine that is part of
Wired Digital, announced Monday that it is launching a $10 to $15
million branding campaign to increase traffic to the site.
</P>
<P>
   _Even Zapata, a Houston-based oil exploration
company-turned-fish-oil specialist that unsuccessfully bid $1.7
billion for Excite in May, has acquired 24 Web sites and is
stitching them into a super site, called Zap.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have built a site consumers will visit and stay in
permanently because we own all of the properties,'' CEO Avie Glazer
said. ``We're different from a Yahoo or AOL. They rent space to
other sites and run the risk of promoting them until consumers
become more interested (in the rented sites) and go straight to
them, bypassing an AOL or Yahoo.''
</P>
<P>
   The stampede of online heavyweights into a narrow market has
created congestion and prompted speculation that there will be a
shakedown separating the winners from losers.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts assert that the portal market is too crowded and will
undergo consolidation during the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a shakeout because there are too many players,''
said analyst Jill Frankle, of International Data Corp. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Zona Research's Balderston said investors &UR;  &LR; will continue to plow
money into online stocks until the market ``winnows out the haves
from the have nots.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Eventually, they'll realize that eyeballs aren't translating
into revenues and justifying these market caps,'' Balderston said.
</P>
<P>
   Until that day arrives _ and no one has a clue when _ investors
will continue to go gaga over portal companies and major media
companies will eye further investments and potential acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're seeing real revenues flow into public companies,''
Motro said. ``This isn't like the push market. This is a real
market.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
