<SLUG> BC-TRAVELZOO-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET FIRM GIVING AWAY ITS STOCK  
 BY DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - TRAVELZOO   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
At a time when Internet stocks are fetching astronomical prices, an
obscure Bahamas-based company is giving away its shares.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The company, travelzoo.com, says that by distributing free
shares, it generates that valuable Internet commodity: traffic.
</P>
<P>
   More than 600,000 people have visited the site, according to a
counter on the home page. The site's main line of business is
advertising discount airfares and resort packages culled mostly
from other Internet sites. On July 15, DoubleClick, a New
York-based Internet advertising company, began selling ads on the
site.
</P>
<P>
   The company acknowledges that it's ``hard to say at the moment''
how much the shares are worth. It's operating on the theory that
the shares will be valuable when the company launches an initial
public offering.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is home to no shortage of scams, and Web watchers
are cautious about travelzoo.com's too-good-to-be-true offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a good deal or one of the best scams I've ever
heard of,'' said Ira Winkler of Severna Park, Md., an Internet
privacy expert and the author of ``Corporate Espionage.''
</P>
<P>
   John Heine, a spokesman for the Securities and Exchange
Commission, which is aware of the site, declined to say whether the
company is under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it is based in the Bahamas to take advantage of
``the freedom and flexibility to pursue exciting, cutting-edge
business concepts.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the SEC says it still can investigate an offshore
company if the firm sells securities in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   According to the company's Web site, people can sign up for
three free shares. The shares are held electronically in the
Bahamas. If a shareholder gets a friend to sign up, the shareholder
gets another free share, up to a maximum of 10 shares.
</P>
<P>
   The company goes on to say that shareholders ``are eligible to
receive dividend payments'' and can sell their stake for a profit
when travelzoo.com goes public, which it claims could happen
``fairly soon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Becoming a co-owner of travelzoo.com is risk-free,'' the site
says.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Bartel, the company's chief executive, was in Germany
yesterday and was unavailable for comment, said his brother, Holger
Bartel, a Bay Area resident.
</P>
<P>
   Holger Bartel, who said he is not affiliated with the company,
said his brother plans to open an office next month in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Travelzoo.com's Web site described Ralph Bartel as a 32-year-old
former reporter and news editor with German television. It said he
holds an MBA from the University of St. Gallen in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Subrahmanyam, a finance professor at University of
California at Los Angeles, said the site is not necessarily a scam
even though its business plan sounds unusual.
</P>
<P>
   By spreading the word through e-mail, Subrahmanyam said, the
company hopes to drum up interest in an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site says the founders will keep 3 million shares while
giving up to 700,000 people as many as 7 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler, the author, said that means the company is either
stupid or fraudulent. ``Nobody ever gives away 70 percent of their
company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler also warned that the site could sell shareholders' names
to direct marketing companies, which pay as much as $50 a name.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The site claims that it won't sell names, but Winkler said,
``If they lie, big deal. You would have to go to the Bahamas to sue
them.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  But Holger Bartel maintains that the shares are not worthless.
``Yahoo, Excite _ they didn't make any revenues for the first year.
Would people have said it's not worth anything?''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
