<SLUG> BC-NOLO-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERKELEY PUBLISHER FIGHTS TO PREVENT BOOK SALES BAN  
 BY AMY DOAN 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - NOLO   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Nolo Press, the Berkeley-based publisher of self-help books and
software, has filed a court petition for information that it says
it needs to fight a possible sales ban in Texas.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nolo says a committee working under the jurisdiction of the
state's high court has been quietly investigating Nolo's sales of
books and software in Texas to determine whether they constitute an
illegal practice of law in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by the lack of information on the investigation, Nolo
asked the Texas Supreme Court last week to force the committee to
publicly disclose its rules, the identity of members and
information it has about the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're operating in a total vacuum,'' said Steve Elias, Nolo's
associate publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Nolo has sold its books and software in Texas since the
mid-1970s without any complaints, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Berkeley publisher, whose titles include ``Fight Your Ticket
... And Win!'' and ``Good Divorce,'' has a hearing scheduled for
August 20 before the so-called Unauthorized Practice of Law
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Composed of six lawyers and three nonlawyers, the committee has
the authority to determine on a case-by-case basis which services
and acts constitute the practice of law. Should the committee rule
against Nolo, it could ban sales of its products in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Elias said the committee is ``simply trying to stamp out
self-help law'' and preserve Texas' traditional law business.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Ticer, chairman of the Dallas subcommittee overseeing the
UPL Committee, said Elias' comments were ``highly inaccurate'' and
that the committee's objective is to protect consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Ticer declined comment on the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is the only state that continues to apply
unauthorized-practice-of-law regulations to books, Elias said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in a 1967 New York case involving the best-seller
``How to Avoid Probate,'' New York's highest court ruled that
published materials may not be considered legal advice and that
they should be covered under the First Amendment.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
