<SLUG> BC-STREET29-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARK VEVERKA/STREET SMARTS  
 GEOCITIES MAY BE THE NEXT INSTALLMENT OF INTERNET MADNESS 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - STREET SMARTS   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Coming soon to a brokerage near you: Internet IPO Madness III _
featuring online service provider GeoCities. First there was
Inktomi, that madcap maker of search engine software. Then there
was Broadcast.com, that wacky online provider of audio and video.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And now there's GeoCities, that nutty Web site of ``online
communities,'' which critics expect to be the summer's next
blockbuster initial offering.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so the big screen analogy is over the top. But during this
summer of trepidation over Asian instability and domestic corporate
profits, Internet-related IPOs have been responsible for some of
the biggest megahit-deals of the season.
</P>
<P>
   San Mateo-based Inktomi saw its shares soar as high as five
times their initial value since its June IPO. And Dallas-based
Broadcast.com shares have risen as high as four times their initial
value since its IPO earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The lights-out performance of these IPOs are likely to presage
an equally successful rollout of GeoCities shares to the public,
investment banking and brokerage sources say.
</P>
<P>
   GeoCities management and bankers are currently conducting their
road show for institutional investors, which is expected to wind
down during the second week of August. The shares could be priced
as early as August 10.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Securities and Exchange Commission filing, the
shares are supposed to be priced between $12 and $14. But judging
by the massive popularity of the Broadcast.com issues, it's a fair
guess that the shares will get priced a few bucks higher, bankers
and fund managers say.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling much of the lofty expectations for the offering is the
fact that its lead manager is Goldman Sachs, the same investment
bank that brought Yahoo and Broadcast.com public. (Inktomi was
lead-managed by Morgan Stanley). Co-managers on the deal are
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette and Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
</P>
<P>
   About 4.8 million shares may be offered. In addition, another
712,000 shares may be sold to the underwriters if the original
allotment sells out, according to the filing.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman is known for identifying and representing the leading
companies it thinks will dominate particular technology sectors, or
in this case, a subsector such as the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers contend that a Goldman-led technology IPO can
often become a self-fulfilling prophecy, giving a little-known
company with no profits and an iffy business model (such as
GeoCities) the ability to attract wads of quality capital from the
world over.
</P>
<P>
   They may have a point. Once again, Goldman seems to have hitched
its wagon to one of the strongest players in a particular area of
the Internet. (Strong, that is, if you throw traditional financial
measurements out the window.)
</P>
<P>
   GeoCities is the big dog among ``online communities,'' with one
of the fastest growing Web sites of its kind. Its cyber-community
of personal Web sites are segregated into some 40 different areas
of interest, or ``neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you have people talking about their pets and their
personal lives,'' but their neighborhoods ``could evolve into a
very targeted audience that (eventually) could be very lucrative,''
says Chris Elwell, vice president of Internet.com, an online
division of Mecklermedia in Westport, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   GeoCities attracts Web surfers by giving away sites for free,
calling owners of such sites ``Homesteaders.''
</P>
<P>
   And the community's popularity is exploding. GeoCities has grown
from a mere 10,000 sites in October 1995 to more than 2.1 million
sites at present, according to the filing. (GeoCities executives
were unable to comment due to quiet-period requirements.)
</P>
<P>
   What's more, in June GeoCities attracted 14.8 million viewers to
its site and was the third-most visited Web site on the Internet
among home users, according to independent Internet research firms
cited in the filing.
</P>
<P>
   In short, GeoCities is one of the busiest gateway Web sites that
has yet to go public. And when you look at the
market-capitalizations of those that have gone public, almost all
boast market-capitalizations of more than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   So the motivation for taking GeoCities public may seem like a
no-brainer in so far as the bankers and management are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   But should individuals own the stock?
</P>
<P>
   First of all, it's nearly impossible to buy initial shares
because institutions and high-net-worth brokerage customers get top
priority.
</P>
<P>
   Second, if you want to buy and hold for the long haul, Internet
stocks are probably not where you want to be, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the same fundamentals weaknesses in other Internet
stocks exist with GeoCities. The companies' losses are mounting,
swelling from $3 million in 1996 to $8.9 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Its revenues from advertising depend on short-term contracts
that last only one to two months, which makes for very murky
visibility of quarter-by-quarter performance.
</P>
<P>
   Morever, the company relies on one customer for about 12 percent
of its revenues: Egghead Direct, the software retailer that has
re-invented itself as an electronic commerce company.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some observers question the quality of the eyeballs
that are attracted to online communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at GeoCities, its audience tends to be more
downscale than those of some of the search engine sites,'' says
Craig Gugel, a vice president of Organic Online, a San
Francisco-based Internet advertising firm. Still, the public
curtain is likely to go up on GeoCities in less than two weeks, and
investors are expected to give the new issues a big thumbs up. The
madness continues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., SF 94103,
by phone at 415-777-8444 or by e-mail at mveverka &LR; sfgate.com. He
also appears on KRON-TV's Daybreak on Tuesdays and Thursdays.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
