<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLAPSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A TIMES SQUARE BLOCK, BARRICADES AND ANGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the ordeal of cleaning up Times Square entered its
second week Tuesday, city officials said that a block to the north
of the Conde Nast building's construction collapse _ 44th Street
between the Avenue of the Americas and Broadway _ would likely
remain closed at least through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came on a day when tempers flared on the block,
which is home to several hundred people who have been forced out of
their residences since the July 21 collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't live like this,'' said Arleen Getzel, an office
manager and resident at the Church of the Nazarene on 44th Street.
Unlike residents and property owners on 43rd Street, who live
directly under the Conde Nast construction site and have been told
that their block would be closed for weeks, those on 44th Street
said they were exasperated by the continued delays, particularly
since there were indications that the block would be reopened
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is crazy,'' said Ms. Getzel, who normally spends most of
her days working with the homeless. ``Now we are homeless. I have
been sitting alone in a miserable hotel for a week now, and they
should just let us go in, get our stuff and make plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, officials at the site of the construction
accident, considered the city's worst in more than a decade, said
enough progress had been made so that they could reopen sections of
the Avenue of the Americas and 42nd Street to rush-hour traffic
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   All that would remain closed Wednesday, they said, are 43rd
Street, 44th Street and the north sidewalk of 42nd Street _ all
between Broadway and Sixth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   But for those still kept behind police barricades, the city's
assurances that work was proceeding as fast as possible apparently
provided little consolation. Business people displaced by the
accident said the ordeal may not end when all Times Square streets
are opened. Simply being kept away from their offices, computers
and clients could result in long-term losses, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid my business will just go to someone else,'' said
William Rogan, an architect who lives and works in an apartment
behind the 44th Street barricades. Among his biggest clients is
Ralph Lauren, for whom he is rushing to complete the designs of
women's clothing display areas for more than 400 stores, all of
which are needed for the fall fashion season.
</P>
<P>
   His problem now, Rogan said, is that all his plans are locked
away in the computer in his home office. ``I have not even begun to
calculate my future losses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Zlotnick has been kept out of his graphic design business
at 120 W. 44th St. ``They might give us a bone but it won't make up
for the aggravation the loss of business and loss of momentum we've
suffered,'' he said. ``My cell phone bill is already sky high.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Gubin, who works in advertising, was trying to get into
his office Tuesday morning at the barricaded street corner of 44th
Street and Seventh Avenue. ``I have friends around town,'' he said,
``I've been using their offices to make calls. I've been stalling
my clients, deferring business.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday, Jerome Hauer, director of the
Mayor's Office of Emergency Management, offered little hope of
relief for those on 44th Street. He said he saw little chance that
they would be allowed to return to their homes or businesses until
sometime Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The delay, he said, was the result of the same problem that has
afflicted cleanup efforts since the collapse: the unpredictable and
often harrowing work necessary to shore up the broken scaffolding
on the Conde Nast building before taking it down.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, for instance, workers dangling in a construction bucket
more than 20 stories above the street nearly got into a serious
accident while trying to drape nylon mesh from the east side of the
damaged scaffolding. When a sudden wind gust turned the bucket
halfway around, one of several cables that secured it to the
building snapped like a rubber band.
</P>
<P>
   That left engineers on the site to reconsider their schedule.
Although the entire east side of the scaffolding earlier had been
expected to be draped in nylon by Tuesday morning, he said much of
that work still needed to be done. Similar work on the north side
of the scaffolding was only half-completed Tuesday, and must be
finished before police barricades can be removed from 44th Street,
Hauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Frustration over the tedious process was not confined to those
who live and work on 44th Street. For instance, there was an
exchange of court challenges over the fate of pets apparently still
stranded in buildings on 43rd Street. While city officials said
that all the pets they could find had been removed from the other
streets affected by the construction accident, a small number of
pets are known to remain inside buildings on 43rd Street.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Luis Gonzalez of the State Supreme Court in the Bronx
agreed to a court petition by 43rd Street residents Monday and
issued a temporary order that directed the police to allow the
residents to enter their buildings and retrieve their pets if they
signed waivers absolving the city from liability.
</P>
<P>
   But within hours of that court order, and before any of the pet
owners had crossed police lines, lawyers for the city filed an
appeal that prompted the judge to issue a stay of his order.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the blocks of 43rd and 44th Streets under the
shadow of the Conde Nast building remained abandoned Tuesday, even
as throngs returned to the center of Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, the Roundabout Theater Company's productions of
``Side Man'' and ``You Can Never Tell'' reopened after each show
had canceled eight performances, together costing $200,000 in lost
ticket sales. Although forced to negotiate police barriers that
separated the Times Square sidewalks from vehicular traffic, those
attending the plays were allowed to arrive at the theater at 45th
Street and Broadway from the sidewalks on the east side of the
square.
</P>
<P>
   The company in charge of the Conde Nast construction site,
Tishman Construction Corp., and its insurer, Liberty Mutual,
continued to process claims for financial relief from displaced
businesses and residents.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kielar, senior vice president of Tishman Realty &AMP;
Construction Co., said late Tuesday that 407 claims had been
approved, and $216,000 in money had been distributed by the
insurer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
