<HEADLINE>
FRANCE OVER CROATIA _ AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Frenchman Guillaume Raoux was happy with his
victory over Croatia's Goran Ivanisevic at the Mercedes-Benz Cup,
but he was positively gleeful about his home country's World Cup
victory two weeks ago. And he was fully aware of the coincidence
provided by his match with Ivanisevic _ France beat Croatia to
advance to the World Cup final.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a French World Cup jersey, Raoux said he and his
countrymen were still celebrating the win: ``We'll stop in four
years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Today's matches: The schedule is heavy with doubles matches,
and only two top seeds _ No. 7 Byron Black and No. 2 Tim Henman _
are playing singles.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 a.m. matches are Black vs. Gianluca Pozzi; and Brandon
Coupe/Kent Kinnear vs. Grant Stafford/Kevin Ullyett. Those will be
followed by, in singles, Kenneth Carlsen vs. Raoux and Sargis
Sargsian vs. Santa Monica's Michael Joyce; and in doubles,
Jan-Michael Gambill/Vince Spadea vs. Martin Damm/Jim Grabb, Tuomas
Ketola/David Roditi vs. Patrick Rafter/Sandon Stolle, Black/Pat
Galbraith vs. Wayne Ferreira/Marcos Ondruska and Eric Taino/Adam
Peterson vs. brothers Luke and Murphy Jensen.
</P>
<P>
   The 7:30 p.m. match features Manhattan Beach's Jeff Tarango vs.
England's Henman. That match will be followed by John Lafnie De
Jager/Robbie Koenig vs. brothers Bob and Mike Bryan of Camarillo.
</P>
</TEXT>
