<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLAPSE-FUNERAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIM IN TIMES SQUARE ACCIDENT REMEMBERED AS LOVING LIFE IN NEW
YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By LYNETTE HOLLOWAY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For years, Robert Feliconio urged his aunt, Thereza,
to move to Florida, saying New York City was too dangerous for a
woman her age.
</P>
<P>
   But Thereza Feliconio, who was in her 80s, refused, saying she
could take care of herself. Now, he wishes he had pressed harder,
he said Tuesday after attending a memorial Mass in her honor at St.
Patrick's Cathedral in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Feliconio died in her one-room apartment on July 21 when the
collapse of scaffolding at the Conde Nast building in Times Square
sent a chunk of metal through the roof and into her top-floor room
in the Woodstock Hotel, a 12-story single-room-occupancy building
that caters to the elderly poor. Not only did the accident take Ms.
Feliconio's life, but it also forced city officials to close the
heart of Manhattan for days because of concerns about the unstable
scaffolding.
</P>
<P>
   While thousands have been inconvenienced by the collapse,
perhaps none have suffered more than Ms. Feliconio's family, and
Tuesday, she was remembered at her favorite church by about 70
people, including Mayor Rudolph Giuliani; Douglas Durst, the
developer of the Conde Nast building, and Richard Kielar, senior
vice president of Tishman Realty and Construction Co., whose unit
was the site's construction manager.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of five children, Ms. Feliconio grew up in Sao
Paulo, Brazil. She was married briefly in her 20s and was a partner
in a bus company, her nephew said. She sold her interest in the
company before moving to New York 30 years ago, but it did not make
her rich.
</P>
<P>
   Once here, she worked as a health care worker until her
retirement more than a decade ago. She moved to the Woodstock from
a one-bedroom apartment after her retirement, Robert Feliconio
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been trying to get her out of New York City, to be very
honest, for quite a few years,'' said Feliconio, a 62-year-old
retired schoolteacher from Odessa, Fla. ``But she was just in love
with this city, in love with the New York way of life. We just
couldn't get her out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing Thereza Feliconio loved most about the city was its
culture, relatives said. Her favorite shows included ``The Phantom
of the Opera'' and ``Beauty and the Beast.'' She also enjoyed
dining out and shopping at the city's many department stores,
though she did not have much money, her relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   She looked as if she were about to take the stage herself, they
said, always carefully made-up and dressed. And like most women of
her generation, she was reticent about her age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody really knows her age, but we'd place her at 82,''
Robert Feliconio said. ``She was too elegant to tell anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Marino, a cousin who lives in Hamden, Conn., and
visited her frequently, said Thereza Feliconio was the consummate
New Yorker. ``She walked everywhere,'' Ms. Marino recalled. ``I
don't remember her taking a cab or the subway.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. John Ferry, who led mourners through the 23rd Psalm and
read the Gospel account of the resurrection of Lazarus as part of
the hourlong service, recalled a woman who was devoted to the
church. He said that St. Patrick's Cathedral was the center of her
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``To outsiders, New York City seems very impersonal, very cold
and not concerned with individuals,'' he said. ``Yet if you are a
New Yorker, born here as I was, or came here as Thereza did, you
know that nothing can be further from the truth. It is at times
like these that New Yorkers rise to the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Two lawyers retained by Robert Feliconio's father and Thereza
Feliconio's brother, Carlos, of Hollywood, Fla., said they were
impressed by the city's outpouring of sympathy, but said it did not
change their belief that someone was negligent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tragedy like this doesn't occur but for someone's
negligence,'' said Steven Schwartzapfel, who stood next to his
partner, Robert Marcus. ``We promised the family that we would seek
and hold the wrongdoers responsible for causing the tragic and
senseless death of Thereza Feliconio.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Auster, a spokeswoman for the American Red Cross, which
has been helping scores of residents left homeless by the accident,
accompanied about 30 Woodstock residents, some walking with canes,
to the church Tuesday. They came by two chartered buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an air of melancholy,'' she said. ``In the church, I
was sitting behind another Red Cross worker, who was patting the
arm of an elderly man who was upset. A lot of people cared about
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``But overall, everyone's OK,'' she said. ``The service was
hard, but so is the fact that they haven't been allowed back into
their apartments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
