u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NFL-PASSING-NYT &LR;      07-28 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-PASSING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PASS CAN SET UP OR START UP AN OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
   (rl) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The essence of winning football is the running game. This
question follows: Does the run set up the pass, or does the pass
set up the run?
</P>
<P>
   It is a puzzle as old as the game. As National Football League
training camps unfold in earnest this week, each team attempts to
solidify exactly what role the passing game will play in its
season.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in thinking on the question can be dramatic among
the NFL's 30 teams. Oakland, for example, says that the deep,
vertical passing game is the way to go. That approach sets up the
run and breaks down defenses and keeps the opponent always on its
heels. It strikes fear. Pittsburgh, however, insists that pounding
the football up the middle via the run softens any defense. It
makes the enemy bring its safeties up to support the run defense.
Then pow. Hit 'em with the home run, the deep pass.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, in fact, lies somewhere in between. It is all about
efficiency. Choose your strategy: run first or pass first. Simply
carry it out efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   And when you do pass, work on improving in a few specific areas
that are crucial to success.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you run or pass, the first essential ingredients of a
productive offense are, of course, a stout and mobile offensive
line and skilled players at the skill positions to make the offense
click. Avoiding turnovers is critical. Avoiding dropped balls in
the passing game is critical, too.
</P>
<P>
   Given all that, success in today's NFL passing game frequently
hinges on increasing average yards gained per pass attempt,
allowing fewer sacks and using the short pass as a substitute for
the run.
</P>
<P>
   If a team can master these interrelated areas, it is on its way
to a successful passing offense.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers from the 1997 NFL season say so.
</P>
<P>
   The teams that ranked No. 1 through No. 7 in average yards per
pass attempt, with sacks included as attempts, all reached the
playoffs last season. Five of those teams won 11 or more games.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland (No. 3), Cincinnati (No. 7), Atlanta (No. 8),
Philadelphia (No. 12) and Indianapolis (No. 13) sat pretty in
average yards per pass attempt without considering sacks allowed.
Factor in the sacks, and their rankings dropped to 10, 9, 15, 17
and 21, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   One way around the puzzle of running first or passing first is
to use the pass as the run.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, San Francisco has been the champion of
this tactic. How many times did Joe Montana and Steve Young play
catch with tight end Brent Jones? Jones would run 4 yards, turn
around, catch the ball and fall down for 3 more yards, and the
result was the equivalent of a 7-yard run. The game clock kept
running, too, keeping the ball away from the opponent's offense.
Easy stuff. Or those swing passes the 49ers used to a variety of
backs _ Roger Craig or Ricky Watters, now Garrison Hearst _ for 5
and 6 yards or a little more. Stay inbounds and the clock runs.
Again, the equivalent of a running play.
</P>
<P>
   That is en vogue in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Where do we stand in the passing game, teams ask? Here are some
answers. Following each team is its number of sacks allowed and
yardage lost on those sacks.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (62 sacks for 430 yards): The Colts must throw more
quickly and throw more often to tight end Ken Dilger. He caught 27
balls last season and averaged 14.1 yards a catch. That's a hot
average for a tight end.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI (22 for 153): Dan Marino is protected well and throws it
fast. The Dolphins need more speed and fewer dropped passes to take
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (50 for 317): Not only 50 sacks allowed, but also 33
interceptions thrown. No wonder the Saints suffered. They must
improve in both pass protection and possession time.
</P>
<P>
   DENVER (35 for 210): The Broncos took chances and made the
gambles pay off. Last season they swung back and forth on the
run-first/pass-first question: quarterback John Elway set up back
Terrell Davis and then Davis set up Elway. Versatile. Makes them
tough to defend. Helped make them champions.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE (40 for 218): For the last two seasons this team
has led the league in average yards per pass attempt with sacks
included. Several teams allowed fewer sacks but lost more yardage.
(Dallas, for example, allowed 39 sacks for 313 yards lost.) That
says that Jaguars quarterback Mark Brunell is agile and elusive.
</P>
<P>
   GIANTS (32 for 238): Their average yards per pass attempt in
both categories, with and without sacks, was at the bottom of the
league, yet they won their division. Two things are clear: the
running game was good and the defense was spectacular. For success
in '98, the Giants need big improvement here.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND (58 for 530): Jeff George led the league in passing
yards (3,917). He led the American Football Conference in touchdown
passes (29). Yet he still spent too much time on his back, and the
Raiders paid for their all-or-nothing scheme. Too often, it was
nothing. The Raiders will tinker more with the short passing game.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY (32 for 236): The Chiefs ranked in the lower half of
the league in average yards gained per pass, but with free agent
Derrick Alexander joining Andre Rison, they have a receiving
package that can burn.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA (78 for 495): Where do you start to fix this?
</P>
<P>
   JETS (48 for 313): The more Glenn Foley plays, the more the
Jets' passing numbers should improve. If Vinny Testaverde starts,
he will have to reduce his interceptions (15 last season in
Baltimore).
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (36 for 228): Receiver James McKnight led the league
with 18.7 yards a catch last season. A steady mixture of deep
passes to McKnight and short ones to the new Seahawk back, Ricky
Watters, spells success.
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY (32 for 196): Only six NFL teams lost fewer than 200
yards when sacked. This was one. The others were Pittsburgh (152),
Tennessee (199), Miami (153), Green Bay (191) and Washington (198).
</P>
<P>
   Does the run set up the pass or does the pass set up the run?
</P>
<P>
   It is a matter of choice for NFL teams in the '98 season. Drops
and interceptions, however, are not; they kill a passing offense.
Completing big plays, avoiding sacks and using the short pass as a
run bring the passing offense to life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
