<SLUG> BC-SKATE-GOODWILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 18, KWAN IDLING AT THE CROSSROADS
</HEADLINE>
   (rl) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Michelle Kwan will not graduate from high
school for a couple of weeks, so it's understandable that she
doesn't have the rest of her life mapped out just yet. For now, she
is committed to participating in the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt
Lake City. But that is down a long, unknowable road. Right now, all
she is looking for is a place to pull over.
</P>
<P>
   Figure skating begins Wednesday at the Goodwill Games, and Kwan
is a spokeswoman for the Games as well as the top female
competitor. There is a $75,000 reward for first place, along with
her promotional fee, which is believed to be in six figures. She
has been going nonstop for a year, with the Olympics and a 59-stop
tour. Like any 18-year-old, she is waiting to exhale.
</P>
<P>
   She has cleared the decks for a monthlong vacation in August.
Skating begins again in September, and not until then will Kwan
begin making firm plans for the coming season. She wants to compete
at the 1998 national and world championships, her coach and agent
said. But, as of now, Kwan has committed only to a pro-am in
October in Daytona Beach, Fla. ``What she needs is a real rest,''
said Frank Carroll, who coaches Kwan in Lake Arrowhead, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   She feels no pain from the stress fracture in her left foot, she
said. How much she competes this season will be determined by how
well she is able to raise the bar on her own high standards. ``I
don't want to come out and be the same old Michelle,'' she said at
a news conference today.
</P>
<P>
   That means she wants to add more technical difficulty to her
routines. Last year, it was impossible with a stress fracture in
the second toe of her left foot. This year, she wants to perfect
triple-lutz-triple-loop and triple-toe-triple-toe combination
jumps. And after talking about a triple axel for four years, she
joked, she wants to be able to land one regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've stayed at a certain level in technical ability,''
Kwan said. ``It's time to really expand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, she watched the taped replay of her
silver-medal-winning performance at the 1998 Winter Games in
Nagano, Japan. She understands what was lacking. A little speed,
``a little more oomph'' in her cautious routine. In retrospect, she
said, she was a little too nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was a little too overwhelmed by everything,'' Kwan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Five months later, however, she doesn't feel the searing regret
she thought she might feel at winning silver instead of the
expected gold.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, she said, she was thinking: ``If I don't win, what
am I going to do with myself? I thought if I didn't win, my life
would be over.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the silver came a revelation. Life didn't end. Neither
did skating. Her graciousness in defeat may even have made her more
popular than she would have been in victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just know that that's not all there is to skating,'' Kwan
said. ``A gold medal is great, but I feel there is more that I can
accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she misses competing against Tara Lipinski, who won the
gold medal and, having fulfilled her lifelong dream at 15, decided
to turn professional. ``I do miss her, because it's nice having a
challenge,'' Kwan said. ``But I feel there is a challenge against
myself also.''
</P>
<P>
   The world silver and bronze medalists, Mariya Butyrskaya and
Irina Slutskaya, both of Russia, are competing here, but they
should pose no threat to Kwan, who will perform her Olympic
routines at the Goodwill Games. In fact, there is no female skater
in the world with Olympic ambitions who can match Kwan's grace and
artistry.
</P>
<P>
   Television networks will be willing to throw money at her like
flower petals to keep her in the competitive side of the sport.
After her, there is no one. The real challenge for Kwan is to
decide whether she truly feels joy at the prospect of another
Olympics or whether she only feels unfulfilled at having won silver
instead of gold. She has put college off for at least a year to
concentrate on skating. She will be only 21 during the 2002 Salt
Lake City Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she wants to compete, she should compete,'' Carroll said.
``Her parents aren't telling her she has to stay in. I'm not
saying, `Michelle, you didn't win the gold, you've got to stay in.'
She's 18. Make some decisions. She's the one taking charge of her
life. I think it's nice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
