<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANUGUERRA-OBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATTEO MANUGUERRA, 73, FRENCH BARITONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Matteo Manuguerra, a French baritone who was admired for his
versatility and dramatic acuity, died in Montpellier, France, on
Thursday. He was 73 and lived in Montpellier.
</P>
<P>
   He died of congestive heart failure three days after a stroke,
his manager, Robert Lombardo, said.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1971, when he made his Metropolitan Opera debut as
Enrico in Donizetti's ``Lucia di Lammermoor,'' Manuguerra appeared
regularly at the Met, where he sang 127 performances. Among the 15
roles he sang at the house were Marcello in Puccini's ``Boheme,''
Alfio in Mascagni's ``Cavalleria Rusticana'' and several Verdi
roles, including Carlo in Verdi's ``Forza del Destino,'' Renato in
``Un Ballo in Maschera,'' Amonasro in ``Aida'' and Germont in ``La
Traviata.''
</P>
<P>
   His performances in the title role of ``Rigoletto'' were
particularly noteworthy and had grown increasingly rich over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   Manuguerra was also a frequent guest of the Opera Orchestra of
New York, which presents operatic rarities at Carnegie Hall. He was
in the Opera Orchestra's casts for Donizetti's ``Lucrezia Borgia,''
Zandonai's ``Francesca di Rimini,'' Meyerbeer's ``Africaine,''
Verdi's ``Battaglia di Legnano'' and Catalani's ``Wally.'' His last
appearance in New York was in the Opera Orchestra's performance of
Bellini's ``Straniera'' in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Manuguerra was born in Tunisia to Italian parents in October
1924, and later acquired French citizenship. He began his vocal
studies after World War II and settled in Argentina, where at the
age of 35 he enrolled at the Buenos Aires Conservatory and the
Instituto Lirico. He returned to France in 1963 to make his debut
at the Lyons Opera as Valentin in Gounod's ``Faust.'' After three
years in Lyons he joined the roster of the Paris Opera, where he
added ``Lucia di Lammermoor,'' ``Rigoletto'' and ``La Traviata'' to
his repertory.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, Manuguerra made his American debut as Gerard in
Giordano's ``Andrea Chenier'' at the San Francisco Opera. In the
United States, Manuguerra also performed with the Lyric Opera of
Chicago, the Dallas Opera, the Houston Grand Opera and the New
Orleans Opera. In Europe he made notable appearances at the Vienna
Staatsoper, the Arena di Verona and Covent Garden, as well as in
Bilbao, Spain; Frankfurt, Germany; Essen, Germany, and Bordeaux,
France, and at the Perelada Festival in Montpellier.
</P>
<P>
   Manuguerra is survived by his wife, Michelle, two sons, Mathieu
and Marc, and a daughter, Marianne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-98 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980728.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7415 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRONGFULDEATH-TRIAL-K     07-28 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRONGFULDEATH-TRIAL-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Lawsuit begins over death at veterans hospital  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ Lawyers for a 71-year-old Missouri widow
set out to show Monday what the FBI could not: that a murderer
stalked the hallways of the veterans hospital in Columbia six years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Havrum opened a wrongful-death lawsuit in federal court
Monday. She alleges negligence and malpractice led to the death of
her husband, Elzie Havrum, at the Harry S. Truman Memorial Veterans
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Havrum says her husband, a World War II veteran who earned
a Purple Heart, died of a codeine overdose a nurse administered.
Havrum's death is one of 33 at the hospital the FBI called
suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``He trusted his medical care to the same government he
served,'' Havrum's lawyer, John Kurtz of Kansas City, said Monday
in his opening statement. Havrum, he said, ``left the service much
as he left his life'' _ in a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   But a government lawyer said Havrum died of lung and heart
disease and that no one saw the nurse in question, Richard A.
Williams, do anything improper. Havrum had received three Tylenol 3
tablets, which contain codeine, for pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence will show Mr. Havrum did not die of codeine
toxicity,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Curt Bohling.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 32, has refused to comment on the case recently but
told a reporter last year he didn't give Havrum any unauthorized
medication. Williams could not be reached at his St. Louis area
home Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen of Havrum's relatives were in the courtroom Monday but
declined to comment. Helen Havrum is seeking unspecified damages.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is not on the witness list for the two-week trial
before U.S. District Judge Nanette K. Laughrey, but his wife,
Melissa Williams, gave a deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Elzie Havrum died at age 66 on June 15, 1992, after being
admitted for shortness of breath. He had chronic asthma and
emphysema, but he ran a Friday night auction business at his
Fulton, Mo., home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never slowed down much,'' his son, David Havrum, testified
Monday. ``He kept going.''
</P>
<P>
   Helen Havrum said she assumed her husband died of natural
causes, but then by the fall of 1992 reports surfaced about a high
rate of deaths at the hospital's Ward Four East, where Elzie Havrum
died.
</P>
<P>
   One study showed patients were 10 times more likely to die while
Williams was on duty than while other nurses worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were not the most sick, they were not the ones most
expected to die,'' Kurtz said Monday. Some nurses had referred to
Williams as the ``angel of death,'' Kurtz said.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Havrum said the hospital erred in keeping Williams on duty
two to three months after a sharp increase in deaths began showing
up during his nursing shift.
</P>
<P>
   But a witness testified Monday that the hospital didn't dawdle
in investigating the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't waiting. We were reviewing those deaths every time
they occurred,'' said Linda McGary, who oversees the hospital's
quality care program. A board of doctors reviews care given, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   McGary said, however, that deaths were not tracked by wards in
which they occurred. A short-term increase in deaths by ward would
be considered more of a ``variation than a trend,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No hospital in the country tracks death data in any other
way,'' Bohling said in his opening statements.
</P>
<P>
   Nurses noticed an unusual increase in deaths on Ward Four East
beginning in April 1992. McGary testified that a full investigation
began in late July after her staff and a police officer started
asking questions.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was then transferred out of patient care, after which
the death rate on his ward returned to normal levels. He left the
hospital staff in December 1993 and has since moved from job to
job.
</P>
<P>
   In the Havrum case, like most others, Williams was the nurse who
found the patients in question either dead or near death.
</P>
<P>
   Williams stated on hospital forms that he found Havrum in
``severe respiratory distress'' about 1:10 a.m. June 15. By the
time a doctor arrived five minutes later, he was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsies on Havrum's exhumed body found conflicting evidence of
codeine. Government experts first indicated his liver had six times
the fatal range of codeine, but later tests ordered as part of the
Havrum case determined he only had as much codeine as contained in
three pills he took that night.
</P>
<P>
   Expert witnesses for Havrum, however, maintain that codeine
level was within a fatal range and that it could have been
injected. The autopsy found an unexplained needle mark on his left
buttock and elbow, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses quizzed by Bohling Monday said the amount of codeine
needed to kill someone would not be available on the nursing floor
and that checks are made after every shift to account for what
drugs are removed.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz indicated that Williams could have obtained codeine from
other sources.
</P>
<P>
   Bohling said there is no proof of a fatal codeine level, which
he called essential to Havrum's wrongful-death case.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that finding can't be made,'' Bohling said, ``nothing else
follows.''
</P>
<P>
   The Havrum case puts the federal government in the position of
trying to defend the conduct of Williams after spending five years
investigating him and the deaths of his hospital patients.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI exhumed 13 bodies in early 1993 and conducted hundreds
of tests and interviews. In January of this year, the FBI termed 11
of the hospital deaths ``highly suspicious'' and 22 ``moderately
suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   But in January, the FBI announced it could not prove a crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
