A7416 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODWILL-SWIM29-COX     07-28 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-SWIM29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. team defeats Chinese in Goodwill swim meet
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ The U.S. recognized few of the names on the
Chinese swimming roster for the Goodwill Games. And even the one
name officials did know, they weren't sure if it was Yan Chen the
world champion in the 400 freestyle and 400 IM or Yan Chen the
backstroker.
</P>
<P>
   It was the world champion, but she and her 16 teammates looked
small and vulnerable against a U.S. team that defeated them 88-34
Tuesday night in a dual meet.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese won only three of the 14 events and no world records
were set by either team at the Nassau County pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the Chinese) are the biggest question mark in
swimming,'' said U.S. swimmer Lea Maurer, a world champion
backstroker. ``They're the most unpredictable team I've ever swam
against.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only do opponents know who will turn up, they don't know
what they'll look like.
</P>
<P>
   You want physically imposing? The U.S. women had broader backs
and bigger muscles than most of the Chinese, a team that once
inspired awe and suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Maurer said her teammates discussed the Chinese physiques.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the verdict's still out,'' she said. ``I think that
they look fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after huddling for a ``USA on the warpath'' cheer, a U.S.
400-meter medley relay team of Maurer, Megan Quann, Misty Hyman and
Richelle Fox defeated China by a whopping 11.84 seconds, 4:08.43 to
4:20.27. At the Atlanta Olympics, the U.S. took the gold and China
the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning, when some people found out the Chinese were
going to swim, some people didn't want to swim here,'' said U.S.
coach John Collins, who coaches Maurer and Cristina Teuscher (who
handed Yan Chen a defeat in the 200 free). ``They thought they're
dirty and shouldn't be here in this country. Because of the recent
history, what happened in Perth where they got caught with drugs
... everything we thought about them was true.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese swimmer caught carrying human growth hormone was
banned for 15 years and four teammates _ three women and a man _
were suspended for two years for doping violations.
</P>
<P>
   Although FINA, the international swimming governing body, does
not believe the Chinese Swimming Association is promulgating ``a
systematic process of doping,'' the Chinese aroused suspicion at
the 1994 Worlds when they won 12 of 16 gold medals. A year later,
two world champions were banned for drug violations before the
Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, China won only one gold medal, three silvers and two
bronzes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the Chinese are thinking about the 2000 Olympics,''
Collins said. ``Coming over here is a big experience for them. I'm
not sure their expectations coming here were to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Each team has two more dual meets against Germany and a team of
World All-Stars.
</P>
<P>
   The women's swimming doubleheader began with the All-Stars
defeating Germany 64-58.
</P>
<P>
   Germany has also had troubles with performance-enhancing drugs,
and the East German doping trials are still going on. Several
Olympic medalists have been identified as steroid users.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he didn't think this was China's best team, ``but I
don't think this is our top-grade team, either.''
</P>
<P>
   This U.S. team was missing some superstars.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Van Dyken, who won four gold medals in Atlanta, underwent
shoulder surgery and is out until December. Kristine Quance, a top
IM and breaststroker, got married last spring and is pregnant.
Brooke Bennett decided to skip the meet to concentrate on
nationals, as did the University of Georgia's Kristy Kowal, a world
champion breaststroker.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
